<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7146 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CYBERTIMES-ECOMMERCE-     10-25 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-ECOMMERCE-SALES-STILL-NEW-TREND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDING THE TRAFFIC SURGES ON THE WORLD WIDE WEB
</HEADLINE>
  By BOB TEDESCHI 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   Part of what has made e-commerce one of the most compelling
spectator sports of the year is this fact: No matter how much
experience executives have had running multimillion-dollar
companies in other industries, when it comes to Web retailing, many
of them are still making things up as they go along.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is anticipating and preparing for changing
traffic patterns on the World Wide Web. While traditional retailers
can say precisely when and why their customers arrive -- and can
maximize their efficiency accordingly -- Internet merchants have
frequently been caught by surprise in the past year by traffic
surges.
</P>
<P>
   As e-commerce merchants brace for their second meaningful
holiday shopping season, however, they are beginning to decipher
some of the rhythms of their Internet shoppers. Namely, while Web
traffic in general becomes heavier as the day goes on, many
Internet retailers report that traffic is actually heaviest during
the middle of the day, between 2 p.m. and 3 p.m. EST -- suggesting
that workers blessed with high-speed Internet connections remain
anchored to their desks at lunch time, sandwich in one hand, mouse
in the other.
</P>
<P>
   So, with the holidays rapidly approaching, some retailers are
shoring up their sites' technological infrastructure and hoping
they have enough capacity to handle the midday traffic smoothly.
Others, meanwhile, are looking beyond the back-office technology
issues into marketing opportunities presented by the 9-to-5 set.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, not every retail site is subjected to the same
midday shopping rush, analysts and executives said, because other
factors help determine the peaks as well. The type of goods sold
and the type of consumer the company attracts, for example, can
also affect a site's traffic patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lower-consideration purchases like books, gifts or flowers are
much more likely to be made during the daytime hours, since people
tend to see those things as a task that can be done quickly,'' said
Melissa Shore, an analyst with Jupiter Communications. ``With
things like computers, people will do a lot of research and then go
home and talk it over with their significant other or see if it's
compatible with their system, then go online and buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Travelocity, a travel site owned by the AMR Corp. that recently
announced a merger agreement with Preview Travel, peaks at 3 p.m.
EST, according to Terrell Jones, Travelocity's president. ``There
are a lot of busy dual-income families who can't book something at
night, when most travel agents are closed,'' he said.''And the
high-speed access at work certainly has an effect.''
</P>
<P>
   But marketing is also a factor, Jones said. Preview Travel
advertises heavily on America Online, which has heavier traffic
during the evening hours. ``So Preview's activity tends to be later
also. We're on Yahoo, which tends to peak earlier in the day,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Handling those peaks, of course, requires resources. Just as
brick-and-mortar stores plan for heavier shopping times by
scheduling more staff, Internet retailers need to rely on more
technology and personnel to get them through the rush. The great
fear of all Web merchants is that a traffic surge will catch them
by surprise -- landing them in the inauspicious company of Ebay,
Toysrus.com and ETrade as examples of sites that have occasionally
failed to handle their own peak loads.
</P>
<P>
   But even if a surge in users does not result in a system crash,
it can slow down the performance of a Web site sharply and alienate
potential customers. ``Our primary concern is making sure we can
handle all the traffic that doesn't come evenly,'' said Gabe Fried,
manager of research at Toysmart, an online toy retailer. That job,
he said, is complicated by the fact that traffic trends can change
quickly in response to marketing efforts, like an early-morning
promotion Toysmart recently began with Sesame Street.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign yielded ``a rather large shift in our peak hours
and processing hours,'' Fried said, but with beneficial results:
the site's traffic is now distributed more evenly through the day.
``That's better for us because it means less of a load on our
servers,'' he said, ``and better for users because the fewer of
them we have at one time, the faster the site is.''
</P>
<P>
   Web sites with less predictable traffic patterns could be in for
a long holiday season, said Jeff Nickerson, a partner in the
electronic business practice at PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``Last
holiday season, there were a lot of sites that were shocked, and
the consumers were a bit forgiving,'' he said. ``This time around,
there are so many more merchants that if stuff doesn't perform
well, sites will lose money big time.''
</P>
<P>
   More aggressive Web retailers, meanwhile, are looking into ways
to cash in on Internet users' lunchtime shopping habits.
Brookstone, which sells through its Web site, catalogs and stores,
is planning a radio advertising campaign that may include lunchtime
advertising, a spokesman said. Others are considering scheduling
more banner advertisements to be displayed on various Web pages
during lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike radio and television broadcasters, however, not every
Internet publisher -- not even America Online -- has the
technological means to serve a banner ad for a specific time slot.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology is available. The Internet advertising
company Doubleclick enables the 8,000 sites in its network -- and
others that license the company's technology -- to serve ads
whenever they want, a company spokeswoman said. Thus far, she said,
the service has been most popular with financial advertisers, which
typically want their ads to appear mainly between 8 a.m. and 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could argue that, yes, it does matter,'' said Nickerson,
of PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``People are more likely to buy during
these times than in other parts of the day. It's like the Internet
rush hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Since so many people are shopping at work, one would expect the
companies already involved with workplace Internet access to seek a
piece of the action. According to Ms. Shore of Jupiter, they may
get it. She predicted that e-commerce sites would start joining
forces with companies that set up intranet sites for corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say Amazon partnered with Peoplesoft, which puts
together a customized intranet for Time Warner,'' she said.
``Amazon could get massive exposure to Time Warner's employees, and
Time Warner could get discounts from Amazon that they could pass
onto their employees as a benefit. It makes sense for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Related Sites
</P>
<P>
   Preview Travel: http://www.previewtravel.com
</P>
<P>
   Travelocity: http://www.travelocity.com
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart: http://www.toysmart.com
</P>
<P>
   Brookstone: http://www.brookstone.com
</P>
<P>
   Doubleclick: http://www.doubleclick.com
</P>
<P>
   America Online: http://www.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Tedeschi at tedeschi(AT)nytimes.com welcomes your comments
and suggestions.
</P>
</TEXT>
