r a BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      10-25 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN RIDING REFORM ISSUE, CHALLENGES RIVALS TO TAKE STAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Arizona Sen. John McCain is trying to run a
presidential campaign and at the same time reform the U.S.
political system, rather like trying to shoe the horse as he rides
it.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain is determined to turn that apparent disadvantage into
an opportunity, his aides say, by taking the issue on the campaign
trail and outflanking his political opponents with it every chance
he gets.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, McCain will take his first stab, challenging his
GOP competitors on the eve of a debate in New Hampshire to support
a plan to fund an education voucher program by eliminating
subsidies for oil, sugar, gas and ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to ask each Republican to stand with the children
of America rather than corporate America,'' said Dan Schnur,
McCain's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Despite polls showing that campaign finance reform remains low
on the radar screens of most voters, McCain is betting he can make
it resonate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to reform education, if you want to reform the
military, if you want to reform the tax code, the gateway to that
is campaign finance reform,'' McCain told ``The Republic'' recently
during a break from the debate on the Senate floor on his doomed
campaign finance reform bill. ``Clearly, reform is a major theme of
the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, it remains uncertain whether campaign finance
reform is helping McCain get any additional traction in his
presidential race. Texas Gov. George W. Bush pays it only glancing
attention. And campaign observers say voters, too, pay the issue
little heed.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Senate, the issue earned McCain the scorn of his
fellow Republicans, who lashed out at him for attempting to ban the
very contributions that have helped propel the GOP into control of
the nation's two legislative chambers for the first time in two
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, a handful of
Republicans lacerated McCain for accusing them of corruption on his
campaign Web site and in speeches on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   McCain sloughed off the personal nature of last week's debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through much more difficult times than temper
tantrums from Mitch McConnell,'' McCain shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   The surprisingly nasty battle was grounded in McCain's race for
the GOP presidential nomination, he believed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presidential politics clearly plays a role in this,'' McCain
said. ``The prospect of President McCain vetoing and going after
pork-barrel spending is not their fondest hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain said, he's not just making a play to voters. This
has been his top issue for a long time and will continue to be, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain isn't sure he'll bring the bill back up next year so
close to a presidential election. And he won't speculate on its
effect on his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to do what I think is right and then, when it's over,
assess the impact,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Richard Pious, a political scientist at Columbia
University, said McCain's leadership on the campaign finance reform
bill is responsible for McCain's political fortunes ``in their
entirety.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, Pious said, establishes McCain's credentials as ``a
maverick, as a good-government progressive, as someone who can be
effective on the character issue.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides make no secret of their intention to cash in on
the issue, which, while bringing the wrath of McCain's Senate
friends down on him, also garnered him a steady stream of
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of ways, this issue is a domestic-policy version of
Kosovo,'' Schnur said. ``It gives John McCain extraordinarily high
exposure, but more importantly it gives him exposure in the context
of public policy, not campaign politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a number of observers believe the boost McCain gets
will be minimal at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaign finance isn't on the radar screen of most
Americans,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political scientist at
Claremont University.
</P>
<P>
   The issue may give McCain some outsider status with voters but
won't add much fuel to a campaign, she said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's chief rival for the nomination, Bush, seems to sense
that. The front-runner in the race, he has ignored McCain's reform
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, McCain sent Bush a letter exhorting him to join
the fight against big money and urge the GOP Senate caucus to vote
for his bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign responded by saying it would send McCain a
Bush bumper sticker.
</P>
<P>
   During a campaign stop last Monday in Phoenix, Bush reiterated
his opposition to McCain's bill.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush said he's against soft-money contributions, he's
more interested in instant disclosure of contributions and
``paycheck protection'' for labor union members, meaning that
unions can't give dues money to political parties without asking
their members.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm for is raising the individual limits and instant
disclosure,'' Bush said. ``I'm the only candidate in the race for
president who has got near real-time disclosure on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides are quick to attack the Bush campaign's seeming
disregard for reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate to see a candidate or his campaign treat a
serious issue with such disdain,'' Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the campaign reform issue is helping him, McCain
is picking up speed in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   An American Research Group poll released this week in New
Hampshire showed that McCain had again advanced on Bush, garnering
26 percent support to Bush's 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And some observers say Elizabeth Dole's departure from the race
Wednesday gives McCain a clearer shot at the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, McCain's admirers say, he'll score points
over more cautious candidates because he's jumping into the midst
of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a risk-averse campaign so far, and he (McCain)
hasn't been,'' said GOP pollster Kellyanne Fitzpatrick. ``It's not
a popular position within his own party, and I think when it's
explained to Americans, it's not a popular position, either. But
they will credit the man who steps into the ring wearing red to
face the bull.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
