<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEST MAN' GETS BETTER OF `FORCES'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matrimonial comedy ruled at the nation's multiplexes as ``The
Best Man'' easily won the top box office spot with an estimated
$9.1 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,346 theaters during a moderate Friday-Sunday
period, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's ``The Best Man,'' in an echo of the late-summer
success of ``Runaway Bride,'' took in an impressive $6,766
per-theater average.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of a group of African-American friends at a wedding
party generated the only solid business among the half-dozen new
films despite being shown at the fewest theaters of any Top 10
film.
</P>
<P>
   The film, produced by Spike Lee and directed by his cousin
Malcolm Lee, stars Taye Diggs as a writer whose novel creates chaos
when members of the wedding party discover the book borrows heavily
from their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The gross was the lowest for a No. &UR;  &LR; 1 film this year, replacing
the $9.4 &UR;  &LR; million weekend for ``Forces of Nature,'' and came during
what is traditionally a slow moviegoing period with competition
from baseball's World Series and the height of the football season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't expect big numbers this time of year, so the gross
for `The Best Man' is pretty respectable,'' said industry tracker
Arthur Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   Studio distribution chief Nikki Rocco said she was thrilled by
the performance and cited an aggressive e-mail campaign and strong
sales by the movie's soundtrack album as key factors in winning the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source tracking service,
said Universal's campaign had been able to attract
African-Americans and the date crowd. ``The audience for this film
is usually not tapped into as much it should be,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum noted ``The Best Man'' performed similarly to another
comedy with parallel themes, Paramount's ``The Wood,'' which opened
in mid-July with $8.5 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,191 theaters on its way to a
final $24.5 &UR;  &LR; million gross.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's ``Double Jeopardy'' solidified its status as the top
fall film by finishing second in its fifth weekend, declining only
25 &UR;  &LR; percent to $7.7 &UR;  &LR; million at 3,002 theaters to push its 31-day
gross past $91 &UR;  &LR; million. ``Jeopardy'' easily outdistanced 20th
Century Fox's second weekend of ``Fight Club,'' which faded quickly
from first to third with a 42 &UR;  &LR; percent decline to $6.3 &UR;  &LR; million at
1,966 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's opening of Martin Scorsese's gritty ambulance-driver
drama ``Bringing Out the Dead,'' which carried the strongest
reviews of the new films, followed in fourth with an adequate
$6.2 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,936 sites. The studio noted the debut is similar
to those of two other Scorsese films _ ``The Color of Money'' and
``Goodfellas'' _ each of which went on to gross more than
$40 &UR;  &LR; million.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said exit polls for ``Dead'' generated positive
response, adding that expectations were not particularly high
within the industry. ``Films released this time of year are not
expected to do that well,'' he said. ``Most of them will be
obsolete by the time the big holiday films start coming out next
month.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal's second weekend of ``The Story of Us'' took a
43 &UR;  &LR; percent hit to finish fifth with $5.5 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,166 sites,
edging DreamWorks' sixth weekend of emerging Academy Awards
contender ``American Beauty'' with $5.4 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,459 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty'' has hit nearly $49 &UR;  &LR; million and could double that
should stars Kevin Spacey and Annette Benning receive Oscar
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Two new entries, each carrying some of the year's most
blistering reviews, battled for seventh with Warner Bros.' romantic
comedy ``Three to Tango'' taking $4.7 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,234 theaters to
edge Destination Films' scare-fest ``Bats'' with $4.6 &UR;  &LR; million at
2,549 locations.
</P>
<P>
   Holdovers took the last two spots with Warner's fourth weekend
of ``Three Kings'' with $4.4 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,411 theaters to edge
Disney's 12th weekend of late-summer smash ``The Sixth Sense'' with
$4.3 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,191 sites. ``Sense'' has totaled $255.6 &UR;  &LR; million
after 80 days, leaving it just $4.5 &UR;  &LR; million short of passing
``Jaws'' as the 12th-highest domestic grosser of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Two other openings for offbeat dramas turned up dead on arrival
as Sony's ``Crazy in Alabama'' grossed only $1 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,214
theaters and New Line's ``Body Shots'' generated a minuscule
$310,000 at 309 locations. The total for ``Body Shots,'' which
revolves around date rape, was nearly eclipsed by a pair of highly
praised art-house entries _ Fox Searchlight's ``Boys Don't Cry''
with $285,000 at 37 theaters and Disney's ``The Straight Story''
with $268,000 at 32 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Overall business hit $78 &UR;  &LR; million for the weekend, up 6 &UR;  &LR; percent
from the same weekend last year and year-to-date business closed in
on the $6 &UR;  &LR; billion mark, about 7 &UR;  &LR; percent ahead of last year.
``It's a major positive sign that demand for product remains
strong,'' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The coming Halloween weekend will see a pair of strongly
divergent movies open _ Warner's ``House on Haunted Hill'' and
Miramax's ``Music of the Heart'' with Meryl Streep in a true story
of a violin teacher in East Harlem. Bucksbaum said ``Haunted
Hill,'' which has received a recent promotional push, should finish
first with about $10 &UR;  &LR; million. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
