<HEADLINE>
CALL HIM FATHER ANTI-TIME: MILLIONAIRE INVESTS IN STRUGGLE AGAINST
AGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: ALSO MOVING IN THE ``A'' CATEGORY )
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Like most people, Bobbie Clift doesn't enjoy growing
old.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most, she's doing something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing better than to feel like you're not growing
old,'' said Clift, 39, a Nashville businesswoman.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a good feeling, in fact, that Clift now flies to
Phoenix three times a year and pays thousands annually for
treatments at an anti-aging clinic opened recently by Phoenix-area
millionaire John Sperling.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling, 78, founder of the University of Phoenix, plans to
open nine upscale ``age-management'' clinics in Arizona and
California, and to invest at least a million dollars a year into
aging research.
</P>
<P>
   The first Kronos Clinic _ named for the Greek god of time _
opened in Phoenix; the second is scheduled to open in Scottsdale in
the Phoenix area in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts on aging scoff at such efforts _ similar clinics
have sprung up elsewhere _ saying there is no conclusive evidence
that aging can be retarded. They also question the treatments' high
cost.
</P>
<P>
   But not Clift. She said she'd been frustrated because, despite
aggressive exercise and nutrition, she felt her performance levels
slipping.
</P>
<P>
   After six months of Kronos treatment, she said, her energy level
is back up to her adult prime, ``my lung capacity is now back to
where it was when I was 30,'' and her skin and face have a more
``youthful glow.''
</P>
<P>
   But fighting Father Time doesn't come cheap. Because she takes
human growth hormone injections, Clift's regimen costs $12,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I don't buy a new car this year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The willingness of Clift and aging baby boomers to spend freely
for extended youth is not lost on Sperling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I wouldn't mind making another billion,'' he said,
adding that the clinics will first be marketed to affluent women,
40 to 65 _ the group that has already made vitamins, herbs,
wellness and workout spas a multibillion-dollar industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Sperling said he also sees the business as an opportunity to
make a contribution to humanity as more than just the wealthy
benefit from the treatments and the research.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling hopes his clinics will help change the way people age
by showing them how to prevent potential health problems. He
believes the idea of using doctors to stay well, instead of waiting
to treat illness, may yet catch on with the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is mass disaffection with traditional medicine now,'' he
said. ``Many doctors are as fed up as the patients.''
</P>
<P>
   But the clinics are only part of the story, he said. Sperling
has also dedicated a minimum of $1 million annually for the Kronos
Foundation to underwrite university-based aging research projects
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He has conferred with top scientific experts on aging and is
currently sorting through proposals in such diverse areas as
age-related DNA damage, oxidative stress and hormone replacement
therapies. Among his recent visitors was researcher Michael Rose of
the University of California-Irvine, who has earned international
acclaim for DNA work that has doubled the life span of laboratory
fruit flies.
</P>
<P>
   In the clinic, doctors will conduct up to 150 tests on each
patient to help design individualized programs for general health,
appearance and longevity.
</P>
<P>
   After a consultation covering lifestyle and family history,
patients are given tests to examine hormone levels, oxidative
stress and cancer risks.
</P>
<P>
   The cost is $1,200. A complete workup to assess cardiac health
is $1,600. The doctors may prescribe nutritional changes, lifestyle
changes, vitamins, antioxidants and hormones _ programs that
generally can cost from $120 to $800 per month.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic pharmacy will individualize vitamin formulas
according to each person's deficiencies and biochemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling has recruited big names to Kronos. Leading his research
effort will be Dr. Richard Cutler, a pioneer in gerontology.
</P>
<P>
   Cardiologist Dr. Tali Arik, president of the Kronos Group, said,
``Ask most doctors why you are getting old, and they won't have an
answer. But that's not the case with our doctors here.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a pioneer has its price: Arik says some of his peers look
askance at his joining Kronos.
</P>
<P>
   But he and two other doctors who have joined, Dr. Charlotte
DeHaven from Mesa Lutheran and Dr. Cheryl Shafer, formerly of Mayo
Clinic, say they're practicing the best kind of medicine:
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Does Sperling want to double his own life span?
</P>
<P>
   Well, he'd like to live to 100, if he stays healthy _ which he
tries to do by following an age-management program designed for him
that includes four or five customized vitamin and mineral capsules
per day as well as plenty of exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Shafer said she found out from her own work-up that her
melatonin levels were extremely low, which accounted for why she
had been a poor sleeper.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts on aging, however, are shaking their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Walt Nieri, past president of the Arizona Geriatric Society
and director of the Sun Health-St. Joseph's geriatric fellowship
program, thinks Sperling's clinics are a little off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think wellness needs to be an expensive process,''
Nieri said. ``When you put a price tag on it and cater to the rich,
it raises some suspicions.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieri does not doubt Sperling's intentions, and gives him high
marks for funding research. But he thinks Sperling should wait
before offering treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want to live healthily until we die, and to look
good,'' Nieri said. ``But there are no conclusive clinical studies
proving that any treatments delay the aging processes.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the research has been done on the aging of cells, Nieri
said, and even these reports have yielded conflicting results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans in general have become accustomed to the fact we can
do almost anything _ landing a man on the moon, doing medical
procedures previously undreamed of _ so their expectations are
high,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's just a matter of what you want to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperling said he also expects a little snickering from the
public. At first, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They also snickered when we started the University of Phoenix
for an adult student body,'' he said. ``Twenty years ahead of the
boom in adult education.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
