<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      10-25 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALLY MCBEAL' FAILS THE TEST OF COMEDY: LAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   True confession, right up front: I'm one of those people who
doesn't really ``get'' ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand, I like the show fine. It has much to
recommend it. David E. Kelley's writing is almost always sharp (if
occasionally overly goofy), Calista Flockhart has a good comic
delivery, Greg Germann makes an enjoyable weasel of a boss (even if
he is channeling Michael McKean from the old HBO series ``Dream
On'').
</P>
<P>
   But some viewers love the show. (To their credit, if ratings
mean anything, they're avoiding the truncated ``Ally.'') To them,
it's more than a TV series _ it's a way of life, a sign that
someone understands the world of work and all its weirdness the way
they do.
</P>
<P>
   Those people doubtless cheered when, earlier this year, ``Ally
McBeal'' won the Emmy for best comedy. But that's the thing _ if
it's the best comedy on television, shouldn't it at least make me,
you know, laugh?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the show provides plenty of humor. But not the kind
that makes you actually laugh out loud. Though vastly different in
theme and execution, ``Ally'' ``McBeal's'' humorous effect is more
along the lines of ``A Prairie Home Companion,'' Garrison Keillor's
radio show _ it's humor for people who don't like to actually laugh
but who like to nod and say, ``Mmm, that's funny,'' with a wry grin
on their face instead.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's ``Ally McBeal'' season premiere follows in that
tradition. Without giving too much away, just know that a quick
tryst for Ally and an anonymous partner leads to all sorts of
head-scratching high jinks, ha, ha.
</P>
<P>
   As for laughter, well, yes, it's humorous when John Cage says,
``Richard says communication is the death knell of any
relationship.'' Yes, it's funny when Fish says, ``You're a gender
bigot, Judge. I'd like you to walk a mile in her diaphragm.''
</P>
<P>
   But does it actually make you laugh? Is ``Ally McBeal'' in fact
the funniest show on television, a qualification that seems
reasonable enough when naming it best comedy?
</P>
<P>
   No. Not even close. In fact, there are few comedies left on
television that can be counted on to dependably cause a viewer to
close his eyes, open his mouth and let loose with a belly laugh.
Not coincidentally, wags are now pronouncing the death of the
sitcom. (Don't worry, it's a semiregular occurrence; when
``Seinfeld'' was hitting it big, the same geniuses pronounced the
death of the hourlong drama. Guess what's booming now?)
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, here's an unscientific look, not meant to be
comprehensive, at a few of the more notable network comedies and
how they rank on the laugh meter: &QL; 
GUFFAW:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simpsons'' _ Funniest show on television, hands down.
You'd think that after a decade, a traditional family sitcom (even
if it is about a non-traditional, cartoon family) would start to
fade. No chance. As good, or better, than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action'' _ Every episode offers at least three laugh-out-loud
moments. Too bad no one watches it to enjoy them. &QL; 
HEARTY LAUGHTER:
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier'' _ It's slipped a bit, but so far, this season shows
signs of rebounding. Gotta love that Niles Crane. Unless you're
Daphne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends'' _ Once it got popular, no one called it a
``Seinfeld'' rip-off anymore. Through-the-roof ratings will do that
for a show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' _ As comfortable as a chocolate
milkshake after school at the malt shop. And about as sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the Hill'' _ When Fox sandwiched this between ``The
Simpsons'' and ``The'' ``X-Files,'' it had the best two-hour block
on television. The network broke it up, naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night'' _ OK, so it's not technically a comedy. And
``Ally McBeal'' is?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose Line Is It Anyway'' _ Ditto. &QL; 
CHUCKLE:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Drew Carey Show'' _ Formerly in the above category, it's
slipped noticeably.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal'' _ Enough said already.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just Shoot Me'' _ If David Spade and Wendie Malick got more
air time, this would move up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie'' _ A truly funny guy, Eddie Griffin can't
quite make the transition to sitcom hilarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Harvey'' _ Ditto. Maybe he and Griffin could team up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Futurama'' _ Proof that Matt Groening isn't infallible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spin City'' _ Well, sometimes, anyway. &QL; 
STONE-FACED STARE: Suddenly ``Susan'' _ I'll take Tuesday in the
next-show-canceled office pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veronica's Closet'' _ Tempting to say it slipped, but it was
never funny to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stark Raving Mad'' _ Remember what happened to Aquaman when he
was out of the water too long? That's what'll happen to this if
(when) NBC moves it out from between ``Frasier'' and ``ER.'' Just
ask Veronica, above.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third Rock From the Sun'' _ How? Why? Its actors keep winning
Emmys. Don't the voters bother to even watch the show? &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
