<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS ON TOP OF BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Mike Holmgren admitted that after last week's
disappointing loss to the Chargers in San Diego, he wasn't quite
sure what to expect from the Seahawks Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The team's first-year coach knew what he wanted against the
Buffalo Bills at the Kingdome. He had spent the week preaching
about making a quick start after his team's sluggish effort against
the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the message sank in, and materialized in an
impressive 26-16 victory before a sold-out crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Ahman Green returned the opening kickoff 54 yards, which paved
the way to a 7-yard touchdown pass from Jon Kitna to Derrick Mayes
_ the first time this season the Seahawks opened a game with a TD
drive, and only the second first-half touchdown of the season by
the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also responded, holding the Bills to seven plays on
their first two series and ending the next two with interceptions
by free safety Jay Bellamy and strong safety Kerry Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the model of consistency, this team,'' Holmgren said,
half-joking but also right on in his assessment of the Seahawks'
performance Sunday compared to that in last week's 13-10 loss to
the Chargers. ``It sure feels a lot better than it did last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Being back on the winning track and back in first place will do
that. At 4-2, the Seahawks share the AFC West lead with the
Chargers and Kansas City Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks got an assist from the Green Bay Packers, who
slapped a 31-3 loss on the Chargers. That's the same Packers who
host the Seahawks next week in their first Monday Night Football
appearance since 1992, and the same team that Holmgren coached the
past seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren was, of course, asked to comment about his return to
the Land of the Cheeseheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll he happy to do that tomorrow,'' he said. ``Right now, I'm
enjoying this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory over the Buffalo was one to be savored, even if the
Bills were playing without Pro Bowl guard Ruben Brown, leading
receiver Eric Moulds, linebacker John Holecek and defensive end
Phil Hansen. Hey, the Seahawks didn't have wide receiver Mike
Pritchard, strong safety Darryl Williams or offensive tackle Todd
Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   Being able to play without some of your best players is a big
part of surviving in the give-and-take world of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks offense did more taking than giving, and the
defense refused to give in despite taking the best shots Bills
quarterback Doug Flutie had to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren released his conservative stranglehold on the offense
and Kitna responded by completing 17 of 30 passes for 276 yards,
including touchdown throws of 7 and 43 yards to Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bills looking to take away the outside, Kitna was able
to exploit the middle of the field with passes to Mayes (six
catches for 105 yards), Sean Dawkins (four for 91) and tight end
Christian Fauria (three for 42).
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes back to our play-calling,'' Kitna said. ``When we
start opening things up, and you're not just throwing to one side
of the field or the other, the defense doesn't know where you are
throwing the ball, and that's when guys can go out and make plays
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks defenders harassed Flutie all afternoon. They
intercepted two of his passes, and tipped, batted or deflected 13
others. They sacked him twice and hit him on a half-dozen other
occasions. Flutie did pass for 294 yards and two TDs, but had to
put the ball in the air 50 times to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was great was our coaches putting together a reel of
great Flutie plays he made once he scrambled in past games,''
linebacker Chad Brown said. ``Our looking at that reel all week
really helped.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the relentless efforts of the defensive linemen, who
refused to stop chasing Flutie even when their efforts seemed
futile; and the defensive backs, who found themselves in the
uncomfortable situation of wanting to break toward the line to help
contain Flutie but knew they had to plaster their receivers
regardless of how long it took.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Michael Sinclair on the line play: ``Flutie is
slippery. He was able to make some plays, but for the most part I
thought we did pretty good job of disrupting their offense. If it
had been a different quarterback, I think I would have had a lot of
sacks. Flutie did a great job of getting away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice, Sinclair had Flutie in his grasp. Twice, Flutie spun
free. But Sinclair finally got his sack, and it came at a very
opportune time. After Flutie had moved the Bills to the Seattle 36
and was looking like he was about to trim the Seahawks' 26-16 lead
with 5{ minutes to play, Sinclair not only sacked him but forced a
fumble that was recovered by Sam Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Willie Williams for the defensive backs: ``It takes a
lot of focus with him running around back there. Usually, you cover
your man for a count of, `One-thousand-one, one-thousand-two,
one-thousand-three, one-thousand-four.' With this guy, you're
going, `One-thousand-five, one-thousand-six, and even
one-thousand-seven,' and wondering what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The special teams contributed Green's tone-setting return of the
opening kickoff, four field goals from Todd Peterson and a couple
of energizing hits on kickoff coverage from Robert Wilson and Brian
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the match that started the fire,'' Green said of his
return. ``That was the thing that got things blowing up in the
first half.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Seahawks back on the winning track.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
