<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLD-SERIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES GRAB GAME 2 AFTER PARADE OF STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The loudest cheers at Turner Field came before Game 2
of the World Series Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Rose was there. So were Ted Williams, Willie Mays and local
icon Hank Aaron. The home of the Braves was awash in baseball glory
when the sport recognized the greatest players in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Then one of history's greatest teams went to work. And the fun
for the home fans was over.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees had five hits in the first inning Sunday
night. Atlanta has four hits in its first 17 innings this series.
It was David Cone's turn to dominate, and he pitched the Yankees to
a 7-2 victory and a 2-0 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was remarkable,'' Cone said of the pre-game scene. ``And it
worked out well for me. The fans were so into the ceremony that
nobody got on me in the bullpen. It was a great distraction (and) I
warmed up without being noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, Cone would be hard to ignore. He fired four hitless
innings before Greg Myers singled to lead off the fifth, and
pitched seven one-hit innings overall.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez pitched seven one-hit innings to win Game 1.
The Yankees' starters, inconsistent at times this year, have been
stingy so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're only as good as your pitching,'' said shortstop Derek
Jeter, who had two hits to extend his postseason hitting streak to
15 games. ``They've got some great hitters on that team, and for
the most part our pitchers have shut them down.''
</P>
<P>
   The last team to win the first two World Series games on the
road was Atlanta, against the Yankees in 1996. But the Braves lost
the next four games and the series, and are now in danger of
dropping their fourth World Series in five trips this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play every game like it's our last game,'' said Cone. ``I
know that sounds like a cliche, but this team really does go for
the jugular.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees haven't dropped a Series game since Game 2 in 1996.
They swept San Diego last year and now have won 10 in a row in the
Fall Classic, a streak surpassed only by their ancestors, who won
12 straight from 1927-32 behind Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   After being held to just two hits in Game 1 Saturday, the Braves
made several lineup changes. Bobby Cox inserted left-handed hitters
Ozzie Guillen, Keith Lockhart and Myers, replacing regulars Walt
Weiss, Bret Boone and Eddie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   But after the cold weather held down a deep drive by Brian
Jordan to end the first inning, the lineup was largely helpless in
what may have been Cone's last outing as a Yankee. The 36-year-old
right-hander, a free agent this winter, is not sure he'll be
brought back next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's on my mind, probably more than it should be,'' Cone
said. `` ... The best times of my life have been pitching for the
Yankees. (But) They've got some difficult decisions to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone won only twice in 13 starts after his July perfect game,
and the Yankees, who gave him only a one-year deal after his 20-win
season in '98, may have concerns about his durability. Top prospect
Ed Yarnall is a possible replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the Yankees _ yes, the Yankees _ have financial
concerns. They don't want to raise their $86 million payroll, yet
Derek Jeter, Mariano Rivera and Andy Pettitte are due for
arbitration and Roger Clemens can demand a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more important than a rotation _ I have trouble
visualizing a clubhouse without David Cone,'' said Yankees manager
Joe Torre. ``He means so much to this ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in October. Cone, who beat the Boston Red Sox in Game
2 of the American League Championship Series, improved to 6-1 in
the postseason as a Yankee. He was even more dominant than he was
in his last Series start against Atlanta, when he worked six
one-run innings to win Game 3 in '96.
</P>
<P>
   Braves starter Kevin Millwood was in Class A then, and he's
since become one of baseball's best young pitchers. He started this
postseason with a complete game one-hitter in the Division Series.
But his outings have gotten shorter and shorter since.
</P>
<P>
   After lasting into the eighth and sixth innings in his
second-round starts, Millwood was lifted before getting an out in
the third Sunday night. The two-inning performance was the Braves'
shortest start in their 27 World Series games this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had good stuff,'' Millwood said. ``I just threw it over the
middle of the plate. I tried to make adjustments, but nothing
worked for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Run-scoring singles by Paul O'Neill, Tino Martinez and Scott
Brosius gave the Yankees a 3-0 lead in the first. Millwood worked a
scoreless second, but struggled in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball wisdom says it's better to remove a pitcher one batter
early than one batter late, and that was proven again. Millwood
allowed singles to Bernie Williams and Martinez leading off the
third, and stayed in to face the left-handed Ricky Ledee. Ledee,
hitless in Game 1 after going 6-for-10 in the '98 Series, smashed a
double to left-center, scoring Williams and bringing in left-hander
Terry Mulholland from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees increased their lead to 5-0 off Mulholland when
Guillen, the shortstop, tried a Mays-style basket-catch on a soft
pop by Cone, dropping it for an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything bad,'' Guillen said. ``I didn't kill
anybody. I just made an error. I've made mistakes before.''
</P>
<P>
   So have the rest of the Braves at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
