<HEADER>
A7175 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     10-25 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUTIE CHASE GREAT DRAMA FOR NFL SUNDAY MATINEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ All day long, they were laughing at Michael Sinclair.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' sack master spent much of Sunday afternoon chasing
wildly around the Buffalo Bills backfield.
</P>
<P>
   All he had to show for it was a fistful of air.
</P>
<P>
   The guys on the Seahawks sideline shook their heads and chided
their Pro Bowl teammates, whose stats were lagging and whose ego
was taking a few lumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys were saying to me, `Looks like you just don't want a
sack today,''' Sinclair said after the Hawks had secured their
26-16 victory but had come to understand what it's like chasing Mr.
Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   OK, there were a few white threads off Doug Flutie's jersey
under Sinclair's fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Sinclair did get ahold of Flutie. It was a brief, slippery
moment in which everyone in the Kingdome seemed to watch like it
was the high-drama of their favorite, delicious cartoon show.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie was Jerry out-foxing Tom. The Road Runner eluding Wile E.
Coyote. In this show, the little guy is the one you root for.
</P>
<P>
   Even for Seahawks fans, even for Sinclair fans, you can't be a
fan of the game if you don't root for the little guy to keep
breaking free, to keep making plays, against all odds.
</P>
<P>
   It almost seemed unfair when, early on in the game, Sam Adams
rocketed off the line and nailed a vulnerable, back-dropping
Flutie. But the Hawks defenders were willing to show no mercy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get a piece of him. I wanted to put that in his
head that we were coming for him,'' Adams said. ``You have to make
that point, a quarterback that good. The ability to make plays like
that _ that's a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Hawks did not get as much of Flutie as they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   So many times Sunday, Sinclair pursued. So many times, just like
Merlin, the magical Flutie juked and shimmied and ripped himself
out of Sinclair's grasp _ until Sinclair had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth quarter. The Hawks' comfortable 23-3 halftime
lead had dwindled to 26-16, mostly because this one guy wearing No.
7 for the Bills refused to go down, no matter how many passes
Flutie's teammates dropped or how many yards his rushers could not
get him.
</P>
<P>
   But with just over five minutes left in the game, it sure seemed
there was still plenty of time for Flutie to pull off another
charmed chapter in his now storybook career.
</P>
<P>
   But finally, with Flutie already having heaved 42 pass attempts
in his valiant and nearly one-man comeback effort, Sinclair could
smell it was time.
</P>
<P>
   So on first-and-10 on the Hawks 36-yard line, Sinclair twitched
and jittered on the line, waiting for Flutie to call for the snap
deep in his shotgun position.
</P>
<P>
   And when Flutie did make the call, Sinclair turned the corner,
coming on like a bull who finally captures the red cape in his
angry stare. Finally, Sinclair took firm hold of the elusive beast
named Flutie, hauling the pint-sized giant killer to the turf.
</P>
<P>
   The ball flopped free and Flutie lay sprawled while Sinclair's
teammate Sam Adams pounced his 300-pound body on top of the
football, wrapping it and the game up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can tackle him in a phone booth,'' Sinclair
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refs should check his uniform. He must have had super suds
on his jersey or something.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk around the NFL since Flutie overcame his
ridiculous exile to the Canadian Football League and began turning
heads again by beating up teams in a league where he had all but
been rejected, there is still a feeling Flutie can't be quite that
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you watch film of Buffalo, you watch Flutie and
you think it must be those other teams that can't catch him. But
when he comes to my place, it's going to be another story,''
Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he did a great job of getting away from us. If it had been
a different quarterback today, I think we would have had a lot of
sacks. Flutie did a great job of getting away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks could walk away feeling happy about their work
Sunday. They pushed their record to 4-2 and gained a three-way tie
for first place in the AFC West with the Chargers and Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was impossible not to relish what Flutie was doing out
there, scrambling, making lives amusingly hellish after the Hawks'
watched a 20-0 lead dwindle.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie had only 83 yards on 7-for-16 passing in the entire first
half, including two interceptions. But before he was done, he had
collected 294 yards on 24-for-50 accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put pressure on him to make a lot of plays. He made some
that nobody else would have made, I know that,'' Bills coach Wade
Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough to set off fireworks or challenge any of John
Elway's comeback records, but Flutie was captivating to watch. His
energy seemed almost unmatched _ at least until Sinclair finally
got his hands on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were right there. I never felt we were out of it
up until the fumble,'' Flutie said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   He still looked pumped. He still exuded a feeling that, given
another set of downs, he could go out and make the score closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked around at each other after the game and said it was
a fun game,'' Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like playground ball. Chasing little kids around.
That's what it felt like.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real slippery, very athletic and he makes a lot of plays.
So many times being in the NFL, you look for the typical guy who
looks good on paper. The 6-foot-4 guy, 230 pounds,'' Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But here's a guy who's a playmaker. He isn't big. He isn't
tall. But man, the guy's a playmaker. We got after him pretty good
today. It was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   We have come to relish nothing less in these NFL Sundays of
chasing Mr. Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
