<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-VOTE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-860&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY OF PERON LOSES ITS HOLD ON ARGENTINA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating throughout)   (sw) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ Mayor Fernando de la Rua of Buenos
Aires, a somber centrist who campaigned pledging to clean up
government graft and breathe oxygen into a sluggish economy,
appeared to win a landslide victory in presidential elections on
Sunday, ending a decade of rule under the flamboyant and
unpredictable Carlos Saul Menem.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua's victory, which he claimed in a triumphant appearance
at a downtown hotel, was widely expected, but significant for
breaking the domination of the populist party founded by Juan
Domingo Peron, for decades the most prominent politician in
Argentina and a man whose shadow has hung over its politics years
beyond his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compatriots, I thank you,'' de la Rua said, swamped by
cheering supporters. ``I come to thank you as your president-elect.
This is a triumph for all of you. All Argentina won.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Menem, the Justicialist Party veered off its traditional
populist course and toward free-market policies, creating a potent
coalition between the working class and an emerging upper middle
class.
</P>
<P>
   But the last year of deepening recession and a wide variety of
government scandals soured many Argentines toward Menem's rule,
busting the new coalition and leading to de la Rua's easy victory.
He appeared to coast through the campaign, refusing to debate his
leading opponent, Eduardo Duhalde, the Buenos Aires governor, or to
divulge many details of his policies.
</P>
<P>
   With 65.9 percent of the official results counted, de la Rua,
the candidate of the center-left Alianza coalition, was winning
48.8 percent of the vote. Coming in a distant second was Duhalde,
the 58-year-old candidate of Menem's party, who was winning 37.5
percent and conceded defeat on Sunday night. Domingo Cavallo, a
former economy minister running on a conservative third-party
ticket, was winning 10.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a clear mandate,'' de la Rua declared. ``We need to
develop a social system that includes everyone with equality of
opportunity for all. We will end corruption and impunity.'' And in
an implicit swipe at Menem, who became known for his fast cars and
socializing with entertainers and sports stars, he added that his
government ``would leave egotism behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes after polls closed, all major Argentine networks
declared de la Rua the winner, and his supporters poured into the
streets dancing across Buenos Aires's main thoroughfare, the
Avenida 9 de Julio. De la Rua, an author of several law books and a
lover of gardening and golf, promised during the campaign to slice
an expanding budget deficit that he said would lower interest rates
and attract foreign investment. He pledged to grant incentives to
small and medium-sized businesses as a way to decrease the 14.5
percent unemployment rate, as well as narrow the gap between rich
and poor that has grown as the Menem administration has sold off
government agencies and enacted a slew of deregulatory measures.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he would crack down on tax evasion and government
corruption, suggesting that at least some top officials in the
Menem administration could go to jail.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua, however, repeatedly promised during the campaign not
to touch the cornerstone of Menem's economic policy _ pegging the
value of the Argentine peso one-to-one to the dollar, which ended a
long history of hyperinflation and economic instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole country has high expectations,'' said de la Rua, 62,
wearing his usual blue blazer and ascot to his polling place in the
upper-class Buenos Aires neighborhood of Barrio Norte. In his
signature deadpan style, he added, ``I guess my life is going to
change a little tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   After voting, de la Rua talked amiably with reporters about the
recent baptism of a new grandson and predicted an orderly
transition. But he also made a special appeal to Menem to avoid any
costly last-minute pork-barrel projects leading up to the
inauguration on Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   As mayor of Buenos Aires, de la Rua was not known for any major
initiatives. But he put the city budget in the black, lengthened
the subway system, widened public health services and improved
services for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Duhalde blocked Menem's attempts to contest a constitutional ban
against running for a third consecutive term, but he never managed
to unite and fire up his party. He veered between distancing
himself from Menem and embracing the successes of the last decade,
especially the end of hyperinflation.
</P>
<P>
   The election appears to mark the first time that the party of
Peron will lose power by popular mandate and not by military coup _
breaking an almost uninterrupted string of election victories that
gave it a domineering position in Argentina politics over the last
two generations.
</P>
<P>
   Its devastating defeat could have repercussions for years to
come, with what remains the country's largest political force going
through a probable power struggle to decide whether it returns to
its traditional left-wing direction or merely fine-tunes Menem's
free-market policies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, many analysts predict that de la Rua will not be a
forceful President. He will govern by leading an alliance of the
centrist Radical Party and the more liberal Frepaso Party, a group
that broke away from Menem's party in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties, joined in the Alianza, appear to have picked up
a few seats in the lower house of Congress, but they will not have
a working majority. Menem's Justicialists will continue to control
the Senate through at least the 2001 elections, and to dominate the
Supreme Court and most of the provincial governments _ despite
losing the gubernatorial seats in Mendoza and Entre Rios on Sunday.
A handful of governorships and part of the lower house of Congress
were contested in Sunday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a government that will have to negotiate, a big
break from the way Menem was able to govern,'' said Mariano
Grondona, a columnist for the Buenos Aires daily La Nacion. ``It's
the end of the era of the caudillo,'' he added, referring to the
Spanish term for the traditional strongman.
</P>
</TEXT>
