<HEADLINE>
GREEN'S KICKOFF RETURN JUMP-STARTS SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For someone who has been integrated into the Seattle
Seahawks offense so slowly, Ahman Green sure got off to a fast
start Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Green returned the opening kickoff 54 yards _ just shy of his
career best 57-yard effort _ and later turned in a pair of long
runs from scrimmage to set up two first half Seattle scores in the
Seahawks' 26-16 victory over Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you get a kickoff return like that to start a game,
it certainly helps when you're playing at home,'' Seahawks
quarterback Jon Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   Green's return provided the team exactly the kind of jumpstart
Seattle coach Mike Holmgren has been asking for in recent weeks.
But Green's three carries for 29 yards _ his first rushing attempts
of the year _ may prove equally as significant. With Green in the
backfield the team gets a speed and slash style running option to
complement primary running back Ricky Watters' power and endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Green and Watters combined for 110 yards, Seattle's most
productive rushing output of the season _ besting a 94-yard,
all-Watters effort against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very encouraged with what he (Green) did today, even
though he didn't carry the ball a lot,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the season goes along, Ricky Watters is going to carry the
ball most of the time, but it is a nice change-up with Ahman and I
hope now we can do that a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are promising words from Holmgren, who has been deliberate
and calculating in including the second-year pro Green in his
play-calling. While Green was gaining confidence returning
kickoffs, Holmgren began slowly increasing his rushing duties
during practice, especially in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Far from getting impatient with Holmgren's pace, Green said he
understood his coach's time line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy with what I got today,'' Green said. ``It's
something to build my confidence on. It's even more of a plus to me
because I got to go in and contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that was bothering me (in past weeks) was
making sure I was learning the playbook. I'm a perfectionist and
once I got into the mix today I felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared Green's play invigorated the entire Seahawks offense
and certainly the kickoff return set a positive tone. Then on
Seattle's final first-half possession, Green reeled off a 16-yard
run off right tackle, then answered with a 13-yard carry behind
left tackle on the next play. The drive resulted in a Todd Peterson
field goal for a 23-3 lead at half.
</P>
<P>
   Green didn't carry the ball again, but Watters, who insists he
never needs extra motivation, doubled his first-half output in the
second to finish with 75 yards on 22 carries. His 19-yard run in
the third quarter was his longest of the year and comes during what
Watters called a ``real difficult week.'' He was excused from two
practices to attend to family-related matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always ready to go,'' Watters said. ``I had a hard week
but I wanted to show I could handle it and come in and have a great
game. I felt like (my mind) was clear today and I was ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our running game is no going like it should, I take it
personally even if it's not me. It seems like every week we get a
little better and a little better. ... We were clicking. We felt
good.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Holly Cain
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8015
</P>
<P>
   or hollycain &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
