<HEADLINE>
BUMBLING BILLS SEEK ANSWERS AFTER DEBACLE IN DOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALIYA SAPERSTEIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Buffalo made so many mistakes in its 26-16 loss to the
Seahawks Sunday, the Bills' players were unable to put their
fingers on exactly what caused all the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the million dollar question,'' said rookie cornerback
Antoine Winfield, shaking his head in dismay. ``I'm going to have
to watch the film to be sure. All I know is we couldn't get
anything done.''
</P>
<P>
   A clipped Wade Phillips, who seemed ready to explode at any
moment during his postgame questioning, was willing to take a stab
at the answer, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a terrible first half. Just horrible,'' said the
Buffalo coach. ``That cost us the ballgame _ we couldn't make the
plays to get all the way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips continued to castigate his team, singling out the
Bills' defense _ which came into the game ranked sixth in the NFL,
but was missing two starters in Phil Hansen and John Holecek _ for
particular criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had horrible pass defense,'' Phillips said. ``I have no
answer for it. ... The secondary was terrible. Coverage was
terrible. We made some plays that were unbelievably poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was most dismayed at having to watch Derrick Mayes
score on a 43-yard pass over the middle after having called for
double coverage on the Seahawks' wide receiver. Winfield and safety
Manny Martin were the Bills who got burned as the Seahawks took a
20-0 lead midway through the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't doing anything (special). They were just like any
other receivers we played,'' said Winfield of the Seahawks. ``We
were playing a lot of zone coverage and they were just hitting on
the deep routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't execute. We had good coverages called,'' he
added. ``We just didn't make the plays we needed to make.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Seahawks racked up 385 yards, 241 yards of which came
in the first half and 105 of which were by Mayes alone, Buffalo's
offense struggled almost as much as its defense.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Pro Bowl guard Ruben Brown, running back Thurman
Thomas and Pro Bowl wide receiver Eric Moulds helped cripple the
Bills, who had half a dozen dropped passes, and 15 more knocked
away by the Seahawks. That left quarterback Doug Flutie with a 24
of 50 performance for 294 yards and two interceptions. Flutie also
was sacked four times, two of which came on third down and forced
punts.
</P>
<P>
   Both Brown and Moulds were injured in the loss to Oakland last
week, while Thomas has beenout with a bruised kidney and liver
since the first play of Buffalo's first game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to have an injury bug right now,'' said Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills may have more important things to recover from after
the beating at the Kingdome. Phillips keyed on solving Buffalo's
habit of getting behind early in games as perhaps the only way the
Bills will be able to move on from their second straight loss to
two more road games at Baltimore and Washington. Sunday, the Bills
were down 23-0 before they managed to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting down in every game and it's hard to come
back,'' Phillips said. ``I think it is probably coaching, and I'm
taking me first. We have to get them more prepared at the first of
the game. ... I realized we've turned it over and (our opponents)
have had it in our territory on the first drive the last three
games. Every time they have scored a touchdown. We have to remedy
that.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if one remedy might be switching quarterbacks,
Phillips said tersely, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie _ despite keeping his team within striking distance until
Seahawks defensive end Michael Sinclair sacked him, causing a
fumble with five minutes remaining _ was willing to shoulder some
of the blame for the debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all took our turns making mistakes,'' said the oft-doubted
quarterback. ``After we got down, a fire started burning and I kept
saying, `We have to get back into the game.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts with me, I guess. I have to get the ball in better
places and get guys fired up to play.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Aliya Saperstein
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8370
</P>
<P>
   or aliyasaperstein &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
