<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TAKE CONTROL AS CONE SILENCES BRAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Major League Baseball honored the All-Century Team at
Turner Field last night, a ceremony that had infinitely more drama
than the game that followed.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Century revelry also gave Atlanta Braves fans something
cheer about with the heralded appearances of local idol Hank Aaron
and national martyr Pete Rose. The thundering ovations accorded
both served as a stark contrast to the shock and disbelief to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   The Battle of the Decade is turning into a lopsided affair.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees, piling on further proof they're as good as
any team in any decade, pounded All-Star pitcher Kevin Millwood for
five runs in two-plus innings and took a two-game advantage in the
World Series with a 7-2 victory over the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone, sitting on a 3-0 lead before he threw his first
pitch, was as good as Orlando Hernandez in Game 1, shutting out the
Braves on one hit through seven innings before calling it a night.
The Braves salvaged a couple runs off reliever Ramiro Mendoza in
the ninth inning to avoid the shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching sets the tone for what we're trying to do, and David
Cone was terrific for us tonight,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really strong tonight,'' said Cone, starting for the
first time in 10 days and only the third time in a month. ``The
extra rest has really helped me; it's put life back in my arm. I
was a little wild; that's what extra rest will do for you, but I
was able to work out of some jams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, after losing two on their home field, now must win
at least two of three in the unfriendly confines of Yankee Stadium
to get this series back to Turner Field. They seek a reversal of
what happened in 1996 when the Braves won the first two games of
Series at Yankee Stadium, only to have the Yankees win the next
four.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question, we're aware of what happened back in
'96,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   It still doesn't look good for the Braves, not against this
relentless team. The Yankees have won nine of 10 in this postseason
and 20 out of 23 going back to last year's playoffs. The Yankees
have also won 10 consecutive World Series games dating to the
comeback against the Braves and the sweep of the San Diego Padres
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Only 11 of 45 teams have come back from a 2-0 deficit to win the
World Series. Only three teams have done it after losing the first
two games at home: the 1985 Kansas City Royals, the 1986 New York
Mets and the 1996 Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't expect to do that this time of year, not
against great teams,'' Cone said. ``But that's a tribute to our
starting pitching. We've had some really great games pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, looking almost as bad as the Rangers against Yankees
pitching, have been outscored 11-3 and out-hit 20-7. By the seventh
inning, Braves fans had replaced the Tomahawk chop with the
desperate chant, ``We want a hit!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a bad game,'' Atlanta manager Bobby Cox said. ``We
didn't hit the ball \RSaturday night\S, and we didn't hit it
tonight. We really weren't tearing the ball up against the Mets.
Both pitchers were tough, we figured it would be tight but we
haven't had the pitching to keep it tight.''
</P>
<P>
   After his team had only two hits in Game 1, Cox tried to inject
more offense in his lineup by using left-handed hitters Ozzie
Guillen at shortstop, Keith Lockhart at second base and Greg Myers
behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Myers had two of the Braves' five hits and had a run-scoring
single. But Guillen let in an unearned run in the third when he
dropped Cone's soft line drive for an error, and Lockhart cost the
Braves another run when he threw wildly trying to complete an
inning-ending double play in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   However, the game had pretty much been decided before then. The
Yankees probably had it won in the first when Chuck Knoblauch,
Derek Jeter and Paul O'Neill started the game with consecutive
singles, giving them a 1-0 lead. Millwood got Bernie Williams to
hit into a double play, but a single by Tino Martinez, a walk to
Ricky Ledee and single by Scott Brosius made it 3-0. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
