<SLUG> BC-FBC-UW-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATING CARDINAL KEY TO HUSKIES' PAC-10 TITLE HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TED MILLER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Skeptics have kicked Stanford around most of the
season. Now the Cardinal is kicking back.
</P>
<P>
   After Stanford overcame a three-touchdown deficit to dust
nemesis USC 35-31 on Saturday, the Cardinal and its 5-0 Pac-10
record can't be doubted any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've been enjoying (the doubts),'' University of
Washington coach Rick Neuheisel said Sunday. ``There's no question
they are a legitimate team.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford hasn't been 5-0 in conference play since 1970, the last
time it played in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel and the Huskies can only hope that Stanford's
legitimacy won't be enough to end a 14-game losing streak at Husky
Stadium, where the two teams square off Saturday at 12:30 p.m. The
game has been picked up by ABC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's last win at Husky Stadium? A 24-21 decision in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, which suffered verbal slings and arrows from the media
because of a 52-point loss to Texas and a defeat to lightly
regarded San Jose State, is the conference's only unbeaten team.
The UW and Arizona State, the Cardinal's next opponent on Nov. 13,
are tied for second with 3-1 marks. ASU hosts Oregon on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win this week if we want a shot at the conference
championship,'' Neuheisel said. ``It's a big-time game and big-time
games are what Husky fans expect.''
</P>
<P>
   The showdown figures to be a scoring slugfest. Stanford's
offense averages nearly 37 points per game. Meanwhile, its defense
was ranked 110th in the nation before it gave up 587 yards to the
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, which surrenders nearly 33 points per game, owns the
conference's worst pass defense. USC threw for 415 yards against
the Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   But that defense was stout enough to stop USC when it counted.
Tim Smith intercepted a pass as time ran out with USC on the
Cardinal's 7-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic nature of the victory over USC inspired even
reticent Cardinal coach Tyrone Willingham to break character _ if
only for an instant.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, it's awfully big,'' Willingham said. ``Right
now, we're living in the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is far better defending the run. It gave up just 125
yards on the ground per game before yielding 172 to the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   The question is which Huskies offense will show up. Two weeks
ago, the UW was a power-running, option attack that topped the
conference in time of possession. The past two weeks, the Huskies
haven't run as well and have lost the time of possession battle.
</P>
<P>
   If the UW has to throw, it will do so without its best receiver,
Chris Juergens, who is doubtful after spraining his ankle in the
Huskies' 31-27 victory over California. He adds his name to a long
list of banged up UW players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're held together by glue and string,'' Neuheisel quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is much healthier than the Huskies, though its
second-leading receiver, DeRonnie Pitts, sprained his ankle against
USC and is questionable for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That should put pressure on flanker Troy Walter, the
conference's leading receiver. Walter, who is already the Pac-10
career receiving yards leader, caught five passes Saturday, which
gives him 218 for his career, six short of the conference record.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal, typically one of the conference's best passing
teams, also is balanced this season. It has rushed for 1,140 yards
after producing just 831 yards on the ground all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford could practically ensure a tie for the conference title
with a victory. After the UW, the Cardinal has just two conference
games left on its schedule (ASU and Cal).
</P>
<P>
   Washington also has the conference champtionship as its goal,
which will be on the line Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I've said before: The Rose Bowl is always your goal,''
Neuheisel said. ``But the only way to get there is to win this
week.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ted Miller can be reached at 206-448-8017
</P>
<P>
   or tedmiller &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
