<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS, SANDERS SILENCE TRASH-TALKING REDSKINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ The Cowboys propelled themselves back into the NFC East
driver's seat by completing a season sweep of the Washington
Redskins, 38-20, at Texas Stadium yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   In one fell swoop, the Cowboys overcame the Eagles game, the
Giants game, wholesale public skepticism, nine penalties, six
dropped balls and a week's worth of doubt and criticism heaped upon
the Chan Gailey offense.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Chan Gailey offense fired back yesterday. It converted
nine of 15 third-down situations, rolled up 352 total net yards,
put up points on its first three possessions for the first time all
season and scored twice as many touchdowns in one game as it had in
its previous two games combined.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all yesterday, the Chan Gailey offense overcame
itself.
</P>
<P>
   And in the process, the Cowboys, in effect, took a one-game lead
on the Redskins in the standings, based on the NFL tiebreaker
system in which head-to-head competition is the first criterion.
The Cowboys and Redskins are 4-2, followed by the New York Giants
at 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   While Deion Sanders' 70-yard punt return for a touchdown in the
fourth quarter iced the game, nothing yesterday at Texas Stadium
was bigger than a 13-play, 93-yard touchdown drive by the Cowboys
that began late in the third quarter, with the Cowboys precariously
clutching a 24-20 lead.
</P>
<P>
   This drive turned out to be a microcosm of the Cowboys' season,
or at least the turn the season had taken in the wake of 13-10 road
losses at Philadelphia and New York the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive, the Cowboys had to overcome two penalties and
three dropped passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we haven't been able to do lately,'' said
Gailey. ``But we got some opportune penalties \Ron the drive\S.
Plus, I thought one of the big differences in this game was
third-down'' conversions.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end David LaFleur alone had a false start and two of the
three drops on the drive. Wide receiver Alvin Harper had the other
drop; running back Chris Warren had a holding penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But the big play was pass interference called against Washington
nickel back Darryl Pounds, who was covering Harper on third-and-20
from the Cowboys' 9. It gave the Cowboys an automatic first down at
the Dallas 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan called an outstanding game today ... I think we threw 'em
off on the route that Alvin ran, and we got the pass
interference,'' said Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman, who completed
20 of 32 passes for 244 yards and two touchdowns, with no
interceptions and no sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The \Rpass interference\S was a big because it came on
third-and-long ... \Rand\S you don't make those very often in this
league.''
</P>
<P>
   Three plays after Harper was obviously fouled into the turf,
Cowboys first-year wide receiver Jason Tucker fought off
bump-and-run coverage on third-and-seven and streaked down the
Washington sideline, past celebrated rookie cornerback Champ Bailey
on what turned out to be a free play (The Redskins were offside.).
Tucker took Aikman's perfect toss in full stride for a 52-yard gain
to the Redskins 19. Aikman finished the drive with a 1-yard
touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, playing with a first-quarter concussion that kept him
out of the game until he took it upon himself to return early in
the third quarter, put this game on ice with a 70-yard punt return
for a touchdown with 9:03 left. The Redskins still haven't touched
him.
</P>
<P>
   Washington brought the NFL's No. 1 offense and No. 31 defense
into this game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys held the Redskins to 15 fewer points and 232 fewer
total net yards than they did in the Cowboys' 41-35 overtime
victory in the Sept. 12 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Cowboys have scored 79 points and rolled up 893
yards in two victories over Washington this season. In these two
games, they've scored 11 offensive touchdowns. In their other four
games combined, they've scored seven touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had \Rthe Redskins\S on their heels for most of
the game,'' said Aikman, referring to Gailey's play-calling that
allowed a passing attack that involved nine receivers and a running
game in which Emmitt Smith finished with 80 yards on 24 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins coach Norv Turner can be excused for thinking that the
Chan Gailey offense undergoes some kind of metamorphosis against
his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly are a lot more wide-open on offense against
us,'' said Turner, in a classic understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Turner also pointed a deserved finger at his own players for the
bulletin-board material provided mostly by Redskins receivers
Albert Connell and Michael Westbrook, who directed their taunts and
threats during the week at Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told our team repeatedly during the week, `We're coming to
Dallas. We've been here before,' '' Turner said, ``and anyone who
thought this game was going to be any different than it was ...
wasn't listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was amused by the trash talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just amazed any time that kind of talk is done in this
league,'' Aikman said. ``I don't understand it. It's not boxing.
We're not having a hard time selling tickets. I think a lot of guys
want to bring attention to themselves and get some publicity, and
have the whole world recognize them ... I don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Redskins got it.
</P>
<P>
   Both barrels. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
