<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7184 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     10-25 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY, A LIGHT GOES ON FOR GAILEY'S BEDEVILED OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ That fine line between idiot and genius swung
back the positive way for Chan Gailey yesterday. But stay tuned _
it's an on-going weekly judgment call by fans, media and maybe even
some of his quick-to-privately-backstab players.
</P>
<P>
   Four offensive touchdowns and 31 total points against the
Redskins not only returned the Cowboys to the win column, it also
upgraded Gailey's football IQ.
</P>
<P>
   On this afternoon, he wasn't dumber than a bumper hitch. The
light was on, and somebody was actually home. But even after a
38-20 victory, how bright will that bulb burn after upcoming trips
to the land of Colts and Vikings? With the Packers, Miami and the
Patriots also on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   This team chopped down a few trees yesterday, but is not out of
the woods. For Gailey, however, it was at least a brief reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I'd liked to be judged is by where we are as a team
and an offense when the season is finally over,'' Gailey said,
requesting the impossible in this part of the football world.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you go through what we've gone through the last
couple of weeks,'' he added, ``it does bring up immediate
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When does it turn? When does a sense of urgency consume our
team? Will it be today, or will it take another week or two? But
what I'd hoped would happen, happened today.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning a total team victory with the previously deadhead
offense so productive it took the pressure off a Cowboys defense
known to bend and break.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Gailey had read all the sports-page rips aimed his way. As
a non-listener, he did miss the talk-show roast. But offense is
Gailey's baby. And the baby was sick. It had been stuck on 10
points for two consecutive losses. The head coach was having his
head handed to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction to the criticism was I wished everybody wasn't
saying all that stuff about me,'' Gailey said. ``But on the other
hand, if we'd played better, they wouldn't have said the stuff to
begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, always an honest sort, swears he didn't take it
personally. ``If you do, then it impacts the way you think,'' he
replied. ``I'm not going to allow that to happen. In general, I
didn't agree with why we were being criticized. But I understand.
It's a part of the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did success happen yesterday? Was there a change in
offensive philosophy, leading to this touchdown breakout? Did
Gailey simply call better plays? Is Washington's defense not up to
snuff with that of Philly and the Giants? Or did Nelson Mandela, a
Texas Stadium visitor, offer Gailey a few offensive tips?
</P>
<P>
   ``The man does know how to handle pressure,'' grinned Gailey,
very impressed when he spotted Mandela in the postgame locker room.
</P>
<P>
   But while Gailey tweaked the offense, there were no major
changes. A few frills were eliminated, mainly Emmitt Smith running
more between the tackles instead of outside.
</P>
<P>
   More important, however, this victory and this offensive
turn-around was more about the line being dominant instead of being
dominated. It was about a very sharp Troy Aikman being on-target to
a makeshift group of receivers, who still had a way-too-many
half-dozen drops.
</P>
<P>
   And for what it's worth, nobody in the Cowboys' locker room put
the Redskins' defense in the same class as the last two they've
faced. Washington did show stacked fronts at times, but mainly
stayed in a basic 4-3, without an abundance of blitzes. The Giants
had disrupted the Cowboys six days earlier with constant eight- and
nine-man run blitz packages.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping to a 17-0 lead also gave both the Cowboys' offense and
defense (buried by the Redskins' 35-points-a-game offense in the
season opener) a sudden sense of superiority. ``Enough can't be
said about the quick start we had, and what that meant to us
mentally,'' center Mark Stepnoski said.
</P>
<P>
   As the Redskins constantly closed in (it was 17-13 and 24-20 in
the second half), the offense responded with a touchdown answer.
And they did so with Emmitt and receiver Rocket Ismail missing a
portion of the second half due to injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Gailey had a good play-calling game. Anything that works,
then that's good. A lot worked this time. Like the same end-around
to Rocket that backfired so badly in New York, gained 19
second-quarter yards as the key play in a touchdown drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't get carried away with any pats on the back this week,
the same as I couldn't let the negative stuff brother me last
week,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   If possible, it'd be best to keep those priorities in order as a
hard stretch of schedule continues.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
