<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA'S LINEUP CHANGES DON'T WORK IN THE FIELD OR AT THE PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The thinking behind Braves Manager Bobby Cox's
decision to shake up his lineup was that perhaps inserting the
left-handed hitters Ozzie Guillen, hitting .250 in the post-season,
and Keith Lockhart, hitting .286, would kick-start a moribund
offense _ that had managed just one hit off the Game 1 starter
Orlando Hernandez _ against the right-hander David Cone, the Game 2
starter.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox could never have imagined that the two _ who between
them had made seven errors this season _ would inflict so much
damage in the field that there was no way they could make up for it
at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   As the Braves' offensive woes continue _ they have a total of
seven hits in the first two games of the World Series _ Cox is left
to revert to Plan A for Game 3: he will go back to his regular
lineup to face the left-hander Andy Pettitte. The one-day
experiment failed in the Yankees' 7-2 victory on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen was starting for the 46th time this season at shortstop
and that meant Walt Weiss, who started Game 1 and every game of the
championship series, would be on the bench. Lockhart, who was
making his 19th start at second base in replacing Bret Boone, is a
34-year-old who did not establish himself in the majors until he
was 30 and who is now used mainly as a pinch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Their personalities are as different as can be _ Guillen brash
and talkative, Lockhart reserved and soft-spoken. But both made
critical mistakes that contributed to the Yankees' rout that sends
the World Series to Yankee Stadium with the Braves down by two
games to none. Their abysmal play created a gaping hole in the
middle of the infield, and the Yankees stepped through it for two
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen, a major leaguer for 15 seasons, had made seven errors
playing shortstop this season and this was his first World Series
start. His error in the third inning was particularly painful to
watch, a routine catch turned to Little League farce. With the
Braves already trailing by 4-0 and two on and two out, David Cone
hit a 1-2 jammed liner to Guillen. The ball appeared to slice just
a bit as it neared him.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen lowered his glove to make an underhand catch, but _
whether the ball hit the tip of the glove or made no contact at
all, or if Guillen was blocked by Ricky Ledee going to third _ he
dropped it and Tino Martinez scored to extend the lead to 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball took a funny sink,'' Guillen said. ``I've missed
balls before. I will miss more balls. Why be embarrassed? I didn't
do anything bad. I didn't kill anyone. I didn't beat my wife. I
made a mistake and they scored. I played good. I made one
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cone popped out to Guillen in the fifth, the Braves fans
offered a mocking cheer for Guillen, which Guillen good-naturedly
accepted. ``They pay,'' he said, ``to do what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Guillen, who was batting second in the
order as part of Cox's plan to try to eke out a few more hits than
the Braves did against the Yankees in Game1, grounded into an
inning-ending double play in the bottom half of the third inning.
He went 0 for 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a good at-bat yet,'' Guillen said. ``We only
have one hit or two hits in a game. You're not going to win with
one hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart was only slightly better. He made no errors when he
started at second base this season. And he was not charged with an
error in the fourth, but his mistake led to another Yankee run
anyway. With Derek Jeter on third and Bernie Williams on first,
Martinez grounded to Guillen. He dropped to a knee to toss the ball
to Lockhart for the force on Williams at second base.
</P>
<P>
   But Lockhart had been expecting a simple underhand flip from
Guillen and he was caught off-guard when Guillen flung it at him.
As Lockhart turned to finish what seemed a sure double play, the
ball caught in his glove and Lockhart could not get a grip on it.
He finally removed it, but then threw the ball out of Ryan Klesko's
reach at first base. As the ball rolled to the screen in front of
the Braves' dugout, Jeter scored to put the Yankees ahead, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you why this is happening,'' Lockhart said
quietly, trying to explain why the normally fundamentally sound
Braves unraveled so rapidly. Lockhart did walk twice and scored one
of the runs in the ninth inning, but by then, in the near quiet of
a cleared out park, the Braves were already trying to figure out
why they had fallen into such a terrible funk.
</P>
<P>
   The doubt will linger into the off-day workout Monday, when the
Braves will take batting practice at Yankee Stadium, scrambling to
coax some hits before the series slips away without even one Braves
rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to work with some guys and see what's going on,''
Cox said. ``We're just honestly trying to score some runs right
now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
