<HEADER>
A7193 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     10-25 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGERS BLITZED BY PACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Welcome to the AFC West, the NFL's version of the
Pacific-10 Conference, where the only distinction is the size of
the paycheck and better parking privileges.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm day at Qualcomm before 68,274, many of whom came for
the cheese, the San Diego Chargers, leaders of the AFC West, threw
six interceptions and posted a rousing three points in a 31-3 loss
to the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   They did this despite having possession of the ball for 34 of
the game's 60 minutes, including 22 of the first 30. To say this
was a waste of time would be a waste of time if not for the
relevance to the rest of the AFC West and the Chargers' tradition
of offensive ineptness.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers remain atop the weakest division of Paul
Tagliabue's conglomerate with a 4-2 mark, tied with Kansas City and
Seattle and a half-length ahead of Oakland. They share this heady
space even though they've scored just one offensive touchdown or
less in their last three games.
</P>
<P>
   That stat is just one small part of a larger trend. In their
last 28 games dating back to the end of the 1997 season, the
Charger offense has been held to a touchdown or less 21 times. No
one from Duracell or Energizer is rushing to build an ad campaign
around this team.
</P>
<P>
   But then everyone in the AFC West shares a frailty, like the
Chiefs trying to win without a running game and the Raiders testing
fate game after game. The Charger quarterbacks are journeymen Erik
Kramer and Jim Harbaugh, but then so is everyone else in the AFC
West -- Elvis Grbac, Rich Gannon, Jon Kitna. Brian Griese is a
sophomore backed up by Bubby Brister.
</P>
<P>
   It is to the Chargers credit that there is no myopia in the
locker room, no delusions of adequacy. They realize they're blessed
to be in the west, where there are no quarterbacks like Brett Favre
and no team capable of running away from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in first place,'' said Junior Seau, the former
Trojan and Chargers' defensive leader. ``We lost to a team that's
better, and we realize that. I'm happy to be where we are. I don't
think anyone expected us to be (4-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``We put this offensive scheme together this summer, with a new
coach and two new quarterbacks. It's going to take a awhile to
jell. Right now, it doesn't look good. But it can get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Seau couldn't say that a year ago, when by now the Ryan Leaf era
had already fallen to earth like a scud and the team was in
tatters.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers are trying to win games with quarterbacks who have
sub-.500 career NFL resumes, Erik Kramer and Jim Harbaugh, but then
so are a dozen or so other teams. Those teams not blessed with a
Favre are either playing veterans with checkered pasts or rushing
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer threw four interceptions a week ago, but Chargers coach
Mike Riley decided to stick with the former Lion because the team
won, 13-10 over Seattle. Kramer threw three interceptions Sunday
and also gagged on a play at the end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Down 14-3 with six seconds left and no timeouts, he didn't throw
the ball away when pressured and was sacked. ``I tried to make
something out of nothing,'' he said. ``That was a poor decision
brought on by the previous interceptions. I wanted to get us back
in the game. I'm choking on my pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Charger fans had chanted for Harbaugh to replace Kramer before
that play. But head coach Mike Riley, the ex-USC aide who gave up
the security of the Oregon State job to coach in the NFL, waited
until it was 28-3 and the fourth quarter before switching to the
one-time Bear and Colt quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably waited too long,'' said Riley. ``But Jim hadn't
played for awhile and I thought we had a chance (with Erik).'' It
probably wouldn't have made a difference. When Harbaugh did come
in, his first pass was picked, and he had two more intercepted
before the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   The counterpoint to the Chargers trying to win Sunday with
relics from the NFC Central was Favre seizing every opportunity for
the Packers. This Green Bay team bears little resemblance to the
Packers team that played for Super Bowls a few years ago. These
Packers do not run the ball or defend like those teams.
</P>
<P>
   But Favre is enough. He completed 12 of 22 for 173 yards and
three touchdowns, slicing up the Chargers by running a fast-paced
offense and throwing the ball very quickly. In stark counterpoint
to the Chargers' inability to score more than a touchdown a game,
Favre has now thrown for two TDs or more in 57 of his last 80
games.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's start was his 115th in a row, and he will tie Ron
Jaworski's NFL record of 116 straight next week. The two active
quarterbacks with the longest streaks behind him aren't exactly
comparable -- Trent Dilfer (70) and Kordell Stewart (38).
</P>
<P>
   Favre was coming off his worst game as a pro last week in
Denver, but no one would know it by his play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very impressed with his quick release,'' said Riley.
``He gets rid of the ball very quickly and he has great composure.
We did some good things against him defensively, but he is so good
and difficult to stop, especially when you give him extra
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always anxious to play,'' said Favre. ``If you play
long enough, you're going to have a game when you can't do anything
right like last week, and games when you play great. You just keep
moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good advice for the Chargers. If it can work for
Stanford, why not the former Oregon State coach?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
