<HEADLINE>
KINGS HANG ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Kings scored. They fought. But
most of all Sunday night, they remembered how lousy it felt to get
embarrassed. They vowed there would not be a repeat of Friday
night's Phoenix meltdown against San Jose and proved it with a 4-3
victory over the league's hottest team.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings withstood a penalty shot and a late goal by the Sharks
that had the crowd of 15,270 at the Staples Center getting nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we came together for this game and we were not going to
lose it,'' said Luc Robitaille, who scored the 525th goal of his
career to pass Bryan Trottier for 21st all-time. ``We just knew
with all the hard work we had done since Phoenix that that wasn't
going to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Patrick Marleau made it a one-goal game with 2:36 to
play, Robitaille thought the biggest difference came in the final
minute of the second period when Kings goalie Stephane Fiset
stopped a penalty shot from Mike Ricci, a former teammate in Quebec
and Colorado. Fiset had been accused of throwing his stick at
Ricci's shot near the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (5-3-2) were leading 4-2 at the time. Against Phoenix,
they had a 3-1 lead and a power-play opportunity when the Coyotes
scored a short-handed goal and turned the game around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I faced him in practice for six years,'' said Fiset, who has
stopped five of eight penalty shots in his career. ``He never tried
to deke me, so of course he would try tonight. It was big for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   But several players said it was not as big as leaving Fiset in
goal after allowing three cheap goals against Phoenix. Coach Andy
Murray also had benched the first two lines for the final six
minutes of that game but played them Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big confidence boost for us,'' said Fiset, who will
get a rest Tuesday against Washington after playing all but one
period of the first 10 games. ``It showed that he believes in this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Kings losses had come after blowing leads, so
clearly they wanted to get on top Sunday and stay there.
</P>
<P>
   They took the lead just four minutes into the game on Bryan
Smolinski's second goal of the season, a blast from the point with
Andy Sutton off for elbowing. Just over five minutes into the
second period, seldom-used left-winger Dan Bylsma got his first of
the year after taking a pass from behind the net by Rob Blake.
</P>
<P>
   For Bylsma, who has played so little he was sent to minor-league
Long Beach for a game two weeks ago, it was his first goal since
the 1997-98 season. But he already had made an impression in this
game, flattening Gary Suter on a check at center ice midway through
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille then joined in, making it 3-0 with 10:49 remaining in
the second period. It was his eighth of the season but just his
first in five games.
</P>
<P>
   But after going 0-2-1 in their past three games, the Kings had
to maintain the pressure. Ricci cut it to 3-1 with a power-play
goal midway through the second, but the Kings came back with a goal
by Donald Audette, who stripped the puck from 19-year-old rookie
Brad Stuart and sailed it over the left shoulder of a sprawling
Sharks goalie Mike Vernon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
