<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR: SUCCESS IS ABILITY TO BOUNCE BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Kings general manger Dave Taylor
suffered along with the coaching staff after Friday night's 6-3
loss to Phoenix, but he also remembered why he hired them.
</P>
<P>
   In coach Andy Murray, he saw an skilled communicator who hadn't
been a head coach at the NHL level but had built a reputation in
handling players at the international level.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor knew that would be needed after Friday's game, when so
many Kings played poorly. Murray went to the whip after the game
but worked Saturday to rebuild the players' confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You aren't going to play well every night,'' Taylor said.
``There are 82 games. But you don't want a bad night turning into
bad habits.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was pleased when the Kings dominated play in the first
period Sunday and opened the second by killing off an Ian
Laperriere penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, those are signs the guys can come back from a bad
game,'' Taylor said. ``They didn't have much jump against Phoenix,
but they showed some grit against San Jose.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said one of the things he liked most about Murray _ who
was an assistant at Philadelphia, Winnipeg and Minnesota _ was his
philosophy on the power play. Murray liked to feed the big shot at
the point and keep his power-play unit intact.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a league-leading 31.4 percent success rating
(11 goals in 35 attempts). The Kings' first goal Sunday, by Bryan
Smolinski, came on the power play, as did their third, by Luc
Robitaille, midway through the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy keeps things simple and, with Rob Blake at the point, we
have the big shot,'' Taylor said. ``He wants his lines together. I
think guys play better the more they know each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Fight on: One of Murray's biggest points during Saturday's
workout was staying aggressive for an entire game. The Kings were
outshot 17-7 in the third period Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, defenseman Sean O'Donnell was whistled for two fighting
penalties. At one point midway in the second period, the Kings had
four players in the penalty box. O'Donnell was in for fighting,
Steve McKenna (roughing), Aki Berg (tripping) and Donald Audette
(tripping).
</P>
<P>
   Since one team cannot have more than a two-man advantage on the
ice, the Sharks played 5-3 and quickly scored on a goal by captain
Owen Nolan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
