<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GROGGY SANDERS, DEFENSIVE GEM GET THE ROYAL TREATMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ So there we all were in the postgame locker room
...
</P>
<P>
   The Reverend Do-Rag, Deion Sanders, clad only in his white bath
towel; me, in my J.C. Penney sportcoat; Owner Jones, grinning as if
he'd just eaten another canary; Prince Bandar of Saudi Arabia, the
franchise good-luck charm; Nelson Mandela, former president of
South Africa and the 1993 Nobel Peace Prize winner, and a gathering
assortment of media riff-raff and sweaty jockstraps.
</P>
<P>
   When you win, you see, life is good. Everybody, even Nobel Prize
winners, wants to hang around with you.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys won big yesterday, humbling the Washington Redskins,
38-20, in a game that smacked of redemption. Life was good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was absolutely lovely,'' Mandela said, as he worked the
room behind a small vanguard of security men. ``I thoroughly
enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   As fate would have it, the day featured only two awkward
moments. The first came when Sanders was smacked head-on silly by
Redskins special teamer Dan Turk, a blow that sent Prime Time
wobbling to the locker room. The second uncomfortable scene came
when somebody handed Mandela a tacky Cowboys ballcap to wear, which
he politely did.
</P>
<P>
   When you win, alas, you can get away with anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember half the game, but the offense played
great,'' announced Sanders, who claimed to still be woozy an hour
after the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Deion was only half-right. On this day, the Cowboys'
offense purred like a Lincoln, but the defense performed even
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get your butt beat, you want to come back and play
well,'' defensive coordinator Dave Campo explained.
</P>
<P>
   In the season opener at Washington, Campo's bunch had
surrendered 504 yards, including 382 through the air by quarterback
Brad Johnson. Their game-day successes since then had been laced
with asterisks left by lesser quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel, though, like our defense has been improving
from week to week,'' Campo contended.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back losses had not helped Campo's case. But he's right.
Since the track meet at Washington, the Cowboys' defense has
replaced cornerbacks Kevin Mathis and Charlie Williams with
veterans Sanders and Kevin Smith, who were both injured. In
addition, Alonzo Spellman, Darren Hambrick and Randall Godfrey are
no longer newcomers at their positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a very young defensive football team,'' Campo said. ``A
lot of people don't realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday, it didn't matter. The Cowboys held the Redskins
to 272 yards and forced them to struggle on third down. For the
home team, life was good.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the things that we talked about all week,''
linebacker Godfrey said. ``They were, I think, the No. 2 team in
the league in third-down conversions, and we knew we had to keep
their offense off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   To stop the Redskins on third down, Campo and his staff
emphasized stopping Johnson and the Norv Turner offense on first
down. Washington came into the game leading the NFL in average
yards gained on first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were converting about 40 percent on third down,'' Campo
went on. ``But we saw that a lot of those situations were
third-and-1, third-and-2 or that range. If we could get them into a
third-and-longer situation, we could have a chance to use some of
our coverage stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis worked. Toss out the Redskins' one long-gainer of
the day on first down, a 21-yard third-quarter pass, and the
Cowboys' defense held Washington to only a 2.6-yard average on
first down. The average third-down situation for the Redskins ended
up being third-and-7.
</P>
<P>
   The ``coverage stuff'' kept Johnson, for the most part, from
launching the bomb. Even when Sanders wobbled off the field, the
defense held together.
</P>
<P>
   His collision had cast an eerie silence over an already mute
crowd of 64,377. Back in the locker room, as the first half played
on, Sanders was approached by owner Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember me?'' Jones asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you're the guy who signs my checks,'' the Reverend
Do-Rag answered, apparently snapping to his senses.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders returned in the third quarter, and whatever bolts had
been loosened in his absence were swiftly tightened.
</P>
<P>
   In Jones' box, former President Mandela, Prince Bandar and
Jerry, the king of the Cowboys, looked on, obviously delighted.
</P>
<P>
   It was a grand day for the home team. It was a good day to host
royal guests.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great day for the defense to redeem itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were back in first place. No prizes _ yet. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7198 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-1     10-25 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES ROMP IN GAME 2 WITH 7-2 VICTORY OVER BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT22-37 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nobody uttered the words, but many of the Yankees were
thinking the same thing as they hauled their bats and gloves to the
clubhouse Sunday night after their 7-2 mauling of Atlanta in Game 2
of the World Series: remember 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how the Atlanta Braves won the first two games of the
World Series on the road that year, the way the Yankees have this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how dominant the Braves were in those games, as the
Yankees were here.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how the Yankees came back to win the final four games
of that World Series _ and, Joe Girardi and Jim Leyritz were
thinking, do not let it happen this year.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone allowed one hit in seven innings on Sunday night, as
Orlando Hernandez did in Game 1, and the Yankees have a
stranglehold on this World Series. They have won 10 straight games
in World Series play, 9 of 11 in this post-season. Atlanta totaled
seven hits in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   They also have Tom Glavine pitching Game 3 on Tuesday night in
Yankee Stadium, and then John Smoltz in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we're up against,'' Girardi said. ``They're very
capable, and we know that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves also are in deep, deep trouble; they tried a new
lineup on Sunday night and there wasn't any indication it would
make any difference against the Yankees' experienced starting
rotation. ``We didn't hit the ball last night,'' said Bobby Cox,
the Atlanta manager. ``We really didn't hit the ball tonight until
the ninth. We're just honestly trying to score some runs right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox went to Plan B for Game 2. Don Baylor, the Braves' hitting
coach, approached Keith Lockhart after Atlanta's defeat in Game 1
on Saturday and suggested that Lockhart stay ready because he might
play in Game 2. What Lockhart did not know was that Cox had been
planning major lineup changes.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had embarrassed the Braves' right-handed hitters with
his slider _ in particular second baseman Bret Boone, catcher Eddie
Perez and left fielder Gerald Williams. Knowing that Cone has a
similar approach to that of Hernandez, who throws his slider from
different angles to confound right-handed hitters, Cox stacked his
lineup with left-handed hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart started at second in place of Boone, who had 144 starts
during the regular season, Ozzie Guillen was the shortstop instead
of Walt Weiss and Greg Myers opened at catcher rather than Perez.
``We're just throwing it out there,'' Cox said, ``and seeing if
they won't change things.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some risk to Cox's strategy: Guillen and Lockhart are
inferior to Weiss and Boone on defense. But Cox could have assumed,
with much justification, that the shortcomings of his substitute
middle infielders would not have manifested themselves. Kevin
Millwood is a fly ball pitcher of the first order, who averaged
0.88 ground balls for every fly ball this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee, the Yankees' left fielder, studied videotape of
Millwood on Sunday afternoon, like a student cramming for a final
exam. What he saw was Millwood whipping his fastball at 93 to 95
miles an hour, overpowering hitters before dropping in his sharp
curveball or a slider.
</P>
<P>
   The Kevin Millwood who pitched on Sunday night was nothing like
the pitcher Ledee studied. His fastball in the first inning was 90
to 91 mph, his slider was inconsistent, he did not really use his
curveball. During the season, opponents hit just .102 against
Millwood with two-strike counts, but on Sunday night, he had no
weapons with which to finish off the Yankees' batters.
</P>
<P>
   And the Yankees were in a rare state of mind, some of them
furious after witnessing the tense interview Jim Gray of NBC
conducted with Pete Rose directly in front of their dugout before
the first inning. Paul O'Neill moved to shake Rose's hand after the
interview, and after the game, he and other Yankees were in a rage.
``You're talking about a man's life, his reputation,'' O'Neill
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if some of them focused that anger on the Braves.
Chuck Knoblauch, the first batter of the game, fell behind, no
balls and two strikes, and Millwood leaned back and pumped a high
fastball, a Neanderthal approach that might have been effective if
he had better stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch slammed a single into left-center field, and this
would be Millwood's pattern in the first inning. After Derek Jeter
pulled a single into left field _ the Yankees had first and second
and nobody out _ O'Neill fell behind, no balls and two strikes, and
fouled off three two-strike pitches before he hit a single to
center field, scoring Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams grounded into a double play, Jeter taking third,
and it appeared Millwood might get out of the inning allowing just
the one run. But Tino Martinez fell behind, one ball and two
strikes, and then smashed a line single to left, driving in Jeter.
Ledee drew a walk, and like those before him, Scott Brosius fell
behind no balls and two strikes, before grounding a ball toward the
middle, to the left of Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, the Braves' regular shortstop, might or might not have
reached the ball; Guillen did not, and Martinez scored as the slow
roller reached center field. The Braves had one hit in all of Game
1, they were facing a tough pitcher with a revamped lineup, and
they were behind by three runs before their first at-bat. Millwood
required 38 pitches to get through the first inning, and more
telling was the fact that of those, the Yankees' swung and missed
just one time.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood slogged through the second inning, throwing another 18
pitches. But Williams led off the third inning by falling behind in
the count, 1-2, then bouncing a ball to Lockhart's right, and past
him _ a ball Boone would have reached easily. Martinez singled and
Ledee crushed a double between the outfielders in left and center,
Williams racing home with the Yankees' fourth run. Terry Mulholland
relieved Millwood. ``I stunk,'' Millwood said later. ``I thought I
had pretty good stuff, I just couldn't get where I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, Cone was next, his hitter's senses dulled by
years of playing in the American League. But he waged a surprising
battle with Mulholland, fouling off five pitches; the Yankees would
foul off 24 pitches in the first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Then Cone reached out and poked a ball with the end of his bat,
the pain of imperfect contact slicing through his hands as his
little pop fly spun at Guillen. The Braves' backup shortstop took a
couple of steps to his right, held out his glove for an easy chance
_ and he dropped the ball. Martinez went across home plate; Yankees
5, Braves 0, and Cox put both hands on the top of his head in
frustration, in a Homer Simpson pose. Guillen and the Braves were
booed heavily as they ran off the field at the end of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   There were more follies. Jeter doubled to lead off the fourth
and took third on a fly ball. After the Braves intentionally walked
Williams, the Atlanta infield played back, looking for a double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Martinez grounded to Guillen, who flipped to
Lockhart, who bobbled the ball for a moment before stepping on
second and, in fear of losing the double play, fired the ball high
and wide of first baseman Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   More boos. The Yankees now were in command, 6-0, and half their
runs were a direct result of the play of the Braves' middle
infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been getting any hits, any runs,'' Lockhart said.
``Bobby tried to do something different. It didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans would begin quietly fleeing Turner Field and the cold
shortly thereafter, not hanging around to see the outcome of the
only remaining drama of the evening: could the Braves get a hit off
of Cone?
</P>
<P>
   Eligible for free agency after this season, Cone was pitching
perhaps his final game for the Yankees, and he stymied the Atlanta
left-handers with his split-fingered fastball. He was so very
careful, avoiding the middle of the plate even with the big lead.
He threw 35 pitches in the first three innings and only two were on
the inside half of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Cone pitched to the conditions. An outside slider to
Brian Jordan hung in the bottom of the first inning and the Braves'
cleanup hitter crushed a high drive to left field, certainly a home
run on most days. But the wind was gusting from left to right and
Jordan's fly fell about five feet short.
</P>
<P>
   Cone walked three batters in the first four innings, but Atlanta
had no hits. When Myers skipped a single through the middle to
start the fourth, the fans roared sarcastically, out of patience,
and maybe out of hope in the last World Series of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was replaced after seven innings, after striking out four
and allowing no runs. The Braves had three hits in the ninth inning
to improve their World Series average to .121, but the effect was
just cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees command the match-up now; they are in control. And
they remember 1996, vividly; it's all very clear, without words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say anything to my team,'' said Joe Torre,
the Yankees' manager. ``This game of baseball is very tough.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
