<HEADLINE>
ROSE IS STILL ROSE, HUSTLING THE SPORT HE LOVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the day of what could well be his last chance for
absolution from Major League Baseball, Pete Rose skipped an
early-afternoon news conference introducing the All-Century Team to
spend the morning at an Atlantic City casino.
</P>
<P>
   Not gambling, mind you. He was there signing photos and baseball
cards of himself at a card show.
</P>
<P>
   For a fee, naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie'' was hustling again.
</P>
<P>
   It's what he has been doing _ seemingly nonstop, if you've
caught his act on the Home Shopping Network _ for the past 10
years, since baseball handed him a lifetime suspension for gambling
on the game he loves so much while managing the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, as a prelude to Game 2 of the 1999 World Series,
Major League Baseball sold out to a popular credit-card company and
allowed Rose to bring his shell game back to the baseball diamond.
</P>
<P>
   A sold-out Turner Field greeted Rose's introduction with the
loudest and most-sustained ovation of the melodramatic event,
louder and longer than those for Babe Ruth, or wheelchair-bound Ted
Williams, or even favorite son Hank Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Rose cannot find his name on a Hall of Fame ballot, but he
remains solidly entrenched in the hearts of the common man, who
still fondly remembers ``Charle Hustle'' and his irrepressible zest
for the game.
</P>
<P>
   The music built to a crescendo, the fans roared, Jane Fonda
wiped tears from her cheeks and Rose's eyes moistened as he was
introduced with the other great outfielders of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   As heart-tugging as it seemed, it was not a shining moment for
baseball, which allowed itself to be used in a promotional gimmick
and broke its own rules in the process.
</P>
<P>
   As a suspended player, Rose is technically not allowed to
associate with anyone in baseball without that person also placing
himself at risk of suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig, your own case is now before you.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we decided to do this All-Century Team, we brought
together lists of the top 100 players taken from three different
sources,'' said Rich Levin, spokesman for the commissioner's
office. ``Pete Rose was on all three lists. So was Shoeless Joe
Jackson \Rsuspended for his participation in the Chicago Black Sox
scandal in 1919\S.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no thought of leaving either player off because of
their suspended status, Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   And so Rose came back to the ballpark last night, sanctioned by
the sport which won't officially acknowledge he even exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he'd get a huge ovation,'' Levin said, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   Rose arrived for his own pregame news conference flanked by his
nodding attorney on one side and his 15-year-old son, Tyler,
wearing a Yankees' cap, on the other. It's all part of the Pete
Rose Traveling Road Show, complete with well-rehearsed one-liners _
``I mean, Charles Manson gets a hearing once a year, doesn't he?''
_ and earnest declarations of his continued devotion to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, with his bad haircut, has become a caricature of himself,
a shill whose message has become shrill and tired. The act should
be well-polished; he has been practicing it on his syndicated radio
show for the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   No one questions Rose's love for the game. The only thing he
clearly loves more is himself.
</P>
<P>
   Braves bench coach and former Rangers manager Pat Corrales once
said that he never played with a more selfish player in his life
than Rose, but that was OK because Pete played the game to win.
</P>
<P>
   Things haven't changed much.
</P>
<P>
   Rose remains as self-centered as ever. It's not that his cause
isn't just or that he doesn't deserve to be in the Hall of Fame.
It's his tacky, I'm-going-to-be-me approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot help but like Pete Rose,'' said his old Big Red
Machine teammate Johnny Bench when the rest of the All-Century Team
gathered earlier in the day. ``Baseball rules is where the
separation is. Rules are rules, whatever your name is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in America, from the president on down, who's had a
problem has always said, `I'm sorry.' America loves to forgive and
forget. If that were enough to do it, I would almost beg and plead
that he do it. He shouldn't be short-changed from being in the Hall
of Fame if there's a way of getting around it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's at least part of the problem. Rose, as defiant as ever
even though baseball investigator John Dowd allegedly found betting
slips with his fingerprints on them, still semantically waltzes
around the issue of remorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is not going to hear me say, `I'm sorry,' '' Rose
said defensively. ``Do you honestly think I'm glad this happened?
Does Johnny?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would do anything in my power to change what has happened to
me in the last 10 years. You know how I feel. You know I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, being sorry for what has happened to him doesn't
necessarily translate into regrets over breaking baseball's
most-sacred taboo. Rose has never publicly admitted to gambling on
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're ticklish about gambling,'' Rose admitted. ``I know
that as well as anybody. More than anybody, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   He has never, Rose said before the event, met or even talked to
Selig, who has steadfastly refused to review the suspension handed
down by the late Bart Giamatti 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That could change if Selig decides to suspend himself. He and
``Charlie Hustle'' will suddenly have a lot in common. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
