<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP FUEL LEADER SCHUMACHER ENDS DROUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENNIS, Texas _ Second-generation drag racer Tony Schumacher made
sure that he will not be the second answer to a National Hot Rod
Association trivia question at the Texas Motorplex yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   And now the only question facing Schumacher during the season's
stretch run is this: Can he win the NHRA's prestigious Top Fuel
championship in his first full season?
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher took care of the trivia when he defeated Scott
Kalitta, a former two-time Top Fuel champion, in the final of the
14th annual O'Reilly Fall Nationals. Rob Bruins failed to win a
race en route to the 1979 NHRA Top Fuel title. He remains the only
professional champion never to have visited Victory Lane during the
course of his title-winning campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A nonwinner in eight previous final-round appearances stretching
back to the summer of 1998, Schumacher covered the all-concrete
Motorplex quarter-mile in 4.621 seconds and 323.39 mph in the Exide
Batteries Dragster to defeat Kalitta. The race's No. 1 qualifier,
Kalitta slowed to 5.072 seconds at 205.62 mph after giving
Schumacher a race up to halftrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird because I saw him at half track, and I went,
`What, are you joking?''' said Schumacher, of Park Ridge, Ill.
``And all of a sudden he disappeared _ and that was really cool. I
went around him, and that's it. You're done. We ran 323, so if I'm
an inch ahead of you, you're not catching me at that point. That's
what makes it cool. Love it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Schumacher was busy clutching his first NHRA Oscar,
multiple-champions John Force and Warren Johnson were adding to
their considerable hardware collections. Force won the Funny Car
final over Tommy Johnson Jr. after clinching his record ninth
Winston championship _ and seventh in a row _ earlier in the
afternoon. Only the retired Bob Glidden, with 10 Pro Stock titles,
has won more NHRA championships than ``Brute'' Force. The victory
was the 80th in Force's career, five behind Glidden's all-time
record.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, meanwhile, claimed his fifth career Pro Stock title and
second in a row with a victory over former two-time series champion
Jim Yates. Johnson, of Sugar Hill, Ga., also posted his 79th career
victory in the GM Goodwrench Pontiac Firebird, third all-time
behind Glidden and Force.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher began this meet with a 20-point lead over five-time
series champion Joe Amato. That translates into one round of
racing. Amato was eliminated in the second round by Doug Kalitta,
Scott's cousin, leaving Schumacher with an 81-point lead heading
into the Matco Tools Supernationals at Houston Raceway Park in
Baytown next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The season-ending NHRA Finals are scheduled for Pomona (Calif.)
Raceway on Nov. 11-14.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher, 29, is the son of Don Schumacher, one of drag
racing's most successful Funny Car drivers when he retired in 1974.
The elder Schumacher and his team made their debut at the U.S.
Nationals over Labor Day weekend in 1998. A little over a year
later, they are poised to shock the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Force, of Yorba Linda, Calif., clinched his title when teammate
Tony Pedregon was eliminated by Whit Bazemore's Kendall Chevrolet
Camaro Z/28 in the second round. Force commiserated briefly with
his teammate, but added that overall it had been a great day for
John Force Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking I'll never make it to the press room,'' said
Force, referring to the winner's postrace news conference. But
Force ran 4.827 seconds at 319.60 mph in the Castrol GTX Ford
Mustang. Johnson, who learned Friday that owner Joe Gibbs' team was
losing its sponsorship from Interstate Batteries at season's end,
ran 4.843 seconds/319.82 mph. That made it the quickest
side-by-side race in Funny Car history.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
