<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOP100-NICKLAUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP 100 COUNTDOWN, NO. 68: `OLDEN BEAR' LOOKS GOLDEN IN WINNING
1986 MASTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crowd at the Augusta National Golf Club roared. But the Bear
roared louder.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus had earned the nickname The Golden Bear with 17
victories in the majors and two U.S. Amateur titlesheading into the
1986 Masters, but the last of them had come six years earlier, when
he had won the U.S. Open and PGA Championship at age 40.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Nicklaus had won only twice, leading to the
conclusion that he could no longer compete at the highest level.
His 1980 victories were considered a heroic last hurrah from one of
the game's greatest players. So sure of this were the pundits that
the week before the Masters, an Atlanta newspaper mockingly
referred to the 46-year-old Nicklaus as The Olden Bear and said his
chances of winning his record sixth green jacket were all but nil.
</P>
<P>
   After two rounds, there was little room for argument. Nicklaus
shot 74 and 71, good enough to stick around for the weekend, but
hardly in contention. And while his 69 on Saturday pleased the
crowd and left him four shots behind leader Greg Norman, Nicklaus
was not on anybody's list of serious contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Eight holes into Sunday's final round, Nicklaus, still at 2
under par, trailed Seve Ballesteros by six shots. Suddenly, he
found his touch. He birdied nine, 10 and 11, and the large gallery
that always followed the Bear began to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   After a bogey at 12, Nicklaus dropped in another birdie at 13
and then drilled a 202-yard 4-iron to within 12 feet on the par-5
15th. When he holed the putt for eagle to move within two shots of
Ballesteros, the crowd erupted in cheers that could be heard in
every corner of the Augusta course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so loud,'' Norman said, ``it made the U.S. Open seem
like playing around a graveyard.''
</P>
<P>
   It was soon to get louder. While Ballesteros was hitting into
Rae's Creek on 15, Nicklaus hit the shot of the day at the par-3
16th, missing a hole-in-one by inches. After another birdie, he
shared the lead and it seemed the entire population of Augusta was
screaming in delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from the tee to the green it was actually deafening,''
Nicklaus said. ``The people were absolutely unbelievable. I
couldn't hear a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A birdie at 17 put Nicklaus in front by himself, and when he had
finished his 65 _ including a record-tying 30 on the back nine _ he
was escorted to the Bobby Jones Cabin to watch the challengers take
their best shots. One by one they fell away. Ballesteros bogeyed
17. Tom Kite, needing a birdie at 18 to force a playoff, left a
12-foot putt short.
</P>
<P>
   And Norman, who had fallen back early but charged down the
stretch with four consecutive birdies to grab a share of the lead,
hit his second shot on 18 into the gallery and wound up needing a
16-footer for par to tie. His putt slid past, leaving Nicklaus atop
the golf world again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I was done, washed up, through, that I had no
chance,'' Nicklaus said. ``I was thinking all week, `So I'm washed
up, huh?' Something like that can really spur you on. ... I think I
showed today that occasionally I can still play this game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7206 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     10-25 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRECEDENCE ASIDE, TYSON WON'T BE DISQUALIFIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mike Tyson probably didn't mean it and will get his
$10 million, Orlin Norris is injured and boxing _ such as it is _
goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada State Athletic Commission will review Saturday's
debacle, which ended as a ``no contest'' when Tyson landed a punch
after the bell and Norris injured his right knee when he fell.
</P>
<P>
   However, don't expect the commission to overturn referee Richard
Steele's ruling that the punch was an ``accidental foul'' and
disqualify or suspend Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Ratner, the director of the commission, said the governing
body has that power but intimated that such a move is highly
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   So, you get what you got: a mess.
</P>
<P>
   Norris, who dislocated his kneecap, an MRI revealed, believes
the punch was unintentional and that Tyson likely didn't hear the
bell, as he contends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an intense first round,'' he said. ``We both were
throwing punches and fighting out of the round's final clinch. It
was also very noisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly feel that Mike did not foul me intentionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is precedent to DQ Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Norris' own brother, Terry Norris, was disqualified twice
against Luis Santana, once for a punch after the bell and once for
hitting Santana in the back of the head.
</P>
<P>
   Another example is Roy Jones Jr., who was DQed when he punched
Montell Griffin when Griffin's knee was on the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Were their indiscretions more malicious than that of Tyson, who
hit Norris with a left hook a good two seconds after the bell to
end an uneventful first and only round?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, not.
</P>
<P>
   However, again, the commission will be reluctant to overturn
what is a judgment call by the referee and create a bigger mess in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   That means Tyson's $10 million, which was withheld pending the
hearing on Thursday, probably will be turned over to him and the
fighters will move on with their careers.
</P>
<P>
   For Norris, that could be a while.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken to a local hospital for an MRI. He returned to his
hotel 2{ hours later on crutches and in pain, according to adviser
Michael Marley.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, ring doctor Flip Homansky confirmed what he believed
immediately after the fight: That Norris' knee !ital!had!off! been
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MRI clearly shows the path his kneecap took when he went
to the ground,'' Homansky said. ``When he stood up, it popped back
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way he could have continued. He very well might
need surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless Homansky is wrong, that would seem to refute Tyson's
claims that Norris threw the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son was hurt. He's no quitter,'' said Orlin Norris Sr., the
fighter's father.
</P>
<P>
   Norris' handlers were reluctant to talk until after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, they'd love a rematch and the money that goes with
it. Norris made $800,000 for his three-minute's work and presumably
would command a similar payday if the fighters meet again.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Woodworth, Norris' manager, said he would withhold comment
``until all the legal ramifications are taken care of,'' the
implication being he wants to do everything possible to force a
rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Goossen, Tyson's promoter, said immediately after the fight
that a rematch was a possibility but later backed off, saying it
was important to sort out this mess before making any plans.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is tentatively scheduled to fight Shannon Briggs on Feb.
26 at Madison Square Garden in New York, but no official
announcement has been made.
</P>
<P>
   What can we expect in that one? When Tyson's involved, anything.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incident was remarkably bizarre _ but no one was
terribly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous two fights, he chewed on the ears of Evander
Holyfield and admitted he tried to break the arm of Francois Botha
in a clinch.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the biggest gamble in Las Vegas is buying a ticket to
see Tyson fight.
</P>
<P>
   Ask anyone who paid to see Saturday's fight. Never has there
been a more disgusted group of sports fans, who let their disdain
be known with boos and expletives until well after the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Said one frustrated woman: ``They have to give us a refund,
don't they?''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, no. That's boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement?: Tyson's postfight comments about leaving the sport
were made in frustration. Obviously, he believes the world has
stuck it to him one more time.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked why he was penalized two points for the late
punch, he said, ``Because I'm Mike Tyson.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he won't retire just yet.
</P>
<P>
   He knows this is the only way he can make this kind of money; he
must pay off debts and provide for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Clarification: The fact that Steele took points from Tyson is
consistent with the ``accidental foul'' ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Fighters lose points all the time on fouls they don't mean to
commit.
</P>
<P>
   Down and out?: Robert Garcia had always said he'd retire if he
lost a fight. He's talked about returning to school and starting
another career, possibly as a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's not so sure. He doesn't want to go out this way.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxnard resident was brutally knocked out by Diego Corrales
in the seventh round on the Tyson-Norris undercard to lose his IBF
junior lightweight championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to prove I'm not a quitter,'' he said Sunday morning.
``Great fighters lose, they come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll try to get a shot at another world title. I just
want to talk to my family first.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who was winning the bout against the 6-foot Corrales
through five rounds, couldn't pinpoint exactly what went wrong
after that. He went down three times from right hands, the last
time for good.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested he left himself open to punches after he missed his
own shots, but settled on a more simple explanation. ``Hey, he
caught me with a good shot. That's boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another debacle: It was an unfortunate weekend for boxing.
</P>
<P>
   The night before Tyson-Norris, Naseem Hamed and Cesar Soto
turned a promising featherweight matchup into a pathetic wrestling
match in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed should've been disqualified for flipping Soto in the fifth
round. If nothing else, fans in Detroit and watching TV would've
been spared the remainder of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   On the same card, junior featherweights Erik Morales and Wayne
McCullough engaged in a thrilling brawl.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't terribly competitive; Morales won handily. However,
the fighters were willing to take punches to give them, and it made
for an exciting show.
</P>
<P>
   Morales is probably the fighter who can beat Hamed if the
overrated Englishman has the guts to face him.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough doesn't have the power to become a great fighter but
his courage and determination should be a lesson to other fighters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
