<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHOUSE-BCS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILL OUT, FOLKS, BCS STANDINGS DON'T MEAN MUCH NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perfect. The first edition of the 1999 Bowl Championship Series
rankings will be announced at halftime of tonight's
Atlanta-Pittsburgh (yech!) ``Monday Night Football'' game. This
marriage of pro and college football is brought to you by ABC
Sports, which is engaging in typical TV cross promotion (it's the
home of the BCS).
</P>
<P>
   The BCS rankings, which incorporate the writers and coaches
polls, eight computer ratings, strength of schedule and won-loss
record, will be used for the second consecutive year to determine
who plays for the national title. Being No. 2 is as important as
being No. 1, so there will be considerable interest in the debut
list.
</P>
<P>
   And here's why this is such a super, synergistic coupling: Just
over a month into the NFL season, it's obvious there is no domiant
team. And with just over a month to go, it's just as apparent there
is no true No. 1 team in college football.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Florida State is No. 1 and will stay there after a 17-14
victory over Clemson in a family feud. But the Seminoles certainly
have not been running roughshod over Division I-A foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we played like No. 1,'' Florida State coach
Bobby Bowden said. ``But whoever's No. 2 probably didn't play like
No. 2 either.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Penn State, which survived four Drew Brees passes
that would have given Purdue an upset victory. Clearly, it doesn't
matter where a team is ranked; every game is a landmine.
</P>
<P>
   Last season turned into a three-month playoff that ended with a
dramatic final Saturday. This season is shaping up the same way.
Florida State, Penn State, Virginia Tech, Kansas State and
Mississippi State are the remaining undefeated teams hoping for a
chance to play in the Sugar Bowl on Jan. 4. Tennessee and Florida
each have one loss but are still in the hunt. Georgia Tech and
Nebraska are one-loss long shots.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech and Tennessee will have particular interest in BCS
Version 1.
</P>
<P>
   The defending champion Volunteers (5-1) are sneaking into
position for a title run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a new motto: Why not us?'' said Tennessee coach
Phillip Fulmer, who has won six of his past seven games against Top
10 opponents. ``You look around the country, and there may not be a
great football team or one dominant team. Why can't we take this
thing?''
</P>
<P>
   Who knew that when Tennessee lost at Florida that it was
advantage, Volunteers. Tennessee could wind up finishing second in
the Southeastern Conference East division and still play in the
Sugar Bowl. Florida, which has tough games with Georgia and Florida
State remaining, could face a rematch with Alabama in the SEC
championship game. And speaking of rematches, a Tennessee-Florida
national title game in the Sugar Bowl is not out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know where, but we should be ranked up there,''
Tennessee senior quarterback Tee Martin said after his team's 21-7
victory over Alabama. ``You never know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies (6-0) are in prime position to finish undefeated. The
question is Virginia Tech's strength of schedule. It opened the
season with a victory over Division I-AA James Madison. Plus, the
Hokies play Miami and Boston College, teams whose schedule strength
will be diminished because of games against I-AA teams. And, the
Big East Conference's overall weakness likely will effect Virginia
Tech's computer profile.
</P>
<P>
   And now time for a plea of sanity. For the rest of the season,
there will be hours of talk show and inches of newspaper copy
produced about the system's inequities, debating the pros and cons,
the whys and the why nots. Take a chill pill, folks. It doesn't
matter where a team is BCS-ranked on Oct. 25 or Nov. 15. All that
matters is which teams are No. 1 and No. 2 on Dec. 5 when the final
BCS poll is released.
</P>
<P>
   That's why they play the games. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
