<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXYNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. COOLS ITS HEELS AWAITING OPPONENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Los Angeles Galaxy's 2-0 sweep of Colorado gives
coach Sigi Schmid a full week to prepare for the Western Conference
finals, which starts at 2:30 p.m. Sunday at the Rose Bowl against
either Chicago or Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid hopes Chicago and Dallas beat each other up in
Wednesday's third and deciding game at the Cotton Bowl. Dallas won
the first game 1-0, and Chicago evened the series with a 4-0
triumph Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just played a tough series with Colorado,'' Schmid said.
``When you play a series like this you have people banged up. We
can use the extra rest. Now we can watch Dallas and Chicago kick
the (heck) out of each other for a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Double duty: Galaxy striker Carlos Hermosillo's MLS contract
will expire Sunday. When the MLS signed Hermosillo to a two-year
contract, the league expected the MLS championship to be completed
in October. For the first time, the championship will be played in
November, meaning Hermosillo becomes Necaxa's property Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Not worried, Schmid said everything will be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have already come to an arrangement with all the
appropriate parties,'' Schmid said.
</P>
<P>
   Franchino's first: Joey Franchino scored the first MLS goal of
his career in Sunday's victory. Franchino was a 79th-minute
insertion and scored in the 84th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in thinking defense to solidify the 1-0 lead,'' he
said. ``I was fortunate to get a goal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7211 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-HNS &LR;      10-25 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Dom or the cheap stuff?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Broadway or Park Avenue?
</P>
<P>
   Those decisions are the challenges awaiting the New York Yankees
when they return home, presumably to put an end to this World
Series charade. What about the Atlanta Braves?
</P>
<P>
   At this point, they hardly warrant concern. The Braves barely
showed up in Sunday's 7-2 loss in Game 2. The Yankees took a 2-0
lead in the best-of-seven series, which shifts to New York for the
next three scheduled games, beginning Tuesday at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we took a little wind out of their sails,'' Yankees
starter David Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe they totally deflated the Braves, who have lost six
consecutive World Series games _ all to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   New York ripped Braves starter Kevin Millwood for three runs in
the first inning and two in the third, immediately zapping any
suspense from the game. Meanwhile, Cone was having his way with the
Braves' hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Cone pitched four no-hit innings and the first seven innings of
a combined five-hitter with relievers Ramiro Mendoza and Jeff
Nelson. The Braves have only seven hits in the first two games of
the Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't hit many balls hard at all,'' Braves hitting
instructor Don Baylor said. ``They've shut us down. We've had
periods of inconsistency like this before. You can get by with it
in the middle of the regular season, but they (the Yankees) are two
games away from a world title. We're running out of time.''
</P>
<P>
   While a two-game deficit isn't exactly a death sentence for a
team with the Braves' pitching, the New Yorkers wouldn't be out of
line if they've already placed the champagne order, mapped out a
parade route and refamiliarized themselves with the riot-control
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves may not be totally done, but they're certainly
starting to brown on both sides. On Sunday, they added poor
pitching and sloppy defense to their real poison _ the lack of any
semblance of offense _ forming a deadly concoction.
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox benched his best defensive infielders
in favor of more offense. The result was a few Yankees singles that
made it through the infield only because of the declining range of
Ozzie Guillen and Keith Lockhart, neither of whom added an ounce of
spark to the Braves' offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like no matter where I was playing, the ball was
always a little bit out of reach,'' said Lockhart, who started at
second base. ``The Yankees were finding all of the holes. When a
team is hitting the ball well, that's what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who extended their World Series winning streak to
10 games dating to 1996, pounded out 14 hits. At their current
rate, the Braves won't collect their 14th hit of the Series until
Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were gracious hosts to the MasterCard All-Century
Team prior to Sunday's game. Perhaps MasterCard could return the
favor by letting the Braves have a few hits on credit. The NL
champions apparently exceeded their limit somewhere around the
Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' Cox said. ``We kept waiting to get
something going. David kept the ball down; he had breaking stuff.
He wasn't overpowering at all. He didn't throw that hard, but his
ball was sinking like crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   With a .202 opponents' batting average during the regular
season, Millwood was the toughest pitcher to hit against in the
Senior Circuit. The Yankees, who have won 20 of their last 23
postseason games, weren't impressed.
</P>
<P>
   They treated Millwood like a pitching machine in one of those
interactive arcades, dialing up five runs on eight hits in two
innings plus against the young righthander.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the first seven Yankees reached base against Millwood,
who didn't have his usual pinpoint command from the very beginning.
Paul O'Neill, Tino Martinez and Scott Brosius each had RBI singles
in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood appeared to settle down after the second, but it was
only an illusion. The Yankees tagged him for three consecutive hits
to lead off the third, including an RBI double by Ricky Ledee, who
essentially ended Millwood's night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Kevin was kind of in the middle of the plate where he
shouldn't have been,'' Cox said. ``It was all a matter of location.
He got right in that area that's good to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was almost as if the Braves had two starting pitchers,
considering Terry Mulholland began warming up in the bullpen in the
first inning before eventually replacing Millwood in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees added a fifth run in the third when Guillen dropped
a soft liner _ it would have been the third out of the inning _
allowing Martinez to score from third. Chuck Knoblauch's RBI single
gave the Yankees a seven-run lead in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Greg Myers, who had two of the Braves' five hits, broke
up the Yankees' shutout with a two-out RBI single off Mendoza in
the ninth. Nelson, who served up a pinch-hit RBI double to Bret
Boone, notched the final out to secure the victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-25 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ For the Yankees, it was like a living tribute to the
greatest names in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   To the Babe and Joltin' Joe. To the Iron Horse. To the Mick and
Yogi.
</P>
<P>
   Of all those great Yankees, only Yogi Berra was at Turner Field
on Sunday night when the game's All-Century Team was honored before
Game 2 of the World Series. But it also was as if they all were
there.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet swings. Pitching flawlessly. Showing classic Yankees
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if echoes from those unforgettable days bounced off
the rafters of Turner Field and reverberated into the hearts of
these 1999 Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone was dominant and gritty. Derek Jeter and Scott
Brosius were virtually unstoppable and clutch. Bernie Williams and
Tino Martinez carried powerful and mighty sticks.
</P>
<P>
   The defense was impeccable, the hitting timely and the onslaught
relentless.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees just kept coming, like blasts from the past, and
buried the Braves for the second night in a row, this time 7-2, to
take a 2-0 World Series edge.
</P>
<P>
   But the most enlightening image of the night wasn't only the
Yankees falling into a groove for the ages, but the Braves
continuing to fade and droop.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if the Braves' night also was dedicated to one of
baseball's greatest names _ one that didn't quite make it to the
All-Century Team but epitomized this night and what the Series has
become.
</P>
<P>
   Enos Slaughter. The Braves were. Slaughtered, that is.
</P>
<P>
   And now might be a good time to abridge all World Series
predictions: Yanks in two. It's over; the rest is details.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees all but clinched this final Series of the 1900s with
a classic show of pinstripe dominance, chasing Braves ace Kevin
Millwood early while hammering out 14 hits and looking unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   With the Series returning to New York and the potentially
dominant Andy Pettitte and Roger Clemens scheduled to start Games 3
and 4, it looks like a question not of if, but of when.
</P>
<P>
   The only intriguing questions remaining in this Series might be
these: Will the Braves get swept? And will Pete Rose deck NBC
reporter Jim Gray if the two cross paths between here and the
Bronx?
</P>
<P>
   Little did we know Sunday night that the most heated showdown we
would see would be the pre-game exchange between Gray and Rose
during an interview about Rose's lifetime baseball ban.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have been meek from the start of this Series, and no
one has epitomized the uncharacteristic instability more than
manager Bobby Cox. Usually steady and true with his moves, Cox has
seen almost everything he has done backfire.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Cox started young talent Millwood, hoping Millwood could
win in front of the home crowd and leaving the playoff-tested Tom
Glavine and John Smoltz for the hostile confines of Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Millwood didn't make it out of the third inning, giving up
five runs on eight hits and all but clinching the Yanks' 10th
consecutive win in the World Series _ six in a row over the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Cox also tried to shake up the lineup for Sunday's game, with
equal success. After the Braves could muster just two hits in the
Game 1 loss, Cox inserted Ozzie Guillen, Keith Lockhart and Greg
Myers into the lineup instead of defensive whiz Walt Weiss,
National League Championship Series hero Eddie Perez and Bret
Boone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just trying to find some offense,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   But he lost probably his best defensive infielder with the move
_ Weiss _ and it cost the Braves dearly when Guillen committed a
huge gaffe in the third inning. Guillen dropped a soft liner off
Cone's bat that could have ended a jam but only made it worse.
Guillen also went oh-fer on the night offensively, as did Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a bad game. We got beat up,'' Cox said. ``We're a
team of good pitching and timely hitting and didn't get it. It's
frustrating, but I don't know if it's helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   It is. There are those who will tell you this burning of Atlanta
can be reversed with just a few more tweaks by Cox and some better
luck. They'll remind you of the 1996 World Series, when the Braves
hammered out a couple of wins at Yankee Stadium, then lost four in
a row.
</P>
<P>
   But this Series is all but over because the Yanks' 2-0 edge not
only sapped the life out of the Braves but sent them looking for
answers that aren't there.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees pitchers have proved to be better than their Braves
counterparts. Pettitte and Clemens should continue the trend.
Offensively, the Yanks have dominated without falling into a big
groove.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have not hit a home run in the Series, and nothing
but singles accounted for their first six runs of the two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really completely happy with how we've played,''
Yankees manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the scary part.
</P>
<P>
   This thing is over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
