<HEADER>
A7214 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-BARKLEY-H     10-25 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-BARKLEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ The party was for Charles Barkley, but he gave
away the presents.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``No, nothing, I don't want anything,'' Barkley said of the
rocking chairs and fishing rods that so often accompany the sort of
farewell tours that he began Sunday. ``I've got everything. There's
no use giving me anything. I don't need any more.''
</P>
<P>
   So to mark the occasion of his official retirement announcement
Sunday, Barkley dropped off parting gifts before beginning the end
of his career. He gave $1 million each to his scholarship funds at
Leeds (Ala.) High School and Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   He gave another $1 million for a scholarship at the Cornerstone
School, an inner-city school in Birmingham. And with his return to
play after four games resting a sore elbow, he helped give the
Rockets a 98-96 win over the Detroit Pistons that they admitted,
even in the preseason, they had to have.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had to rally from eight points back in the final
four minutes against the Pistons' guests from the Yakima Sun Kings.
But that hardly mattered. With the preseason-closing games against
the Spurs to come this week, the Rockets avoided slipping to a
worrisome 1-5. And a victory allowed a night devoted to celebrating
Barkley's career to end happily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a win,'' Rockets center Kelvin Cato said. ``We
needed to come together and have something positive. Everybody's
played well, but we haven't played well together. And it was great
to see Chuck get a win on his day. But he's not gone yet. We'll
talk about it after 82 games and the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact of Barkley's return was obvious from the outset. He
had nine assists, five before taking his first shot, and nine
rebounds. He made five of eight shots for 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to have Charles back,'' Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ``He really does make a difference. His
experience is invaluable. His passing _ he's such a complete
player. With his retirement, it was good to see someone honor him.
He's done so much for the league. I always enjoyed watching him
play because of his passion. I like the guy so much, I want to see
him get his due.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley said he has gotten all he wants, more than he ever
expected. He said he cannot imagine how even the NBA championship
that has eluded him could enrich his life. For that matter, he did
not know how he could be happier.
</P>
<P>
   But he plans to try to find out.
</P>
<P>
   He said Sunday he is negotiating to purchase a private jet. He
plans to take golf lessons and then to play four hours of golf a
day to finally get his first victory over Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks about you like a dog when he beats you,'' Barkley
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has considered several film roles, having decided the
situation comedy and talk-show offers that have been floated would
require too much work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'd like to do some acting,'' Barkley said. ``Some
(of the roles) are interesting. Some are terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he is still considering running for governor of Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to advance people,'' he said. ``I don't think God
gave me this gift so I can play basketball, have $50 million in the
bank and live happily ever after. It's good to have that. Don't get
me wrong. But there's more to life.''
</P>
<P>
   He even revealed his more immediate hopes to purchase an NBA
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could get one for a couple hundred million,'' he said,
``that would be a bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would not want to purchase a team with Jordan, who
negotiated to buy the Charlotte Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I would have to do what Michael tells me,'' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Jordan would be the controlling partner, Barkley
simply said, ``Because he's Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Birmingham on Sunday, Barkley was the conquering hero
returned home. He was surrounded at a halftime ceremony by his
mother, Chauncey Glenn, his grandmother, Johnnie Mae Mickens, his
high school coach, Billy Copeland, and college coach, Sonny Smith.
</P>
<P>
   He was presented with a permanent plaque to be displayed in the
Birmingham-Jefferson Convention Complex. Birmingham Mayor William
Bell gave him a key to the city and declared the day ``Charles
Barkley Day.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Barkley made his retirement decision official.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to announce that this is going to be my last season
here in Birmingham,'' Barkley told the crowd. ``You guys have been
with me from the beginning. Everybody else sort of jumped on the
bandwagon along the way. I appreciate everybody behind me for
really the last 19 years. I got a great opportunity being born in
Leeds. The people at Auburn were terrific to me, and the people of
Alabama have been great to me. Now I'm honored to finish my career
playing for the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sadness in my mind or my voice. I mean it's time to
do something else. I'm going to have some fun now.''
</P>
<P>
   Tense in the first half, but with that out of the way, he seemed
to begin having fun in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   And though the Rockets continued to struggle _ they had 32
turnovers, including 11 by Steve Francis; they made just 42.1
percent of their shots _ they led by 15 early, came back to win
late and celebrated a favorite son throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was emotional because I had a lot of family and friends
here tonight,'' Barkley said. ``Tonight was very stressful for me.
Tonight's the last time I am going to talk about the retirement
this year. I am going to get it over with. I'm glad it's out of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stressful. I made the decision to go out and say it
with my family and friends there. Now, it's over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
