<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7221 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BOX-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     10-25 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LAS VEGAS _ Somebody once said boxing was theater with blood. In
these desperate times, one might say the sport is more of a Three
Stooges routine without the deep intellectual meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Pierce Brosnan, the current big-screen portrayer of
James Bond, had it right as he rose from his ringside seat and
stalked out of the MGM Grand's Grand Garden Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a joke!'' sniffed 007.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mike Tyson's latest misadventures Saturday night once
more left the fight crowd shaken, not stirred.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd grumbled. The crowd booed. The tense scene might have
gotten uglier if the ring hadn't quickly been filled by a greater
police presence than eventually caught up to Bonnie and Clyde.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you thought boxing had run out of eyes, Tyson managed
to blacken yet another one. He cheated everyone. Again.
</P>
<P>
   What he did was write another ugly, pathetic chapter in a
rapidly declining career that is marked by a succession of
controversies rather than a string of knockouts.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson clipped Orlin Norris with a left after the bell to end the
first round. Tyson claimed he did not hear the bell. But it is
difficult to believe he did not see referee Richard Steele, who had
his body between the two fighters when Tyson reached over his
shoulder to deliver the blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just tired of the bull,'' Tyson said later.
</P>
<P>
   Aren't we all?
</P>
<P>
   Before the fight, Tyson virtually bragged, ``Nobody else could
have as many comebacks as me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the question is, Who else would need so many?
</P>
<P>
   But when you're using the prime time of your career making a
tour of the nation's prison facilities, abusing wives, raping
beauty-pageant contestants, kicking and punching strangers and
attempting to mutilate your opponents in the ring, there seems to
always be another hill of perceived persecution to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Could there be something in the air at the MGM Grand _ the roar
of the lions? _ that brings out the animal in Tyson?
</P>
<P>
   It was in the very same ring in June 1997 where Tyson lost
whatever aura of invincibility and any remaining respect as an
athlete he had when he bit off a piece of Evander Holyfield's right
ear, then went back a short time later to snack on his left ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once is bad enough,'' said referee Mills Lane on that night.
``But twice is dessert.''
</P>
<P>
   This time around Lane, in his role as an analyst for Fox,
happened to be sitting to my immediate left when Tyson crossed the
line again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always some damn thing with this guy,'' Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes. It was January of this year, in yet another comeback fight,
when Tyson grabbed Francois Botha by the arm during a clinch and,
he later admitted, tried to break it. The first time he got into a
clinch with Norris on Saturday night, Tyson ignored Steele's
instructions to break and instead threw a punch that drew a
warning.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the main story line of the fight was whether
Tyson could return to the brawling form of his heyday in the early
'90s and end the fight with Norris in a minimum amount of time. But
nobody in the audience could have expected a three-minute bout
would end up following one more twisted path in Tyson's
theater-of-the-absurd career.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Ratner, executive director of the Nevada State Athletic
Commission, said Norris' $800,000 share of the purse was paid, but
Tyson's $10 million cut was withheld pending a review today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The referee ruled that it was an accidental punch, and we
don't want to read any more into it until we review the films,''
Ratner said. ``But because of the circumstances, well, we just
thought it wouldn't hurt to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Circumstances that say Tyson's career, which always has been
boxing's version of a three-ring circus, has deteriorated into a
carnival sideshow attraction to be placed alongside the bearded
lady and other freaks.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson and promoter Dan Goossen spent a good deal of time putting
the blame for the latest fiasco on Norris, the victim. They
questioned his injured knee, his head, his guts, his heart. They
said he was afraid to come back out for the second round and take
his beating.
</P>
<P>
   And while the athletic commission is investigating, it might do
well to listen to the ringside audio near Norris' corner, where
voices can be heard telling their man: ``Stay down. Don't let him
go out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy theorists easily could concoct a scenario in
which all Norris wanted to do was get off easy for the biggest
payday of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit him in his jaw, and he hurt his leg,'' Tyson said.
``He's a coward.''
</P>
<P>
   And Iron Mike is a sociopath.
</P>
<P>
   These days in the cesspool of boxing, that's where hope floats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
