<HEADER>
A7239 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-CORRECT     10-25 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-CORRECTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES ARE ROLLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Correcting byline) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They haven't instituted the scorched earth policy that
Sherman did a few years back when his troops made an unwelcome
appearance in this historic southern hamlet, but the Yankees
continue to cause misery in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   These New York Yankees, of course, are slightly more peaceful
than the aggregation that Sherman commanded, preferring to do their
damage with their bats, arms and gloves in a non-violent approach
that has left the Atlanta Braves violently ailing.
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely what the Yankees did Sunday evening in an
overwhelming fashion, impaling the Braves, 7-2, in a boring affair
that wasn't faintly as close as the final score suggests.
</P>
<P>
   This World Series won't be officially over until the Yankees win
four games, a total they figure to reach in the middle of the week
at Yankee Stadium if they continue to function at such a divine
level and their opponent continues to stumble and bumble haplessly.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in just two games, the Yankees have turned what was
expected to be a tight series into such an uneven competition that
the most riveting bit of drama in Game 2 came before the first
pitch was thrown and didn't even involve any of the participants.
</P>
<P>
   They should have replayed that heated nationally televised
debate between Team of the Century outfielder Pete Rose and NBC
sideline interviewer Jim Gray on the Turner Field scoreboard
because, apparently, it caused a greater reaction from viewers
around the country than did the one-sided game that was decided the
moment the reeling Braves manager, Bobby Cox, made out his lineup.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, watching Jim Gray, a mediocre Howard Cosell copycat of
limited talent, inciting Rose with hardball questions turned out to
be far grander theatre than watching Derek Jeter, Chuck Knoblauch,
Tino Martinez, Bernie Williams, Paul O'Neill, Ricky Ledee pound out
one base hit after another and David Cone retire one Brave batter
after another on the clear, 49-degree evening.
</P>
<P>
   It's just getting uglier and uglier for the Braves, who were
one-hitted across seven innings by the Cuban exile, Orlando (El
Duque) Hernandez, on Saturday night and, proving that wasn't a
fluke, came right back to be one-hitted across seven innings by
Cone.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Braves have been consistent.
</P>
<P>
   This was a total Braves collapse, from their batters failing to
hit to their fielders failing to field to their manager reverting
to classic World Series form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just played a bad game,'' said Bobby Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Cox also managed a bad one.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox might be Manager of the Year in the National League
this season and he might have done his best work in his career, but
the guy has a lengthy history of falling apart in these World
Series game dating back to 1991 when he cost his team a probably
triumph against the Minnesota Twins because of a curious loyalty to
a home-run-prone left-hander named Charlie Leibrandt.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't enough space to list all of Cox's miscalculations
during the Braves' World Series failures this decade against the
Twins, Toronto Blue Jays and Yankees, but we can add a few more to
Cox's ledger in light of the weird lineup he drew up for the second
game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going with the same group of doughty fellows that
overcame a serious challenge from the New York Mets, Cox decided to
go with three new starters against the Yankees for no more
compelling reason than they happen to bat from the left side of the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, except Ozzie Guillen, who replaced the reliable
Walt Weiss at shortstop, is old and can't field any longer; Keith
Lockhart, who replaced the sure-fielding Bret Boone at second base,
makes the erratic Chuck Knoblauch look like Robbie Alomar in the
field; and Greg Myers, who replaced NCLS Most Valuable Player Eddie
Perez at catcher, isn't exactly a renowned handler of pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   All three men endured problems Sunday night, as Guillen dropped
a infield popup I could have caught, Lockhart threw a ball halfway
to Savannah, and Myers failed to coax anything meaningful out of
the Braves' starter, Kevin Millwood, who gave up eight hits and
four earned runs in just two innings.
</P>
<P>
   One idly wonders why Cox even started Millwood, a 24-year-old
right-hander who won 18 games during the regular season but doesn't
have the post-season credentials of a John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Cox waiting until Game 4 to pitch Smoltz, who is one of
the prime big-game pitchers in baseball?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he figures the Braves might be in an 0-3 precipice by
then, and will need Smoltz to keep his team afloat.
</P>
<P>
   I can't figure it out, but I've spent the entire 1990s trying to
figure out many of Cox's October moves.
</P>
<P>
   The loudest cheers of the night came before the game when Pete
Rose was introduced during the Team of the Century ceremony and in
the fifth inning when Guillen caught a popup off the bat of Cone
after dropping one from Cone in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not our night,'' Bobby Cox kept saying.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't look like the Braves' series, but they can take
solace in the fact that it was only three years ago that they
opened with two easy wins over the Yankees in New York _ 12-1 and
4-0 _ only for the Yankees to come back to win the next four in a
World Series streak that now has reached 10.
</P>
<P>
   But these Yankees aren't those 1996 Braves.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees play the game the way it is supposed to be played,
and they just keep throwing pitchers out there that the Braves
simply can't solve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hitters are pressing. . .no doubt about it,'' said the
Atlanta hitting coach, Don Baylor. ``We've been trying to rally,
make something happen. And nothing is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching sets the entire tone of our team,'' said the Yankee
manager, Joe Torre. ``It just has been so good, and it's a lot
easier for us to play from ahead than from behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out of it,'' said Ozzie Guillen in the solemn
Atlanta dressing room. ``We've had to overcome so many things this
year, and I think we can overcome this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have about as much chance of overcoming these lordly
Yankees as Jim Gray does of being invited to Pete Rose's next
gambling bash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
