<SLUG> BC-NEWPCS-PENTIUM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INTEL INTRODUCES SPEEDY NEW CHIP  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Intel will roll out a new generation of smaller,
faster Pentium III microprocessors today (October 25), and top PC
vendors will be on hand to show off notebook, desktop and server
computers incorporating the new chips.
</P>
<P>
   Code-named Coppermine, the new Pentium IIIs will put Intel back
in front in the PC-performance race, displacing rival Advanced
Micro Devices. For users, the new chips should mean a measurable
increase in computer speed, especially in demanding applications
like 3-D graphics.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic improvements will come in notebook PCs,
because Coppermine chips, running at speeds of up to 500 megahertz,
will be the first Pentium IIIs suitable for use in mobile machines.
Previously, the fastest Intel chip for portables was a
400-megahertz Pentium II.
</P>
<P>
   Acer, Compaq, Dell, Gateway, HP, IBM and others are expected to
announce Coppermine-based notebook models today. Most will
introduce the new chip first in high-end models aimed at business
executives and priced at more than $3,000. But both Acer America
and Gateway will offer laptops that include the new chip for only
$1,999.
</P>
<P>
   Desktop versions of the chips will run at speeds of up to 733
megahertz, compared to the 600-megahertz maximum of current Pentium
IIIs.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the increased speed and mobility possible is a new
production process that squeezes the Pentium III's internal
circuitry down from .25 micron in width to .18 micron _ about one
five-hundredth the width of a human hair. Even though the
Coppermine chips incorporate 28 million transistors, they'll be
smaller than a 33-cent postage stamp, according to Intel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their higher frequencies, the new chips feature
several internal enhancements that further boost performance,
especially in demanding applications like processing 3-D graphics.
</P>
<P>
   With the appropriate memory and supporting chips, for example,
desktop systems with Coppermine chips will be able to move data
between the main processor and memory _ along the data channel
known as the ``frontside bus'' _ at 133 megahertz, compared with
100 megahertz today. In Coppermine notebook models, this channel
will run at 100 megahertz, compared with 66 megahertz today.
</P>
<P>
   The Coppermine chips will incorporate the ``Level 2 cache'' _ a
small amount of ultra-fast memory that gives the processor quick
access to frequently used data and programming instructions _
directly into the main chip, where its contents can be tapped even
more quickly. With previous Pentiums the Level 2 cache was on
separate chip, which made access slower.
</P>
<P>
   The combined effect of these and other enhancements, according
to Nathan Brookwood, principal analyst at Insight 64 in Saratoga,
will be to make the new chips roughly 10 percent faster than their
predecessors on average, assuming that the two chips were running
at the same clock speed. Because in reality the new chips will run
at higher clock speeds, the actual performance boost will be
larger.
</P>
<P>
   How much larger, however, depends on the task in question.
Dell's new Coppermine systems score between 1 and 42 percent fthan current Pentium III models in various benchmark tests,
according to a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Intel lost its traditional leadership position back in August,
when rival Advanced Micro Devices introduced its new Athlon chip,
running at 650 megahertz. Earlier this month, AMD boosted that
chip's top speed to 700 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's lead could be short-lived, however: AMD is expected to
boost the Athlon's speed to 800 megahertz by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the coming months, both companies ``are just going to drive
performance to startling new heights,'' Brookwood said. ``The
people who need that kind of performance are definitely going to
notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the potential of the new chips won't be realized
immediately, however, because technical glitches have forced Intel
to delay release of supporting chips that were supposed to let
PC-makers combine the Coppermine chips with a new and faster memory
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Some PC companies, including IBM and Micronpc, have switched to
support chips from an Intel competitor that don't support the new
type of memory, which is known as Rambus or RDRAM. Other companies
will use other Intel chip sets, but these don't offer all the
features the delayed chips were supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many companies planning to roll out desktop PCs with
Coppermine chips, Compaq will offer a 650-megahertz Presario model
starting at an aggressive $1,129. Gateway will add the chip to its
Performance line, with prices starting at $2,099 for a model with
600-megahertz version of the chip, while Hewlett-Packard will
announce a $2,299 Pavilion model with a 733-megahertz version.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to desktop and notebook Coppermine chips, Intel also
will add versions of it in its Xeon processor family, which is
designed for use in servers and high-performance workstations.
</P>
<P>
   Insight 64 analyst Brookwood said, however, that these chips
likely will appear only in low-end servers, mainly because the new
design limits the chips' Level 2 cache to 256 kilobytes. Current
Xeon Pentium III chips have up to eight times as much cache, and
designers of large server systems generally prefer larger caches
even if they operate slightly more slowly, according to Brookwood.
</P>
</TEXT>
