r f BC-PORTALS-OVERSEAS-SFCH     10-25 1510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTALS-OVERSEAS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NET FIRMS SEE BIG POTENTIAL IN FOREIGN MARKETS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For proof of how cosmopolitan the Internet has
become, look no further than MyWeb Inc.com, which describes itself
in company handouts as being ``headquartered in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the provider of TV-based Net access, which went public
in February, has 80 workers in China, 60 in Malaysia and eight in
Singapore. And at its global headquarters in the Financial
District?
</P>
<P>
   One employee, on hand mostly to field calls from U.S. investors.
</P>
<P>
   Such calls are becoming more frequent _ a trend that underlines
the vast potential for Internet companies seeking to open the Net
to millions of non-English-speaking users.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about English, the portal race is pretty much
over,'' said Charlene Li, senior analyst at Forrester Research,
which tracks changes in the online world. ``You have Yahoo and AOL
duking it out. But in other countries, the portal race is just
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this year, nearly 60 percent of the world's
Internet users will reside outside the United States, according to
International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Microsoft unveiled a Spanish-language online
service in conjunction with Mexico's largest phone company,
Telefonos de Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest prize is China, where the number of people
online is expected to quadruple from 4 million today to more than
16 million by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, by comparison, is projected to have about 125
million Net users by the same time, nearly double the current 70
million.
</P>
<P>
   If current growth rates continue, some analysts believe that
China could surpass the United States for people online by the end
of the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The non-English world is definitely growing faster than the
English-speaking world,'' said Heather Killen, Yahoo's vice
president of international operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still no market (for total Internet users) that is
bigger than the U.S. market,'' she observed. ``But markets outside
the United States are growing faster.''
</P>
<P>
   This hasn't been lost on MyWeb, which operates search and
directory portals in China, Malaysia, Hong Kong and Singapore. Each
is accessed via a set-top box using an ordinary TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a U.S. entity,'' explained T.S. Wong, MyWeb's
28-year-old president and chief executive, ``but we have no
business operations in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the company boasts a U.S. market value of more
than $100 million, and has surged in just four months of operation
to become the eighth-most visited site in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, the PC is the primary point of access,''
Wong said while on one of his monthly visits to the Bay Area. ``But
in many other countries, there are many more TVs.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: In China, there are only 11 million PCs and about
320 million TV sets. No wonder, then, that Microsoft's Bill Gates
was in Shenzhen earlier this year unveiling plans to bring WebTV,
the leading U.S. provider of TV-based Net access, to the mainland
by using a Chinese version of the Windows CE operating system in
set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   MyWeb, which launched its China service in June, is hoping to
fend off such deep-pocketed competition by moving quickly to stake
out market share.
</P>
<P>
   The company now claims more than 20,000 users in China but hopes
to have 200,000 more boxes atop Chinese TVs within the next six
months, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being nominally headquartered in the United States, Wong
hopes that MyWeb will be seen by Beijing authorities more as a
local enterprise than a foreign enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling at the moment is that our competition will come
from mainland companies,'' he said. ``Foreign companies will
attract too much attention from regulators.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, America Online is hoping this won't be the case.
The planet's biggest online service, with some 18 million users
worldwide, launched a Hong Kong service last month in what most
observers see as a beachhead for eventual expansion to the Chinese
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   AOL already has a Japanese-language service based in Tokyo,
along with an Australian version of its English-language content.
In Europe, AOL Germany this month became the company's first
non-U.S. subsidiary to top 1 million members.
</P>
<P>
   ``International growth is clearly an important opportunity for
us,'' said Jack Davies, president of AOL International. ``It is a
real important growth driver for our business.''
</P>
<P>
   If, or when, the company advances into mainland China, it will
find itself facing some new challenges. One potential obstacle is a
recent pronouncement from China's information industry minister, Wu
Jichuan, virtually barring foreign investment in Internet firms.
</P>
<P>
   Davies said an AOL China service isn't yet in the cards
``although it's an attractive long-term opportunity.'' He
characterized his company as being ``in a watching and studying
mode.''
</P>
<P>
   For AOL, as well as all other Internet concerns, the primary
worry at present is the relatively high cost of Net access in most
other nations.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet user in China may pay the equivalent of about $20
for monthly service _ no small amount where the mean annual
household income is approximately $2,500. On top of that comes
steep per-minute phone charges.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the matter of making money _ not always the highest
priority for growth-happy Net outfits. With online ad revenues even
more scarce abroad than in the United States, many Internet
companies are banking on e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, IDC is projecting that e-commerce sales will soar
from $5.6 billion last year to $430 billion by 2003. In Asia, the
total is seen ballooning from $2.7 billion to $72 billion, though
most online sales will be confined to Japan, Hong Kong and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is tricky in China, where few people have credit
cards and delivery services aren't exactly models of reliability.
</P>
<P>
   MyWeb hopes to overcome at least the delivery side of the
equation by shipping goods _ mostly household supplies _ via taxi
cabs. Meanwhile, China.com of Hong Kong, another Internet service,
is mulling a cash-on-delivery plan for online purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted that other people think e-commerce will be
difficult,'' said Ian Henry, China.com's president of international
operations. ``That's because we're working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a spectacular initial public offering of its shares in
July, China.com is lagging its rivals. A recent survey by CNNIC,
China's official Internet domain registry, found that China.com
ranked 40th for page views, well behind rival portals like SinaNet
and Sohu.com.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry pointed out that the China.com portal is only one
piece of his company's ``pan-Asian'' strategy. There also are Hong
Kong and Taiwan portals, as well as more lucrative Web-development
operations throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   He said China.com, which collaborates with AOL for the latter's
Hong Kong service, would welcome a Chinese version of AOL to the
mainland, arguing that the two companies would target different
segments of the market. He also said China.com is pulling for
TV-based MyWeb to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to get people online,'' Henry insisted. ``We just
want eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, getting people online doesn't necessarily
translate into increased eyeballs for all content providers. MyWeb
users, for example, see a MyWeb screen when they turn on their TVs.
If they choose not to surf the Web, they can switch immediately to
ordinary programs.
</P>
<P>
   A similar format will be used by Microsoft in launching a
Chinese version of WebTV. The software giant already serves up MSN
portals in Hong Kong and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But when people start surfing, chances are good that many will
turn to the best-established brand on the Net: Yahoo. In the CNNIC
ranking, Yahoo was the fourth-most-visited site among Chinese
Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, Yahoo operates in 12 languages. And in a number of
nations, including Japan, it attracts more visitors than any other
site.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's Killen is especially enthusiastic about the future of
non-PC Internet access devices. She called TV-based services ``the
next really big frontier,'' and said Yahoo is working with various
wireless communications firms for providing Net access via cell
phones.
</P>
<P>
   According to Forrester Research, a majority of Scandinavians and
Asians will be accessing the Net using cell phones within a few
short years.
</P>
<P>
   At MyWeb, such rapid changes mean that CEO Wong barely has time
to catch his breath while globe-hopping to his company's various
properties. He's projecting a 300 percent jump in revenue over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just huge potential for opportunities,'' Wong said.
``The number of TVs sold in Asia every year is simply
mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up? It hasn't been lost on the folks at MyWeb that India's
population is about to exceed 1 billion. An Indian TV portal will
be launched early next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
