r f BC--WEBSITE-SFCHRON &LR;      10-25 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--WEBSITE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
WEB SITE OPENS CHARITIES' BOOKS TO THE PUBLIC EYE &HT;    By BERNADETTE TANSEY
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The first Web site to give the public a look at
the books of 180,000 charities was so mobbed after it went up last
week that the operators were forced to shut it down temporarily for
upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.guidestar.org, began offering access last Monday
(October 18) to the charities' IRS Form 990s _ the nonprofit
equivalent of a tax return. Previously, these were available only
by asking for copies from the individual charities or the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The forms show how much a charity spends on good deeds and how
much goes toward fund raising, salaries and other administrative
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Schmidt, president of Philanthropic Researc Inc., which
runs the site, said the system had registered 650,000 hits by
midday on the first day. He estimated that three times that many
people tried to log on that morning but couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday afternoon, Guidestar had to take down its site to
install a new server. When it came back up on Wednesday, however,
the 990s were no longer available, though financial summaries and
other information were. Guidestar said it started bringing the 990s
back online Thursday, but on Friday (October 22) they were still
hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the 990s, the site still provides a wealth of
information, all in one place.
</P>
<P>
   Site visitors can search for charities by name, city, state,
category, keyword and/or income.
</P>
<P>
   There's a brief description of the charity's mission, and by
clicking on ``more financial information,'' visitors can see a
summary of the 990.
</P>
<P>
   The summary shows a rough breakdown of revenues (from donations,
grants and other sources) and expenses (programs, administration
and other). By dividing program expenses by total expenses, a donor
can see what percentage of outlays go toward good works.
</P>
<P>
   While the summary is a good first step, it could distort the
charity's true financial picture, said Daniel Langan, a spokesman
for the National Charities Information Bureau, a charity watchdog
group. To see what's really going on, donors should see the full
990.
</P>
<P>
   The 990 breaks expenses down into far more categories, including
fund raising, management, rent, travel and even postage and
telephone expenses. The latter two categories might indicate
whether the charity is doing a lot of phone and mail solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's $10 million in annual expenses and most of that
goes for telephones, postage and printing, then you should go ahead
and contact the charity and say, `Why is that?''' Langan said.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to scrutinize the 990: Langan said some charities
count certain fund-raising costs as ``program'' expenses if the
solicitation included material that might be deemed educational,
such as a list of warning signs for breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   This could make the charity look like it's spending more on
programs than it really is.
</P>
<P>
   To find out if the charity is doing this, look at the 990 under
``Part II, Statement of Functional Expenses,'' which includes a
section that requires a charity to reveal how much in fund-raising
expenses were reported as outlays for programs.
</P>
<P>
   Other nuggets in the 990: Some charities are required to reveal
salaries of board members and top-paid executive staff. Cash gifts,
investments and the amounts spent on specific community projects
also may be detailed.
</P>
<P>
   The 990s at Guidestar are computer scans of the actual paper
document sent to the IRS _ some complete with smudgy handwritten
numbers and obvious wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   The 990s were provided to Guidestar by the IRS in a joint
project with Philanthropic Research and the National Center for
Charitable Statistics, with major funding from the Ford Foundation,
the W.K. Kellogg Foundation and the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Guidestar does not plan to recommend individual charities,
develop performance rankings or create hard-and-fast formulas for
evaluating nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   But Schmidt said that within six months, the site will provide
analytical tools for donors who want to use their own criteria to
evaluate nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   Guidestar warns visitors not to place too much emphasis on the
990 numbers, and cautions that a single year's tax return is only a
snapshot of the organization's management. Schmidt said charities
must be evaluated differently according to their age, size and
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comparing a new charity to an established one would be like
comparing Amazon.com to General Motors,'' Schmidt said. ``(A
startup) is likely to have higher fund-raising costs because it has
to build the capacity to raise money before it can spend it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Langan, of the National Charities Information Bureau,
believes there are some standards that should apply to all
nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charity, to meet our standards, has to devote a minimum of
60 percent of annual expenses to programs,'' Langan said.
Nonprofits should not have more than one director who is paid for
serving, and that member should not be the president or the
treasurer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those standards are posted on the NCIB's Web site, www.give.org.
This site also has a good explanation of how to read a 990.
</P>
<P>
   Like most new Web sites, the Guidestar project still has some
work to do.
</P>
<P>
   Some 990s are not up-to-date. For example, the latest data
available for the San Francisco Opera Association is from 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Guidestar hopes to post current information on 220,000
nonprofits by the end of the year. It will not post financial
information on church-run charities or charities with less than
$25,000 in revenues _ neither of which are required to file 990s _
or on foundations that only make grants to other nonprofits, which
file a different IRS form.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the nonprofit world believe that simply by making
financial records readily available, the Guidestar site will lead
to more ethical and efficient use of donor funds.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt thinks that the site could spawn a cottage industry of
philanthropic watchdog groups who use the data to recommend
charities.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Philanthropic Research say the 990 posting is the
beginning of a wave of Internet philanthropy resources that could
revolutionize charitable giving in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, the revolution is going to be driven by
information,'' said Bill Meehan, co-chair of Philanthropic
Research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
