<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 UCSF BIRTHS A RESEARCH CENTER AS IT AMPUTATES AN EMERGENCY ROOM  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It is the best of times and the worst of times
for the University of California at San Francisco, which breaks
ground today (October 25) on a new research facility at Mission
Bay, even as it cuts services at Mount Zion Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an obvious symbolism in these two events,'' says Dr.
Warren Gold, president of the UCSF Faculty Association. ``The
medical-discovery side of the campus is extremely healthy, but the
medical-delivery side is sick.''
</P>
<P>
   University leaders, Gold included, are justifiably proud of
Mission Bay, which makes its ceremonial debut on San Francisco's
eastern flank.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, UCSF scientists have become world
leaders in medical research, an accomplishment symbolized by the
Nobel Prizes awarded to UCSF Chancellor J. Michael Bishop, UCSF
Professor Stanley Prusiner and former UCSF Professor Harold Varmus.
</P>
<P>
   The entire biotech industry traces its existence to
breakthroughs made by UCSF researchers, who were instrumental in
such milestones as the 1974 discovery that DNA from different
organisms could be spliced together.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, UCSF scientists have performed their medical miracles
while crammed into the main campus on Parnassus Heights. They need
and deserve the modern quarters planned for Mission Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The new research campus is expected to become a magnet for drug
and biotech firms, cementing Northern California's position as a
world center for the biomedical industry and giving San Francisco a
boost in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The optimism surrounding Mission Bay stands in stark contrast to
the dismal situation at Mount Zion.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital administrators are grappling with how best to shut down
Mount Zion's busy emergency room, which serves one of San
Francisco's poorest neighborhoods, just as flu season is getting
under way.
</P>
<P>
   The same aura of belt tightening and gloom hangs over the entire
UCSF Stanford Health Care system. Many doctors are taking pay cuts;
nurses are juggling more patients; support staffers are getting
pink slips. Morale, to put it mildly, is in the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   This same malaise extends far beyond the well-reported problems
arising from UCSF's merger with Stanford University. Talk to any
medical professional and they'll say our system of paying for
medical care seems ready to collapse. Patients and doctors accuse
HMOs of stinginess. Lawmakers struggle to control Medicare costs.
Yet millions of Americans still lack any insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   So here we are, expanding UCSF's research engine even while its
emergency rooms sputter for lack of financial fuel. I put this
irony to Professor Lloyd ``Holly'' Smith Jr., associate dean of
medicine at UCSF.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us feel the main health care problem is not the cost
or the inequitable distribution, serious as these are, but the
continued existence of diseases for which we have no answers or
only halfway answers,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is one of the people who made UCSF what it is today, by
recruiting some of the brightest minds in medicine and guiding them
as they transformed a once-ordinary teaching hospital into a
research giant. In a sense, the marvelous research campus that will
rise at Mission Bay springs from seeds Smith helped plant decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   So it behooves us to listen when Smith says, ``The university
can't solve the health care problems of the nation, but we can help
find the answers to rheumatoid arthritis or schizophrenia or
AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. But somewhere amid today's congratulations, we
ought to pause for a moment and reflect on what it says about our
society that we'll spare no expense at unraveling the secrets of
the genome but we balk at providing emergency-room care for a poor
kid with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   IPO OUTTAKES: Space considerations forced me to omit some
intersting facts from a daily article last week about the new
momentum for initial public offerings of biotech firms.
</P>
<P>
   The article made the point that biotech IPOs seemed to be on the
rise after a long dry spell. Some data provided by Burrill &AMP; Co.,
the San Francisco investment bank, would have driven home the point
even more strongly.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter just ended, biotech firms raised a stunning
$2.25 billion in follow-on offerings _ additional stock issued by
companies that are already public.
</P>
<P>
   Looked at another way, biotech firms raised as much in follow-on
offerings last quarter as they did in all the follow-on financings
filed in 1997, 1998 and the first half of 1999 combined.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, banker Steve Burrill predicted the end of
biotech's long IPO drought on Wall Street, saying a strong market
for secondary financings usually preceded an IPO rebound. The
flurry of recent biotech IPOs could prove his point.
</P>
<P>
   BETTER THAN MOTHER'S MILK?: Some scientists believe nanny goats,
ewes and other mammals can be altered genetically so that their
milk produces protein drugs beneficial to humans. The idea would be
to harvest the milk, then extract and refine the drug of interest
to humans.
</P>
<P>
   But in a recent edition of Nature Biotechnology, Canadian
scientists at Universite Laval in Quebec reported that they
successfully had altered male mice in such a way that their semen
produced human growth hormone.
</P>
<P>
   Although they only managed to produce a minute amount of the
drug, they postulate that the system could become far more
efficient if they are able to repeat the experiment in male boars,
which can produce up to half a liter of semen at a time.
</P>
<P>
   No word, however, on how the scientists intend to routinely
harvest that ejaculate.
</P>
<P>
   Look for BioScope every Monday in the Business section. Send
your biofeedback to Tom Abate by e-mail at abate &LR; sfgate.com; fax
(415) 543-2482, phone (415) 777-6213.
</P>
</TEXT>
