 TRACKING TOP FUND MANAGERS  &HT;     By HARRY DOMASH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Let's face it. Mutual fund managers have a big
advantage over you and me. Although we get plenty of information on
the Internet, they get it better and faster because they can afford
to pay big bucks for it. They're trading hundreds of thousands of
shares every month and generating big commissions, so naturally, if
analysts have new information, they'll tell the fund manager before
us.
</P>
<P>
   So wouldn't it be great if we could find out which stocks top
fund managers are buying or selling? It turns out you can for some
funds.
</P>
<P>
   IPS Millennium Fund (www.ipsfunds.com), is listed at five stars
(highest rating) by Chicago's Morningstar, a leading mutual fund
rating service. The fund's shareholders earned 86.7 percent on
their money during the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   You can find out what the fund's manager, Robert Loest, is
buying and selling, and why he's doing it, almost on a real-time
basis on the fund's Web site. From the IPS home page, select IPS
Millennium Fund and then click Portfolio Manager Diary.
</P>
<P>
   The diary is a stream-of-consciousness log of Loest's thinking
as he makes buy-and-sell decisions throughout the trading day. It's
outstanding! The diary is up to date as of the previous trading day
and goes back one month. It appears to include Loest's thoughts
about every trade he makes for the two funds he manages _
Millennium and the newer New Frontier Fund.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, talking about two Real Estate Investment Trusts
that he sold on October 15, he said, ``I decided it was a mistake
ever getting back into them.'' Commenting on the market that same
day, he said: ``I kept hearing all day from everyone on CNBC that
Fridays are not the day to get into the market on severe declines.
. . . Well, since it seems like everyone including your cab driver
already knows this, I figured I'd better buy on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of his comments are enlightening. For instance, when
talking about buying RFMD (RF Micro Devices) on October 8, he
explained what it made (chips for digital cell phones) and why its
stock was down that day. (It couldn't keep up with demand). You
can't get this kind of insight in paid reports, but it's free here.
</P>
<P>
   IPS also gives you the top 10 holdings for the Millennium and
New Frontier funds as of the end of the previous month (click top
10 stocks from each fund's main page), including a short
description and analysis of each top holding, and a link to each
company's Web site in case you want to research the company
further.
</P>
<P>
   FIRSTHAND TECHNOLOGY: The Firsthand Technology Value Fund sports
an average annual return of 47 percent during the past five years,
the best return of any mutual fund. Naturally, it also is listed at
five stars on Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   You can find out what fund manager Kevin Landis has bought or
sold in recent months by going to Firsthand's site
(www.firsthandfunds.com), clicking on Value Technology Fund, then
Portfolio Data and, finally, Historical Portfolio Information.
</P>
<P>
   Firsthand's information isn't as current as IPS' data. Its
managers don't want the competition to know what they're doing, so
they keep their trades secret for at least a month. If you look in
October, you'll see the portfolio as of August 31.
</P>
<P>
   For each holding, Firsthand shows you the number of shares
owned, the price paid, the total market value of the holding, and
the percent of the fund's assets it represents. There's also a link
to each holding's Web site. Firsthand also displays the amount of
the fund's assets held in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Firsthand's Portfolio Listings page lets you compare their
funds' portfolios between any two report dates. For instance, when
I entered July 1999 for the start date and August 1999 for the end
date, Firsthand displayed the July and August holdings, and the
difference between the two portfolios in a separate column. By
looking at the difference, you can see which stocks the fund was
buying and selling.
</P>
<P>
   I could see that the Technology Value Fund dumped 300,000 shares
of Aspec, a maker of semiconductor development software, and loaded
up on Novoste, buying 668,800 shares of the
medical-equipment-maker. I also noticed that the fund increased its
cash position from 1.6 percent of assets in July to 11.9 percent in
August, an unusually large amount of cash for a growth fund,
telling me the managers were getting conservative.
</P>
<P>
   You can find the same information on the site for Firsthand's
other funds.
</P>
<P>
   MUNDER NETNET: The Munder NetNet Fund (www.mundernetnet.com),
also listed at five stars by Morningstar, specializes in Internet
related companies and returned a sizzling 171 percent during the
past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Munder's portfolio information on the site is current as of the
end of the previous month (September). Munder shows you which
stocks were bought and sold during the month (click on Buys &AMP; Sells
on the top menu) and why. It also shows a complete list of holdings
(click Holdings) along with a short description and analysis of
each stock.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of information, considering that this fund holds
more than 90 companies. However, it doesn't show how many shares
are owned or what percentage of the total portfolio each company
represents.
</P>
<P>
   OPENFUND: OpenFund (www.openfund.com) is a brand new fund
specializing in high-tech companies. OpenFund goes a step further
than the other funds, showing its portfolio holdings in real time.
(Click Inside OpenFund on the left.)
</P>
<P>
   The display is updated every time a trade is made. The managers
also give a blow-by-blow commentary (click On the Trading Desk) of
why they're doing what they're doing. Also, if you're really bored,
you can click on their Live Trader Cam and see live shots of the
traders in action.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Domash lives in Aptos, Calif., and publishes the Winning
Investing newsletter. You can read his columns at
www.winninginvesting.com or contact him at
hdomash &LR; winninginvesting.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
