<SLUG> BC-ALTAVISTA-MAKEOVER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ALTAVISTA GETTING $40 MILLION FACE-LIFT  &HT;     By TOM STEIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Preparing for a possible public offering early
next year, AltaVista Co. is getting a $40 million makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from Yahoo's playbook, AltaVista of Palo Alto,
Calif., wants to reach beyond its search engine roots and become a
Internet portal powerhouse, offering a wide range of news and
entertainment, an e-commerce platform and next-generation search
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The new site, which goes up today (October 25), will include a
new logo and customizable, continually updated content from 100
media sources, including the New York Times, the Washington Post
and the Associated Press. It also features a shopping service and a
network of some 1,000 Webcams, or online cameras, that snap
pictures from locations around the world, including the Nasdaq
trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to drive more traffic to the site and make the
company more palatable to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're legendary for search, but not known for having a network
of services like Yahoo,'' said AltaVista chief executive Rod
Schrock. ``We are introducing the renaissance of AltaVista that
will fuel our growth and possibly put us in a position where it's
time to go public.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo is the No. 1 Web site in the United States, with 32
million unique visitors a month. AltaVista is in 17th place, with
9.5 million visitors, according to research firm Media Metrix in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, which acquired 83 percent of AltaVista in June from, wants
to market it more aggressively than its previous owners, Digital
Equipment Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said AltaVista clearly is taking aim at Yahoo with its
new strategy, but they wonder if the market can support more than
one or two major Internet portal sites.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Bane, an Internet analyst with the Yankee Group research
firm in Boston, said there are already too many portals and expects
a shakeout. But, she added, ``there is still room for anyone who
can improve the consumer experience. Yahoo has the strongest brand,
but they don't have the market locked up just yet.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that one thing AltaVista has over its competitors is a
free Internet-access service that allows users to surf the Web for
free in exchange for watching banner ads. ``Free Net access could
be AltaVista's ace in the hole in this portal game,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista said it is updating its existing free Net access
service, which has been downloaded by about 650,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is spiffing up its search engine by adding an
``intuitive interface'' that lets users search across eight
dimensions, including Web pages, discussion groups, directories,
news, shopping, audio clips, photo images and video images.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista will launch a $120 million advertising and marketing
campaign, slated to kick off on tonight's (October 25) Monday Night
Football game.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its relaunch, AltaVista will Web cast a 1 p.m.
concert today (October 25) in New York City by Grammy Award-winning
singer Lauryn Hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
