 LYCOS, ALTAVISTA TRYING TO BECOME VIRTUAL MALLS  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lycos Inc. and AltaVista Co., two of the Web's
busiest search directories, today (October 25) will become the
latest Internet portals to join in the search for new electronic
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos will launch LycosShop, which the Waltham, Mass., company
touts as the first to let Web shoppers compare, select and buy
goods all in one place.
</P>
<P>
   LycosShop will start with about 10,000 products from about 1,000
sellers, including big name brands like Gap, Barnes &AMP; Noble, Crate
&AMP; Barrel, Eddie Bauer, Service Merchandise and L.L. Bean.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AltaVista will launch a new shopping comparison
service as part of a $40 million makeover that will be announced
today (October 25).
</P>
<P>
   The two, which are both partially owned by CMGI Inc., are only
the latest portals vying to become virtual malls.
</P>
<P>
   Others include Amazon.com's zShops, Intuit Inc.'s Quicken
Shopping Channel and Yahoo Inc.'s YahooShopping service.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos Executive Vice President Ron Sege said about 40 percent of
the people who use Lycos are searching already for more information
about a future purchase, so the company hopes to capitalize on that
traffic and its brand name.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands of dot-com this and dot-com thats which
you've never heard of before and who you're not going to give your
credit card to,'' Sege said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Web research firm Media Metrix, Lycos was the 10th
most popular Web site, with about 13.4 million unique visitors in
September. Yahoo was first, with 32 million; AOL second, with 28.4
million; and Microsoft third, with 28.1 million. AltaVista was
17th, with 9.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   All the online shopping services let users find specific product
information such as price, color and features. But Sege said
LycosShop also offers product reviews written by professionals and
regular consumers. Also, he said, there is a computerized form that
lets shoppers rate products, such as digital cameras, based on
their own criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos' main source of revenues still will be from advertising,
but the merchants also will pay Lycos 2 percent or more from each
online sale.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos' virtual mall will start out smaller than its competitors.
Last month, Amazon's zShops started with 500,000 items listed,
which was well behind the 3.75 million items sold on YahooShopping.
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Barry Parr of International Data Corp. in Mountain
View, Calif., said LycosShop could grow more quickly because it is
a more complete Internet shopping service than Amazon's zShops,
which is trying to be more like ``the Kmart or Wal-Mart of the
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible that Lycos may have come up with something
here,'' said Parr, IDC's director of consumer e-commerce research.
``They have really leap-frogged Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Parr said he expects other online shopping malls to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if any of these sites will make a big difference
this Christmas season,'' Parr said. But if Lycos ``can deliver on
what they've promised to do, I think it has the potential to really
help consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sege said planning for LycosShop began after the holiday season
in 1998 and originally was going to include television home
shopping. But that was contingent on the $22 billion merger between
USA Networks and Lycos, which collapsed in May after CMGI, which
owns 20 percent of Lycos, objected. CMGI, a Boston investment firm,
eventually purchased 83 percent of Palo Alto's AltaVista for $2.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista will reveal more details about its new shopping
service today (October 25). Parr, who also was briefed on
AltaVista's plans, said the new site also will have a customized
shopping comparison service.
</P>
<P>
   The company's strategy is to cater to ``Web enthusiasts, the
heaviest users of AltaVista,'' Parr said. ``It's also a good
strategy, it's smart, and it's doable.''
</P>
<P>
   Parr said he is curious to see how Yahoo reacts to the
competition from Lycos and AltaVista, which both are trying to use
e-shopping to bite into Yahoo's still-sizable Web traffic lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
