<SLUG> BC-PCSALES-HIGHER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PC-MAKERS REJOICE OVER 25% RISE N WORLDWIDE SALES  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR;   &LR; Chronicle Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   Driven by strong consumer demand all over the world and a sharp
rebound in Asia, global PC sales in the third quarter soared 25
percent over the same period last year, according to a preliminary
report from the International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Framingham, Mass., research company pegged worldwide
personal-computer shipments at 27.9 million units for the three
months ended September 30, up 7.1 percent from the second quarter.
The biggest year-over-year increases came from Japan (37 percent)
and the rest of the Asia-Pacific market (38 percent), which last
year were still mired in economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. PC sales were 11.7 million units, up 23.2 percent over the
same quarter last year and 7.8 percent over the second quarter. IDC
attributed the strong growth, both in Asia and in the United
States, in large part to the ``nearly free PC'' marketing model,
under which consumers are offered rebates that reduce the up-front
cost of buying a new PC to less than $500 _ or in some cases to
nothing _ in exchange for a long-term commitment to an Internet
service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a relatively slow 20 percent rate of year-over-year
growth, Compaq Computer retained its No.1 ranking in global PC
sales, with shipments of 3.8 million units. In the United States,
however, Dell expanded its lead over Compaq by shipping 2.1 million
units, up 58 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   IBM held on to the third position worldwide, but it slipped to
fifth in the United States. Hewlett-Packard held fourth place in
both rankings, while Gateway climbed from fifth to third in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Apple and Packard Bell NEC finished in a tie for the sixth and
seventh slots in the United States, according to John Brown,
director of worldwide PC-tracking research at IDC. Packard Bell NEC
and other NEC divisions together ranked fifth in worldwide
shipments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 03:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7249 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     10-25 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRIDGE LOSES ITS INNOCENCE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Golden Gate Bridge has been violated.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Couch French Fry here (potatoes are far too healthy) was
watching the 49ers' game, which is actually good for the diet. My
chips lost their taste. Then I realized I was dipping the guac with
my cork margarita coaster.
</P>
<P>
   The medley of interceptions was interrupted for a commercial
break, and the once-virginal Golden Gate Bridge was shown with a
huge ad banner plastered onto &LR;  one of the towers. No subtle ad over
the toll plaza; this one could be read from the moon.
</P>
<P>
   It was a commercial for Nortel Networks, who gave us that fine
comercial where the old-fogey CEO stands at a teleconference and
poet-speaks the Beatles' ``Come Together,'' as handsome hardhats
and cool brothers groove in unison, having suddenly realized how
amazingly hip those corporate Sil-Val money-hoarder guys really
are.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel has managed to desecrate the Golden Gate Bridge and John
Lennon, back-to-back, no small accomplishment. Nortel is the
Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence of the ad world.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anything is sacred. It was another depressing day
watching Steve Young prowl the sideline, where he's in constant
danger of getting skulled by an errant Jeff Garcia pass.
</P>
<P>
   BUT AT LEAST Steve is the only athlete in a baseball cap on TV
these days who isn't spitting like a Rainbird sprinkler. If all the
spits we're going to see on TV during the World Series could be
collected and put into a giant fishbowl, it would be a must-see art
exhibit in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Expectorations'' it would be called, or ``Spit
Happens,'' and it would overshadow all other art. It would render
the elephant-dung Madonna as unimportant as a painting of dogs
playing poker with a velvet Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   Young, meanwhile, continues to seek a medical person who will
bless his return to football, and he has scheduled appointments
with Dr. Strangelove and Dr. Seuss. (Note: Since I genuinely like
and admire old Steve, there will be no Dr. Kevorkian jokes here.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet, suddenly I have this terrible vision of Young 10 years from
now, standing on the sidelines at Candlestick in his baseball cap
and  &LR; with his clipboard, and the TV guy is saying that Steve is
talking about returning to action soon, yet Young is unaware that
the 49ers have long since moved to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe what Steve is doing with that clipboard is making
police-artist sketches of the guys who have been mugging him for
years.
</P>
<P>
   I'll refrain from giving Young advice, but as my friend Dr.
Feelgood says, ``This city doesn't need another half-witted
lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   AT LEAST STEVE knows when to keep his mouth shut. On the
telecast of Saturday's Stanford-USC game, as the Trojans were
jumping to a 21-0 lead, announcer Keith Jackson said, whoa Nellie,
``There won't be enough room on the scoreboard for USC today!''
</P>
<P>
   There was, however, enough room in Jackson's mouth for his foot,
as Stanford won 35-31.
</P>
<P>
   Big day for Stanford. For the musically reclined, the Stanford
Lurching Band soundly defeated the USC Starching Band, and that
battle o' the bands was like an Al Gore-Jesse Ventura debate.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF TROJANS, USA Today made a slight mistake. It ran a
cute story about how the Cliff House in San Francisco, in its
guest-room mini-bar refrigerators, stocks condoms, or ``intimacy
kits.''
</P>
<P>
   Close. It's actually the Clift Hotel that provides this amenity.
</P>
<P>
   Gives me the shivers just to think about it. To each his own,
but I know if I was searching for such intimate apparel while
hotel-guesting, I sure wouldn't get it from a mini bar.
</P>
<P>
   MEANWHILE, if New Year's Eve in S.F. is going to be a
cataclysmic bust-out, and it will be, first the city has to survive
Halloween in the Castro. Word I get is that the
last-Halloween-of-the-century theme has the lads in the 'hood
already reaching levels of enthusiasm above and beyond the normal
crazed call of Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   So if you haven't shopped yet, don't even  &LR; try &LR;  to go out and
find a Rev. Jerry Falwell mask.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of holidays, is it too early to leap into the
Christmas spirit? Not for those plucky S.F. Firefighters, who have
already launched their holiday Toy Program. Last year, the program
got off to a late start due to budget cuts, but Chief Demmons
wasn't going to let that happen again. The program is fully-staffed
and smokin'.
</P>
<P>
   MEANWHILE, BACK to the 49ers, losers of three in a row.
Remember, men, when you're in a skid, turn your steering wheel in
the direction of the skid, so you can see what you're crashing
into.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that at the excellent Jim Russell School of Highway
Survival at Sears Point, where they teach you how to control wild
skids, handle emergency braking situations and do high-speed,
tire-smoking slaloming. In short, the basic tools you need to find
a parking space in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 49ers, give coach Steve Mariucci credit for this: He
is resisting Young's pleas to get back into action. Yet relations
are not strained between the coach and the QB. It was cute when, as
the game was winding down yesterday, Young dumped the Gatorade tub
on Mariucci's head.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
