<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 03:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7250 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-DAVIS-MISSION-SFCHRON     10-25 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-MISSION-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DAVIS' TRIP TO EUROPE, MIDDLE EAST MIXES TRADE, 
 POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Gov. Gray Davis and a select group of his top campaign donors
are testing the economic value of red-carpet diplomacy.
<P>
   Davis' two-week trade mission through Europe and the Middle East
concludes Friday, but the real results probably won't be clear
until long afterward, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Will lasting business contacts have been created in the
countries Davis visited, greasing the wheels for lucrative deals
for California? Or will the pomp and circumstance fade into
nothing?
</P>
<P>
   Political sniping has already started, with critics saying the
trade mission is merely political payback to donors among his
delegation, such as supermarket magnate Ron Burkle.
</P>
<P>
   Backers reply that the trip, as well as Davis' high-profile
diplomacy earlier this year with Mexico, demonstrates a new
assertiveness by California government on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   The trip took Davis last week from London to Ireland and
Scotland, where he met with heads of state and corporate leaders,
saying, ``I'm here to make the case for California. ... I'm here to
sell it.'' He arrives in Greece Monday and will visit Israel and
Egypt later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of Davis' political enemies say they don't mind an
ulterior motive or two as long as he brings home the bacon. And
they are quick to admit that there's nothing new in foreign
junketeering _ Davis' predecessors did the same, as do other
states' governors.
</P>
<P>
   But some veterans of state economic policy say Davis seems to be
so focused on the larger diplomacy that he may be slighting the
dry, unglamorous detail work that makes the deals happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high-level vision is certainly there, but exactly how you
implement it is going to require a lot more thought and effort than
appears to have happened 'til now,'' said Sean Randolph, president
of the Bay Area Economic Forum, a San Francisco-based alliance of
corporations and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Current indications and past experience suggest that the trip's
measurable results will be meager _ at least in the short term:
</P>
<P>
   -- Domestic politics. Most members of the delegation
accompanying Davis (aside from his own aides) represent large firms
and institutions that do no foreign trade and are not likely to,
either _ nursing homes, insurance and real estate firms, lobbyists,
business associations, labor unions. Most were major donors to
Davis' 1998 campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   -- Leaderless trade offices. Upon taking office, Davis followed
his predecessors' practice of firing most of the directors of
California's nine foreign trade offices. But five offices still
remain without directors, including London, where Davis spent four
days last week. These offices carry out the day-to-day work of
helping California firms make foreign deals, and experts say they
can't do their job without proper staffing.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mexico follow-up. Despite Davis' diplomatic overtures to
Mexico earlier this year, in which he and Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo exchanged official visits, California officials now admit
that no new  &LR; significant trade deals or new policy initiatives have
resulted.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Imprecise Barometer
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Mexico trips show how a trade mission's success is
hard to calculate.
</P>
<P>
   By all indications, the Mexico initiative was a diplomatic coup.
It reversed years of hostility caused by Governor Pete Wilson's
hard-line stand on immigration, opening up opportunities for
cooperation between California and Mexico on issues ranging from
trade to pollution cleanup to the education of migrant workers'
children.
</P>
<P>
   But after the trips, little was done on any issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexico trips were symbolic and diplomatic, to start a new
era, but let's not pretend that they were trade trips,'' said
Carlos Valderrama, president of the Foreign Trade Association of
Southern California, who held several top posts in the state Trade
and Commerce Agency under Governors George Deukmejian and Pete
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Valderrama said that Davis' decision to fire the Mexico office
director, and his subsequent failure to replace him, has prevented
the state from taking economic advantage of the new goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the delays, Davis is pushing full speed ahead with
further diplomatic expansion. He is planning to open new offices in
Shanghai, Sao Paolo, Buenos Aires, Singapore, Manila and a
still-undetermined site in India, to complement existing offices in
Frankfurt, London, Hong Kong, Tokyo, Mexico City, Seoul, Taipei,
Johannesburg and Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion will boost the state's foreign-office budget by 35
percent to $6.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't find any private company where the CEO comes in and
fires every head of overseas posts,'' Valderrama said. ``Everyone
knows there's a transition when a new governor comes in. But in the
past 10 months, there's been no transition at all. It's a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Davis' travel agenda has been chock full. In London,
for example, he lobbied Prime Minister Tony Blair to buy Boeing
cargo planes made in Long Beach for the Royal Air Force _ with no
immediate response. He also opened a state technology trade fair,
and he cut the ribbon at a new California trade office building in
London.
</P>
<P>
   The trade fair, Cal-IT Europe 1999, an annual event that was
started by Wilson, is one of many such fairs organized by the Trade
and Commerce Agency in countries around the world to hawk
California wares. The shows help firms make contacts with foreign
buyers and investors, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say this sort of humdrum, nonpartisan bureaucratic work
_ more so than glitzy diplomacy by politicians _ is what helps
trade happen year after year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Payoff Possible
</P>
<P>
   Have patience, state officials reply, Davis' foreign headlines
will pay off eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely important for the governor to be out there
touting our products,'' said Lon Hatamiya, secretary of the Trade
and Commerce Agency, who is accompanying Davis on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't take any market for granted _ high tech, aerospace,
environmental technology. The governor can open doors that wouldn't
be possible without him. California is looked at as a world leader,
and the governor symbolizes that.''
</P>
<P>
   The exposure could help burnish a statesman's image for Davis,
something he would need if he aspires to national office. Before
the trip, Davis had never visited Europe _ a lack of travel
experience similar to that of Deukmejian, who did not even have a
passport before he went to Tokyo in 1987 to open the state's first
overseas office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreign trips are very helpful to a politician who wants to
seek higher office,'' said Sean Walsh, Wilson's longtime spokesman,
who traveled abroad frequently with the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You log the footage away in your video vault and put the
articles in your clip file, and pull them out later to justify your
national stature.''
</P>
<P>
   But Walsh warned against being overly critical of Davis. ``If
Davis reaps personal political benefits, so be it. That's one of
the advantages of being governor. (Foreign trips) help the
California economy, so good politics is good policy, and vice
versa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
