<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 03:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7258 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BRAIN-GRAVITY-SFCHRON     10-25 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-GRAVITY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAIN MAY NEED GRAVITY TO DEVELOP, BIOLOGISTS WARN PROMOTERS
OF  SPACE COLONIES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Colonizing space, let alone raising children out there,
could be a lot trickier than you imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists revealed study results Sunday suggesting that
children born in space might suffer permanent nervous-system damage
unless exposed to earthlike gravity at key points during their
early development.
</P>
<P>
   This means the youngsters could have trouble walking on Earth
because their nervous systems have never been exposed to gravity
and, instead, their neurons would be permanently wired for the
low-gravity world of space.
</P>
<P>
   Even adults might have difficulty readjusting fully to life on
Earth after prolonged periods of weightlessness, experts said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest word on ``the brain in space'' set a futuristic tone
for the opening of the weeklong annual meeting of the Society for
Neuroscience here.
</P>
<P>
   While some 20,000 participants spent most of the day hearing
about neurodegenerative diseases and the inner workings of the
mind, top space biologists held forth in a corner of the sprawling
Miami Beach Convention Center, conjuring up half-serious
speculations of far-out infants and pregnant women being spun
around in centrifuges to make sure they receive the proper daily
dose of G's.
</P>
<P>
   But experts said the space studies also may shed some important
light on more down-to-earth concerns _ including the largely
unexplored details of how gravity shapes life as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a unique laboratory here to look at fundamental
biology,'' said David Liskowsky, head scientist in a program for
gravitational biology at the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Liskowsky said one novel set of findings _ showing a pervasive
effect of gravity on cell metabolism, brain development and DNA
synthesis _ is particularly intriguing. However, he also emphasized
that the findings are very preliminary and by no means threaten any
planned missions, including the International Space Station now
being built.
</P>
<P>
   Women are already forbidden to head into orbit if they are
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we are not ready to have children born in space,''
he said. ``This is pretty much new territory here.''
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising results yesterday were drawn from studies of
18 pregnant mice launched into space carrying some 200 mouse
fetuses at varying stages of development. The as-yet-unpublished
study was outlined for reporters by Richard Nowakowski of the
Robert Wood Johnson Medical School in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Nowakowski detected faint but distinct signals that nerve cells
_ and possibly every cell in our bodies _ may need gravity cues to
grow and function properly. The brain cells he examined were
thought to have no particular link to gravity-related functions.
Yet profound changes were noted when the space fetuses were
compared with carefully matched counterparts on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Cell death, a normal aspect of development, slowed down in
space, as did cell proliferation. Tiny structures that have to move
about within the cells and that normally travel ``with the cellular
equivalent speed of a Ferrari'' slowed to a crawl, Nowakowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Without gravity to guide migration of nerve cells that form the
outer layer of the cortex, the space-grown brains wound up smaller,
and although they appeared to be normal otherwise, they turned out
to have fewer nerve cells than normal mouse brains.
</P>
<P>
   Just what functional importance this would have in an adult
animal awaits further study. But it appears as if the brain
struggled to adapt as it developed, only to mask what could be
deleterious changes, Nowakowski said, ``the way a fresh coat of
paint can cover up serious structural problems'' in a house.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the muscle wasting observed in astronauts may be
indirectly linked to such deep-seated cellular effects of
microgravity, although a more likely possibility is that mere lack
of use is to blame. In any case, loss of muscle strength in space
so far has been proved to be temporary, and there are no confirmed
reports of any long-term illness in people returning from long
periods in space.
</P>
<P>
   Another study, presented by neuroscientist Kerry Walton of the
New York University School of Medicine and Dr. Robert Kalb of Yale
University, showed abnormal branching of motor neurons in the
spinal cords of young rats that had been in orbit. These branches,
called dendrites, form the connections that allow the brain to
direct movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if you took the dendritic tree and just stripped away
all the branches,'' Kalb said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these abnormalities may be permanent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Animals, like astronauts, showed a remarkable ability to adapt
to the rigors of weightlessness. But when they got back to Earth,
laboratory rats reared in space could not figure out how to walk
properly, even after four months of trial and error. Walton's
studies also showed gravity is needed for newborn pups, which are
born blind, to learn how to hold themselves upright.
</P>
<P>
   Some other findings seemed to confirm that adult subjects _
including human astronauts _ can fairly easily recover balance and
navigational abilities that have been lost in space.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Fuller of the University of California at Davis
discovered that microgravity had a surprising, if temporary,
slowing effect on the internal ``body clock'' that keeps all
mammalian life in synch with the 24-hour day. Just how gravity
could somehow touch upon this innate ``circadian rhythm,'' in
addition to the obvious effect of light-and-dark cycles and sleep
patterns, remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility, Fuller said, is that the same sort of
fundamental metabolic changes observed by Nowakowski could be at
work.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike changes in temperature or the length of the day, changes
in gravity have never been a factor in evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what could happen in the next millennium. So far,
however, ``we have not built the compensatory mechanisms'' to
handle zero or low gravity, Fuller said.
</P>
</TEXT>
