<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 09:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7347 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-POLITICS-LITERATURE     10-25 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-POLITICS-LITERATURE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHING, THE MORAL MIRROR OF POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The publishing world has offended Barbara Bush's family so much
this month, it's almost enough to make her regret her whole
literacy campaign.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush the elder was still reeling from ``Dutch,'' in which
Edmund Morris implied that the Bushes weren't on the coziest terms
with the Reagans, when his son learned about ``Fortunate Son:
George W. Bush and The Making of American President.'' The author,
J.H. Hatfield, alleges that Governor Bush was arrested for cocaine
possession in 1972. But amid reports that Hatfield served five
years in prison for hiring a hit man, St. Martin's Press last week
withdrew the book.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has called ``Fortunate Son,'' ostensibly based
upon him, ``science fiction.'' Edmund Morris has acknowledged that
his book ``Dutch,'' occasionally based on the Reagan White House,
is partly fiction, while the Bushes have said that some of the
non-fiction parts are fiction. ``Primary Colors,'' sometimes based
on the Clinton White House, actually is fiction.
</P>
<P>
   These books all play fast and loose with the truth, as
politicians tend to do.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd to see George Sr. and Junior feeling slandered; one
expects gossip-happy authors to latch on to more accessible
political dynasties, like the Kennedys, with their fast-lane life
styles and tremendous charisma.
</P>
<P>
   It was the late John F. Kennedy Jr. who attempted with his
magazine George to create a bridge between the glamor of politics
and the gloss of print, to take the dreams of his father's
``Profiles in Courage'' and T.H. White's ``The Making of the
President, 1960'' into a crass, celebrity-obsessed culture.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Politics and publishing have a lot in common. Both
thrive on promises and on sound bites. Both inspire personalities
to reinvent themselves, exaggerate their credits and lie about
their pasts. And both allow for folks to drum up large sums of
money in advance without disclosing too many details about the
project at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps if politicians were more forthcoming, they would be
smeared less. The American people can be very forgiving. They might
even forgive candidates for trying drugs, if given the chance. But
candidates typically won't risk it.
</P>
<P>
   Take Bill Clinton, who insisted he never inhaled. This premise
is certainly possible, knowing his desire to please all of the
people all of the time: He appeared to puff, to placate his smoking
buddies, yet knew he wanted to enter politics and say he'd never
done drugs. So he simply held the joint to his lips, in a perfect
moment of bipartisan pandering and poignant self-denial.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Bush will specify only what he has ``not'' done _
that is, not used an illegal drug in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that denial and self-denial at the highest levels
bring the unauthorized biographers out of the woodwork. St.
Martin's pulled ``Fortunate Son'' off shelves on the ground that if
Hatfield were a convicted felon that would undermine his
credibility _ as if authoring such works as an unauthorized
``X-Files'' encyclopedia lent him much credibility in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   The everyday lies expected in politics can loom larger when they
are under oath or inside the pages of a book. By offering books of
half-truths, publishing offers a moral mirror of politics. But
politics offers the distinct evils of sinning and lying about it.
In publishing, lying can be a crime in itself, since it can
constitute libel.
</P>
<P>
   If Hatfield invented the cocaine charge, that's a serious crime.
But if he's merely a convicted felon who hired a hit man, that
doesn't preclude him from being a successful writer. Indeed, St.
Martin's Press underestimates the forgiveness of the American
people. People might not mind a former convict writing a book as
long as the book is really good. The literati are especially
forgiving, as shown by Norman Mailer's fondness for ``Belly of the
Beast,'' written by the murderer Jack Henry Abbott. And three of
the world's greatest novels were written in prison; John Bunyan,
Cervantes and Dostoyevsky all did time.
</P>
<P>
   The American dream expressed in both politics and literature is
the dream of rebirth and redemption, the notion that anyone can
reform and move on: Former drug users can have political careers;
former felons like Hatfield can write non-fiction works with 54
pages of source notes. The public can forgive almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   Anything, that is, except a bad book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 09:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0252 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-POLITICS-LITERATURE     10-25 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-POLITICS-LITERATURE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHING, THE MORAL MIRROR OF POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The publishing world has offended Barbara Bush's family so much
this month, it's almost enough to make her regret her whole
literacy campaign.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush the elder was still reeling from ``Dutch,'' in which
Edmund Morris implied that the Bushes weren't on the coziest terms
with the Reagans, when his son learned about ``Fortunate Son:
George W. Bush and The Making of American President.'' The author,
J.H. Hatfield, alleges that Governor Bush was arrested for cocaine
possession in 1972. But amid reports that Hatfield served five
years in prison for hiring a hit man, St. Martin's Press last week
withdrew the book.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has called ``Fortunate Son,'' ostensibly based
upon him, ``science fiction.'' Edmund Morris has acknowledged that
his book ``Dutch,'' occasionally based on the Reagan White House,
is partly fiction, while the Bushes have said that some of the
non-fiction parts are fiction. ``Primary Colors,'' sometimes based
on the Clinton White House, actually is fiction.
</P>
<P>
   These books all play fast and loose with the truth, as
politicians tend to do.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd to see George Sr. and Junior feeling slandered; one
expects gossip-happy authors to latch on to more accessible
political dynasties, like the Kennedys, with their fast-lane life
styles and tremendous charisma.
</P>
<P>
   It was the late John F. Kennedy Jr. who attempted with his
magazine George to create a bridge between the glamor of politics
and the gloss of print, to take the dreams of his father's
``Profiles in Courage'' and T.H. White's ``The Making of the
President, 1960'' into a crass, celebrity-obsessed culture.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Politics and publishing have a lot in common. Both
thrive on promises and on sound bites. Both inspire personalities
to reinvent themselves, exaggerate their credits and lie about
their pasts. And both allow for folks to drum up large sums of
money in advance without disclosing too many details about the
project at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps if politicians were more forthcoming, they would be
smeared less. The American people can be very forgiving. They might
even forgive candidates for trying drugs, if given the chance. But
candidates typically won't risk it.
</P>
<P>
   Take Bill Clinton, who insisted he never inhaled. This premise
is certainly possible, knowing his desire to please all of the
people all of the time: He appeared to puff, to placate his smoking
buddies, yet knew he wanted to enter politics and say he'd never
done drugs. So he simply held the joint to his lips, in a perfect
moment of bipartisan pandering and poignant self-denial.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Bush will specify only what he has ``not'' done _
that is, not used an illegal drug in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that denial and self-denial at the highest levels
bring the unauthorized biographers out of the woodwork. St.
Martin's pulled ``Fortunate Son'' off shelves on the ground that if
Hatfield were a convicted felon that would undermine his
credibility _ as if authoring such works as an unauthorized
``X-Files'' encyclopedia lent him much credibility in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   The everyday lies expected in politics can loom larger when they
are under oath or inside the pages of a book. By offering books of
half-truths, publishing offers a moral mirror of politics. But
politics offers the distinct evils of sinning and lying about it.
In publishing, lying can be a crime in itself, since it can
constitute libel.
</P>
<P>
   If Hatfield invented the cocaine charge, that's a serious crime.
But if he's merely a convicted felon who hired a hit man, that
doesn't preclude him from being a successful writer. Indeed, St.
Martin's Press underestimates the forgiveness of the American
people. People might not mind a former convict writing a book as
long as the book is really good. The literati are especially
forgiving, as shown by Norman Mailer's fondness for ``Belly of the
Beast,'' written by the murderer Jack Henry Abbott. And three of
the world's greatest novels were written in prison; John Bunyan,
Cervantes and Dostoyevsky all did time.
</P>
<P>
   The American dream expressed in both politics and literature is
the dream of rebirth and redemption, the notion that anyone can
reform and move on: Former drug users can have political careers;
former felons like Hatfield can write non-fiction works with 54
pages of source notes. The public can forgive almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   Anything, that is, except a bad book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
