<SLUG> BC-R-SIERRALEONE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GLIMPSE OF THE FUTURE IN THE PAIN OF TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ The camp for amputees lies on a hill in
the most scenic stretch of Freetown, a favorite spot for British
vacationers before war destroyed Sierra Leone. The palms dotting
the surrounding hills, the nearby wide white beach, the faded
resorts promising respite, all stand in contrast to life inside the
camp: a one-legged girl hopping along one of the labyrinthine
walkways; a young man with one arm sitting on the porch of his
tarpaulin tent-house; an older man with arms hacked off below the
elbows; yet another with very short stumps.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the amputees in this camp _ there were 516 when
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright paid a visit Monday _ were
mutilated by rebels who advanced on Freetown last January. Many
were taken to the city's main public hospital where they languished
for days; then many went to a refugee camp at the national stadium
where they languished for weeks. Eventually they arrived at this
camp, which is run by Doctors Without Borders.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of another international relief organization,
Handicap International, the amputees are learning to use
prosthetics with surviving muscles, to wash themselves, to raise a
spoon to their lips. Some tasks the armless might never master,
though, like buttoning a shirt or tying a knot. But there is more
here than grinding work to relearn the basics. Isatu, a 13-year-old
girl with no arms, plays with her younger sister and friends on the
beach, touching them with her stumps, digging into the sand. A
46-year-old man, who in July said he would never wear unsightly
artificial arms with metal hooks, now takes a pen from a visitor
with his prosthetic and proudly writes down his name on a
reporter's notepad: Lamine Jusu Jarka. In a country where less than
a third of the people can write, isn't it a shame that Jarka's
handwriting is now barely legible? It will improve, he vows.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the government has done almost nothing for the amputees.
A few months ago, rumors swept the camp that the government had
gotten German surgeons to come here, and that transplants were
being performed in Europe. They became angry at the government when
the Germans never came.
</P>
<P>
   If the current peace agreement between the government and the
rebels hold _ hopes were raised Friday by a United Nations decision
to send 6.000 peacekeepers _ what will happen to the amputees? Will
the government take care of the thousands who are estimated to have
lost limbs to machetes? Even if the will exists, what can the
government do in a nation that is regarded as the world's poorest
and where everything must be rebuilt? The question is complicated
by the peace agreement, which granted amnesty to all combatants.
Foday Sankoh, the head of the rebellion responsible for most of the
war's atrocities, acknowledged his group's guilt months ago.
Recently, though, he has been backpedaling. Atrocities? Not me. He
appears more interested in the commission on mineral resources that
he will head. He has never visited this camp.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the amputees might have to rely on the system that
the vast majority of ordinary Africans rely on: the extended
family. In the world's poorest continent, relatives help one
another out; sometimes a sole member supports a large number of
relatives or close friends. If someone lucky enough to have a job
loses it, 15 people suffer, the saying goes. Here in the camp, most
amputees live with their families, secure in the knowledge that
they will never be abandoned. A few of them, however, have lost all
their families. No one knows what will happen to them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
