that stands by early September, when the network got its first
node, as the birth date of the Arpanet. Others continue to claim it
was late October, when the first electronic bits passed from UCLA
to a computer at the Stanford Research Institute, about 300 miles
to the north. Some profess to have invented packet-switching, the
data transmission technology that made it all possible. Still
others claim to have had the idea for a network in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Brinkley does not believe the Internet will hamper
historians' ability to gather facts. ``I don't think the Internet
has reinvented history,'' he said. ``It's just expanding and
complicating it a bit. History is always contested, and over time
frivolous claims get discounted, and more serious claims get more
attention, and eventually there's a consensus around a particular
answer. You won't have the open-ended disputes that are going on
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Time may also slow the rush for recognition. Every so often, the
Internet is not glorified but blamed _ for inflation, for the slump
in dot-com stocks, for widening the gap between haves and
have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the true dark side comes along, you won't see people
scrambling to take credit for that part,'' Denning said. ``It will
be, `That's not the part I had anything to do with.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they'll say that was Al Gore's part.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 09:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7354 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-CELEBS-IPO-REVIEW-N     10-25 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CELEBS-IPO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTHA STEWART VS. THE WWF: THE FINAL CONFIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By GEORGE JOHNSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news from Wall Street last week drew attention to probably
the most startling contrast imaginable in American popular culture:
Martha Stewart and the World Wrestling Federation, both going
public to investors on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Stock buyers were clearly more enamored with the mistress of
domesticity than with the minders of Stone Cold Steve Austin and
The Rock. She reportedly became a billionaire overnight, at least
on paper.
</P>
<P>
   But on the other hand, Ms. Stewart and the WWF have a lot in
common, if you take a warped look at quotations from the current
issues of her magazine, Martha Stewart Living, and the wrestling
federation's two magazines, WWF Magazine and WWF RAW.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts follow.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture Alterations  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martha: Inevitably you have more guests than dining-room chairs. So
you drag a couple of chairs in from another room, but they are a
different style. To unify this motley collection, make a matching
set of chair-back covers.  &QL; 
The WWF: At the 1999 Royal Rumble, Mick Foley was blasted 12 times
by a chair swung by The Rock. A few weeks later, the Road Dogg
drilled Al Snow four times, swinging a chair on ``Raw.'' ...
Unprotected chair shots are metallic reservations for the
``Alzheimer's Hilton'' and competitors in this business try to
avoid them at all costs.  &QL; 
Aromas!  &QL; 
Martha: You can follow your nose the 15 miles between the two
shops; the irresistible smell of cinnamon sugar and hot biscuits
pulls you from one to the other.  &QL; 
The WWF: Nothing rejuvenates pure evil like the putrid smell of his
victims' blood.  &QL; 
A Love of the Wild &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martha: Do you know? Some species of cactus _ prickly pears _ grow
wild on well-drained, sunny sites as far east as Florida and
Massachusetts, and up into Canada.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The WWF: As Boss Man left the dressing room, Snow leaped onto him
from a platform _ blasting him with a steel chair and dragging him
into the dressing room, where Boss Man battered Snow with a case
containing his dog, Pepper, and hit him with a blackboard. Snow
rammed his rival's head into a glass case and a garage door, and
the pair continued their fracas onto the street.
</P>
<P>
   They soon wound up fighting at an outdoor cafe and in a downtown
Minneapolis bar ... Snow borrowed a chain from a customer to use as
a weapon, delivered a moonsault from the bar, hit the Boss Man with
a billiard ball and scored the pin on a pool table after smashing
the former corrections officer with his own nightstick.  &QL; 
Sandwiches  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martha: Open-face sandwiches are layered with roasted vegetables,
ham, turkey and Swiss, then heated until the cheese melts. They are
served with homemade dill pickles and sweet-potato wedges.  &QL; 
The WWF: A ``Rock sandwich'' doesn't consist of meat or tuna fish
but instead several fresh slices of smoked ``shut your mouth'' and
some honey-baked ``smackdown.'' There's no cheese _ The Rock
doesn't like cheese! Rolls  &QL; 
Martha: Today, with time in short supply, fresh-baked dinner rolls
are a particular treat. While they take a little more effort, rolls
are no harder to bake than bread. They are, of course, nothing more
than bread dough that has been formed, usually by being rolled in
the palms, into smaller, individual portions. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The WWF: D'Lo countered with the Real Deal, a tilt-a-whirl slam and
legdrop. When he tried somersaulting onto his rival, though,
Jarrett rolled out of the way. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Decorating  &QL; 
Martha: Ask the children to help decorate (the Thanksgiving table).
They can place felt finger puppets atop candy sticks for a sweet
yet simple centerpiece; older kids can cut and glue paper shapes
for a Mayflower centerpiece and help arrange plates and cutlery.  &QL; 
The WWF: ``As fans of body art,'' the wrestler Prince Albert says,
``of course we're concerned about maintaining a clean and safe
environment when we pierce and tattoo. We wouldn't want someone's
nipple or tongue to get infected and turn green!''  &QL; 
Women Getting Together  &QL; 
Martha: I think I tasted some of Sara's food at a party in New
York, asked to meet her, and persuaded her, and her friend Jane
Stacey, a baker, to come and work for me in Connecticut as chefs in
my growing catering business ... They immediately made the parties
I catered even more special.  &QL; 
The WWF: Smarting from a recent attack by the champion, Tori came
into the ring with fists swinging, debilitating her rival with
series of suplexes. After bouncing off the ropes, Ivory slid under
her foe's legs, drove her face into the mat and executed a giant
swing.
</P>
<P>
   Tori tackled her opponent, spun her upside down and hoisted her
over her shoulders. When Tori tried a sunset flip, however, Ivory
shifted her weight and fell on top of the contender for the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the humiliation, Ivory tried ripping off Tori's outfit
after the bell. Suddenly Luna _ absent from the Federation for
months _ stampeded into the ring and chased the Women's Champion
back to the dressing room.  &QL; 
Cravings  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martha: In some families, [Thanksgiving is) largely about stuffing.
After the first helping, the guests all wait for their fullness to
subside so they can have more.  &QL; 
The WWF: Gangrell has a hunger, a thirst, an appetite for control
over and complete domination of others. Within him is an innate
drive to lead a tribe of men he can manipulate _ bend to his will.
 &QL; 
Bluster  &QL; 
Martha: Even people who cherish the blustery winds of winter agree
that they are best left outdoors where nature intended.  &QL; 
The WWF: You call yourself a fan? Well, son, if you're not a member
of the Squared Circle Club, you're just a piece of trash!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0909EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
