<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7356 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN26-COX     10-25 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Campaign funding reform charade ends for another
year
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as predictably as the diva keeling over in the last act of
the opera, political campaign funding reform has died its annual
death in Congress, this year the victim of a coup de grace by the
Senate's Republican leadership. Which, of course, did not allow the
straight up or down vote on the issue that it had once said it
would permit.
</P>
<P>
   Reform had passed in the House, and a Senate majority apparently
stood at the ready, but it takes 60 votes to spike a filibuster and
Majority Leader Trent Lott kept enough in his pocket to prevent
that.
</P>
<P>
   I say ``apparently'' because it is in no way clear that either
of the majorities was real. Confidence that Lott would queer the
deal let some disinclined Republicans in the House log a pretty
pro-reform vote, suitable for re-election framing, without much
risk reform would really happen.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it sure that the Democrats, beating the drum for reform
these days, are the converts to it they say they are. Democratic
majorities dodged opportunities to enact reforms earlier in the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry for the cynicism, but the real game seems to be to give
members a chance to vote for reform every now and again, if they
want to for the record, safe in the knowledge that each roll call
is just a set-up.
</P>
<P>
   (I'm reminded of a hustle in the Georgia Legislature some years
back. The House would vote to ban nude dancing in Atlanta, but the
issue would die in the Senate. The next year they'd switch roles.
That way, every legislator got to vote, by God, against nekkid
dancing, without ever endangering it. One year, the chambers
accidentally voted for the ban together. It took a panicked
procedural scramble to keep the ladies in chill bumps.)
</P>
<P>
   Most members of Congress realize big money has deeply corrupted
politics. Even so, most have optioned themselves and their parties
to rich commercial interests, if they have not simply sold
themselves outright. We don't have elections any more. We have
auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Reform opponents have even come up with a euphemism for the
bidding: free speech. You can't limit political contributions
because dollars, they say, are speech. If this means _ and it does
_ that the banks or the oil companies or the insurance industry get
millions of votes to your one, well, that's democracy for you.
</P>
<P>
   No, it isn't. Our founders were political realists, but they'd
gag on that one.
</P>
<P>
   Some members are even honestly rather than just rhetorically
offended by the money grubbing, but every one of them was elected
by the current system, and both parties depend on it, and all of
them are terrified of the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   So Democratic President Bill Clinton turns the Lincoln bedroom
into Motel 6 for moguls, and House Majority Whip Tom DeLay huddles
weekly with trade association representatives and other lobbyists
and sucks so much money out of them for the GOP that he's known as
``DeLay, Inc.''
</P>
<P>
   Our franchise has been bought out from under us and it will stay
bought unless a fed-up electorate demands its return.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
