<SLUG> BC-R-JAPAN-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND YOU THOUGHT JAPAN WAS STUCK IN THE MUD 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Nissan Motor Co. could well serve as a metaphor for
postwar Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, David Halberstam held up Nissan in ``The
Reckoning'' as a shining example of Japanese economic prowess in
marked contrast to American ineptitude. But in the last decade
Nissan has mirrored all that is wrong with this country .
</P>
<P>
   Staggering under Himalayan sized debts, an arthritic bureaucracy
and bloated inventories of boring cars, it reflects a Japan
burdened by massive public liabilities, an aging population, an
ossified corporate sector, one-party rule and a weak financial
system.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Nissan announced a radical plan to transform itself,
paring 20,000 workers, shutting down factories and embracing
foreign management know-how.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, too, is changing, despite the conventional wisdom that
has written it off as a moribund economic power. Here, more than in
most places, changes in business portend widespread change in the
community because business is such an integral part of Japanese
society.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, even as its economy has gone from bad to
worse, Japan has evolved, beyond the West's field of view. Change
has come so far now that even if Japan wanted to keep it a secret,
it no longer could.
</P>
<P>
   It keeps popping out and exhibiting itself like the mischievous
alter ego of the solemn puppets that appear in Japan's highly
stylized bunraku, or puppet theater, creating embarrassment and
havoc for Japan but hope and excitement in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the changes have been overshadowed by the broader
economic landscape, which remains overcast. But they are startling.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a few:
</P>
<P>
   _Japanese consumers are living better than they did during
Japan's economic bubble of the 1980s, and now they can demand
better prices, more choices and less government interference in
their economy. And they are increasingly likely to express their
displeasure at the polls: The party that has ruled Japan almost
exclusively since World War II has for the last several years
retained its grip on power only as part of a coalition, and it was
handed a humiliating setback in elections last year for the Upper
House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   _Foreigners are being allowed to buy Japanese companies _
something once unthinkable. Japan's financial crisis has toppled
that barrier, and Japan has even allowed a crown jewel of its
industrial heyday, the Long-Term Credit Bank, to come under foreign
control. The hope is that foreign owners will bring in services
common outside Japan and force Japanese competitors to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   _Japan is continuing to place its bets on manufacturing
technology, and those bets are paying off with leadership in an
array of products, from cars that run on both electricity and
gasoline to higher-tech display screens used in computers and
cellular telephones. These investments are raising Japan's
productivity rates, with the result that Japanese workers are
working fewer hours than their American counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Ezrati, an American who is chief investment officer at
Nomura Asset Management, is so convinced that change is afoot in
Japan that he named his new book on the subject ``Kawari: How
Japan's Economic and Cultural Transformation Will Alter the Balance
of Power Among Nations.'' Kawari means change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan was never going to eat us alive,'' Ezrati said. ``And
they aren't going to die a miserable death now.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the largest single impetus for change that he cites in
his book is the deregulation of the financial sector, which started
in April 1998 and has allowed a flock of American and European
bankers to begin plying their wares and services here in direct
competition with Japanese financial services companies, which were
long accustomed to operating in a largely closed market. The GE
Capital Corp., General Electric's vast financial services arm, has
snapped up several large Japanese companies, and dozens of similar
deals have been struck.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most symbolically astounding advance by foreigners
was the purchase of Long-Term Credit Bank, the institution that
bankrolled the transformation of Japan after World War II, by
Ripplewood Holdings LLC. The bank became available for acquisition
because it got itself into trouble making speculative real estate
loans and failing to use proper credit analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ripplewood intends to use the bank as a sort of skeleton
from which it can offer innovative products and services like
private banking and securities services, as well as consumer
lending, which in Japan has been a province dominated not by banks
but by specialized companies that charge exorbitant interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Major political figures were afraid that a bank controlled by
foreigners would call the loans of major corporations and political
patrons, and might discover some of the less savory aspects of the
financial back-scratching that goes on between big companies here
and many politicians. But those objections lost out to the argument
that turning Long-Term Credit over to Ripplewood would raise the
bar for all Japanese banks in much the same way that Citibank's
introduction of 24-hour automated teller machines forced them to
adopt round-the-clock banking.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, competition is already forcing changes. Two Japanese
banks, Sumitomo Bank and Sakura Bank, announced a merger that
violated a long-held Japanese taboo against lending money outside
their particular keiretsu, or cluster of manufacturing and
financial companies. But the two banks had belonged to different
groups, and the merged bank put Japan on notice that keiretsu
loyalties would no longer be sacred.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 0914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
