<HEADER>
A7362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     10-25 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 31)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE TENNIS PARTNER &LR;  By Abraham Verghese. Harper Perennial, $14.
A physician's story of his friendship with a young Australian
intern struggling to maintain control of his inner demons is also
one about medicine, grief and, above all, human nature. ``Verghese
is a fine writer, lyrical and controlled, and he captures the
attachment between the two men _ its motives, its allure _ with
both precision and charm,'' Caroline Knapp wrote in The New York
Times Book Review in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LOVE OF A GOOD WOMAN: Stories &LR;  By Alice Munro. Vintage
Contemporaries, $13. Most of these eight long stories are rooted
around 1960 and deal with the way people lived then and how they
live now, offering a rich portrait of a generation of women who
discovered a different set of rules in adulthood. This collection,
which was selected by the editors of The New York Times Book Review
as one of the best books of 1998, is ``characteristically superb,''
Michael Gorra wrote. At times ``Munro's work has the dazzling but
utterly illusory simplicity of the Wordsworth who ... could
collapse one moment, one memory, into another with an unrivaled
combination of clarity and subtlety.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL EVANS: How My Heart Sings &LR;  By Peter Pettinger. Yale
University, $15.95. The first full-length biography of the
enormously influential jazz pianist is as interested in his
exquisite playing as it is in his long private struggle with heroin
and cocaine addiction, which led to his death in 1980. The ``book
is packed with ... shrewd critical commentary,'' Terry Teachout
wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; READING JAZZ: A Gathering of Autobiography, Reportage, and
Criticism From 1919 to Now &LR; , edited by Robert Gottlieb (Vintage,
$20), features about 150 previously published pieces pulled
together by a noted book and magazine editor. ``This comprehensive
and intelligently organized collection reflects not just editorial
skill but a well-informed enthusiasm for the music,'' Peter
Keepnews wrote in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HUNDRED DAYS &LR;  By Patrick O'Brian. Norton, $13.95. In the
19th installment in the author's popular franchise of naval
historical novels, the bluff Commodore Jack Aubrey and the
brilliant ship's surgeon Stephen Maturin take on Balkan and North
African mercenaries during the hundred days between Napoleon's
escape from Elba and Waterloo. ``There is no doubt the fans will
like'' this tale, Paul Kennedy wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ROAD HOME &LR;  By Jim Harrison. Washington Square/Pocket Books,
$14. Five members of a part-Sioux family take turns narrating the
history of three generations of their Nebraska clan and their
complex connections to one another and to the natural world. ``To
read this book is to feel the luminosity of nature in one's own
being,'' Thomas McNamee wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WALKING WITH THE WIND: A Memoir of the Movement &LR;  By John Lewis
with Michael D'Orso. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $15. In chronicling
how the 1960s changed the United States (and his own role in that
transformation), an eminent civil rights leader revisits the
triumphant first half of the decade and the assassinations and
disillusionment that followed. Last year the reviewer William H.
Chafe called this a ``powerful memoir'' written ``with simplicity
and passion.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TROUBLE IN MIND: Black Southerners in the Age of Jim Crow &LR; , by
Leon F. Litwack (Vintage, $17), is a harrowing study of the South
between Reconstruction and World War I, a nightmare world of
segregation, brutal violence, disfranchisement, dashed dreams of
freedom and indignities large and small. ``Litwack's is a
heartbreaking book about a heartbreaking time,'' Edward L. Ayers
wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUBY &LR;  By Ann Hood. Picador USA, $13. This novel about the
strange bond between a grieving widow and a pregnant teen-age
runaway explores the unpredictable demands of sorrow. Last year the
reviewer Megan Harlan admired ``Hood's caustic wit, brightly
detailed prose and thoughtful delineations of two women struggling
with private, powerful regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIKE NEVER BEFORE &LR;  By Ehud Havazelet. Anchor, $12.95. These 10
interlocking stories about two generations of an Orthodox Jewish
family are unpredictable in their aims but share themes of
assimilation, the unforgivingness of time and the wasting of love.
The author ``can wriggle inside the personality of just about
anybody,'' Craig Seligman wrote last year. ``The writing soars.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CEREUS BLOOMS AT NIGHT &LR;  By Shani Mootoo. Bard/Avon, $12.50. Set
on an imaginary Caribbean island, this tale is about two displaced
souls whose marriage sets off an explosive chain of events, ranging
from adultery to murder. ``Mootoo's impressive first novel mixes
elements of magic realism and Gothic horror in a style that is by
turns lyrical and lurid,'' Diane Cole wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFTER SILENCE: Rape and My Journey Back &LR;  By Nancy Venable
Raine. Three Rivers, $14. In this bold account of the author's rape
in 1985 and its aftermath, she digs deep to analyze the feelings of
profound violation, rage, self-blame and shame brought on by the
crime. ```After Silence' is a book that dignifies the human
spirit,'' Richard Shweder wrote in 1998. ``It should be read by
everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
