<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, Oct. 31)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Oct. 16 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE,
</P>
<P>
   by J.K. Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE SIMPLE TRUTH, by David Baldacci. (Warner,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) An appeal by a man serving a life sentence
</P>
<P>
   for murder creates chaos in Washington's legal
</P>
<P>
   community.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE WILDFLOWERS: Misty, Star, Jade and Cat, by V.C.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews. (Pocket, $3.99 each.) A series of novels
</P>
<P>
   about troubled girls from broken homes.
</P>
<P>
   4. TOM CLANCY'S NET FORCE: Hidden Agendas, created by
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy and Steve Pieczenik. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Computer terrorism in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   5. ALL THROUGH THE NIGHT, by Mary Higgins Clark.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket Star, $7.99.) A Christmas mystery involves
</P>
<P>
   a missing child and a missing chalice.
</P>
<P>
   6.(x) BILLY STRAIGHT, by Jonathan Kellerman. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A 12-year-old boy witnesses a brutal murder in
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   7. WHEN THE WIND BLOWS, by James Patterson. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $7.99.) A girl helps a widow and an FBI
</P>
<P>
   agent uncover a deadly plot.
</P>
<P>
   8. A MAN IN FULL by Tom Wolfe. (Bantam, $8.50.) Life
</P>
<P>
   in Atlanta on the cusp of the millennium, as Old South
</P>
<P>
   values collide with a new world.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE REEF, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.50.) Searching
</P>
<P>
   for a jeweled amulet in the depths of the Caribbean,
</P>
<P>
   a woman deals with mysteries and romance.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE LOOP, by Nicholas Evans. (Dell, $7.99.) A biologist
</P>
<P>
   faces professional and romantic problems when she
</P>
<P>
   tries to protect wolves in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE DONOVAN LEGACY, by Nora Roberts. (Silhouette,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) Three romances involving a Celtic family.
</P>
<P>
   12. LOYALTY IN DEATH, by J.D. Robb. (Berkley, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A New York woman contends with a bomber stalking her
</P>
<P>
   and the city.
</P>
<P>
   13. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Vintage, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   A young woman growing up in Kyoto has to reinvent
</P>
<P>
   herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   14. RIVER, CROSS MY HEART, by Breena Clarke. (Back Bay/
</P>
<P>
   Little, Brown, $14.95.) A girl's drowning and
</P>
<P>
   its effects on her older sister.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Perennial, $14.) Five female characters
</P>
<P>
   narrate a novel set in the Belgian Congo during that
</P>
<P>
   country's fight for independence.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) ENCHANTED, by Nora Roberts. (Intimate Moments/
</P>
<P>
   Silhouette, $4.25.) A new romance involving the
</P>
<P>
   Donovan family.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) An Irish-American writer recalls his childhood
</P>
<P>
   amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   2. BLIND MAN'S BLUFF, by Sherry Sontag and Christopher
</P>
<P>
   Drew with Annette Lawrence Drew. (Harper Paperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) American espionage by submarine, from the
</P>
<P>
   Cold War to the present.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man
</P>
<P>
   who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   5. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger. (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Perennial, $14; Harper Paperbacks, $6.99.) The story of
</P>
<P>
   the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single crew.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Perennial, $13.) How a murderer helped James
</P>
<P>
   Murray compile the Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $10.95.) The author of ``A Child
</P>
<P>
   Called `It''' recalls his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   8.(x) MIDNIGHT IN THE GARDEN OF GOOD AND EVIL, by John
</P>
<P>
   Berendt. (Vintage, $12.) The mysterious death of a young
</P>
<P>
   man in Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   9. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages. (b)
</P>
<P>
   11. ADVENTURES OF A PSYCHIC, by Sylvia Browne
</P>
<P>
   and Antoinette May. (Hay House, $12.95.) A psychic
</P>
<P>
   tells her life story.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) Life in the Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest season in
</P>
<P>
   history.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) THE GIFTS OF THE JEWS, by Thomas Cahill. (Talese/
</P>
<P>
   Anchor, $14.) What Western civilization owes an ancient
</P>
<P>
   nomadic tribe.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) OPHELIA SPEAKS, by Sara Shandler. (Harper Perennial,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) Girls discuss their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) REAL BOYS, by William Pollack. (Owl/Holt, $13.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A clinical psychologist discusses the emotional
</P>
<P>
   development of boys.
</P>
<P>
   17.(x) THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE CARBOHYDRATE ADDICT'S LIFESPAN PROGRAM, by Richard
</P>
<P>
   F. Heller and Rachael F. Heller. (Plume, $15.95.) How to lose
</P>
<P>
   weight and become fit in middle age. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION,
</P>
<P>
   by Robert C. Atkins. (Avon, $14 and $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ways to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. PROTEIN POWER, by Michael R. Eades and Mary Dan
</P>
<P>
   Eades. (Bantam, $6.50 and $14.) Two physicians offer
</P>
<P>
   a protein-rich, low-carbohydrate plan for losing
</P>
<P>
   weight. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. THE CARBOHYDRATE ADDICT'S DIET, by Rachael F. Heller
</P>
<P>
   and Richard F. Heller. (Signet, $6.99.) A program for
</P>
<P>
   weight loss. (b)
