<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7376 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN27-CO     10-25 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: All the news that's fit to pique
 &HT;    (For release Oct. 27, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last decade or so, in a runup to the millennium
observance, the media has been packaging much of its information
into trendy lists: the 100 Best Movies of the Century, the
All-Century Baseball Team, the 20,000 Women in the Late Wilt
Chamberlain's Life.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers also play a role. Several publications _ both newspapers
and news magazines _ regularly produce numerical lists such as :
714, the number of home runs hit by Babe Ruth, or 1, the number of
children produced by the Bill and Hillary Clinton marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In order to do this, editors have had to strain much as a
crossword puzzle creator strains to shroud his clues. (Example from
last Sunday's New York Times: 47 Down, ``D.D.E. for one'' _ three
letters.)
</P>
<P>
   I am drawn to these numerical lists, not so much because they
interest me, but because they often are a puzzle unto themselves.
The people who put them together are worthy successors to those
who, decades ago, produced what were called ``fillers'' in
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The ``fillers'' usually were no more than three or four lines,
without a headline, and at the bottom of a story that ran too
short. That's where I learned _ and have since forgotten _ how long
fingernails grow in a day, how many cubic feet of water is in the
Caspian Sea and how fast a cheetah can run.
</P>
<P>
   The modern ``fillers'' people, those who now produce lists and
numerical litanies, are stretched to meet the demand to produce
and, thus, fall into the footsteps of the enigmatic crossword
puzzle creators.
</P>
<P>
   Reading one such numerical list in a news magazine the other
day, I perfectly understood what the height in meters (468.48) that
a new Chicago skyscraper will be, even though I can't fully fathom
meters. But it was telling me that a building in Chicago will be
this high.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the next item that threw me. Quote:
</P>
<P>
   ``20,000: Level, in becquerels, of radioactive cesium per
kilogram found in wild boar caught by hunters in Bavaria, 13 years
after Chernobyl.''
</P>
<P>
   Likely, this is a significant finding. But, first, it drove me
to a dictionary. I am neither a rocket scientist nor a member of
the Mensa Society. I suppose a lot of people know what a
``becquerel'' is but I don't and am not ashamed to admit it. I also
don't know what ``cesium'' is. (Neither does the Spell Check on my
computer.)
</P>
<P>
   I did not know whether or not to be alarmed by this information,
or whether it was good or bad for the wild boar.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I looked up the words in a dictionary and found that
``becquerel'' is a unit for measuring radioactive decay and that
``cesium'' is a chemical element, the most electropositive of all
the elements. Gee.
</P>
<P>
   Now knowing all that, what does it mean? Does this tell us that
the wild boar in Bavaria as well as the rest of us are in trouble?
Or does it mean that the Chernobyl scare is behind us? Are 20,000
becquerels of radioactive cesium per kilogram good or bad?
   Perhaps this is information best not left to formulated
listings.
</P>
<P>
   This, alone, was not the sole reason I was perplexed by the
numerical list. The next number left more questions than answers _
``300 billion: Dollars needed annually to save the planet,
according to scientists from Cambridge and Sheffield.''
</P>
<P>
   And to finish it off, it concluded with this piece of coherent
information:
</P>
<P>
   ``40: Number of nanograms of the sex pheromone splendipherin a
male magnificent tree frog (Litoria splendida) needs to attract a
female.
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
