<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defenders of state-sponsored religion have disowned heritage
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I don't understand why Chet Edwards' detractors
haven't criticized him for pandering to Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   Pandering. That's right.
</P>
<P>
   Understand, you couldn't blame an office-holder around here for
pandering to Baptists. It's Waco's second-largest two-legged
subgroup, grackles first.
</P>
<P>
   So, accuse him of this: being a back-pocket guy to Baptists on
their historic positions, like telling government to stay out of
religion.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Against state-organized (and student majority-led)
school prayer. Against posting of the Ten Commandments in school
halls. Against the ``Religious Freedom Amendment'' which would open
the door to school vouchers going to religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   You're saying that a lot of Baptists support those things.
Please admit: It's pretty ironic.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards has become one of Congress' most prominent spokesmen
against state meddling in religion. This even when it puts him at
odds with religious conservatives, of which Central Texas has many.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Edwards stood on the floor of the House to oppose a
resolution for a national day of prayer. Edwards against prayer?
No. Against government telling citizens how to live their religious
lives? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution contained these words: ``Whereas it is the
necessary duty of the people not only to humbly offer up our
prayers.'' And, ``it is incumbent on all public bodies, as well as
private persons, to revere and rely on God Almighty for our
day-to-day existence.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't imagine most Protestants would disagree with the
necessity of prayer. But most Protestants ought to squirm when
government tells them it's their duty.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards did more than squirm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of having a national voluntary day of prayer is one I
can support,'' he told the House, ``but ... I am deeply bothered by
the clauses of this resolution which would put the U.S. Congress on
record as telling individuals that it is a 'necessary duty' to
pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Government, stay out of matters of religion. If that's not a
fundamental Baptist line, it should be, because Baptists fled to
America to get away from state-established religion.
</P>
<P>
   The same for Protestants in general.
</P>
<P>
   Or didn't you know that?
</P>
<P>
   It seems that as a group, so-called conservative Protestants
selectively have forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of Protestantism was rebellion against majoritarian
oppression. Martin Luther led a movement against the Catholicism
that dominated Europe. Bloody inquisitions were staged by despots
of faith to keep belief and believers in line.
</P>
<P>
   Among the rebels, among the first Protestants, were the
Anabaptists. So rebellious and individualistic were they that they
didn't last long as one kind. They split into Baptists, Mennonites,
Dunkers, Moravians and other bands and brands.
</P>
<P>
   When Columbus discovered fertile ground across an ocean and the
Pilgrims planted seeds of European culture thereon, Protestants saw
in the American continent a religious sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   But religious freedom didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   Once ensconced in colonies, religion proved as oppressive and
exclusive as the influences fled. The Puritans of the Massachusetts
Bay Colony, for example, declared any Anabaptist persona non grata.
</P>
<P>
   It was this atmosphere that motivated the framers of the
Constitution to forbid establishment of religion.
</P>
<P>
   As to the phrase, ``wall of separation between church and
state,'' reviled as heretical by the religious right, Baptists have
their fingerprints on it. The words were penned by Thomas Jefferson
in a letter to the Danbury Baptist Association.
</P>
<P>
   Take note, sons and distant cousins of Anabaptists. Jefferson
wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Believing with you that religion is a matter which lies solely
between man and his God, that he owes account to none other for his
faith or his worship, that the legislative power of government
reach actions only, and not opinions ...''
</P>
<P>
   On separating church and state, Jefferson was pandering to
Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
