<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elizabeth Dole quit without showing what she had to offer
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last woman who ran for president, Patricia
Schroeder, quit the race in an emotional outburst of tears.
Elizabeth Dole quit this week with a chilling, unemotional
declaration: Money is the message, and she couldn't raise enough of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, the trail-blazing congresswoman from Colorado and
liberal champion of women's rights, left her mark on public policy.
But the conservative Dole honed a style that was feminine and
presidential _ a style other women politicians will emulate.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in front of every podium, stepping close to her
audience, exuding warmth without losing her professional demeanor,
Dole symbolically took down the barriers that often keep men from
hearing what a woman politician is saying, especially on matters
like tax policy, foreign affairs and nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Both Schroeder and Dole are Harvard Law graduates who brought
sterling qualifications and unquestioned integrity to the arena of
presidential politics _ although they espoused very different
political philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two, Dole had the best shot of making it.
</P>
<P>
   She was running close behind George W. Bush, the man she says
has raised 80 times more campaign money than she did. When she quit
last week, she noted that there's an America outside the Beltway,
including a lot of young, enthusiastic women who cared more about
her candidacy than the money gap might indicate. But Dole left
those women without a clear reason to continue the struggle for a
woman president.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder didn't do that.
</P>
<P>
   She crafted the original family values message even though it
was later hijacked and distorted by the religious right. Her style
was often sarcastic, sometimes so abrasive that her supporters
winced. But she made her mark. Because of her work, there isn't a
candidate in either party today who turns a cold shoulder to issues
that affect working women, family health care, child care, family
leave and preschool education. Schroeder made those so-called
women's issues everybody's issues. And she wasn't afraid to face
off with those in her party who disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Dole could have used her dramatic exit to make a real difference
on the issue she claimed caused her to quit _ the dominance of
money in politics. But that would have required bucking her party,
which she was not willing to do. Only on the gun issue did she veer
from GOP dogma, and it was a safe veering. She said weapons like
the AK-47 ought to be illegal, and gun safety locks should be
mandated. But she refused to say how she'd vote on the
McCain-Feingold campaign finance bill the day after her party
killed it in the U.S. Senate for the fourth time.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what she'd do about the money problem, she mouthed
the warmed-over Bob Dole position on reform. She talked about the
need for full disclosure and the ``phasing down'' of soft money _
the 800-pound gorilla that makes big bucks more important than big
issues.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't even explain why she was having money trouble. She
hinted that she didn't have the good ol' boy networks to tap and
that coming out of a humanitarian organization, the Red Cross, she
wasn't able to leverage big contributions. There was something
hollow about that as the reason to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the puzzle was why her husband's vast financial contacts
didn't pay off for her in the way former President George Bush's
have for his son. Maybe Bob Dole should step up and answer that
question. After all, his old nemesis Bill Clinton is missing no
opportunity to raise money for his wife's senatorial bid.
</P>
<P>
   When Schroeder ran for president, she talked about the dimension
women bring to the policy table by virtue of their life experiences
_ the understanding of equal partnerships, the inclusiveness, the
peace-making skills, the practical view of how policies, from
defense to the environment, affect human relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said the country is surely ready for a woman president, but
she never shared why a woman president might make a difference.
Until women like Dole answer that question and stick out the
battle, there won't be one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
