<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    iBook's appeal deeper than looks
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If my 12-year-old son is any example, computer
columnist John Dvorak is wrong. Boys aren't turned off by the
``girlish'' look of Apple's new portable computer, the iBook.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, my son can't seem to keep his hands off of the
clam-shaped, iridescent blue-and-white iBook. He takes it in the
car. He takes it to piano lessons. He even takes into the bathroom.
I suspect he'll take it with us to New Jersey when we visit my
mother for Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   What draws my son to this funny-looking, 6.6-pound hunk of
glowing plastic, rubber and metal runs deeper than looks alone. In
its design, Apple has managed to convey a sense that the iBook is a
special computer just for kids. That means: Hands off, Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Given my son's attachment, I'm betting the iBook will be a big
hit for Apple when the computer finally reaches full distribution.
Right now the company is struggling to get iBooks into customers'
hands, beset by unexpected problems with its suppliers of parts.
</P>
<P>
   Besides looks, the iBook includes several other innovations. The
battery lasts up to six hours, one of the longest battery lives for
any portable. There's a handle on the back that lets you carry the
iBook like a briefcase. The computer is surprisingly easy to carry
this way, despite its weight.
</P>
<P>
   The iBook also can connect wirelessly to the Internet. It does
so through an antenna hidden in the plastic lid.
</P>
<P>
   To connect wirelessly, though, you'll need two other devices: a
$100 internal card and something called an AirPort, a $299 base
station that can connect any iBook within 150 feet to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The AirPort isn't available yet, but is scheduled for release in
November.
</P>
<P>
   STRONG BASICS
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these innovations, the iBook is strong on the
basics. Its color 12.1-inch screen is exceptionally sharp.
Performance is crisp, and the iBook runs such demanding programs as
Microsoft's Word 98 and Excel well.
</P>
<P>
   The iBook retails for $1,599, although right now it's hard to
find. To learn more about this new portable, check out reviews at
such popular Mac Web sites as MacWorld Online, Apple Insider and
MacCentral.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
