<HEADER>
A7386 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-MEDIA26-COX     10-25 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Cyberspace' author has new print title
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Novelist William Gibson, who coined the word
``cyberspace'' 15 years ago, talks with Yahoo Internet Life for the
magazine's November issue. Gibson discusses his sixth novel, ``All
Tomorrow's Parties.'' Ever the iconoclast, Gibson says in this
interview that he isn't a science-fiction writer. He calls his
renown from coining the term cyberspace a ``tattoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Web is a great marketing tool. But it's not an easy
job wooing potential customers. The October issue of Beyond
Computing looks at what it takes to make a successful business Web
site. The article discusses how to design a first-class site as
well as how to run it 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Building on the success of its ``The Age of Empires'' real-time
strategy game, Microsoft has released a sequel. It's called ``The
Age of Kings'' and covers the Middle Ages. In ``Age of Kings,'' you
can command up to 13 civilizations, including the Franks, Japanese,
Byzantines, Vikings, Moguls and Celts. You can also refight the
campaigns of such historical figures as Joan of Arc, Saladin and
Genghis Khan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Age of Kings,'' like its predecessor, is still largely about
warfare. But Microsoft has added new levels of complexity, letting
players win through trade or technology. This game, available only
for PCs with Windows 95 or higher, features animated violence. It's
recommended for ages 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Golf was among the first games on early computers. Now the game
has migrated to the newest platform, hand-held machines. Electronic
Arts has released a game for the PalmPilot called ``Tiger Woods PGA
Tour Golf.'' In this game, players are Woods or one of six other
professional golfers on replicas of PGA 18-hole courses.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Out.com unplugged itself from the Internet as
the leading Web site on gay and lesbian lifestyles and issues. Now
the site is readying a comeback, revamped with a better design and
more information. The site also has a major new partner in GFN.com,
or the Gay Financial Network. Out.com is not yet up but you'll find
GFN.com at www.gfn.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
