r f BC-TECHNOBUDDY26-COX     10-25 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft makes breakthrough in mouse hygiene
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If cars were designed like your computer mouse, rush
hour would last a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   Just to move your cursor on the screen, the mouse goes through
as much rolling and turning and spinning inside as a washing
machine. So things can get messed up easily. And the mouse is a big
deal _ almost everything you do with your computer requires rolling
and clicking that mouse.
</P>
<P>
   People _ me included _ tend to be more fascinated by trendier
things such as processor chips, the merits of the size of the cache
and the speed of the chip. Hardly a day goes by without
near-hysterical news about some new version of Windows or an
even-faster chip from Intel.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes down to using a computer, some things haven't
changed much in the last decade. For the most part, we communicate
with the computer by typing on a keyboard much like the one on the
Royal Office Model typewriter I used to torture at my first
newspaper job. And while the mouse is relatively new, it hasn't
changed much since the days of the first Macintosh computer.
</P>
<P>
   If you dissect the mouse on your computer desk, you'll see that
_ as you roll it on the mouse pad _ a small rubber ball inside
rolls along with it. That ball rests against rollers that translate
the motion into electrical signals your computer can understand.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of steps just to move the cursor on your screen.
And since the mouse is mostly mechanical, all sorts of things
happen to it during the course of its life ... few of them good.
The ball gets coated with dirt and, in turn, transfers that dirt to
the rollers. Pretty soon, the innards of the mouse are all gunked
up and your cursor will be jumping around like a hyperactive frog.
</P>
<P>
   So today, we'll do two things: discuss cleaning the critter and
talk about one of the first real innovations in the mouse since the
cat was invented.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning is simple. Just remove the rubber ball and clean it
with a mild soap-and-water solution (wipe the mouse pad down with
the same solution, since removing the dirt there will keep your
mouse working better). Then use a cotton-tipped swab soaked in
alcohol to clean the rollers inside the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   To keep your mouse perking along, you'll need to repeat the
cleaning about once a month.
</P>
<P>
   But if all that sounds like a hassle, there's finally hope for
those of you who do not wish to bathe mice. Microsoft has
introduced what I like to think of as an, uh, altered mouse. It has
no ball inside. Instead, it uses a light beam that shines on your
desktop (you no longer need a mouse pad, although you may find that
you feel more comfortable using it anyway).
</P>
<P>
   Things being the way they are, this new mouse won't get the
attention that the press gives a new release of Windows or a new
chip from Intel. After all _ and I've been using the new mouse for
several weeks now _ it really works the same as a clean,
well-functioning mechanical mouse. Microsoft says it is more
precise than a regular mouse, and maybe it is. But I didn't notice
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll never have to clean it and never have to hunt up a
new mouse pad when the old one starts to feel weird.
</P>
<P>
   The new gadget _ called the optical Intellimouse Explorer_ sells
for about $75, or you can get a less-fancy model for $55 or so.
Buying one won't change your life, make your spreadsheets more
accurate or your e-mails more fascinating. All it will do is ensure
that you'll never have to bathe a mouse again.
</P>
<P>
   For my money, that's a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1053EDT &QL; 
