A7391 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-GADGETS-CARDS26-COX     10-25 0310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GADGETS-CARDS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make personalized greeting cards for all occasions
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you often find yourself spending hours in
front of greeting card racks futilely searching for the card that
features the perfect illustration and says just what you want to
say just the way you want to say it, you may be a candidate for
home greeting card software.
</P>
<P>
   Greeting card software allows you to create personalized cards
that can include the name of the person receiving the card, your
own specific messages and family photos.
</P>
<P>
   American Greetings CreataCard Platinum 4 is capable of producing
all kinds of cards and invitations, plus it can make post cards,
photo calendars, posters, decorative labels and other desktop
publishing items. The package comes with a sample pack of greeting
card paper and envelopes.
</P>
<P>
   The software package can also be used to design Web pages, and
American Greetings claims users can do more than 500,000 projects
with it.
</P>
<P>
   CreataCard Platinum 4 has a manufacturer's suggested retail
price of $49.99, and it's available in most stores where software
is sold. The package includes three CD-ROMs packed with drawings,
photos, verses and borders. One of the CD-ROMs sets up a connection
to American Greetings' online Art &AMP; More Store, where you can buy
extra illustrations and verses.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, CreataCard Platinum 4 has a user-friendly
main screen. It's immediately apparent how many different things
you can do and how to get started.
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, the images and verses you'll use are split
between two CD-ROMs requiring switching discs. Also the package's
system for helping you print on both sides of the paper is somewhat
cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
