<HEADER>
A7396 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CYBERSCENE26-COX     10-25 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Before hammering or painting, check some fix-it tips
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to leaky toilets, drafty windows and
squeaking doors, most of us turn to the Yellow Pages and our credit
cards instead of the computer.
</P>
<P>
   But that beige box on your desk and the World Wide Web can be
more useful than a hammer when it comes to taking care of many
ordinary household chores. While you may eventually use that
hammer, you may also find some advice that saves money and your
thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start our do-it-yourself tour of the Web at a site called,
logically enough, Doityourself
</P>
<P>
   .Com at www.doityourself.com/. Tips are divided into categories,
and almost everything, including the kitchen sink, is available.
There are too many categories to list entirely, but among topics
covered are brick and masonry, building and plans, cleaning,
electrical, flooring, glass and windows, hardware, kitchens and
baths, and painting.
</P>
<P>
   To give you a notion of the depth of the advice, let's look at
just a snippet of the tips offered on the fairly common
do-it-yourself job of replacing an electrical wall switch:
</P>
<P>
   1. Determine the type of switch needed. If the light can be
turned on from two different wall switches, buy a ``3-way switch.''
If only one switch turns on light, buy a ``regular switch.''
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove fuse or flip circuit breaker to ``off'' at the panel
box, usually found on the ground floor or basement.
</P>
<P>
   3. Unscrew and remove the face plate from the wall switch. And
so on ...
</P>
<P>
   The advice is accurate and easy to follow, even for someone with
no experience at all. You will note, however, that the text is
rather sloppy. Two typographical or spelling errors were found (and
corrected in this column) in the section quoted. That sort of
sloppy editing may frighten the novice into worrying that the
advice itself is sloppy. At least on the items checked, it was not.
</P>
<P>
   Our next stop is a place called the Hints-n-Tips Web site at
hints-n-tips.com/. The material here also is organized into
categories such as plumbing, appliance care, and DIY
(do-it-yourself). This site doesn't have the depth of the first one
(although when a topic is covered, it seems to be covered clearly
and accurately). One possible reason for the lack of detail is that
many of the hints have nothing to do with the home. Instead, there
are categories for travel, food and drink, computer repair, and
leisure. Some people may like the notion of a one-step Web site for
hints and tips of all kinds.
</P>
<P>
   You won't be surprised to learn that Martha Stewart _ the
doyenne of do-it-yourself _ has a Web site of her own. It's at www
</P>
<P>
   .marthastewart.com/. Most of the tips here involve decorating.
This isn't the place to go if you want a lively debate on the
merits of cordless drills or the real scoop on jigsaws. On the
other hand, where could you find another site that suggests so many
cool things to do with pine cones?
</P>
<P>
   Our last stop is at Ask Annie Household Tips and Formulas.
You'll find it at www.ecomall
</P>
<P>
   .com/greenshopping/annie
</P>
<P>
   .htm. If you have a moldy refrigerator (in other words, if you
are a single guy) or need to clean up a filthy Fiberglas bathtub,
this is the place for you. You'll get practical tips on some
real-world problems that may not be as cool as figuring out how to
build a new deck, but that you are a lot more likely to face. One
great feature of this rather plain Jane site is it gives you the
ability to get answers to specific questions by sending an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
