<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's nostalgia time for chip art
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like bombardiers during World War II, computer chip
designers want to leave their mark with _ and on _ what they
create.
</P>
<P>
   In World War II, bombardiers often drew pictures or wrote
messages on the bombs that they dropped. Chip makers have, for
years, created tiny works of art on the unused space on the
prototypes of silicon chips. Circuits are smaller now, engineers
are overworked and more chip production is automated, so chip
graffiti is starting to fade.
</P>
<P>
   One Canadian company, Chipworks, is hoping to preserve a bit of
the color. The November issue of Wired magazine includes a short
piece about a miniature gallery of silicon chip art, which can be
seen at www.chipworks.com
</P>
<P>
   /SiliconGallery/07main
</P>
<P>
   .htm.
</P>
<P>
   The November issue also takes a look at a new technology called
DigiScents, which lets you smell things through your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Digital smell works when the computer sends a signal to a small
box filled with a tiny fan and small vials of scented oils. The
signals tell the small box which vial to heat. The fan pushes the
smell out of the box and into your nose.
</P>
<P>
   The story predicts that the first waft in the online odor wave
should be headed your way soon. DigiScents Web site,
www.digiscents.com, will be up and running soon.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-DISTANCE BARGAINS AVAILABLE
</P>
<P>
   The big long-distance phone companies now have rates as low as 5
cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   But we are a nation of bargain hunters. If you think you could
somehow be paying less for your long-distance calls, check
iPhoneBill.com.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the company can save you money on your long-distance
bills depends on where you live, whom you call and how long you
talk. But the site has a feature in which visitors can type in
their home phone number, the number they are calling and the length
of the call to find out whether iPhoneBill.com can carry it more
cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Planet Earth Communications, offers rates as low as
2.9 cents per minute, but many are between 6 cents and 10 cents a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   The company bills calls in six-second increments.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
