<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reformatting scrapes barnacles off hard drive
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There comes a point in the life of most heavily used
computers when the hard drive needs to be reformatted. With my
computers, that time comes sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the fault of the computer, of course; if anything is
to blame it's Windows 95 and 98, with their arcane registry files,
and the apparent inability of either Windows or proprietary
uninstall programs to scrape every vestige of a program off the
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Shuffling programs onto and off a hard drive makes the poor disk
accumulate barnacles like a rusty guano freighter. Since I do this
shuffle once or twice a week, it's little wonder that the barnacles
eventually become obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   I had to reformat my drive this past week, although in this case
it would be fair to call it an exorcism rather than a reformatting.
</P>
<P>
   The first indication of major difficulties came when I needed to
use Microsoft Fax. It wouldn't work. It wouldn't even start up.
Clicking on the in-box produced a message saying there wasn't
enough memory and urging me to shut down some programs, even though
none were running.
</P>
<P>
   OK, time to wipe the old slate clean.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't need to do much backing up, and accomplished it by a
direct connection via parallel port to a nice laptop computer I'm
testing. This may not be the quickest backup system, but I don't
have a tape drive and I don't care to sit around shoving Zip disks
in and out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, reformatting a hard drive is easy. The tricky thing is
regaining control of it once it's wiped clean. To make sure I
didn't get stuck somewhere out there in cyberspace, I checked in
with Gateway support before starting the operation. Hey, I'm just
smart enough to know how things can leap up and bite you when you
aren't looking. If you get professional advice, you can always
blame any subsequent problems on the adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the advice didn't work. I called back and got some
advice from somebody else. It ultimately didn't work either, but it
got me to a point where I could figure out what to do to make
things right.
</P>
<P>
   A major problem is having only a Windows 98 upgrade disk. An
upgrade disk doesn't want to work if it can't find a previous
version of Windows on the drive. As a result, I had to install
Windows 95 and then promptly upgrade it to 98. The entire operation
probably required four hours, although I spread it over a couple of
evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Here I sit now, looking at a computer with nothing on it but
Windows 98, Eudora Pro, Netscape and Agent. Boots like lightning.
Shuts down in a wink. It's like having a new computer again.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, the ghost is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Some of you may remember the bizarre problem that arose a year
ago, not long after I got the computer, when I found that the
machine was turning itself on every midnight. The only way I could
prevent it was to unplug it. I got a surge protector, and that
didn't do any good, except I could use it to turn off the power to
the computer and thus prevent the weird midnight boot.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, not even Gateway, could figure out the problem. But the
reformat cured it, proving the problem lay somewhere in the
software.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to try another way of preventing the buildup of
barnacles, which is to use one of the many programs that will store
a copy of the registry file. If I store a copy of a good registry
file before installing a program, then after removing the program
with the Windows Remove Program feature, I can restore the registry
as it was before the program was installed.
</P>
<P>
   This should cure the problem _ if I can remember to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
