<HEADER>
A7403 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-FEATURE-COSTUMES2     10-25 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-COSTUMES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What to wear for the witching hour
 &HT;    By Cathy Hulbert
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here's a scary thought: Halloween is just around the
corner and you don't have a costume yet.
</P>
<P>
   Wait! Don't scream! (No need to wake up the dead before their
big night.) According to some metro Atlanta kids, parents and
artists, Halloween costumes can be frighteningly simple _ and
cheap. Here are some examples to get your brain bubbling:
</P>
<P>
   THE TABLE
</P>
<P>
   Michael Leonard, 9
</P>
<P>
   Setting the table may be a grim thought, but how would you like
to be a table? Imagine yourself as a walking, talking table with
your head as the main course! To make this costume, designed by
Michael's mom, Rheba Leonard, take a box that will fit over your
shoulders and a piece of material for the tablecloth. Cut holes for
your head in both. Also cut arm holes on the sides so you can hold
your candy. Cut a neck-sized hole in a plastic buffet tray (you can
find these in the grocery store deli). Make a slice on one side so
it can open up and then wrap it around your neck.
</P>
<P>
   Glue plastic food items on the table. Add a plastic vase or
battery operated candles. You can set your table with plastic
silverware and dishes, or go ``buffet'' style, like our model.
Older kids can also ghoul it up with blood trickling from the neck.
Dinner is served!
</P>
<P>
   CAPTAIN HOOK
</P>
<P>
   Erica Grau, 13
</P>
<P>
   Aye, maties! Captain Hook the pirate is a great option for girls
and boys. Start with black clothing. Create a vest by tracing the
contours of a real vest onto two pieces of felt cloth, advises
Elise Grau, educator and costume designer for the Center for
Puppetry Arts. Cut out the vest pieces and use hot glue to attach
them together into a wearable red and black pirate's vest.
</P>
<P>
   A pirate's hat, decorated with skull and crossbones, can be made
out of black poster board. Cut out the front shape. Then cut out a
two-inch strip of cardboard that can stapled at the ends to form a
ring around the top of the head. Then staple the front shape to the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   Cut a sword out of cardboard and wrap it in heavy aluminum.
Staple a rubber band to the back of the sword to let it hang from a
belt loop. For an earring, cut a circle out of yellow poster board
and cut a slit in the side. It can rest just inside the ear on one
side and behind the ear on the other. A black felt patch can be
stapled onto elastic and worn around the head. For the captain's
``hook,'' cut out a hook shape from sturdy material (cardboard
wrapped in foil will work). Cut an x-shape into the bottom of a
plastic cup. Insert the straight end of the hook into the bottom of
a cup. Then put the top of the cup over your hand.
</P>
<P>
   THE BLACK WIDOW
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Rawls Hill, 10
</P>
<P>
   Little Miss Muffet never met a spider like this one. The black
widow costume starts with black clothing, such as leggings and a
turtleneck. Ariel's mom, Marla Rawls Hill, used inexpensive black
boas, cut them in two and stitched them to the body of the costume.
She wrapped coated metal wire around the legs to make them bouncy.
Black thread was tied to two of the legs and to Ariel's wrists so
she could make the legs move up and down. To make the body of the
costume, two pieces of black poplin material were cut into an
hourglass shape, filled with fiber fill material (used for quilts)
and attached together using seam tape and an iron. The body sits
only on Ariel's front and fits like an apron.
</P>
<P>
   THE DOG
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Pearson, 11
</P>
<P>
   If you're not into creepy-crawlies _ how about being man's best
friend. Dog costumes can resemble your favorite breed. (They can
also be made scary like Cujo!) White sweatpants and a white turtle
neck can be covered with black felt spots _ loosely hand-stitched
or even pinned on _ to make a Dalmatian, according to Cheryl
Pearson of Lithonia. Make triangular ears out of felt material. The
ears will rest on a head band if pipe cleaners are attached to the
back. Blacken your nose with face paint and use ribbon for a
collar, making it as decorative as you'd like.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget the tail, which you'll want to wag when you get
your ``treats.'' Stuff a sock with other socks and pin it to your
lower back, not so low that you can't safely sit down.
</P>
<P>
   THE MUMMY
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Housel, 9
</P>
<P>
   If you want something simple _ yet horrifying _ how about a
mummy costume made from strips of an old white sheet? Make sure you
check first with your parents, then cut a large sheet into strips
that are about 4 inches wide and as long as possible. Use fabric
glue or a needle and thread to connect the strips into one or two
really long pieces. Then wrap the material around your body,
starting with your head. You can pin the strips to your clothes to
feel more secure. Make sure that you wear white clothing
underneath, because mummies do have a way of coming unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   THE BAG OF JELLY BEANS
</P>
<P>
   Margaret DeGrace, 9
</P>
<P>
   And finally, we'll end on a sweet note. How about turning
yourself into a bag of jelly beans? Simply take a clear garbage or
lawn bag and cut holes for your arms and legs, suggests Margaret's
mom, Lisa DeGrace. Once you're inside, fill your bag with colored
balloons. Keep the costume around your neck with a piece of bright
ribbon. Curly ribbons in your hair will make you extra fancy. Make
sure you wear good running shoes. A lot of candy fiends will be out
that night!
</P>
<P>
   WATCH OUT FOR GHOSTS AND GHOULS!
</P>
<P>
   Halloween can be scary _ and sometimes not in a good way. We
want you to have a great time, but be careful out there.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some quick tips to keep you safe and make Halloween
fun:
</P>
<P>
   1. NEVER trick-or-treat alone. Younger kids should always be
accompanied by an adult. If you're older, have at least two buddies
with you at all times.
</P>
<P>
   2. Don't go inside houses. Be as cautious of strangers as you
would at any other time.
</P>
<P>
   3. Carry a flashlight, and avoid houses that are completely
dark.
</P>
<P>
   4. Don't eat your treats until you're home. Adults can help you
examine the way they are packaged. If something isn't wrapped
securely, throw it out.
</P>
<P>
   5. Don't play near lit jack-o'-lanterns, which can cause
costumes to catch fire.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
