<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Russia battles Chechnya
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fighting between Russian and Chechen forces heated up
last week. Russian officials admitted attacking an open-air market
in Grozny, which is the capital of Chechnya, a region now part of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechens said the attack killed more than 100 civilians and
injured 400 others. The Russians said the market was filled with
terrorists buying weapons. The attack was the worst on Grozny since
fighting started again in September.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya was once an independent nation and has a strong sense
of national pride, explains Loch Johnson, a political science
professor at the University of Georgia. That is why it wants to be
independent again. It has fought with Russia through much of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY TOUGH ON BLACK CATS
</P>
<P>
   Around Halloween, many black felines fall victim to pranks or
worse. So, some shelters won't allow people to adopt them until
Halloween is long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Harming a black cat _ or any animal _ is against the law in
Georgia. Currently, it's a
</P>
<P>
   misdemeanor, but animal activists would like to see it made a
felony. Felonies receive harsher punishments
</P>
<P>
   than misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS NEED PERMISSION TO TALK TO COMPANIES ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   The federal government announced rules last week to help protect
children when they venture online. The rules, which take effect
April 21, require parental permission before companies can collect
information about a child. The rules will also require parents be
notified before kids can enter contests online.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses who want to sell things to kids often use Web sites
to gather information, such as kids' likes, dislikes and how much
money they spend. The government wants to make sure children aren't
taken advantage of.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
