r l BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A26-COX     10-25 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to know how I could get a copy of a newspaper
write-up on the moon landing in July 1969, especially the picture
of Buzz Aldrin standing on the moon's surface with the American
flag reflected on his helmet faceplate. I'd like the New York
Times, Chicago Sun-Times, the Austin American-Statesman or any
large city paper. Also, I'd like to know where I could get a poster
of that famous shot of Buzz Aldrin. _ Betty Jameson
</P>
<P>
   A: The famous date is July 20, 1969. The 16-by-20-inch poster,
available from NASA by calling (281) 283-7715, is less than $5. The
newspaper edition is a bit harder to find. Originals may be
available from anydate.com at (800) 653-9174, but requests for this
date are numerous. An original front page may cost several hundred
dollars. Reproductions (full-size, complete issues on traditional
newsprint) are more affordable ($14.95) and always available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am concerned about a convenience store in my neighborhood.
This store sells alcohol and tobacco to underaged youths on a
regular basis. I have witnessed this several times and have never
seen anyone asked for identification. To whom can I report this? _
J.E.L.
</P>
<P>
   A: Report suspicious sales to the Texas Alcoholic Beverage
Commission at (888) THE-TABC (843-8222) and the Texas Tobacco
Prevention hot line at (800) 345-8647. You may be asked to give
your name, phone number and mailing address, but you can make an
anonymous report.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need an ironing board cover for an ironing board that is
built into the wall. The length of the board is 42 inches. I have
found covers for table-top boards, but they are too small. If you
are able to direct me to a store that sells these, I would be so
grateful.
</P>
<P>
   _ Linda Hall
</P>
<P>
   A: The Container Store stocks an All-in-One Cover and Pad
($8.99) that should fit your 42-inch board. Another source is
Hide-a-Board Ironing Center (maker of a complete hidden board
unit). Covers ($10.50) are available by calling (800) 873-4766. Q:
In the past few weeks traffic helicopters _ at least, I hope they
are traffic helicopters _ have been buzzing over our home early
every weekday morning. Is there a regulation on where they can fly
and how close to the ground? _ P.X.A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Helicopters are regulated by the FAA, says agency spokesman
Stephen Homer. The regulation is vague (at best): ``Helicopters may
be operated at less than the minimums (altitudes) if the operation
is conducted without hazard to persons or property on the
surface.'' Sounds like carte blanche to me. If you feel these early
morning fliers are not operating ``without hazard,'' contact the
FAA Flight Standards District office at (800) 322-7873 or 10100
Reunion Place, Suite 200, San Antonio, TX 78216, Attn.: Operations
Unit. Give the copter's registration number (check the tail), as
well as the date, location and time of operation. A video or
photograph of the flight path would help.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was issued shares of a private corporation as compensation
for my sweat equity. Since the time I left employment, the
corporation has accepted a merger agreement. The other company
states only half of my shares are valid, even though I have the
full amount of the original certificates in my possession. I feel I
am wronged and need to know who to turn to for help. _ E.T.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sweat equity, readers, refers to company shares purchased
with deeds rather than dough. It is rare that a merger agreement
exchanges stock one for one. Before you take action, obtain a copy
of the certificate of merger from the secretary of state. The stock
exchange rate will be clearly stated, says Mike Dunn, corporate
finance attorney at Brobeck, Phleger &AMP; Harrison. Feeling
shortchanged after reading it? Pen a letter to the acquiring
company detailing the problem. Still not happy? Hire an attorney
with impressive letterhead to plead your case.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am invited to Thanksgiving dinner and am cooking a turkey
(a real one _ not a relative). The gathering is north of Dallas.
How do I cook it on Wednesday and safely transport it in the car
for more than four hoursThursday? If I arrive with a ptomaine
treat, I won't be invited back. _ C.W.
</P>
<P>
   A: Here is advice from the folks at the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's Meat and Poultry hot line. Save their number for
future fowl fixes: (800) 535-4555. Cook the turkey thoroughly
Wednesday evening. Cool for 20 minutes. Remove the stuffing and
carve the bird into sections (legs, wings, two breast sections).
Refrigerate turkey in portions, not whole. On Thanksgiving morning,
ice the sections in a cooler for the trip. When you arrive, wrap
the sections in foil, add gravy or broth, and reheat in a
325-plus-degree oven (10-15 minutes per pound or until steaming
hot) before devouring.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I applied for citizenship in July 1998 (I'm originally from
England); at the time my son was 10 years old and I was informed I
did not need to apply for him. He would automatically become a
citizen when I did. I had my fingerprints taken in January and have
heard nothing since (there is a big backlog due to staff shortages,
etc.). What happens if my son reaches the age of 12 before I become
a citizen? Would I then have to start an application for him? Is
there a specific age when you have to make a separate application
for a child? I can't seem to get through to the right department at
the Immigration and Naturalization Service to find out. _ Lorraine
E.
</P>
<P>
   A: Relax, Lorraine, you have time.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization spokesman Ray Dudley says a child
``who is a lawful permanent resident and under 18 years of age and
unmarried may automatically derive citizenship through a parent if
the parent becomes lawful citizen.'' Is the father a citizen? If he
is, the child is already a citizen and need only fill out an N600
form, application for a certificate of citizenship. When you become
a citizen, file an N600 for your son. For a form call (800)
870-3676 or download free forms at www.ins.usdoj.gov/. For more
information, call INS at (210) 967-7064 in San Antonio or try _ and
I know it is frustrating _ (800) 375-5283. That number is always
busy because it receives approximately 1,700 calls an hour. Whew!
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it time to take our hummingbird feeders up? _ Susan Patton
</P>
<P>
   A: Depends on which camp you follow. Some bird lovers wait until
they have not seen a hummingbird at the feeder for 10 days before
storing it for the winter. Other birders leave the feeders out
since some hummingbirds choose to winter in Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why does one not have to sign a receipt or enter a personal
code when using a credit card at an automated gasoline pump? If I
use a credit card at an ATM, I enter a personal code. At a
department store, I sign the receipt. At an automated pump, I need
not do either. At the same station, if I pay inside, I sign a
receipt. How is it that credit card companies allow gasoline pumps
to not use any verification?
</P>
<P>
   _ Chip Wolfe
</P>
<P>
   A: The credit card companies consider this type of at-the-pump
transaction to be the same as those conducted over the telephone or
Internet. No signature on either type of line. Visa spokesperson
Tiffany Hilton says the company relies on its fraud detection
system to catch unauthorized use.
</P>
<P>
   UPDATE, UPSHOT, UPROAR
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of birds ... Are you interested in Project Feeder
Watch sponsored by Cornell Laboratory of Ornithology? This
winterlong survey of North American birds is conducted every year
by thousands of bird-feeder watchers. About 43 percent of U.S.
households provide food for wild birds. To join, call (800)
843-BIRD or visit birdsource.cornell.edu /pfw/online.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968. Due to the number of
inquiries, not all questions can be answered or acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
