<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7409 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN26-COX     10-25 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping car on the road and out of casket a challenge
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It's an open-and-shut case of vehicular
homicide. A guy in Morenci, Mich., is standing trial for committing
a crime that most of us, at one time or another, have seriously
contemplated. He shot his transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The accused admits to firing four shotgun blasts into his pickup
truck
</P>
<P>
   because, despite continuous repairs, the stupid thing still
wouldn't start.
</P>
<P>
   The victim was parked only 30 feet from the perpetrator's house
and therein lies the rub _ the law says you can't kill your car
within 150 yards of a
</P>
<P>
   residence.
</P>
<P>
   Americans invest an amazing amount of emotion in their cars,
kind of a
</P>
<P>
   love-hate thing, so it shouldn't come as a surprise when
somebody decides to
</P>
<P>
   blow one away. All of us at one time or another have cursed our
cars for real
</P>
<P>
   or imagined slights, and threatened to drive them into the lake
_ or bay, or
</P>
<P>
   whatever's handy. We even define ``mixed emotions'' as watching
our
</P>
<P>
   mother-in-law drive off a cliff in our new Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   My father, who lived to be 93, had a lifetime of seriously
ambivalent
</P>
<P>
   relationships with automobiles. It apparently began in 1924,
when he and my mother, newly married, were living in New York City.
Daddy decided it was time for them to own a car. In fact, he
already had one in mind _ a shiny black coupe he'd been eyeballing
in the Ford dealer's window.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days later and a few hundred dollars lighter, Mother
and Daddy drove their new car out of the showroom and headed for
the countryside. Barely two minutes into the jaunt, it quit running
_ right in the middle of a bridge. Every attempt to coax it back
into life was a failure that frustrated my father even more.
Finally, he walked around to the passenger's door and helped my
</P>
<P>
   mother out. They hoofed it back to the Ford place where my
father handed the stunned salesman the keys, asked for his check
back, and told them where they could find their car.
</P>
<P>
   Late in 1940, Daddy bought my mother a new Chevy for Christmas.
I went with him to pick it up. It was a Super DeLuxe, two-tone blue
and gray, 4-door sedan. He wrote the dealer a check for $795 and we
took it home. By the following Christmas, the country was at war
and there was not a new car to be had. Automobile manufacturers
retooled and soon tanks instead of convertibles were
</P>
<P>
   rolling off the assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   One snowy day about midway into the war, Mother and I were
driving across
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's high-level bridge when her Christmas present dropped
its left rear
</P>
<P>
   fender. She said it was too dangerous to try to stop and pick it
up, so we drove on. A few minutes later we pulled into the
underground parking lot at the Terminal Tower Building where my
father was waiting for us.
</P>
<P>
   Mother slid over as Daddy came around to the driver's side. He
opened the door, tossed his hat and briefcase on the back seat,
kissed my mother and me, and in a purely conversational tone asked,
``Doris, had you noticed the left-rear fender is gone?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Harry, I had. It's on the high-level bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it doing there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably getting run over.'' End of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   That evening at dinner, Daddy casually asked mother if she'd
call the Chevy dealer the next morning and have him see if he could
scare up a couple of fenders for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why two?'' my mother asked, obviously surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because, Doris,'' my father explained, ``when I kicked the
damned thing
</P>
<P>
   another one fell off.''
</P>
<P>
   There were, of course, no new fenders to be had, but it really
didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   The next week somebody stole our two front tires.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett (AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
