<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7417 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     10-25 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Monday, Oct. 25, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENTAL-ACTIVISTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ With smoke spewing from
factories and waterways bubbling with chemicals, the 1970s were a
decade of awakening, when citizens stepped outside and saw
ecological destruction from their doorsteps. Nowhere was that
awareness greater than on college campuses, including the State
University of New York at Albany, where an activist curriculum and
environmental club had local and national impact. By DINA
CAPPIELLO.
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-ROOTS (San Francisco) _ Seventeen-year-old Jason Lew is
one of 10 Chinese Americans reconnecting with their families'
homeland through ``In Search of Roots,'' a yearlong program of
research and study sponsored by the Chinese Culture Center of San
Francisco, the Chinese Historical Society of America and the
Overseas Chinese Affairs office in Guangdong province of the
People's Republic of China. By ANDREA WOO.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-UCSF (San Francisco) _ When the U.S. Human Genome
Project was launched in 1990, the University of California at San
Francisco did not join the international effort to map the
estimated 100,000 genes in human DNA. UCSF scientists were a
natural fit for the Human Genome Project, but the project couldn't
fit in UCSF. There simply wasn't enough laboratory space. That will
change with the construction of UCSF's new 43-acre research campus.
By SARAH YANG.
</P>
<P>
   JUSTICE-SURVEY (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ Nearly a decade of
tabloid-friendly court dramas, from the trial of William Kennedy
Smith to that of William Jefferson Clinton, have caused a massive
decline in the public's faith in the justice system, according to a
Union College study released last week. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ In previous election years,
Francisco Labastida would have been all but certain to become the
president of Mexico. But now he is fighting for it. For the first
time in the nation's history, voters go to the polls in the
Institutional Revolutionary Party's first primary race on Nov. 7,
and there are three other politicians competing against Labastida.
By SUSANA HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FISHER-BIKES (San Francisco) _ Gary Fisher, the man widely
recognized as one of the founding fathers of the mountain bike, has
a new model, ``Sugar,'' which he describes as a ''happy little
bike,'' that is just hitting the stores. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   JACK-O'-LANTERNS (Undated) _ Pumpkins are as American as apple
pie, but jack-o'-lanterns migrated here from Ireland. If you are
not good at carving, or don't like the mess of scooping out the
pulp and seeds, try painting your pumpkin. And remember: Pumpkins
also make great decorative accessories. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DAVID-CARRADINE (Rhinebeck, N.Y.) _ At the Omega Institute, a
campus-style retreat devoted to holistic studies, David Carradine
was making his debut. The actor best know for his role in the 1970s
cult-hit ``Kung Fu'' was starring in a new role: leading a workshop
on the inner roots of tai chi, a centuries-old Chinese fitness and
health practice sometimes described as meditation in motion. By
DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   TV-TIME-LIFE (Undated) _ Jennifer Love Hewitt has spun off the
angst-filled ``Party of Five,'' where she played a super sweet
girlfriend, and into her own series of that girl grown up, ``Time
of Your Life.'' By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL/BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BANK-Y2K (Albany, N.Y.) _ Planning to make a large cash
withdrawal from Cohoes Savings Bank before New Year's Eve? You'll
most likely get an earful before you get your money. The bank is
one of hundreds that has made tellers the last defense against
people emptying their bank accounts due to the Y2K computer
problem. Doing all they can to eradicate Y2K fears, banks are
training their staff to watch for uncharacteristically large cash
withdrawals. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RATTO-COLUMN (Altanta) _ Well, if the team of the decade
thing doesn't work out for them, maybe the Atlanta Braves can try
not to be confused with the San Diego Padres. Sunday's 7-2 loss to
the New York Yankees marked the first time since the Braves started
dominating the National League that they looked unworthy of their
place. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Minneapolis) _ The 49ers defensive line doesn't know
what to say anymore. Each week, they line up prepared to chase
after opposing quarterbacks. Each week, they're left to wonder why
a front four can be walled off so easily and so often. The team's
40-16 loss to the Minnesota Vikings only added to the mystery. By
JEFFRI CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   FBM-RAIDERS (Oakland, Calif.) _ Perhaps it's some sort of cosmic
justice that Oakland regaled in a 24-23 victory over the New York
Jets Sunday evening, because for the better part of three quarters,
there wasn't much taking place at the Coliseum to suggest victory
was at hand. By MICHELLE SMITH.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ With each cast of my fly rod,
the river seemed full of hope, challenge and reward. I worked my
way thigh deep across from a riffle, then whipped the line
back-and-forth twice and delivered it gently into the run.
Everything was just right, a perfect spot. A big steelhead must be
here, I thought, maybe several. By TOM STEINSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ My local bookstore has shelves of
relationship books with titles like ``Women Can't Hear What Men
Don't Say,'' ``It's a Jungle Out There, Jane'' and even ``Verbal
Abuse Survivors Speak Out.'' I couldn't find a book on the most
important kind of relationship in the Bay Area, the one between
homeowner and contractor. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The words of the New York
Constitution proscribe casino gambling in the state. The document
also spells out the kinds of gambling that are permissible _ Lotto,
pari-mutuel racing, charitable bingo, among others _ and additional
rules to keep the gambling that is allowed from becoming
commercialized. Despite the constitutional restrictions, Indian
casino gambling has been established in two locations in the state
and there is a push to set up a third. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
