<P>
   At Halloween, the boys are always dressed as cowboys, pirates,
soldiers, spacemen and monsters. They become little men of action
or powerful, terrifying monsters. They fantasize dominance. Little
girls are princesses, fairies, brides and angels. In their glitter
and flounces, the girls join the time-honored tradition of helpless
loveliness. It seems that for children, nothing much has changed in
spite of the women's movement, men's groups, the Age of Aquarius
and guys doing dishes. How have girls and boys remained so
untouched by all the years of social upheaval? A thoughtful and
entertaining essay. (Slugged:
BC-HALLOWEEN-COSTUME-CLICHES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF, category code l)
</P>
