   &UR; FRIGHT NIGHT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (600 words) Includes a color slide of the night sky filled with
stars. &QL; 
 &UR; By BOB BERMAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   October can be eerie, all right. Down on Earth the chill winds
blow and the fall colors vanish, replaced by stark, barren
branches. In the sky too, it's a perfectly spooky month _ the ideal
backdrop for the autumn night when the most people roam beneath the
stars: Halloween. In this feature from Discover magazine, Bob
Berman, author of ``Secrets of the Night Sky'' (HarperPerennial
Books), reports on what can be seen in the night sky on spook
night, and how celestial objects tie in to the history of
Halloween. (Slugged: BC-HALLOWEEN-FRIGHT-NIGHT-ART-NYTSF, category
code l)
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
