wrong with wanting things.''
</P>
<P>
   Brownie Humphrey grew up poor in the South, wanting things that
her family could not afford. She met Robert Wise while attending
the Texas Centennial celebration in 1936. They married shortly
thereafter. With the Depression hard upon Dixie, the newlyweds lit
out for Detroit. Robert Wise found a job on a Ford assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   The union was unhappy and short-lived. Three years after the
birth of their only child, a son named Jerry, they divorced in
1941. By then, though, the industrious Brownie Wise had adopted the
pen name ``Hibiscus'' and was writing a column for women in the
Detroit News.
</P>
<P>
   In the column, ``Hibiscus'' was a transplanted Southern belle
who lived in a modern, well-furnished house called ``Lovehaven''
with her successful and adoring husband, ``Yankee,'' and their
infant son, ``Tiny Hands.'' The sentimental columns about marital
bliss and conspicuous consumption contrasted starkly with Wise's
actual circumstances. She and her son and been abandoned by Robert
Wise and were financially imperiled, according to the Smithsonian
book.
</P>
<P>
   To augment her writing income, Wise started selling Stanley Home
Products. The company employed former housewives as saleswomen and
encouraged them to push its wares through their social contacts.
</P>
<P>
   At about this same time, halfway across the country in
Leominster, Mass., a former DuPont chemical company employee named
Earl Tupper was trying to design plastic products for home use. In
1942, he invented a flexible plastic bowl with a ``non-snap'' lid
that could be sealed securely after the air inside the container
was released.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately aware of the possibilities for the product, the
fledgling inventor envisioned a ``Tupperization'' of the American
home. Spills and odors would be eliminated and leftovers exalted
through use of the lightweight plastic containers with the airtight
seal, he foresaw.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, America's housewives were unreceptive. Tupperware
arrived in stores in the late 1940s, after the war had ended, and
languished on shelves.
</P>
<P>
   After initially being hailed as the miracle material for the
future, plastic had disappointed many consumers by cracking or
being otherwise unreliable. Also, to be appreciated, the unique
Tupperware lid and ``burp'' had to be demonstrated, and store
clerks were not up to the job. Although heavily advertised in
magazines, by 1948 ``stacks of Tupperware collected dust on the
shelves of hardware stores across the United States,'' Clarke
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   However, in Detroit, Brownie Wise had discovered Tupperware. She
purchased some through a plastics dealer and began selling it along
with her line of Stanley Home Products. Indeed, Wise and a group of
saleswomen that she had organized as the Patio Parties team were
selling so much Tupperware that Earl Tupper summoned her to
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of meetings, Tupper decided to abandon all store
sales. He hired Wise to set up a national distribution system using
her ``hostess plan.'' A middle-aged, divorced mother with no formal
business training, Brownie Wise would head the newly formed
Tupperware Home Parties Inc. to sell the growing line of plastic
containers.
</P>
<P>
   The system was an immediate and spectacular success.
</P>
<P>
   Working on commissions, a Tupperware distributor _ almost always
a woman _ would recruit an acquaintance to invite friends and
neighbors to a party in her home. At this quasi-social affair, the
distributor would demonstrate Tupperware products and take orders.
The ``hostess'' received Tupperware ``gifts'' for providing the
home and customers.
</P>
<P>
   With young families filling new suburbs across America,
Tupperware parties quickly became a national institution.
</P>
<P>
   Without the parties, said Clarke, ``Tupperware would have been a
design failure _ for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Although still single, Brownie Wise abruptly began living a
flamboyant Southern lifestyle similar to the one she had envisioned
in her ``Hibiscus'' column. Corporate headquarters for Tupperware
Home Parties would be a gleaming white building surrounded by 1,000
acres of gardens and lakes on the Orange Blossom Trail near
Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Wise's own lakeside mansion in nearby Kissimmee was filled with
the ``modern'' furniture of the '50s. There was an indoor swimming
pool and a cabin cruiser docked out back.
</P>
<P>
   She drove a ``Tupperware Rose''-colored convertible and kept a
matching pink canary caged in her office.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian book describes how Wise was asked by a women's
magazine if she had considered remarriage. ``Why should I?'' she
replied. ``My work provides me with all the fun, excitement and
emotional outlets I could ever want. ... It enables me to give
other women in financial trouble the same chance I had to help
themselves to happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, she became the first woman to appear on the cover of
``Business Week.'' The key to Tupperware's success was the women
who recruited ``hostesses'' and enthusiastically demonstrated the
product at parties, she told the magazine. ``If we build the
people, they'll build the business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For motivation, she invited top distributors to elaborate
Homecoming Jubilees. At the 1954 event, Wise dressed in Western
garb and invited distributors to ``dig for gold'' on the grounds of
the company's Florida headquarters. Issued shovels, the women dug
out buried mink stoles, diamond rings and other loot _ including a
toy car to be exchanged for a real one.
</P>
<P>
   The 1957 Homecoming Jubilee featured a ``wish fairy'' _ complete
with tiara and magic wand _ who granted the wishes of top
saleswomen.
</P>
<P>
   Wise reveled in the glamour and materialism. But Earl Tupper, a
stern New Englander, thought such displays showed bad taste. He
thought the publicity about the parties and Jubilees was
overshadowing the product itself, Clarke wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, Wise left Tupperware with a $30,000 separation payment
for what was called ``semi-retirement.'' The details of her
departure were never announced to the public or even to her
party-giving saleswomen.
</P>
<P>
   Later that same year, the Tupper Corp. and Tupperware Home
Parties Inc. were sold to the Rexall Drug Co. for $16 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wise stayed near Kissimmee and worked as a marketing consultant
for several cosmetics firms. She died at the age of 79 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Part of her legacy is the Museum of Historic Food Containers
near Orlando. Created by Wise in the 1950s as the Museum of Dishes,
the facility traces the history of cooking and food storage from
Egyptian earthenware from 4000 B.C. to, well, Tupperware.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
