KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
Oct. 26. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   DOLE: Bob Dole delivers a talk at Kansas State University.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER: A Smithville teen who's in a wheelchair is charged today,
probably in both Clay County and in Massachusetts, with making
terroristic threats across the Internet. We cover the court action
and profile the kid. Bill Graham and Jerry Berrios. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL: When it comes to the American Royal, Brenda Spencer and
Julie Weiss are two people from different backgrounds. For Spencer
the Royal is a family tradition. Each year the Kansas architect
follows her dad's footsteps by running the Royal's ``Ring Gang,''
15 guys who keep Hale and Kemper Arenas operating smoothly. Weiss
is a Kansas City advertising account executive who hadn't attended
the Royal since she was a kid. Now she's coordinating this year's
new mass media ad campaign. They represent the crossroads for
Kansas City's 100-year old rodeo and livestock event: celebrating
tradition while replacing the loss of about 40,000 FFA attendees.
This year the Royal has different entertainers such as Bill Cosby,
more prize money for the big livestock events and other attractions
to bring in crowds. Ruth Igoe. 35. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MEL: Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan calls a morning news conference
after Republicans contend that a 39-year-old newspaper photograph
of Carnahan in blackface shows Carnahan is not the progressive
Democrat he claims to be. Will Sentell.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   CODES _ This much we know. Sometime in the near future, we will
exhaust our supply of new area codes, which means, theoretically,
we won't be able to get telephone lines for our offices or homes.
What is less certain is exactly when. One industry group says the
nation's phone numbering plan is okay for 25 years. But other
experts, meeting this week in Washington, predict we will deplete
our 10-digit system as soon as 2006. By Paul Wenske. Graphic
</P>
<P>
   TRADE _ An independent Kansas City area restaurant has called
itself Big Boy's for more than 30 years raises issues of trademark
and intellectual property rights. Joyce Smith
</P>
