</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACK-O'-LANTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK-O'-LANTERNS HAVE THEIR ROOTS IN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pumpkins are as American as apple pie, but jack-o'-lanterns
migrated here from Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The name stems from an Irish legend about a stingy man named
Jack, who was too mean to get to heaven and who played tricks on
the devil. In death, Jack's penance was to walk Earth carrying a
lantern carved from a turnip and illuminated by a burning piece of
coal.
</P>
<P>
   He became known as ``Jack of the Lantern,'' or
``Jack-o'-lantern.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish tradition was to place jack-o'-lanterns carved from
root vegetables in windows and by doors to scare away Stingy Jack
and other spirits on Halloween, or All Hallows' Eve, the day before
All Saints' Day, when churches honored the saints.
</P>
<P>
   In Medieval times children went door-to-door, singing and
begging for soul cakes for the wandering spirits. If no cakes were
offered, beggars or souls played pranks. Irish immigrants
introduced secular Halloween customs to the United States in the
late 19th century. Pumpkins replaced root vegetables and
``souling'' evolved into trick-or-treating. Today, many pumpkins
feature decorative carvings and portraiture.
</P>
<P>
   To aid in the carving, the kitchen knife has been replaced by
pumpkin carving kits costing up to $6, which also include a series
of templates for art-challenged carvers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Guinness Book of World Records, the world's
largest carved jack-o'-lantern came from an 827-pound pumpkin grown
in 1992 in Nut Tree, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not good at carving, or don't like the mess of
scooping out the pulp and seeds, try painting a face on your
pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkins also make great decorative accessories, either as a
grouping on a table or for holding hot or chilled soups, dips,
candy (use a plastic liner) or votive candles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7477 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-HNS &LR;      10-25 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S PRESIDENTIAL FRONT-RUNNER FINDS HE MUST WORK FOR VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The man who could be the next president of Mexico
could not get away from the well-wishers. They hugged him, gave him
advice and offered food.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida, the leading candidate to win the nomination
of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, had to gulp down
a dripping taco before he was able to drive off in a waiting black
Chevrolet Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   On a hazy Saturday, in the relaxed mood that only a weekend can
bring out in this jammed capital, Labastida had just finished
talking to a supportive, albeit somewhat discontent, crowd of about
3,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   In polite but firm voices, the likely Labastida supporters from
four rural electoral districts talked about their hopes for the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   They want more jobs, better salaries, less corruption; they
demanded rights for women and teachers; they complained about the
environment and their small plots of land, where it is becoming
harder to survive growing corn and beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no equality in this country!'' one woman shouted when
it was her turn at the microphone. ``We are just as intelligent as
men, and we want a place in this world. Don't be fooled by
promises! Make the candidates prove it with their actions!''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, crisp in a blue shirt and brown khakis, listened and
jotted notes. He would have an answer for the angry young woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want very much to be candidate of women,'' he told the crowd
gathered at the sports complex. ``I understand that the conditions
for equality have not been fully realized.''
</P>
<P>
   He then promised to create a national institute for women, to
promote social justice, increase wages and fight corruption and
crime.
</P>
<P>
   In previous election years, Labastida would have been all but
certain to become the president of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But now he is fighting for it. He is in the unprecedented
position of having to campaign to become the presidential nominee
of the PRI, which has dominated Mexican politics for 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 7, Mexican voters go to the polls in the PRI's
first-ever primary race, and there are three other candidates
competing against Labastida to decide the party nominee in the 2000
election.
</P>
<P>
   The primary race is heating up, with the candidates stumping for
votes and bombarding the airwaves with American-style television
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In these ads, Labastida is the candidate with ``clean hands,''
the one not soiled by shady dealings, and the cameras zoom him on
his entwined arms.
</P>
<P>
   It alludes to the non-clean hands of Roberto Madrazo,
Labastida's closest rival in the PRI contest, whom critics allege
took corrupt money to finance his campaign for governor of Tabasco
state.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo accuses Labastida of being the ``official candidate,''
the chosen heir in a failed political system.
</P>
<P>
   The other men vying for the PRI nomination are Manuel Bartlett,
the former governor of Puebla state, and former PRI leader Humberto
Roque Villanueva.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, 57, who has been Mexico's secretary of the interior
and of agriculture, has had to fight this image of the chosen one _
not a good option in a country growing weary of the system.
</P>
<P>
   But his effort proved counter-productive. So he turned it to his
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make power work for you,'' say his political ads, admitting,
in a way, the force behind him.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, voters saw him as the favorite successor to
President Ernesto Zedillo, whose 6-year term expires next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has helped with voters to know he is the official
candidate,'' said 21-year-old law student Luz Maria Gutierrez. ``Of
all the four candidates, he is more honest and sincere. But in
Mexico, it helps when you know the candidate is the president's
choice. It's the way people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the PRI's history, that is the way it's been done in
Mexico _ the president selected his successor, and this man always
won.
</P>
<P>
   But now there is a nascent democracy. While welcomed by most, it
also perplexes many longtime PRI members, men like Jesus Molotla
Mundo, 66, a crusty farmer wearing a straw hat as he waits on a
bench with three friends to hear Labastida speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why there are four candidates. Do you know
why? This has never happened before. It is strange,'' Molotla said.
``But you know, they all make promises, and as soon as they become
president they forget about their promises. Maybe this one will be
different.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The son of a doctor, Labastida grew up with three brothers and
two sisters in the small town of Los Mochis in western Sinaloa
state, where he was governor from 1987 until 1992. He has said he
learned firsthand about the suffering and needs of the poor while
going on rounds to the countryside with his father.
</P>
<P>
   While a student of economics at the National Autonomous
University in Mexico City, Labastida married when he was 20. He has
five grown children, and today he is married to Maria Teresa
Uriarte, a doctorate in history who heads a research institute at
the Autonomous University, where Labastida also was a professor of
international economics.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being the apparent front-runner, Labastida has stiff
competition in 48-year-old Madrazo, whose renegade campaign could
also end up dividing the PRI when the primary race is over.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett and Roque have made the same promises of Labastida and
Madrazo, but they don't get personal. They don't mention anything
about official candidates, they don't call each other ``liar'' or
``failure,'' as Madrazo and Labastida have been known to do.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a Labastida presidency, Bartlett and Roque could end
up working in the Cabinet. Maybe even Madrazo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to see how we can incorporate them,'' admitted
Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   He talks like a winner. He sees the possibility of losing, but
doesn't think it likely.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks the PRI or his candidacy has been hurt by the
``official'' candidate label, Labastida is quick with a
mathematical answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't we see this in terms of numbers, because arithmetic
is the most precise language. Verbal language is filled with
emotion and adjectives, but numerical language expresses what is
occurring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preference for the party at this time last year was at
over 37 (percentage) points,'' he added. ``Now it is over 47
points, 10 points over. So this has not hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
