<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7481 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-ENVIRONMENTAL-ACTIVIS     10-25 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENTAL-ACTIVISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT GROUP SPURRED ENVIRONMENTAL AWAKENING IN '70S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DINA CAPPIELLO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ They met late into the night in a darkened room
deep inside the art department on campus. Students and professors
crawled through open windows to grab a seat. With shades drawn,
they made plans to heal the planet.
</P>
<P>
   With smoke spewing from factories and waterways bubbling with
chemicals, the 1970s were a decade of awakening, when citizens
stepped outside and saw ecological destruction from their
doorsteps.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was that awareness greater than on college campuses,
where the first Earth Day, a nationwide teach-in, took place on
April 22, 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pollution was everywhere. Certain parts of the river you could
throw a match on and they'd burn. Developers were trying to rape
the land that wasn't developed,'' said Don Rittner, a 1973 graduate
of the environmental studies program at the State University of New
York at Albany. ``You had a generation that looked around and said,
`What are we doing to our planet?' and decided to do something
about it. That was the birth of the environmental movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before New York state had an Environmental Conservation
Department, SUNY-Albany had a Protect Your Environment club. The
group formed during a time of protest, borrowing energy from the
anti-Vietnam War movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1969 we basically shut down the university,'' said George
Keleshian, the president of what came to be called PYE. ``There was
a lot of questioning at the time by students about the impact of
the corporate structure on the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   PYE's office was open 24 hours a day, and people called daily
asking for help with environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even local religious leaders asked me to explain what was
going on,'' recalled Louis Ismay, a professor in SUNY-Albany's
short-lived environmental studies program.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called the Environmental Forum, became a weekly
stage for the major environmental issues of the day. Toilet paper
floated down the Hudson River, and in a section known as the Albany
Pool, massive fish kills occurred every summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ismay's nine-credit course had two major requirements. The first
was to have a broad understanding of the issues. The second was to
choose one and take a leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to tell them that you could catch more flies with honey
than vinegar. Environmentalism shouldn't have to be
confrontational,'' he said. ``It's righteous indignation. You have
a right to be indignant about destruction of the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   The fury fostered on campus spread to outlying communities,
seeping into the public's consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grass-roots impact on environmental issues was embraced in
the oft-quoted bumper sticker `Act Locally, Think Globally,''' said
John Mylod, director of Hudson River sloop Clearwater from 1976 to
1994. ``More people became aware of the impacts pollution carries
and the restrictions on natural resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader was the featured speaker for Earth Day on April 22,
1970. He declared PYE the most active group in the nation and in
his next breath announced the formation of the New York Public
Interest Research Group, an advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who was anybody in the environment was involved. We
were tackling issues that were national and international from this
area,'' Keleshian said.
</P>
<P>
   Political science professor Robert Reinow wrote a book titled
``Moment in the Sun,'' which predicted a glut of people inhabiting
an exhausted Earth, and taught a class, ``Man Against the
Environment.'' Said Ismay: ``Every country in the world was
distributing buttons that said, `Nuclear Power, No Thanks.'''
</P>
<P>
   The fervor at SUNY-Albany wouldn't last long. PYE dissolved,
along with the Environmental Studies Program, when its funding was
cut in the late 1970s. Some blame it on a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of resentment for the Environmental Studies
Program,'' said Jon Thoreau Scott, its acting director for three
years. ``The faculty was not inclined to have a program they
thought was wishy-washy and in which the students were
rabble-rousers.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Stewart, director of the university's present-day
Biodiversity, Conservation and Policy master's program, was one of
those concerned about the activity fueled by the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The involvement of the students scared the administration to
death,'' she said. ``The war movement was all tied up with the
environmental revolution. It didn't last.''
</P>
<P>
   Or did it? Without doubt, the battleground has changed. In the
'70s, ``You could take cardboard and picket a plant and force
change,'' Mylod said. ``This has become much more difficult in the
last 20 to 30 years. Now you need legislation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
