<HEADER>
A7531 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-25 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASINOS ONLY INVITE TROUBLE FOR INDIAN TRIBES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Constitution proscribes casino gambling
in the state. The document also spells out the kinds of gambling
that are permissible _ Lotto, pari-mutuel racing, charitable bingo,
among others _ and additional rules to keep the gambling that is
allowed from becoming commercialized.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the constitutional restrictions, Indian casino gambling
has been established in two locations in the state and there is a
push to set up a third. Two lawsuits basing their opposition to
Indian casino gambling on constitutional grounds have been filed in
at the entry level of the court system, the state Supreme Court.
More than likely, the final interpretation of the constitution will
be made by the state's highest court, the Court of Appeals, some
distance down the road.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the argument are the Indian tribes, supported by
Gov. George Pataki and his administration, following in the
footsteps of his predecessor, Mario Cuomo. They base their stand on
the singular economic prosperity that casino gambling promises to
bring to otherwise economically parched reservations, with their
vast numbers of unemployed or underemployed Indians.
</P>
<P>
   They are supported by the U.S. government through its Bureau of
Indian Affairs. Since Congress in 1988 passed the Indian Gaming
Regulatory Act, the bureau has directed the governors of states to
conclude compacts with tribes seeking to set up casinos on their
reservations, which are considered to be sovereign territory.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the governor and some of his deputies to court is a
coalition of strange bedfellows _ the horse racing interests
seeking to protect their turf allied with religious groups making
their stand on moral grounds, along with strict constitutional
constructionists. Extremely interested on the sidelines are the
likes of Donald Trump, trying to guard the revenues of his own
gambling casinos in not-so-far-away Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   One of the arguments made by the plaintiffs is that the U.S.
government has no power to instruct New York's governor to violate
his own constitution. They also argue that even if both houses of
the State Legislature vote to support the compact with the Indians
made by Cuomo and enlarged by Pataki, which they have yet to do,
they would first have to amend the state's constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the New York Constitution, in addition to
forbidding casinos, bars anyone but volunteers from operating or
managing the gambling games. Paid help is not allowed. This is the
opposite of what the Indian enterprises are about.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is not strictly limited to the reservations set up by
treaties and congressional mandate over the past 100 years and
more. By a device, they can buy land far away from their home
grounds, as the St. Regis-Mohawk Tribe is hoping to do in the
Catskills, and have it assumed as an Indian trust territory by
Washington. Then, the Indians can set up casinos in more populated
areas that would provide the multitude of gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   This conflict goes beyond the contentions of the parties
involved. In the first place, it speaks loud and clear to
deprivations of many Native Americans, who are sitting out the
great economic boom. New York state cannot evade doing its share,
along with the federal government, to see that Indians emerge from
their status as second-class citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Providing that help by supporting gambling rights for the
Indians is not solving the problem so much as compounding it.
Instead of marshalling the resources of government to fulfill
obligations, the state becomes a cohort in exploiting the
vulnerable among us. There is ample evidence that the people who
can least afford it are most addicted to gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, organized crime lurks at the edges of casino gambling,
and the New York Constitution takes note of it. So much money can
be involved that the bonanza is a magnet to draw all sorts of funny
money from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   As casino gambling proliferates in the state, it surely would
become a principal contributor to politicians and political
campaigns, buying its way into ever greater insulation from
governmental supervision and restraint. It has happened elsewhere,
why not here?
</P>
<P>
   Even if gambling were a quick fix for some Native-American
travails, it creates a host of nasty problems that will soon enough
undermine the best of intentions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
