<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7536 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-DAVID-CARRADINE-HNS &LR;      10-25 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVID-CARRADINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KUNG FU' STAR FINDS NEW ROLE IN TEACHING CHINESE MEDITATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RHINEBECK, N.Y. _ The spacious lodge is full of aging baby
boomers sitting still in a meditative pose as they follow David
Carradine's every move and directive. He offers four words of
advice: ``Don't forget to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   No one else laughs, although the actor best known for his role
in the 1970s cult-hit television series ``Kung Fu'' can't help
himself. Sitting in a lotus position on a platform at the front of
the room, he flashes a boyish grin. ``It's important,'' he adds.
``Breathe slowly and deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to dance; extreme activity,'' he says, ``and then we
need to sit; extreme quietness. Try and think about very little, or
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first Friday in October, and stars filled the autumn
sky over the Hudson River Valley. At the Omega Institute, a
campus-style retreat on 140 acres in rural Dutchess County devoted
to holistic studies, Carradine was making his debut. Earlier in the
year, such notables as Deepak Chopra and Robert Bly had been
teaching here.
</P>
<P>
   Carradine was leading a three-day workshop on the inner roots of
tai chi, a centuries-old Chinese fitness and health practice
sometimes described as meditation in motion, and this was the
closing minutes of the opening session.
</P>
<P>
   Both the course and the instructor clearly fascinated the 150 or
so men and women, most of them older than 40, who had paid $225 to
attend the workshop, plus as much as an additional $250 to stay
over for two nights in a cabin at Omega, some 60 miles south of
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Carradine had brought with him four teachers, including two
martial arts experts who led the group through exercises for most
of the first two hours. But the celebrity who became a devotee of
kung fu and Shaolin philosophy well ahead of the '90s New Age curve
was the reason all had come, hoping to expand their own mind-body
connections and possibly make tai chi a part of their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest son of one of America's most successful acting
families (his father was character actor John Carradine, who
appeared in such notable films as ``The Grapes of Wrath''; his
younger half-brothers include Keith and Robert Carradine), the
teacher has survived a well-documented marathon struggle with
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   He says he's been sober for more than three years now, and, at
63, David Carradine is lean and wiry, save for a slight paunch. His
cheekbones and high forehead are pronounced, and there is some gray
in the thinning, straight, sandy hair.
</P>
<P>
   Carradine knows how to entertain. He is a raconteur, recalling
how the offbeat TV series (1972-'75) made him aware of kung fu, and
inspired an interest that quickly blossomed into a passion that has
been the one constant in his life for the last quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   Carradine's stories seem to have no middle or end; they are, it
is safe to say, more free-flowing than tai chi exercises.
</P>
<P>
   He was barefoot, wearing black pants and a black T-shirt with a
large dragon stenciled across the back. An amulet hung around his
neck, and there was a watch on each wrist.
</P>
<P>
   After spending three years on the ``Kung Fu'' TV series, which
shows up regularly on reruns featuring then-unknown guest stars
such as Harrison Ford and Jodie Foster, Carradine turned his
attention to movies.
</P>
<P>
   But other than landing the role of Woody Guthrie in the heralded
``Bound for Glory'' (1976) and teaming up with his brothers and the
Keach and Quaid brothers in the stylistic western ``The Long
Riders'' (1980), this one-time dancer and Broadway actor's career
went backward or nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   So well-known as Kwai Chang Caine, the wandering
Chinese-American warrior-philosopher-priest in the ``Kung Fu''
series, Carradine was reduced to taking parts in mostly forgettable
straight-to-video movies full of high kicks and revenge.
</P>
<P>
   He was also drinking and carrying on, living an out-of-control
existence while at the same time pursuing Chinese martial arts that
are based on harmony and self-discipline. Carradine declined to be
interviewed during his three days at Omega, and it was unclear how
or even whether he explains this seeming paradox.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, speaking to People magazine to promote his
role in ``The New Swiss Family Robinson,'' a made-for-TV movie in
which he played a buccaneer bad guy who menaces the stranded
family, Carradine reflected on his turbulent times:
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame it all on the alcohol,'' he said. ``I am an
arrogant son of a b---. I did a hell of a lot of damage and it
wasn't clear if my career was going to survive at all.''
</P>
<P>
   His personal life was in shambles, too, as he was married and
divorced three times. He is now on marriage No. 4, to actress
Marina Benjamin, and he credits her with helping him quit drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Carradine says sobriety has allowed him to mend fences with his
three children: Calista, 37, an actress; Free, 26, a special
effects artist; and Kansas, 21, a student. Free, who also uses the
name Tom, was one of the results of Carradine's highly publicized
six-year relationship with actress Barbara Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   The one vice Carradine has apparently been unable to overcome is
cigarettes. While herbal tea is now his drink of choice, unfiltered
English Oval smokes were never far away. Three times during the
first two-hour session at Omega, while other instructors led the
group, Carradine stepped out of the lodge. The unmistakable smell
of strong tobacco wafted through the open windows.
</P>
<P>
   Carradine promised that during the course, through an extensive
Saturday and Sunday morning, those at the workshop would gain some
insight into how tai chi works, and how important it is ``to get
your own temple in order.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is almost too much New Age for me, but I want to improve
the moment to moment texture of our daily existence,'' he said.
``You need to experience the tension before you can get rid of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lifetime is not long enough to master the art of tai chi.
You'll always have something new happening to your mind and body.
But unlike aerobics or bike riding or something like that, you
won't be stuck in repetition. It's a growing thing. And, unlike
aerobics, you won't have to listen to disco either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
