A7540 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-ARTISTIC-MILLENNIUM-A     10-25 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTISTIC-MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Music, art and literature have defined the high points of the
human spirit over the last thousand years. In a series of articles,
The New York Times Magazine has identified some of the major
influences on our hearts and minds.
</P>
<P>
   The articles described below have been written for the
``Millennium Issues'' of the magazine and are available for oneshot
purchase from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   For purchase information, contact one of the following New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `HAMLET' IS THE BEST `POEM' OF THE MILLENIUM
 &UR; (700 words)
 &UR; By HELEN VENDLER
</P>
<P>
   It is no betrayal of the form to proclaim ``Hamlet'' the
greatest poem of the millennium. Its lyric structure gives us
Hamlet's high consciousness, tragic and mocking, arching like a
glittering spider web over the dramatic action. Hamlet is always at
the center: All the other figures in the play are there to provoke,
to repudiate, to interrupt his brilliant cascades of language.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-POEM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BYRON AND THE LOST ART OF IMMORTALITY
 &UR; (1,500 words)
 &UR; By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN
</P>
<P>
   By age 36, Lord Byron, the original bad boy of English
literature, had made a nation of repressed women swoon despite his
escapades. Notwithstanding a malformed foot, he was as famous for
his athletic prowess as for his brand of cynicism. He lacked only
one thing to insure his immortality: a really good death. And this
came about with perfect filmic melodrama in 1824. Byron and his era
gave us the cliche of the artist gladly outraging society,
asserting the primacy of his opinion and claiming absolute
indifference to public reaction. These became essential aspects of
Romanticism, and 200 years later they are still entwined in our
definition of creative genius.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLEN-ME-KIMMELMAN)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST STORY OF THE LAST THOUSAND YEARS
 &UR; (2,000 words)
 &UR; By A.S. BYATT
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thousand and One Nights'' has everything a tale should
have. Sex, death, treachery, humor, surprise and a happy ending.
Though it appears to be a story against women, it actually marks
the creation of one of the strongest and cleverest heroines in
world literature. Scheherazade triumphs because she is endlessly
inventive. Her stories deal with love and life and death and money
and food and all the other human necessities.
</P>
<P>
   Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-STORY
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAINTERS HAVE OFTEN WRITTEN THE FIRST DRAFT OF HISTORY
 &UR; (2,200 words)
 &UR; By JOHN RUSSELL
</P>
<P>
   Seven major images of the millennium have shaped our
understanding of history. All are unforgettable. All, in one way or
another, are about definitive moments not only in individual lives
but also in the lives of all of us. They tell us what human beings
will do to other human beings. Some of it is encouraging. Some of
it isn't. Either way, we get it full in the face.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-SCENES-RUSSELL)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINALLY, ART THROUGH WOMEN'S EYES
 &UR; (1,300 words)
 &UR; By HOLLAND COTTER
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, in high art, men were the image shapers, and it's
not hard to notice that their pictures of women differ from women's
pictures of women. This is significant when we consider how deeply
our cultural reflexes, and our sexual politics, have been
influenced by images of women: woman as mother, as goddess, as muse
or sex object. Now after centuries of conforming to men's views and
stereotypes, female artists are taking control of their own images.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-ART)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE `VANISHING POINT' INTRODUCED PERSPECTIVE TO PAINTING
 &UR; (500 words) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The signal art work of the millennium (let's narrow it down and
stick to the West) no longer exists, and is only mentioned in a
text from the 1480s, a biography of Filippo Brunelleschi. The
Florentine architect is credited with inventing perspective, the
system for representing three dimensions in two, so that, in a
painting or drawing, a beautiful lady's string of pearls would look
closer than the map on the wall. Perspective works by having a
vanishing point, or single spot at which all parallel lines going
from near to far theoretically converge, the effect of which
creates an illusion of depth.
</P>
<P>
   (SLUGGED BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-ART)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST COMEDY OF THE LAST THOUSAND YEARS
 &UR; (500 words)
 &UR; By DAVID LODGE
</P>
<P>
   Who wrote the best comedy of the last thousand years? Well,
there was Shakespeare, and there was Moliere. But if we use as a
simple measure the power to amuse, then we'd have to decide for
Oscar Wilde's ``Importance of Being Earnest.''
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-COMEDY)
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
<P>
   (New York headquarters: 212-499-3300 or 1-800-972-3550; fax,
212-499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   Visit our Web site at http://nytimes.com/syndicate.
</P>
