A7550 &Cx1f; tab-z
r v BC-LOVE-MILLENNIUM-ADVIS     10-25 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVE-MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   When you think about it, love really has made the world go
'round over the last thousand years. In a series of articles, The
New York Times Magazine looks at love's history, including some
high points and low points.
</P>
<P>
   The articles described below have been written for the
``Millennium Issues'' of the magazine and are available for oneshot
purchase from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   For purchase information, contact one of the following New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUE LOVE MAY LAST FOREVER, BUT IT HASN'T BEEN AROUND THAT LONG
 &UR; (1,100 words)
 &UR; By JOYCE CAROL OATES
</P>
<P>
   Love in the Western world has come to mean, in the popular
imagination, romantic love almost exclusively. But it may come as a
surprise to learn that the very concept of ``love'' based on
emotion as a high value, and not as an outlaw passion, is
relatively new in the history of mankind. In the ancient world,
romantic love would seem to have been virtually unknown, and rarely
celebrated. Our generic term ``love'' didn't exist. The sentiment
of romantic love as we know it was the homoerotic love of older
Greek men for boys. Marital love, which surely existed, seems oddly
not to have been much honored, at least in surviving literature.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-IDEA)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HELOISE, THE MILLENNIUM'S ULTIMATE LOVER
 &UR; (500 words)
 &UR; By JEFFREY EUGENIDES
</P>
<P>
   Why does Heloise, a reluctant, heartbroken 12th-century nun,
stand out among the millennium's romantic figures? Not simply
because of her shameless intelligence, which won her the right to
be treated as a thinking self at a time when most women were not.
Nor because of her gifts as a classical logician. It is because of
her lifelong refusal to condemn or forget the pleasures of a
passion that ruined her life.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged: BC-MILLEN-ME-EUGENIDES)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST LOVESONG OF THE MILLENNIUM
 &UR; (750 words)
 &UR; By LORRIE MOORE
</P>
<P>
   Richard Strauss knew that love triangles make the best music,
and proved it in ``Der Rosenkavalier.'' At the opera's penultimate
moment, the older woman (the Marschallin) elegantly gives up her
young lover (Octavian) upon glimpsing him newly in love with
someone his own age (Sophie). Love is simultaneously embraced and
selflessly surrendered in a song that has the melodic depths and
passion of Wagner but the libretto and spirit of Mozart. The clock
has run out on the Marschallin's romantic life. She has had her
chance, her time, and now she must bow out _ how suited to the
close of this last thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-LOVESONG)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW COULD SUCH A PASSION EVER DIE?
 &UR; (450 words)
 &UR; By JOSEPHINE HART
</P>
<P>
   The sex scandal of the millennium didn't involve Clintons or
Windsors, although it did involve an English king. This one changed
the laws of God and man, created a saint and destroyed a courtier
of Machiavellian brilliance. It was Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn. How
could such a passion ever die? Perhaps, as has been said, ``only
the little loves last.''
</P>
<P>
   Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SCANDAL
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
<P>
   (New York headquarters: 212-499-3300 or 1-800-972-3550; fax,
212-499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   Visit our Web site at http://nytimes.com/syndicate.
</P>
