</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-IDEA)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MOST IMPORTANT CONCEPT OF THE MILLENNIUM
 &UR; (3,000 words)
 &UR; By RICHARD POWERS
</P>
<P>
   The most important idea of this millennium was set in motion by
a man named Abu Ali al-Hasan Ibn al-Haytham, born around the year
965. The idea he championed is so ingrained in us that we don't
even think of it as an innovation. But he resolved a scientific
dispute that had remained deadlocked for more than 800 years, using
observation rather than reason. Over the course of 1,000 years,
this conceptual shift would would transform every aspect of
existence.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-CONCEPT)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO WAS THE BEST LEADER OF THE MILLENNIUM?
 &UR; (500 Words)
 &UR; BY GAIL COLLINS
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look how well she governs,'' the once-reluctant subjects
of Elizabeth I, the Virgin Queen, later would remark. For the
ravishing ruler exceeded all expectations, and by now she is
namesake to an era.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-LEADER)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST RANDOM SHOT IN HISTORY?
 &UR; (500 words)
 &UR; By CHARLES McGRATH
</P>
<P>
   A nameless bowman in the forests of Normandy took a random shot
and from 100 yards pierced the right eye of King Harold of England.
It was during the Battle of Hastings in 1066, and that arrow in the
eye changed the English language.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SHOT)
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
