<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   War and peace and the pursuit of freedom have been recurring
themes over the last millennium. In a series of articles, The New
York Times Magazine has highlighted some of the significant events
that have shaped our socio-political geography.
</P>
<P>
   The articles described below have been written for the
``Millennium Issues'' of the magazine and are available for oneshot
purchase from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   For purchase information, contact one of the following New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `EVERY DICTATOR'S NIGHTMARE'
 &UR; (2,200 words)
 &UR; By WOLE SOYINKA
</P>
<P>
   The message, whether from Yoruban elders or the Founding
Fathers, the Bible or the Koran, is the same: Certain fundamental
rights are inherent to all humanity. It is a noble idea that has
spread by its own power in this millennium and has now begun to
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-DEMOCRACY)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MOST COMPELLING REVOLUTION OF OUR TIME
 &UR; By ALAN BRINKLEY
 &UR; (750 words)
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Mohandas K. Gandhi, the peacemaker, India won its
freedom without firing a shot. He has been mythologized since his
assassination in 1948, but he deserves his position as a symbol of
one of the most important phenomena of modern history: the
simultaneous assault on colonialism and on the oppression of
individuals, which has transformed much of the 20th-century world.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-REVOLUTION)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST TREATY OF THE MILLENNIUM
 &UR; (600 words)
 &UR; By FAREED ZAKARIA
</P>
<P>
   Some treaties mark the birth of whole new concepts of
international relations. The Peace of Westphalia in 1648 brought an
end to the Thirty Years' War, the deadliest conflict in history
until then, in which perhaps 10 million people died. It also
ushered in the modern state system that governs our world _ the
very system that is now, 350 years later, being undermined by
transnational forces like the euro, the Internet and Amnesty
International.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-TREATY)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOST IMPORTANT BATTLE OF THE MILLENNIUM
 &UR; (800 WORDS)
 &UR; By R.W. APPLE JR.
</P>
<P>
   Much was at stake when Burgoyne rolled the dice and lost the
Battle of Saratoga. As a result, France entered the war on the
American side and Washington and his ragtag army at Valley Forge
saw the road to ultimate victory. The millennium would see other
great battles, such as Gettysburg and D-Day. But in the last 1,000
years, I think, only the defeat of the Turks by Jan Sobieski near
Vienna in 1683 rivaled Saratoga. It turned back the tide of Islam.
Saratoga did more. It launched two centuries of revolution
elsewhere. It marked the beginning of the end of the British
Empire. And it breathed life into the United States of America.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO WAS THE BEST LEADER OF THE MILLENNIUM?
 &UR; (500 Words)
 &UR; BY GAIL COLLINS
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look how well she governs,'' the once-reluctant subjects
of Elizabeth I, the Virgin Queen, later would remark. For the
ravishing ruler exceeded all expectations, and by now she is
namesake to an era.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-LEADER)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST RANDOM SHOT IN HISTORY?
 &UR; (500 words)
 &UR; By CHARLES McGRATH
</P>
<P>
   A nameless bowman in the forests of Normandy took a random shot
and from 100 yards pierced the right eye of King Harold of England.
It was during the Battle of Hastings in 1066, and that arrow in the
eye changed the English language.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SHOT)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST UTOPIA
 &UR; (700 words)
 &UR; By MARGARET ATWOOD
</P>
<P>
   Every time we try to implement ``utopia'' on a grand scale, we
accomplish its disastrous opposite. Perhaps that is why the word
itself means ``no place.'' The best utopia of the last thousand
years may well have been built by the Shakers, a breakaway group of
Quakers who went to America in 1774 under the leadership of
``Mother'' Ann Lee. They were a kindly, melodious and harmless
bunch. They were pacifists; they didn't try to impose their ideas
by force. They made a lasting contribution to furniture design and
music, which is more than some can say, and best of all, they were
self-limiting.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-UTOPIA)
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
<P>
   (New York headquarters: 212-499-3300 or 1-800-972-3550; fax,
212-499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   Visit our Web site at http://nytimes.com/syndicate.
</P>
