Friedman, the Nobel Prize-winning economist, called the
intervention a ``crazy idea.'' Today, more than a year after its
infamous shopping spree, the government began offering those shares
to the public. Whether Hong Kong is deemed crazy, or clever, will
depend on how many investors buy them. By Mark Landler.
