<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LEARJET _ A Lear jet apparently carrying three passengers and a
crew of two enroute from Orlando to Dallas crashes in South Dakota.
There are no survivors. (Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   FLEEBAILEY _ ORLANDO _ Hoping for dramatic courtroom testimony
as famed attorney F. Lee Bailey takes the stand again in his
efforts onto hold to his $2 million fee. (Staletovich, Palm Beach
Post)
</P>
<P>
   FALLING FROM THE SKY
</P>
<P>
   Part Three of a six-part investigative series by The Dayton
Daily News on the the recent rise in military air crashes and their
causes. The Daily News found that the U.S. military routinely sends
planes and helicopters in the air that it knows are plagued with
deadly safety problems. The series is based in part on
never-before-seen information from three databases from the Army,
Navy and Air Force safety centers.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-MAINTENANCE _ The system used to maintain military
aircraft is itself broken. Hundreds of crashes can be linked to
work performed by unqualified mechanics, parts installed
improperly, engines overhauled incorrectly and inspection records
that were falsified. Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-TIMMER _ A Hamilton, Ohio, man died in a helicopter that
should have been grounded. The test result that would have grounded
the craft arrived in the field three weeks after the crash.
(Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN _ WASHINGTON _ Pat Buchanan announces he is leaving the
Republican Party _ ``the party that has long been my home'' _ to
seek the Reform Party presidential nomination. Meanwhile, New York
developer Donald Trump said he would file papers Monday changing
his voter registration from the Republican Party to the
Independence Party _ the Reform affiliate in New York. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ADS _ The George W. Bush presidential campaign previews its
first ads, which will be running in Iowa and New Hampshire, sites
of the first primary/caucus contests. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman). WITH: Screen grabs
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MANDELA - ATLANTA _ Nelson Mandela speaks Monday night at the
Carter Center during the Aspen Institute's two-day conference on
the international poverty gap. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-AUSTIN _ BEIJING, China _ An interview with Austin Mayor
Kirk Watson, who is visiting China on a trip promoting his city's
high tech industry. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-PREGNANCY _ WASHINGTON _ The Department of Health and Human
Services releases a new teen pregnancy report from the National
Center for Health Statistics. This report will have state-by-state
teen pregnancy statistics broken down by race and ethnicity. (Hill,
Cox News Service). 20.
