<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7659 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-TECH     10-25 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLEN-ADVENTURE-TECH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING CONTEMPLATION.COM, AWAY FROM THE ALL-SURROUNDING BUZZ  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 By PICO IYER  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 c.1999 Pico Iyer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeling that the world was too much with me, I took myself off,
last summer, to Laos. The more my private moments seemed to be
invaded by beeping faxes and ringing phones and half-unwanted
chirps of ``you've got mail,'' the more I felt drawn to a place
that was said to be the sleeping beauty among nations _ ``the
currently favored adjective ``underdeveloped' would be an
unwarranted compliment,'' Time had opined some years before.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as I arrived, I knew why I had come.
</P>
<P>
   In Vientiane, the capital, kids were fishing along the main
street _ an unpaved red-dirt path _ and a call across town involved
ringing an operator, waiting for her to call back and then tugging
gently at the wire while speaking in a whisper. At 1 p.m. on the
Friday I arrived, the center of downtown _ Laos' Times Square _
consisted of me, a drowsy rickshaw driver and a fountain with no
water.
</P>
<P>
   When I stepped into my hotel, however _ a simple midprice place
along the Mekong _ I was greeted by the Ghost of Laos Future. A
room beside the lobby blinked with flashing screens accommodating
E-mail needs, and Top Cat was agitating for some pizza on the
Cartoon Network near my bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, sir,'' said the cashier when I took my leave of
Laos, congratulating him on how (relatively) quiet and unspoiled
his country was. ``Next time you come, we'll have full Internet
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they will, and another way to flee the all-surrounding
buzz will be lost to us. The fact that we can get anywhere today,
almost instantly, means that we can be got anywhere, all the time.
And the fact that friends and bosses can find us so easily means
that it is ever more difficult to get lost. Beepers, cell phones,
Global Village modems: The only adventure I crave these days is to
get to a place where no one can reach me (and where I, therefore,
can reach a deeper self).
</P>
<P>
   I thought about all this when I got back from Laos, and I
recalled how even in Bhutan, I'd found more video stores than on
Melrose Avenue. In North Korea I'd been surrounded by the Village
People singing ``Y.M.C.A.'' Even in desperately poor Haiti, I'd
received faxes from a New York office through the night. Adventure
today means finding one's way back to the silence and stillness of
a thousand years ago.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that I got into my old Toyota and began driving up the
California coast. I drove for three hours, the freeway dwindling
into a single-lane road, and the scenery by my side turning from
motels into cows and then empty fields. The road began to climb,
running along the ocean, and the signs began to say things like
``Rock Slide Area Next 60 Miles'' and ``Rough Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming to a 15-foot cross by the side of the road, I turned onto
an even narrower lane and within five minutes had climbed to a
Benedictine hermitage 1,300 feet above the Pacific Ocean. The last
time I'd visited, the whole place had been almost completely cut
off from the world for more than three months, El Nino rainstorms
having washed away the main road. Now, suddenly, I was in a place
where nothing happens.
</P>
<P>
   What I saw, at the top of the ridge, was a fairly
undistinguished building dating from the late Eisenhower years, and
a small semicircle of rooms arranged as in a motel court, with
numbers on their doors. What I didn't see were phone lines,
television antennae, traffic jams. The presence of all that was
absent was intense.
</P>
<P>
   Entering my compact ``cell,'' I took off my watch and listened
to the emptiness. In front of me, an expanse of blue ocean,
eucalyptus trees along the slope, a small fox on the wooden fence
in my private garden; next to me, some Dawn dishwashing detergent
and a sprig of holly in a bottle labeled ``Balsamic Vinegar.'' I
unpacked a few clothes, and the novels and essays that, on this
journey, seemed the aptest guidebooks. I sat in the small chair in
the garden and watched snatches of mist race up the hillside.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, an archetypal adventure, common to every
culture from Basho's to Peter Matthiessen's. Yet it is a voyage
that grows more precious as it grows more elusive, and more and
more of the world tunes in to news on the hour, every hour. And
though I could try to find the same stillness in my quiet mountain
home, unplugging the phone and closing the door firmly, when I've
tried it in the past, I've found myself too hemmed in by the
familiar props of my everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Here, though no Catholic, I am steadied by the sense of common
purpose; and when I sit in the dark and listen to the rain beating
against the wooden roof, I can feel as if I'm back in some pre- or
post-millennial state of mind described in a holy book. Or in no
time at all.
</P>
<P>
   At some level, I do nothing in the hermitage: I read, I think, I
write to distant friends; several times a day I walk along the same
road I've walked along for eight years now. It is not a
particularly ascetic regimen. The food (set out in the kitchen and
eaten in silence in one's cell) is worthy of a San Francisco
restaurant, instant-coffee makers sit in every heated room and a
bookshop offers tapes and greeting cards and Sufi texts.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure, such a place reminds me, is mostly about forgetting
some things (deadlines, data, dates), the better to remember others
(the people you love, the hopes you've lost sight of). The events
of the day are sunrise, nightfall, stars.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years I've seen the hermitage, like other
pretechnological sites around the nation, grow more and more
popular, as people try to step outside the moment and return to a
Thoreauvian sense of the unknown. Seven years ago, I could show up
here, more or less unannounced, and claim a room for the night; now
I have to make a reservation six months in advance, and guarantee
my suggested donation (of $45 a night) with a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Which suggests to me, really, that our fascination with the new
only quickens our hunger for the old. Though the hermitage could be
seen as analogous to cyberspace _ it has no boundaries, no bearings
and leaves you alone with your thoughts _ it is distinguished from
that nowhere space precisely by being rooted and ruled, its tolling
bells marking out a centered universe. The one friend of mine who
has also taken the place to heart is, not surprisingly, the one who
showed me a Global Positioning System in his car and flew so often
that he once won the ultimate frequent-flier award _ 30 days of
unlimited travel across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The monks, whose lives find value in their service to the world,
are delighted, I'm sure, that technology has put their remote
mountain home just a click away from Tibet. They can accept fax
orders for their fruitcake now and share their blessings by E-mail
(monks &LR; contemplation.com). When the roads washed away, a
68-year-old brother drove me in by a back road. A white-hooded
hermit for 38 years, he explained with glee how he had gauged the
day's weather from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The point, I think, is that spurning the uses of the modern
world makes as little sense as surrendering one's soul to them. Yet
``it's never too late,'' as Allen Ginsberg wrote, ``to do nothing
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   (Pico Iyer is the author, most recently, of ``Tropical
Classical'' and, coming out this winter, ``The Global Soul.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
