<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7666 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-MILLEN-ME-KIMMELMAN-N     10-25 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLEN-ME-KIMMELMAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYRON AND THE LOST ART OF IMMORTALITY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By age 36, Lord Byron, the original bad boy of English
literature, had made a nation of repressed women swoon despite his
escapades _ he seduced boys and slept with his half sister, and
threw his wife and newborn daughter out of the house _ and had
written one of the great satiric poems of all time, ``Don Juan,''
which he allowed to be understood was partly autobiographical.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding a malformed foot, he was as famous for his
athletic prowess as for the brand of cynicism that made ``Byronic''
an adjective. We even owe to Byron the classic mother-in-law joke.
His mother-in-law had been dangerously ill, he wrote, but was now
dangerously well again.
</P>
<P>
   He lacked only one thing to insure his immortality: a really
good death. And this came about with perfect filmic melodrama in
1824, while he was leading an ill-planned campaign in Greece's war
of independence against the Turks.
</P>
<P>
   He had outfitted a warship (and gone so far as to design the
men's uniforms _ although even his second in command refused to
take his plumed helmet with the Byron crest out of its pink box).
Then Byron caught a fever; at the end, abandoned by mutinous
troops, he died a gloriously unnecessary death in the marshes at
Missolonghi, bled by his doctors.
</P>
<P>
   If Byron's contemporaries didn't exactly regard that death as a
good career move, we can see it now as a pivotal moment in cultural
history. He and his era gave us the clich of the artist gladly
outraging society, asserting the primacy of his opinion and
claiming absolute indifference to public reaction.
</P>
<P>
   These became essential aspects of Romanticism, and 200 years
later they are still entwined in our definition of creative genius.
Now, however, fame also attaches itself merely to the trappings of
the Byronic persona: the extravagant life style, the operatic
demise. The heroic self, all too often, has degenerated into the
hyped celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Being over the top has frequently turned out to be a good
business strategy for the ambitious artist. ``I have been attacked
by the government, by the priests and by the newspapers,'' Gustave
Flaubert wrote. ``Nothing is lacking for my triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   Madonna or the painter Francis Bacon could easily have said the
same thing in this century. Controversiality alone doesn't imply
genius or guarantee immortality _ remember Rudi Gernreich? _ but it
obviously doesn't doom an artist to obscurity or poverty either.
</P>
<P>
   Monet, the standard example of the misunderstood Impressionist,
had praise heaped on him and lived his last decades like Croesus in
Giverny. Even van Gogh, whose misery continues to give hope to
every unrecognized artist, came alarmingly close to success before
he shot himself. Had he lived past 40, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   He might have bought the asylum at St.-Remy as a chateau for his
third wife and spent his dotage like Picasso, in saturnalian
excess, sunning on the Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than writers or painters, composers illustrate best
the Romantic equating of nonconformity with glory. By the late 18th
century, pure instrumental music _ music not written for the king
or the church but simply for the pleasure of an emerging
bourgeoisie _ was coming into its own.
</P>
<P>
   With the rise of a middle class, composers were beginning to
think in terms of public concerts and paying crowds. Musicians like
Liszt and Berlioz, both of them basing works on Byron's poems,
wrote with this new audience in mind.
</P>
<P>
   But religious music had expressed piety; court music, elegance.
They reflected the goals of their subjects. What were the new
symphonies supposed to celebrate? Making money? Individuality
therefore became a prime criterion of artistic value, an excuse for
artists entering a marketplace that many of them claimed to
disdain.
</P>
<P>
   As Charles Rosen, the pianist and writer, has put it, during the
Romantic era ``the work has its own law, its own reason for
existing: it is produced by the artist not for a purpose but
because he must _ ``out of an inner necessity.'''
</P>
<P>
   So the artist now sought to make a living by, as it were,
selling his soul _ his individual sensibility. The more individual
the sensibility, the better the artist _ an idea that naturally
flowed into the larger sphere of politics and public life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Force of mind is developed only by attacking power,'' was Mme.
de Stael's phrase for the concept of the underdog individual versus
the dominating mass, which Byron translated as ``All Talent has a
propensity to attack the Strong.''
</P>
<P>
   If Byron has come to seem to us like a virtual parody of
Romantic excess, it is partly because he refused to stick to any
one esthetic or moral philosophy. He was a freethinker dogged by
Calvinist guilt; he had stood up for the poor but took childish
pride in his aristocracy.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of self-indulgence that Byron embodied involved an
elevation of private esthetics over reason. Enlightenment reason
had lost much of its luster after Robespierre. As a bedrock
ideology for the modern artist, the Romantic credo of individuality
was to become particularly irresistible because it didn't depend on
any one view of the world to which everyone had to conform.
</P>
<P>
   Conformity became the only enemy, which helps to explain why
Romanticism as a historical movement is still so poorly remembered:
it consciously resisted any one definition. The Romantic revolution
was like William Morris's description of a battle that men fight
and lose: ``the thing they fought for comes about in spite of their
defeat,'' Morris wrote, ``and when it comes, turns out not to be
what they meant, and other men have to fight for what they meant
under another name.''
</P>
<P>
   This also seems like a metaphor for the Romantic concept of the
misunderstood genius _ the individual artist of the most
exceptional talent _ although we ought to be careful about
attributing too much, ultimately, to the Romantic age. Victor Hugo,
like Byron a larger-than-life character, fooled around with scraps
of lace dipped in colored ink.
</P>
<P>
   He signed stones that he found on the beach. But we really
haven't the slightest idea whether this meant to Hugo what it
implies to us. We know only that he wasn't a forward thinker about
the art of his time. The critic Sainte-Beuve said that Hugo ``spent
his entire life going from one man to another, helping himself to
whatever they had to offer,'' which was funny coming from
Sainte-Beuve, who had an affair with Hugo's wife. Still, it was an
astute statement: Hugo pointed the way ahead by looking backward,
to what had already been done.
</P>
<P>
   Historians in 100 years may find it more interesting than we do
that so much art in this century was not about individual
expression but the reverse: it was based on one or another of the
various totalitarian forms of collectivism or on the collectivist
philosophy of the artist collaboratives.
</P>
<P>
   Fluxus, the most effervescent of these postwar collectives, was
started by a true original, the Lithuanian-American composer,
collagist and writer George Maciunas, who dressed like an
accountant and thought like Bakunin. He was the antithesis of
Byron, except that, fortunately, he had a sense of humor. With mock
gravity he declared the goal of Fluxus to be to ``destroy the
authorship of pieces and make them totally anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   And a result was a hodgepodge of experimental publications,
concerts, objects, happenings, games and gags that encapsulate, as
well as anything else, the anything-goes utopian ideals of the
1960's and 70's.
</P>
<P>
   If Fluxus isn't widely known today outside art circles, it is
because anonymity and ephemera also virtually guarantee obscurity,
while Byronic self-aggrandizement remains, of course, the path to
immortality. At the end of the millennium, despite the collectivist
counterreaction in the 20th century, it is still the individual who
inspires the masses.
</P>
<P>
   In Vietnam today there are 1,000 temples dedicated to a cult of
Victor Hugo. Which is nothing compared to the number of albums sold
by Milli Vanilli, the 80's pop duo who faked their way to stardom
by lip-syncing songs recorded for them by other people. The idea of
the heroic individual now having devolved into mere celebrityhood,
modern magazines and television make people famous simply for
having had their pictures taken. Talent isn't necessarily an issue.
</P>
<P>
   The downward historical trajectory goes from William Faulkner's
notion of fame (''to be, as a private individual, abolished and
voided from history, leaving it markless, no refuse save the
printed books'') to Kato Kaelin. Fame, stripped of its old
spiritual sense of everlasting existence derived from valued
accomplishment, accrues these days to Linda Evangelista and Kate
Moss, who look good in advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if Byron were around, he'd be sleeping with a model.
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Kimmelman is chief art critic of The New York Times.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
