r d BC &LR; - &UR; PUMPKIN-SEEDS-LADN     10-25 0134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
ROASTED PUMPKIN SEEDS  
 
</HEADLINE>
 BC - PUMPKIN-SEEDS-LADN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  1 cup seeds from a freshly cut pumpkin 
2 tablespoons vegetable oil 
Salt to taste
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Rinse well and dry seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a saute pan or skillet and brown seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Remove with a slotted spoon and put on a baking sheet in a
single layer. Salt to taste. Bake seeds in preheated 325-degree
oven 15 minutes or until crisp. Cool on paper towels. Makes 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Substitute 1/2 teaspoon garlic salt for salt, if desired.
Can also add 1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper with garlic salt.
</P>
<P>
   !ital!From ``The New American Vegetable Cookbook'' by Georgeanne
Brennan, Isaac Cronin and Charlotte Glenn (Aris Books). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC &LR; - &UR; PUMPKIN-COOK-LADN     10-25 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BC - PUMPKIN-COOK-LADN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So just how do you cut up and cook a fresh
pumpkin? Here are some different options. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FRESH PUMPKIN PUREE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Use in pumpkin pie or any recipe calling for pumpkin puree. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 (6- to 7-pound) ripe pumpkin &QL; 
Water &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Halve pumpkin crosswise and scoop out seeds and strings. Place
halves in a large baking pan with a bit of water, hollow side down,
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 1 1/2 to 2 hours, or until
fork tender. Remove from oven and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape pulp from shells and puree, a little at a time, in a
blender 15 to 20 seconds, or on high speed in a food processor
fitted with a metal chopping blade 10 to 15 seconds. Mix in salt.
Makes 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The New Doubleday Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson and Elaine
Hanna (Doubleday). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOILED PUMPKIN &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 (3- to 4-pound) ripe pumpkin, cut in 2- to 3-inch chunks OR
strips and peeled &QL; 
1 quart boiling water &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons salt &QL; 
Pinch pepper &QL; 
2 to 3 tablespoons butter OR margarine
</P>
<P>
   Place pumpkin, water and salt in a saucepan; cover and boil
gently 25 to 30 minutes, until fork tender. Drain, add pepper and
butter. Serve. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   TO PARBOIL FOR USE IN OTHER RECIPES: Boil as directed but reduce
cooking time to 15 minutes; omit seasonings. TO STEAM: Place
pumpkin chunks or strips in a steamer over rapidly boiling water.
Cover and steam 30 to 35 minutes, until fork tender. Season and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   MASHED PUMPKIN: Boil and drain pumpkin as directed; mash. Heat,
uncovered, over low heat, shaking pan occasionally 3 to 5 minutes
to drive off excess moisture. Add pepper, butter and 2 to 3
tablespoons whipping cream, if desired. Mix well, or beat until
fluffy with an electric mixer. Mashed pumpkin is also good with a
little brown sugar or honey added, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The New Doubleday Cookbook'' by Jean Anderson and Elaine
Hanna (Doubleday). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MICROWAVE PUMPKIN &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Halve a small pumpkin, or cut a larger one into big chunks.
Place flesh side down in a microwave-proof dish with a little
water. Cover with plastic wrap and cook on high power, rearranging
and turning often, until fork tender. (Figure around 16 to 24
minutes on high for a 4- to 5-pound pumpkin cut in half). Cool,
drain off any liquid. Puree pumpkin in a food processor, or mash. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
