<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL: RUNNING OF ALL BUT BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Welcome to the NBA's Black-and-Blue Division.
</P>
<P>
   Throw out the fraudulent Chicago Bulls _ are they something or
what? _ and you have the best-balanced division in the league. With
the exception of the disreputaBulls, you have seven teams with
quite legitimate playoff aspirations. Given what's going on in the
Atlantic Division, who could say otherwise?
</P>
<P>
   The Central Division features a worst-to-first turnaround by the
Hornets, who last year were predicted to finish even lower than the
Bulls. The reason? Their two best players were out, their coach was
in a snit, and their marquee free agent was Derrick Coleman. But
the Hornets changed coaches, made a big deal (which looks better
every day), and now are the presumptive favorites in the division.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's champ, Indiana, has a spectacular new building and a
real tug-of-war going on between the win-it-now crowd (Larry Bird)
and the let's-reload-before-we-become-the-Bulls crowd (management).
One Davis has been traded (Antonio) and the other is upset over his
contract (Dale). The backcourt starters are both 34 and the center
has feet that would make Bill Walton blush.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto, meanwhile, is perceived to be a team on the move, and
for good reason. If they ever get a point guard, or if Alvin
Williams somehow morphs into one, the Raptors will be even better.
</P>
<P>
   You can throw a blanket over Milwaukee, Atlanta, Detroit, and
Cleveland. One doesn't appear to be demonstrably better than the
others, although the Pistons still have Grant Hill (for the time
being, anyway). The Bucks seem to have suffered the least of the
four, so they get the early nod to lead the pack. The Cavs have a
rookie coach, but also have Danny Ferry on the last year of his
10-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   The only team without a chance is, of course, those cagey Bulls.
Gee, they're doing a masterful rebuilding job there, aren't they?
They missed out on all the free agents last summer _ oops, we
forgot Will Perdue and B.J. Armstrong _ so now management is trying
to brainwash the dupes out there into thinking that they'll get
Hill or Tim Duncan next summer. Yeah, sure. Maybe Tyrone Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, they'll be awful again, further discrediting
what they did earlier in the decade. At least the Celtics tried to
be decent (with the notable exception of 1995-96). The Bulls'
``Refuse To Win'' mentality couldn't be more transparent.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a preview of the division, with the teams listed in
projected order of finish.
</P>
<P>
   1. CHARLOTTE HORNETS &QC; 
-- Last season: 26-24, fifth place. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key additions: Baron Davis, Todd Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key losses: Chucky Brown, Chuck Person.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key returnee: Anthony Mason.
</P>
<P>
   -- Team song: ``Even It Up.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Comment: You gotta like this team on paper. Coach Paul Silas
already had a good team, and then he lucked into rocket man Davis
in the draft. The Hornets can go big or small and beat you either
way. Say what you want about phlegmatic Elden Campbell _ and there
are times when he's out in the ether _ he remains one of the top
three healthy centers in the conference. Coleman appears to have
gotten religion, and Mason, quirks aside, is relentless. Eddie
Jones is one of the top 2 guards in either conference; he'll get a
chance this season to pick up those playoff stats, which have been
a downer. David Wesley may be keeping the seat warm for Davis, but
he's not a bad guy to have running the show. Plus, he can keep
defenses honest with his shooting. The Hornets can also be a pain
on defense with Jones and Davis on the perimeter and Campbell and
Coleman to block shots. Everyone likes this team now. It's easy to
see why.
</P>
<P>
   2. INDIANA PACERS &QC; 
-- Last season: 33-17, first place. Lost to New York in the
conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key additions: Jonathan Bender, Zan Tabak.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key losses: Antonio Davis, Fred Hoiberg.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key lame duck: Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   -- Team song: ``I Don't Want to Wait.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Comment: How much do these guys have left in the tank? Bird
is on record as saying not only that this is his last year, but
also that he can't go into the season without a decent backup for
Rik Smits. So he has Zan Tabak? The Pacers can go two ways, either
one understandable. They can recognize this might be their last,
best chance, or they can do what they did three years ago when they
knew Larry Brown wasn't coming back. They took that year off. The
loss of Davis is significant in the short run; three years from
now, if Bender develops as many think he might, we might be hailing
it as an outright Indy theft. But that's not going to help the
Pacers now, unless the kid is even savvier than Kevin Garnett.
Antonio Davis was a huge force (even if he did get smoked by Marcus
Camby in the playoffs), and now Dale Davis is in high dudgeon over
his contract. If they play, and play hard, the window is still
open. But barely.
</P>
<P>
   3. TORONTO RAPTORS &QC; 
-- Last season: 23-27, sixth place. Did not make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key additions: Antonio Davis, Muggsy Bogues, Dell Curry, Alex
Radojevic.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key losses: John Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   -- Team song: ``It's Getting Hotter in the North.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Comment: These guys have the pieces in place to make a
serious upgrade and don't seem all that much less powerful _ on
paper _ than either of the two teams above them. They've got
grizzled tough guys (Davis, Kevin Willis, Charles Oakley) to go
along with dazzling young'uns (Tracy McGrady, Vince Carter) and
assorted others who can shoot (Curry), block shots (Michael
Stewart), and defend (Doug Christie). The big question mark is at
point guard; is Williams up to it or will the no-knees-left Bogues
be pressed into serious service? Toronto wanted to plug that hole
this past summer and made a run at Eric Snow. The Raptors still
have some very moveable players if they feel they have to make a
deal down the road. But with a very acceptable starting five and
some enviable depth _ we haven't even mentioned Dee Brown, who is
on the shelf for now _ the Raptors should become the first Canadian
playoff team in NBA history.
</P>
<P>
   4. MILWAUKEE BUCKS &QC; 
-- Last season: 28-22, fourth place. Lost to Indiana in first
round.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key additions: Dale Ellis, J.R. Reid, Danny Manning.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key losses: Dell Curry, Michael Curry.
</P>
<P>
   -- Team song: ``Easy to Be Hard.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Comment: Only five players remain from the Bucks team that
started the season last February: Ray Allen, Glenn Robinson, Ervin
Johnson, Tractor Traylor, and Vinny Del Negro. But even bigger is
the availability of Sam Cassell, who was all but gonzo last year.
If he's healthy and stays healthy, he can be a big plus. George
Karl's teams also play defense _ a previously foreign concept to
the Big Dog _ and the presence of all those veterans can't hurt in
the locker room. (Ellis, of course, played for Karl in Seattle.) A
real wild card here for Milwaukee is Tim Thomas, who came over from
Philadelphia. If he develops as Karl thinks he might, he could be a
terrific addition off the bench. Traylor and Reid will provide bulk
up front, and Johnson can block shots, if not much else. The big
question is how much of a hit the Bucks took in losing the Currys.
Ellis might replace Dell. But Michael's toughness won't be easy to
replicate.
</P>
<P>
   5. ATLANTA HAWKS &QC; 
-- Last season: 31-19, second place. Lost to New York in the second
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key additions: Isaiah Rider, Jim Jackson, Lorenzen Wright,
Bimbo Coles, Jason Terry, Cal Bowdler.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key losses: Steve Smith, Mookie Blaylock, Tyrone Corbin,
Grant Long, Ed Gray.
</P>
<P>
   -- Team song: ``I Know There's an Answer Here.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Comment: This team could have gotten to the conference finals
last spring had it remained healthy and been able to make shots. It
did neither and succumbed to the Knicks in utterly humiliating
fashion. Still, the breakup is staggering and a lot is riding on
the new guys. Rider is who he is; this also is the last year of his
contract. Wright is a nice addition up front, but is Bimbo Coles an
even swap for Blaylock? (Terry eventually may settle there when he
figures out how the NBA works.) There are also a lot of questions
about Lenny Wilkens's ability to handle all the potential
distractions _ we've already seen Rider acting up (it's a good
thing he wasn't in Kitty Hawk or we'd still be taking trains). But
the Hawks like the mix (forget what you saw in Providence if you
were one of the 100 who watched). And while we're at it, isn't it
time Dikembe Mutombo puts an end to his ``overrated'' tag?
</P>
<P>
   6. DETROIT PISTONS &QC; 
-- Last season: 29-21, third place. Lost to Atlanta in the first
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key additions: Terry Mills, Michael Curry.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key losses: Joe Dumars.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key maybes: Bison Dele, Derek Harper.
</P>
<P>
   -- Team song: ``The Last Time.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Comment: A lot hinges on whether Dele and Harper decide to
play. If they do, the Pistons could be back in third place. If they
don't, they'll be lucky to make the playoffs. They have the best
ACC team right now _ a notch above Wake Forest _ but they can't be
serious about Eric Montross/Don Reid with Christian Laettner at
power forward. They have the supernova in Hill, who may use this
season to determine if he really wants to stay or join Tim Duncan
in San Antonio. (Wouldn't that be a nice fit, given the Spurs' need
for a small forward?) Harper would help in the locker room _ we
think _ and provide a capable backup to erratic Lindsey Hunter.
They have some good outside shooters in Jud Buechler and Terry
Mills, a super slasher in Jerry Stackhouse (who has to start
playing one of these days), and the relentless Jerome Williams.
That should be enough to get them to the dance.
</P>
<P>
   7. CLEVELAND CAVALIERS &QC; 
-- Last season: 22-28, seventh place. Did not make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key additions: Lamond Murray, Mark Bryant, Andre Miller,
Trajan Langdon.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key losses: Derek Anderson, Johnny Newman.
</P>
<P>
   -- Team song: ``Nobody Home.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Comment: These guys could be a lot better this season and
still find themselves right where they were last year. They have a
new coach in Randy Wittman and they also have a lot riding on the
Waltonesque feet of Zydrunas Ilgauskas. If he can play this season,
and play the way the Cavs know he can play, then Cleveland will be
a potentially dangerous team. (Bryant was picked up as insurance,
although he's no Andrew DeClercq.) They will have the inside game
and the outside game with bombers galore in Wesley Person, Murray,
and Langdon. That's a good mix. The Cavs were generally pretty
sound defensively under Mike Fratello, and it's hard to envision
that changing with a Bobby Knight disciple at the helm. This could
easily be the best seventh-place team in the league. If the Z man
avoids the IL and the rookies develop as hoped, the Cavs could move
up a notch or two.
</P>
<P>
   8. CHICAGO BULLS &QC; 
-- Last season: 13-37, last place. Did not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key additions: Elton Brand, Ron Artest, Will Perdue, B.J.
Armstrong, Hersey Hawkins, Fred Hoiberg.
</P>
<P>
   -- Key losses: Ron Harper, Brent Barry, Mark Bryant, Andrew
Lang, Bill Wennington.
</P>
<P>
   -- Team song: ``The Impostors.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Comment: Well, at least the Jerrys can relax knowing they
have not done what the Celtics did. That, of course, was their big
fear. No, they've turned themselves into the Clippers, which is
even more mystifying. Somehow, the basketball fans in Chicago are
being asked to fork over good money to see a team that again has
decided to take a pass on the season. Oh, we'll see a lot of Brand
and Artest because they have to play; there's no one else. Everyone
else of any consequence is in the last year of his contract,
including the Bulls' last holdover from the Glory Days II, Toni
Kukoc. (Armstrong and Perdue were around for Glory Days I.) Think
those guys will be really pushing the envelope for victory No. 20
in mid-April? The big question is whether the Bulls can outmaneuver
Orlando _ also tanking it _ for the worst overall record. That's
part of the plan, of course. Just ask the Clippers how it all comes
together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
