<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7702 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BRONCOS-     10-25 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BRONCOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS BEAT DENVER FOR FIRST TIME SINCE '81 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He was kicked in the shins, and his knee and
ankle were twisted. Ben Coates was hurting.
</P>
<P>
   So why was he smiling?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding?'' said Coates. ``We beat Denver. I've never
beaten Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots hadn't beaten Denver since Sept. 29, 1980, losing
11 straight games. Sunday's game could have been another loss.
Instead, the Patriots watched as a 24-13 third-quarter lead
evaporated before they hung on for a 24-23 victory before 60,011 at
Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There was a collective holding of breath when Denver's Jason
Elam attempted a 59-yard field goal with 1:45 remaining. However
the attempt by Elam, who has kicked a 63-yarder, tying the all-time
record, fell short in a gusty and swirling wind. With no timeouts
remaining, the Patriots took over on downs and sealed the victory
to make them 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss te out of 10 times,'' said Elam. ``It was not a
given by any means, so you swing as hard as you can and hope it has
the distance. Those posts don't look very big from back there. I
should have eaten my Wheaties this morning. You just do the best
you can and hope it goes through.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos, who had put together fourth-quarter drives of 85
yards for a touchdown and 59 yards for a field goal to make it
24-23, started their last drive at their 20 with 3:15 left. The
Broncos could have used the retired John Elway and the injured
Terrell Davis. Instead, they had Brian Griese and Olandis Gary.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't quite the same, but the Broncos, who started the
season 0-4 before winning two, started nicely. They were aided by
an interference call on Steve Israel, and Gary broke two tackles on
a 15-yard catch and run gain to the 44.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Milloy made a key stop on Gary for a 4-yard loss, and a
7-yard pass from Griese to Ed McCaffrey, on which the big receiver
went end over end after being hit, got them to the 40. After a
third-down pass to Rod Smith was incomplete, the field goal team
came out.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offense looked good, with possibly its best
performance of the season. The Patriots ran the ball 28 times for
133 yards, the same amount as Denver with one more carry. They had
28 running plays, and Drew Bledsoe dropped back to pass 26 times.
The offensive line looked like blocks of granite, not limestone, as
for the first time this season a Patriot runner went for more than
100 yards (Terry Allen with 17 carries for 106 yards and two
touchdowns).
</P>
<P>
   ``We just set our minds to running the ball,'' said offensive
coordinator Ernie Zampese. ``We didn't run anything different. The
guys just blocked like crazy. We wanted to make an impact with the
running game. Terry Allen ran like Terry Allen.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen suffered a concussion during a third-quarter drive, giving
rookie Kevin Faulk a chance at the end. Faulk had ripped off a
15-yard touchdown run in the first quarter, his first in the NFL.
On the play, everyone pulled left but Faulk made a quick cut to the
right and was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offensive line did a great job,'' said Allen. ``When they
block like that, it's easy to run the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulk was superb on the return game, too, breaking a 33-yard
kick return and a 20-yard punt return. He had 238 all-purpose
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there trying to compete at 100 percent,'' said
Faulk, who has struggled with an ankle sprain the past month.
``Terry had a great game. He's doing what he's done for the last
nine years, that's running the ball and scoring touchdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   It got tricky in the fourth quarter after the Patriots lost
linebackers Marty Moore (ankle sprain) and Vernon Crawford
(strained knee ligaments), leaving them with two healthy players at
that position. That forced New England to use defensive backs Larry
Whigham and Lawyer Milloy on the weak side until Crawford came
back, although at far less than full strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found ourselves having to figure out what to do after every
single play,'' said defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell. ``We were
trying to coach Larry along. It was a hectic time, but we got it
done. We found a way to cover the things we needed to cover.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots scored a season-high 10 first-quarter points.
Faulk's nifty run capped a six-play, 59-yard drive, which included
a 20-yard pass from Drew Bledsoe (13 for 22, 214 yards) to Coates.
Adam Vinatieri kicked a 28-yard field goal with 2:37 remaining in
the quarter after Lamont Warren tripped at the 10, 3 yards short of
a first down.
</P>
<P>
   Elam hit a 40-yard field goal with 11:11 left in the second
quarter and the Patriots soon lost Moore, forcing them to use
Crawford, normally a strong-side linebacker, on the weak side.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos exploited this immediately when Gary found a massive
hole for a 60-yard gain to the 28. Two plays later, Griese
connected with Smith for a 28-yard touchdown with 7:52 remaining in
the quarter, making it 10-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots scored 26 seconds before halftime when Bledsoe
spotted Terry Glenn on a deep route over the middle for a 67-yard
catch. Glenn, who had been shut out until that time, beat safety
Tyrone Braxton and faked Dale Carter with a move to the outside at
midfield. He ran it all the way to the 1, from where Allen got in,
giving the Patriots a 17-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   On Denver's first possession of the third quarter, Elam capped a
seven-play, 62-yard drive with a 28-yard field goal, but the
Patriots answered. Allen kicked things off on the ensuing drive
with a 39-yard scamper. Later in the drive, Allen ran for 18 before
scoring on a 1-yard rush behind the left side of the Patriots'
line, which got superb push all day.
</P>
<P>
   From there it was a matter of survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we feel we're back on track,'' said cornerback Ty
Law. ``There's one more game before the bye week, and hopefully
we'll be 6-2. After that, we plan on going 8-0.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
