<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS FAMILY FELT PAIN AT FENWAY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For many Red Sox fans, the highlight of the 1999
season was the Saturday afternoon playoff victory over the Yankees
when Roger Clemens was hooted off the mound in the third inning of
a 13-1 Sox win.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of gloating in old Fenway that day. Irate that
Clemens dared return to Boston in a Yankee uniform, fans were
estatic when the Sox knocked him out early in his duel with Pedro
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The KO itself wasn't enough. Fenway legions chanted, ``Where is
Roger?'' throughout the afternoon, taunting Clemens long after he
was gone. There was some perverse, cruel pleasure in the routing of
the Rocket, as if mere victory was not enough. It was rough on
Debbie Clemens and two of her sons, sitting in Section 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treated him like dirt,'' Debbie said Sunday when her
husband was honored as one of the 30 greatest major leaguers of the
20th century. ``It hurt my feelings a lot. It was like all of his
wins there meant nothing. He gave everything he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's why they don't ever win in Boston. The fans
have it backward. There is no sportsmanship in that town. It's
mean. It's miserable and mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at Pedro and I think, there's Roger 10 years ago. And I
know what's going to happen to Pedro in that town. It wasn't like
that here in Atlanta last night. The fans here were great. They
don't have that hatred. I wish they would have better
sportsmanship. It's what you teach your children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I don't know why I should have expected things to
be any different. They did it to Bob Stanley. They were ugly to Jim
Rice. I thought it was sad. I don't know what Roger ever did to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He won 192 games (tied for first in Boston history with Cy
Young) and three Cy Young Awards while pitching for the Red Sox.
But Boston fans won't forgive him for pitching better in Toronto
than in his final four years in Boston. And joining the Yankees put
Clemens in the Bill Parcells pantheon, another perfect villain for
wise-guy columnists and hate-radio hosts who've never spoken to him
or looked him in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was emotional,'' said Debbie. ``I was stunned. Why? What
did he do? They should be yelling at (general manager Dan)
Duquette. They loved Roger, then made him a villain. We went
through that cycle a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie and Roger Clemens spent 13 seasons in Greater Boston and
had all four of their sons while he was playing for the Red Sox.
They owned a house in Framingham and enjoyed a nostalgic foliage
tour along the Massachusetts Turnpike when they came back to
Beantown for the playoffs. But game day provided a rude awakening.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were chanting, `Have another doughnut,' '' said Debbie.
``I still don't get that one. People think he's fat. He's not fat.
Look at him.''
</P>
<P>
   On the fateful Saturday, she sat with sons Koby, 13, and Kory,
11. Koby cried. Kory went to the souvenir stand and ordered pizza.
They left after the fifth. Kory asked his dad if he was OK when he
saw him after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My oldest guy is a little emotional. I think it's because he
was in Deb's belly during the 1986 World Series,'' said Clemens.
``But my little guy, the lefthander, he couldn't care less. He
knows Dad's all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those fans just treated me like a visitor. I heard they were
chanting, `Where is Roger?' Well, I was shaving the first time they
did that. That's where I was. And the second time I think I was
signing balls for my teammates. All I know is, I did a lot of great
things there in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   These are heady days for the Rocket. Sunday he posed for
pictures, sitting between Warren Spahn and Hank Aaron. He joined
Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Ty Cobb, Spahn, Aaron, and 24 others on the
team of the century. And Wednesday night in New York he's scheduled
to pitch the fourth game of the World Series. It will be his first
Series appearance since Mike Greenwell pinch hit for him in the top
of the eighth inning of Game 6 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been close to the ring before,'' he said. ``And I'm real
thankful for this opportunity, to have it again. I don't have that
ring on my finger yet, but it's dangling in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens's mom, Bess, and his sister, Bonnie, joined Debbie at
Atlanta's Marriott Marquis for the unveiling of baseball's
All-Century Team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look up and I see my face there with Christy Mathewson and I
walk by my mom and give her a high five. I just feel real
fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma Clemens was feeling pretty fortunate, too. And it's fortunate
she wasn't in Boston for the Clemens hate-fest nine days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Where is Roger?
</P>
<P>
   He's at the World Series, warming up for Game 4, standing
alongside Nolan Ryan, Sandy Koufax, Bob Gibson, and the other gods
of the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
