<SLUG> BC-RUN-CHICAGO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHANNOUCHI SMASHES MARATHON MARK 
</HEADLINE>
 MARATHON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Khalid Khannouchi was biding his time. At 17 miles,
rival Moses Tanui had blasted from out of nowhere into the lead
pack. Not to worry. By 18, the Kenyan was ahead by 4 seconds; a
mile later the gap was 17 seconds. Still, Khannounchi waited. At 20
miles, Tanui was a formidable 34 seconds ahead and looking toward
an easy victory.
</P>
<P>
   He was just where Khannouchi wanted him, and at mile 22 the
Moroccan took off. The struggling Kenyan was soon looking over his
shoulder at a surging Khannouchi, who improbably caught Tanui with
less than 2 miles to go in Sunday's Chicago Marathon and virtually
sprinted to victory, smashing the world record in 2 hours 5 minutes
42 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' said Khannouchi, 27, ``I have my dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanui, a two-time winner of the Boston Marathon, was second in
2:06:11, the third-fastest time in history and a personal best by 1
minute 22 seconds. Tanui later said he made his move too soon after
unaccountably muddling his conversion of miles into kilometers.
</P>
<P>
   The defending champion, Ondoro Osoro of Kenya, was a distant
third in 2:07:59. American David Morris finished fourth in 2:09:31.
</P>
<P>
   With $100,000 awarded for breaking the world record,
Khannouchi's win was good for $165,000. The previous record,
2:06:05, was set a year ago in Berlin by Ronaldo da Costa of
Brazil, who began Sunday's race but dropped out at mile 15 with
lower back pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my city,'' said an elated Khannouchi after the race,
and he wasn't kidding. In 1997, he won here in 2:07:10, at the time
the fastest marathon debut in the world and the fourth-fastest time
in history. Last year, although crushed by finishing second to
Osoro while battling a stress fracture in his left heel, he
nonetheless ran 2:07:19. Sunday's mark means that Khannouchi, who
has lived in New York for six years and is awaiting US citizenship,
has run three of the fastest 20 marathons in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people that didn't appreciate the job that I did
last year,'' he said. ``It makes me feel bad. I said I will come
back and prove them wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the race, Khannouchi tucked himself in toward the
back of the lead pack, which went through the halfway point at 1:03
(``Exactly what they wanted,'' said Paul Evans of Great Britain,
one of the pace setters). With him were Osoro, Kenyans Simon Bor,
Joseph Kahugu, and Sammy Korir, and Brazilian Eder Moreno Fialho.
When the pacers stepped aside at mile 17, Osoro was officially but
nominally in the lead of a pack of eight runners that suddenly
included the hard-driving Tanui.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't panic,'' said Khannouchi of the Kenyan's seemingly
effortless move. ``I knew it was too early.'' As a group of
Chicago-area Moroccans implored him to go faster, Khannouchi said
he wanted to shout, ``Don't worry, I know what I am doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Khannouchi stayed in contention as Tanui sped away with
times of 4:40, 4:40 and 4:33 for miles 17, 18, 19, and by mile 22
even the Moroccan was still 27 seconds back. But that was about to
change spectacularly, as Tanui began to fade and Khannouchi decided
it was time to strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make a quick move,'' he said. ``I stayed relaxed and
saved my energy. The last 2 miles I ran incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   That he did. Shaving about 5 seconds per half-mile off Tanui's
lead, Khannouchi stalked Tanui for 2 miles before the faltering
Kenyan looked over his left shoulder to discover the Moroccan
quickly gaining. Having already realized he had surged far too
early (at 30K instead of 35K) and faced 3.1 more miles than he had
been planning on, Tanui had no answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking, I must go and finish the race,'' said a
resigned Tanui, who will take home $90,000 in prize money and
bonuses. ``It was anyway my mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pair disappeared into the 310-meter-long tunnel beneath
the McCormack Place convention center, Khannouchi had a 3-meter
lead but wasn't ready to celebrate (``Moses Tanui has a great kick
and he could come back and catch me''). By the time they emerged
from the darkness it was closer to 40 meters. From there, it was a
race against the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes watery from the wind and a 20-degree wind chill at the 7:30
a.m. start, Khannouchi couldn't see the clock on the pace car for
the last 4 miles, and didn't know how close he was to the record
until he crossed the finish line and stumbled into the arms of his
wife and coach, Sandra. ``We did it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I happen to hold it for only one hour,'' said Khannouchi of
the world record, it would be all right with him. ``If somebody
would come and break it now, I'd be happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
