<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HEALTHY DOSE OF GIVE AND TAKE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Denver gave. The Patriots took. It's as
simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos Sunday as much as said, ``If you want to run it, go
ahead. We're stopping Drew Bledsoe.'' And for the most part they
did. What kept them from winning, as New England claimed a 24-23
victory, were Patriot running backs Terry Allen and Kevin Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   Allen is a master craftsman with a football under his arm. He
has a sixth sense of where the defenders are going to go before the
ball is even snapped.
</P>
<P>
   With several brilliant individual moves, Allen carved out 106
yards to key the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk had 238 yards of combined offense. His work on returns
provided good field position for his offense, which had it much
better than Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly because of Faulk, the Patriots' average starting point
was their 35. For Denver, it was their 19, which became critical in
a 1-point game.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots only had 54 offensive plays, which is unusual. And,
almost unbelievably, they won without ever having a drive of more
than seven plays.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's defensive coordinator, Greg Robinson, one of the best
in the game, always defenses the Patriots well.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson wanted to keep Bledsoe from making big plays to his
wide receivers. He wanted his coverage to be such that his rushers
had time to get some hits on Bledsoe. They did, but not enough.
Bledsoe was sacked four times, twice at key points in the fourth
quarter when Robinson simply outmanned the New England offensive
formation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those last two blitzes they came with eight or nine guys,''
said Bledsoe, ``and we just didn't have time to get rid of the
ball. I wanted to go to my hot receiver, and they had him covered.
So I had to hold onto the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Glenn, Vincent Brisby, and Shawn Jefferson had a total of
five catches. Bledsoe had just 13 completions, but not all of the
Denver defensive game plan worked.
</P>
<P>
   Allen did the most to beat it. With the Patriots leading, 17-10,
in the third quarter, Allen put together what would prove to be the
winning sequence for New England. On first down at his 31, Allen
ran toward the middle, made a quick hop to his right at the line,
put a head fake on a linebacker, then took off down the sideline
for 39 yards. Three plays later, on second and 10 at the Denver 19,
he blew through the middle for 18 yards to the 1, and finished it
with a blast into the middle to give New England 24 points. After
that, Denver shut down the Patriots' running game. In the final 23
minutes, New England gained 22 yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The telling part of the game for New England was the closing
minutes of the second period and the opening of the third, when
Allen got the final touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied at 10 with 1:13 left in the first half, and
Bledsoe was faced with second and 12 on his 32. Denver was
pressuring with each play. Bledsoe faded to throw, sidestepped a
rusher, stepped up, and threw a frozen rope down the right hashmark
to Glenn, who eluded two defenders and scrambled to the 1, setting
up an Allen scoring run.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents continue to focus on Bledsoe. Sunday, offensive
coordinator Ernie Zampese changed up a little. ``We used more
double tight end and more two running back (formations) than we
have before,'' said Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   The second tight end, and extra running back, gave the Patriots'
running game more punch. Tony Simmons didn't play a down as a wide
receiver after leading the team two weeks ago in Kansas City with
seven catches.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese wanted to protect Bledsoe as best he could, give him
some semblance of a running attack to work with, and not expose him
to wide open shots from the Denver defense, which always has a few
blitzes in its package that the opposition hasn't seen before.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Griese did a nice job for Denver. Don't forget, he was
playing without Terrell Davis and Shannon Sharpe, his two major
weapons. It was obvious that coach Mike Shanahan's offensive
package is not as deep and diversified as it was when the great
John Elway was around.
</P>
<P>
   There were no turnovers. Griese was under a lot of pressure, but
he didn't panic and throw the ball into coverage. Denver had a big
edge in total net yards, 442-325, yet lost.
</P>
<P>
   New England played the first 42-plus minutes without getting a
penalty, while Denver had seven. But just about the time one was
thinking ``home cooking,'' they had five coming down the stretch,
which helped keep a couple of Denver drives alive in the fourth
period.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise in the game, beyond Allen's running from
scrimmage, was the way the Patriots had the wide edge on special
teams. On return yardage they had 210 yards, as opposed to 132 for
Denver. Denver generally has some of the best special teams in the
league, and the Patriots had been hurt by injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
