<SLUG> BC-ROW-HEAD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MEN'S EIGHT CONTROLS RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
 OF CHARLES REGATTA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ It wasn't so much a race as it was a 3-mile
victory lap. The US men's eight hadn't taken a spin in front of the
home folks since they'd won their third straight world title in
August. Sunday was their chance to have an entire river to
themselves and hear hosannas from both shores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of a reward,'' coach Mike Teti said, after the
Yanks had beaten the Germans by 12 seconds to claim their record
fifth straight championship at the Head of the Charles Regatta
Sunday afternoon. ``When they heard themselves announced as the
1999 world champions before the start, that was kind of a rush for
these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a point of pride for them to leave the rest of the
field in their wake. ``It's not so much a matter of pressure,''
said Teti, ``but the expectation is that if you're the world
champions, you're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   For the dozens of oarspeople wearing US Rowing gear here, that
was exactly the expectation and with rare exceptions they turned
the Head into their intramural championships. The men's four,
rowing as the Princeton Training Center, retained its crown by a
whopping 33 seconds over the Craftsbury Sculling Center. The men's
and women's lightweight eights, the women's double of Wendy Wilbur
and Stephanie Gregg, and lightweight scullers Dave Sanderson and
Christine Collins are all national team members. All of them won
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   So did Don Smith, a US sweep oarsman who stepped into a single
scull and knocked off a tough international field that included two
former world champs. ``It's good to do well in a race that hasn't
treated me that well in the past,'' said Smith, who beat US Olympic
sculler Cy Beasley by 9 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Head is an aquatic roulette wheel, spinning out winners and
losers whimsically. ``That's the fun of the race,'' Teti said.
``It's tough to gauge. You don't really know where you are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian women's eight didn't know until just before they
got their medals that they'd edged the US by 1 second for their
third title in four years. ``We knew we had beaten the (defending
champion) Danish because we had caught up to them,'' said cox
Lesley Thompson. ``And we knew it was close with the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's singles was close enough between Australia's
Georgina Douglas and Canada's Marnie McBean that it was flashed as
a dead heat on the Magazine Beach scoreboard. Douglas, who ended up
winning by 28 hundredths of a second, had no idea.
</P>
<P>
   She had flown up from Melbourne on Tuesday and spent the week
getting over jet lag and trying to reckon how many times the river
could twist. ``I row on a river (the Yarra) as well,'' said
Douglas. ``So I'm used to looking around and going under bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference Sunday was that Douglas was also trying to weave
her way through a world-class field that included not only McBean,
the best all-around oarswoman in history, but also world bronze
medalist Rumiana Neikova of Bulgaria (who ended up 11th), defending
champ Julia Chilicki (eighth), and top US sculler Leslie
Burns-Rawley (third).
</P>
<P>
   That was no accident.
</P>
<P>
   Regatta officials made a point of beefing up the elite singles
fields this year, bringing in a bunch of folks who'll be in Sydney
next summer. The men's field was brutal _ two former world titlists
in Jamie Koven, and Juri Jaanson of Estonia, plus world double
winner Luka Spik of Slovenia, and Dutch champion Merlin Vervoorn.
</P>
<P>
   Though Smith was seeded second behind two-time victor Koven,
he'd always had trouble negotiating the serpentine course. Not
Sunday. ``Don stole the show, no doubt about it,'' said Koven. ``He
made a move on me at the 2-mile mark, just before the big turn. He
rowed a great race. I just wish I could have been up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the women's eight, the US men had a rowover. Once
the Canadians scratched and the Germans brought only two men from
their world boat, the Yanks thought they might be home free. ``We
pulled away from (second-seeded) Princeton right away,'' said
Porter Collins.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, they had a vast swatch of open water. As long as
cox Pete Cipollone didn't doze off and hit an abutment, the world
champs were in for a style cruise. Once they came swinging around
Dead Man's Curve, they could have rowed with one hand and waved
with the other.
</P>
<P>
   It was a row for show. On Wednesday, the US men fly to
Switzerland for a long-distance race on Lake Geneva that finishes
in front of the Olympic museum in Lausanne. Juan Antonio Samaranch,
chief Lord of the Rings, will present the medals. If the Yanks
flash their credentials, maybe he'll give them his Sydney set for
safekeeping.
</P>
</TEXT>
