<HEADER>
A7720 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-TYSON-ANALYSIS-BO     10-25 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULLING NO PUNCHES ON TYSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ There should be no fourth second chance for Mike
Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. Not after he embarrassed himself and disgraced
the sport that has made him a millionaire for the third time in his
last three fights.
</P>
<P>
   Not after his pattern of disregard for the rules and for his
opponents was on display once again for the world to see.
</P>
<P>
   Not after he did what he'd promised he'd do a week before the
fight when he told the Los Angeles Times he'd do anything in the
ring, including bite an opponent again, if he felt he had to.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen to Orlin Norris Saturday night. He escaped
with his ears intact. But he couldn't say the same for his knee
after Tyson's latest fiasco ended in a no-contest when he
cold-cocked Norris two seconds after the bell ended the first round
at the MGM Grand Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In a familiar pattern, the former heavyweight champion then
blamed Norris for refusing to continue participating in a street
fight rather than the prizefight he'd contracted to be part of
after his right knee suffered what Dr. Flip Homansky said was a
dislocation.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Tyson tell it, in his last three fights Evander
Holyfield stuck his ears in his mouth, Frans Botha stuck his arm
under Tyson's and tried to break it, and Norris proved a coward for
not continuing on when his knee popped when he was popped after
referee Richard Steele clearly said, ``Stop punching.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was the victim again Saturday night, as he always claims
to be. A victim of his reputation, his celebrity, his sport's
hatred of him, and his opponent's willingness to stay down to
ensure a $2 million payday for a rematch that was in his contract
if something ever went awry for Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   A victim not of his own lack of self-control but of everyone
else's conspiracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want to fight anymore,'' Tyson said after he
learned his $10 million purse was being withheld pending a full
review of the incident by the Nevada State Athletic Commission this
week. ``I'm tired of this bull. Anyone who's competitive, even if
he's got a fractured leg, would get back up and fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked back to his corner. That shows you how twisted his
knee was. He must have hurt it getting on the stool.''
</P>
<P>
   No, he hurt it after a manic-depressive who is regularly taken
off the antidepressant medication Zoloft several weeks before men
without a conscience send him into the ring to act out in bizarre
fashion hit him in the face with a short left hand after the bell.
</P>
<P>
   As the stunned Norris collapsed to the floor, his knee buckled
under him and he stayed on his back before starting to rise as
Tyson stared menacingly at him, a bully on the loose. Steele
immediately deducted 2 points from Tyson and then turned his
attention to Norris, who walked splay-legged to his corner and sat
on his stool with his leg extended in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   When the bell sounded to open the second round, Norris didn't
move and his chief handler, Abel Sanchez, walked over to Steele and
said his fighter couldn't continue. When he did, Tyson stalked to
the center of the ring toward Norris but Steele directed him to a
neutral corner where he paced liked the caged and frightened animal
he has become in the ring since Holyfield first exposed him.
</P>
<P>
   After a long discussion between Steele, Nevada State Commission
executive director Marc Ratner, and Homansky, the bout was ruled a
no-contest pending further review by the full commission. When that
was announced Tyson seemed to spin into a rage but promoter Dan
Goossen rushed in along with Tyson's cornermen and calmed him as
Norris continued to sit with an ice bag strapped to his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He quit,'' Tyson said. ``How do I hit him in the jaw and he
hurt his leg?''
</P>
<P>
   Probably because when he hit him it was a) after the bell, b)
coming out of a clinch, c) after Steele had ordered both men to
stop punching, and d) while he was still holding Norris with one
arm. Other than that, there was no reason Norris shouldn't have
been able to defend himself from an opponent who no longer has the
self-control to follow even the most basic rules of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just hit me after the bell and I went down the wrong way on
my right knee,'' Norris said before leaving for Valley Hospital on
a stretcher while still in his trunks to undergo an MRI.
</P>
<P>
   Later Goossen would claim Norris's cornermen were heard telling
their fighter to stay down and implying this was a devious plan to
ensure a rematch rather than an act of concern for their charge.
The possibility that this suggestion was made because Norris's knee
was already beginning to swell eluded Goossen in a way Norris could
not elude that punch.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter what they told him after Tyson did to Norris
what he had done to Botha after the first round of their fight and
what he had done to Holyfield in the first round of their first
confrontation. He fired his gun after an official cease-fire had
been declared. When Norris's brother, Terry, did the same thing he
was immediately disqualified and lost his super welterweight title
but this is Tyson the human ATM, not some journeyman, so the rules
do not apply. Or at least are not applied in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   This time they should be. This time should be the last time
Tyson gets the opportunity to disgrace himself and the memory of
Hall of Fame trainer Cus D'Amato, the man who tried to save him
from the streets but unwittingly set him on an even more
self-destructive path.
</P>
<P>
   The Tyson who leveled Norris late looked nothing like the one
who had dropped two sparring partners with crisp combinations in
open sparring sessions last week. In those controlled sessions he
appeared to be the same fearsome fighting machine he had been the
night he became the youngest heavyweight champion in history 13
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But when the bright lights were turned on him Saturday night,
Tyson melted again. He appeared tense before the opening bell and
when the fight began he missed one wild hook after another, landing
only two body shots and a soft jab until he threw the
extracurricular left hand that may have thrown his career into its
final act if the Nevada Athletic Commission stands for anything but
the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Only with Orlin Norris's hands down and under orders not to
punch did Iron Mike Tyson unleash a knockout blow.
</P>
<P>
   It is time to count Mike Tyson out and let him move on with his
life. Without boxing, maybe he can still have one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
