<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING CHAMP KOVEN IS FIFTH 
</HEADLINE>
 OF CHARLES-KOVEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ From Europe they came, some of the best men scullers in
the world invited for the first time to row in a championship class
in this 35th Head of the Charles Regatta.
</P>
<P>
   They were all chasing one American _ Jamie Koven, defending
champion of this event and former world champion _ but ended up
getting beat by another.
</P>
<P>
   As the elite singles began the big lefthand turn into the Eliot
Street Bridge, 31-year-old Don Smith, a men's fours rower on the US
national team, had streaked past Koven, all the top Europeans, and
the other Americans.
</P>
<P>
   One of the final races in the two-day event, the championship
singles was rowed in late afternoon with chilly gusts of west wind
rippling across the lengthening shadows on the river.
</P>
<P>
   In second place was another US rower, Cyrus Beasley, who,
recovering from a dislocated shoulder, rowed his strongest race
since he was injured in an accident in August. Beasley rowed in the
Olympics, and won gold medals for singles scull in the '95 and '98
World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley started 32d and rowed through much of the fleet for his
second-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   As defending champion, Koven started first, hitting what seemed
a strong stride around the first turns. But as the race extended
past the 2-mile mark, Koven began to fade as Smith and Beasley came
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see I was going by him,'' said Smith, who at 6 feet 7
inches, 207 pounds is the tallest rower in the race. ``I was using
Jamie as a gauge, and as I began moving on him in the third mile, I
knew I was having a good race.''
</P>
<P>
   Koven, who ended up fifth, said his early race was strong, but
``I paced well for a couple of miles but then I didn't have much
left. I was disappointed in my race.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Smith's 32-stroke pace held up as he steered 90
degrees left in front of the Cambridge Boat Club, squirted under
the Eliot Street Bridge, and sprinted for the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily a rower on the fours team, Smith hopes his finish will
help gain him the sponsorship he needs to train as a single. A
graduate of MIT Business School, Smith has been working as an
investment analyst, but because he's in training toward the 2000
Olympics, he feels the need to get more training time.
</P>
<P>
   Smith won a gold medal in the eights at the 1994 FISA World
Championships and the Goodwill Games. He won gold in the eights and
pairs at the 1995 Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm one of the top singles in the US. There's a lot of
good competition out there. Winning the Head of the Charles can't
hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of the elite European rowers in this year's event
created a spark, said Smith. And those invited, most finishing in
the top 15, said they would be back, if invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very nice race, fabulous,'' said Luka Spik, a
20-year-old world champion from Slovenia. Spik said he thought he
had a chance at winning the race, but on a sinuous river like the
Charles, ``It is very difficult to pass another boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Merlin Vervoorn from the Netherlands, another international
medalist, said the Head of the Charles' invitation of elite rowers
would turn the regatta quickly into a ``world-class event.''
</P>
<P>
   The mix of elite racers and club amateurs is not only rare, but
``very impressive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Regatta co-founder D'arcy MacMahon said that while the elite
rowers would add a competitive edge to the race, the Head of the
Charles will remain low-key in the commercial elements of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need sponsors, but this race will never be about money.
It's about the rowers, the volunteers, and the spectators. It's sad
how commercial sports get, and we don't want that to ever happen
with this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for the ego to have Olympians and these top racers
here,'' said MacMahon, ``but the heart of this race will always be
the crew from East Oshkosh who got themselves here on bake sales
and car washes. We can never forget them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
