<SLUG> BC-ROW-HEAD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S SINGLES CAME DOWN TO WIRE 
</HEADLINE>
 OF CHARLES-WOMEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The projected finish of the women's
championship singles placed Georgina Douglas in first place, but
the Australian rower was reluctant to pronounce herself the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing the bright yellow and dark green colors of her country
as she returned to the Cambridge Boat Club, Douglas avoided comment
about the results in a race decided by time with penalties factored
in. She laughed off questions about the importance of a win over
scullers who had beaten her at the World Championships in August.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas knew how tough the competition was and would not believe
she had won until she saw the results. The Australian sculler's
decision to wait proved wise. The race was so tight that three
versions of the results circulated before the awards ceremony. When
the last printed copy of the results became available, Douglas
learned she had won the championship singles in 20:20.06. The
Australian's time bested friend and rival Marnie McBean by .28
hundreths of a seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But the close finish did not spark any bitterness or
disappointment by McBean. Instead, it brought to light the close
relationship between the two elite rowers. When Douglas was
announced the winner, McBean was the first to offer
congratulations. The two have trained and raced together in the
past and flip-flopped finishes this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty excited because when I come over from Australia
with such a big time difference, it's something that I never
expect,'' said Douglas about her win. ``I just came out to have fun
and be competitive. Having trained for only a couple of weeks, I
didn't expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   About McBean, Douglas said: ``We get along quite well off the
water, but you can't take your friendships onto the water, because
if you do that you're the only one that's going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Added McBean, ``I would say there's a friendly rivalry.
Professionally, we know we always want to be ahead of the other
one, but we also know that we get along quite well. And 20 years
from now I'd rather have a friend than a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The race turned on Dead Man's Curve, which runs from just before
the Cambridge Boat House under the Eliot Street Bridge. McBean took
a wide turn around the bend. At one point, the Canadian sculler
thought she saw her Australian competitor steal a look back at the
wider line she had chosen. Douglas knew she could make up time on
an inside turn. She went on the attack and made up what would later
prove valuable seconds. When McBean passed the Cambridge Boat
House, she had the fastest split. Then, Douglas passed the same
checkpoint and she had the fastest time.
</P>
<P>
   McBean tried to make up the seconds she had lost en route to the
finish, less than a mile away at that point. The Canadian fell just
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take the best course that you can,'' said Douglas. ``It
was probably to her disadvantage that she took (the turn) a little
bit wider.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Douglas and McBean were exchanging trade secrets
as they trained in Australia and raced as a double at the
Australian Nationals. Normally, the two compete against each other
and trade places. McBean defeated Douglas twice during her two
months in Australia. Douglas traveled to Canada and defeated McBean
in the Commonwealth Regatta in London, Ontario. At the World
Championships, McBean finished sixth overall, followed by Douglas
in seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we probably both gained from training with each
other,'' said McBean, whose impressive rowing resume includes three
Olympic gold medals and three World Championship gold medals. ``I
was giving her tips on how to row a tailwind. She was reminding me
about power application.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not McBean and Douglas will renew their friendly
rivalry next year in Sydney remains to be seen. The Canadian is
certain she will row in the singles event at the 2000 Olympics. The
Australian has told selectors to place her in the boat with the
best chance of medaling. But Sunday along the Charles River, both
competitors knew exactly where the other one was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
