<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS EXPECT TO PICK UP THE PACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ The Celtics are about to step up the pace. They
have won only once in regulation time in five exhibition games
going into Monday night's game against Atlanta in Biloxi, Miss.,
and there will be an increased sense of urgency with the
regular-season opener looming in Toronto Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to judge how we are going to do right now,'' guard
Dana Barros said. ``This is a learning process and we have to
figure out the best rotations. Not that these games haven't been
serious, but it's about time to start picking up the pace and
getting a little more serious about games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' 93-92 loss to Utah Saturday night highlighted both
their strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Celtics imposed their aggressiveness and
transition game on the Jazz. But John Stockton began finding
openings in the Celtic defense, and Utah took control in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rick Pitino blamed the breakdowns on a lack of
conditioning, but said the Celtics would be able to sustain the
pace once the regular season begins.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics were unable to disrupt the Jazz offense in the
second half, and their transition game suffered. They displayed
little effectiveness in the half-court game, with the exception of
Barros, who scored 22 points on nine field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with the Celtics and (Pitino) longer than anyone
else, so I know the system,'' Barros said. ``I know my role and
what is expected and I don't have to spend a lot of time figuring
it out. Some of the guys may take a little more time to get used to
the system here. They might have been used to different roles on
different teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense is not clicking consistently but once we get in a
little better shape we'll be able to push the pace the whole
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics seem athletic enough to set the pace against many
teams. But they missed Danny Fortson, who is recovering from right
foot surgery, against Utah. And, they suffered when Stockton began
penetrating effectively in the second half, setting up open shots
and preventing the Celtics from finding a rhythm. The Celtics held
a 59-47 halftime lead but converted only one field goal in the
first 6:31 of the second half as Utah began setting the tempo. The
Celtics scored only 14 points in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utah, even with Karl Malone out, is a wiser team in the
halfcourt than we are right now,'' Pitino said. ``We have to take
advantage of that in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to try to be able to sustain the pace for both halves
of the game. This is a new pace for everybody in basketball. If we
can sustain the pace we had in the first half we will have more
success. When we slow down and play under the influence of fatigue
we lose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walter McCarty, who has influenza, returned to Boston Sunday and
will miss Monday night's game . . . The Celtics practiced for 2 1/2
hours at Lexington Coliseum. Wayne Turner participated in the
session and is probable for Monday night after missing the Utah
game with bursitis in his right elbow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
