<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S NO. 1? IT'S NOT EXACTLY CLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ What's evident from seeing the carnage of several Top
10 teams is that the question of who's No. 1 has no definitive
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State (8-0) made enough mistakes to lose two games
Saturday but still hung on to beat Clemson, 17-14, in the Bowden
Bowl, which matched Seminoles coach Bobby Bowden against his son,
Tommy, in the first father-son duel in Division 1-A history.
</P>
<P>
   It was also Bowden's 300th career win and marked the return of
wide receiver Peter Warrick after two games in limbo because of
legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   But as Bowden said Saturday night, ``Are we still No. 1? Yes.
But we certainly didn't play like it.''
</P>
<P>
   No, they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that no one else did either. Penn State (8-0) was
outplayed but beat Purdue, 31-25. Nebraska (6-1) was outplayed in
losing to Texas, 24-20, and neither Kansas State (7-0) nor Virginia
Tech (6-0) has quite the juice to convince the pollsters it is the
best team in college football.
</P>
<P>
   So what we have is a handful of teams worthy of the top spot,
including steadily rising Tennessee (5-1), which knocked off
Alabama, 21-7, for the fifth straight time Saturday, and in
Tuscaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   The first Bowl Championship Series rankings will be released
Monday night and no doubt will cause another flurry of controversy,
particularly if Virginia Tech, which is the favorite of most of the
computers, is on top. But those rankings currently are for
informational and argumentative purposes only.
</P>
<P>
   Games are still to be played and teams will rise and fall as
they did Saturday, when Nebraska, Michigan State (6-2), Michigan
(5-2), Alabama (5-2), and Texas A&AMP;M (5-2) all were among upper-tier
teams that lost.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an underlying theme, it is being sent by Kansas
State and Virginia Tech. If you do the Hokie pokey and avoid tough
nonconference opponents, you too can enjoy an unbeaten season and
high BCS rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Which is indeed ironic. One of the arguments against a playoff
system is that it would diminish the regular season and the good
teams would duck each other because a loss could affect their
status as a playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   So we have no playoff system, and the teams benefiting the most
are those with the softest schedules.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston College coach Tom O'Brien is probably facing the toughest
challenge of his career. The Eagles' 31-28 loss to Miami could be a
season-killer unless O'Brien can convince his team there is life
after it blew a 28-0 lead to the visiting Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   If O'Brien can't do it, it could affect the entire program.
</P>
<P>
   BC had fallen as low as it could three years ago when the
betting scandal ripped the Eagles apart. After two 4-7 seasons,
'Brien built some confidence with the Eagles' 4-0 start, although
against admittedly inferior competition.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-14 loss to Temple Oct. 9 temporarily destroyed that
confidence, but the quick and seemingly insurmountable lead against
Miami appeared to have the Eagles poised to move forward again.
</P>
<P>
   Now they must deal with what is arguably one of the toughest
losses in the school's history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bowden Bowl was toughest on Bobby Bowden's wife, Ann, who
watched the game with about 50 friends and relatives wearing a
combined Florida State-Clemson sweatshirt. After the game, Ann
admitted her loyalties still remained with her husband, Bobby.
Joked Tommy, ``She's not my mother, she's my father's wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Turnabout is fair play. After getting beaten by a combined score
of 80-7 over the last two seasons, Oklahoma defeated Texas A&AMP;M,
51-6. It was the Aggies' worst loss in 98 years . . . Who's hot?
Wisconsin. The Badgers (6-2) have won their last two home games
against Indiana and Michigan State by a combined score of 99-10.
Who's not? Michigan State. The once-mighty Spartan defense has been
outscored, 92-38, the last two weeks, including a 40-10 pounding by
Wisconsin Saturday in which Badgers running back Ron Dayne put
himself back in the Heisman Trophy forefront with 214 rushing yards
and two touchdowns. Said Michigan State coach Nick Saban, whose
team committed 11 turnovers in the losses to Purdue and Wisconsin:
``I'm a little shocked because I thought we were ready to play.''
Obviously not.
</P>
<P>
   Also in a state of disbelief was Michigan coach Lloyd Carr, who
saw his Wolverines squander a 27-7 third-quarter lead to Illinois
and lose, 35-29. ``I have no idea how this team will rebound,''
said Carr . . . The slow start, fast finish award goes to Kansas
State and Miami. The teams trailed Oklahoma State and BC,
respectively, by a combined 49-0 and then fashioned comebacks in
which they outscored their opponents by a combined 75-0.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maryland's 45-7 rout over North Carolina continues the Terps'
resurgence. With a 5-2 record, they are one win from becoming bowl
eligible and off to their best start since 1985 . . . After
Tennessee beat Alabama, the Volunteers took out cigars and chanted:
``We own Alabama.'' Alabama coach Mike Dubose wouldn't disagree:
``I said going into the game that Tennessee may be the best
football team in the country, and they didn't do anything to make
me think otherwise.'' . . . One of the best coaching jobs in the
country has been turned in by first-year man June Jones, who has
guided Hawaii to a 5-2 record after a 35-21 win over Tulsa. The
Rainbows were 0-12 last season . . . Things are getting worse for
South Carolina, which is 0-8 after an 11-10 loss to Vanderbilt. Lou
Holtz, in his first year with South Carolina, is suffering through
the worst losing streak of his career, the Gamecocks have lost a
nation-longest 18 straight, and his wife, Beth, is battling throat
cancer . . . Mississippi State's 17-16 victory over LSU improves
the Bulldogs' record to 7-0, their best start ever. They are in
prime position to win the SEC West race and face either Florida or
Tennessee in the league championship game in Atlanta in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
