<HEADLINE>
EXPAND YOUR PUMPKIN OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 4 takes  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: This story, in four takes, includes recipes. sidebars are
PUMPKIN-COOK AND PUMPKIN-SEEDS) 
 
 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Halloween and pumpkins go hand in hand _ and
there's plenty of good eating in store beyond pumpkin pie.
Possibilities range from soups and butters to breads, pancakes,
stuffings _ even entrees _ pies, desserts and more.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Great Little Pumpkin Cookbook,'' by Michael Krondl
(CelestialArts; $5.95), you'll find interesting innovations, such
as a pumpkin stuffed with layers of chicken, chiles and tortillas
and then baked; or Pumpkin Tamales With Smoky Tomato Salsa; Pumpkin
Stuffed Ravioli With Pumpkin Seed Cream; Savory Italian Rice,
Spinach and Pumpkin Torte; Farfalle With Pumpkin and Pecorino
Cheese; Indian Pumpkin Fritters; Pumpkin Spanakopita; Catalan Pork,
Bean and Pumpkin Stew; Pumpkin Blintzes with Caramelized Ginger;
and a wealth of other creations using the golden orb in one form or
another.
</P>
<P>
   You can cook and puree fresh pumpkin flesh _ which isn't
difficult but takes a little time and patience _ or you can opt for
using canned pumpkin puree _ which may be the best route for busy
cooks.
</P>
<P>
   After experimenting with cooking fresh pumpkin _ which turned
out to be a big hassle _ it's easy to understand why the majority
of cooks rely on convenient canned pumpkin puree or canned pumpkin
pie mix (with sugar and spices in the pumpkin) on supermarket
shelves, ready to use on a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the eating pumpkins grown commercially end up in cans _
some 150,000 tons of them _ notes Krondl in his book. And Libby's
owns about 80 percent of the canned market. In 1929, the company
began its pumpkin processing operations, and the first canned
pumpkin made its way to grocers' shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let me discourage you if you want to try your hand at
cooking fresh.
</P>
<P>
   But if you plan to cook fresh pumpkins, be forewarned. ``Most
large pumpkins are bland and watery and best suited to
jack-o'-lanterns,'' writes Krondl. He recommends using the orange
cooking varieties _ such as sugar or pie pumpkin _ which weigh
about 7 pounds. Or another possibility for cooking fresh is the
cheese pumpkin variety _ which is beige on the outside and has
thick and tasty orange meat.
</P>
<P>
   If you purchase your pumpkin from a grower, ask about the
varieties best for cooking and pureeing. When choosing a pumpkin
for cooking, some growers advise selecting a dark orange one. The
darker the color, generally the more meat or flesh it will have.
Also select pumpkins that are firm and with skins free of cracks,
spots or excessive scars.
</P>
<P>
   Although some varieties may yield better cooked pumpkin results
than others, I've cooked up medium-size (not gigantic or oversized
ones) run-of-the mill Halloween pumpkins (variety unknown)
purchased at the market _ and they've produced good, edible pumpkin
puree. Experiment if you have the time and inclination.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to peel a pumpkin, notes Krondl in his book, is
to cut it in half and scoop out the seeds and stringy pieces. Then
cut into 2- to 3-inch-wide slices and cut away the hard skin. (Some
recipes call for removing the skin after cooking, which is often
easier.) You can store cut-up, uncooked pumpkin up to four days in
the fridge.
</P>
<P>
   If your fresh pumpkin turns out too watery once it's cooked and
pureed, cook it over low heat (to drive off some of the moisture)
until it is the desired consistency, or the consistency of canned
pumpkin. Or place the watery pumpkin in a strainer and allow it to
drain an hour or two, stirring occasionally. And if you end up with
a surplus, remember that pureed pumpkin can be frozen if
well-wrapped.
</P>
<P>
   When you use pumpkin in recipes, figure that 1 pound raw,
uncooked pumpkin will yield about 3/4 to 1 cup of cooked mashed
pumpkin. And when it comes to nutritional value, pumpkin shares
similar food values with other deep yellow winter squash. On cup of
unseasoned pureed pumpkin has about 75 to 80 calories and only a
trace of fat. Pumpkin is also exceptionally high in vitamin A (in
the form of beta-carotene) and is high in dietary fiber.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter whether it comes from your garden, a farm stand or
even a can, whether it's cut out to be a fearsome porch ornament,
an ingredient in exotic stew, or plain old pie, you know it'll
carve a grin on your face. It does on mine,'' writes Krondl.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of good eating in pumpkin _ either fresh or
canned. Clip and save these recipes to use now and throughout the
holiday season. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MORE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
