u s BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-BOS     10-25 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES NURSING ACHES AND PAINS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ To a man, Boston College's football team ached Sunday
from the stinging disappointment of Saturday's 31-28 loss to the
No. 23 Miami Hurricanes, a game in which the Eagles squandered a
28-0 lead by allowing Miami to score 31 points in the final 17:11
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played the way we wanted to play this game,'' BC coach Tom
O'Brien said. ``But we just need to learn how to finish it.''
   And this was supposed to be the easy part of the schedule?
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, O'Brien spoke about how his team had survived the
toughest part of the schedule and had nothing to lose in the five
remaining games after the burden of unfair expectations had been
lifted by a 20-16 Big East victory over Pittsburgh Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, it made sense, but putting it into practice was
another story. The only thing that looked easy was Miami's miracle
comeback, which ranked as the biggest in school history. Now BC
(5-2, 2-2) will have to regroup for a trip Saturday to Syracuse,
where the Eagles will encounter a rested squad of Orangemen (5-2,
2-1), who took the weekend off after a humiliating 62-0 loss two
weeks ago at Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a tough one for us, because we've gone through
two emotional games,'' O'Brien said. ``You don't like to play real
high, and I don't like to play too low. I like to play at an even
keel. We've gone from a skyrocket of emotions and one end of the
spectrum to the other, so I think this will be a key game for this
football team. If we can go play the same way we've played the last
two weeks with some fire and emotion and enthusiasm then we'll have
made bigger strides than the little steps we've been taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked after the game what the loss told him about his team,
O'Brien said pointedly, ``We need to recruit athletes into this
program and the ones we have better grow up, that's what it tells
me.'' Sunday, though, O'Brien indicated he was not ready to rely
upon his heralded freshman class for more contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just meant that the kids that we have _ that we perceive to
be our athletes and our best players _ the kids we're playing, they
have to play smarter and they have to play better,'' O'Brien said.
``We had too many mistakes mentally and too many missed tackles.
Granted you miss a field goal and you fumble a football, which are
bad, bad mistakes, but you're allowed to stop them on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   After BC surged to a 21-0 halftime lead by gaining 250 yards
(177 rushing) and 19 first downs on 51 offensive plays, the
Hurricanes turned the tide in the fourth quarter by capitalizing on
John Matich's 33-yard missed field goal, Cedric Washington's fumble
at the BC 6, and a critical fourth-and-17 conversion that set up
Andy Crosland's 30-yard winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Miami quarterback Kenny Kelly, who said he was hobbled late in
the game when his left ankle was wrenched by BC defensive tackle
Chris Hovan, completed a 22-yard pass to Reggie Wayne that set up
the winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to do the same things that got us there (to a 28-0
lead), but they changed their defense, and went much more
pressure-oriented,'' O'Brien said. ``A lot of those runs we split
were against their two-deep zone coverage when they were playing
pass. We did a good job of changing up what our tendencies were,
but in the second half they had eight, nine guys around the ball
and played man on the perimeter and were going to make us throw the
football.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kelly tied the game with a 10-yard TD pass to tight end
Daniel Franks, the Eagles took the field at their own 22 with 3:42
remaining. But BC went three-and-out when junior quarterback Tim
Hasselbeck fired three consecutive incompletions, including a deep
ball down the middle on third-and-10 to a double-covered Dedrick
Dewalt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we could've run it one time, but that would've been the
only other thing we would've done,'' O'Brien said. ``But you had
two opportunities where officials can make a call and they don't
make it two out of three times. Two out of three times they grabbed
Dewalt and the ball was not uncatchable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Eagles went for a touchdown _ and lost _ when it
seemed as if all they needed in that situation was a first down.
Conversely, Miami had a chance for a touchdown on fourth-and-17
from the BC 35, but instead went for a first down and wound up
winning the game on a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the tape you can see why (Hasselbeck) throws
it to (Dewalt), because he's behind them, so you have to go with
what you read and trust in the quarterback,'' O'Brien said. ``He
thought he had a shot, and he took it, so I can't fault him for
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
