<HEADER>
A7744 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     10-25 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKING EACH OTHER A GOOD SIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Pete Carroll and Steve Sidwell protected
Lawyer Milloy and Larry Whigham as well as they could Sunday and
Milloy and Whigham protected a defense in distress. This is called
being a team.
</P>
<P>
   In the talent-depleted NFL of 1999, the presence of versatility
in personnel is often as important as anything the big-money
superstars can do on a day like Sunday, when defeat hung in the air
like the dying leaves that surrounded Foxboro Stadium. Defeat and
the panic that would follow it were not far from the Patriots as
one linebacker after another fell to the wayside, a knee hurt here,
an ankle sprained there, until the only people left to play were
people to whom linebacker was only a name on a piece of paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have marquee players here, but this is a team,'' longtime
Pro Bowl tackle Bruce Armstrong said after defensive backs Milloy
and Whigham had spent too much time playing linebacker for their
own good after only two were left in one piece with more than a
quarter left against the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Neither will remind anyone of Dick Butkus, but both earned a
bronze star with an oak leaf cluster for their efforts in a 24-23
victory that could have turned into a disaster if they had done a
little bit less and the Broncos had done a little bit more.
</P>
<P>
   If the Broncos had, New England would be on a three-game losing
streak this morning that would be considered a free fall. But they
are not facing that ticklish situation because Sunday Milloy,
Whigham, and to a lesser extent, Ty Law, went beyond the call when
the call was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody had to step up and do it,'' Armstrong said. ``You
start the summer with all these guys getting reps and then you're
down to 53 with 46 plus one on Sunday. Ideally you want to have
your (starting) 22 players and your special team (starters) out
there, but it isn't like that. That's when you have to count on
other guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even I can't appreciate something like what they do. Guys like
Whigham and (backup linebackers Vernon) Crawford and Marty Moore. I
never had to know two or three positions and be ready if my number
was called. My number was always called. They have to prepare like
it will be, never knowing each and every game what's going to
happen. This game everything happened.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of what happened happened even before the game began. Ted
Johnson, Tedy Bruschi, and Bernard Russ were already in street
clothes along with other walking wounded, so the Patriots were
forced to put their two best defensive backs _ Milloy and Law _ on
special teams. That is not a place where you often want to see your
most productive defensive players, but after seeing their special
teams pulverized the last two Sundays reinforcements were required
and the call went out.
</P>
<P>
   When it did a $50 million cornerback and a soon-to-be
million-dollar safety answered with abandon, which is the only way
to answer such a plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their attitude about it was terrific,'' coach Pete Carroll
said. ``They didn't hesitate.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Whigham or Milloy when they were told they would be
playing linebacker in the second half after first Moore and then
Crawford went down with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Milloy weighs 208 pounds yet found himself staring into the eyes
of offensive guards who weighed 287 and 281 pounds, respectively.
Not far away the 205-pound Whigham was holding the fort at the
plugger position normally played by Bruschi, staying on the edge of
the defense as often as his coaches could keep him there, but still
forced to blitz and play the run far more often than a backup
safety would think wise under normal circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a defensive back used to wide receivers releasing on me,
not 300-pound linemen,'' Whigham said. ``I got one nice hit in, but
that's why my neck hurts. We called a lot of blitzes and base
defenses so I didn't have to sit up on their guards but
unfortunatley (linebacker Andy) Katzenmoyer made one wrong call and
I had to go up in there. I proved I'm no linebacker on that play,
but you have to be willing and able to do anything they ask of you.
They drew it up for me and coach (Steve) Sidwell made some calls to
get me to the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   He also made some calls that left Milloy in the middle, a spot
he is not unfamiliar with, but one that is different from when he
is asked to creep up from his safety position to add extra bodies
at the line of scrimmage. Such exotic blitzes were no longer a part
of New England's defensive scheme once their linebackers went to
the infirmary, so something else had to be done and someone had to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a team, somebody does. If you are a collection of
disparate parts, nobody does. Sunday the scoreboard read ``New
England 24, Denver 23.'' The winners write history. The winners
were a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Vernon and Marty went down it was hard to imagine how we
were going to paste it together,'' Carroll said. ``Tons of things
were gone. I'd say 95 percent of what we normally do on defense was
gone. I liked it because we were really having to coach them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to draw things up in the dirt a little bit. As a coach,
you like that. We had to be resourceful and we were. And those guys
had to play. We were just fighting every play.''
</P>
<P>
   And they did. They fought not like classic linebackers, but like
street fighters, playing well enough for long enough to hold off a
Bronco team whose running game resurfaced (133 yards and 4.9 yards
a carry) and whose young quarterback (Brian Griese) blossomed,
going 25 of 38 for 316 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Played well enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   As a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a little bit of confusion at times but we pulled
together,'' Milloy said after making a game-high 14 tackles. ``If
we hadn't had so much adversity with injuries last year and with
our special teams this year it would have been more of a hostile
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sidwell kept it simple for somebody who hadn't lined up at
those positions. We couldn't blitz like we usually do. We had to
stay in base defenses. Our scheme is so vast we couldn't do a lot
of the things we normally do, because we had players on the field
who had never played their positions before. But we were scrappy
out there. Nobody griped.''
</P>
<P>
   They just played football.
</P>
<P>
   Like a team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
