<HEADER>
A7754 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-OFFENSE-     10-25 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-OFFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE RAN, BUT COULDN'T HIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ First the happy tidings, that the Patriots
finally beat Denver, and, as Chris Slade put it, ``This was not
only a big one for us because we needed it bad, but it was a big
one for all the guys who never beat them . . . the Andre Tippetts,
the Bruce Armstrongs, the Ben Coateses, and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   And seldom has the long-suffering Armstrong been happier,
because not only did the Patriots run the ball, but Armstrong also
put a supreme push on the Broncos' Bill Romanowski on Terry Allen's
1-yard TD run in the third quarter Sunday. Armstrong drove the
linebacker a yard or so into the end zone, allowing Allen to score
easily. Sights rarely seen the last decade in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Fitting enough that Drew Bledsoe gave Armstrong the ball he had
carried off the field after the quarterback's last taking of a knee
that ran out the clock because the offensive line, much maligned,
had produced. The lesson? ``You have to slug it out and then slug
it our some more,'' said Armstrong. ``You can't rush the ball if
you don't have the attempts.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the unhappy tidings. The offensive line produced, but the
offense did not. The offense never had a drive of more than seven
plays, and for the third straight week could not come through when
the team had a good lead and one more score would have sealed the
issue. And once again, it was left to the defense to save a tight
game. ``We may not be playing the best football in the league right
now,'' said wide receiver Shawn Jefferson, ``and we're also not
playing the ugliest football, either. But it's good that we're 5-2
when we know we can play better.''
</P>
<P>
   True, as Jefferson said, ``the guys on the other side of the
ball are being paid, too,'' and the Broncos, now 2-5, were
desperate. The Super Bowl champs had to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   That said, how the Patriots' offense played after gaining a
24-13 lead in the third quarter, after the defense had forced
Denver quarterback Brian Griese into a three-and-out with 6:47 left
in the quarter, when all the momentum was with New England, was not
good. Three times the offense got the ball after the momentum was
theirs and Bledsoe and Co. could produce only two first downs.
Points seemed out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only take what the defense gives us,'' said Jefferson
of how the Broncos' all-out blitzing in the second half stymied the
Patriots. Or, as Armstrong put it when asked if the offense still
needs to find that put-'em-away attitude, ``We may have to learn
that we can run the ball on first down and run the ball on second
down, but we can get first downs by running on third downs, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most disconcerting is how opposing defenses now come
with all-out blitzes and the Patriots seldom make the other team
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the game, Bledsoe was sacked on a blitz ``and Drew
said he held onto the ball too long,'' said Armstrong. ``It's not
our philosophy to throw the ball away or to run with the ball,'' he
explained. But it was late in the game, when the Patriots had the
lead and twice had third-down situations to wind down the clock,
that the offense did not come through. The last of those came with
3 1/2 minutes left, the Patriots with the ball on the Broncos' 38,
facing third and 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots called for maximum protection with eight blockers
and Vincent Brisby on the left and Terry Glenn on the right. Brisby
recalled the Broncos ``came with an all-out blitz of eight guys.''
Armstrong remembered, ``it was an all-or-nothing blitz and they
brought nine guys. It's all or nothing. There's little you can do
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But once upon a time in football, receivers would
recognize all-out blitzes and adjust their routes to the open
spaces left by the blitzers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The receivers stayed in their routes on the play,'' said
Brisby. He broke to the left sideline on his medium route and Glenn
broke to the right sideline; the middle of the field was completely
open. Bledsoe was on his back before the receivers had completed
their routes.
</P>
<P>
   And the defense, for the third week in a row, was forced to save
what the offense could not. Once again, the Patriots could not make
the opposing defense pay for blitzing, even though the pass
protection was better than adequate. ``When they came after us with
a full blitz,'' said coach Pete Carroll, ``we had to get rid of the
football and we didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 5-2 and our best football is ahead of us,'' said
Jefferson. And making opponents pay for blitzing hopefully is also
ahead for the Patriot offense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
