<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7757 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-FAULK-BO     10-25 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-FAULK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAULK SAW OPENING, TOOK IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Kevin Faulk had to break through a few
traffic jams at the line of scrimmage Sunday. But when it came to
his first touchdown as a pro, he compared the 15 yards between
himself and the Denver goal line to your local driving range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it looked like a golf shot, wide open,'' said a smiling
Faulk, describing the swath of green on the right side that he
skipped through untouched at 7:27 of the first quarter. The
touchdown got the Patriots off on the right foot in their 24-23
victory over Denver.
</P>
<P>
   It was a victory that was fashioned in large part by what
Patriots coach Pete Carroll called his ``1-2'' running backs punch,
Faulk and veteran Terry Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk, who had missed two full games and part of another because
of an ankle injury, had five carries for 24 yards and 210 return
yards that gave the Patriots good field position.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who had to leave the game in the fourth quarter with a
concussion, had his first 100-yard game with the Patriots, gaining
106 yards on 17 carries with a pair of rushing scores.
</P>
<P>
   New England's 133 yards rushing complemented the 214 yards
passing by quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who appreciated the
contribution of his running backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real benefit to our offense if we can have that kind of
balance,'' said Bledsoe. ``It makes things much easier for me. And
it makes things much easier for our passing game. We can mix it up
a little bit. Hopefully that will be a trend that we can
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe praised Allen for running hard and breaking tackles and
Faulk for his all-around effort, on special teams and in the
backfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Allen) can come back from the concussion, we'll continue
to have that 1-2 punch that gives us two different looks,'' Bledsoe
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Broncos held Green Bay to 21 yards on the ground a
week earlier, Carroll realized the urgency of showing more than one
dimension to Denver. He said the offensive line and running backs
had their best game of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the numbers wound up, but I'm sure we had
more than 5 yards a carry (actually 4.8) against a very good
rushing defense,'' he said. ``The line needed a little boost and we
need to see if we can keep it going.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've had Kevin and Terry at the same
time when they've both been ready to go full speed and both guys
were effective. Terry ran very tough and Kevin was real quick.
Kevin was a big factor in the field-position aspect of this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time we've seen that 1-2 punch. We've been
talking about it since the end of camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulk, who gave credit to the line, said that while there's
still room for improvement, Sunday was a breakthrough for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into the game, we had hoped to get 4 yards no matter
what the play or the blocking was,'' said Faulk. ``Whatever I have
to do to help the team, I'll do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting 4 yards every time we ran the ball feels great. Terry
showed what he's been doing for nine years, and I feel I can give
100 percent even though my ankle is about 85 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulk has been urged by his coaches to run more ``downhill,'' as
he phrased it, but he couldn't help but go right and then home free
on his touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just reaction,'' he said. ``The defense had a stunt on.
I spotted it, got a block, and went outside. I could have run for
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a week would be fine with Carroll, if Faulk continues to
run like he did Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
