<HEADER>
A7760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     10-25 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT THE MOST FLATTERING PROFILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots beat the Broncos by a point
Sunday. Their win at Foxboro Stadium wasn't ensured until Jason
Elam missed a 59-yard field goal with 1:45 remaining. If you have a
problem with either of those statements, you don't know New
England's pro football team as well as you think you do.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the 5-2 Patriots a little better, please refer to
this quick profile:
</P>
<P>
   If the typical Patriot has an electric bill due on the first of
the month, he will certainly pay it on the first _ about 60 seconds
before midnight. He won't be late for your lunch date, but he won't
be early. He is in his seat for the feature presentation, but he
never has seen a preview. One of the most insulting things you can
say to him is, ``Let's go for a walk and look at the trees.'' What?
That's too easy. How about finding a very tall tree and bungee
jumping instead?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guarantee: You will fall in love with the Patriots (if
you're not there already). You will fall for them because they
always will make the ordinary seem interesting. But, because of
that love, your life will not be easy. The Patriots have won four
games by a total of 8 points and another by 12. That 12-pointer
came over the 0-7 Cleveland Browns, who lost by 31 points Sunday.
The Patriots have lost twice, by a total of 3 points. They've got
problems, but being dull isn't one of them. One day they will crush
a team by 30 points. Even that will be exciting or vexing,
depending on whom you ask.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Patriots hadn't beaten the Broncos since 1980, they
had a blowout framed for them Sunday. They had a 24-13 lead in the
third quarter and were running the ball well. They had a lead on
the Broncos who, despite what you hear, are not a good team. Terry
Allen had two touchdowns through three quarters, the first Patriot
runner to do that since Curtis Martin did it three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   So if they kept running, they would win, right? Of course not.
As Bill Parcells and Drew Bledsoe have said, you are what the
profile says you are.
</P>
<P>
   Allen couldn't finish the game because of a concussion, so the
running game stopped. Two linebackers were injured, meaning that a
backup defensive back (205-pound Larry Whigham) had to play their
positions. Chris Slade was called for roughing the passer. Steve
Israel was called for pass interference. Twice.
</P>
<P>
   A touchdown and a field goal later, it was a 24-23 game. That
score didn't become official until Elam's miss. You don't see guys
making 59-yarders often, but any Patriot would be lying if he said
he wasn't worried about the kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This 1-point thing, it's here (to stay), I guess,'' New
England coach Pete Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Even that comment wasn't delivered easily. The Patriots hold
Carroll's press conferences in a weight room. So when the coach
speaks to his audience, he has to peek between squatting machines,
benches, bars, and 50-pound barbells to find the people with the
queries. (Related note: The Patriots are also one of the few NFL
teams that have to drive between the locker room and practice
field. If you didn't know these Patriots so well, you might think
their commute was a little strange.)
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 60,011 fans left the stadium, cornerback Ty Law
said the Patriots will critique each other in Monday's meetings.
Criticism is good, especially when it comes from your colleagues,
but there are certain things that cannot change. One of them is
what most fans refer to as an ``annoying'' zone defense on third
down. As much as I hate zones, I have to admit that the zone has to
stay for the Patriots. Law would love to play straight-up on his
man. Israel is able to do the same. But when teams spread out the
field with additional receivers and Whigham and Kato Serwanga enter
the game, playing a zone is much better than the alternative, which
is using backups in one-on-one coverage. The Patriots might like
living dangerously, but they aren't crazy.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the Broncos' comeback Sunday was expected. With
their injuries, the Patriots were limited to their most basic
defense. And, really, when was the last time you saw a 205-pound
linebacker in the NFL? It was probably the same year of the
Patriots' previous win over the Broncos. They were simply trying to
hold on and prevent Denver from doing what Miami had done a week
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were celebrating in the other room,'' Law said of the
Dolphins, who left with a 31-30 win. ``That ticked us off, how they
came into our house and celebrated. We can't let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   On some Sunday afternoon, Bruce Armstrong said, he would love to
stand on the sideline in the third quarter, relaxing because his
team has a four- or five-touchdown lead. Israel said the Patriots
need to blow a team out. Law said ``it's a shame'' that games
continue to be settled in the final minute or two. Armstrong says
all the bizarre finishes will change when the team matures. Maybe
we will start to see some of that maturity after the off week.
</P>
<P>
   Before that comes, there is a game next week in Arizona against
the Cardinals. You would think that it will be an easy one,
especially since quarterback Jake Plummer will not play. The
Patriots will win, because they win more often than they lose. But
you have read the profile of the typical Patriot. An easy win? You
know better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
