<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS YOUNGSTERS HAVE GROWING PAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Second-year quarterback Brian Griese admits
he's sick and tired of learning on the job.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to win and he wants to win now.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie running back Olandis Gary echoes similar sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronco youngsters turned in credible performances Sunday,
but rather than talk about their growing maturity in the NFL, they
groused about missed opportunities in Denver's 24-23 loss to the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset,'' said Griese, who completed 25 of 38 passes for
316 yards and one touchdown, and also ran for another score. ``When
we got the ball with three minutes left on the 20-yard line I had
no doubt that we would go down and score at least a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had four of these (losses) before and I'm getting tired
of them. I don't want to learn anymore. I want to win. Sure, I'm
going to take a lot of things from this game and learn from them,
but that's not the way I want to learn. I want to learn and win at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I judge myself, and I'll say this to the day I die, on whether
we win the game or not, and ultimately that's what matters. We
didn't win, I didn't win, so anything I did doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not to him, but it did to Broncos coach Mike Shanahan, who
slowly but surely is being vindicated for his decision to start
Griese over veteran Bubby Brister.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played well and with a lot of poise,'' said Shanahan. ``I
don't know what his percentages were, the yardage or anything like
that, but he played well under a lot of pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Broncos got the ball with 3:15 left in the game, the
stage was set for Griese and Denver to win for the third straight
time after opening the season with four straight losses.
</P>
<P>
   Griese's passing, Gary's running, and two key Patriot penalties
helped move the ball from Denver's 20 to the New England 40 before
Griese misfired on a third-down pass to Rod Smith. That set up
Jason Elam's 59-yard field goal try that was straight but way
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rod would have caught the ball, but I think it was tipped,''
said Griese. ``We wanted to at least get to the 35. But the great
teams and the great players find a way to make that play and I
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary, who was thrust into the offensive mix when Terrell Davis
went down in Week 4 with a torn ACL, had his biggest day as a
professional last week when he gained 124 yards on 37 carries
against Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday against the Patriots, he gained 90 yards on 19 rushes,
including a 60-yarder he nearly broke for a touchdown. He also
caught four passes for 39 yards.
</P>
<P>
   On the long run off left tackle, on which he was caught from
behind by Chris Carter, Gary said, ``Those guys get paid to stop me
and I get paid to try and get (in the end zone). Unfortunately, I
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was my inexperience, maybe it wasn't. I don't know.
All I know is the learning process is taking a long time and the
losses keep piling up.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan is just as pleased with Gary's progression as he is
with Griese's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made some big plays out there and he ran hard,'' said
Shanahan. ``He had that big run. I was impressed with the way he
played. He's a tough, hard-nosed player, and in a tough situation
he's responded well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
