u s BC-BB-WORLDSERIES-BOS &LR;      10-25 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DOUBLE THE FUN 
</HEADLINE>
 SERIES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's fear and frost on Peachtree Street. But in New
York they're already warming up the floats for another ticker-tape
parade down the Canyon of Heroes for a celebration that even Joe
Mooney's tarp-happy grounds crew won't be allowed to cut short.
</P>
<P>
   As everything touched by Atlanta Braves manager Bobby Cox
continued to turn to ashes in a 7-2 loss Sunday &UR;  &LR; night in Game 2 of
the 95th World Series, the New York Yankees moved within two games
of lighting some fin de siecle victory cigars.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, Rocket Roger Clemens will have a chance to fulfill
his personal wish list by closing out the Series in the Bronx
Wednesday night, and giving the Yankees consecutive sweeps of the
National League champs.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres were last year's four-and-out victims, and
the Braves were headed down that same dead end after a night in
which Cox rattled his lineup card in hopes of producing more
offense. The Braves, who had two hits in Game 1, had one through
seven innings against David Cone. Cox's nominees to prop up the
bats mostly contributed some more trap-door defense, the kind that
led to Atlanta's demise in Game 1, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees ground Braves starter Kevin Millwood into sawdust
with five singles and three runs in the first inning, then swept
him aside three batters into the third. Singles by Bernie Williams
and Tino Martinez and a double by Ricky Ledee made it 4-0 and led
to Millwood's departure, the earliest by a Braves starter in the
World Series since Milwaukee's Bob Buhl was ousted two outs into
Game 3 of 1957.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just think in small bits and bytes,'' said Yankees manager
Joe Torre, alluding to the Yankees' total of 14 hits (11 singles, 3
doubles). ``Because that's what we need to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But pitching sets the tone, and David Cone was terrific
tonight. I was worried about him in Boston, because he hadn't
pitched in about 12 days, but I didn't worry about him tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, remember, originally was penciled in to start Game 3
in New York, but Cox's master plan was undone by the flu bug that
felled Tom Glavine, who was supposed to have pitched the Series
opener but now will be asked to stanch the bleeding Tuesday night
in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees made it 5-0 when shortstop Ozzie Guillen, who had
replaced Game 1 starter Walt Weiss, muffed Cone's soft liner, the
ball ticking off his glove as Martinez scored.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, second baseman Keith Lockhart, Cox's choice to
sub for Bret Boone, threw away a double-play relay, allowing Derek
Jeter, who had opened the fourth with a double, to score.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees opened a seven-run advantage in the fifth. Scott
Brosius, who has five hits in two games in an encore to last year's
Series MVP performance, doubled, took third on Joe Girardi's
sacrifice, and scored on a single by Chuck Knoblauch, who had led
off the game with the first of three straight Yankee singles.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the first seven hitters in the Yankees' order had at
least two hits, with Williams singling three times.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's first-inning hit was followed by hits by Jeter and
Paul O'Neill to make it 1-0. Millwood looked like he might escape
further trouble when Williams hit into a double play, but Martinez
delivered a two-out RBI hit. After a walk to Ledee, Brosius hit a
2-and-2 pitch up the middle for another RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, meanwhile, were as helpless against Cone as they'd
been the night before against El Duque, Orlando Hernandez. Cone
threw away Guillen's bunt for a two-base error in the first, and
admitted he escaped a bullet when Brian Jordan's drive died on the
track in left.
</P>
<P>
   ``A warmer night, and that's a home run,'' said Cone, small
comfort to Jordan, the cleanup man who is 0 for 7 in this series,
as is Ryan Klesko, the man who hits behind him. ``That might have
taken something out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone did not allow a hit until Greg Myers, catching in place of
sore-fingered Eddie Perez, opened the fifth with a line single to
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a bad game,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``We're a team
of good pitching and timely hitting, and we didn't get any runners
on to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta did not advance a runner to third until the seventh,
when Cone walked Jordan and Lockhart and Jordan took third on
Myers's fly ball. But Cone caught Andruw Jones looking at a called
third strike to end his night's labors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think a good-moving fastball is the best pitch in
baseball,'' Cox said, ``and Cone had a good one tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the praise directed at the Braves' pitching this decade,
Yankees pitching has dominated Atlanta's ever since Game 4 of the
'96 Series, the one turned around by Jim Leyritz's crushing
three-run home run off Mark Wohlers.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves did not score in the last five innings of that game,
were shut out the next night in Game 5, and scored just two runs in
the '96 Series finale. With just three runs in two games here _
Chipper Jones's solo home run in Game 1 and two runs with two outs
in the bottom of the ninth Sunday &UR;  &LR; night _ the Braves have scored
just five runs in their last 40 innings against the Bombers in
Series play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' Cox said. ``I don't know if it's helpless.
We just kept waiting to get something going.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five times in Series history, a team has won the first two
games. Thirty-four of those teams have gone on to win the Series,
including seven of the last eight. The only exception? The '96
Braves, who won the first two in New York, then lost four straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we're aware of what happened in '96,''
Torre said, ``and what we did to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The last three teams to win the first two Series games on the
road went on to lose the Series _ the '85 Cardinals, the '86 Red
Sox, and the '96 Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are now 9-1 this postseason, including their
five-game conquest of the Red Sox in the ALCS, which ended with the
Fenway Park grounds crew trying to lay down the tarp on the mound
while the Yanks were still gathered in a group clinch.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees also have won 10 straight in the World Series. The
Yankees of DiMaggio and Dickey won 10 in a row in a stretch from
1937 to '41. The Yankees of Ruth and Gehrig won a record 12
straight, from 1927, the year the Babe hit 60, to 1932, when the
Babe was said to have called his shot against the Cubs in a
four-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't expect to do that this time of year against
great teams,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a tribute to our starting pitching and (closer)
Mariano Rivera. When we've gotten a lead, he's been automatic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
