<SLUG> BC-JUSTICE-SURVEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSOR SAYS PUBLIC LOSING FAITH IN JUSTICE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ Nearly a decade of tabloid-friendly court
dramas, from the trial of William Kennedy Smith to that of William
Jefferson Clinton, have caused a massive decline in the public's
faith in the justice system, according to a study conducted by
Union College.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant professor Richard Fox's random survey of more than
1,000 respondents across the nation shows that 75 percent had less
confidence in the system following the murder trial of O.J.
Simpson, and 58 percent after the impeachment proceedings against
the president.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of these trials and others, as well as a dramatic
increase in mainstream media coverage of such cases, 44 percent of
the respondents said they felt less confident that the courts and
the police would treat them fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stories are entertaining and build ratings, but the
troubling thing is that people are taking substantive meaning from
them,'' said Fox, 32, a professor of political science at the
college for four years. ``These cases should not be the vehicle for
public education about the legal system. They may be nothing more
than inflammatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, not every observer considers the consequences of
court coverage to be negative. Two specialists in law and media
ethics who were given summaries of Fox's study called the data
valuable, but gave his conclusions mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe people should have less confidence in the system,'' said
Albany Law School professor Vincent Bonventre. ``I don't understand
why that's unhealthy. If there are warts in our system, is
ignorance of it going to increase our confidence?''
</P>
<P>
   Bonventre pointed to the 1995 murder trial of Simpson, which the
professor described as a lesson in race, police incompetence and
the way wealth affects the distribution of justice.
</P>
<P>
   But Aly Colon, an ethics instructor at the Poynter Institute for
Media Studies in St. Petersburg, Fla., said the journalistic pack
mentality can harm the public's ability to understand complex
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news media can become so fixated with an event that it
gets reported ad nauseam, so much that people don't know why it's
being reported,'' he said. ``It's the information overload
syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Though media and legal pundits have engaged in considerable
hand-wringing over the coverage of such cases, Fox's study _ which
was released earlier this month _ is believed to be the first to
examine comprehensively how public attitudes toward the law have
been shaped by the decade of scandal trials and court TV.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and co-author Robert Van Sickel of Purdue University in West
Lafayette, Ind., also claim to be the first to give evidentiary
support to claims that the mainstream news media have become
increasingly driven by tabloid-style stories. Their findings will
be detailed in the book ``Tabloid Justice,'' to be released by
Lynne Rienner next summer.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during the three years that led up to the
conviction of serial murderer Charles Manson in 1971, none of the
three major networks led with the story. By contrast, the Simpson
case held the lead position in roughly 100 news reports in
1994-'95, before his acquittal on criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sends the signal that that's one of the biggest news
stories in America,'' Fox said. ``You sort of wish we weren't
sending out that signal.'' Fox, a self-professed media junkie, said
he first began thinking of the book while channel surfing during
the Simpson trial.
</P>
<P>
   As a work of social science, the book is meant to pose
questions, Fox said, but not necessarily answer them. He admits to
being frustrated about the possibility for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market makes it difficult to think about real reform,'' he
said. ``Is one news organization going to stand on its high horse
and say, `We're not going to cover this while we go out of
business'? So we put our hands up in the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
