<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-YARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRITTY CHRONICLE OF THE END OF AN ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; THE YARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Building a Destroyer at the Bath Iron Works &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Michael S. Sanders &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, 253 pp., illustrated, $26 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, the Bath Iron Works in Maine launched the USS
Donald Cook, the 463d ship completed since the shipyard was founded
in 1884, and the 25th in the Arleigh Burke class of guided-missile
destroyers.
</P>
<P>
   The building and launching of the Cook at the Bath yard occurred
without major surprise or mishap. But the very absence of problems
provided Michael S. Sanders with the opportunity _ one skillfully
realized _ to craft a vivid and richly detailed account of everyday
life and work in a blue-collar community and a hard-hat industry.
</P>
<P>
   And as more and more American workers move from jobs in which
they actually produce something to jobs where they manipulate
information, ``The Yard'' stands as a valuable documenting of what
``work'' meant to the millions of Americans who toiled before them.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, a writer and editor who lives in mid-coast Maine,
followed the building of the Cook from the first shaping of steel
sheets into hull sections through their assembly, in a world of
white-hot welding torches and ear-splitting hammer blows, to the
final, delicate placing of wedges under the hull just before
launching. His story concludes with the meaning of it all, the Cook
on its final sea trials and commissioning.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is not only observant, but possessed of an ability to
translate detailed observation into meaningful description. In
that, he is backed up by the unusually generous illustrations _ 40
line drawings that detail every stage in the construction of the
ship, and dozens of photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are plunged into the cavernous shed Sanders calls
``Vulcan's Workshop'' as the 4-to-midnight shift works on the
deckhouse base. ``Every sound is magnified inside the steel
labyrinth, the screech of Merle's grinder leveling off welding
scars, the rhythmic clang of Randy's hammer falling on a punch
laying out a bulkhead, the background thrum of huge ventilation
fans overhead, the crackle and pop of Luke's stick-welding the next
bulkhead over, the hissing rush of a plasma torch cutting through
steel, the characteristic electrical buzz of a welder's pulse-arc
gun melting the endlessly uncoiling wire into a seam, the deep,
complaining bongs as Eric tightens a bolt, dragging several tons of
steel unhappily into alignment, the whole overlaid with the
staccato shouts of mechanics struggling to be heard over the
cacophony.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, inevitably, moments of peril _ which are rendered
even more heart-stopping by the seeming nonchalance with which they
are shrugged off. A 4-inch square of steel rips off its strapping
and clatters to the floor. `` `Jaysus!' Mike yells, jumping back.
His hands were only a few inches from the path of the pad eye.
`That was not funny,' he says. `I coulda knocked ashes into my
coffee.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One of the last actions before the Cook is launched, the driving
of wooden wedges under the hull to allow the removal of fixed
supports so that the hull will float free from its cradle, is one
unchanged (except in size and scale) since the launching of the
Virginie Sagadahoc, the first ship built in the New World, at
Phippsburg, just down the Kennebec River from Bath, 390 years
before.
</P>
<P>
   And this is a doubly nostalgic moment, because the Cook will be
one of the last ships to be launched in the traditional manner,
sliding down grease- and wax-coated timbers into the water. The
yard is already preparing a 10-acre platform on which future ships
will be built and then moved on rails into a submersible drydock.
This will allow for the building of larger, heavier ships that
cannot be built in the traditional manner _ and it is a necessity
if Bath is to continue building ships.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, there are great stories that are part of the
yard's folklore. One of the best involves the launching of the
guided-missile frigate Oliver Hazard Perry, in 1977. It refused to
start down the ways despite the best efforts of the yard crew. Then
someone in the crowd called out to actor John Wayne, who was a
guest on the launching platform: ``Hey, Duke! Give 'em a hand!'' He
got up, waved to the crowd, and walked down to the stern of the
ship. ``He just sort of leaned'' toward the ship, the chief
engineer at the launch told Sanders, ``and all of a sudden, that
ship started.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the future of Bath Iron Works, shipbuilding is one of
the things that have defined the Maine coast from the earliest
days. And ``The Yard'' is in the long tradition of grand writing
about it.
</P>
<P>
   This is a 100-ton, klaxon-horned, iron-and-steel version of ``A
Unit of Water, a Unit of Time,'' Douglass Whynott's lovingly
evocative account of the building of a wooden sailing yacht at
Brooklin, just a few miles farther east.
</P>
<P>
   There is the same wealth of detail, the same sharp-eyed sketches
of workers, the same sensitive placing of the shipyard in the
context of the surrounding community _ only larger in scale and
infinitely grittier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
