<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGN-GETREAL-BOS &LR;      10-25 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH FOR AUTHENTICITY ON THE HUSTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 REAL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If every important phase of a presidential campaign is defined
by a distinct mood, the theme of fall 1999 has been the thirst for
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   The desire for real people rather than realpolitik explains the
rapid rise of former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley and the slower
but steady progress of Arizona US Senator John McCain, just as it
helps explicate last week's demise of former cabinet secretary
Elizabeth Dole and the woes besetting Vice President Al Gore as the
contenders prepare for this week's debates at Dartmouth College.
</P>
<P>
   Why the emphasis on the real?
</P>
<P>
   Former US Rep. Chester Atkins puts it this way: ``In
presidential elections and in second marriages, people look for the
exact qualities missing in their previous choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus we get an energetic Kennedy after a staid Eisenhower, an
honest Carter after a scheming Nixon, an optimistic, delegating
Reagan after a detailed-bogged, gloomy Gus of a Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after almost seven years of a president so wily he's
willing to parse the meaning of ``is,'' the public understandably
wants someone who is (in the traditional sense of the word) what he
seems.
</P>
<P>
   Authenticity is tricky thing, of course. Give voice to your
Fruit of the Loom fantasies and, as Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura
has learned, candor can do as much damage to reputation as a flying
body slam off the top turnbuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no less shrewd a barometer of the public mood than John
Sasso, a veteran of three Democratic presidential campaigns, thinks
true political authenticity -- defined as the quality of being
reasonably forthright and candid, as refusing to pander or
patronize or evade, of showing some independence of mind and issue
-- is proving to be a defining test.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are longing for a politician who is less political, who
is comfortable with himself, who is straight-talking,'' says John
Sasso, a veteran of three Democratic presidential campaigns.
``Authenticity and trust may be the wave in 2,000 the way Jimmy
Carter's `I will never lie to you' was in 1976 or John Kennedy's
`Let's Get the Country Moving Again' was in 1960.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Peter Hart, who has done a number of focus groups
gauging voter feeling, says it's the sentiment that has buoyed both
Bradley and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have seen a lot of the political types and a lot of the
media-produced and consultant produced candidates,'' says Hart.
``They look at Bill Bradley and John McCain and the word that we
hear coming to us is `authentic.' They may not be perfect people,
but what you see is what you get.''
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, that quality is seen in a willingness to brave the
slings and arrows of his own party to battle to ban the soft money
that he thinks, and says, corrupts the process.
</P>
<P>
   That's why former Congressman Guy Molinari, now Staten Island
borough president, an early supporter of George W., decided last
week to break with Bush and support McCain instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched him debating his own Republican colleagues in
sometimes acrimonious debate,'' said Molinari. ``He has the
strength and courage to do that, so I started to search my soul and
my conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, it's been a quiet determination to speak his mind
in his own way on his own timetable, taking thoughtful stands on
big issues like gun control, universal health care, and child
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   One important fact grounding both men in the public mind is that
both came to public attention outside of politics, says Democratic
consultant Mary Anne Marsh. McCain's five and a half years as a
prisoner of war in Vietnam speaks to a courage and mental toughness
unmatched in the field, while Bradley's determined, dignified NBA
career shows him a high-minded competitor determined to do things
his own way, she thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because people know their personal histories and who they are
as people it makes them much more willing to believe the promises
they make as they run for president,'' says Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider the perils of the inauthentic.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's victim was Elizabeth Dole, whose quest started with
high hopes, but was soon hampered by the ultra-cautious nature of a
candidate so programmed she seemed robotic, so averse to
spontaneity that even a seeming casual decision to leave the podium
and mingle the crowd was planned -- and announced -- in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's loss is McCain's gain. In the last few months, McCain has
made steady progress toward establishing himself as the only
plausible alternative to Bush. Dole's departure should formally
crystallize the sense of a choice narrowed to two, for McCain and
Bush are the only two plausible GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   That political paring, in turn, should worry George W.; though
he is charismatic and affable, he's also a candidate built by the
consultancy, and as someone learning the issues as he goes, Bush
can't hope to compete with McCain's candid style.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Texas governor's decision to skip Thursday's GOP
forum at Dartmouth will only underscore that sense.
</P>
<P>
   Which is one reason former New Hampshire Senator Warren Rudman,
admittedly a McCain partisan, thinks the Arizona senator looks
increasingly good in New Hampshire, where, according to the latest
polls, he now trails Bush by only 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's candor can get him in a little trouble sometimes, but
overall I think it's what people are looking for,'' said Rudman.
``The results of the last eight years have been so much
controversy, so much partisanship, so much back-biting, so many
purely political statements as opposed to dealing factually with
the issues that my sense is that people really want someone who
talks right to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudman, of course, is focused on the GOP race -- but his sense
of the public is one that Gore should take notice of.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the vice president's reaction thus far to Bradley's
surge suggests he misinterprets the public sentiment as mostly
public weariness with Clinton. During a recent visit to the Globe,
Gore revealed that mindset, saying, ``I'm counting on Clinton
fatigue fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Gore is undoubtedly suffering from association, his
problem goes far beyond a weariness with all things Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the latest University of Massachusetts
survey, conducted Sept. 29-Oct. 5, which showed Bradley now
narrowly leads Gore in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The single biggest individual difference in voters' minds
between the two? A sense that Bradley is a genuine person. Asked
who ``talks and acts like an upfront person,'' 22.7 percent chose
Gore, while 42.6 percent said Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   In the search of a better connection, Gore has moved his
headquarters from Washington to Nashville, altered his wardrobe,
and even declared that henceforth he will override his innate
inclination to think before he speaks.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the vice-president has come up with a plan to be
authentic. That's not only risible, but risky, should voters spot
the man behind the curtain. ``Gore has a credibility problem that
could become critical if his shape-shifting becomes obvious,''
notes political analyst Lou DiNatale.
</P>
<P>
   It's a risk aggravated by a growing disparity between the new,
candid candidate Gore claims to be and the way he continues to
campaign. Consider: in the three weeks since leaving the dreaded
beltway, Gore has courted -- and won -- the AFL-CIO's endorsement,
while trying to lock up Democratic Party superdelegates, the
party's consummate insiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore has moved to Nashville, but he sends a different message:
I am an insider,'' said Richard Morris, the political consultant
who helped plot Clinton's 1996 campaign. ``His reliance on the
AFL-CIO endorsement and on the super-delegate strategy vitiates the
move to Nashville and only adds to his woes.''
</P>
<P>
   If Gore's psychic address is still K Street, Washington, so,
too, do the campaign barbs he has directed Bradley's way have a
distinct inside-the-beltway feel to them.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the gravamen of his critique of Bradley runs this way:
the former New Jersey senator should be suspect with real Democrats
because he voted for the Reagan budget cuts; supported the contras;
has voted for vouchers for children trapped in perennially
under-performing public schools; and quit the Senate in 1996, to
mull running for president as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   But those arguments Those are weak arguments for half a host of
reasons. For starters, that tack, like his promise to the AFL-CIO
to veto ``any anti-union bill,'' position Gore, once in the
vanguard of the moderate ``New Democrat'' movement, squarely as the
defender of old-line Democratic orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   As Sasso notes, ``Gore may be reinforcing exactly what a lot of
Democrats like about Bradley: that he is not adhering to a certain
orthodoxy and that he is his own person.''
</P>
<P>
   But most tellingly, with the exception of Gore's charge that
Bradley's plan to expand health care is prohibitively expensive,
the vice president's critique of his rival speaks not to principled
policy differences, but rather of tactical sniping, in some cases
on matters more than a decade old.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in other words, nothing more than politics as usual. And
there's nothing at all authentic about that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1519EDT &QL; 
