<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMS IS HURTING GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While some Republicans recognize the need to reach out to
African-Americans and Hispanics in the 2000 election, US Senator
Jesse Helms and other arch-conservatives appear to be doing their
best to distance those groups.
</P>
<P>
   Helms is virulently opposed most recently to President Clinton's
nomination of former Illinois Senator Carol Moseley-Braun as
ambassador to New Zealand. His outspoken stance may well drive more
African-Americans and Hispanics into the outstretched arms of the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee, Helms has the
power and influence to block a nomination, as demonstrated with his
refusal in 1997 to bring William F. Weld's doomed nomination as
ambassador to Mexico to a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   This time Helms is taking on the first black woman elected to
the Senate. If Tom Daschle, the minority leader from South Dakota,
is correct, no former senator has been rejected for an
ambassadorial post since 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Helms's opposition is creating more problems for him and his
party than for her and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   It is well-known, for example, that Moseley-Braun in 1993 almost
single-handedly defeated Helms's proposal to renew the United
Daughters of the Confederacy's design patent on an insignia that
featured a Confederate flag in a wreath. Although the Senate
earlier approved the proposal, Moseley-Braun said in an impassioned
Senate speech that the flag was an emblem of slavery. The Senate
voted 75 to 25 to reject it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, six years later, Helms apparently still is miffed over that
stinging defeat by a freshman senator. Last week, he said he would
block the nomination unless Moseley-Braun apologized to him. ``At
the very minimum, she has got to apologize for the display that she
provoked over a little symbol for a wonderful group of little old
ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Helms's lingering anger at Moseley-Braun for her
defeat of a symbol of slavery and segregation tells more about his
views toward blacks than about her qualifications to be ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was that that prompted him to change the reason
behind his problem with her nomination. He was later quoted saying
that ``this nomination comes to the Senate with an ethical cloud
hanging over Ms. Moseley-Braun.'' Without providing specific
allegations, Helms said that ``charges of ethical lapses led the
voters of Illinois to determine she was not fit to represent them
in the US Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   What Helms was referring to were questions about her handling of
campaign finances and about a trip she made to Nigeria to meet with
the dictator Sani Abacha. Her opponent, Peter Fitzgerald, made
these questions the main focus of his successful campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service opened an investigation of her
campaign finances, but there were no resulting charges or
penalties. Ironically, Fitzgerald was quoted in a news article
saying he ``probably would have voted with Senator Moseley-Braun on
that issue'' of the Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent attempt to further bolster his own opposition,
Helms said in a statement that questions about her were raised by
the New Zealand government. Prime Minister Jenny Shipley said the
New Zealand government raised no questions about Moseley-Braun,
adding, ``I don't think they should bring the New Zealand
government into it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Helms is left with is his own mean-spirited and petty
attempts to block the nomination of a black woman, a former
senator, who defeated him fair and square on an issue. Media
reports on the nomination have pointed out that Helms's opposition
may be rooted in his views on race, and the flag issue.
</P>
<P>
   As most observers familiar with Helms's record knows, he was a
staunch segregationist in the 1950s and '60s. In the 1970s, he
denounced the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. He also launched a
filibuster against legislation making King's birthday a national
holiday. And in the 1980s, he supported apartheid in South Africa.
Many critics viewed his 1990 campaign against Harvey Gantt, an
African-American, as one of the most racist campaigns in recent
memory.
</P>
<P>
   Helms's opposition to this nomination also highlights stances by
other Republicans that reflect poorly on their view toward blacks
and Hispanics. Earlier this month, Senate Republicans voted in a
55-to-45 party-line vote to reject the nomination of Judge Ronnie
White, the first black on Missouri's Supreme Court, to a federal
judgeship. Democrats argue that race was a factor in the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, including Clinton, also point to Republican-led
stalling in the Senate on the president's nomination of Richard A.
Baez, a Hispanic, to the US Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit.
As Daschle said, there appears to be an ``array of anti-minority
sentiment'' being expressed by Republicans on these issues.
</P>
<P>
   If Helms continues to remind voters about his actions and those
of his GOP fellows, he may be one of the best allies the Democrats
have in their quest to wrest control of Congress next year.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
