<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7823 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NEWSPAPER-POLITICS-2N     10-25 1551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-POLITICS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... the Journal piece.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Observers of the Journal were not suprised to find damaging
allegations against Clinton on the editorial page. But what is so
unusual, and unique to Bartley's tenure, is that a story alleging a
violent felony by Clinton was not produced by the news staff, but
by the opinion pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess from where I sit, it doesn't matter to me very much
whether we break a story on the editorial page or on the front
page,'' says Kann. ``The Wall Street Journal probably does more
analytical, interpretive journalism on its front page than most
newspapers, and our editorial page does more reporting, breaks more
news than most, if not all, newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   But managing editor Paul Steiger, who oversees the Journal's
news pages, had reservations about the Broaddrick piece. ``It's not
a story that I would have sent a reporter after,'' he says.
``You've got to make judgments about where you concentrate your
fire. This happened way before Clinton was running for president .
. . It's got to be in the realm of `he said, she said,'
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartley's fiercely independent fiefdom can create the impression
that the Journal's editorial and news pages are published by two
different papers, a journalism phenomenon described as the
unbreachable wall between ``church and state.''
</P>
<P>
   Some old hands still recall how Bartley antagonized the paper's
Washington bureau during a combative 1980 dinner meeting by
suggesting that his editorial page staffers were better news hounds
than the Beltway reporters. Bartley acknowledges that at that
dinner, he was sitting on the news that he was about to win the
Pulitzer prize for editorial writing and ``I was full of myself . .
. There was a message that `you have to understand that we have
access to some sources that you don't.'''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the editorial page alienates crucial Beltway sources,
Steiger calls it an overall ``asset,'' but says, ``yes, there are
people who despise its politics . . . Frankly we can usually make
these people understand the difference'' between news and opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Strange as it may seem, Bob Bartley went on C-SPAN in 1992 and
actually said: ``I don't have any real strong opinions about Bill
Clinton. I don't think he's a menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know at what point I would have explicitly
abandoned,'' that view, he now says. But ``the more you poked at''
the president's Arkansas inner circle, ``the more creatures you
found.'' Rabinowitz says her boss takes genuine ``moral offense''
at the president.
</P>
<P>
   Many editorial pages have made no secret of their quarrels with
Clinton, but none has pursued him with the Journal's vigor. ``The
problem with Clinton was not the sex, but the lies,'' says Bartley,
flashing his lethal wit. ``Sex happened to be the one he got caught
for because it was the hardest to delegate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Journal's case against Clinton long predated Monica
Lewinsky. Early on, the editorial page took aim at Foster, starting
with a 1993 piece called ``Who is Vincent Foster?'' that made a
significant issue of the fact that Foster would not provide the
Journal with a photo. When Foster was later found dead along with a
note that read ``WSJ editors lie without consequence,'' Bartley
went from the hunter to the hunted, with critics questioning
whether he could sleep at night.
</P>
<P>
   After Foster's death, Journal editorials raised the theory that
he had been murdered _ lauding the work of leading murder
conspiracy proponent and fringe journalist Christopher Ruddy _
before finally accepting the suicide ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we said was (Foster's death) was never seriously
investigated and ought to be,'' says Bartley. ``The only guy around
who seemed to be investigating it was Chris Ruddy.'' He dimsisses
allegations that the Journal may have driven Foster to suicidal
despair as White House ``spin . . . We shined the spotlight on this
guy. Vince Foster was thought of as a steely litigator from this
tough law firm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Journal's editorial pages also ardently pursued the Clinton
version of ``X-Files,'' a series of shadowy allegations about drug
dealing and skulduggery near Mena, Arkansas while Clinton was
governor. The story never gained traction in the mainstream press,
but Bartley ran numerous pieces with headlines like ``Mysterious
Mena,'' and ``The Mena Coverup.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits there never was any smoking gun, but ``the point about
Mena . . . and drug smuggling was that Arkansas was a pretty
corrupt place,'' says Bartley. ``He was the governor at the time .
. . Why isn't it a story?''
</P>
<P>
   The fascination with subjects like the Foster murder theory and
Mena not only gained the editorial page a reputation as the media's
leading Clinton hater. It left even some sympathizers shaking their
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as The Weekly Standard didn't like Clinton, we didn't
see as many conspiracies as the Journal,'' says Barnes. And former
editorial page staffer Jude Wanniski chastises Bartley for
``chewing up all his energies playing Captain Ahab trying to get
the White Whale in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bartley speaks, it sometimes looks like the words are
causing him pain. He gives no hint of that passion and
pugnaciousness. But according to his chief deputy, the juices don't
really start flowing until the hunt begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Bartley has probably the best news instinct of any
journalist I've been around,'' says deputy editorial page editor
Dan Henninger, a 22-year Journal veteran, who now supervises much
of the daily workload. ``He loves to chase the news. It actually
physically animates him in a discernable way.''
</P>
<P>
   Steiger, the managing editor, credits Bartley with pioneering
``the reported editorial.'' With Bartley, that can mean the tricky
intersection of fact and opinion. A Journal editorial on Broaddrick
asserted that ``the truth doesn't necessarily lie in a 50-50
balance between consenting parties. The truth is sometimes served
by reporting based on a view of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   That idea sparks some debate. ``Their reporting is not real
reporting,'' says Alter. ``It sometimes digs up great stuff, but at
a fundamental level, it's pretend reporting'' because it doesn't
always examine both sides of an issue.
</P>
<P>
   In a decade-old piece in The American Lawyer headlined ``Daily
Diatribe of the American Right,'' Stuart Taylor asserted that the
editorial page's reporting on a variety of legal issues _ from its
assault on Michael Dukakis' veto of pledge of allegiance
legislation, to its campaign against opponents of Robert Bork's
Supreme Court nomination _ was driven more by raging ideology than
a quest for the facts.
</P>
<P>
   A similarly critcal 1996 Columbia Journlism Review piece by
freelancer Trudy Lieberman called ``Bartley's Believe it Or Not!''
accused the editorial page of being ``riddled with errors.'' It
cited inaccurate Journal attacks on everything from judicial
nominees to the Smithsonian's Enola Gay exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Never one to let a challenge go unanswered, Bartley retaliated
with a 2,000-word Journal piece assailing Lieberman's employer, the
Consumer's Union, as a lackey for big-money lawsuits and lawyers.
In a piece on the controversy that he wrote for the liberal
magazine The Nation, Eric Alterman concluded that picking a fight
with Bartley ``is a bit like leaping head first into a tank of
starving piranhas.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Bartley's biggest _ and most revealing _ battle was the
famous ``Yellow Rain'' affair. Butting heads with The New York
Times and a good chunk of the scientific community, the Journal's
editorial page waged an intense campaign throughout the 80's to
convince readers that so-called ``Yellow Rain'' in Southeast Asia
in the 1970's was a sinister Soviet biological weapon. (In his
recent memoir, former Times executive editor Max Frankel indulged
in a bit of gloating, mocking the Journal's position when, as he
put it, Yellow Rain ``turned out to have been bee excrement.'')
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Bartley remains ``convinced we're right'' about
``Yellow Rain.'' Lipsky calls the subject ``the most important of
the (Journal) controversies . . . It was the implication behind it,
it was that the Soviets couldn't be trusted to stick to a weapons
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   In several telling ways, Yellow Rain was classic Bartley. It
represented reporting based on a world view. And most importantly,
it allowed this quiet man to engage in his favorite passion _
loudly slugging it out with the media establishment, the scientific
community, and anyone else who doubts the righteousness of his
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Bartley admits the ``one time in which (his job) wasn't much fun
was the Bush administration,'' when he had a president he couldn't
love or loathe. Of George W., he says: ``We would hope . . . that
as the campaign goes on Bush develops more of a message on the
issues.'' One gets the strong sense that given his druthers,
Bartley would have more fun spending the next four years
carpet-bombing President Al Gore or Bill Bradley than pulling his
punches with another Bush administration. Conscientious objector
status just doesn't suit him.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Arthur Laffer, one of Bartley's early supply-side
gurus and an old friend, neatly sums up the Bartley credo. ``Bob
really wants to be in the battle til he's dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
