<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7834 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-LOWELL-DISCOVERY-LADN     10-25 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOWELL-DISCOVERY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTOPHER LOWELL EXPANDS HIS OEUVRE ON DISCOVERY CHANNEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: this story filed on both `e' entertainment and `l' lifestyle
wires) 
 
 
By MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Basic-issue gray carpeting, faux wood paneling ...
Martha Stewart wouldn't be caught dead in this place. That's just
fine with Christopher Lowell, vox pop decorator and king of the
Discovery Channel with his ``Christopher Lowell Show.''
</P>
<P>
   An eight-hour marathon of the retooled one-hour daytime show
(formerly called ``Interior Motives With Christopher Lowell'')
garnered some of Discovery's highest-ever daytime ratings over
Labor Day weekend. It's now airing regularly, twice a day at noon
and 3 p.m. weekdays. Lowell gets about 2,000 pieces of fan mail a
week. He plans to launch his own magazine next year, along with a
catalog full of exclusive products, his first book (from Random
House) and a line of paint (he's not yet saying who the
manufacturer is) to be sold in stores around the country.
</P>
<P>
   One of his few regrets: that he can no longer go to Home Depot
without being mobbed. ``Oh, please ... It's like I'm doing a
personal appearance,'' says Lowell with a wave of his hand. ``It's
like I'm a doctor. People come up to me and say, `I have this sofa
...' But,'' he quickly adds, ``I have great fans. They see me as a
trusted friend.''
</P>
<P>
   On the backlot of Universal Studios, the trim, balding and
bearded Lowell presides over ``Camp Christopher,'' a collection of
five unremarkable brown trailers surrounding a makeshift basketball
court (``I've never seen Christopher play basketball ... it's
mostly the show's crew,'' admits a show assistant). The show moved
to the Universal lot this season from a studio in Chatsworth,
giving the show, if not its offices, an upscale new look.
</P>
<P>
   The office decor may not be fancy, but there's plenty of coffee
and encouragement to go around for the hard-working staff. ``You
Can Do It!'' is the slogan that appears on the walls of the
offices. It's a philosophy Lowell takes very seriously; he's even
named his own corporation You Can Do It Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I created this show, I was the first to say, `This is
about personal transformation. This is about self-esteem,' Lowell
says. We get thousands of letters from people who have taken up
these projects little by little. They may watch for a year, then
slowly start trying some things. They get up off the couch, get
moving again, get involved in life again.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell is as much a combination of fitness cheerleader Richard
Simmons and motivational guru Tony Robbins as a spiritual relative
of Stewart. He's a smart businessman first, but he also has a sense
of mission to ``make a difference in people's lives,'' he says
earnestly. Though he's quick to give credit to his staff and the
people at the Discovery Channel, Lowell isn't exactly modest about
his own talents and accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had a lot of talent in a lot of different areas,'' he
says matter-of-factly. ``I wanted to feel like I was using it to
make a difference in people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell has certainly made his mark on the Discovery Channel,
where, he says, he's become the cable network's ``first personality
franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Christopher' is our No. 1 series; there's no question about
that,'' agrees Chuck Gingold, senior vice president of daytime
programming for the Bethesda, Md.-based Discovery Channel. ``He is
a unique personality, flamboyant, and lots of fun. He speaks in a
style that's accessible, with his whole `you can do it'
philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell isn't resting on his laurels, though. With a carafe of
coffee and a pack of Benson &AMP; Hedges on his desk, Lowell seems to
think, talk and live at full-tilt speed.
</P>
<P>
   He's apparently always been that way: Born into a creative
family (his father was a professional carpenter, a ``master
joiner''; both his grandmother and great uncle were well-known
antiques dealers), Lowell left home at the age of 9 to play piano
with the Southern California Boys Choir. He later became a
marketing executive in the cosmetics and home-furnishings
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Lowell decided to leave a high-paying position to try
entrepreneurship. He opened a home design store/classroom in
Chagrin Falls, Ohio (near Cleveland). By 1994, he'd turned his
attention to the venture full-time. He starting producing a show
for local television in an effort to expand the business. That
show, ``Interior Motives,'' was picked up by the Discovery Channel
in 1996 and quickly became a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Probably because of his own frenetic lifestyle, Lowell
understands the need to make the home a tranquil oasis in a hectic
world. He calls this idea ``sanctuary living.'' Lowell has homes in
Laurel Canyon and San Diego where he can retreat. He says he's not
approached quite as much in California, where ``people are used to
seeing celebrities ... My popularity is more between the coasts,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   With the show's move to the Universal backlot _ where it now can
be seen on the Universal tram tour, between the ``Psycho'' house
and the ``Leave It to Beaver'' house _ and his host of new projects
on the horizon, Lowell knows there is more pressure on him than
ever before. In addition, the show's format has expanded from
interior design to include themes like cooking and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell says what will continue to distinguish his show from
those of Martha Stewart and a host of other
decorating-and-lifestyle mavens is his emphasis on practicality.
``Martha Stewart is not a how-to show,'' says Lowell. ``She shows
us how she lives in the Hamptons. Beautifully, I might add. But
it's aspirational, not practical. She's got a staff of 90 people
and a big budget. I put myself on the same budget for my room redos
as my main audience, and I only do things that viewers can easily
do themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell is big on simplicity: hot-glue guns, hammers and scissors
are about the most complicated he gets in terms of the tools he
uses on the show. His projects focus on problem-solving (making a
small room look bigger, finding uses for wasted space) rather than
impressing guests at chi-chi dinners and cocktail parties.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell's book next year will outline his theory of the ``seven
layers'' of decorating, starting with architecture and paint and
ending with plants and lighting. The idea, he says, is to take the
fear out of decorating by showing women that it's no more
complicated than applying makeup or accessorizing a dress. He plans
future books that will go into more depth on each of the
``layers.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what comes next after all this, the fast-moving Lowell
says that's yet to be decided. ``I've been approached about doing
things like CDs for home entertaining and motivational tapes,''
Lowell says. ``Discovery has basically told me that I have a home
with them for as long as I want. As long as it's fun and
challenging, I'll do it. That, and making a difference, is what
propels me forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1531EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
