u e BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS &LR;      10-25 0192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; RECOMMENDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Selected from books recently reviewed in the Globe:
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainsong'' by Kent Haruf (Knopf, $24). An outcast girl in a
Colorado town finds love and care on the farm of two eccentric
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``More Matter: Essays and Criticism'' by John Updike (Knopf,
$35). A new collection from a busy pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stiffed: The Betrayal of the American Man'' by Susan Faludi
(Morrow, $26). A feminist approach to the woes of the guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nelson Mandela'' by Anthony Sampson (Knopf, $30). An
authorized biography of the South African president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lovers for a Day: New and Collected Stories'' by Ivan Klima
(Grove, $24). Tales of the ironies and distractions of love, by the
prolific Czech writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Star Called Henry: Volume One of `The Last Roundup' '' by
Roddy Doyle (Viking, $24.95). A young Dubliner's coming of age amid
the violent history of modern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Life'' by Claire Messud (Harcourt Brace, $24). A
haunting novel of a family's flight from Algeria to France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
