<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
  
 MARKET TIMING IN   401(k) IS NOT A GOOD IDEA  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We were having a discussion at work the other day about
playing your 401(k) investment options when the term ``net
unrealized appreciation'' came up. My company's 401(k) plan allows
investment switches between various options. Some of the financial
wizards among us switch in and out of the company stock as the
price fluctuates, hoping to catch an additional gain by timing it
right. One individual said he had heard the practice was a very bad
thing to do as it effectively raised the average purchase price of
all your shares and increased the tax base. Can you provide a
layman's description of the potential tax ramifications of 401(k)
investment switching?
</P>
<P>
   J.W., Boston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In a word: none. When you put pretax money into a 401(k), you
face no tax liability until it is withdrawn, at which point all of
the money, including the accumulated investment gains, is taxable
as ordinary income.
</P>
<P>
   Investments within tax-deferred accounts are not subject to
capital gains taxes, so thus there is no concern about base costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Net unrealized appreciation'' is a term that applies to
investments that could create a capital gains tax liability if they
were sold. It's an important measure to watch if you're buying a
mutual fund for a taxable account and are worried that it might
deliver you an unpleasant tax bill in the form of a capital gains
distribution; the higher the net unrealized appreciation, the
greater the possibility of such a jolt.
</P>
<P>
   It is because of these (and other) distributions that a fund can
create a tax liability for you even in a year when it operates in
the red. But it is of no concern if your investments are in a
401(k) or IRA or any other tax-deferred vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, though, is that I'd like to get my oar into your
discussion of market timing within a 401(k). I think it's a bum
idea, not because of any tax ramifications, but because market
timing is one of the most difficult games to play.
</P>
<P>
   It's fine if you get it right, but it can be disastrous if you
get it wrong. If your friends are indeed great market timers, they
could probably do better by quitting their jobs and joining the
very thin ranks of successful market timers on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But usually, it's the buy-and-hold investors who do best in the
long run, and I suggest you follow that practice.
</P>
<P>
   (at)j
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like your opinion on whether we are on the right
track. I am 39 and my wife is 37, and we have the following
investments, all in American Century funds: In taxable accounts I
have $18,000 in American Century Growth, to which I add $150 a
month; $7,500 in American Century Balanced; and $3,600 in American
Century Global Growth. In a SEP-IRA I have $14,000 in Growth, and
$1,800 in American Century International Growth. I have two Roth
IRA accounts totaling $1,600. My wife has a $2,000 Roth IRA in the
Growth fund, to which she adds $75 a month. We also have $3,000
worth of IBM stock, and $25,000 in a savings account _ for safety
because I sometimes go four to six weeks without work. I am an
independent consultant earning about $125,000 a year and my wife
has a small retail business earning about $25,000 a year. Are our
investments diversified enough, and how will our position be in 15
years?
</P>
<P>
   L.S., Sharon, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Alas, unless you start saving more, your position is likely
to be pretty bleak in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   I calculate your combined savings rate at 5.1 percent of your
total income. Keeping your emergency savings aside, if your
investments earn average annual total returns of 10 percent and you
keep saving at the $641 monthly rate, you'll have $470,983 in 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   If inflation runs at an average 3.5 percent, that will have the
same buying power of about $280,000 in today's money _ enough to
provide you with an income stream of $18,200 a year. That's a
fairly precipitous drop from $150,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   So before you begin worrying too much about diversification, I
suggest you worry about your budget. It seems to me that you would
need to roughly triple your savings rate now _ and add to it
whenever you can _ to have any realistic shot at a comfortable
retirement in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Tripling the contributions would take the accumulation to
$982,695, and even that is not a lavish amount for people who have
been living on $150,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   As for diversification, you have very little of it. Twentieth
Century Ultra and Growth funds both hold portfolios dominated by
large-cap domestic stocks, while the stock side of the Balanced
fund is in similar shares. Nearly half of the Global Growth
portfolio is in US or Canadian large-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   I'd consider one of American Century's Small Cap funds _ Small
Cap Quantum, Small Cap Value, or New Opportunities. None of them
has the kind of records you have seen with your large-cap holdings,
but I think that's more a function of the unpopularity of the
sector rather than the funds themselves.
</P>
<P>
   I would also look for a mid-cap fund. There are none within the
American Century family that appeals to me, so you might consider
Vanguard's Mid-Cap Index fund to represent that sector.
</P>
<P>
   I would aim for a portfolio with no more than 60 percent of your
retirement savings in large-cap domestic stocks, with the balance
spread among small-cap, mid-cap, international, and perhaps health
care funds _ restricting the final investment to offerings such as
Fidelity Select Health Care, which focus on pharmaceuticals and
medical equipment investments (rather than HMOs and similar
companies and biotechnology companies).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
