<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BUSINESS-BOOKS-ONLINE     10-25 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-BOOKS-ONLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SUMMARY, A NEW WEB BUSINESS IS BORN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Wilcox wants to create the Cliffs Notes of business books
_ key concepts and summaries of recently published books designed
to help people easily research a broad set of categories _ from
management to finance and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbing through a stack of new books in Barnes &AMP; Noble
Booksellers or an airport bookstore only to find one or two that
address key issues, or slogging through a 300-page tome that failed
to deliver what the dust jacket promised, are problems Wilcox says
he has solved.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 15, he is scheduled to launch www.means business.com, an
on-line database service for researching 1,500 business concepts
along with book summaries distilled from 400 recent books on
business. They range from the popular ``Inside the Tornado,'' by
Geoffrey Moore and Peter Drucker's ``Adventures of a Bystander,''
to more specialized books as ``Rethinking the Sales Force'' by Neil
Rackham and John Devincentis, and ``Competitors: Outwitting,
Outmaneuvering and Outperforming,'' by Liam Fahey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The re-engineering of the work force in the early 1990s has
required people to rethink their careers, figure out how to stay
ahead in their jobs by understanding new business concepts and
getting the latest information quickly at their desktop computer,''
said Wilcox.
</P>
<P>
   Users receive free preview screens that provide a one-line
explanation of a book's concept and the length of the extract. For
more details, users pay $8 to $15 for a collection of eight or more
extracts from several books about a single business concept.
</P>
<P>
   If one book has all the concepts the user is seeking, they are
printed out as 20 to 30 extracts, each three to five paragraphs and
organized consecutively as they are in the book. It costs $12 to
$15, which is about half the price of the hardcover book. However
from the Web site, users can buy the complete book for the cover
price.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox estimates that typical users will spend $200 to $300 per
year with wwwmeansbusiness.com. For researchers expected to use the
service often, there is a flat $700 per month fee.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of selling business concepts and extracts as well as
complete books appeals to book publishers Harper Collins, McGraw
Hill, John Wiley, Warner Books and Oxford University Press. They
are among 11 of the 14 largest publishers who have signed long-term
catalog license agreements with Boston-based MeansBusiness. Under
the agreements, authors of each book will receive an undisclosed
percentage of MeansBusiness revenues for subsidiary rights as well
as royalties on any books sold, said Wilcox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is teeming with innovation but what MeansBusiness
has done stands out as unprecedented, because it is very creative
and has a clear utility to users,'' said Adrian W. Zackheim,
associate publisher of Harper Collins general book group and
editor-in-chief of Harper Information, which includes Harper
Business books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the concepts being used by people to do research, from
preparing a speech, putting together summaries on detailed topics
to groups working as a team to complete a project.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically most books on business management generate sales of
under 5,000 copies with 10,000 copies considered a modest success
and 100,000 copies a blockbuster (well below the 250,000-plus found
in best-seller nonfiction books).
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the books are essentially brochures of the consulting
industry, but beyond the self promotion, they include the kinds of
detailed concepts and experiences that can help business people,''
said Wilcox.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox found what he calls ``smart people who can type fast'' _
to read the books and extract the relevant parts using the authors
own words. Once the concepts and summaries are gleaned, the authors
and their publishers review them before they are put in the
database.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (MeansBusiness) have a damm good idea and are clearly
going one-up on what people have done already,'' said Dale Kutnick,
president of Meta Group, a market research firm in Stamford, Conn.
``We are becoming much more of a clip art society, where snippets
and bullets of information are becoming the mode that people want
to operate. They want to be smart in 10 minutes of reading _ not
plow through a 300-page book.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all its promise, Kutnick is not sure that selling
concepts and summaries on a fee basis is the right business model.
He prefers a lower-priced subcription fee.
</P>
<P>
   And Zackheim of Harper Collins is not so sure publishers will
sell many complete books through MeansBusiness. ``We are
intrigued,'' he said, acknowledging it may take some time for
people to understand how access to conceptual information _ ideas,
principles, theories, models and methodolologies _ aggregated from
books will work on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me awhile to grasp what they were doing,'' he
concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
