<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-VIDEOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD AND THE BAD ON VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``Arlington Road'' _ This chilling suspense film,
starring Jeff Bridges as a suspicious history professor, didn't do
much at the box office. Don't let that deter you from renting this
first-rate, very disturbing thriller. It's for smart people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blair Witch Project'' _ Originality rules. The charming
artistry of this movie isn't really the film itself but the
anti-mainstream tale of its birth and life. It's great to see a
project that breaks all the rules win. Perhaps the commercial
success of this phenomenon will inspire others to cut through the
old tired formulas as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy Ruxpin: The Movie'' _ I thought he was dead. Not so. The
boy toy of the '80s has been resurrected by the marketers for this
lame story about trying to find the Princess. There are much better
films for kids but those who grew up with Ruxpin might gets some
nostalgic yucks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DVD UPDATE: The good news is that ``Chinatown'' and ``Apocalypse
Now'' are being released on DVD on Nov. 23. The latter contains a
commentary by Francis Ford Coppola but not, as far as we know, his
wife Eleanor Coppolla's provocative 1991 documentary ``Hearts of
Darkness: A Filmmaker's Apocalypse.'' As Coppolla recalled in 1979,
as quoted in ``Halliwell's Film Guide,'' ``We had access to too
much money, too much equipment, and little by little we went
insane.'' ``Chinatown'' (1979), one of the best films ever made,
also had one of the most creatively contentious sets. According to
Paramount, they've assembled new interviews with director Roman
Polanski, screenwriter Robert Towne, and producer Robert Evans.
Nothing from stars Jack Nicholson and Faye Dunaway but, if the
other three tell the acrimonious details of the production it
should be nearly as dramatic as the film. Also, Jonathan Demme's
``Stop Making Sense,'' his meditation on David Byrne and Talking
Heads, is out on DVD on Tuesday with audio commentary by all the
band members and Demme.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS: Nov. 9: ``Notting Hill,'' ``Life is
Beautiful'' (dubbed English language version), ``Instinct,'' ``The
Castle,'' ``Heaven,'' ``Pal Joey'' (DVD), ``Sore Losers,'' ``Black
and White,'' ``Strangers,'' ``Ma Vie En Rose'' (DVD), ``Break Up,''
``Heartbeeps,'' ``The Milky Way,'' ``Rogue Trader.'' Nov. 16:
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' ``The Loss of Sexual
Innocence,'' ``Tea with Mussolini,'' ``The Last Picture Show''
(DVD), ``The Castle,'' ``Dr. Akaki.'' Nov. 23: ``The Haunting,''
``The Iron Giant,'' ``The Autumn Tale,'' ``The Draughtsman's
Contract'' (DVD), ``A Zed and Two Noughts'' (DVD), ``Entrapment,''
``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut.'' Nov. 30: ``The Wild Wild
West,'' ``Deep Blue Sea.'' Dec. 7: ``Hoods,'' ``Inspector Gadget.''
Dec. 14: ``The General's Daughter,'' ``The Harmonists,'' ``The Very
Thought of You,'' ``A Knight in Camelot,'' ``Drop Dead Gorgeous,''
``Teaching Mrs. Tingle.'' Dec. 21: ``Summer of Sam,'' ``Super Cop
2.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
