<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      10-25 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Current reviews by Globe critics:
</P>
<P>
   (BS) ``Bats'' Lots of computer-generated bats taking out a Texas
town. But they're no scarier than those rubber bats dangling from
strings in '50s sci-fi potboilers. This cheeseball movie has all
the guano you could hope for _ in the batcave and in the
screenplay. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS) ``The Best Man'' The most appealing black romantic
comedy since ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.'' That film's lead,
Taye Diggs, returns here as a writer with a steamy autobiographical
novel he hopes won't be published until after a weekend reunion
with his old pals. They talk trash and sort out old business in
bright, warm, breezy, generous ways in a sophisticated debut from
writer-director Malcolm E. Lee. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS) 1/2 ``Body Shots'' Four couples pair off in LA, only to
have their scenester fun come to an abrupt end when one of the
women accuses an ex-football player of date rape. This slick,
flashy, but ultimately hollow outing has moments, but for a film
that behaves as if it wants to be Neil LaBute with palm trees and a
beach scene, it plays like ``The Breakfast Club'' pulling an
all-nighter. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS)(BS) ``Boys Don't Cry'' Kimberly Peirce's strong,
haunting film based on a hate crime, the rape and murder in
Nebraska of transsexual Brandon Teena. The film brings us inside
the characters of Hilary Swank's sweet, confused, spunky,
complicated, beguiling Brandon, and the alienated young woman who
shared his fantasy, Chloe Sevigny's cooly smoky Lana. Fascinating
in its texture and detail, the film depeens into a surprisingly
profound meditation on identity and isolation. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS) 1/2 ``Bringing Out the Dead'' Who better to take a
camera out on the streets of New York at night than Martin
Scorsese? But his film about a sensitive paramedic (Nicolas Cage)
is too heavily freighted by the man's savior complex. His guilt
gets in his way _ and in the way of a film that's otherwise
compassionately and entertainingly wired. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS) 1/2 ``Crazy in Alabama'' A pretty good directing debut
from Antonio Banderas. He challenges himself by trying to join a
couple of disparate story strands, one involving a civil rights
struggle, the other involving an abused woman staging her own civil
rights struggle by decapitating her husband and taking off for
Hollywood. Melanie Griffith carries the film, playing a
larger-than-life Southern-gothic lollapalooza. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS) ``Marcello Mastroianni: I Remember'' Made during
the downtime on his last film shoot, this documentary is the molto
simpatico swan song of postwar film's great charmer. He hated the
Latin-lover stereotype, he disarmingly declares, and did his best
to play weak men. Not that it kept him from international stardom.
What's not to like about his recollections, including his memorable
collaborations with Federico Fellini? (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS) 1/2 ``Rosie'' Belgian director Patrice Toye makes
an impressive directing debut with this quietly devastating study
of a 13-year-old girl trying to make sense of her life with her
mother in a dreary suburb of Antwerp. Most of the film takes place
on the face of a non-professional, Aranka Coppens, whose stifled
intensity, confusion, and innocence make her one of the year's most
touching heroines. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS)(BS) ``The Straight Story'' Exchanging his usual
surrealistic weirdness for simplicity and eloquence, David Lynch
fashions a heartfelt and altogether disarming piece of Americana.
It's based on the true story of a 73-year-old Iowa farmer, Alvin
Straight, who decided it was time to reconcile with his ailing
brother in Wisconsin, and took off on his lawnmower to do it.
Richard Farnsworth _ that courtly, twinkling old gent and former
rodeo rider turned actor _ is sheer perfection as the sweet but
stubborn geezer. (G)
</P>
<P>
   (BS) 1/2 ``Three to Tango'' Cute characters, especially Neve
Campbell's independent mistress of an arrogant tycoon played by
Dylan McDermott. She's a tough-cookie throwback to the '30s. But
the humor, based on the rich guy's mistaken belief that the tail he
puts on her, Matthew Perry's architect, is gay, never rises above
lame sitcom. (PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
