<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPIRITED COLLINS SHOULD BE PROUD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was left to New Hampshire's Senator Bob Smith to
get to the nub of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's beat President Clinton just one time on something,'' the
newly independent former Republican thundered on his favorite
cause, eliminating abortion rights. ``I'm sick of losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Better keep the Bromo handy, Bob.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest struggle in the abortion wars, a more mature
legislator in a struggle that was much different from previous ones
was Senator Susan Collins. During the annual fight over what has
been politically labeled ``partial-birth abortion,'' Maine's
freshman Republican was somewhat dispirited. A classic swing vote,
Collins felt lousy about seeing a ban on unlimited political cash
from special interests blocked by another filibuster earlier in the
week. And she was on the short end of a 61-38 vote on an attempt to
find common ground behind prochoice and antiabortion senators.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, she should have been greatly encouraged. Collins is a
major part of a fresh effort in the Senate that has good prospects
and three prongs. The first involves common ground initiatives; the
second is exposing both the absurdity and literal deception in the
partial-birth abortion banners' position; and the third is a fresh
assertiveness on the part of prochoicers, based on the reality of
the threat to abortion rights as set forth in Roe v. Wade. Taken in
order:
</P>
<P>
   Collins was a cosponsor last week of a proposal that would have
prohibited abortions after viability of the fetus outside the
mother's body has been established. Designed to track Roe's
guidelines, exceptions would involve saving the life of the woman
and protecting her health from ``grievous physical harm,'' defined
narrowly, and two doctors (one non-attending) would have to certify
each case. The two-doctor rule was added, to attract more support
to an earlier proposal that never got traction last year.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't ideal, and might not pass court review because of the
absence of protection for mental health, but the proposal made
senators think, as reflected in the votes of Northeasterners. Some
prochoicers voted to kill the proposal by Democrat Dick Durbin of
Illinois with the 61-38 majority: Republicans John Chaffee of Rhode
Island and Jim Jeffords of Vermont, and Democrats Jack Reed of
Rhode Island and Chuck Schumer of New York. But more supported it:
Edward Kennedy and John Kerry of Massachusetts, Collins and Maine
Republican Olympia Snowe, and Democrats Patrick Leahy of Vermont,
Christopher Dodd and Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, and Patrick
Moynihan of New York.
</P>
<P>
   But more revealing were the killing votes of New Hampshire's
antichoice twins, Smith and Judd Gregg. They opposed a proposal
that would eliminate elective abortions after viability was
determined even as they voted to support one that would not, in
prolife language, save a single baby.
</P>
<P>
   Their floor leader, Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania, said his
proposal would ban only one abortion procedure and would not
prevent so much as one late-term abortion. Regardless of the
procedure, the fetus would be just as dead.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum also said prolifers would only support exceptions for
the life of the mother, leaving out those forced to deliver fetuses
(including those that might be lacking a brain or could survive for
no more than minutes) even if delivery destroys a woman's ability
to have future kids.
</P>
<P>
   And that, as Collins told me, ``raises serious questions about
the real intentions of the supporters'' of the ban.
</P>
<P>
   The real purpose is to directly undermine Roe in the guise of
legislating procedures for aborting fetuses. The actual language of
bills like Santorum's and 29 others proves it.
</P>
<P>
   The targeted procedure is described vaguely enough that experts
regularly testify that it could be read to ban other procedures. It
makes no distinctions among pregnancy trimesters. And it has no
exceptions to protect the physical or mental health of a pregnant
woman. That's why out of 30 state statutes like Santorum's, 18 of
21 legal challenges have produced quick injunctions against
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows these laws are unconstitutional on their
face,'' said Collins. But the threat to choice is real, and it's
time the threat produced political action as it did a decade ago.
That's why Tom Harkin, Democrat of Iowa, offered a nonbinding
resolution calling the Roe decision correct and worth sustaining.
It passed, but only by a 51-48 test vote with one opponent (John
McCain) absent. And the Santorum measure gained one vote from 1997,
though it is three short of the 67 required to override a certain
Clinton veto.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin's purpose, quickly backed by Vice President Al Gore, was
to show that abortion rights hang by a thread in the current
Congress. It should be a wakeup call for prochoicers in both
parties. People like Collins have helped unmask the opposition.
They need to press on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
