<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7846 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-PRINCESS-BOS &LR;      10-25 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PRINCESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS ARE ANIMATED FOR `PRINCESS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ When Jennifer Chang became the librarian for
MIT's Anime Club, she inherited half of the 500 tapes of Japanese
animation, or anime as it's called, that the club has accumulated
in its 10 years of existence.
</P>
<P>
   Every other Friday the 19-year-old MIT sophomore grabs a few
videotapes from her tiny dorm room, which doubles as the club
library, and heads across campus to Room 335 in Building E-51.
There she shares the technicolor booty, screening a mixture of
television series, straight-to-video releases, and feature films
for about 150 people who crowd into the room.
</P>
<P>
   The consistently large turnouts are a testament to the avid
underground following the art form has gained over the years,
thanks to the Japanese creators' groundbreaking design, complex
characters, and involving story lines that surpass any animation
produced by US studios. With such an avid and constant exposure to
Japanese animation, it's no wonder many club members are greeting
the release of the feature-length animated film, ``Princess
Mononoke,'' with enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   The dazzling anime eco-fable set in 16th-century Japan is
directed by Hayao Miyazaki, the man some people call the Walt
Disney of Japan. Like Disney, Miyazaki created a successful
animation studio that produced characters like Totoro, a cuddly
cross between an owl and cat, and Kiki, the teenage witch star of
Miyazaki's ``Kiki's Delivery Service.'' They are as instantly
recognizable in Japan as Mickey Mouse is here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Princess Mononoke'' became so successful after its 1997
release in Japan that it flew past ``E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial''
in ticket sales to become one of the highest-grossing films in that
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us have already seen it. And a lot of (other) people
want to see it, but haven't been able to find it,'' says Jeremy
Bowman, 25, in a blase, can't-we-get-on-to-a-more-interesting-topic
tone. He saw the film when he was working in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Some club members watched English-subtitled versions of
``Princess Mononoke'' straight from Japan. Others caught a
September preview of the English-dubbed version at the Brattle
Theatre in Cambridge. Demand was so high for the two screenings
that tickets sold out in half an hour, says Marianne Lampke,
co-director of Beacon Cinema Group, which programs and books Boston
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nine members of MIT's Anime Club who recently gathered at
the student center to discuss their interest in the art form admit
that Japanese animation is not well known outside their club
circuit, except for the pint-sized cartoon fans who are hooked on
imports like ``Pokemon'' and ``Sailor Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I mention the movie to someone they say, `What?'''
says Arcel Frazier, 27, causing everyone to giggle in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax Films, which is releasing the PG-13 rated ``Princess
Mononoke'' in the United States, is putting a lot of marketing
muscle behind its effort to entice older potential fans to see the
movie. The studio has published a lush coffee-table book,
``Princess Mononoke: The Art and Making of Japan's Most Popular
Film of All Time.'' It hired hip Hollywood actors including Claire
Danes, Minnie Driver, Billy Bob Thornton, and Gillian Anderson to
provide the voices. And the studio put ``Princess Mononoke'' on the
film-festival rounds, where it garnered raves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I would want anyone to think is that this is
your typical Walt Disney animated movie,'' says Dennis Rice,
Miramax's marketing president. ``It's really a movie that should be
enjoyed by anybody from the ages of 13 to 90.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston has a fervid anime fan base. A recent Boston series
featuring the work of Miyazaki and other directors of Studio Ghibli
_ think of it as a Walt Disney Studios for teenagers and adults _
played to packed screenings, says Lampke. Harvard University,
Boston University, and Brandeis University boast anime clubs,
although MIT has the oldest. Club members wander from Anime Crash
to Million Year Picnic to Tower Records searching for unique work
to add to their collections.
</P>
<P>
   It's the animation's beauty that makes such die-hard fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It basically takes the format of television or a movie and
adds on a layer of creativity,'' says Carl Stern, 23, a former
president of the MIT anime club.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Ann Oyama, 20, a junior and club president, ``You can draw
anything. You're only limited by your imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being gorgeous, anime also has such involved
storylines that the work almost becomes addictive. Jason Switzer
got hooked on it as a child after tuning into the ``Robotech,'' an
epic sci-fi war series, in the early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found I couldn't just watch one episode and pick up the
story,'' says Switzer, 24. ``I had to actually watch all of them in
sequence.''
</P>
<P>
   Although fans range from tiny tots to adults in their 30s, most
of the anime shown on American television is targeted to
youngsters. That's made it hard for older fans to find dark,
envelope-pushing work like ``Princess Mononoke.''
</P>
<P>
   The film tells the tale of a girl raised by wolves who joins a
group of forest gods in a battle against human invaders. Viewers
get an eyeful of decapitations and severed limbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional problem with a lot of the Japanese animation
is a lot of it doesn't make it past censors in the US,'' says
Bowman. ``It's not designed for children.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese stories don't follow American-style morals in which
good characters survive and bad characters get their comeuppance.
In the original ``Sailor Moon'' series shown in Japan, all the main
characters die, says Bowman, but, thanks to some judicious cutting,
its young American audience didn't see that bloody end. Some MIT
club members feared ``Princess Mononoke'' would suffer the same
sunny end as ``Sailor Moon'' once Miramax got its hands on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard about Disney (Miramax's parent company)
getting `Mononoke,' I said, `Well, they're going to hack it to
bits,' '' says Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Princess Mononoke'' escaped that fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movie embodies (Miyazaki's) vision,'' says Miramax's
Rice. ``There's absolutely no reason why we would want to change
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Miramax hired screenwriter Neil Gaiman, who made the
film more accessible to contemporary American audiences, and hired
the talented actors to make Gaiman's words come alive.
</P>
<P>
   The casting was particularly welcomed by anime watchers.
Although English-dubbed versions of anime exist, the result is
often like watching a Fellini movie vocally acted by the cast of
``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice talent that they get simply don't know how to act
with emotion,'' Jeff Linholm, 27. ``It's just flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Anime fans hope that if ``Princess Mononoke'' is successful,
other studios will invest money to dub adult-themed anime that a
company like Disney might shy away from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' says Linholm with relish, ``you could open the door to
some of the really good stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1542EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7847 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-CONSUMERISM-LADN     10-25 1684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CONSUMERISM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES PUT MATERIALISM IN FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: note call for italics below. Also includes sidebar,
FILM-CONSUMERISM-SIDE) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In ``American Beauty,'' Kevin Spacey's
dissatisfied suburban husband Lester Burnham excoriates his
ambitious wife, Carolyn (Annette Bening), for her materialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't life,'' Lester screams at Carolyn after she has cut
short an amorous moment because she was afraid he would spill beer
on their expensive Italian sofa. ``This is just (BEGIN
ITAL)stuff(END ITAL).''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. It isn't life; it's a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in what can only be described as ironic, Hollywood this
fall is telling us through a number of highly regarded movies that
(BEGIN ITAL)stuff(END ITAL) doesn't necessarily bring happiness.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the American movie industry has been the world's
acknowledged leader in commodifying creativity for much of this
century, reducing art to a mass-marketable product. At the same
time, the Hollywood entertainment community itself has been
identified with consumption at its most conspicuous, setting the
pace for the rest of the culture when it came to buying luxury
cars, swimming pools, cellular phones and thousands of other status
toys.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at the end of the millennium (not to mention the end of the
acquisitive '90s), a diverse flock of major studio releases is
questioning the value of materialism more passionately than at any
time since the late 1960s. And ``The Graduate,'' after all, did
little more than snidely sniff at the concept of ``plastics.'' The
new movies launch full-frontal assaults on anything made of plastic
and a whole lot more. But this being Hollywood, there are strings
attached.
</P>
<P>
   The most overt example of the trend is the graphically violent
satire ``Fight Club.'' Co-star Edward Norton claims the film is
about ``reaching the stage in life when you recognize that you're
not going to achieve spiritual peace through your home
furnishings.'' At one point, the camera pans through Norton's
character's apartment adding descriptions and prices of his
furniture like it's an IKEA catalog. ``We used to read
pornography,'' laments Norton's character. ``Now, it's the Horchow
Collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet you'll also spot such brand names as Starbucks coffee,
Krispy Kreme donuts and Apple computers throughout the film because
those companies contracted with the studio behind ``Fight Club,''
Twentieth Century Fox, for product placement.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' explores the spiritual emptiness of
tastefully appointed, color-coordinated suburban living. But even
Spacey's Lester's rebellion against this empty world involves
acquiring stuff: a cherry red 1970 Firebird, a fancy
battery-operated toy car, etc. You could even argue that the
teen-age cheerleader Lester lusts after is another aquisition he
hopes to make.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Three Kings,'' clueless American soldiers who've just
fought to save Persian Gulf oil for democracy engage in detailed
debates about the merits of competing luxury cars and discuss the
superior tensile strength of Louis Vuitton luggage. On a literal
treasure hunt, they discover vast caches of looted luxury goods in
Iraqi bunkers. Then they discover that such merchandise means very
little when the real things of life are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   A similar realization befalls the pampered young wife Ashley
Judd plays in the hit revenge comedy ``Double Jeopardy.'' She
begins the movie all Armani-clad, on the redwood deck of her
fabulous Puget Sound home, watching the birthday present from her
financier husband sail up to the dock. After she's falsely
imprisoned for murdering said spouse, the woman loses all interest
in possessions, devoting all her energy to vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in nearby ``Mumford,'' a young computer billionaire
can't buy true companionship and an investor's neglected wife fills
her home with mail-order items that she never removes from their
original packaging.
</P>
<P>
   That Hollywood should finally discover what every generation in
human history has come to realize is amusing. That it seems so
heartfelt, coming from such an overpaid and overindulged lot, is
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that such a swarm of movies is addressing
long-unexamined attitudes indicates that serious consideration is
indeed going on. Obviously, with the end of the century looming,
people are in a self-assessing mood. Moreover, there are good
historical reasons why several different generations of Americans
should be questioning mindless materialism at this point in their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The three most severely critical films _ ``Beauty,'' ``Fight''
and ``Kings'' _ come from relatively young directors in the early
stage of their careers: Sam Mendes, David Fincher and David O.
Russell, respectively. They're also artists who don't make films
according to the commercial, escapist formulas that the industry is
geared for marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a group of young filmmakers who are reflecting society
to us, directors willing to take chances in showing us the life we
lead and the world in which we live, as opposed to more escapist
fare,'' observes Paul Junger Witt, one of ``Kings' '' producers.
``With few exceptions, films of the last few years have been
over-bloated, effects-driven pieces that taught us very little
about ourselves, if anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is, hopefully, a reversal of that, to films that are more
content- and story-driven,' Witt continues, then adds in regard to
``Three Kings,'' ``I think there's a great deal of irony and humor,
for example, in the excess that's found in these bunkers in these
small, poor Iraqi villages.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the young recruits played by Ice Cube, Mark Wahlberg and
Spike Jonze in ``Kings'' would be just about the age of the
alienated corporate dweeb Norton plays in ``Fight Club.'' According
to the actor, his contemporaries have been uniquely indoctrinated
into a ``buy-and-be-happy'' frame of mind, and are now at the age
when accumulated life experience makes that credo harder and harder
to, well, buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a broad generational crisis, having been the first
generation really raised from the cradle on television and having
had our value system to a great degree _ to a disturbing degree _
informed by an advertising culture that says, `These are the
signifiers of your life that will make you happy,' '' Norton
reckons. ``You reach a point, growing up, where you realize you
have a lot of things but you're still not happy. Then you have to
come to grips with the emptiness of that promise that can't be
fulfilled, and free yourself from the cocoon of this idea that
you're going to be defined by your possessions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' deals with characters who are both older and
younger than those in ``Fight Club.'' Fortysomethings seek the
youthful joy materialism and the soul-killing work that supports it
have squelched (tellingly, both ``Beauty'' and ``Fight Club'' have
major scenes in which jobs are shoved _ but lavish severance
packages are pragmatically procured). The film's teen-agers hunger
for the meaning they see missing in their parents' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has an idea about what the American dream is,''
notes Spacey. ``This film deals with a lot of those ideals and
images, either the seeking of money and success and comfort or, in
my character's case, the decision to break away from all of that
stuff and not give a s--- about it anymore. Maybe the point is
that, for all that search for things outside of ourselves, at the
end of the day the things that are important are really much closer
_ sometimes, they're actually inside of you.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of inner peace and realization is, sometimes, a
bumpy and rocky road for a lot of people to take. But, ultimately,
it's not about status and it's not about how much you can buy. It's
about things that are much simpler.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Kasdan and Bruce Beresford, the directors of
``Mumford'' and ``Double Jeopardy,'' are from a still older
generation _ one that remembers both the mass rejection of
capitalist materialism in the 1960s and how its youthful rebels
came crawling back as yuppie scum a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   Kasdan, in fact, made the definitive movie on the subject, ``The
Big Chill,'' in 1983. It was a hit at the time, and one of the few
released by a Hollywood studio for the next 15-odd years that would
be built around human stories and filmmakers' personal visions.
Movies themselves became such marketing-driven products in the '80s
and '90s that guys like Kasdan and Beresford felt like strangers in
their own artform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movies of the '70s wanted to tackle the most complicated
ideas they could figure out, but the '90s thing was the simpler the
better, let's not challenge the audience,'' Kasdan observes. ``It
became a merchandizing situation: How do you maximize the number of
people who will go to the office the next day and say, `Oh, I had
the best time at that movie.' ''
</P>
<P>
   While ``Mumford'' bombed and ``Jeopardy,'' the most
conventionally entertaining of the movies mentioned, is the biggest
popular hit, both ``Beauty'' and ``Kings'' have enjoyed respectable
audience response. ``Fight Club,'' which topped the box-office last
week, is already a cultural success, having been the subject of
much debate in the media before the first ticket was sold.
</P>
<P>
   But does any of this mean that studios are going to continue
bashing the very consumer culture that they thrive on? Maybe, but
don't be surprised if something else that Hollywood has always
excelled at producing _ hypocrisy _ is part of the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as Norton jokes, some things about this
art-and-commerce business (and, probably, human nature) are never
going to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a major spring cleaning,'' the actor says when asked if
``Fight Club'' inspired him to reject his own stuff. ``I got rid of
ALL of last season's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But don't ask Brad to give up his GMC Yukon.'' &QL; 
___
</P>
<P>
   Daily News Staff Writer Marla Matzer contributed to this story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
