<SLUG> BC-FILM-CONSUMERISM-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD COZIES UP TO COMMERCIALISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: note call for italics below) 
By MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Studios that are part of multibillion-dollar
marketing conglomerates putting out movies that essentially say
``commercialism is bad''? Please.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these facts:
</P>
<P>
   _ Talent agency powerhouse Creative Artists Agency recently
bought an approximately 50 percent stake in an ad firm, saying they
would integrate popular culture into marketing and branding
strategies for corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   _ William Morris is marrying such corporate clients as Tommy
Hilfiger with such film companies as Miramax, who agree to shill
their goods in teen-targeted pictures.
</P>
<P>
   _ Twentieth Century Fox, the studio behind ``Fight Club,''
started looking for product placement well over a year ago
(certainly, the controversial movie wasn't many image-conscious
advertisers' cup of tea), and the film's director, David Fincher,
comes from a background of making commercials and music videos _
the latter, of course, advertisements for recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have movies that cost so much, you have to look for
product placement,'' says Emanuelle Boarde, head of marketing for
``Fight Club'' production company New Regency. (``Fight Club''
reportedly cost $65 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Look quickly near the film's very end for some subtle placement
for Puma, maker of tennis shoes and athletic gear. That's no
accident: New Regency holds a 32 percent stake in Puma. ``We're not
going to force Puma into movies where it doesn't fit,'' Boarde
says, ``but they place Puma product as much as they can. Of course,
a lot of it ends up on the cutting-room floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the press's often snide attitude toward product
placement, most moviegoers don't seem to mind it as long as it
doesn't seem inappropriate and forced. The truth is, movies look
contrived if they (BEGIN ITAL)don't(END ITAL) feature real
products, since we all use them and see them and want them in real
life. And if companies will contribute toward a budget that brings
us all more lavish movies ... where's the harm?
</P>
<P>
   So if Hollywood is actually more closely linked to the
commercial business than ever, why the on-screen backlash?
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kronovet, co-founder of Santa Monica commercial production
firm Gun for Hire, has some theories about why film directors may
have a love-hate relationship with commercials, even as more and
more directors are crossing back and forth between both media. His
firm employs many directors with extensive film and television
credits to direct commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are good reasons people want to direct commercials: A TV
commercial is probably the most expensive production there is, with
300 to 400 grand being spent for 30 seconds of film ... Plus, it's
more time than they usually get to concentrate on particular
scenes,'' Kronovet says.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, says Kronovet, ``Commercials are a very
collaborative process. You're constantly being watched and
second-guessed as a director. This kind of committee-oriented
production has never been easy for creative people.'' Still, that
hasn't stopped hip directors, from Spike Lee to Kevin Smith, from
making forays into the 30-second ad.
</P>
<P>
   Could directors like Fincher be taking slick revenge on the
business that nurtured them? Possibly. But we have to realize that
it's all really a joke. Art and commerce reside no more closely
anywhere on Earth than in the movie business. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
