<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FALLING FROM THE SKY: Order to ground copter arrived two weeks
after fatal crash
 &HT;    
 &HT;    This is part of a six-day series from the Dayton Daily News on
the safety of military aircraft, the result of an 18-month
investigation and study of databases of incidents from the
military's safety centers. The series is available for use starting
Sunday, Oct. 24, through Friday, Oct. 29.
 &HT;    Photos and graphics are moving from the New York Times News
Service.
 &HT;    Stories are moving on this schedule:
 &HT;    Moved Friday for Sunday, Oct. 24: CRASH-MAIN, CRASH-SC,
CRASH-HOW.
 &HT;    Moved Friday for Monday, Oct. 25: CRASH-METAL.
 &HT;    Moving Monday for Tuesday, Oct. 26: CRASH-MAINTENANCE,
CRASH-TIMMER.
 &HT;    Moving Tuesday for Wednesday, Oct. 27: CRASH-COUNT,
CRASH-BUTTON.
 &HT;    Moving Wednesday for Thursday, Oct. 28: CRASH-CONTRACTORS.
 &HT;    Moving Thursday for Friday, Oct. 29: CRASH-KNIGHTS,
CRASH-MCNALLY.
 &HT;    Starred files will move in long and short versions.
 &HT;    The first day's installment is also available as a CoxNet Focus
page at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
 &HT;    If you have questions, please contact CoxNet at 404-526-5456.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Russell Carollo
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Chief Warrant Officer Paul S. Timmer of Hamilton,
Ohio, flew to his death in a helicopter that should never have left
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 25, 1991, Timmer was piloting a UH-1 helicopter carrying
four other people and cargo over El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve days before that crash, an oil sample was taken from a
gearbox on the helicopter and sent to a lab. The lab labeled the
sample with a ``T,'' an Army maintenance code indicating
contamination serious enough to ground the helicopter until the
problem was fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after takeoff, the main rotor began to turn so slowly
that soldiers from another helicopter could count the blades as
they moved. Timmer tried to make an emergency landing on flat land,
but instead the helicopter crashed into a lake.
</P>
<P>
   Timmer and the four others were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen days after the fatal crash, a report alerting mechanics
to ground the helicopter because of the oil contamination problems
was made available to Timmer's unit. Although the crash apparently
was not directly linked to the contaminated oil, the lab report
would have kept the helicopter on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Army spokesman Mark J. Jeude called the delay an ``unacceptable
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have looked at timeliness in our sample results,'' Jeude
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, five people are dead because somebody didn't
do a report,'' said Steve Timmer, a retired Hamilton police officer
and father of the dead pilot. ``It took them five weeks to get them
out of the lake and get him back to me. I couldn't open the
casket.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Carollo writes for the Dayton Daily News in Dayton,
Ohio. The complete text of this series is available at
www.daytondailynews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
