<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AFRICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MEMORABLE JOURNEY WITH `WONDERS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every time you wake up, he seems to have produced something new
between hard covers or for the pages of a magazine, notably The New
Yorker. So prolific is Henry Louis Gates Jr. _ cultural reporter,
literary scholar and critic, memoirist, encylopedist _ that you
can't help wondering if the man is many-times cloned or, at least,
grievously hobbled by overwork. For merely one example of his
recent output, the Harvard professor and director of the
university's W.E.B. Du Bois Institute for Afro-American Research
coedited the soon-to-be-published and formidably thick ``Africana:
The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience.''
</P>
<P>
   If he's not a multiple of himself or an imminent burn-out case,
one can only imagine he's a finger-wagging pedant and probably
overbearingly Type A to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Well, wrong again, judging by Gates's most ambitious foray yet
into documentary television, ``Wonders of the African World,''
which debuts Monday night. The three-night, six-hour BBC production
is an unconventional and utterly refreshing look at the continent
through the lens of a curious, informed African-American determined
to celebrate his hyphenated roots without trimming troubling
historical truths.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he revives long-neglected history, including the
reign of the black pharaohs in ancient Nubia, now the Sudan, where
impressive but rarely visited pyramids house 40 generations of
once-powerful kings and queens. That's Monday night, in program
one. In the fourth hour, Tuesday, Gates nimbly explores the vibrant
Christian tradition in Ethiopia, ``the only African nation,'' he
reminds us, ``never to be colonized.'' The episode is treated as
something of a mystery tour, a pursuit of the lost Ark of the
Covenant. The original 10 Commandments, etched into stone tablets,
are presumably in the ancient city of Axum, guarded by a rarely
seen monk.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, who wrote and voiced the film's narration, is also
on-camera much of the time, usually wearing a Harvard T-shirt,
making casual observations, acting as historical guide and
facilitator, meeting and greeting contemporary royals, schmoozing
with random townsfolk, and so on. If his little caravan breaks down
on one or another dusty road, the camera peers into the passenger
window of the stalled vehicle and there he sits, congenially
chatting to you _ being, one supposes, himself.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly, Gates's presence never grates _ at least based on
the four hours of ``Wonders'' that I saw. On the contrary, his
easygoing candor and sweet spontaneity set this documentary apart
from others as much as its enlightening contents do.
</P>
<P>
   By engaging history directly and personally, he makes it live in
all of its ambiguous glory and timeless sadness. In Kenya, Gates
draws proud attention to the remarkable accomplishments of the
Swahili, great city-builders, it turns out, in the late 14th
century. But he also confronts their later exploits when,
intermingled with Arabs, they profited handsomely by exporting
spices and slaves.
</P>
<P>
   In an Anglican church in Zanzibar built over the old slave
market, Gates says, ``This place gives me the creeps.'' Behind the
throw-away lightness is deep, unconcealed grief.
</P>
<P>
   And as vocally proud as he is of old African cultures, he never
tires of exposing the prejudices he sees among some African blacks.
</P>
<P>
   In a dialogue with some dark-skinned Zanzibari villagers who
proclaim their Persian ancestry, he says, ``You look African. To
me, the people here look about as Persian as Mike Tyson.''
</P>
<P>
   Episode three, which examines the old West African slave
kingdoms of Dahomey and Asante, where slavery existed even before
Europeans arrived, is crosshatched with pain.
</P>
<P>
   In the city of Ouidah, in modern Benin, we meet African
descendants of the port's wealthiest slave trader who remain
status-conscious aristocrats to this day. Often ironical in his
reflections, here Gates pauses to offer an unadulterated lament:
``I've often thought that Africa has suffered so much, in part
because of its own curse of selling its own people away.''
</P>
<P>
   History is never objective. It is because we experience
``Wonders of the African World'' through Gates's clearly stated
sensibility and emotion, as well as his roaming intelligence, that
it's so engaging and memorable.
</P>
<P>
   There is something keenly, openly American about him, even
including at times an endearing awkwardness, that continually
personalizes this epic and makes it all seem to matter.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps needless to add _ couldn't you have guessed? _ Gates
has written a companion book to the television series, also called
``Wonders of the African World.''
</P>
<P>
   WONDERS OF THE AFRICAN WORLD WITH HENRY LOUIS GATES, JR. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Produced by: Ben Goold and Jonathan Hewes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Nick Godwin, Nicola Colton, Helen Appio &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
