<HEADER>
A7862 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBA-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-25 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME IS RUNNING OUT FOR THE `TEAM OF THE DECADE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Well, if the team of the decade thing doesn't work out
for them, maybe the Atlanta Braves can try not to be confused with
the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that may be a bit harsh. After all, the Braves
themselves know how surmountable a 2-0 World Series lead can be,
having been surmounted themselves in just such a fashion three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's 7-2 loss to David Cone and the New York Yankees as
the forgettable second act to the Team of the Century pageantry
marked the first time since the Braves started dominating the
National League that they looked unworthy of their place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a team of good pitching and timely hitting,'' Atlanta
manager Bobby Cox said, thoroughly befuddled. ``Tonight we didn't
get enough men on base to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox sounding helpless is odd to the ear. The Braves entered this
Team-Of-The-90s spat with the game's best record, the longest
running success story, and only a World Series victory away from
getting what many people believe is their due.
</P>
<P>
   But barring a meaningless ninth-inning rally Sunday, the Braves
have been extraordinarily compliant _ as overwhelmed in their way
as the Padres were when the Yankees swept them last October.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the whelming came at the hand of Cone, which in itself
is a bit strange, given that he has had a circulatory problem that
affects his throwing hand. He had been rested copiously, and
pitched as many day games as the Yankees could arrange.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on another brisk evening at Turner Field, he made liars of
the Braves for seven innings. His worst throw of the night was to
first base (well, right field) on Ozzie Guillen's grounder to the
right of the mound in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else he served up was at least partially reminiscent
of his perfect game earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt strong, really strong,'' Cone said, even admitting that
he himself was impressed by his performance. ``It was just a matter
of not giving in to them, not letting their big hitters get
anything to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, though, haven't had any big hitters for a while now.
``We didn't hit the ball tonight,'' Cox said, ``we didn't hit it
last night (getting two-hit by Orlando Hernandez and three
relievers in a 4-1 loss), and we didn't really tear up the ball
against the Mets, either, so ...''
</P>
<P>
   So what? Well, for starters, what's the surprise there? It's the
World Series, remember? The Braves treat the World Series as a
Wiffle Ball tournament. Cox, fed up by the extended teamwide slump,
changed three men in his lineup Sunday. The result was that catcher
Greg Myers got the Braves' first hit rather than Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the lineup watched Cone as they watched Orlando
Hernandez the night before, like seventh-graders confronted by
their first trigonometry pop quiz.
</P>
<P>
   But they also didn't pitch for one of the few times in their
postseason history. Right-hander Kevin Millwood, filling in for
Greg Maddux who had filled in for the gastrically distressed Tom
Glavine, provided the backbeat for a conga line of Yankee
baserunners _ six of the first seven he faced, and 10 of 15
overall. By the time he was removed in the third inning, the
Yankees led 3-0, although it may as well have been 33-0 for all the
good it would do the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much sucked,'' Millwood said in a particularly sharp
bit of self-analysis. ``That's about it. It was a really bad game
for me. I could have faced any major league team today and the same
thing would have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And they surely didn't field. Guillen, another of Cox's fresh
insertions into the dormant Atlanta lineup, mangled two plays by
himself, one a dropped popup from Cone that most Frisbee-catching
dogs handle in their sleep.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Braves lost their usually loyal crowd, and began
to take on that look of the squirrel in your front yard _ the look
the Padres showed the baseball-speaking world last year after Game
Two.
</P>
<P>
   They cheered lustily when Guillen successfully surrounded
another Cone popup in the fifth, but mostly grumbled to themselves
during the Braves' lightning-fast at-bats. The city had been
roasted by medioids who felt their devotion to their team was soft
and doughy, but mostly they had been led to believe this Series was
going to be even more tense than that series with the Mets. They
hadn't planned on this.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, they didn't see the ugly turn the evening took even
before the game began, just on the basis of Pete Rose's pregame
interview on NBC. He had just received a long and spirited ovation
from the crowd at Turner Field for the not-entirely deserved honor
of being voted one of the best outfielders of the 20th century when
he was then confronted by the network's designated yappy dog, Jim
Gray. The interview quickly degenerated into a quick volley of that
popular board game, ``Admit It! You're Guilty! _ Like Hell I Will,
You Little Twerp!''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange was so mutually petulant that viewers across the
nation had not only nearly forgotten that most of the ceremony was
an impressive tribute to the other honorees, who had richly earned
their props, but were momentarily torn between whether they would
rather hit Rose or Gray in the face with a snow shovel.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, however, saw only the good vibes from the pregame
show, so much so that they forgot their principal duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ceremony was great, because the fans forgot to get on
me,'' Cone said. ``I expected to get some heckling while I was
warming up, but it was quiet. Everyone was watching that, and it
was great.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson: If the Team of the Century is helping the Yankees,
what chance do the Braves and their hitting-optional attack have?
Right now, it seems like not much of one at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
