<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-MCBEAL-BOS &LR;      10-25 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MCBEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S A NICE GIRL LIKE ALLY ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David E. Kelley, producer and writer, has a provocation
fixation. He is addicted to pushing buttons, and you can't get very
far into any of his shows _ ``The Practice,'' ``Snoops,'' ``Ally
McBeal'' _ without coming face to face with a handful of gender
slights, at least one social taboo, some sexy language, and, of
course, plenty of leg. Was that defendant on last week's ``The
Practice'' actually exhibiting his genitals to the jury? You
betcha. Despite his neighborhood-boy looks, Mr. Kelley is a
high-powered controversy monger, and he is not as different from
Howard Stern as you (and he) might think.
</P>
<P>
   His showiest show, ``Ally McBeal,'' returns Monday night for its
third season, and the first two episodes are Kelley at his most
incendiary. The fireworks include Ally having anonymous sex in a
car wash; a priest walking in on a cheating bride; Renee and
Whipper forcing men to remove their shirts during job interviews;
and Fish lines like ``I'd like you to walk a mile in her
diaphragm.'' Next week's roster of outrageousness includes Ally and
Ling making out on a romantic date; a cleavage-heavy woman getting
sued for harassment by female co-workers; Elaine providing the
Biscuit with sexual stimulation; and Nelle confessing that she
wants to be spanked in bed. It's all a great big fantasia of sexual
hot spots, wrapped up in some of the glossiest visuals and
narrative devices that you'll find on TV. Men as sex objects, women
as sex objects, men's double standards, women's double standards,
bisexuality, erotic fantasy vs. reality _ hey, let's party!
</P>
<P>
   And that's what ``Ally McBeal'' has become: a racy party, with a
cast of kooky characters, wild plot twists, timely legal cases, and
kicky hairstyles that seem to have a life of their own. Kelley
doesn't resort to Butt Bongo Fiesta _ that would be Howard Stern's
game _ but it's not hard to imagine him taking inspiration for next
week's spanking and lesbian plots from any number of Stern
segments. In the past, it has been fun trying to figure out what
Kelley is saying with all of this, and debating whether the show
portrays real women or only a male fantasy of them, and bringing a
Freudian interpretation to the foam on Fish's latte. But as ``Ally
McBeal'' becomes overcrowded with in-your-face sex and gender
issues, it actually gets less interesting and less provocative.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``Ally McBeal'' more than titillation is its entirely
original set of characters and their ensemble chemistry, which
culminates in the signature bar sequences. These are some of the
most imaginative creations on TV, and it's hard not to enjoy their
uniqueness, from Ling's massive hat in Monday night's over-the-top
wedding scene to Ally's ``dyke'' outfit next week. And let's not
forget about the Biscuit's whistling nose. The same cast members
are back this season, with no new additions, although it looks like
we'll see more of Lisa Nicoln's Renee and Dyan Cannon's
Whipper, as the two begin a private practice together. It also
looks like Calista Flockhart is developing a new acting style (in
addition to her new full-bodied hairstyle), as she relies less on
her trademark hyperventilating and stammering. Now if she can only
persuade Kelley to slow down his own heavy breathing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
