<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7865 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-25 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL VISITS SERVING BUSH'S CAMPAIGN WELL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush may not have known the
ethnic breakdown of the 525 students at Kimball Elementary School
in this city's Beacon Hill section, but you can bet one or more of
his campaign staffers did.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-three percent of the children are Asian-American, 29
percent are Anglo and most of the remainder are black, a mix that
made Kimball an ideal location for the Republican presidential
candidate's latest photo opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had already visited a heavily Hispanic school in a nearby
city only a couple of hours earlier and been rewarded with a photo
of himself on his hands and knees, shooting marbles with a few of
the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates and their consultants dream of such photos _ the only
thing better is television video _ because they make politicians
seem like real people (almost) and give them an opportunity to
visually portray a chosen message.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has been visiting schools throughout the country since
he launched his national campaign, has more than one message.
</P>
<P>
   The first, according to spokeswoman Karen Hughes, is the
governor's longstanding commitment to improve education, to take
his successes in Texas _ and at least one of his failures (private
school vouchers) _ and expand on them from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major reasons Governor Bush is running for
president is because we want to leave no child behind. We want to
educate every child, and we want to send a clear message that every
child in America can learn,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   A second message is aimed at people who usually don't vote for
Republicans. To appeal to them, since their support could be
crucial in the general election if Bush is the GOP nominee, the
governor is going to places, such as schools with heavy minority
enrollments, that most Republican political candidates don't visit.
</P>
<P>
   Bush courts the country clubs and boardrooms _ the familiar GOP
terrain _ as well. His record fund-raising success is testimony to
that. But those stops are liberally (for most Republicans)
interspaced with visits to places heavily populated with minorities
with whom the governor can be photographed or about whom he can be
quoted.
</P>
<P>
   One of my colleagues suggested that Bush's visits to minority
schools carry still a third message, closely related to the first
but aimed specifically at traditional Republicans. The governor,
according to this theory, wants to assure conservatives that the
education and welfare changes he is championing will go a long way
toward putting more people into jobs and ending government
handouts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's interest in schoolchildren undoubtedly is sincere. He
cares about their futures in addition to caring about what they can
do for his immediate, political future. And the children enjoy his
visits, although many of the younger ones don't really know who he
is or why he sits there, surrounded by all those TV cameras,
reading to them.
</P>
<P>
   The cultivation of photo opportunities has been an essential
ingredient of political campaigns as long as there have been
cameras, and they became more pronounced with the advent of
television.
</P>
<P>
   But the politics of such events are transparent, and Bush's are
no exception. In Seattle, the governor recited lines from a
well-worn script, some of which were obviously aimed at reporters,
not at the fourth-graders picked to meet with the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   When one fourth-grader asked Bush what he would do for education
if he were elected president, Bush said he would transfer more
power over the schools from Washington, D.C., to the states and
cities because he believes in ``local control.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely he didn't expect 9- and 10-year-olds to have the foggiest
idea of what he was talking about, although children of that age
have been treated to that answer in several states now.
</P>
<P>
   A few Democratic parents who were volunteering at the school
that day understood the answer but didn't think much of it. After
Bush had departed, they told reporters that the governor had been
there to ``grandstand,'' not to learn about the funding problems
experienced by many Seattle schools, if, indeed, he had any idea
that there were funding problems.
</P>
<P>
   But a color photo of Bush and two of the Kimball students
dominated the front page of one Seattle newspaper the next morning.
And the governor undoubtedly was featured with the children in TV
news clips as well.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, a school had served the Bush campaign well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
