<HEADLINE>
49ERS DEFENSIVE LINE GETTING NOWHERE SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The defensive line of the San Francisco 49ers
doesn't know what to say anymore. They're tired of the questions
and just as discouraged by their own endless search for answers
</P>
<P>
   Each week, they line up prepared to chase after opposing
quarterbacks. Each week, they're left to wonder why a front four
can be walled off so easily and so often. The team's 40-16 loss to
the Minnesota Vikings on Sunday only added to the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case with several quarterbacks this season,
Minnesota's Jeff George had enough time to find his relatives in
the sold-out Metrodome crowd before unleashing his passes. The
49ers recorded only one sack _ by Bryant Young in the first quarter
_ and even that came so early that it was forgotten in the rest of
the mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' 49ers defensive tackle Junior Bryant said.
``We know we're putting our secondary in a bad position. You can't
give a guy like Jeff George that kind of time to throw the ball.
You can't give any quarterback that much time. We just haven't been
doing our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this season, the 49ers secondary has taken most of
the blame for the team's defensive troubles. The cornerbacks are
small, but easy targets. But, as any coach will tell you,
consistent pressure on a quarterback can do wonders for a defensive
back's ego. Without it, even the most subtle flaws in the defensive
backfield will stand out.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers haven't had anything resembling a pass rush this
season, as their 13 sacks prior to this loss attest. They've had
massive men hurling their bodies into unimpressed guards and
tackles, getting nowhere slowly, dismantling nothing in the other
team's offensive game plan. George threw for 250 yards and three
touchdowns. Rarely did he have to worry about his health.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part for the 49ers to stomach was that of any game,
this was one where they needed their front four to produce.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings' potent passing attack demanded that the 49ers play
more nickel and dime defenses than normal. Therefore, the blitzing
that had helped the pass rush in previous games had to be kept to a
minimum unless the team wanted to expose their defensive backs to
even more trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been better rushing the quarterback when we've brought
linebackers and safeties this season,'' 49ers head coach Steve
Mariucci said. ``We have good pass rushers. We just haven't gotten
to the quarterback enough. We have to be able to get to the passer
with our front four. We just have to get better at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The real question, however, is whether the 49ers really can get
better in this area. After star defensive tackle Bryant Young and
his underrated sidekick, Junior Bryant, there isn't much positive
to say about the line play.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Charles Haley came out of retirement to give the
team an experienced pass rusher but at age 35, he's not likely to
improve as the season wears on. As for the other end, Gabe Wilkins,
he never was known for his pass-rushing ability. That leaves
pass-rush specialist James Posey, a 240- pound end who was nearly
knocked through the Metrodome turf on one passing play.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers realize their pass-rushing troubles won't change
quickly. The trading deadline passed last week without a trade for
Tampa Bay defensive end Regan Upshaw working out. There are no
hidden gems waiting to sign free-agent contracts. What you see is
what you get with this defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   And what the 49ers have gotten so far hasn't been anything close
to what they had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an answer for it,'' Wilkins said. ``You see what
we do. You see that we're trying. But if I could answer those
questions as to why we aren't doing a better job, there wouldn't be
any reason to ask them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
