<HEADER>
A7877 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-25 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: LITTLE-KNOWN KILLER OF THE YOUNG AND THE SEEMINGLY
HEALTHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An apparently healthy, athletic 7-year-old boy named Billy dies
mysteriously in his sleep in his bedroom in Sarasota, Fla., while
his father grinds coffee in the nearby kitchen. An apparently
healthy 19-year-old woman from Minnesota, known to be a good
swimmer, dies after a near-drowning while swimming laps in a pool 4
feet deep. An apparently healthy 30-year-old Florida mother walks
to a fountain for a drink after playing soccer and drops dead.
</P>
<P>
   These three are among as many as 4,000 children and young adults
who died last year of long QT syndrome, a usually unrecognized
inherited defect in the heart's rhythm. Often, the first clue that
something is wrong with the way the heart beats is sudden cardiac
death. The heart muscle suddenly goes into fibrillation, beating so
fast and shallowly that no blood can circulate. Unless the heart is
shocked back into a normal rhythm within a few minutes, there is
little hope for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Long QT syndrome is believed to be a common cause of unexplained
sudden deaths among school athletes, as well as the probable cause
of many unexplained drownings.
</P>
<P>
   Long QT syndrome is caused by a mutation in a gene that
regulates the heart's electrical system. The mutation causes a
defect in heart muscle structures called ion channels that
predisposes the heart to lapse into a very rapid, ineffectual
rhythm called fibrillation.
</P>
<P>
   The syndrome is named for the QT segment of the
electrocardiogram, which lasts slightly longer than normal. It is
usually a hidden defect because few children and young adults have
electrocardiograms. In most cases, the mutation is inherited as an
autosomal dominant, which means the defective gene is located on a
non-sex chromosome and each child of an affected parent has a 50-50
chance of inheriting it.
</P>
<P>
   In patients with the syndrome, the heart takes longer to
recharge itself between beats. Under most circumstances, this
causes no symptoms. However, certain conditions can set off an
abnormal cardiac rhythm, resulting in fainting spells, dizziness,
palpitations, seizures or sudden death. Among the factors known to
start erratic beating of an affected heart are swimming, intense
physical exertion or being suddenly startled or frightened.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the 19-year-old swimmer and 30-year-old soccer
player, intense physical activity was the likely trigger. But Billy
was asleep when he died. His mother, Sharon Levy, suspects that the
noise of the coffee grinder may have set off his fatal cardiac
rhythm. Or perhaps he had been frightened by a bad dream.
</P>
<P>
   Early diagnosis, while a person is still well, can be
life-saving. In about 90 percent of cases, daily doses of the drugs
called beta-blockers can help to maintain a normal heart rhythm.
For others, a pacemaker can be implanted to regulate the heart's
rhythm or an automatic defibrillator can be installed that can
instantly detect and correct an erratic rhythm. The Florida woman's
sisters, for example, who also have long QT syndrome, now have
automatic defibrillators.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. G. Michael Vincent of Salt Lake City, medical director of
the Sudden Arrhythmia Death Syndromes (SADS) Foundation, recommends
that children with long QT syndrome refrain from competitive sports
and that coaches and teachers should never push such a child to
engage in an activity associated with instense physical or
emotional stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   Noncompetitive, recreational activities are usually appropriate
for people with long QT syndrome, Dr. Vincent said, but they should
stop whatever they are doing if they experience palpitations,
lightheadedness, weakness or blurry vision. Stopping the activity
can often prevent progression to more serious symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   A buddy system is advisable during activities so that someone
can be on the lookout for early symptoms. Because swimming or
entering a pool is especially dangerous for people with long QT
syndrome, they should always be accompanied by a knowledgeable
person who can rescue them if necessary. However, Vincent said, any
patient who experiences symptoms of long QT syndrome and is not
receiving treatment should avoid all physical activities and even
strong emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a sophisticated genetic analysis is performed, long QT
syndrome cannot be detected after a person dies. In most cases,
however, by testing other blood relatives it is usually possible to
make a correct determination of the cause of death. Mrs. Levy said
Billy was an adopted child and the pediatric medical examiner who
performed the autopsy suspected long QT syndrome had caused his
death. This prompted Mrs. Levy to search for Billy's birth parents
because in all likelihood one of them carried the same defective
gene. His biological mother tested normal, but his father, age 20,
was found to have long QT syndrome, a diagnosis that may well save
him and any future children he may have from sudden, premature
death.
</P>
<P>
   But diagnosing long QT syndrome can be tricky. In about 10
percent of cases, the QT interval on the initial electrocardiogram
appears normal, and in another 40 percent, the QT interval is not
sufficiently prolonged to permit a clear-cut diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   For example, before the Minnesota woman died, her
electrocardiogram suggested that she had long QT syndrome, which
could have been caused by complications resulting from her
near-drowning. But suspicious physicians at the Mayo Clinic decided
to analyze a piece of her heart muscle removed at autopsy to see if
there was a defect in the gene linked to this syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   They found a mutation, then tested her relatives for the
syndrome. Her maternal grandfather, mother and an 18-year-old
sister were found to have the mutation, and the mother's
electrocardiogram also showed long QT syndrome. But the sister's
electrocardiogram appeared to be normal _ only one of eight
cardiologists judged it abnormal. However, because she carried the
defective gene, she is now receiving daily treatment with a
beta-blocker to reduce her risk of sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   The SADS Foundation emphasizes that any young person who
experiences fainting episodes or seizures should be tested for long
QT syndrome. Anyone who suffers an unexplained loss of
consciousness should have an electrocardiogram done. So should
anyone with a family history of unexplained fainting or sudden
death in young people. Because one-third of people with this
syndrome have no symptoms, it is not safe to assume that a person
without symptoms has not inherited the syndrome. A symptom-free
person with long QT syndrome is no less susceptible to sudden
death.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mayo Clinic physicians, writing in the Oct. 7 issue of
The New England Journal of Medicine, insist that reliance on an
electrocardiogram is not adequate. They pointed out that without
genetic testing, the 18-year-old sister ``would have been
considered normal and would not have been treated.'' ``She also
would not have received genetic counseling,'' the physicians
continued, ``including information about the 50 percent chance of
passing this mutation to future offspring, the risks associated
with swimming and other strenuous exertion and the list of
medications to avoid.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
