<HEADLINE>
A MATTER OF STILLNESS: DENZEL WASHINGTON AND `THE BONE COLLECTOR' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Denzel Washington with Queen Latifah in
a scene from ``The Bone Collector.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Denzel Washington issues a challenge.
 &HT;    Looking at a group of journalists assembled in a suite at New
York's Regency Hotel to hear him talk about his new movie, ``The
Bone Collector,'' the actor lays out the terms.
 &HT;    ``While I'm in the room, try to sit still, without moving at
all,'' he says. ``See if you can do it.''
 &HT;    Washington looks steadily at one nervous writer, who after a few
seconds flinches. A killer smile flashes across the actor's face.
 &HT;    ``Too late!'' he says triumphantly. ``You moved.''
 &HT;    It's just his way of conveying something of the experience of
making ``The Bone Collector,'' a serial-killer thriller which opens
Nov. 5. In it, he plays Lincoln Rhyme, an ex-cop and ace forensics
specialist left a quadriplegic after an accident.
 &HT;    When a rookie officer (Angelina Jolie) stumbles across the
handiwork of a brilliant serial killer, Rhyme rediscovers his
passion for life and the thrill of the chase, relying on her to
serve as his eyes, ears and feet.
 &HT;    Washington's role required him to spend as much as 15 hours a
day, from one to three hours at a time, immobile in a bed.
 &HT;    ``There are a lot more difficult things than that, but it was a
challenge,'' Washington says. ``A part like this is just one I
couldn't turn down.''
 &HT;    Researching the role, Washington met with real-life
quadriplegics _ people able to move neither their legs nor their
arms, as opposed to paraplegics, whose legs alone are immobilized _
to get some sense of their lives. His consultants included fellow
actor Christopher Reeve, paralyzed in a 1995 riding accident.
 &HT;    ``I spent six or seven hours with Chris and, obviously, he was
the most famous person I spent time with,'' Washington says. ``I
met a construction worker who lives on $600 a month disability, and
his sister had to take care of him.
 &HT;    ``I met another guy who was a real-estate attorney with a great
career,'' the actor adds. ``He was the most upbeat, positive guy
you'd ever want to meet. He was the first guy I met.
 &HT;    ``You don't know how to act. I said,'' Washington recalls,
adopting a tentative voice, ```How are you?'
 &HT;    ``He said, `What's the matter with you? Stop moping. Speak
up!'''
 &HT;    Eventually, the actor says, he was able to get past his initial
hesitance and uncertainty.
 &HT;    ``After a while, you go, `OK, this is a human being,''' he says.
``He has a great passion for life, as does Chris. He wants to get
up and walk, and he believes he will.''
 &HT;    Washington reports that the most common frustration in
quadriplegics' everyday existence is the loss of independence.
Someone must help them do everything, from bathing to eating or
going to the bathroom.
 &HT;    ``You never get used to it,'' the actor says, ``but you deal
with it. Most of them, at one point or another, contemplated
suicide. You go through that.''
 &HT;    What he saw moved him immensely, Washington adds _ and made him
appreciate how good he has it.
 &HT;    ``One guy flipped over a bicycle,'' he says. ``One guy tripped
and fell and banged his head. You know Chris' story. It can be a
simple thing _ we're so fragile.
 &HT;    ``But you find a way to live,'' he concludes. ``For the most
part, these guys want to live.''
 &HT;    Sometimes, he adds, his conversations with quadriplegics were
even funny.
 &HT;    ``One talked about paraplegics,'' he says. ``He said, `Oh,
they're fakers, taking all the parking spaces.'
 &HT;    ``So it's all relative.''
 &HT;    Obviously, since his role kept Washington immobile, the casting
of Jolie was a crucial decision in making the movie work. She had
to be credible as a police officer, as Rhyme's student and,
ultimately, as his love interest.
 &HT;    Washington had never heard of Jolie when producer Martin Bregman
and director Phillip Noyce telephone to say ``We've got the girl!''
The actor, who has contractual approval of his co-stars, watched
Jolie's star-making turn in HBO's ``Gia'' and quickly agreed.
 &HT;    ``Thank goodness they got an actress with chops, because I'm
just sitting there,'' Washington says. ``Angelina has a lot going
on. She's fun to watch _ and not bad to look at, either.
 &HT;    ``And the sex is a real big part of all these guys' lives,'' he
adds. ``I thought their sexual lives were over. They're like, `Oh
no, Denzel.'
 &HT;    ``One guy told me, `You learn to give.' And women like that.
You're more creative.''
 &HT;    Viewers shouldn't worry that they're heading into a
movie-of-the-week. ``The Bone Collector'' is a thriller, Washington
emphasizes, and it delivers the goods. The movie isn't about a
quadriplegic, but about a detective who happens to be paralyzed.
 &HT;    ``None of it was to educate people,'' he says. ``There was no
mission statement. This is just the guy's situation.
 &HT;    ``It's not a `how-to-be-a-quadriplegic' film,'' he adds firmly.
``It's a film about a murderer. The last thing anybody needs to see
is me or anybody feeling sorry for them.''
 &HT;    His next film, ``The Hurricane,'' lets Washington make up for
his extended bed rest with a vengeance. Directed by Norman Jewison
_ who steered Washington in his breakthrough film, ``A Soldier's
Story'' (1984) _ it casts him as Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, a
real-life boxer who spent 20 years in prison for a murder he didn't
commit.
 &HT;    The film, which will open on Dec. 29, is being touted as an
Oscar contender that might land Washington a Best Actor statuette
to go beside the Best Supporting Actor award he won for ``Glory''
(1989).
 &HT;    ``It's a good movie,'' Washington says confidently. ``It's a
very, very good movie.
 &HT;    ``Actually, I was training for it while we were filming `Bone
Collector,''' he adds. ``That was great, because at the end of the
day, boy, I wanted to get out of that bed, throw punches and run
around.''
 &HT;    In a way, he says, the roles are similar.
 &HT;    ``One guy was stuck in his body and the other was stuck in his
cell,'' the actor says. ``They're both locked up.''
 &HT;    As turn-of-the-millennium movie stars go, Washington is a bit of
a throwback _ he's more interested in acting challenges than in the
kind of modern, high-concept action flicks that his friend and
colleague, Wesley Snipes, specializes in.
 &HT;    ``I tried that,'' Washington says with a laugh. ``I'm not good
at running and jumping. I did a couple of those films, like
`Ricochet' (1991). It's just not my thing.
 &HT;    ``Wesley loves it,'' he adds with a chuckle. ``He likes to fight
and jump and run, and that's great. He loves beating folks up.
 &HT;    ``I'm a talker. I like to talk.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Bone Collector,'' consult
the official Website at www.thebonecollector.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
