<HEADLINE>
ONE IN A `MILLIONAIRE': REGIS PHILBIN BRINGS PRIME-TIME GAME SHOWS
BACK FROM THE DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Regis Philbin in a scene from ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire.'') 
 By SIMON HOUPT  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be released in Canada until November 2, 1999. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If imitation is the sincerest form of flattery, it's a miracle
Regis Philbin's head still fits on a television screen.
</P>
<P>
   Since Philbin helped take ABC's game show ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' to the top of the ratings during a two-week stretch
in August, it seems every television producer in Hollywood is
racing to get a new or revived game show into prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Classics such as ``What's My Line,'' ``The $64,000 Question''
and even the notorious, scandal-plagued 1950s game ``Twenty-One''
are retooling to get back onto the airwaves. Next summer CBS will
send 16 people to a remote island to compete for $1 million in a
Robinson Crusoe-inspired adventure/game show called ``Survivor.''
And as ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' returns for a two-week
stretch on Nov. 7, it will be shadowed by a new game on Fox _ with
a potential $2 million payoff _ called, appropriately enough,
``Greed.''
</P>
<P>
   The game-show format, as old as television itself, is red hot
again _ and it's all because of ``Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Actor Orson Bean, who was a panelist on a half-dozen shows
through the 1950s, 1960s and 1970s, calls watching ``Millionaire''
this past summer his ``guilty pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it because everybody else in America is watching,''
Bean says. ``It's an event.''
</P>
<P>
   Philbin seconds the motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The television audience today is so fragmented,'' he says.
``You can't sit down together as a family and watch anything
anymore _ there's nothing that everybody is interested in. But with
this show, families are coming together again to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Philbin says he knew the show would be a hit and, even though he
had turned down previous offers to host other game shows, he begged
executive producer Michael Davies for the opportunity to do
``Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had enjoyed game shows over the years, like `What's My
Line?' and `Who Do You Trust,''' Philbin says, ``but they had been
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, my gosh, this one is all dressed up for the next
millennium,'' he says. ``It feels like it takes place in a rocket
ship. It's got lights flashing around, it's got that music, it's
got all the things that a game show today should have _ including a
million dollars, which is still a tremendous sum of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as ``Millionaire'' geared up for its initial
13-episode run last summer, its success was far from a slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the original version of the show had been an enormous
success in Britain in September 1998, but ABC's own research
department found that American viewers had very little interest in
game shows. The producers didn't even have a pilot to help sell
``Millionaire'' to the network.
</P>
<P>
   But in a summer choking on reruns, with ABC consistently placing
third among viewers, the network badly needed something to
jumpstart its ratings. Besides, it had nothing to lose _ desperate
times breed desperate measures.
</P>
<P>
   If you missed ``Millionaire'' the first time around, don't worry
_ the format is deceptively simple. A contestant sits in a
so-called ``Hot Seat'' as Philbin asks a series of multiple-choice
questions.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the questions are laughably easy: ``P.T. Barnum said
there was one of these born every minute. Answer: a) a person, b) a
sucker, c) a loser or d) an Osmond.''
</P>
<P>
   With each right answer the prize money increases, as does the
level of difficulty. But every time you answer a question, you risk
losing the money you have accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   If you need some help, you can turn to three so-called
``Lifelines'': You may phone a friend for help, poll the audience
for their opinion or reduce the four multiple-choice answers down
to two.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters even easier, you get to see the question before
deciding whether to continue playing or quit, with all your
earnings intact. If all goes well, after 14 correct answers you're
facing the $1 million question.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a piece of cake, right? Think again: Only two
contestants have won $500,000, and neither took a shot at the $1
million prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy sitting there in the Hot Seat with all that
money on the line,'' says contestant Doug Van Gundy, who was the
first to win $250,000. ``At one point, I felt like I was going to
pass out _ I was so overwhelmed I just forgot to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy became something of a local celebrity in his native
West Virginia after he greeted his win by thrusting his arms in the
air and weeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people like the idea that some average schmo like me
can walk in off the street, armed only with the everyday detritus
of information you take in, and can turn around and win a big chunk
of money,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, we're so interested in the achievements of the
individual,'' Van Gundy adds. ``The focus here is on one person.
You don't see that in any other game show.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of other game shows, producer Davies doesn't seem too
worried about the upcoming competition from ``Greed'' and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many other sitcoms that came out after `Friends'
that were `Friends'-style,'' he says, ``and most of them didn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Simon Houpt is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' consult the ABC Website at www.abc.go.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
