<SLUG> BC-AL-PACINO-IN-THE-INSIDER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INSIDE' STRAIGHT: AL PACINO ENTERS THE TOBACCO WARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Al Pacino in a scene from ``The
Insider.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Al Pacino had an idea.
 &HT;    At the end of his new film ``The Insider,'' an indictment of the
tobacco industry, he thought there was a chance for one final
touch.
 &HT;    ``So I went up to Michael Mann, our director, and said, `Look,
this might be really great,''' Pacino recalls. ```What if, at the
end, I light up a cigarette?'
 &HT;    ``We actually shot the scene,'' he adds, ``but it got cut. I
guess that took away from the film's true impact.''
 &HT;    And the notoriously intense actor actually chuckles.
 &HT;    Believe it or not, says Russell Crowe, who co-stars in ``The
Insider,'' which will open on Nov. 5, it's not unusual for Pacino
to inject a note of levity.
 &HT;    ``I was very surprised by Al on the set of this movie,'' Crowe
says. ``Al is really comfortable with himself. He's always at ease,
which did not fit in with the fan's perspective I have of him.
 &HT;    ``You always hear about how Al is intense,'' he adds. ``It's
just not true. I see him as relaxed _ unless he's watching a
baseball game on TV. Then he does get a bit intense.''
 &HT;    Arriving for an interview on a cool fall day in Los Angeles, the
59-year-old Pacino doesn't look intense. Handsome and casual in a
black-leather jacket, black sweatshirt and dark, tailored slacks,
he has his short, black hair spiked to stand up at the ends. He
also sports a tiny goatee, which he rubs from time to time like a
good-luck charm.
 &HT;    He can use it _ ``The Insider'' is one of the most controversial
movies of the year, not so much for its attacks not on the tobacco
industry as for its assault on one of journalism's sacred cows, the
venerated television-news program ``60 Minutes.''
 &HT;    In 1995, ``60 Minutes'' star Mike Wallace (Christopher Plummer)
recorded an explosive interview with Jeffrey Wigand (Crowe), a
scientist and former executive with Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco
Corp. Wigand alleged that B&AMP;W CEO Thomas E. Sandefur had
deliberately lied under oath when he testified during Congressional
hearings that cigarettes were not addictive.
 &HT;    Pacino plays former ``60 Minutes'' producer Lowell Bergman, who
had talked Wigand into telling his story. At the last minute,
however, CBS lawyers and executives cut Wigand out of the piece,
citing fears of a lawsuit by the tobacco company.
 &HT;    Most observers see the episode as perhaps the biggest blunder of
Wallace's long career, essentially a sellout under corporate
pressure. Wallace is irate about the film, and Pacino knows it.
 &HT;    ``Look, if any one of us had a segment of our lives made into a
movie, we would be a little upset, too,'' the actor says. ``I think
the problem is, he is so close to what happened that he's worried
about how it will be portrayed.
 &HT;    ``So his reaction is natural. But I wonder what his reaction
will be after he sees the picture.''
 &HT;    When Pacino was offered the film, it immediately reminded him of
one of his greatest previous roles, the title role in ``Serpico''
(1973).
 &HT;    ``In a strange way, I started thinking about `Serpico' again,''
Pacino says. ``It's about a man trying to do the right thing
against great odds.''
 &HT;    As he did with New York Police Department whistleblower Frank
Serpico, Pacino spent time with the real Bergman to develop his
interpretation of the character.
 &HT;    ``Maybe this film was easier because I was playing a real
person,'' he says. ``I do think it's easier to play someone who
exists _ it's like having a model for your painting.''
 &HT;    Bergman is an intense person, Pacino says, but also quiet and
unobtrusive.
 &HT;    ``He's not overt,'' the actor says. ``Here's an example: I saw
Lowell the other night for the first time in a year. I almost
walked right by him. Like any good journalist, he has a way of
blending in _ he disappears into a crowd.''
 &HT;    Pacino has never been that kind of guy. Born Alfredo Pacino in
New York, he's been a performer since he was 4, entertaining his
grandfather on the roof of his apartment building. After studying
acting at New York's prestigious HB Studios _ he'd previously
dropped out of Manhattan's High School of the Performing Arts _ he
made his movie debut in ``Me, Natalie'' (1969).
 &HT;    Francis Ford Coppola saw him playing a junkie in ``The Panic in
Needle Park'' (1971) and immediately cast him as Michael Corleone
in ``The Godfather'' (1972), for which he was nominated for an
Academy Award as Best Supporting Actor.
 &HT;    The rest is movie history, including Oscar nominations for ``The
Godfather Part II'' (1974), ``Serpico,'' ``Dog Day Afternoon''
(1975), `` ... And Justice for All'' (1979), ``Dick Tracy'' (1990)
and ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' (1992). He finally won in 1992, taking
home the Best Actor award for his performance as Lt. Col. Frank
Slade in ``Scent of a Woman.''
 &HT;    Lately Pacino also has been directing, including his
Shakespearean quasidocumentary, ``Looking for Richard'' (1996), and
the recently completed ``Chinese Coffee,'' a drama in which he
doubles as director and star.
 &HT;    ``I think it's a possibility that I will direct more in the
future,'' he says. ``But I'm not sure I'm comfortable thinking of
myself as a director, because I don't have a great, overwhelming
desire to do it.
 &HT;    ``I guess there are a lot of directors who make movies without
that passion,'' he says, smiling. ``But they have a great gift _ I
never saw myself as having that gift.''
 &HT;    On the other hand, he says that acting is still a source of
elemental satisfaction to him.
 &HT;    ``Honestly, there are still moments, even after all of these
years, when I forget that the camera is even there,'' Pacino says.
``I'm just being this other person.''
 &HT;    Finding other people to be is harder, however, especially for an
actor who relishes films that have something to say about
contemporary society.
 &HT;    ``I guess times have changed, which is understandable,'' he
says. ``There are so many outlets for the news these days that
people don't want to make movies about the issues.''
 &HT;    Partly as a result of that change, the actor has been spending
more time on stage in recent years, including a recent production
of Eugene O'Neill's ``Hughie,'' for which he served as director and
star in New York and Los Angeles.
 &HT;    ``I like to return to the stage because that's where it all
started _ I'm familiar with it,'' Pacino says. ``I also enjoy the
idea of performing live, because your entire life is about that 8
p.m. curtain. When you don't have a steady diet of that type of
adrenaline in your life, you almost physically miss it.
 &HT;    ``Of course, when I'm doing a play I think, `I don't want this
adrenaline _ I don't want this tightrope,''' Pacino admits. ``But
once that curtain opens and I say the first line, there is no
turning back. And I love it.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Insider,'' consult the
