<HEADLINE>
CHARIOTS OF FIRE: AT 40, `BEN-HUR' IS STILL AN EPIC AMONG EPICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Charlton Heston in the chariot-race scene
from ``Ben-Hur.'' 
 By TOM SOTER  
 c.1999 Diversion magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Q: What 119-year-old novel by an obscure Civil War general
became one of the greatest religious screen epics of all time?
 &HT;    A: Well, here's a hint: The movie version features a
breathtaking, nine-minute chariot race with Academy Award-winner
Charlton Heston driving his own team of stallions.
 &HT;    The answer, of course, is ``Ben-Hur'' (1959), a 222-minute film
that, even as it turns 40 this November, remains an epic among
epics. And of course there's that immortal chariot race which, even
in today's era of computerized special effects, looks remarkably as
if it actually happened _ which, in fact, it did.
 &HT;    ``Ben-Hur'' took years of planning and more than a year of
filming, and cost a then-unheard-of $16 million. It was a huge
gamble that paid off richly for Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, breaking
box-office records, grossing nearly $80 million worldwide, saving
the financially ailing studio and winning 11 Academy Awards, a
record matched only once, by another epic, ``Titanic'' (1997).
 &HT;    It also triggered a tidal wave of biblical epics. ``The Robe''
(1953) and ``The Ten Commandments'' (1958) had been popular, but
after ``Ben-Hur'' the floodgates opened: ``King of Kings'' (1961)
and ``Barabbas'' (1961) were followed by ``Sodom and Gomorrah''
(1963), ``The Fall of the Roman Empire'' (1964), ``The Greatest
Story Ever Told'' (1965) and, of course, ``The Bible'' (1966).
 &HT;    Set primarily in A.D. 33, the movie centers on a Jewish prince,
Judah Ben-Hur (Heston), and his boyhood friend, a Roman soldier
named Messala (Stephen Boyd), who feud over the Romans' treatment
of the Jews and eventually fight to the death in that sensational
chariot race.
 &HT;    Like many epics, Judah's saga is episodic. He is convicted of a
crime he didn't commit, and on his way to punishment meets Jesus.
He then spends three years as a galley slave, fights in a mighty
sea battle, becomes a Roman citizen and a famous charioteer,
defeats Messala, rescues his family from a leper colony and
witnesses the events leading up to Jesus' crucifixion.
 &HT;    The original novel was written by Lew Wallace, a Civil War
general, diplomat and governor of New Mexico who spent eight years
writing what he subtitled ``A Tale of the Christ.''
 &HT;    Novelist and co-screenwriter Gore Vidal has observed, however,
that it was not really a tale of the Christ at all.
 &HT;    ``It was,'' he says, ``the tale of a Roman boy and a Jewish
boy.''
 &HT;    The massive novel eventually became a best-seller, reportedly
selling 50,000 copies a year, and became a stage play in 1899 and a
silent movie in 1907 and again in 1925.
 &HT;    The 1925 ``Ben-Hur,'' starring Ramon Novarro, was a huge success
for MGM, so much so that when the financially struggling studio
needed a savior in the mid-1950s, it looked no further than
Wallace's novel.
 &HT;    This time around, MGM rented Cinecitta Studios in Rome.
 &HT;    ``It looked very much like an American studio,'' Heston writes
in his autobiography, ``which is not surprising _ Mussolini had
sent his son to Hollywood to get an idea of what a studio should be
when he'd planned it in the '30s.''
 &HT;    To direct, MGM chose William Wyler _ a two-time Oscar-winner but
still an unlikely choice, since he was best known for
character-based dramas such as ``These Three'' (1936), ``Jezebel''
(1938), ``Wuthering Heights'' (1939) and ``The Best Years of Our
Lives'' (1946).
 &HT;    Nonetheless, producer Sam Zimbalist _ who would die of a heart
attack before the film was completed _ was aiming for a thinking
man's action story, and thought Wyler would bring the right touch.
 &HT;    Wyler _ who once quipped, ``It takes a Jew to make a really good
movie about Christ'' _ picked his Ben-Hur from the cast of his
previous film, ``The Big Country'' (1958), selecting Heston over
possible alternatives including Marlon Brando, Burt Lancaster, Rock
Hudson and Kirk Douglas.
 &HT;    Heston was no stranger to epics, having starred as Moses in
``The Ten Commandments.'' But he saw Judah as a more believable,
complex individual, reflected in Karl Tunberg's script, later
heavily rewritten by Vidal and then by British playwright
Christopher Fry.
 &HT;    ``His changes were seldom structural,'' Heston recalls of Fry in
his memoirs, ``but almost always stylistically crucial, such as
changing `You didn't like the food?' to `The meal did not please
you?' ... Every scene he touched was the better for it.''
 &HT;    Vidal claims to have included a key subtextual ingredient to
help explain Messala's burning hatred for Judah _ a latent romantic
interest between the two men.
 &HT;    ``There is something emotional between these two, which is not
stated and which blows the fuse in Messala,'' the writer told
Herman. ``He is spurned, so it's a love scene gone wrong.''
 &HT;    The chariot race, which cost $1 million and took five weeks to
shoot over a three-month period, was actually choreographed by
second-unit director Andrew Marton and stunt coordinator Yakima
Canutt.
 &HT;    Marton used doubles to shoot the race in long shots, then asked
Heston and Boyd to re-create many of the sequences in closeup. For
more than a month, Heston spent at least two hours a day learning
how to drive a chariot.
 &HT;    The most daring stunt was unplanned: As Judah's chariot leaped
over the wreckage of another one, an unexpected bounce flipped
stunt driver Joe Canutt into the air and onto the rigging between
the horses.
 &HT;    ``I thought he was a dead man,'' Heston recalls. ``The chariot
weighed half a ton, with steel-rimmed wheels sure to cut him in
half, or at least cripple him ... He dropped the reins, grabbed the
front of the chariot, turned and dropped to a handstand on the
tongue behind the running team, then flung himself clear.''
 &HT;    A closeup shot was later filmed, showing Heston climbing back
into the moving chariot.
 &HT;    The race wasn't the only arduous part of the shoot. The company
worked six days a week, with Wyler logging as much as 14 hours
daily. Heston did 16 takes of one line _ ``I'm a Jew'' _ before he
could satisfy the demanding director, and also spent days rowing in
a galley, leading him to quip, ``I want to get back home, but I'm
damned if I thought I'd be rowing all the way.''
 &HT;    Actor Jack Hawkins, playing a Roman, was equally exhausted.
 &HT;    ``When we were working under the boiling Italian sun and the
temperature was in the 90s, I had to wear almost 50 pounds of
armor,'' he recalls. ``How those sailors of ancient Rome ever stood
up, much less fought a battle, I'll never know.''
 &HT;    The arena for the chariot race was the largest ever built for a
Hollywood film, stretching across 18 back-lot acres. There were
1,500-foot straightaways and a 10-foot-high central island with
four giant statues, each 30 feet high. It used 1,000,000 pounds of
plaster, 40,000 cubic feet of lumber, 260 miles of metal tubing and
40,000 tons of white sand. A track of identical size was built next
door for training the horses.
 &HT;    For all the spectacle, however, ``Ben-Hur'' ultimately succeeded
because of its message. Unlike such campy epics as ``The Ten
Commandments'' or ``The Robe,'' the film's religious and historic
events are merely a framework for its theme _ the danger of
becoming what you hate.
 &HT;    Its hero is not a plaster saint but a flawed, obsessed man. At
the end of the movie, after Messala is fatally injured, Judah
realizes what hate has done to both of them, and he seeks out
Jesus, who represents love, and asks for forgiveness.
 &HT;    ``Forgiveness is greater, and love is more powerful, than
hatred,'' one character warns. And, whatever the age and whatever
the audience, that message is universal.
 &HT;    Of course, it also helps that Judah drives one mean chariot.
 c.1999 Tom Soter  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Tom Soter is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
