 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Oct. 26. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Hank Wernken; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GAZA-WESTBANK (Erez Crossing, Gasa Strip) _ The first safe
passage route between Gaza and the West Bank opened Monday,
re-establishing a lifeline between the divided portions of the
Palestinian world. The opening marked another concrete step forward
in the Israeli-Palestinian peace effort, but its delay hinted at
the difficulties that lie ahead as Prime Minister Ehud Barak aims
to forge a final peace agreement. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-MUSHARRAF (Islamabad, Pakistan) _ The Chicago
anesthesiologist picked up his morning newspaper and read a
headline that made him mad. ``Pakistan Wakes Up to a Dictator,'' it
said. Pakistan was the doctor's native country and that was his
brother, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, they were talking about. The doctor
was upset about news accounts that suggested his brother was an
anti-western fundamentalist. Far from it, he said in a telephone
interview. By Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN-REFORM (Falls Church, Va.) _ Invoking a ``new
patriotism,'' Pat Buchanan put aside a lifetime of Republican
fervor Monday and shifted his lagging presidential quest to a run
for the Reform party nomination. And as soon as he did, he was
attacked by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican front-runner
considered most liable to damage should Buchanan generate a serious
tri-corner competition. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT9.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley have a lot more in common than either would like
to admit to presidential primary voters. Each will try to emphasize
differences that matter to those voters when they debate for the
first time in New Hampshire on Wednesday night. But in fact, the
two Democrats have spent the bulk of their public service careers
as generally liberal members of Congress, with a quite similar
approach to the job. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PLANE-STEWART (Undated) _ A Learjet carrying golfer Payne
Stewart and four other people flew uncontrolled over the nation's
heartland for hours Monday before crashing in South Dakota, killing
everyone aboard. The twin-engine plane, which took off from
Orlando, Fla., may have suffered a pressurization failure during
its scheduled flight to Dallas, government officials said. (Summary
from wires.) By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   With map; two photos, NYT5 and 6, have also moved for use with
OBIT-STEWART.
</P>
