   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ President Clinton vetoed his third
spending bill today, the bill paying for the Commerce, State and
Justice departments. At the same time he signed into law a $268
billion military spending bill, avoiding the potential of a
crippling split among Democrats as the parties hurtle toward the
finale of their budget showdown. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Story will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRAZIL-SKULL (Rio de Janeiro) _ A human skull that is
prominently displayed at the National Museum here has been
attracting crowds and controversy in equal measure since it was
first unveiled early this month. After two decades in storage, the
fossilized cranium has now been identified by Brazilian scientists
as the oldest human remains ever recovered in the Western
Hemisphere. The skull is that of a young woman, nicknamed Luzia,
who is believed to have roamed the savannah of south-central Brazil
some 11,500 years ago. Even more startling, a reconstruction of her
cranium undertaken in Britain this year indicates that her features
appear to be Negroid rather than Mongoloid, suggesting that the
Western Hemisphere may have initially been settled not only earlier
than thought, but by a people distinct from the ancestors of
today's North and South American Indians. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
