<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATTERNS: Going Gently, Into Sleep and Old Age
</P>
<P>
   Next time you skip a few hours of sleep so you can get in a
little more work, or maybe just that last bit of Letterman,
consider the possible consequences: you may pay for the sleep
deprivation not just the next morning, but somewhere down the road
as well.
</P>
<P>
   A new study suggests that chronic lack of sleep may make the
aging process that much harder.
</P>
<P>
   The report, in The Lancet, an international medical journal,
said that over the past century, the average length of time people
slept had decreased to about seven and a half hours, down from
nine.
</P>
<P>
   This has occurred as people try to accommodate not only the
demands of shift work but broader social lives, the journal said.
</P>
<P>
   To test the physiological effects of such sleep loss,
researchers at the University of Chicago studied 11 young men over
16-day periods.
</P>
<P>
   For the first three nights, the men were allowed to sleep 8
hours; for the next six, they slept 4 hours; for the final seven
nights, they slept 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers then measured their carbohydrate metabolism and
hormone functions, and found that both had been harmed.
</P>
<P>
   The effects, they say, resemble those found in the normal aging
process _ and so may increase the severity of age-related chronic
disorders.
</P>
<P>
   RISKS AND REMEDIES: A Gene, a Threat and a Buildup of Iron
</P>
<P>
   As many as 1 in 10 people may be at increased risk of heart
attack or stroke simply because they carry a gene that can lead to
a serious metabolic disorder, even if they are in good health,
recent studies suggest.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the carriers of the gene for the disorder, known as
hemochromatosis, were not shown to be at any special health risk.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers have one copy of the mutated gene associated with the
disease, while sufferers of hemochromatosis inherit one mutated
gene from each parent.
</P>
<P>
   People with the disease absorb too much iron and often sustain
serious injury to the liver, pancreas and other organs.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce iron buildup, sufferers of the disease regularly have
blood drained from their bodies, sometimes as often as once a week.
</P>
<P>
   (The condition has received added attention recently as Federal
health officials consider whether to allow that blood to be used to
help the nation's dwindling blood supply; at the moment, it is
simply thrown away.)
</P>
<P>
   Although they have been spared the burdens of hemochromatosis,
carriers have slightly elevated levels of iron in their blood, and
some researchers have theorized that the added iron could pose a
risk of coronary disease.
</P>
<P>
   Two studies published in a recent issue of Circulation: Journal
the American Heart Association, have now found evidence to support
that theory.
</P>
<P>
   That could raise some broad health questions, including whether
the carriers _ who can get a diagnosis only with a genetic test _
should start having their blood drawn to deplete the iron buildup,
said Dr. Jerome L. Sullivan of the University of Florida at
Gainesville, who wrote an editorial accompanying the studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suggests a new risk factor in a fairly sizable chunk of the
population,'' Sullivan said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   TREATMENTS: Untapped Potential for a Common Herb
</P>
<P>
   Anesthesiologists, like many doctors, tend to be wary of herbal
medicines. Just this year, several anesthesiology associations
began a campaign to warn people facing surgery that their doctors
needed to know if they were taking herbal remedies, since some
could have dangerous interactions with anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   But now anesthesiologists have begun turning to an herb to help
treat a deadly and often intractable lung condition that affects
hundreds of thousands of people a year.
</P>
<P>
   The herb is borage, valued until now mainly for its slightly
cucumberish taste and its eye-pleasing purple and pink flowers. The
disease is acute respiratory distress syndrome, which can result
from trauma (like a car accident), infection and other causes, and
has a fatality rate as high as 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have turned to an arsenal of weapons to cure it, some
high tech, but have so far accomplished little. Now, researchers
from the Mayo Clinic report that in a study of 150 hospital
patients who had oil from borage seeds administered through tubes
in their stomachs, the death rate from the respiratory syndrome
dropped by about 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A second study with a smaller group of patients had similar
results, and researchers now plan further study. The findings were
presented at the recent annual meeting of the American Society of
Anesthesiologists.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers believe the benefits come from a component of the
herb called gammalinolenic acid, which has natural
anti-inflammatory qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excited would be an understatement,'' said Dr. Michael J.
Murray, the Mayo anesthesiologist who conducted the study, when he
was asked his reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ADOLESCENCE: On Sex, Students Have a Lot to Learn
</P>
<P>
   Despite renewed efforts across the country to educate teen-agers
about sex and repercussions like pregnancy and disease, many young
people say they still need more information. A new study of high
school students suggests that they are right.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide survey of 1,012 public school students conducted
for the Kaiser Family Foundation, the health care philanthropy,
found these gaps in students' knowledge:
</P>
<P>
   _15 percent of those who reported being sexually active said
they did not know they could obtain condoms without their parents'
permission, and 39 percent did not know they could buy birth
control pills on their own.
</P>
<P>
   _More than half the girls asked did not know that emergency
contraceptive pills could be taken after intercourse to protect
against pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   _And nearly half those surveyed did not realize that their
chances of becoming infected with the AIDS virus through sex
increased if they had another sexually transmitted disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser foundation reported that students also said they
needed more information about where to get tested for AIDS and
other diseases, how to use condoms and what to do if they or an
acquaintance had been sexually assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Hoff, an official for the foundation, said she was
surprised by the lack of knowledge, given the age of the students
questioned. She also said it appeared that girls were more willing
to own up to their ignorance than boys. ``We need to do more to
target young men, and make sure that they're getting information on
sexual health issues as well,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   SAFETY: A Halloween Scare for Parents: Traffic
</P>
<P>
   It's not the ghosts, the goblins or even all that sugar that
puts many children at risk when they go out trick or treating.
</P>
<P>
   It's the cars.
</P>
<P>
   More than 700 children are killed by cars each year, and 24,000
more are injured.
</P>
<P>
   But a study by the Federal Department of Health and Human
Services, cited by the National Safe Kids Campaign, found that from
1975 to 1996, children were four times as likely to be fatally
injured by a car on Halloween night as on any other evening.
</P>
<P>
   With hordes of Pokemons, ballerinas and assorted ghouls poised
to hit the streets on Sunday, the Safe Kids Campaign
(www.safekids.org), a nonprofit organization based in Washington,
has issued its annual tips for making the holiday safer. The group
urged parents to take these precautions:
</P>
<P>
   _Don't allow children under 12 to trick or treat without adult
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   _Decorate costumes and bags with reflective tape.
</P>
<P>
   _Teach children to walk, not run, while trick or treating, and
not to dart between parked cars.
</P>
<P>
   _And beware of costumes that can restrict a child's vision.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
