<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7907 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BLACK-HOLES-ART-2     10-25 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BLACK-HOLES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A GALAXY'S ASSEMBLY LINE, WHERE THE BLACK HOLES MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Calif., Ill., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new calculation suggests that dense star clusters, which are
sprinkled throughout galaxies in Earth's cosmic neighborhood, act
as assembly lines for tightly orbiting pairs of black holes and
then spit them out of the cluster. There, they eventually fall
together and merge into one.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, if all goes well, scientists will be able to take the
first steps toward testing that theory with a new $350 million
instrument called a gravity wave observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, a cataclysmic merger of black holes should throw
off ripples in the fabric of space called gravity waves. It was to
detect those waves for the first time, from a variety of sources,
in particular from pairs of neutron stars, that physicists designed
the Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory, or LIGO,
which is actually two stations, one in Louisiana and one in
Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   LIGO will be dedicated on Nov. 11 and begin shakedown operations
in January.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, astrophysicists had assumed that black hole pairs
were so rare they would be almost impossible to detect. The
scientists preparing to work at LIGO assumed that their first
capture of gravity waves would come from less powerful events in
the cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   The new calculations, by Dr. Simon F. Portegies Zwart of Boston
University and Dr. Stephen L.W. McMillan of Drexel University,
suggest that detectable mergers of black holes could be as much as
a thousand times more common than the neutron stars LIGO had set
its sights on.
</P>
<P>
   As is customary in astrophysics, the calculations have been
posted on a Web site managed by Los Alamos National Laboratory
(xxx.lanl.gov/abs/astro-ph/9910061). They have also been accepted
for publication at the journal Astrophysical Journal Letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge difference,'' McMillan said. ``When you start
making these things in clusters,'' he said, referring to the black
hole pairs, ``the conditions are very favorable.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Barry C. Barish, a physicist at the California Institute of
Technology, who is the director of LIGO, said that if the
calculation was correct, its implications for the observatory's
first five to six years of operation were striking.
</P>
<P>
   The LIGO detectors that will be in place during that time are
much less sensitive than those to come later, and the black hole
pairs could make the difference between seeing gravity waves or not
seeing them at all during that first phase.
</P>
<P>
   If the new calculations prove true, improvements might boost
LIGO's later detection rate from several events a year to as many
as one or two a day, said Dr. Stuart Shapiro, an astrophysicist at
the University of Illinois in Urbana-Champaign, who is involved in
calculating those rates. ``That's when you can do real science,''
Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Gravity waves have teased physicists for decades, because they
have announced their presence only indirectly. For example, when
Dr. Joseph H. Taylor and Dr. Russell A. Hulse of Princeton observed
a pair of neutron stars caught in a tight orbit around each other,
work for which they received the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1993,
they theorized that the stars should produce gravity waves.
</P>
<P>
   The whirling neutron stars, superdense cinders that sometimes
remain when an ordinary massive star collapses and explodes as a
supernova, slightly stir the four-dimensional fabric of space and
time around them.
</P>
<P>
   According to relativity theory, that stirring action should send
out a weak signal of gravity waves.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor and Hulse could not measure those waves directly. All
they could do was show, with years of work, that the rotation of
the two-star, or binary, system was gradually speeding up as the
stars spiraled closer together.
</P>
<P>
   The acceleration is exactly what would be expected if the energy
was being carried away by the gravity waves.
</P>
<P>
   Even LIGO, which is being built by Caltech and the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology and will measure the minute stretching and
shrinking of space caused by such disturbances, will not be capable
of picking up such a faint spray of gravity waves.
</P>
<P>
   But when two neutron stars get so close that they crash together
and merge, the resulting burst of gravity waves should be
detectable if the collision occurs within one of the thousands of
galaxies that are within about 50 million light-years of Earth.
</P>
<P>
   That process relies on ordinary stars' occasionally being born
in pairs, exploding as supernovas and leaving behind neutron stars
with masses of about 1.5 times that of the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Black holes contain the mass of 10 or more suns and are even
more exotic, having collapsed behind a gravitational shroud called
an event horizon from which nothing can escape, not even light. The
chances that pairs of black holes could form as neutron star
binaries do is vanishingly small.
</P>
<P>
   So McMillan and Portegies Zwart looked at the possibility that
black hole pairs might, in effect, be manufactured inside the tight
knots of stars called globular clusters.
</P>
<P>
   In the clusters, which can contain millions of stars, individual
black holes fall to the middle because of their great mass, the
team realized.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, the black holes attract each other gravitationally
and pair off, forming binaries.
</P>
<P>
   The binaries then carom off other black holes and eventually
pick up enough speed to escape from the cluster. Out in the dark
wasteland of space, the black holes spiral inward just as the
neutron stars do, and finally they merge in a spectacular
collision.
</P>
<P>
   Because the black holes are more massive than neutron stars,
said Barish of LIGO, more gravity waves are emitted and the events
are easier to see from far away. ``We see something that happened
deeper into the universe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The greater range adds up to a much bigger volume of space that
LIGO can monitor, Barish said.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the new work stress that an imperfect knowledge
of clusters and black holes means that their estimates are
uncertain by a factor of 10 or so. ``We still have no guarantees,''
said Dr. Kip S. Thorne, a LIGO collaborator and a physicist at
Caltech.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thorne said he thought the new calculation suggested
``that we are likely to see a very large number of black hole
mergers.''
</P>
<P>
   Because gravity waves are predicted by Einstein's relativity
theory, physicists would hail their detection as a major coup. The
possibility that LIGO will see gravity waves from black holes
brings an additional bonus, said Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their terrific gravitational fields, space-time is
warped around black holes more strongly than anywhere else in the
universe, according to Einstein's equations of relativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A gravitational wave is a direct messenger of that
space-time,'' Shapiro said. ``The upshot will be the first
confirmation of Einstein's theory of relativity'' where the fabric
of space-time is twisted almost beyond recognition, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
