<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7912 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GENOME-RACE-ART-2     10-25 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-RACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS REACH MILESTONES IN GENOME RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKVILLE, Md. _ Two rival teams racing to decode the human
genome have each neared or passed significant milestones.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to tell which of the teams is ahead because they are
pursuing the same goal along different paths. But both are
apparently on track with ambitious schedules that call for ``first
drafts'' of the genome to be completed next spring or summer.
</P>
<P>
   The publicly financed consortium, a group of academic centers
mainly in the United States and Britain, said last week that it had
essentially decoded the first human chromosome, the 22d and
smallest of the 23 pairs.
</P>
<P>
   The decodable part of the chromosome is 33 million units of DNA,
or about 1 percent of the entire genome, which is at least three
billion units.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week the consortium's rival, the Celera Corp. of
Rockville, Md, said it had decoded its first billion units of human
DNA. But the decoded pieces are in short fragments, and the harder
part of the task is deciding how the fragments fit together.
</P>
<P>
   The public consortium, financed principally by the National
Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md, and the Wellcome Trust of
London, has been working to sequence the human genome since 1990.
It completed its pilot project, decoding the genome of the
laboratory roundworm, in December.
</P>
<P>
   Celera, headed by the genome sequencing pioneer Dr. J. Craig
Venter, jumped into the race only in May of last year. As the test
of his high-risk strategy, Venter chose to decode the DNA of
another standard laboratory organism, the Drosophila fruitfly,
which he said will be completed by January.
</P>
<P>
   At Celera's plant in Rockville, Md., the finishing touches were
being made last week to a futuristic control room that could be
modeled on that of the starship Enterprise. From an array of
monitors, supervisors will control the 300 DNA sequencing machines,
the robots that prepare fragments of DNA for analysis and a
HAL-sized computer that assembles the fragments into complete
genomes and analyses the babel of genetic data.
</P>
<P>
   In a nearby hall, a suite of DNA sequencing machines emitted a
deep-throated hum as they forced fragments of DNA through hair-fine
tubes where electric eyes read the sequence of bases, as the four
different units of DNA are known. In the computer room, a glitter
of green lights signaled the arrival of the DNA sequence
information through optic fiber switches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing a billion bases every three and a half weeks,''
Venter said during a tour of the plant. Corporate responsibilities
have forced him into the unusual costume of a suit and tie but not
dulled his delight in the sophisticated machines at his disposal or
the thrill of tackling a mountainous problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We operate 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.'' Asked why the
hurry, he cited a need to file patent applications and quickly
build a genetic database for clients.
</P>
<P>
   Celera's sequencing strategy is quite different from the safe
and methodical approach of its rival. Essentially the consortium
bites off small fragments of known position in the genome and
decodes them one by one. Venter's idea is to tackle the whole
genome all at once and assemble all the pieces in one gigantic
jigsaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   With both team's strategies, the pieces of DNA analyzed by the
sequencing machines are typically 500 bases long. Because the
pieces are cut at random from the DNA in the genome, they tend to
overlap, and a computer's genome assembly program can easily fit
together contiguous pieces _ known as `contigs,' _ by matching the
overlapping ends.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that after the contigs have grown to a certain
size, the assembly program finds it cannot unambiguously match any
new ends. A chief reason for these gaps is that animal genomes are
full of repetitive DNA, regions where the same short string of DNA
units is repeated over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Without further information, the assembly program has no way of
determining how many of these repeated units lie in the gaps
between neighboring contigs.
</P>
<P>
   To bridge the gaps caused by the repetitive regions, the Celera
team relies on generating pieces of linking DNA from the genome
being decoded. The links are long DNA fragments of known length, of
which only the two ends are sequenced.
</P>
<P>
   Celera's assembly program can then position neighboring contigs
by looking for a bridging link that has one end matching DNA in one
contig and the other end matching the other. Enough links are
generated to insure that each neighboring pair of contigs is
spanned on average by at least two bridging link. With the size of
the gap established, it becomes much easier for the assembly
program to thread its way through the repetitive DNA between the
two contigs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fruitfly genome formed the first large-scale test of this
strategy. By last month Celera's machines had produced 3.2 million
fragments of DNA, each about 500 bases long. Dr. Eugene W. Myers,
the chief designer of Celera's assembly program, said that he had
97 percent of the fruitfly genome, including virtually all of the
genes, in correctly assembled contigs. The remaining gaps are
mostly very small, he said, ``which bodes extremely well for our
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   This refutes critics, Myers said, who had predicted ``that we
could not do the compute.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely not getting lost or fooled by the repeats _
we are navigating right around those babies,'' he said, expressing
confidence the fruitfly genome would be completed by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Rubin, a Drosophila expert at the University of
California at Berkeley who has been working with Celera scientists
on the fruit-fly project, said he had not yet seen their data but
that if everything had gone as they said, ``It looks like their
strategy has passed its test with flying colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers expects that the human genome, though more than 15 times
larger, may prove easier to assemble than the fruit fly's because
its repeated elements are more dissimilar and thus easier to
distinguish from each other.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the assembly of the human genome will require a computer
calculation of considerable size. Celera's powerful computer can
assemble the Drosophila genome in 12 hours but will need three
months for the human genome, Myers calculates. Since it will take a
year to generate the human sequence data, the plan is start the
computer on its assembly run before all the sequencing data is
available.
</P>
<P>
   To acquire the necessary degree of overlap between its DNA
fragments, a genome must be sequenced several times over. Having
switched its machines from fruit fly to human DNA, Celera expects
to have sequenced six billion bases by March and nine billion by
May or June. The latter figure, covering the genome three times
over, should suffice to complete the decoding of 97 percent of the
human genome, said Dr. Mark Adams, Celera's vice president for
genome programs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the consortium had by mid-October completed 446
million bases of sequence, about 14 percent of the human genome,
with a further 15 percent nearing completion. Most of the finished
sequence is in long, disconnected fragments, but a team led by Dr.
Ian Dunham of the Sanger Center, near Cambridge, England, has
almost completed chromosome 22, apart from 10 small gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Dunham says the chromosome contains 400 to 600 genes but he has
not yet looked for patterns in the chromosome that might reveal the
evolutionary logic of its construction.
</P>
<P>
   The public consortium is making its data public, believing that
medical and scientific progress depend on open access to the
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Venter has also said he will make his primary human DNA sequence
available, but he intends to keep other information proprietary.
The primary DNA sequence will be of enormous medical importance,
but much commercially valuable information is expected to lie not
in the standard genome, but in the DNA variations commonly found in
the population. It is these variations, which can make a gene
perform better or worse, that help determine a person's
susceptibility to disease.
</P>
<P>
   Celera scientists intend to pick up many of these common
variations in their first human genome sequence, since they will
sequence both the maternal and paternal strands of DNA of an
individual and so pick up the differences between them. Celera will
also sequence several other people's genomes so as to generate a
large library of the common DNA variations.
</P>
<P>
   It now seems that it will be impossible to complete the human
genome in terms of sequencing every DNA base. The tips and central
region of each chromosome have so many repeated units that they are
essentially unsequenceable. Because of the difficulty of knowing
when everything possible has been done, it may be the human genome
race will have no sharply defined finishing post and no clear
winner.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Venter should come in first, it seems that the
consortium will attain its goal, that of seeing the human genome
sequence finished and placed in the public domain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
