<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TEEN-PREGNANCY26-COX     10-25 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-PREGNANCY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEEN PREGNANCY RATE FALLS SHARPLY, GOVERNMENT REPORTS
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The teenage birth rate has fallen sharply since
1991, with the highest rates of decline recorded among black women,
the federal government reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala said the
decline was mainly due to three factors _ a fear of contracting
AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases, a growing rejection
of casual sex, and welfare reform laws that sent a message to young
men about child support obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there were 51.1 births last year for each 1,000
women aged 15 to 19,
</P>
<P>
   the department reported. That was down 18 percent from a rate of
62.1 in 1991, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the improvement was due to a 26.1 percent decline in the
same period among black teenagers, to a rate of 88.2, and a 12.2
percent decline among Hispanic teenagers, to a rate of 97.3, the
department said.
</P>
<P>
   The figures give some hope to efforts aimed to curb teen
pregnancies and births, said Isabel Sawhill, president of the
National Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lower rates of teen births are a result of less sex, more
contraception and a growing recognition among teens themselves that
their focus should be on education and growing up,'' Sawhill said
at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``We believe the strength of teen pregnancy
programs is working in local communities,'' Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   Sawhill said communities must take the initiative in reducing
teen pregnancies by implementing programs tailored to their needs,
adding that sex education in the schools is insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Teens need help negotiating their way through the pressures of
engaging and risky behavior, Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the National Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy
released a manual to help communities design successful prevention
efforts. It contains the latest research on teen pregnancies and
provides strategies for after-school activities and building
fund-raising coalitions, Sawhill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal should be to maintain the momentum,'' Sawhill said.
``This manual is the chart book to keep us on course.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
