<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOBS CAN TAKE A TOLL ON TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The high school principal bent a knee toward the floor
and clasped his hands in supplication. ``I beg you,'' he beseeched.
``Write something about high school kids working.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three in 10 full-time high school students are employed.
According to government statistics, nine out of 10 of them work
less than 35 hours a week, but some hold full-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Educators aren't against students working. They know some
families need the income. They also know jobs can be terrific
teachers _ of responsibility, time management and career
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   But educators oppose students working more than 15 to 20 hours a
week. And they're really averse to teens working from the time
school lets out until shifts end at 10 p.m., 11 p.m. or later.
</P>
<P>
   Students who work long, late hours fall asleep at their desks
the next day. They may not be listening. They may not be
participating in school activities. They may not be learning.
</P>
<P>
   Walk in any high school classroom on any morning. The odds are
good you'll find at least two or three teens nodding off.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, science finds they may be wired that way. Sleep
research shows that the circadian rhythm of teen-age bodies
predisposes teens to stay up until 11 p.m. and sleep late into the
morning _ several hours past the typical high school start time.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep researchers also say teens need, but don't get, nine hours
of sleep a night.
</P>
<P>
   Students who close restaurants at 11 p.m. aren't likely to head
right to bed. They'll do homework (maybe, maybe not), get on the
Internet, watch television or talk on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   University professors say the problem doesn't stop at high
school graduation. They see lots of in-class sleepers. And what
really bugs teachers is that many young workers aren't motivated by
true financial need. Working is just ``the thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For what reason?'' a university educator asked. ``Many of them
don't need to work. They're living their lives in fast forward
instead of getting the maximum learning benefit available to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, I surveyed hundreds of teens for a report
on working teens. A majority said adults should chill out and let
them work. They wanted the money to buy things, they said. Besides,
there was plenty of time left to pursue loftier professional goals.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But some teens, and apparently their parents, don't
have the good sense to put a lid on school-day work hours.
</P>
<P>
   The government imposes a limit of 18 hours a school week for 14-
and 15-year-old workers and forbids work after 7 p.m. for that age
group during the school year. I wouldn't want similar dictates for
16- to 18-year-olds. There are too many personal circumstances to
consider.
</P>
<P>
   But if teens and parents can't put reasonable limits on
school-day work hours, then the appeal goes to employers: Don't
hire full-time students to lock up, work late on school nights or
work full-time-equivalent hours during the school year.
</P>
<P>
   Doing well in school and learning should be teens' work. If
``invincible'' teens can't see they're being robbed, maybe you can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7928 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MEDICAL-MOM-$ADV31-CO     10-25 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-MOM-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON STOPS FOR PICTURES WITH SAILOR'S BIRTH-DAMAGED SON
 &HT;    Eds: Restores note with release date.
 &HT;    Moving in Washington (w) and Lifestyle (l) categories for
release Sunday, Oct. 31.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Georgina Denman believes her severely birth-damaged
son, Tyler, has a ``special and unusual effect'' on people.
</P>
<P>
   It worked on Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The wife of a Navy enlisted man, Denman recently managed to get
a few minutes with Clinton _ by merely asking to see him, even
though she did not have an appointment or advance clearance.
</P>
<P>
   She is convinced Tyler was the reason.
</P>
<P>
   Denman is a member of a small group of active-duty wives who
call themselves ``Casualties of Tricare.'' They have been trying
for several years to get the Defense Department to change a
controversial policy that denies skilled nursing care to some
military dependents on the grounds that their conditions cannot be
improved.
</P>
<P>
   Active-duty and retiree dependents are left to get care through
Medicaid or charity, often a difficult and humiliating process.
</P>
<P>
   When Tyler was born, complications left him without oxygen for
19 minutes. His heart had stopped beating and he was left
neurologically damaged. He is kept alive by a respirator, an array
of monitors and other the machines and the constant attention of a
pediatric nurse.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, the Defense Department's Tricare program paid
for Tyler's nursing care.
</P>
<P>
   However, Denman said, Tricare case managers warned her
repeatedly that they might shift him to ``custodial care'' status.
</P>
<P>
   The term is dreaded by Tricare beneficiaries with children or
other dependents who must have skilled nursing care. Tricare
defines custodial care patients to include those who have no hope
of recovery, even if the care is necessary to keep them alive.
Although the program pays for some benefits, including one doctor
visit a month, it will not pay for skilled nursing care.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, Tyler's status was changed and his nursing care
terminated.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of sympathetic Orange County, Calif., officials,
she got him approved for Medicaid. Her husband, Hospital Corpsman
2c John Denman, commutes to his work as an instructor at Camp
Pendleton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyler would not survive without this care,'' Georgina Denman
said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, active-duty mothers of disabled children mounted a
campaign to get the Tricare policy changed. Largely because of
their efforts, next year's Defense Department appropriations bill
requires Tricare to provide ``all medically necessary health care
... regardless of the health care status.''
</P>
<P>
   During the mothers' lobbying campaign, Denman came to
Washington, bringing Tyler and his nurse, Temple Fee, to talk with
members of Congress and Tricare officials about the policy.
</P>
<P>
   When she learned Clinton was in a meeting, down the hall from a
reception she was attending, she went to the nearest Secret Service
agent and asked if she could please speak with the president of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him my husband was a Navy corpsman and asked him if
there was any chance in a bahzillion my little boy could see the
president,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Eying Tyler, asleep in his wheelchair, the Secret Service agent
shook his head and explained to her that requests like hers had to
be approved in advance... and he'd really like to help her...and
there was no way... and...well, he'd check.
</P>
<P>
   Denman, Fee, Tyler and Edith Smith, a volunteer military family
advocate, waited in a coffee shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, the agent came running in there and told us to
come on and to hurry,'' Denman said.
</P>
<P>
   The agent stationed the group near a door and after a few
minutes Clinton came through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president came right over and said hello to Temple and
me,'' Denman said. ``I told him I was from Arkansas and I was a
Navy wife we were here to lobby for military health care reform.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Clinton put his hand on Tyler's head and she told him,
``This is my son, Tyler.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyler, it's an honor to meet you,'' Clinton said as a White
House photographer took pictures.
</P>
<P>
   And her son?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyler has a strange and wonderful effect on people,'' she
said. ``He's beautiful, and they are attracted to him. But he slept
through the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
