<HEADER>
A7933 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CANCER-TREATMENT-1500     10-25 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-TREATMENT-1500(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HOPE FOR CANCER VICTIMS: BURN LIVER TUMORS AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Sewell examined the young cancer patient's entire
abdominal cavity with ultrasound, searching for any additional
lesions before he deployed a five-pronged probe, armed with
electrical energy, to destroy the large tumor growing in the middle
of her liver.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes after the probe began heating up, steam seemed to
rise from the malignant cells. Temperature monitors at the tip of
each prong registered 100 degrees centigrade. The tumor began to
lose its pink color after about 10 minutes, and with five
overlapping follow-up burns actually began to look scorched.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer was dying of the heat _ the tumor burned away in the
operating room at Harris Methodist HEB in Fort Worth while I
watched, along with several surgeons, including one from Houston
who was on hand to learn more about laparoscopic thermal ablation
of cancerous liver tumors.
</P>
<P>
   Radiofrequency Interstitial Tissue Ablation (RITA), as the new
minimally invasive treatment is named, offers hope to people with
cancerous tumors in the liver, especially the estimated 75 percent
whose tumors cannot be surgically removed at diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Christi Herb, 37, found a lump under her arm that
turned out to be a swollen lymph node that had already been invaded
by malignant cells from the 3-centimeter tumor discovered in her
left breast.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the 26 lymph nodes tested were positive for the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a mastectomy plus four rounds of chemotherapy starting
last September,'' recalls Herb, who lives in Keller near Fort Worth
with her husband and two young sons. ``Then in January, I had a
bone-marrow transplant with high-dose chemo, and in March and April
I had 51/2 weeks of radiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the aggressive treatment, a CAT scan in July _ six
months after the bone-marrow transplant _ showed a shadow on her
liver.
</P>
<P>
   The needle biopsy was inconclusive, but the tumor was growing so
quickly, she opted for a laparoscopic biopsy and the new thermal
ablation treatment. The shadow turned out to be a 5-centimeter
(golfball-size) tumor in the middle of her liver. A quick biopsy
found it malignant, and Sewell went forward with the heat ablation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this, we can completely obliterate the tumor with no open
surgery,'' said Sewell, a general surgeon. ``There is much less
risk and less trauma to the patient, and we are able to treat
multiple lesions that we couldn't treat in the past. The exciting
thing to us is to discover something different that benefits the
patients we previously couldn't help at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Followed by chemotherapy to rid the body of any cancer not
directly ablated by the heat probe, laparoscopic thermal ablation
is becoming a viable option for treatment of tumors in the liver.
</P>
<P>
   Sewell learned the procedure from Dr. Alan Siperstein of the
Cleveland Clinic, who did the first in this country in January 1996
and reported on his first 57 cases at this year's annual meeting of
the Society for Surgical Oncology.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the trial testing the safety and efficacy of the
procedure will not be published until next month, but Siperstein
says laparoscopic thermal ablations are very safe and may be as
efficient at destroying tumors as traditional resection (surgical
removal of the tumor).
</P>
<P>
   ``The great advantage is recovery time,'' Siperstein said, ``a
day instead of a week in the hospital, and a couple of days versus
a month or more to completely recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our trial, which is still ongoing, we have a very low rate
of complications and an 88 percent success rate in destroying liver
tumors. Only 12 percent of them have come back,'' said Siperstein,
whose study recently was expanded to include 65 patients because
the initial results were so good.
</P>
<P>
   Patients enrolled in the study had all failed first-line
treatment _ which is surgery, if possible, and chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Results are quite encouraging,'' Siperstein said in a
telephone interview. ``We started this with very cautious optimism.
At this point, I'm very optimistic. It has the potential for cure,
and it's clearly safer than cryosurgery'' (a treatment that freezes
the tumor tissue but often causes extensive bleeding and cannot be
used if the tumor is near a major blood vessel).
</P>
<P>
   Sewell said the new treatment adds significantly to what doctors
have to offer patients for liver cancers, which kill 1.25 million
people worldwide each year.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   The new procedure was developed in Italy, where most liver
cancer is primary (that is, it originates in the liver), rather
than metastatic (spread to the liver from another site). But the
treatment works equally well for other types of liver tumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we all want is what is safest for our patients and
creates the highest possibility of success,'' said Sewell. ``This
is one more treatment option, but for many liver tumors it is
ideal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if it is equivalent to surgical resection yet,
but only about 25 percent of the time is surgery even possible.
Thermal ablation is not nearly so traumatic to the patient, and it
can be used in many patients whose cancer cannot be surgically
removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radiofrequency ablation is unproven, but to sit back and do
nothing for a patient with liver cancer is unacceptable,'' Sewell
said.
</P>
<P>
   David Wise, 52, of nearby Bedford, had open surgery in June 1998
to remove what was thought to be a benign tumor in his small
intestine. Not only was the tumor malignant, but it had spread to
three spots on the liver as well. Only one could be removed at the
time of surgery; the other two involved too much of the liver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chemotherapy was the only treatment available, but six months
of chemo, four days each month, four hours per day, did nothing to
shrink those last two
</P>
<P>
   tumors,'' Wise said. ``They didn't get any bigger, they just
stayed the same.''
</P>
<P>
   He underwent thermal ablation in February and has had CAT scans
every three months since then. They show that the two tumors are
dead and have shrunk almost to the point of disappearing as new
liver tissue grows and replaces the dead tissue. There is no sign
of any new lesions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a very rare type of cancer that has a five-year survival
rate of only 15 percent, but now with this new procedure I'm as
good as new,'' Wise said. ``It was like a death sentence was
lifted. ... I feel like I have a second lease on life. I just hope
I keep all my tumors in places that can be treated with this.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Herb, she was cheering on the sidelines at both her sons'
soccer games three days after the surgery. Her treatment required
only one night in the hospital, and she wasn't sure that was
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has just really blessed me through all of this,'' said
Herb. ``My final goal is to get my life back. I want to have breast
reconstruction with all my own tissue, but the timing is up to God.
I think he made this available just in time for me. I just rely on
God and trust him to get me through each procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
