<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7946 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GAMMA-RAYS-2TAKES     10-25 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GAMMA-RAYS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING THE SOURCE AND THE POWER OF GAMMA RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ala., N.M., Ill., Calif., Utah)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ancient sky watchers saw the heavens as a kind of cosmic
sculpture garden, eternal and unchanging.
</P>
<P>
   But modern astronomers who study huge explosions called gamma
ray bursts are discovering a universe that is more like a wild,
all-night disco party. And with the help of a new generation of
gamma ray observatories, astronomers say the party is just
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference in Huntsville, Ala., last week, astronomers
reported that one new detector, Milagro in the Jemez Mountains of
New Mexico, has apparently recorded the most energetic radiation
ever seen from a gamma ray burst, nearly a trillion electron volts.
</P>
<P>
   The observations suggest that gamma ray bursts _ already
considered the most violent events in the universe _ may be even
more energetic than had been believed, raising new questions about
the source of their power.
</P>
<P>
   During the conference, several scientists reported that the
tremendous energies of gamma ray bursts make them both mysterious
and useful. The flashes of radiation are so brilliant, said Dr.
Donald Q. Lamb, an astrophysicist at the University of Chicago,
that new, gamma-sensitive satellites can use them to study the
formation of stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bursts might actually reveal the moment of first light,''
Lamb said. ``This just breaks open a whole host of wonderful
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The first stars, Lamb explained, probably formed when the
universe was hundreds of millions of years old, so they would now
be billions of light-years away and could never be seen in their
own light. But if some of the massive early stars exploded as gamma
ray bursts, astronomers could study the epoch. The gamma rays would
carry fingerprints of the gases through which they passed, yielding
information about star formation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bursts are like beacons, flashing us messages from the
early universe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb and other scientists said gamma ray bursts, the most
rollicking phenomena in the universe, could soon become the most
revealing.
</P>
<P>
   In traditional astronomy, ``you'd sit at the telescope all night
and look at your data slowly come in,'' said Dr. Neil Gehrels, an
astrophysicist at the NASA Goddard Space Flight Center and the
principal investigator of a $163 million satellite called the Swift
Gamma Ray Burst Explorer, which the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration will launch in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we can look at other wavelength bands, we've discovered
that the sky is transient and changing all the time,'' Gehrels
said. ``People didn't realize that in the classical astronomy.''
</P>
<P>
   The new instruments go beyond Swift and Milagro, a $3 million
detector whose name means ``miracle'' in Spanish. NASA has
scheduled a launch in January of the $20 million High Energy
Transient Explorer, or HETE-2, which is intended to detect
gamma-ray bursts and relay their coordinates to observatories
almost instantly.
</P>
<P>
   A much more ambitious NASA project, the $270 million Gamma Ray
Large Area Space Telescope, could be launched by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new field of astronomy is opening up,'' said Dr. Gerald J.
Fishman, an astrophysicist at the NASA Marshall Space Flight Center
who was one of the conference's organizers.
</P>
<P>
   This rush of data comes as astronomers have begun closing in on
the locations and reasons for the bursts. Discovered by chance in
the 1960s, gamma ray bursts are detected about once a day from
random points in the sky. Detectors on satellites usually make the
measurements, since Earth's atmosphere is opaque to gamma rays, a
form of radiation that is 100,000 times more energetic than
ordinary light.
</P>
<P>
   For decades after the discovery of gamma ray bursts, astronomers
could not determine whether they were exploding nearby, in this
galaxy, or deep in space. But two years ago, observations focusing
on the optical ``afterglows'' of some bursts, analogous to the
dying embers of a fire, were able to fix distances to some of them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7947 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GAMMA-RAYS-2TAKES     10-25 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GAMMA-RAYS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: of them.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those distances turned out to be as great as 10 billion
light-years. In order to be visible from those distances, gamma ray
bursts had to be the most powerful blasts since the Big Bang, the
explosion under one theory in which the universe was thought to
have originated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that gamma ray bursts are the most
brilliant objects in the universe,'' said Dr. Shrinivas Kulkarni,
an astronomer at the California Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, observations by Kulkarni and others have
suggested that the bursts might channel their energy in a beam,
like a flashlight. If the beam happens to be pointed toward Earth,
a brilliant flash could result from a less energetic explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have evidence that beaming is taking place,'' said Dr.
Tsvi Piran of the Hebrew University in Jerusalem. Beaming would
still require immense energy, Piran said.
</P>
<P>
   Theorists do not yet understand how so much energy can be
released as gamma rays in so short a time. The ``best bet
candidates,'' said Piran, involve the sudden collapse of a very
massive star or the collision of two superdense objects called
neutron stars.
</P>
<P>
   To investigate the sources of such transient and energetic gamma
rays, astronomers built the Milagro, a collaborative effort
involving Los Alamos National Laboratory and eight universities.
The detector consists of hundreds of light detectors called
phototubes floating within a pond containing six million gallons of
water.
</P>
<P>
   The pond is covered to prevent stray light from setting off the
phototubes. But the detector can sense radiation with energies at
least 10 times as great as any that have been seen from gamma ray
bursts so far. The radiation itself would be stopped by the upper
atmosphere but would start a shower of particles that could pass
through the cover and reach the water in the pond.
</P>
<P>
   There, through interactions with the water, those particles
would generate weak trails of light called Cherenkov emission that
the phototubes would pick up, providing information about the
direction and the energy of the gamma rays. The device operates
continuously, waiting for brief bursts of particles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows us to look for things that go blip,'' said Brenda
Dingus, an astrophysicist at the University of Utah who
collaborates on the project. Milagro began operating last spring.
</P>
<P>
   But the results presented at the conference by another
University of Utah astrophysicist, Dr. Julie McEnery, came from
data collected by a smaller prototype called Milagrito.
</P>
<P>
   During one of about 50 gamma ray bursts monitored by Milagrito,
a shower of particles appeared from the direction of the burst,
suggesting the arrival of what astronomers refer to as TeV
radiation, for ``tera-electron volt,'' a trillion electron volts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best evidence to date of a transient TeV source,''
said Dr. Gus Sinnis, physicist and Milagro collaborator at Los
Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Sinnis and the other collaborators said, however, that there was
a chance of about one in a thousand that the detection could be a
fluke, and that TeV radiation from the bursts would have to be seen
by the larger detector before it could be considered a fact.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Dr. Ed Fenimore, an astrophysicist at Los Alamos National
Laboratory, who is not part of the project, called the early result
exciting, because it would indicate that material in the explosion
``has to be moving even closer to the speed of light than we
thought.'' The higher the speed, the more energy would be required,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several astrophysicists said that the apparent absence of TeV
radiation from most of the bursts would not come as a complete
surprise _ even if they emitted it _ because the universe itself is
not entirely transparent to such energetic radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not all bursts emit such radiation, their brilliance
should be much more visible when all the new detectors are working,
said Lamb of the University of Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
