<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Oct. 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A tranquil weather pattern will continue across much of the
country as several sprawling areas of high pressure cover much of
the nation. Only along the Canadian border will there be any major
areas of unsettled weather.
</P>
<P>
   A low pressure system and its attendant cold front will cross
the Northeast Tuesday. Ahead of the front, there will likely be a
few showers in the Adirondacks and Green Mountains. Along the
Northeast Seaboard, there will be a mixture of sunshine and clouds
while breezes freshen out of the southwest. It will also turn
milder. Meanwhile, behind the front in the northern Great Lakes,
there will be low clouds and isolated showers as cool air flows
over the warm lake waters.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will be abundant from central Texas to northern Florida
and northward into the Ohio Valley as a large area of high pressure
settles into the region. Afternoon readings will warm into the 70s
in many locations following another chilly morning. There will be a
few showers and an isolated rumble of thunder in southern Florida
during the afternoon, though most locations will remain dry.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front sweeping across the northern Rockies will drag some
showers and clouds into central Oregon and Idaho. Most of the
Rockies will be rain-free. Farther south, the Great Plains will
turn unseasonably warm with many readings well into the 80s. In the
Southwest, a few high clouds will spread from southern Arizona
towards western Texas. California will stay mainly sunny and warm,
though patches of clouds will cover the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Frosty Florida
</P>
<P>
   The mercury reached freezing at Tallahassee Monday, a week shy
of the earliest occurrence on record in the Florida capital. The
record minimum was also only two degrees off the lowest reading in
October. Normally, the first freeze occurs on November 25 and some
years have not seen freezing temperatures until January. Oddly,
Boston, New York and Washington have not yet reported readings
below 35 degrees. The airport at Tallahassee has a micro climate
with freezes occurring 36 times in a typical winter, but the
downtown district only notes such chill about half as often.
</P>
</TEXT>
