<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIME OF YOUR LIFE' CLOCKS IN. BUT WAIT A SECOND...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've been witness to the money-back guarantee of Jennifer Love
Hewitt's stardom for so long now, her new drama Time of Your Life
should actually read Finally, a Time for My Life.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who were smitten by Hewitt a few seasons back,
when she was introduced as the pouty, cute-as-a-koala love interest
of Bailey (Scott Wolf) on Party of Five, this is a triumphant
moment. It's as though we're taking this coast-to-coast ride with
her, sharing her highs and lows, sobbing with her each and every
sniff-sniff step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, as the carrier of doom _ as one e-mailer so
affectionately addressed me the other day _ let me just say that
you may want to reassess your trip to Time of Your Life.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt's Sarah did her own reassessing at the end of Monday
night's opening episode, wondering whether she should stay in New
York or head back to San Francisco. She gives this sobbing,
convoluted, melodramatic speech about spontaneity and identity,
freedom and risk-taking _ if I didn't know any better, I'd figure
writer/producer team Amy Lippman and Christopher Keyser were
restaging Keri Russell's should-I-stay-or-should-I-go epiphany from
the Felicity pilot.
</P>
<P>
   I can already hear the comparisons between these two series _
and I gotta say, they're striking, all the way down to Sarah's
well-intentioned but near-obsessive reasons for being in New York
with no job and no place to live.
</P>
<P>
   But Lippman and Keyser haven't ripped off Felicity. They've
ripped off themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Time of Your Life is their Significant Others with a
built-in audience.
</P>
<P>
   Significant Others, introduced at midseason in 1998, was a
whiny, blathering series about recent college graduates navigating
life's land mines. It lasted no more than a half-dozen episodes,
and Lippman and Keyser went back to the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   When Fox started sniffing around the ``P05'' cast for spinoff
possibilities _ Neve Campbell was also sized up, but couldn't
easily be torn away from the family _ a show centered on Hewitt
made the best business sense.
</P>
<P>
   But the pilot Keyser and Lippman submitted to Fox, a melancholy
hour about a young girl in search of her birth father, was quickly
shot down after it was established that Time of Your Life would
lead into the zanier Ally McBeal. This is the downside of
programming by demographics.
</P>
<P>
   Lippman and Keyser are a talented writing team. They know how to
find the emotional buttons in the most rudimentary of scenes. But
bridging light-hearted and hardcore drama has never been their
forte.
</P>
<P>
   That the new Time of Your Life was pieced together quickly might
have resulted in Monday night's episode, which is, to put it
mildly, clunky and messy, as though no one could decide which
direction to take.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sarah seems odd. Hewitt plays her as something of a
clueless ditz, a motormouth who can't shut up. (But at least she's
like Ally, right?) You'd think it would take more than a new time
zone to turn her brain to mush.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday night's episode, Sarah loss her luggage, found an
apartment and met the friends who will become the show's regulars.
She spent most of the episode tracking down the man she thinks is
her father, and the other half trying to decide whether she should
attempt to make it work in big, bad New York. Duh _ as if we don't
know what the decision will be.
</P>
<P>
   To get back to the Significant Others comparison: Time of Your
Life is going for the same gritty, underground New York look,
showing a place inhabited by misfits. Romy (Jennifer Garner),
playing the struggling actress Sarah befriends, actually WAS on
Significant Others. Maguire (Johnathon Schaech) sports the same
type goatee as one of that show's leading characters.
</P>
<P>
   What's most grating about Time of Your Life, though, is the
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Says Sarah, looking into the bedroom of the apartment where her
birth mother once lived: ``Maybe that's where they made me!''
</P>
<P>
   On finding her birth father: ``I came 3,000 miles and I'm just
as far away from finding him as I ever was.''
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about first episodes is that there are seconds
and thirds and maybe even fourths.
</P>
<P>
   Time of Your Life could get better, or go the way of Significant
Others. Six episodes and out. Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins covers television for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
