<SLUG> BC-TECNOLOGY-FATIGUE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO MANY FORMATS, SO LITTLE TIME
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: moving in both the `b' business and `e' entertainment wires.
Also note italics.) 
 
 
By DAVID BLOOM 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Let's play an alphabet game, shall we?
</P>
<P>
   Way back in the old days, we listened to LPs, big circles of
black vinyl that were the medium of choice for music for most of
three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Then everything changed, and fast.
</P>
<P>
   First came eight-tracks, then cassettes, then CDs in short
order. Soon after, we had DATs and MDs, and now MP3s, Liquid Audio,
a2b, Super Audio CDs, AM, FM, satellite radio, digital radio,
Internet radio, streaming media, DVD Audio discs and even more, all
fighting for next-generation dominance of how we listen to music.
</P>
<P>
   But music is far from the only place in which this acronymic
acrimony, this techno tussling has broken out.
</P>
<P>
   Movies, TV and even books are changing so quickly we can barely
keep up with the new names and formats, much less buy the new boxes
with which to play them.
</P>
<P>
   Call it format fatigue, the endless assault of new ways to
watch, store and play the media of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is a question of overall consumer confusion.
People are saying, `Why do I need this?' '' acknowledged Jeff
Joseph, vice president for communications for the Consumer
Electronics Manufacturers Association. ``It's become particularly
acute for consumers familiar with the PC. And we certainly
understand and recognize those concerns as an industry.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all about forward progress, about finding faster, smaller,
more capacious, more convenient, more flexible, just plain better
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But how much forward progress can we stand?
</P>
<P>
   `It's an interesting question,'' said Fabian Wagmister, a UCLA
professor of film and television. ``It really goes way beyond
media, to the extent of whether humans are reaching the limits of
their appetite for consumption of new gimmicky gadgets.''
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, at a certain point, how much of a difference
can we tell between Format A and slightly better Format B?
</P>
<P>
   Richard Clark, a specialist in technology in education at the
University of Southern California, is blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need it,'' Clark said. ``A lot of the more
fine-tuning of technologies isn't of benefit to most people. It's
of incredible benefit to large organizations _ but not to the
individual user.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't even start on computers and the Internet, where
changes in formats, versions and product lifespans are so rapid as
to induce nausea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, right now, if you're not really smart and know
how to install a hundred different plug-ins and know the different
formats, you can't see anything,'' said Wagmister, who founded
UCLA's HyperMedia Studio, where students explore cutting-edge ways
to immerse viewers within new media.
</P>
<P>
   And it's only getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Software product cycles, already short at 18 months to two
years, have begun to evaporate,'' writes James Gleick in ``Faster:
The Acceleration of Just About Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gleick points out, companies continually update software with
patches, bug fixes and minor additions, sometimes within days of
issuing official major revisions. ``Dog years'' _ seven are about
equal to one human year _ have nothing on ``Internet time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital culture is perpetual innovation,'' Wagmister said.
``The only way you can make money is by creating version 2.6.1.8.
Otherwise, digital reaches a point of, `This is all I want: The
picture doesn't degrade any more, the sound is really great. What
more do I need?' And how do they make money from that?''
</P>
<P>
   More power and less cost allows us to carry around tiny digital
devices that can play music or movies, access the Internet, send
e-mail, make phone calls, track appointments and contacts or play
sophisticated games.
</P>
<P>
   But how much of this is true progress, and how much of it is a
rat's exercise wheel writ large?
</P>
<P>
   For instance, just (BEGIN ITAL)try(END ITAL) to keep your
computer software current, and on the same version as everyone with
whom you trade files. You can't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working on a paper with a former grad student who's about
to go to Thailand, and it's difficult to get our computers to talk
in the same language,'' said Bart Kosko, an information scientist
at USC and author of ``The Fuzzy Future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't just take what I e-mail, open it up and start
writing,'' Kosko said. ``He still gets something with all kinds of
artifacts and defects. If we didn't clean it up when it arrived, it
would literally be garbage after a little while. It's too difficult
for people to share information, even when they have the same
computers and the same software. That's an important market
failure. And it's likely to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   It once seemed as though everything was moving toward ``a more
comprehensive, do-it-all environment,'' Wagmister said.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened on the way to the techno-forum: We
were given more options than ever. And they don't always talk to
each other well. And you thought technology was going to make
things simpler?
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple? I don't think so, not for a long time,'' Wagmister
said. ``Both in the industry and in the market, there's lot of
confusion about what we want from this.''
</P>
<P>
   And that confusion leads to the Dark Side of technology and its
malcontents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be any man could make a tape,'' Wagmister said.
``But my wife can't even approach the stereo anymore. And there's
an overall fear of what to get next.''
</P>
<P>
   That fear has hamstrung some wonderful technological advances,
too, such as MiniDiscs, or MDs. Sony debuted the format six years
ago, but only this year does the company expect even 500,000 MD
players and recorders will be sold worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think MD seems to be very good format,'' Wagmister said.
``Yet it's not taking off. I think it's partially just plain
fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Paradox of Productivity.
</P>
<P>
   The productivity of American workers has increased at a fairly
steady rate of 2 percent to 3 percent annually for years, Kosko
said. Meanwhile, the rate of investment in technology has
skyrocketed exponentially during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did all the expenditures go?'' Kosko said. ``You could
argue that the current strong economy is a result of that
investment, though you could point to a lot of other factors as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``One possibility is the suggestion that people trade in their
computers and upgrade software too quickly,'' Kosko said.
</P>
<P>
   New computers are astonishingly powerful, even compared to those
of a few years ago. And we can say the same of other electronic
devices that are increasingly driven by the same technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have long since outstripped the chip power we need to
write letters and send e-mail,'' Kosko said. ``You see it also with
people trading in cars far more frequently than they need to. It
suggests this is more of a lifestyle change. Could it be this
fashion thing of trying to keep up? If everybody held on to their
computer twice as long, they might get more bang for their buck.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, something of a techno-skeptic who is writing a book about
human motivation, has an idea why we do this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-confidence is a big motivator,'' said Clark. ``In this
culture, control is a very big issue. People look to technology as
a boost to this personal efficacy. It gives them all kinds of
personal control.''
</P>
<P>
   That allows CEMA's Joseph to confidently proclaim: ``There will
always be markets for those who understand technology and want a
more lifelike experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph says the shift to digital formats _ turning everything
entertainment into a soup of ones and zeros _ means hope for the
future. Ultimately, a single, centralized device called a media
server will store, manage and play each home's movies, TV shows,
Internet access, music, games and more.
</P>
<P>
   The media server would be connected to speakers, monitors and
control devices throughout the house, so one person could surf the
Net, another watch a show, two others play a video game and another
order pizza and a good book.
</P>
<P>
   Companies' fears of the fallout from format fatigue have led
them to more intelligently engineer their products and create
``backward-compatible'' standards, such as for DVD, that allow new
gadgets to play old media as well as better new formats.
</P>
<P>
   But if we really wanted to ease the ache of technology's forward
leaps, Kosko said we'd call a societal timeout on new stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would increase the likelihood that standards would emerge _
and reduce problems with software by making (those standards) work
better together,'' Kosko said. ``It's like picking fruit from one
tree, leaving a lot of it on the branch as you race on to the next
one. You never get mastery of the tools. To put it into two words:
virtuosity evaporates.''
</P>
<P>
   Though we seem to have too little of it, Wagmister said the
passing of time will help ease our techno-woes, as more power
eventually translates into more ease of use, even invisibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while to know what to do with technology,''
Wagmister said. ``It took filmmaking 20 or 30 years to become what
we know it as. And right now, we're pushing technology into the
market before we know what to do with it. As a consequence, I don't
think we'll see technology making life easier for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   We had better figure this out, though, because Kosko and others
are predicting ``heaven on a chip,'' the transfer of our brain
functions to a device of some sort that mirrors what our gray
matter does in our minds. That's the last place you want to have a
little format conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that sense, there's a scary thought about interoperability
there,'' Kosko said. ``Standards are (BEGIN ITAL)really(END ITAL)
important. But I think this will all work itself out.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
___ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information on
the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail him
at davidbloomearthlink.net, or call (818) 713-3678. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
