<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ABOUT MARTHA STEWART INSTEAD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Real estate tycoon Donald Trump and right-wing
commentator Patrick Buchanan have jumped to the Reform Party,
bringing along their abundant egos and cumbersome political
baggage.
</P>
<P>
   The party deserves better. Neither one has the right stuff to
lead a third party into the White House. Or for that matter a
first, second or fourth party either.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's incoming chairman, Jack Gargan, predicts that
neither man will be its presidential nominee. Perhaps Gargan is a
wide-eyed optimist. Or perhaps he's just more realistic than either
Trump or Buchanan about their prospects.
</P>
<P>
   But if Gargan is correct, someone not yet mentioned will get the
party's nod and its $12.6 million kitty for the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have to look far. There's an obvious candidate out
there the Great Mentioner has overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   This person has what the party requires _ celebrity status,
megabucks and good, nonthreatening and sensible ideas that sell
well.
</P>
<P>
   Who else but Martha Stewart?
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. We're talking Reform Party here, not the Democratic
or Republican parties. The Reformers are a ridiculous sideshow, a
headless horseman, without her. How could it get worse?
</P>
<P>
   And there is more to this woman than embroidering a tablecloth
or basting a turkey.
</P>
<P>
   She is every bit the savvy business mogul that Trump is. When
she took her company public last week, she wound up with a mound of
stock worth $1.2 billion (that's with a b), making her one of the
richest women in the world. Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia _ her
empire of books, magazines, mail-order products, a newspaper column
and television shows _ is a fantastic money-maker built around her
personal sense of good taste. If that's not proof of executive
leadership, what is?
</P>
<P>
   She now has enough money to compete with the big boys in the
presidential sweepstakes. Trump's biggest asset is that he is rich
enough to finance the signature-gathering process necessary to get
the Reform Party on the ballot in the states where it is not. The
party is currently on the ballot in only 20 states.
</P>
<P>
   If Stewart committed some of her fortune and masterminded the
campaign the way she masterminds the running of households, she
could easily trump Trump.
</P>
<P>
   Her obsession with perfecting the art of living well is easy to
ridicule. But she'd be right at home in the Reform Party. The
biggest joke on the political stage is that big clown, the party's
only statewide elected official, Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   At least she is kidded for striving to make things look and
taste nice, not for crude comments about everything from bras to
religion.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Buchanan goes, she can compete with him in high name
recognition, one of his biggest assets. If there's anyone who
hasn't heard of her, he (it's probably a he) must live in an
unfurnished barn.
</P>
<P>
   And she has a lot better reputation than Buchanan for tolerance
and individual dignity. To her, a lifestyle decision is the color
of the bathroom paint, not a woman's agony over whether to bear an
unwanted child.
</P>
<P>
   When she talks about ``family values,'' she means the price to a
couple of investing in a good dining room chandelier. When Buchanan
talks about ``family values,'' he means imposing authoritarian
notions of conservative, outdated traditions on ordinary voters.
</P>
<P>
   So she doesn't know much about foreign policy. Neither does
Trump. Or Texas Gov. George W. Bush, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan professes to be a foreign policy expert, but his
isolationist ideas are nutty and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   So she has never held elective political office. Neither has
Trump or Buchanan. Or Ross Perot, before his two unsuccessful tries
for the presidency on the Reform Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   So she had an angry divorce. So, as the world knows, did Trump.
</P>
<P>
   So nobody knows where she stands on the burning issues of the
day _ education, gun control, tobacco taxes, campaign finance
reform, the nuclear test-ban treaty. So who cares? She looks and
sounds good on television.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart is a perfect fit for the silly Reform Party. It
would be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
