<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7963 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-GADGETS-SIDE26-COX     10-25 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GADGETS-SIDE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why do guys love gadgets?
 &HT;    By Brian D. Crecente
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you're really into gadgets, you might
not want to know why _ it isn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   According to experts, men like stuff because their fathers did,
and because when they were a kid someone probably handed them a
G.I. Joe instead of a Barbie. It's also because men like to be in
control. Oh, and don't forget that when it comes to gadgets, men
are like rats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a study with rats that showed they have a desire for
newness, for novelty in life,'' said Allen Smith, an associate
professor of marketing at Florida Atlantic University. ``That's
been demonstrated in marketing as well.''
</P>
<P>
   No one really needs most gadgets, but they seem to have an
almost magical draw on men. Smith says that's because a product
isn't just about function.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also an abstract need for a product,'' he said. ``The
curiosity, the novelty, having something unique.''
</P>
<P>
   But why men, and why some men and not others?
</P>
<P>
   David Georgoff, a professor of marketing at FAU, says a lot of
it has to do with how men are brought up and what the people who
brought them up were into.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of psychology involved,'' he said. ``There is
sex-typing that goes on as children that determines what you will
like when you grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sociologist Glenn E. Good isn't so kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are fun, they're easy to control,'' said Good, an
associate professor in the Department of Educational and Counseling
Psychology at the University of Missouri at Columbia. ``Guys like
to be in control of things, be the boss of their own little sound
system or car alarms. They have low interpersonal skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Good, past president of the Society for the Psychological Study
of Men and Masculinity, said there are deeper reasons for men's
fascination with stuff as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a controversial issue,'' he said. ``Some say it's
hard-wired into the genetics. Guys are encouraged toward gadgets
instead of relationships. And you are either into gadgets or
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Good says most gadget purchases are spurred by hype and status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they are staying home that day thinking, 'You
know, what I really need is a watch that is a phone.' It's the
hype, it's the status. It's a new thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MIDORI-VIOLIN-REVIEW-     10-25 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDORI-VIOLIN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWIRLING BIG IDEAS IN THE AIR AND SENDING THEM HOME, EFFORTLESSLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Midori is playing, a very fine line of violin
tone _ hardly more than brushed off the string and whisper-soft _
can contain a huge, bulging quantity of musical character. She
showed this essential aspect of her artistry at once on Friday
night at Carnegie Hall, in the first movement of Mozart's A Major
Sonata (K. 526). In her quietness, clarity and balance, she
respected the Classical, domestic origins of the music, but at the
same time her phrasing projected a great strength of musical
communication through the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Though well past her days as a child prodigy, she remains a
slight figure. Music, though, has no weight. She can twirl big
ideas in the air and send them rushing home to her listeners with
tremendous force.
</P>
<P>
   John Corigliano's early sonata, which she played next, provided
opportunities for varieties of color, from the superfine high notes
she extends with perfect steadiness to something like an insistent
bark. This is also much more extroverted music than Mozart's, and
she seemed to love its bravado, its humor and its Stravinskian
agility. Happily, Corigliano was in the hall to hear her.
</P>
<P>
   After intermission came Schoenberg's Phantasy, which was
beautifully and meaningfully played both by Midori and by her
accompanist, Robert McDonald. Here the composer, near the end of
his life, seems to have been remembering the nightmare fantastical
world of his ``Pierrot Lunaire,'' and McDonald reacted
appropriately with brilliant, moonlit passages at the top of the
instrument and vivid changes of nuance. Meanwhile Midori was making
the violin part an intensely expressive declamation in different
registers, and the music was further helped on its way by the
immediacy with which the two players would come together _ or fly
apart _ at sudden moments.
</P>
<P>
   This was a remarkable performance, but so too was that of
Franck's sonata at the end. Midori made the opening melody so
gentle, so fragile, you almost did not want to hear it for fear it
would break in your ears. But music is tough as well as weightless.
For as long as the sonata went on in this vein _ and again when it
returned to similar material _ Midori kept up her fingertip
handling, and yet, as in the Mozart, her musical expression was
sure and large. There was a touching sense that much more was being
implied than could be said, that here was someone smiling through
tears _ or weeping through laughter. The ambiguity was complete,
and right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
