r f BC-GADGETS26-COX     10-25 2016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GADGETS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10 gadgets to keep any guy happy
 &HT;    By Brian D. Crecente
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Splitting atoms? Cloning sheep? Bah! Why
waste technology pursuing knowledge when you can make the James
Bond fantasies of every warm-blooded male come true with
microchips, miniaturization and gizmos galore? We're not talking
Dick Tracy watches and pocket telescopes. We're talking techno toys
that will bathe you in virtual reality, keep you wired 24/7 and do
your laundry and sweep your floor. To help you zero in on the stuff
no one really needs but everyone would love to have, we've waded
through the gazillion gadgets in circulation today to come up with
10 that have one thing in common:
</P>
<P>
   They are so cool, they make guys drool.
</P>
<P>
   I-GLASSES
</P>
<P>
   Who needs a big-screen TV when you can wear a virtual theater on
your head? I-O Display Systems' 8-ounce i-glasses will adorn your
noggin with adjustable earphones and two 0.7-inch displays that
create the illusion of watching an 80-inch screen floating about 11
feet in front of your face. You can plug them into a television,
VCR, cable or video game console. For an extra $1,000, you can get
the Televizer package, which includes the i-glasses and a Panasonic
P-10 portable DVD player and a carrying case.
</P>
<P>
   What it costs: $499 for just the i-glasses, $1,499 for the
Televizer package.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy it: online at www.i-glasses.com.
</P>
<P>
   Why you've gotta have it: Obviously, so you can sit in the
corner and rock yourself into a high-definition stupor while
watching an 80-inch screen no one else can see.
</P>
<P>
   WEARABLE COMPUTER
</P>
<P>
   The lights are low. Soft music is playing. Time to slip into
something a little more comfortable? Nah. Time to strap on this
awesome hunk of hardware and surf the World Wide Web all night.
</P>
<P>
   The Xybernaut wearable computer features a 233 megahertz
computer with a 4 gig hard drive and 128 megs of RAM. It lets you
send and receive live video through an eyepiece and a head-mounted
camera. It gives you full Internet access anywhere, anytime via
cell phone uplink, and allows you to type the next ``War and
Peace'' (or dictate it into a microphone) while jogging through the
park. Here's how it works: A keyboard straps to your wrist. A
battery-powered, 28-ounce computer slips onto a belt and hooks up
to a headset, which includes a miniature video camera mounted above
one eye, a tiny display contraption above the other eye, and a
microphone at your mouth. A separate wrist-mounted monitor can also
be connected to the computer, as can a cell phone and a plethora of
other goodies.
</P>
<P>
   What it costs: From $5,000 to $10,000, depending on what bells
and whistles you get.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy it: www.xybernaut.com, or wait a year, when a
lighter, better and cheaper version is expected to be released to
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Why you've gotta have it: Cut the grass and defragment your hard
drive at the same time! Dash to the fridge without putting the game
on pause! Best of all: It's not just a computer, it's a fashion
statement. INTERNET WATCH
</P>
<P>
   New kind of watch? Yawn. New way of telling time? Now you've got
our attention.
</P>
<P>
   Swatch has invented Internet time. It took the standard 24-hour
day and divided it into 1,000 beats. Each beat is equivalent to 1
minute and 26.4 seconds, with the meridian in Biel, Switzerland,
world headquarters of Swatch. So when you're wearing the Swatch
Beat watch, the Internet day begins (at)000, or midnight Biel Mean
Time, and runs through 999. That means no more time-zone trauma:
When you and Aussiegal agree to a Diablo deathmatch (at)539, you'll
both know exactly what time to show up.
</P>
<P>
   The Swatch Beat also allows you to protect your e-mail downloads
using a microchip embedded in the watch and a special mousepad.
When the watch comes in contact with the mousepad, the computer
automatically downloads your e-mail. If your chip doesn't match-up,
then no e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   What it costs: The standard Swatch Beat watch costs $70 and the
Swatch Access Beat Watch (with mousepad) is expected to cost $160.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy it: Most upscale watch stores, but the Swatch
Access Beat Watch isn't expected until the end of the year. Check
www.swatch.com for more info.
</P>
<P>
   Why you've gotta have it: No cyber-junkie should do without this
cool little timepiece, which also happens to feature a fixed
countdown to the Year 2K. Once the year 2000 hits, you can
reprogram the timer to countdown to whatever you want, assuming we
are all still here ...
</P>
<P>
   SEGA DREAMCAST
</P>
<P>
   The battle between video game consoles and computers has been
tooth-and-nail, but Sega's Dreamcast ends all that by combining the
two. The bulky little game console comes with artificial
intelligence, a 56k modem and Web browsing software so you can play
a game on the Net with your buddy or use it to send and receive
e-mail. Before you know it, the Dreamcast will be doing what it
does best: Sucking away your will to socialize, until life becomes
a blur of mind-numbing eye-candy and booming digital sound.
</P>
<P>
   What it costs: $199.99
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy it: Go to any toy or electronic story and wait for
the next shipment to come in.
</P>
<P>
   Why you've gotta have it: It, um, stimulates right-brain
activity and helps develop eye-hand coordination. (It also happens
to be the slickest, fastest, most intelligent gaming system to see
the light of day. Who needs a computer?)
</P>
<P>
   HAL2000
</P>
<P>
   Kick back and boss your house around with the latest in
automated living systems from Home Automated Living. The HAL2000
uses voice recognition and your home's existing wiring to control
the thermostat, lighting, electrical appliances and security
system. The system keeps track of to-do lists and appointments, and
will even hop on the Internet to answer your questions. Don't
bother with the Weather Channel, just ask your house if it's gonna
rain! HAL uses your Internet connection to hook-up and retrieve TV
listings, e-mail, stock information, news, sports and traffic
reports. You talk to Hal through a microphone connected to its
computer, or by picking up any phone in the house. You can also
call in while you're away and tell your house what to do. Just
don't try to unplug HAL once it's up and running. I'm afraid that's
something I cannot allow to happen.
</P>
<P>
   What it costs: The basic HAL2000 unit costs $389. Add-ons run
from $8 to $249.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy it: Online at www.automatedliving.com.
</P>
<P>
   Why you've gotta have it: Think of the money you'll save having
HAL around to turn off the hall light. (For a gadget geek, it
doesn't get any better than a talking house that does your
bidding.)
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL ROBOT
</P>
<P>
   George Jetson had one, why not you? This 5-inch-tall,
16-inch-wide midget machine named Cye, will vacuum your floors,
deliver the mail and act like a robotic pup. The wheeled tyke from
Probotics Inc., resembles a dustpan and is controlled by your PC
via a wireless link. You can use your mouse to guide the bot
through the house, or let it explore on its own. A point-and-click
map shows you where the robot is and what areas have been explored.
You can also program it for automatic tasks, like vacuuming the
house when the in-laws are coming over for dinner. So what if it
can't mix a martini or swing its arms about wildly and shout
``Danger Will Robinson!'' (it doesn't even have arms). You'll still
have the niftiest robot on your block.
</P>
<P>
   What it costs: $695; a vacuum attachment or wagon will run you
an additional $89 each.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy it: It's available at www.personalrobots.com now,
but not yet in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Why you've gotta have it: Not only will this puppy take the
drudgery out of those daily household chores, it'll take the
drudgery out of your life by letting you chase the cat, close and
open every door in the house over and over again, and four-wheel up
that couch you just bought.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH PHONE
</P>
<P>
   Keeping time has been so overdone, what's a poor watch to do?
Become a cell phone, of course. The SwatchTalk looks like a normal
wristwatch, but 12 inconspicuous buttons around its outer edge and
a hidden microphone and speaker turn it into a watch that would
make Maxwell Smart jealous. A digital display lets you see what
number you're calling, and a ring lets you know when it's time to
answer your watch. Swatch promises that the speakers and microphone
are loud enough to be used without taking the watch off your wrist.
SwatchTalk comes with a charger that will give your watch enough
power to last a ``reasonable'' day.
</P>
<P>
   What it costs: Will list for about $350.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy it: You can't. Swatch is working on extending the
battery life and making it compatible with mobile phone standards
in the U.S. and elsewhere. Look for it in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Why you've gotta have it: The convenience of cellular technology
without the inconvenience of keeping track of a cell phone.
Besides, now you'll be able to talk into your watch and, this time,
someone will be able to hear you on the other end. Dick Tracy out!
</P>
<P>
   TWO-WAY DIGITAL CAMERA RADIO
</P>
<P>
   Whatever kick-started our fascination with two-way radios as
kids, it sunk its hooks in deep. Even in adulthood, most of us
can't walk past a Radio Shack without peering through the window,
trying to catch a glimpse of a walkie talkie. Now there's something
new for clunky transceivers: video. The folks at Kenwood have come
up with a digital camera you can pop onto most major two-ways and
use to capture, store and display up to nine pictures and then
transmit them to another similarly equipped rig in about 30 seconds
over the air.
</P>
<P>
   What it costs: The KVT-10 costs $835; check www.kenwood.net for
info.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy it: Most electronics stores.
</P>
<P>
   Why you've gotta have it: Boss doesn't believe your car broke
down? Send him a picture of your smoldering hood, and don't forget
to add a smile and thumbs up to your 10-4 good buddy.
</P>
<P>
   THE VISOR
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know, only guys in three-piece suits buy palmtop
computers like the Palm Pilot. I mean who wants to sit there with
their tongue half-stuck out for 15 minutes trying to spell some
corporate contact's name with a plastic stylus and Pilot-letters
when you can just grab a pen and jot it down on the palm of your
hand? But what if you could get a palmtop in a bunch of cool colors
and, when your boss isn't looking, pop in a game cartridge or
digital music player? Now you're talking useful. And who needs the
12,000 addresses, 10 years of appointments and 400 e-mail messages
the Visor holds when you also can use the thing as a universal
remote or pager? Now that's cool.
</P>
<P>
   What it costs: $149 to $249. Expansion modules run from $29 to
$129.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy it: Online at www.handspring.com; coming to stores
by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Why you've gotta have it: Here's just a few things you can turn
this palmtop into using the expansion slot: pager, virtual map,
reference library, modem, mp3 player, keyboard, voice recorder,
dictionary, universal remote, digital camera. And it still fits in
your shirt pocket.
</P>
<P>
   PORTABLE DVD PLAYER
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being able to carry around a high-definition film fest
in your briefcase. Suddenly, long waits become a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   A few companies are working on the portable DVD player, but
Panasonic was the first to bring it to the store. At just under 2
pounds, the PalmTheater opens up like a clam shell to reveal a
5.8-inch monitor and two built-in speakers. The paperback-sized
player can show three hours of movies on one battery charge in
either standard or wide-screen modes. Even better: You can plug the
player into your television at home and use it like a standard DVD
player.
</P>
<P>
   What it costs: $1099.95; check www.panasonic.com for more info.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy it: Most electronics stores.
</P>
<P>
   Why you've gotta have it: You, reclined on the couch, bag of
chips near one hand, bottle of beer near other, a mini-movie
theater propped on your belly playing a high-definition version of
``Armageddon.'' Need we say more?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
