<HEADER>
A7968 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-PROFILE-4000(4TA     10-25 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-4000(4TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BUSINESS, BUSH HAS REFINED HIS KNACK FOR BIG LEAGUE POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN and MEDE NIX 
c.1990 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was George W. Bush's first big decision as owner of the Texas
Rangers, a call that might alter the franchise and perhaps his
political future.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, a year after his group bought the team, Bush was
pondering plans for a new baseball stadium. One of his partners
suggested that the team look outside of Arlington and hold an
auction among local cities, a tactic often used by sports owners to
wrest expensive concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush argued against it. Since gaining control of the Rangers, he
had told Arlington leaders that their city would get first crack at
a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it wasn't right to hold a gun to anybody's head,''
said Tom Schieffer, a partner who would lead the Rangers' efforts
to build the new park. ``He was very good at building a consensus,
and that decision has George's fingerprints all over it.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked, financially and politically. Arlington
voters approved a sales tax increase for a new stadium, the value
of the franchise soared, and Bush avoided the political fallout of
a bitter bidding war among North Texas cities.
</P>
<P>
   The building of The Ballpark in Arlington was Bush's biggest
victory in business, turning around what had been an unimpressive
career in the oil industry. Seven months after The Ballpark opened
in 1994, Bush won the Texas governor's race, and last year he
became a multimillionaire when the team was sold.
</P>
<P>
   The events surrounding The Ballpark are worth recounting because
they tell much about the man who would be president. Even as a
businessman, Bush's strength was in politics.
</P>
<P>
   From his lesser-known struggles in the oil patch to his
high-profile years with the Rangers, Bush made his impact by
connecting with people, associates say. Rather than riding to the
top by specializing in high finance or by reshaping an industry,
Bush scored by courting investors, striking deals and handling the
public side of his enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he benefited from the help of powerful allies and
the connections of his influential family.
</P>
<P>
   As the first son of a president, the grandson of a U.S. senator
and a graduate of Yale University and Harvard Business School, Bush
is part of a far-reaching business and social network that has
helped him throughout his life. From an uncle on Wall Street who
raised money for his oil patch start-up to family ties that helped
with his purchase of the Rangers, personal contacts provided
crucial help in Bush's business career.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, some of those same people are now raising
money for his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the door of opportunity was always open for a
guy named Bush,'' said Ed Martin, a Democratic Party consultant who
worked for Gov. Ann Richards in her failed 1994 re-election
campaign against Bush. ``Most people realize that this happens
every day in America's corporate culture. But he's not living the
life that most of us are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is 53, readily acknowledges that he has had
advantages. As important, he says, is that he made the most of
those chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident there have been a lot of first-born sons who
have had famous names who have been miserable failures in life,''
Bush said in an interview with the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   His results in the business world were mixed. During a decade as
an oilman, from the mid-'70s to the mid-'80s, Bush lost millions of
investors' dollars before reversing his fortunes in baseball.
Still, as he campaigns for the White House, he can claim that he
met a payroll in two industries, weathered tough times in business
and produced a winning bottom line with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question,'' said Cal Jillson, a political analyst at
Southern Methodist University in Dallas, ``is how much of George W.
Bush's success is due to his individual effort and how much is due
to the network from which he comes?''
</P>
<P>
   Business colleagues say that Bush worked for what he got,
describing him as an active executive who went to the office every
day and participated in key decisions.
</P>
<P>
   As an oilman, he raised money and built a company from zero to
15 employees. In Midland, he was seen as a hands-on operator who
could be trusted to drill wells for out-of-town investors.
</P>
<P>
   As a baseball owner, he was the public face of an organization
in the news every day and represented the Rangers at Major League
Baseball meetings. He worked closely with Richard Greene, who was
then Arlington mayor, and Schieffer to win voter support for a
sales tax increase to build The Ballpark. Behind the scenes, he led
quarterly meetings and maintained harmony among a group of 30
limited partners.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders may not have realized his impact, Schieffer says,
because Bush delegated authority and rarely second-guessed his
employees. But he says that should not diminish Bush's achievement:
He headed a sports franchise during controversial times and emerged
as a popular figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of sports owners,'' Schieffer said, ``who
couldn't get elected dog catcher.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
