<HEADER>
A7972 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-PROFILE-2ndTake-     10-25 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: dog catcher.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, at a news conference in Arlington, Eddie Chiles
introduced George W. Bush as the buyer of his Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``George is our kind of people,'' Chiles said. ``Texas people.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiles had known Bush for four decades and, when George was a
child, had let the Bush family use his private plane to fly Bush's
little sister to New York for cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   While other investors were clamoring for a chance to buy the
team, Bush said he had an inside track because Chiles was
``family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The other groups, in my opinion, never had a chance,'' Bush
said. ``Maybe it was an unfair advantage that I've known Eddie
since I was 3 years old. Too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has often been on the right side of that equation. From the
oil patch to the Rangers to his campaign for the presidency, he has
been boosted by friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   His uncle Jonathan often helped him raise drilling funds for his
oil ventures in Midland. A prominent Wall Street executive,
Jonathan Bush tapped industry leaders, including George Ball of
E.F. Hutton and William Draper III of the Export-Import Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Philip Uzielli _ a close friend of James A. Baker III,
who was later secretary of state under Bush's father _ put up a
crucial $1 million when his oil company needed cash.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, Bush benefited from more than just the Chiles
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Bush first considered a bid for the Rangers after receiving a
phone call from Bill DeWitt Jr., another man from a powerful
family. DeWitt's father was the former owner of the Cincinnati Reds
and a close friend of another Bush uncle in St. Louis. Four years
earlier, when Bush's oil company was struggling to raise money,
DeWitt's oil firm stepped up and offered a merger that strengthened
both operations.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling together in the mid-'80s on oil business, Bush and
DeWitt talked about running a baseball team. Soon after Bush's
father was elected president in 1988, DeWitt called and suggested
they put together a group to buy the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Chiles' health and finances were faltering. He had
tried to sell the Rangers to Ed Gaylord, a broadcast mogul in
Oklahoma City, and then Frank Marsoni, a Tampa, Fla., car dealer.
But baseball owners opposed them, fearing that Gaylord might use
the team to anchor a TV superstation and that Marsoni would move
the Rangers to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush emerged as a potential buyer, several people in
baseball were thrilled, says Bobby Brown, then the president of the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was seen as an affable, honest guy who respected the game
and its traditions, Brown says. His father was also a big fan who
had been captain of his Yale baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel that the president had any direct bearing on the
negotiations,'' Brown said about the sale to the Bush-led group.
``But obviously, if you have someone with that name and his
father's the president, that doesn't hurt you. I think everybody
realized that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had to hustle to make it happen. He started by calling on
Chiles soon after Gaylord and Marsoni dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the first guy to knock on the door and I kept
knocking,'' Bush said, knowing that others planned to bid on the
Rangers. ``Eddie realized I would be a good steward of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognized this wasn't just an asset of Eddie Chiles. This
was something he loved a lot and I convinced him I would love it a
lot, too.''
</P>
<P>
   To raise money, Bush reached out to classmates from Yale, such
as Roland Betts, and to partners from the oil industry, such as
DeWitt. Some of his father's friends, including former campaign
manager Frederick Malek, were among more than 70 people who
invested.
</P>
<P>
   Bush still needed a big boost from Peter Ueberroth, then
commissioner of baseball. Ueberroth wanted the Bush group to have
more investors from Texas, believing it would ensure that the team
remained in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Ueberroth personally called on Richard Rainwater at his Fort
Worth office. He persuaded the financier to join the group, even
though Rainwater had rejected a similar appeal from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Rainwater brought in Rusty Rose of Dallas, and the two renowned
investors contributed more than $6 million, about 10 times the
amount that Bush put in.
</P>
<P>
   Rose would be the point man for finance, while Bush would handle
the public part of the business, including dealing with reporters,
other owners and fans.
</P>
<P>
   Rainwater and Rose declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Through James Langdon, a friend in Washington, Bush recruited
Schieffer, a Fort Worth lawyer who had teamed with a competing
bidder. Bush needed Schieffer's $1.4 million investment, but he
also wanted to add another Fort Worth voice.
</P>
<P>
   The Schieffer call paid dividends, because he eventually became
part of the executive team. Bush and Rose later chose Schieffer to
be team president and oversee construction of The Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush left for Austin at the end of '94, Schieffer assumed
Bush's role as managing general partner, along with his six-figure
salary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said that his Rangers' tenure represents the crowning
achievement of his business life. His group bought the team for the
equivalent of $86 million in April 1989. Nine years later, with The
Ballpark firmly established as a top facility and the team's record
improving, the franchise and surrounding property fetched $250
million from Dallas financier Tom Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
