<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7973 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-PROFILE-3rdTake-     10-25 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Tom Hicks. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For buying and leading the team, Bush earned $15 million on an
investment of $606,000. Another $1 million to $2 million may come
later, when all accounts are closed.
</P>
<P>
   The big payday stems from a provision that funneled 15 percent
of the investment's capital gains into ``back-end bonuses.'' Bush
received two-thirds of that money and Rose the other third because
they served as managing partners and put more hours into the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also received a higher share for pulling together the
purchase, and got the full bonus even though he gave up the top job
four years earlier to be governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was the catalyst,'' Schieffer said. ``If George wasn't
there, I don't think it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ON-HAND OPERATOR
</P>
<P>
   Jim McAninch remembers the time he called Bush at home at about
4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   It was the mid-'80s in Midland, and one of their wells had come
in unexpectedly. McAninch, Bush's oilfield engineer for four years,
needed the boss' OK to rush in four tank cars.
</P>
<P>
   They talked it over and Bush gave the go-ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was George's company and he ran it that way,'' McAninch
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a businessman, Bush was more than just a famous name,
colleagues say. Both in oil and baseball, he is described as a
visible, hands-on executive who mixed with employees.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is primarily known for raising money in the oil patch and
for pulling together the Rangers' purchase. But in Midland in 1984,
DeWitt's Spectrum 7 Exploration sought out Bush for his operating
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Spectrum, whose owners were based in Cincinnati, had raised
nearly $6 million and was looking to drill in West Texas. When
owner DeWitt asked his sole Texas employee, geologist Paul Rea, to
suggest a partner to provide drilling sites and oil workers, he
proposed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Rea and Bush had been friends since 1975, and Rea trusted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at deals in the oil business, the character of a
person is important,'' Rea said. ``A lot of deals are done on a
handshake, and the paperwork comes in a few weeks later. I knew
that George was completely honest.''
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, Bush also took an active, visible role. He shunned
the owner's private box near the upper deck and sat behind the
dugout so he could mingle with fans and get a better view of the
action.
</P>
<P>
   He helped sell season tickets by making cold calls to
prospective customers. He frequently spoke Spanish with Latin
players, foreshadowing how he would later use language to reach
Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, as he campaigns for president, Bush fondly recalls
his Arlington days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was realizing a dream,'' Bush said during a recent stop in
New Orleans. ``It was a really good part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWitt, Hicks and others credit Bush with improving the
franchise. DeWitt, now chairman of the St. Louis Cardinals, says
that Bush developed a good relationship with Rose, the finance man,
and had the foresight to tap Schieffer for a key role.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 1994 baseball strike, the ownership group never had
to make ``a capital call,'' seeking more money to keep the team
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason that the Rangers have come into prominence as
one of the premier franchises today,'' DeWitt said. ``A lot of it
is due to George's leadership during the early years.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWitt says that Bush's ultimate achievement was completing The
Ballpark without a major incident or scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Greene, now associate publisher of the Arlington
Star-Telegram, was mayor of Arlington during the stadium election.
Bush, Rose, Schieffer and Greene developed the proposal for a
half-cent sales tax increase to provide $135 million toward The
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Greene says that city officials took the lead role in selling
the proposal, but that Bush and Schieffer often participated.
Greene recalls the time that Bush appeared on a live TV show to
debate the merits of the referendum. Bush also appeared on radio
talk shows and made personal appearances, including at area
churches.
</P>
<P>
   On election day, he visited phone centers to encourage workers
who were trying to get voters out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did everything we asked him to do,'' Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest turnout in Arlington history, the proposal passed
by a 2-to-1 margin in January 1991. Opponents criticized the idea
of subsidizing wealthy baseball owners, but the overwhelming
victory silenced many critics and dispelled any lingering acrimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody felt that the other party was getting jobbed,'' said
Brown, the former American League president who now lives in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Bush used his Rangers' post as a public relations
platform, recalling how he would sign autographs on glossy photos
provided at the stadium. Others believe Bush, who regularly met
with reporters and fans before home games, was simply being
accessible and accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really respected the fact that he always sat in the front
row at the ballpark, whether we were doing well or not doing
well,'' said Nolan Ryan, the Hall-of-Fame pitcher who joined the
team just before the Bush group took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting with the fans, he didn't hide; he always signed
autographs and talked about the team,'' Ryan said. ``I think the
fans realized he was a baseball fan and was committed to doing
everything he could to make the Rangers a top-notch organization.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
