<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-PROFILE-4thTake-     10-25 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-4thTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: top-notch organization.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Employees say that Bush gained their respect by declining to
duck the public when the team was struggling. Tom Grieve, general
manager during the Bush years and now a Rangers announcer, recalls
when fans would boo him and Bush during losing streaks. They
especially criticized Bush for not spending more to attract free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Grieve says Bush would often walk from his stadium seat to the
angry fans, greet them with a smile and handshake, and start
talking baseball. That usually defused the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took the heat, boy, more than any of us,'' Grieve said.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICIAN'S SKILL
</P>
<P>
   As a baseball owner, Bush showed a politician's skill at
sidestepping some controversies. At other times, he was willing to
speak out.
</P>
<P>
   When The Ballpark was being built and minority companies said
that they weren't getting their share of contracts, Bush deferred
the dispute to Schieffer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when he was campaigning for Texas governor, baseball
players went on strike and Bush declined to discuss the issues that
were ripping apart the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agreed that it was more important for George to be
talking about what he wanted to do for the schoolchildren of
Texas,'' Schieffer said, even though Bush still held the title of
managing general partner.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer, rather than Bush, became the target for angry players
and fans. When the owners tried to use replacement players the next
spring _ and the plan failed dismally _ Bush was living in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   At Major League Baseball meetings, Bush wasn't shy about voting
against the tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to tell people what I think,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He battled other owners over the decision to oust Fay Vincent as
commissioner. He argued that expansion fees from the National
League should be shared with the American League and won some
concessions, with the Rangers and other American League teams each
receiving $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush was the lone opponent to league realignment, which
lumped teams into six divisions and expanded the playoffs. After
many heated discussions, Bush was told that the Rangers would cast
the first vote on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush jutted out his jaw defiantly, according to Schieffer, and
said, ``Good. I want everybody to know we're a `No.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The owners overruled him, 27 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mind expressing my opinions, and I still don't,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown says that owners appreciated Bush's directness, and that
things never got personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never left as enemies,'' Brown said. ``George always had
the ability to disagree without being disagreeable.''
</P>
<P>
   In quarterly meetings with the Rangers' limited partners, Bush
and Grieve were often challenged about the team's performance. One
owner harped on the disastrous trade that sent Sammy Sosa and
pitcher Wilson Alvarez to the White Sox for designated hitter
Harold Baines. Sosa, then one of the team's most promising
youngsters, went on to become a top slugger and national celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   The internal complaints never became public, and for that, many
credit Bush. Brown says it's tough to keep harmony among wealthy
executives who usually believe they know the answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things the American male thinks he can do better
than anybody else,'' Brown said. ``One is barbecue a steak; the
other is manage a big league baseball team.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, when Bush took over the Rangers, the club was
known for scrimping on salaries and passing on highly paid
athletes. But The Ballpark changed all that, generating enough
revenue to let the Rangers now boast one of the league's highest
payrolls. With some of the brightest stars in baseball, the team
has won three division crowns since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the first four years under Bush, the Rangers' attendance grew
42 percent, helped in large part by Ryan's huge appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when The Ballpark opened, the team was on pace to
attract 3 million fans, compared with 1.58 million in 1988, the
year before Bush took over. But with two months remaining, the
players' strike canceled the season.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the Rangers soared from $28.8 million in 1988 to
$62.4 million in '93. When the strike hit, the team was on pace to
approach $80 million in revenue. This year, the team brought in
more than $110 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, including Bush's friend Betts, have said that Bush
pursued the Rangers because the team could propel his political
career. In the early '90s, Bush frequently toured Texas to promote
the Rangers and raise money for Republican candidates. But he was
irritated when reporters suggested that he was biding time, waiting
for politics to call.
</P>
<P>
   Bush twice corrected a Star-Telegram sportswriter for calling
him a politician in print; Bush insisted that he should be
described as a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   He still wants to evoke that image of his earlier days. On the
campaign trail, Bush dismissed Betts' view, saying he was neither
that calculating nor that focused on politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little more entrepreneurial than that,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Jay Root and T.R. Sullivan contributed to this
report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
