<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7976 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx14;  BC-BUSH-OILPATCH-TEX     10-25 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-OILPATCH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER DEALS KEPT BUSH AFLOAT IN TURBULENT OIL PATCH OF '80S 
(ACCOMPANIES BUSH-PROFILE)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush didn't hit a home run in the oil patch, but he
didn't strike out either.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of 10 years, Bush's oil company never hit the
big gusher and lost millions of investors' dollars during one of
the most turbulent times in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But faced with mounting losses, Bush twice engineered merger
deals with better-financed companies, which ultimately gave him
more than $800,000 to launch a purchase of the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Given the tumultuous times, ``I think I was a success in the oil
business,'' Bush said in an earlier interview.
</P>
<P>
   Bush learned the oil business from the ground up, returning to
West Texas in 1975 after graduating from Harvard Business School.
He negotiated land leases, took classes on geology, raised drilling
funds and built a small company.
</P>
<P>
   With his pedigree and contacts, he could have chosen a less
risky, morelucrative career, says political analyst Cal Jillson of
Southern Methodist University in Dallas. But Bush chose to follow
the same path as his father a generation earlier in the
rough-and-tumble oil patch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in his business life, George really wanted to make it on
his own,'' Jillson said. ``He made a real run for it in Midland.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, his results tracked the oil industry. He was a
millionaire on paper by early 1982, when prices were soaring. But
the bust quickly cut his fortune in half.
</P>
<P>
   From 1979 to 1984, Bush raised $4.7 million from investors. His
firm, initially called Arbusto Energy and later Bush Exploration,
returned just $1.55 million to backers, according to company
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also got tax write-offs of $3.3 million, benefiting
from tax laws that encouraged domestic exploration. Bush, as top
executive, was paid $75,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did all the right things,'' said K. Michael Conaway, Bush's
chief financial officer for five years in Midland. ``We just
weren't lucky enough to find oil and gas.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also suffered from poor timing. On July 28, 1982,
Bush's partnership tried to raise $6 million with a public
offering. But the first wave of the oil bust had hit about three
weeks earlier, and he raised only $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush found 28,000 barrels of oil at a cost of $36 a barrel, six
times the average cost in the industry, according to documents. The
following year, Bush wrote off half of his investors' money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bust,'' Bush acknowledged in a 1994 interview with
the Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Bush had more than 15 employees and, with his poor
drilling record, few prospects for raising more money. Conaway says
Bush imposed a 10-percent cut in salaries for everyone, including
himself.
</P>
<P>
   A more promising solution surfaced when Ohio businessman Bill
DeWitt Jr. inquired about a merger. Like Bush, DeWitt was from a
wealthy family. His father had been friends with a Bush uncle in
St. Louis many years earlier. Now DeWitt was looking for an
operating oil firm to join his Spectrum 7 Exploration venture.
</P>
<P>
   The companies merged in a stock swap. Bush received about 16
percent of the stock in the new company and was named chief
executive of Spectrum 7. Geologist Paul Rea, Spectrum's only
employee in Midland, became president.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the price of oil plunged from $29 a barrel to $10 in
four months, and hundreds of wells were being closed nationwide.
Spectrum recorded growing losses and stood at a crossroads. Bush
decided Spectrum either had to get bigger or be bought out.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to find an acquisition candidate, Conaway said, Bush
jumped at the chance to sell out to Harken Energy, a publicly
traded company that was buying up troubled competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Harken, then based in a Fort Worth suburb, offered stock valued
at $2.25 million. That represented a premium over Spectrum's book
value of $1.8 million, but Rea said the company's assets included
drilling prospects valued at zero on the books.
</P>
<P>
   Like most oil stocks, Harken's shares were depressed at the
time. Monte Swetnam, who later became president of Harken
Exploration, said the stock deal ``was like trading two dogs valued
at $500 each for a cat valued at $1,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the sale, Bush gained a seat on Harken's board, stock
options and a consulting role that paid him up to $120,000, plus
benefits. Supporters say that he brought broad experience to the
Harken role, having weathered the industry for 10 turbulent years.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, oil prices had stabilized and Harken's stock price had
improved. Bush sold nearly all his Harken holdings for $848,560.
</P>
<P>
   Rea says that Bush did well, considering the energy collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we got something,'' Rea said. ``George hung in there
and didn't go under. He was a survivor during the toughest times,
and not many were.''
</P>
<P>
   Swetnam said that Harken had offered board seats to executives
of other acquired firms and that the company did not hire Bush for
his connections, including to his father, then vice president.
Swetnam said he could not recall any producing properties that
resulted from a Bush lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bush came under scrutiny in 1990 for two Harken matters: failing
to promptly report the sale of his Harken stock, and the awarding
to Harken of a drilling contact with Bahrain in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that he filed the necessary documents reporting the
Harken stock sale but that the Securities and Exchange Commission
must have lost the report. The SEC eventually dropped the matter.
</P>
<P>
   On the Bahrain contract, media outlets investigated whether
Harken was selected because the emirate wanted to curry favor with
Bush's father, then president. Swetnam said he met with reporters
from Newsweek, Time and The Wall Street Journal because they were
investigating the connection between Bush and the contract. Harken
had never drilled a deep well in that part of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But Swetnam, who negotiated the contract, said that neither Bush
nor his father played any role in the talks, and media reports did
not dispute that account. Swetnam said Bush was actually the only
Harken board member to oppose the project. The rest of the board
disagreed, and Swetnam later struck a partnership with the Bass
brothers of Fort Worth to provide financing and drilling expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Harken drilled two wells near Bahrain, but both were dry holes.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Todd Mason and Max B. Baker contributed to this
report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
