<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7977 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-BALLPARK-TEX     10-25 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BALLPARK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CRITICIZED OVER HANDLING OF MINORITY CONTRACTS FOR BALLPARK 
(ACCOMPANIES BUSH-PROFILE)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MEDE NIX 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ While he enjoyed a near trouble-free reign as
an owner of the Texas Rangers, George W. Bush was criticized for
how the team handled minority contracts at the The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Arlington City Council agreed to rely on the Rangers to
encourage diverse and local participation in the ballpark's
construction. The council did not insist on quotas or contracting
goals for companies owned by minorities, women or local
businesspeople.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1993, minority groups complained that they were not
benefiting from the project as Bush had promised during the
campaign for voter approval of a half-cent sales tax. Some remain
bitter today, recalling how Bush visited black churches and asked
for their support at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of minorities were questioning where they would fit into
the project,'' said Harry Gudger, former president of the Arlington
branch of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People. ``He stated that minorities would get a part of that. As
things started unfolding, there was an exclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Comer Cottrell, a Bush partner in ownership of the Rangers and
well-known African-American businessman, also criticized the team's
handling of minority contracting.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said in July 1993 that minority firms won many of the
contracts that they bid on. He said the Rangers could not be blamed
if more minorities and women didn't try to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people don't want to bid, we can't force them to bid; we
can do our best to get them to bid,'' Bush told the Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bush avoided much of the debate, especially when it
became heated. He deferred to Tom Schieffer, who was Rangers
president and responsible for letting the contracts. Near the peak
of the controversy, Bush and Schieffer hired Norman Lyons, an
African-American businessman who was active in civic affairs, for
the new position of vice president of community relations.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons then began working with minority contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush was amazingly silent'' when it came to pushing for
these groups, said Luther Felder, then pastor of Grace United
Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was part owner and he was in charge,'' Felder said. ``But
he wasn't able or didn't try to change that project to make it
inclusive of the minority contractors.''
</P>
<P>
   Minority- or women-owned businesses bid on $20 million worth of
contracts on the $193 million project and won $9 million, Lyons
said.
</P>
<P>
   The total was about 5 percent. That compares with about 30
percent minority contracting for Lone Star Park in Grand Prairie,
and a 25 percent goal proposed for the new arena in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to get more people to bid,'' Lyons said. ``This
is not an excuse, but in some cases, like seats, there were only
one or two companies in the U.S. who did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other minority- or women-owned firms couldn't win contracts
because they couldn't do the work in the short time frames required
by the team, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons said that in September 1993, shortly after he was hired
and in the midst of the flap over construction contracts, 5,000
small and midsize minority- and women-owned companies were
contacted about bidding on remaining contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The ballpark concessionaire, Sportservice, also sought minority-
or women-owned businesses as suppliers, Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also determined that minority workers made up 71.5
percent of those who worked on the ballpark project and accounted
for about $20 million in payroll during that time, Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
