<SLUG> BC-PINOCCHIO-DVD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOU WISH UPON A DVD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By ROB LOWMAN 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was Walt Disney's second full-length animated
feature, and Tuesday it becomes the first of his classics to be
released on DVD. Some have argued that the 1940 ``Pinocchio'' was
the studio's greatest achievement.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Disney used groundbreaking animation techniques to
create ``Pinocchio,'' including the multiplane camera, which allows
for the illusion that the camera is moving through a scene as
though it were live action. It took some 750 artists to produce 2
million drawings for the 88-minute film, and the texture and
richness of the animation is still unsurpassed.
</P>
<P>
   But all this wizardry would be a cinematic footnote if it
weren't for the enduring and endearing quality of the storytelling.
The tale of the wooden puppet who is given life has entertained
countless children through the years, but it's the story's moral
underpinnings that give it resonance.
</P>
<P>
   To become a real boy, Pinocchio (Dick Jones) is told by the Blue
Fairy (Evelyn Venable) he must learn honesty, loyalty and right
from wrong. It sounds like a recipe for boredom, but since it's a
plot device, the lesson isn't overbearing. Rather, the moral is
served up in an entertaining way, and there is no character more
entertaining for kids than Pinocchio's ``conscience,'' Jiminy
Cricket (voiced by Cliff Edwards).
</P>
<P>
   It's Jiminy who sings the Oscar-winning tune ``When You Wish
Upon a Star,''which would become a Disney theme song, and as
narrator he serves as both comic relief and a voice for the story's
themes.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1940, the cricket has become something of an icon
(representing either the world of Disney or goodness, depending on
your point of view), or as an exclamation (as in ``Jimmmmmminy
Cricket!'').
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't seen ``Pinocchio'' in a while, you may be
surprised how well it holds up after all these years, and its
message is timeless. The limited-edition DVD lists for $39.99, but
you should be able to find it cheaper. It looks great, but, unlike
many DVDs, there are few extras (the most notable here being the
original trailer). Inexplicably, there is only a ``making of
featurette'' for ``Pinocchio'' on the VHS tape, something you would
expect on the DVD. It's too bad for film buffs, and it makes owning
the DVD less imperative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
