<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN GIVES THE RAIDERS ANOTHER VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHELLE SMITH  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Recent Raiders history is littered with the
carcasses of games they should have won, but didn't. Heck, there
are those cockeyed-optimist types who see an undefeated record in
1999 save for a few unfortunate breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps it's some sort of cosmic justice that the Oakland
Raiders regaled in a 24-23 victory over the New York Jets on
Sunday, because for the better part of three quarters, there wasn't
much taking place at the Coliseum to suggest victory was at hand.
No running game, no open receivers, no way to put a stop to the
rambling of Jets running back Curtis Martin, no way to stem the
tide of turnovers turning into New York scoring opportunities. In
short, no way a team that has played so lackluster as a matter of
course on its home field would come back from a 20-3 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   And then it did.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe these aren't the Same Old Raiders after all. That's not to
suggest, however, that this is a great football team, or perhaps
even a playoff team. But they are good enough right now to beat a
Jets team that was 1-5 coming in with a degree of drama that hasn't
been seen since, well, the week before. Make that seven Raiders
games this season in which the final score was decided by a
touchdown or less.
</P>
<P>
   The difference this time, however, was that it was the Raiders
offense on the field with the psyche of the franchise hanging in
the balance. Quarterback Rich Gannon, who had so much time to throw
and so few people to catch through much of the afternoon,
engineered an 11-play, 90-yard touchdown drive with less than two
minutes left in the game, culminating in a 5-yard touchdown pass to
James Jett with 26 seconds left. The offensive heroics haven't been
seen in these parts since the team was still in its Southern
California parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hung in there, despite the fact that things didn't go well
for us early,'' Gannon said. ``Turnovers were big, fumbles
especially. When you turn the ball over like that, you give the
other team a chance. It was one of those games where we gave them
chances, they took advantage of them and what ultimately happens is
you find yourself down by three scores. We were fortunate to get
out of here with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   And just to confirm the alignment of the planets in the Raiders'
favor, the touchdown pass to win the game went to a guy who wasn't
even supposed to be on the field for that play.
</P>
<P>
   Jett worked his way open in the left corner of the end zone
while Gannon worked his way out of the grasp of two tacklers. The
play was intended for Tim Brown, who was double-covered, not
surprising considering his nearly single-handed resurrection of the
Raiders offense in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Jett was the secondary receiver running an option route, but the
play was designed for Terry Mickens in that role. Raiders head
coach Jon Gruden was trying to get Mickens out onto the field, but
nobody could hear him yelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he was in there, let's just put it that way,'' Gruden
said after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in every football game down to the wire,'' Gruden
said. ``That's just how it's going to be with the Oakland Raiders
this year. No matter who we are playing, it's going to be a tight
football game and we've got to expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Much the same way the Raiders fully expected a fight on their
hands from the Jets, who are not nearly as bad as their record
would indicate.
</P>
<P>
   They knew marquee offensive talents Martin and Keyshawn Johnson
could be significant factors, and they were. They knew Bill
Belichick's defensive game plan would cause them offensive
problems, and it did. They knew they had little room for error and
yet committed four turnovers that led directly to 13 New York
points. And perhaps they knew, from so much experience already this
season, that a game is never really over until it's over, that they
could come back. And they did that too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just huge, anytime you win, but to win like that, with
all that adversity out there,'' center Barrett Robbins said. ``It
can't be a negative. The fact is that we didn't come out and play
as well as we wanted to, but after we settled in the second half
and figured out we were going to have to (throw) the ball to win,
we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit goes to Brown, who ended up with 11 catches
for a career-high 190 yards, none bigger than a 45-yard touchdown
pass from Gannon with 29 seconds left in the third quarter to
breathe life back into an Oakland team that was just about to
flat-line again at home against a quarterback-challenged team with
a shoddy record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play of the day was Tim's touchdown catch to make it 20-10
because it shot some life to our football team,'' Gruden said. ``We
were getting defeated soundly until that play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
