<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION'S MORAL AUTHORITY UNDERCUT BY POLITICAL HATRED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's generational, because I watched friends die in World
War II, a bloodbath encouraged by U.S. isolationism. Or because I
bought into the post-war wisdom that partisanship must stop at the
water's edge. Possibly it's because I served in Congress with eight
presidents during those pre-Gingrich years before hate became a
parliamentary weapon, when any American president was considered a
common national asset, our common duty to protect his international
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, I cannot escape the uncomfortable
conviction that the Senate action on Oct. 13, summarily rejecting
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty on a party-line vote, was a
needless assault on the presidential office, from which both the
world and the United States may suffer.
</P>
<P>
   The deliberate Republican leadership decision to ditch the
treaty, launched 40 years ago in Dwight Eisenhower's second
administration and pursued by the last nine American presidents,
was a spiteful personal slap at President Clinton and a blow to
U.S. prestige around the world.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Senate's first open rejection of a major
presidentially sponsored treaty in 80 years, since a ``little group
of willful men'' led by Sen. Henry Cabot Lodge in 1920 killed U.S.
participation in the League of Nations. Most historians believe
that Senate vote, an undisguised personal rebuff to President
Woodrow Wilson, fatally weakened the League, encouraging military
expansion by Hitler and Japan, thus rendering World War II
unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   This month's Senate vote came as a rude surprise to other
nuclear powers whose governments, at our urging, have ratified the
U.S.-sponsored treaty. Russia and China reportedly were ready to
act following the expected U.S. lead. India and Pakistan,
dangerously torn by their explosive rivalry, had been awaiting our
action to make their decisions. Whatever arguments might have
supported the Senate's action, nobody can doubt that the world is,
as its result, a more dangerous place in which U.S. leadership will
be less persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan showdown was, alas, willful and unnecessary. It
could and should have been avoided. The prime ministers of England,
France and Germany, in an unparalleled expression of concern, had
urged the Senate to avoid a negative vote. Two hours before the
vote, Clinton called Republican leader Trent Lott with a personal
plea to delay action for reasons of national security. Lott airily
rebuffed the president.
</P>
<P>
   With enough GOP votes in his pocket to doom the treaty, Lott
demanded as his price for postponing the vote a signed pledge from
Clinton that he'd never renew his request for treaty consideration
during his term in office. Any such written statement, Lott knew,
would embarrass Clinton personally, badly compromise his world
leadership role, and discourage other countries from signing.
Desperate to head off the potentially fatal collision, Democratic
Senate leader Tom Daschle privately assured Lott he'd personally
see that the vote did not recur this year or next. To no avail.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for insisting on this gratuitous swipe at Clinton
seems clear. Republican leaders detest him so strongly that they'll
risk weakening our country's world role to embarrass him. I find no
other persuasive rationale for Lott's decision.
</P>
<P>
   We've drifted a long way from the days when even members of the
president's opposition party felt a patriotic responsibility to
help protect our chief executive from embarrassment. Here's how I
put it 40 years ago:
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is embarrassed in the eyes of the world, then I am
embarrassed _ because my country is embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were my words in House debate one day in 1960. Eisenhower
was president, I a back-bencher Democrat. A witch's brew of
partisan Democrats and conservative Republicans were trying to
defeat an authorization requested by Eisenhower for funding the Pan
American Health Organization. Eisenhower's word to our neighbors in
the hemisphere was on the line. I didn't want his pledge repudiated
for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   That basic proposition, I still believe, has validity. If the
American president is needlessly weakened or discredited in
important diplomatic negotiations with other countries, our nation
suffers.
</P>
<P>
   I felt that way in 1969 when President Richard Nixon called on
North Vietnam to let the Vietnamese conflict be settled by free,
internationally sponsored elections. I introduced a resolution of
congressional support for that Republican president's bargaining
position and guided it to House passage.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 20 years later, as House Majority Leader, I got an urgent
call one day from President Ronald Reagan. It was the eve of his
scheduled meeting with Soviet Premier Mikhail Gorbachev in Iceland.
Reagan pleaded with Speaker Tip O'Neill and me to intercede with
Democratic members of an ongoing conference committee to restore
specific missile capabilities the House had cut from the military
appropriations bill. Wanting these for bargaining chips, Reagan
confided to us that he'd offer them as inducements for similar
concessions on the part of the Soviet premier. O'Neill and I went
to work to salvage the presidential bargaining position.
</P>
<P>
   These incidents are merely illustrative, by no means unique. For
40 years such cooperation was the rule. Even after his
administration was caught violating laws in Iran-contra, Democratic
leaders were at pains to preserve the personal dignity of President
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Recent years have seen a painful drift from those days of
bipartisan foreign policy. Ambassadorial and judicial vacancies
often go unfilled for long months while the Senate simply refuses
to act on presidential nominations. United Nations dues, now $1.8
billion in arrears, have gone unpaid for years. These things
embarrass the president and undercut America's moral authority.
They hurt us all.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright &LR; tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
