<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TV ADS TOUT EDUCATION, ANTI-TAX RECORD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Republican presidential front-runner George W.
Bush, whose commanding lead is apparently slipping, will kick off a
series of television ads Tuesday in New Hampshire and Iowa, touting
his anti-tax and pro-education record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The paid TV campaign _ Bush's first in his presidential race _
will herald the Texas governor as a ``compassionate conservative
leader'' and a ``fresh start for America.'' The four ads, which
were previewed for reporters Monday, make no references to any of
his opponents for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also will begin airing one radio commercial in Spanish to
target Hispanics in Iowa, who comprise about 1 percent of the
state's population.
</P>
<P>
   The ads will start running three days after a newspaper poll in
New Hampshire showed Bush was losing ground to Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., among Republican voters in that key nominating state. A
campaign spokesman said the timing was coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   The poll by the Concord Monitor also indicated that Bush could
lose the general election vote in New Hampshire if he and former
Sen. Bill Bradley were the major party nominees.
</P>
<P>
   And a new poll by Newsweek magazine showed Bush's national lead
over Bradley and Democratic front-runner Al Gore narrowing.
</P>
<P>
   In one Bush TV spot, an announcer says the governor has been
``hailed as the Republican Party's best hope to win the White
House.'' The announcer says he signed the ``two largest tax cuts in
Texas history,'' while reducing spending growth, improving
education and reducing the welfare rolls, ``junk'' lawsuits and
juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
   In the other three commercials, Bush appears on camera to
promise an ``optimistic and very positive'' campaign, to outline
his priorities for education and to promote federal tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The TV ads include video of children of various races in several
settings, elderly people, Bush at bill-signing ceremonies and
hugging his wife, Laura.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign said the television buy was enough to enable
the average person in Iowa and New Hampshire to see the ads about
three to five times a week. Bush aides declined ``for strategic
reasons'' to release other details about the cost and extent of the
buy.
</P>
<P>
   According to the governor's campaign, Bush is the first
presidential candidate, Republican or Democrat, to run Hispanic
media in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new day,'' Bush says in Spanish during the
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Although one Bush TV spot says the governor has ``reduced the
growth of state government spending to the lowest in 40 years'' in
Texas, Bush already has been attacked over state spending by one of
his Republican opponents, magazine publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   State spending under Bush has increased at a rate of 35 percent,
greater than the 21 percent growth in federal spending during the
past six years of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's budget experts say the growth in spending under Bush
has only been 2.7 percent, when budgetary figures are adjusted for
inflation, population growth and the extra education funds that the
state has transferred to school districts for local property tax
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm said Bush's
ads did not tell the full story, particularly on the governor's
claim to record tax cuts. Although some school districts have cut
their taxes in recent years, others have raised them, she pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
   According to a New Hampshire poll taken last week and published
Saturday by the Concord Monitor, Bush's lead had shrunk to 39
percent, while former McCain had 27 percent. The other Republican
candidates were in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar survey in August, Bush led McCain 45 percent to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Concord Monitor poll, which had a margin of error of plus or
minus 4 percentage points, showed Bush with a 50 percent to 40
percent lead in New Hampshire over Gore in a possible general
election matchup.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush was tied with Bradley at 45 percent to 44 percent. If
Pat Buchanan becomes the Reform party nominee, Bradley would move
ahead of Bush, 45 percent to 41 percent, in New Hampshire, the poll
showed.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republican candidates, McCain and Forbes each have
campaigned in New Hampshire much more often than Bush. And the
Texas governor drew some criticism for skipping the first
presidential debate in New Hampshire last Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   A new national poll by Newsweek, meanwhile, shows Bush's lead
over both Democratic candidates narrowing. According to the survey,
conducted last week with a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percentage points, Bush led Gore, 49 percent to 40 percent, and led
Bradley, 47 percent to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a June Newsweek survey, Bush had double-digit leads over both
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The national lineup among Republican candidates in the Newsweek
poll was Bush, 57 percent; McCain, 12 percent, and Forbes, 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said that regardless of the
polls, Bush continues to receive ``broad-based support.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He will continue to work hard to earn every single vote,''
McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
