<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DOUBT THAT YANKEES ARE TEAM OF THE CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm rooting for the New York Yankees to win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   This is clearly a politically incorrect activity in North Texas,
where the Bronx Bombers are considered aliens from another planet
who periodically invade the city of Arlington and devour the
collective heart of the local baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, rooting for the Yankees is politically incorrect just
about everywhere except New York _ and there are parts of New York
where you wouldn't want to be seen wearing a Yankee T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could say that my fondness for the Yankees reflects
nothing more than my admiration for their manager, Joe Torre; I've
been a Torre fan since his days as a National League batting
champion and Most Valuable player with the St. Louis Cardinals. But
I liked the Yankees long before Torre pulled on those famous
pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown up just across the Mississippi River from St.
Louis, I've always been a Cardinal fan. But I started following
baseball at a time when the Redbirds were mired in a decade-long
slump and the Yankees were on top of the world with the likes of
Mickey Mantle, Roger Maris, Whitey Ford, Yogi Berra, Elston Howard.
...
</P>
<P>
   There were no playoffs back then, only the World Series, and the
Yankees always seemed to be playing in the Fall Classic. Most of my
friends hated the Yankees and stubbornly backed the Yanks' opponent
no matter who it was _ even loathsome Cardinal rivals such as the
Dodgers, Giants and Braves. I stuck with Mantle and the Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   They usually rewarded me by winning.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Cardinals and other great teams, the Yankees eventually
ran out of superstars and suffered some down years. But they are a
dominating force these days and the sports pundits are saying that
the current showdown with the Atlanta Braves will determine which
of these two proud franchises will be remembered as the Team of the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the Yankees win the 1999 World Series and the
mythical team-of-the-decade designation _ and I predict that they
will _ there can be no disputing this: The team that gave us Babe
Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Joe DiMaggio and Mickey Mantle was the Team of
the Century.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the statistics, which are breathtaking. Just consider
the transcending presence that the Yankees have always been. When
people around the world of think of baseball, they think of the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to my beloved Cardinals, to those great
Cincinnati and Oakland teams of the '70s and to this would-be
America's Team from Atlanta, there can be no disputing that the
Yankees have defined big-league baseball for most of the 1900s.
More often than not, they have defined it with dignity and
professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there was that unfortunate vaudeville routine with Billy
Martin and George Steinbrenner in the '70s and '80s and the
unseemly recidivism of Darryl Strawberry in recent years. But
mostly, the Yankees have been a class act.
</P>
<P>
   The classiness of the '99 edition of the team begins with Torre,
who is not only a baseball genius but one of the finest gentlemen
ever to grace a major-league baseball diamond. He was a great
player. He is a great manager.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's team reflects his personality _ so much so that even
chronic troublemaker Strawberry seems to be behaving himself. If
some baseball fans hate the Yankees because they seem arrogant,
well, it's the best brand of arrogance: the serene confidence
produced by winning.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees know how to win. They never panic. They capitalize
on the opponent's mistakes. They find a way to compensate for their
own mistakes, rare though the mistakes may be.
</P>
<P>
   It's no mystery why the Texas Rangers can't get past the
Yankees, no matter how much talent the local heroes bring to the
quest. The Yankees expect to win and they always find a way to win.
The Rangers expect to lose and they always find a way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   It's the difference between a tradition of winning and a
tradition of losing.
</P>
<P>
   Team of the decade or not, the Yankees are winners. They'll
always be winners.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
