<HEADER>
A7987 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-25 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESOTERIC SHOPPING RITUALS DESERVE MALES' RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was just trying to be nice. That's all. It seemed like the
decent thing to do when I inquired of my family, ``Does anyone want
to go shopping with me and my sister today?''
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that I have three males in my family, none of whom
are particularly enthusiastic shoppers. Shopping is not even in my
Top 10 list of things to do, but occasionally the primal urge hits
me and I have to act on it.
</P>
<P>
   So I asked them if they wanted to tag along. Immediately, my
oldest son and my husband said, ``No! Go right ahead. We'll stay
here and watch the game.''
</P>
<P>
   However, my baby boy responded, ``I'll go if I can buy some
Pokemon cards at the mall.''
</P>
<P>
   His father and brother stared at him like he had three eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget the cards,'' his brother advised. ``You don't want to
go shopping with two women. It's horrible. They just talk and talk
and sometimes they don't even buy anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, son,'' my spouse piped in. ``It's not worth it. Not even
for Pokemon cards. You'll get bored and want to come home, but
they'll just keep dragging you from store to store without mercy.
And it takes all day long. You're better off here with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, I would have protested and set the record straight on
the importance of shopping as evidenced by the very clothes they
were wearing. But I didn't want them to go along anyway so I just
said, ``OK, see you guys later.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon further reflection, I feel it is my duty to let you
non-shoppers have a little insight into the dog-eat-dog world of
mall surfing.
</P>
<P>
   First we have to decide who's going to drive and which mall
we're going to grace with our presence. That can take a good half
hour. Hint: If you have a 16th of a tank of gas, you should not
engage in this debate. Just let the other person drive. Eventually,
we decide on a mall in the next county that has the same stores as
the mall down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Upon our arrival, we go from store to boutique to kiosk,
touching all the pretty, colorful trinkets that we like. We can't
just look at them, we have to pick them up and show our friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this. Isn't this precious? Stephanie would love this,
it's so her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it is cute. I used to have one but my son sat on it and
broke it. Then he put it back on the end table like nothing had
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   We spend an hour or so touching things before we finally try
something on.
</P>
<P>
   We model for each other and the other women in the dressing room
who all say, ``That is so cute on you, you should buy that. It's so
you.'' We don't purchase anything, but we feel really good about
ourselves now.
</P>
<P>
   Then we have lunch in the food court. So much fun. Talk, talk,
talk. Finally, we get to the really good part. After the eating and
drinking, we have to go to the ladies' room.
</P>
<P>
   I know you men wonder about the ladies' room. We spend a lot of
time in there and the lines are always so long. Well, I'm going to
let you in on a little secret. I may be tarred and feathered for
telling you this, but it's time you knew.
</P>
<P>
   The first part you already know about. We go in, find a stall,
lift the seat with our foot to look for spiders, clean the seat
with a wet wipe even though we're only going to hover over it, and
we handle our business. We discard the first few sheets of toilet
tissue because some strange woman has already touched them, play
tug of war with the spindle for a few more rounds and then we flush
the toilet with our foot.
</P>
<P>
   After that, we wash our hands and go to the party room. Yes, the
party room. Hidden inside the bathrooms of most major department
stores is a full service juice bar and recreation room. Everything
is free. Some women play cards and smoke cigars. Others just go for
a quick chair massage or a table dance by one of the waiters. They
even have arts and crafts classes at some locations. After 10
minutes or so, the hostess kindly reminds us if someone is waiting
on us and we leave reluctantly. Seating is limited, thus the long
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies, forgive me, but they were going to find out sooner or
later.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that's it. That's why we go shopping all day and come
home with a package of gum.
</P>
<P>
   But do you know what's an even better kept secret? Golfing
outings. Next week, I'll tell you what really happens during those
five hours on the links.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564 or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
