<HEADLINE>
`Y2K': IT'S COMING AND STOCK UP ON GOOD HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So will the turn of the millennium mean a blip or a glitz or a
monumental mess for America? Robert X. Cringely, the PBS specialist
on nerdism, is the latest investigator to address the question. In
``Y2K: The Winter of Our Disconnect,'' he chats with officials,
computer know-it-alls and ``survivalists'' and comes up with more
reasons for indifference than for panic.
</P>
<P>
   Using the breakdown of his car, perhaps owing to a computer
failure, as a pretext, he traces the Year 2000 problem to
programmers past who relied on two-digit dates to save
computer-chip space. That, as most viewers must know by now, means
that when our calendars change from 1999 to 2000, the computers
will register ``00,'' which since history is not their strong
point, they will interpret as 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Cringely assures us that many essential everyday services like
traffic lights, garbage collection and 911 calls, which do not
depend on ambiguous computer dating, will not be affected in the
slightest. And he reports that matters like national defense,
nuclear safety and hydroelectric power are in the hands of
engineers, not computer whizzes. So don't worry.
</P>
<P>
   Where Year 2000 is likely to cause snags, he finds, is on the
accounting front or its back rooms. Computer programs for matters
like reimbursing Medicare charges or collecting bills may resist
quick fixes.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for some group to blame for your checks being
delayed or getting lost, Cringely's candidates are the ``software
centrists,'' who, instead of improving the dependability of the
basic computers, have always preferred to tinker with the
individual programs. Solving immediate problems is easier in the
short run than getting at the heart of what's wrong, and by now
every piecemeal change involves many other changes that programmers
don't even remember, so their efforts to adjust matters to suit the
millennial change could bring unanticipated confusions.
</P>
<P>
   Cringely does not suggest that viewers join those fretful folks
he interviews who are already stocking up on granola and ammunition
and thinking about heading for the mountains to escape catastrophe.
But we should all expect some mix-ups and delays involving checks,
bills, credit charges and other quotidian calculations. The advice
he leaves us with, as he drives off in his newly repaired car, is
to be patient and neighborly: ``Enjoy the millennium!''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `Y2K, The Winter of Our Disconnect' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Tuesday on PBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A production of Oregon Public Broadcasting; produced by Mike
McCleod; Janet Tobias, executive producer; John Lindsay, executive
in charge of production. Robert X. Cringely, host.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
