<HEADER>
A7993 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ART-DUMMIES-1600(2ndT     10-25 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-DUMMIES-1600(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURAL REVOLUTIONARY EXPLAINS `ART FOR DUMMIES'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UNDATED: character, marketing ploy. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``For the fresco show, I tried to get the Fresca soft-drink
company to sponsor it,'' Hoving says with a laugh. ``They really
didn't have a clue what I was getting at, what the connection was,
and why should they? But I figured the name was so close they could
have done something with it. They politely turned me down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Age of Tapestries'' followed the fresco exhibit. In
retrospect, both paled next to Hoving's last great orchestration:
``The Treasures of Tutankhamen.'' The two-year show featured the
breathtaking gold, glass and lapis lazuli collars, bracelets and
headdresses from the mummies' tomb. The exhibit attracted millions
and, ever the showman, Hoving relished knowing that in terms of
ticket sales, no other exhibit ever surpassed King Tut. It would
cap Hoving's 10 years at the Met.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until Tom Hoving arrived, museums were operated as citadels of
very sophisticated culture, which meant they were really sleepy
cupboards,'' says Edmund Pillsbury, former director of the Kimbell
Art Museum. ``But because of his incredible skills as scholar,
impresario and salesman, he made people feel that the museum was a
place for everybody. Now, no one would ever describe Thomas Hoving
as a great diplomat, but his energy and vision alone qualify him as
one of the major figures in the history of American museums.''
</P>
<P>
   The lofty status accorded to Hoving lends a definite weight to
any prognosis he makes on museum growth. Right now, his crystal
ball doesn't present an optimistic picture. ``Unfortunately, the
museum audience is dwindling because museums are finding, to their
horror, that their well-educated patrons are also rapidly aging
people,'' Hoving says. ``To get the 6-year-old there, you might
need Ricky Martin to do a lecture on Spanish painting.''
</P>
<P>
   A museum's salvation, according to Hoving, lies in a shrewd
manipulation of its own collection, turning it like a Rubik's Cube
until the most felicitous combination emerges. What is clear to
Hoving is that recycling predictable shows won't cut it any longer.
``So many museums really can't do yet another blockbuster
Impressionism show,'' says Hoving. ``They should just plumb their
own collections, telling marvelous stories about what they already
have.''
</P>
<P>
   OK. Then, suddenly, Hoving shifts into Knute Rockne mode,
exhorting museums everywhere to heed his advice. ``C'mon, you guys
in charge of museums, give us a little imagination in what you are
showing,'' he says, as if leading a pep rally. ``Don't just show us
yet another fifth-ranked late Renaissance collection or something
on the great masters where most of the works can never leave their
home galleries. I mean, I just saw the Van Dyck show at the Royal
Academy in London, and the three greatest works weren't there, so
why bother?''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Hoving may be writing for the masses, but when he visits
an art gallery, he is still one demanding connoisseur.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
