<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Oct. 26 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ President Clinton vetoed his third
spending bill today, the bill paying for the Commerce, State and
Justice departments. At the same time he signed into law a $268
billion military spending bill, avoiding the potential of a
crippling split among Democrats as the parties hurtle toward the
finale of their budget showdown. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   PLANE-STEWART (Undated) _ A Learjet carrying golfer Payne
Stewart and four other people flew uncontrolled over the nation's
heartland for hours Monday before crashing in South Dakota, killing
everyone aboard. The twin-engine plane, which took off from
Orlando, Fla., may have suffered a pressurization failure during
its scheduled flight to Dallas, government officials said. (Summary
from wires.) By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
