<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHING LUCK RUNS DRY IN STEELHEAD TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALONG THE DESCHUTES RIVER, Ore. _ With each cast of my fly rod,
the river seemed full of hope, challenge and reward.
</P>
<P>
   I worked my way thigh deep across from a riffle, then whipped
the line back-and-forth twice and delivered it gently into the run,
mended the line quickly, then let the fly drift down the edge of
the white water. Everything was just right, a perfect spot. A big
steelhead must be here, I thought, maybe several.
</P>
<P>
   The river was brisk, the morning air sharp, and there were light
tingles on my neck, both from the chill and the excitement. Above
the volcanic basalt canyon walls, an osprey was also out at first
light, hoping for a fish.
</P>
<P>
   I lifted my rod and cast again. Nothing. But that's how it can
be for steelhead. What drives you is hope, that the fish of your
life always seems to be just ahead, perhaps to be hooked on your
next cast.
</P>
<P>
   This was on the Deschutes River in Oregon, which starts as a
trickle at the south flank of the Three Sisters Wilderness in the
Cascade Range, then winds its way for 200 miles out of the
mountains, past dams, and eventually through the Oregon desert
country and into the Columbia River. It is one of the North
America's renowned steelhead streams, producer of the state-record
28-pounder, attracting anglers from across the Western United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers of steelhead in the Columbia system right now are
out of this world,'' said Ed Rice, who organized the trip. ``The
rivers are loaded with them, three times as many as last year,
according to the counts at Bonneville Dam. This could be the best
steelhead trip of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   The steelhead defines the challenge. It is the fastest
freshwater fish of them all, with a burst speed of 27 feet per
second. Hooking, fighting and landing a big one on a fly rod while
wading from shore is not only a preeminent fishing challenge, but
can just plain flip your pancake. The Deschutes is an outstanding
steelhead river for flyfishers because it is filled with
basketball-size boulders in water 3 to 6 feet deep, the ultimate
habitat and casting water.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for this trip started last spring at the International
Sportsmen's Exposition, where two of the finest flyfishers in the
world, Gary Borger and Rice, were giving seminars and invited me to
join them for a trip: ``The best of the best,'' Rice called the
adventure. Eager to join as well was Charlie Meyers _ an outdoors
writer from Colorado with whom I first fished 20 years ago in the
Caribbean Sea _ each of us catching world-record Atlantic bonito on
back-to-back casts.
</P>
<P>
   Rice has caught and released a world-best 165 species of
sportfish on a fly rod and could approach 200 after a trip to
several countries in Africa next month; that includes all the
marlin species except for blue marlin _ a 600-pounder he hooked two
years ago broke the line. Borger comes from the same fabric, having
invented, among many creations, his own fly line: ``Borger's Shadow
Line,'' and being hired by Robert Redford as the consultant for his
movie, ``A River Runs Through It.'' The flycasting scenes in that
movie are not actors Brad Pitt and Craig Scheffer, but actually
Borger's son, Jason, filmed from a distance.
</P>
<P>
   Rice joked that he didn't want to be paired with Borger, at
least not the first day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call him `Hoover,''' Rice explained, ``because if you let
him fish in front of you, he vacuums up everything and leaves
nothing behind.''
</P>
<P>
   In minutes we had landed the boat and jumped out. The rush of
cold water whirled past my waders as I tied on a fly, a skunk
pattern with a laser-sharp hook, and started casting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks really good,'' I said aloud, really to no one, just
talking to the river and the towering stark canyon walls.
</P>
<P>
   Rice had warned me that steelhead on the Deschutes ``hit like a
freight train,'' and to ``always keep a loop of line in your rod
hand, so you have some line to give the fish.'' Otherwise, he
explained, during the ``savage strike,'' the hook can be
unintentionally ripped out of the fish's mouth. Worse yet, Rice
continued, if your line accidentally loops around your reel and
gets caught in a fixed position, an occasional problem when fly
fishing, ``the steelhead will rip the rod right out your hands and
into the river and it's goodbye rod.'' That charged the excitement
even more.
</P>
<P>
   By that evening, we had fished five miles of river, splitting up
in different boats, fishing different spots. At camp that night, on
a plateau sprinkled with sagebrush above the river bank, we
compared notes. So far, nothing. Most fishermen are born dishonest,
but Rice, Borger and Meyers seem to have gotten over it.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, after a camp breakfast, we were all again eager
and excited to get our first fish. I wondered if I could handle one
with just 125 yards of backing line _ every one else had 200 to 250
yards of line on their reels. After all, ``these steelhead can
really fly,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   But that night, comparing notes, it turned out we'd all been
skunked again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, can you believe there is a chance we might get
zeroed on this trip?'' I asked Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you just figure that out?'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody believed it.
</P>
<P>
   I started watching Rice and Borger in action. Each is a true
artist of the craft, their fly rods like brushes, the stream a
canvas, as they paint a scene that Redford managed to capture on
film. After a 45-minute sequence, where Borger worked a 150-yard
seam in the river with his full palate of colors, stepping
downstream a measured foot after each cast for full stream
coverage, he finally turned his back and walked out of the river.
</P>
<P>
   I watched him as he approached, head down, shoulders slumped,
utterly defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' he said, then stopped. ``You?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   On the final day, suddenly all seemed hopeful again. That
afternoon, I was with Rice, the master, and we were working what
seemed a perfect 100-yard run, ideal holding water, a V-wedge seam
along white water. I had a grab, and though the fish wasn't hooked,
it seemed the river fortunes were finally ours to take.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, from well downstream, Rice let out a howling yell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got him! got him!''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, there was another howl, and the river guide,
Bryce Tedford, went sprinting down the river bank to watch the
commotion. I slogged my way to shore, and then in minutes, arrived
at the scene, ready to see Rice break the Curse of the Deschutes.
</P>
<P>
   But Rice, a big man, was not smiling, though his rod was still
bending. In fact, he looked something like an exasperated grizzly
bear. Just 30 feet downstream in the current, right on the surface,
was a fish on its side, not a steelhead, but a sucker, a non-game
coarse fish, that Rice had accidentally snagged in the dorsal fin,
and was dragging in.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as we left the river, we compared histories, and none of
us had ever had a trip like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever seen that many quality people so intense for a
fish that didn't exist?'' Borger said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1819EDT &QL; 
