<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORMONES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women's hormones a complex web
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dr. Elizabeth Lee Vliet will discuss how women's
hormones can be both ``marvelous and maddening'' at a Thursday
conference sponsored by Northside Hospital. Vliet is the author of
the book ``Screaming to Be Heard: Hormonal Connections Women
Suspect and Doctors Ignore.'' Staff writer Patricia Guthrie
recently caught up with Vliet as she shuttled between her women's
health centers in Tucson and Dallas-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Your book goes into great depth on all the different ways a
woman is affected by estrogen and the hormonal changes throughout a
lifetime. What motivated you to compile such information?
</P>
<P>
   A:From listening to women describing their experiences with
menstrual periods and hormonal changes during menopause. The
information for them was not integrated into a cohesive picture as
to how all the pieces fit together. There has been more research
done on menopause in the international medical community than in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Hot flashes, weight gain and mood swings are the usual
physical and emotional effects women are told to expect during
menopause. But there's much more, correct?
</P>
<P>
   A:More than 400 functions are affected by estradiol released
from the ovaries. Most women tend to think of their ovaries
relating only to reproduction and menstruation. They don't see
their hormones as a metabolic function that can affect everything
from glucose regulation, muscle repair, brain function and nerve
cells. There really does tend to be a lack of recognition of all
these effects (by doctors), because women's bodily chemical changes
have not been the focus of medical research in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What health problems could a menopausal woman be experiencing
that she may not suspect are hormone-related?
</P>
<P>
   A:Fatigue, mood changes, memory loss, headaches, cholesterol
changes, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The decision to take hormone replacement therapy seems
emotional for many women, because of breast cancer fears. What do
you tell your patients ?
</P>
<P>
   A:It's actually a decision that can be made very logically. The
problem is it's been approached by the media with much more
emphasis on the breast cancer risk than the other health risks that
come from not taking hormone replacement therapy, such as migraine
headaches, bone loss and heart disease. ... The other problem is
we've used a cookbook approach when it comes to hormone
replacement, giving the same two drugs _ Premarin or Provera _ and
same dose to all women. I don't think we would give men the same
drug and dose for heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Registration for Vliet's lecture is full. But Northside Hospital
is sponsoring a continuing series on women's midlife issues on
Mondays in November. Free seminars are scheduled 7:30-9 p.m. this
Monday(hormone replacement therapy), Nov. 8 (alternatives to
hormone replacement), Nov. 15 (women and heart disease), Nov. 22
(depression, mood changes and hormones) and Nov. 29 (prevention and
treatment of osteoporosis). To register, call 404-845-5555.Patricia
Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
