<SLUG> BC-REGIONAL-MUSEUMS-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE JOINS U.S. IN A PUSH FOR MIDSIZE MUSEUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Texas, Minn., Mass., Va., Ore., Mo., Calif., Conn.,
France)  (js) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ Their buildings, collections and traditions may
be very different, but regional museums in France and the United
States have at least one thing in common: acute awareness that
Americans usually visit museums in Paris, that French tourists head
for museums in New York and that museums in medium-size cities in
both countries are all too often overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in an attempt to demonstrate that cultural life also exists
outside Paris and New York, nine French and nine U.S. regional
museums are joining forces to raise their profiles. As an initial
step, they have agreed to share know-how on new technology,
marketing and fund-raising and, more critically, to start
exchanging masterpieces and developing joint exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   It is proving to be a voyage of discovery. Before the first
meeting of museum directors here this month, they exchanged
catalogs because in most cases they did not know one another's
collections. During their visit to Lyons, several Americans even
met fellow directors from other American museums for the first
time. And before their next meeting in St. Louis next October, both
French and Americans plan to cross the Atlantic to visit their new
partners.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of their relative isolation that the initiative
for this program came from an outsider, Elizabeth Rohatyn, whose
husband, Felix, is the U.S. ambassador to France. Richard Bretell,
former director of the Dallas Museum of Art, was then brought in to
coordinate the U.S. museums, while Francoise Cachin, director of
the French museums department, selected the French participants.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. museums involved are the Cleveland Museum of Art, the
Dallas Museum of Art, the Minneapolis Institute of Art, the
Portland Art Museum in Oregon, the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts in
Richmond, the St. Louis Art Museum, the Fine Arts Museum of San
Francisco, the Sterling and Francine Clark Art Institute in
Williamstown, Mass., and the Yale University Art Gallery and Yale
Center for British Art. The French fine arts museums in the program
are those of Bordeaux, Grenoble, Lille, Lyons, Montpellier, Rennes,
Rouen, Strasbourg and Toulouse.
</P>
<P>
   The chosen museums well illustrate the contrasting French and
American approaches to culture. Most of the nine French museums
were created by Napoleon in 1801 and all are still owned and
financed by city governments. In contrast, the U.S. museums were in
the main founded as independent institutions and depend on
fund-raising. Similarly, while the French museums often have
something of a regional identity, the U.S. museums generally aspire
to be universal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both sides are eager to find common ground. At a workshop on
collection sharing and joint exhibitions, French and American
directors began suggesting works or shows that they could offer and
mentioning exhibition themes that interested them. They clearly
felt it important that some joint projects take place before their
next meeting even though museums generally plan their large
exhibitions at least two years in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their shared interest in appealing to new audiences,
they were disinclined to take the easy path of organizing yet
another exhibition of, say, Impressionist paintings. ``We have a
duty to do more than that,'' said Evan M. Maurer, director and
president of the Minneapolis Institute of Arts. Michael Conforti,
director of the Clark Art Institute, added: ``There must be an
intellectual basis for exchanges.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Next year the Musee des Beaux-Arts of Lille will lend a
collection of Raphael drawings to Cleveland and St. Louis, while
Cleveland and the Musee des Beaux-Arts in Lyons will temporarily
unite their Zurbaran masterpieces. Lille, Minneapolis and the Clark
Art Institute will also reunite their panels of a famous early
15th-century triptych by an anonymous Flemish painter known as the
Master of Embroidered Foliage.
</P>
<P>
   More ambitious plans lie ahead. For 2001 Maurer will organize
``Sacred Symbols: 2,000 Years of North American Indian Art,'' which
will travel to museums in Lyons, Rouen and Lille.
</P>
<P>
   The Grenoble, Lyons and Strasbourg museums will in turn organize
a show of French painting since 1945 for display at Cleveland,
while French medieval art from Lille, Strasbourg and Toulouse will
visit Cleveland and Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are also keen to develop a group identity. One
idea is to create a common Internet platform for the 18 museums as
both an informational and educational instrument; another is to use
multimedia to create ``virtual exhibitions'' of works that are too
fragile to be moved. The partnership should also open the way for
the exchange of curators and joint research projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
