<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Things to remember about daylight-saving time
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daylight-saving time ends Sunday morning. Public health
authorities recommend using the semi-annual clock adjustment as a
reminder of safety measures that should be taken around your house.
</P>
<P>
   Fall temperatures mean you'll be turning on the furnace soon.
Change the furnace filter, and call a professional to check for
potentially deadly carbon monoxide leaks.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a fireplace, have the chimney checked as well. Birds
or animals may have blocked it since you last built a fire, and
that could force fumes back into your living space.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that you'll be protected from the results of any
fumes, sparks or other trouble, change the batteries in your
household smoke detectors.
</P>
<P>
   Turn mattresses, especially if any household members are
vulnerable to allergies: Flip each mattress so the underside is
pointing up, and then spin it so the side that was closest to the
headboard is now at the foot of the bed.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget to turn the clock back.
</P>
<P>
   _M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Comstitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
