their hormones as a metabolic function that can affect everything
from glucose regulation, muscle repair, brain function and nerve
cells. There really does tend to be a lack of recognition of all
these effects (by doctors), because women's bodily chemical changes
have not been the focus of medical research in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What health problems could a menopausal woman be experiencing
that she may not suspect are hormone-related?
</P>
<P>
   A:Fatigue, mood changes, memory loss, headaches, cholesterol
changes, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The decision to take hormone replacement therapy seems
emotional for many women, because of breast cancer fears. What do
you tell your patients ?
</P>
<P>
   A:It's actually a decision that can be made very logically. The
problem is it's been approached by the media with much more
emphasis on the breast cancer risk than the other health risks that
come from not taking hormone replacement therapy, such as migraine
headaches, bone loss and heart disease. ... The other problem is
we've used a cookbook approach when it comes to hormone
replacement, giving the same two drugs _ Premarin or Provera _ and
same dose to all women. I don't think we would give men the same
drug and dose for heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Registration for Vliet's lecture is full. But Northside Hospital
is sponsoring a continuing series on women's midlife issues on
Mondays in November. Free seminars are scheduled 7:30-9 p.m. this
Monday(hormone replacement therapy), Nov. 8 (alternatives to
hormone replacement), Nov. 15 (women and heart disease), Nov. 22
(depression, mood changes and hormones) and Nov. 29 (prevention and
