r e BC-NEWSTAND26-COX     10-25 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Payne wants `to be left alone,' wife says
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under siege from the media and a congressional committee
investigating the Olympic Games scandal, Billy Payne tells his side
of the story to Atlanta ($3.50) writer Rebecca Poynor Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Payne insists that nothing will tarnish the Olympic experience
for him and other Georgians. ``Down the stream, when you ask what
was Georgia's finest hour, you're going to get an overwhelming
response that it was the Olympic Games.'' So what does Payne want?
According to his wife, Martha, ``What he wants, really, is to be
left alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Also of note: Interior designer Monique Gibson takes readers on
a tour of Elton John's Park Place pad in Atlanta. Artwork and
photography fill nearly every wall, thousands of CDs are cataloged
and stored, and a hand-woven tiger velvet spread sets the tone in
John's bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The word on mummies: National Geographic ($4) gives the public
its first comprehensive look at the haunting photographs of the
Inca mummies discovered this spring on a mountain in Argentina. The
two girls and a boy _ sacrifices to the Inca gods _ were found
along with a cache of textiles and artifacts in a burial platform
atop Mount Llullaillaco. Buried under rock and earth, the frozen
bodies were so well preserved they appeared as if they had just
been buried. Such sacrifices were rare, says explorer Johan
Reinhard, and children were used because they were considered purer
than adults.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The guns of Waco: New Yorker ($3) correspondent Peter J. Boyer
sifts through the ashes (figuratively) of the Branch Davidian
compound to get to the bottom of what appears to be a massive
coverup. One of the key questions is whether FBI agents fired their
guns at the Branch Davidians. The agency denies any shots were
fired, but a congressional committee is considering ballistics
tests on the dozen .38-caliber bullets whose casings were found at
an FBI sniper site.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  End of the world: An apocalypse of another sort is the subject
of Newsweek's ($3.50) cover story this week. Reporters Kenneth L.
Woodward and John Leland examine the biblical prophecies and the
stream of books and Internet traffic about the final days.
According to a Newsweek poll, some 40 percent of adults in the
world, including the congregation at the New Hope Revival Church in
Columbus, believe the world will end in a battle of Armageddon
between Jesus and the Antichrist.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The meat of the matter: Apparently you can have your steak and
eat it, too. Time ($3.50) examines the low-carb diet trend of
feasting on beef, bacon and eggs to lose weight. A helpful chart
compares the various plans, from the Atkins Diet to Weight
Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  All that jazz: Doubletake ($10) has a new staff and a new
address in Boston, but the magazine formerly published by Duke
University's Center for Documentary Studies is as lively and classy
as ever. The fall issue features Life photographer W. Eugene
Smith's never-before published pictures of a loft in New York's
flower district 40 years ago. The photographs brilliantly capture
the jazz era between 1957 and 1964, when musical greats Thelonius
Monk, Zoot Sims and Stan Getz would come to 821 Sixth Ave. for
after-hours jam sessions. Smith wisely recorded hundreds of hours
of the sessions on reel-to-reel tape.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quitters who win: Contrary to what our parents may have told
us, staying on the same job until you retire doesn't work anymore.
At least that's what U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.50) found in a
survey of the current worker-shortage job market. Those who remain
loyal to employers usually are stuck with raises of 4 percent or
less. As Atlantan Chuck Dressler discovered, the best way to get
ahead is to quit. Dressler had worked as a bartender at Red Lobster
for less than two years when headhunters called and lured him away
to Mick's for $10,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Undressed Net: Men who are embarrassed to go into lingerie
shops will be relieved to know they can view _ and purchase _
feminine undergarments online. The new Yahoo! ($3.98) provides an
intimate guide to the best places to buy lingerie and other
fashions on the Internet. The bad news: You still have to know your
significant other's correct size.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
