<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOZART-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHWARZ TO QUIT AFTER 17 YEARS AS LEADER OF MOSTLY MOZART 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a move that Lincoln Center officials say caught
them by surprise, Gerard Schwarz has said that he will relinquish
the music directorship of the Mostly Mozart Festival when his
contract ends in 2001. Schwarz, who became the festival's first
music director in 1984 after two years as its music adviser, said
on Sunday that he had told Nathan Leventhal, president of Lincoln
Center, on Wednesday about his desire to leave the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, 52, said in an interview that when his current contract
ends he will have been at the festival for 20 years and that he
wanted to devote himself more fully to his directorships of the
Seattle Symphony and the New York Chamber Symphony, as well as to
composing and arranging. Although he has maintained a home in New
York, he has become increasingly involved in the musical and civic
life of Seattle during his 17-year association with the orchestra
there. As music director of Mostly Mozart, he conducted the
festival's orchestra and oversaw its choice of programs in
consultation with Lincoln Center's programming department.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal said yesterday that he was ``surprised and also
disappointed, because we were coming off a really strong season in
which the orchestra was playing, by all accounts, better than it
ever has.'' He said that Lincoln Center had not started to search
for a successor. In a letter dated Friday, Leventhal asked Schwarz
to accept the title conductor emeritus ``to signify what I am
confident will be your continued association with Lincoln Center
for many years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz said, ``I've been thinking about leaving Mostly Mozart
for a while, because I've been doing it a lot of years.'' He
continued: ``When I was hired as music advisor and later music
director, my charge was to expand the repertory _ because the
festival at that time had not even played all the Mozart piano
concertos _ as well as to make the orchestra cohesive and bring it
some international fame. I feel I've accomplished that.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been credited with upgrading the freelance orchestra,
partly by bringing in members of his New York Chamber Symphony. He
also transformed what had become a formulaic festival in the early
1980's, by incorporating concert operas, rarely heard arrangements
of Mozart works by 20th-century composers and even some
20th-century examples of Neo-Classicism.
</P>
<P>
   But his role at Mostly Mozart has also been diminished
considerably in recent years, starting with cutbacks in the Mostly
Mozart schedule to accommodate the more expansive Lincoln Center
Festival, which began in 1996. Schwarz fought against the cutbacks
and lost, as Mostly Mozart was reduced from seven weeks to four.
</P>
<P>
   More recently Lincoln Center's programming department, directed
by Jane S. Moss, has taken greater control of the festival's
programming, giving a greater emphasis to guest ensembles and
period-instrument bands and reducing the visibility of the Mostly
Mozart Festival Orchestra. Last summer Ms. Moss said that Schwarz
fully endorsed these changes, and he did not argue the point. But
of the season's 19 programs, only 8 were performed by the festival
orchestra, and of those, Schwarz conducted only 3, including the
opening and closing concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Both Schwarz and Leventhal denied that frictions over
programming led to Schwarz's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what it is,'' Schwarz said. ``This summer I took the
Mostly Mozart orchestra on its ninth tour of Japan, and when I got
back, it was time to begin the season in Seattle. There was not a
lot of time for reflection, for studying scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal said he was discussing the question of Schwarz's
successor with Ms. Moss and Beverly Sills, the chairman of Lincoln
Center, but that no one had been approached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't know what form the search will take,''
Leventhal said. ``He was our first music director, so we've never
done a search before. There's no precedent. But Mostly Mozart is an
important priority for this institution, it's one of our most
popular programs. We'll want to cast our net widely and consider
everyone who is appropriate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
