<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DELTA-BLUES-ART-2TAKE     10-25 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-BLUES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOME OF THE BLUES, SINGING A NEW TUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(nk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLARKSDALE, Miss. _ Driving into this sleepy upper Delta city
toward the crossroads where Highway 49 meets Highway 61, the first
thing one sees is a sign that boasts ``Clarksdale: Home of the Big
Frog.'' There is little mention that Clarksdale is famous for more
than amphibians: It is probably the most legendary blues site in
the South. Dozens of blues legends were born or lived in this city
or its county, Coahoma, among them John Lee Hooker, Muddy Waters,
Charley Patton, Pinetop Perkins, Son House and W.C. Handy. Nearly
every Delta blues musician of note performed in Clarksdale
regularly, including Robert Johnson, Howlin' Wolf and Sonny Boy
Williamson. And many of them died here, most notably Bessie Smith.
To this day a visitor arriving on a lucky night can see a venerable
musician rocking the barroom at one of the dozen crumbling juke
joints downtown.
</P>
<P>
   More than the blues came to life in Clarksdale: The soul singer
Sam Cooke grew up here, as did Ike Turner and Jackie Brenston, who
recorded what some credit as the first rock 'n' roll song, ``Rocket
88.'' Local legend has it that a young Elvis Presley used to come
through and hang around the radio station (home to one of the
country's first black disk jockeys) in hopes of getting a chance to
sing on the air.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, however, the only people who recognized the city's
heritage were the international blues tourists who trickled in each
year. There was little for them to see: a small, homey annual blues
festival and a Delta Blues Museum tucked into the Carnegie Library
there. The county had already let the House of Blues, the music
club chain, dismantle the shack Muddy Waters once lived in and cart
it off on a national tour.
</P>
<P>
   But something strange has happened in Clarksdale the last year
or two. As if awakening from amnesia, many whites here have
suddenly become aware of the town's blues heritage. Much of this is
owed to a handful of unusual characters: John Ruskey, a blues fan
who came floating down the Mississippi River on a raft from
Memphis, landing in Clarksdale to stay; a home builder named
Kinchen O'Keefe, better known as Bubba, who funneled his savings
into creating a mini-tourism empire downtown; a former
schoolteacher, Molly Shields, who found a way to keep her aging
boyfriend off the dangerous power lines he works on by opening what
she calls a ``blues pawn shop.'' There are Cathy and James Butler,
who decided to subvert the legacy of the Hopson Plantation,
inherited from Mrs. Butler's forebears, by renting out the
sharecropper's shacks and turning the company store into a social
club. Each has been trying to build a bridge to the city's cultural
past, and one result may be to take Clarksdale into the next
century as one of the South's most irresistible tourist meccas.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as O'Keefe said, ``We've got gold in the stream that needs
mining.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new casinos in nearby Tunica County bringing in over 1
million visitors a year, Clarksdale _ which was a stop on President
Clinton's four-day poverty tour this summer _ has experienced the
impact that tourism can have on an economy. It has invested several
million dollars into developing an area it calls Blues Alley
(complete with a John Lee Hooker Lane) and it is working on putting
its atrophied bus and train stations in order, partly to lure some
of the tourists visiting Tunica and Memphis to the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to keep the tourists in town for longer than
30 minutes,'' said Butler, who in addition to helping run Hopson is
also the city's director of public works. ``But the one thing I
feel everybody's kept in their minds is that things can't get too
clean and flashy. Keep it real or we won't have what we have now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarksdale first came to life in the late 1800s as a lumber camp
established by John Clark, whose daughter, Blanche, inspired the
character of the same name in ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' by
Tennessee Williams, who also made his home in Clarksdale. With the
advent of railways, Clarksdale blossomed in the early 20th century,
becoming one of the most prosperous cities of its size in the
nation and known as ``little New York'' because of all its
millionaires. The city was where the majority black population came
to shop, celebrate and listen to music on days off. But with World
War II and the mechanization of the cotton industry, the city's
population ebbed as sharecroppers moved to cities in the North, and
bankruptcy abounded. Today Clarksdale has been cited as one of the
poorest cities in the poorest state in the nation, with 30 percent
of Clarksdale's residents below the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the city's acknowledged treasures for over 20 years has
been the Delta Blues Museum. But last year the museum's director
died, and a successor has not been appointed. Ruskey, a curator who
had left the museum to work as a river guide, stepped in to take
care of museum business along with Mae Smith, who ran the gift
shop. They helped reopen the Delta Blues Museum on Oct. 10 in a
beautifully remodeled freight station bought by the city in Blues
Alley.
</P>
<P>
   On opening day, visitors wandered through three rooms of
temporary exhibitions, including a wax figure of Muddy Waters, a
headstone that once stood on Mississippi Fred McDowell's grave (it
had been replaced because his name was misspelled), photographs of
blues legends and dozens of other displays chronicling the history
of blues and soul in the Delta.
</P>
<P>
   On a concrete stage out by the old train tracks, local
musicians, including Ruskey and many teen-agers who were taught to
play by the museum's blues education fund (most notably the group
J.T. Express, favorites at nearby juke joints like the Do Drop
Inn), performed for the small crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The bluesman and museum teacher Johnnie Billington, who closed
the show, walked around in the sweltering afternoon in a coat and
tie. Since instructing his students to always dress formally in
public so that they will be treated with respect, he has never been
seen otherwise, residents say, even when mowing his yard on a
sweltering summer afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A block and a half from the museum festivities, O'Keefe stood
behind the counter in his new store, the Sunflower River Trading
Company, surrounded by the local crafts, music and videos he was
selling. With the boarded-up, discolored and dilapidated
storefronts around it, the store looks like a rose that somehow
sprouted from quicksand. Like many others here, O'Keefe has a story
about growing up in blues country without ever being a part of it.
``Mississippi Fred McDowell used to pump gas for my father,'' he
said. ``He used to go to festivals in Europe, then come back and
pump gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Now O'Keefe has embarked on a one-man publicity and renovation
campaign for Clarksdale. Across the street from his new store he
bought the building that once housed WROX radio. He turned the
ground floor into a children's store and the top floor into a
professional-looking dance studio for local children, including his
own. Between those floors are the empty radio studios where a young
Elvis Presley used to pay the owner money to sing on the air, Ike
Turner worked as a janitor and Sam Cooke was a protege of the disk
jockey Early Wright, the Soul Man. That part of the building, he
said, will become a museum and studio celebrating the station's
glory days. He also plans to build the city's first cafe in the
building and to organize package tours of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Several blocks away Ms. Shields and Brower opened one of the
city's odder attractions in June. Brower was working on the city's
power lines when they decided to find a different line of work. So
they opened Carmen's Blues Pawn Shop (named after Brower's
daughter) downtown, where they also sell tourist souvenirs like
autographed CD's by newer area blues acts like Super Chikan, key
chains, and T-shirts. On the wall outside, their nephews have
painted the city's first blues mural: giant caricatures of John Lee
Hooker, Bessie Smith and Muddy Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shields said she was brought up in Clarksdale but never knew
how famous her home was in blues lore until recently. ``We get
people from all over the world here,'' she said. ``Last week we got
31 Norwegians. When people come to town, other than the blues
museum there's nothing. And we wanted to have something where they
can stand outside and take pictures and say these three people on
this mural are famous and they're from Clarksdale.''
</P>
<P>
   Overnight guests began coming this year to Hopson Plantation,
where the first mechanized cotton picker was developed and used and
where musicians like Pinetop Perkins and Wesley Jefferson, the
Mississippi Junebug, once lived. But in a twist on Southern
plantation tourism, visitors do not stay in the big house but
rather in the sharecropper shacks out back, which still retain some
possessions of the original occupants. The owners say they plan to
invite touring bands for warm-up shows in what used to be the
company store, which has been fitted with a small stage and
converted into a social club.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Clarksdale remains a city in transition. Butler said
bankers tend to scoff when he tries to offer a sharecropper's shack
as collateral on a loan. And days go by when O'Keefe doesn't sell a
single item in his store.
</P>
<P>
   ``This weekend was a hard weekend, because you struggle and say,
`Why am I trying to do this?''' O'Keefe said. ``But if I don't do
it, who will? If you turn your back on them, buildings start to
decay and the people with stories about them start to die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
