<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8025 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NEW-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-25 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE NEW NEW THING:' MAKING REAL PROFITS FROM A VISION OF A
PRODUCT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif. , Wash.)  (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Michael Lewis' entertaining new book tells it, the seeds of
the Internet boom were planted one day in the early 1990s when the
entrepreneur Jim Clark glimpsed a friend's huge new yacht. The ever
competitive Clark decided he wanted an even bigger, better boat _ a
boat that could be completely run by computers _ and in 1995, to
finance his 157-foot-long dream, he decided to take the company he
had just founded public. That company was named Netscape, and its
initial public offering not only made Clark a billionaire (and more
than paid for the construction of his dream yacht), but it also
helped set off a frenzied wave of Internet speculation that
effectively redrew the financial landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lewis writes, Clark's envious glimpse of his friend's
boat turned out to be ``one of those small perturbations that
radically altered the world we inhabit.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``The New New Thing'' oversimplifies history for the
sake of making that history accessible to the lay reader, Lewis
does a sprightly job of conjuring up the heady world of Silicon
Valley and its reigning ethos of innovation. In short, he does for
the late 1990s world of techno-geeks and software cowboys what he
did in ``Liar's Poker'' for the 1980s Wall Street world of traders
and arbitrageurs.
</P>
<P>
   The focal point of ``The New New Thing'' is Clark, the founder
of Netscape and two other wildly lucrative companies, Silicon
Graphics and Healtheon. Clark is to Silicon Valley, Lewis argues,
what Silicon Valley is to America, and America is to the rest of
the world. He embodies the forces of risk-taking and disruptive
change, and the instinct for the ``new new thing'' _ the concept
that will, given a small push, ignite the marketplace and change
the world. Clark is the swaggering new American frontiersman,
boldly going where no man has gone before, then moving on to yet
another vista while others try to domesticate his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   In relating the story of Jim Clark, Lewis uses a sort of Tom
Wolfe approach, enlivening his account of complicated financial
deals and even more complicated engineering feats with snappy cameoportraits, exclamatory descriptions and lots of subjective
judgments. Lewis makes no attempt to hide the fact that he sees
Clark as a kind of genius, a utopian ``on an endless search for
some unattainable solution,'' a conceptual artist whose ``talent
for anarchy'' happens to be uniquely suited to this particular
moment in history.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Clark, Bill Gates emerges from this book as a
passive self-promoter who wants the future ``to look exactly like
the present'' and whose company, Microsoft, doesn't want to
discover the new new thing but simply tame it. Even more
dinosaurlike, in Lewis' opinion, are those managers and financiers
who still try to operate by 1950s standards of consensus _ dull,
gray-flannel organization men with whom Clark has continually
clashed.
</P>
<P>
   By tracing the evolution of Clark's three companies _ Silicon
Graphics (which pioneered the possibilities of computer-generated
three-dimensional graphics); the Internet browser Netscape, and the
latest, Healtheon (which aims to computerize health care
management) _ Lewis gives the reader a quixotic guided tour through
Silicon Valley while showing how its success stories revolutionized
American business.
</P>
<P>
   As the successful public offerings of Netscape and Healtheon
demonstrated, Lewis observes, ``the Internet formula for success
turned traditional capitalism on its head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally,'' he writes, ``a company persuaded people to
invest in it by making profits. Now it persuaded people to invest
in it first and hoped the profits would follow.''
</P>
<P>
   In this new world, ``skepticism was not a sign of
intelligence''; it ``was a sin.'' In this new world, ``the
perception of success led to success, and the perception of failure
to failure.'' In this new world, ``You had to show that you were
the company not of the present but of the future. The most
appealing companies became those in a state of pure possibility.''
In other words, Lewis concludes, ``The U.S. capital markets
acquired the personal predilections'' of that anarchic maverick,
Jim Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lewis briefly sketches Clark's background _ an
impoverished childhood in the small town of Plainview, Tex., a
depressing stint in the Navy, and eventually a doctorate in
computer science _ he, like his subject, does not dwell on the
past. He is less interested in understanding the roots of Clark's
restlessness and ambition than he is in documenting Clark's latest
enthusiasms and brainstorms. To that end much of this book is
devoted to chronicling Clark's efforts to get Healtheon off the
ground while at the same time launching Hyperion, his bigger,
better, computerized yacht.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the disruptive effect his hero has had on
traditional business methods, Lewis also spends a lot of time
showing us the domino effect _ sometimes exhilarating, sometimes
anxiety-inducing _ Clark has had on the people who work for him:
from the brilliant young engineers whom he helped make into
millionaires; to the scrambling venture capitalists desperate to
get in on his latest project, to the befuddled members of his yacht
crew doggedly trying to reconcile new-fangled computerized wizardry
with old-fashioned seamanship.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as Healtheon is making him a ``real after-tax
billionaire,'' Clark is already moving on to the next new things: a
company called My CFO that will help rich people organize their
finances, and yes, plans for another boat: ``a sailboat half again
as big as Hyperion, or a bit longer than 250 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE NEW NEW THING
</P>
<P>
   A Silicon Valley Story'
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Lewis
</P>
<P>
   268 pages. W.W. Norton &AMP; Company. $25.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8026 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-airforceaudit26-cox     10-25 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-airforceaudit26-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACCOUNTS MISUSED IN IMPROVEMENTS TO AIR FORCE ACADEMY HOMES,
REPORT SAYS
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Air Force's already strained operations and
maintenance accounts have been used improperly to pay for
renovations to the homes of the superintendent and commandant of
the Air Force Academy, an audit released Monday has found.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Air Force Auditing Agency, requested by Air
Force Secretary F. Whitten Peters, also concluded that many of the
improvements couldn't be justified, including $4,200 for a
fireplace mantel that was added in 1998 ``at the occupant's
request.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the audit's findings:
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 remodeling of the kitchen at Carlton House, home of the
superintendent, cost $308,000, more than twice the budgeted
allowance because of upgrades in counter tops and appliances, many
of which were only a year old. The additional money covered $17,000
for a 90-second cycle dishwasher that auditors said didn't seem
warranted.
</P>
<P>
   The new kitchen at the Carlton House was done even though the
justifying documentation mentioned only poor lighting, ventilation
and a refrigerator that was ``not functional for a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Improvements at Otis House, the commandant's home, include
$40,000 to move a bathroom wall to widen an adjoining bedroom's
interior dimension by one foot.
</P>
<P>
   $14,000 was set aside for converting the Otis House's charcoal
grill to natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a break! $14,000?'' said U.S. Rep. David L. Hobson,
R-Springfield, who heads the military construction subcommittee in
the House. ``I think this stuff is outrageous. These people are
living like kings and queens and the troops are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobson, who is expecting results for a similar audit he
requested from the Navy, said that while he appreciates the
recommendations offered by the Air Force audit to ensure that
operations money isn't used on generals' quarters in the future, he
wants to see someone punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all say they won't do it again,'' he said, ``but unless
somebody is reprimanded it will happen again. Somebody had to order
this for it to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The two 1930's-era homes at the Air Force Academy are private
residences that also are used for public Academy gatherings, such
as graduation parties. For years, the Air Force has split the cost
of the residences between operations and military housing accounts.
Public sections of the houses are maintained by the operations and
maintenance budget, and private sections such as bedrooms are
financed through military housing.
</P>
<P>
   But the audit found that money crossed designations with little,
if any accountability. The oversight panel that must approve
expenditures at the Carlton House is chaired by the general who
lives in the house.
</P>
<P>
   And the audit found little logic behind the way the Air Force
designated rooms either public or private anyway. For instance,
although both the Carlton House and Otis House are used equally for
public functions _ a little more than once a month _ the Otis
kitchen is designated as private, while the Carlton kitchen is
considered public.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when there's no accountability,'' Hobson
said. ``It also just shows an arrogance of position, where people
forgot the public trust.''
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
