<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8027 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-GAZA-WESTBANK-ART-2TA     10-25 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAZA-WESTBANK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFE PASSAGE ROUTE BETWEEN GAZA AND WEST BANK IS OPENED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT18 and 19 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EREZ CROSSING, Gaza Strip _ Khader Juneed, 23, had never set
foot outside Gaza in his life, and his family didn't want him to,
either. His parents feared he might never return, and so when he
came home proudly last week with a shiny new Israeli-issued permit
that would allow him to travel to the West Bank, they forbade him
to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, Juneed said, he acted as if he were leaving for
work. He put his construction boots in one black plastic bag and
his painter's pants in another. And then he hitched a ride to the
border with Israel without saying goodbye, not even to his wife and
three children.
</P>
<P>
   As he waited in line to be searched by Israeli soldiers, Juneed
opened a green vinyl folder to show off the magnetic crossing card
that he, like many other young and underemployed Gazans, sees as an
exit permit from a life without a future.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life I lived behind the high walls of Gaza, like a
prisoner behind a fence,'' he said. ``Now I am grabbing at the
opportunity to know the Palestinian world on the other side. To
Gazans, the West Bank seems like the land of plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   The first ``safe passage'' route between the Gaza Strip and the
West Bank opened Monday, re-establishing a lifeline between the
divided portions of the Palestinian world. The opening went
smoothly, with relatively quick processing at the border and barely
any protest from Israelis, except for six men with an angry banner
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   It marked another concrete step forward in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace effort that was revived by Ehud Barak,
who took office as prime minister in July. But the route came four
years after it was first promised and four weeks late under the
timetable of the latest Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   And the recent delay, caused by haggling over procedures that
revealed distrust on both sides, hinted at the difficulties that
lie ahead as Barak aims to forge a final peace agreement under a
tight deadline _ by next September.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, little fanfare marked a moment the Palestinians have
long awaited, the re-creation of a link between the two cultures
and the two economies that make up the Palestinian territories _
and the would-be Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   About 11 a.m., the first of about 20 buses simply rolled away
from Gaza through the 28-mile corridor through mostly desolate
Israeli countryside to the southern West Bank town of Tarqumiya,
near Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the day, some 600 Gazans, mostly young men,
made the journey through checkpoints on both sides, with a total of
four document inspections, two computerized, before they were
cleared to board local buses to their final destinations.
</P>
<P>
   For some it meant a reconnection with long-lost relatives, but
for most, like Juneed, it offered vague but hopeful possibilities _
maybe of a better job, maybe of nothing more than a brief respite
from the grinding insularity of Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at us, hanging out the windows, waving,'' Hamed Malahi,
22, said as he pressed his face against the cool windowpane of the
first bus. ``We look just like the freed prisoners.'' He was
referring to the Palestinians recently released, in buses, from
Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   Official enthusiasm was tempered Monday by an afternoon incident
in Bethlehem that vividly evoked the days of intense conflict.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli soldier shot and killed a Palestinian man, whom
Palestinians identified as Musa Abu Ihlaiel, 28, a souvenir vendor.
Israeli army officials said the soldier had opened fire after the
man had tried to stab him during a routine document check at the
roadblock near Rachel's Tomb.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians poured into the streets in response and hurled
rocks and bottles at Israeli soldiers, who responded by firing
rubber-coated bullets and releasing tear gas, witnesses said. Five
Palestinians and one Israeli soldier were lightly wounded.
</P>
<P>
   In Gaza, too, there were some tensions, although no violence, as
Palestinians who were denied access to the safe-passage route
complained about the secrecy of the Israeli application process.
</P>
<P>
   The route has been a tender subject for both sides, bringing
into relief Israel's anxieties about abetting terrorism by linking
the Palestinian territories and the Palestinians' anxieties about
the way the Israelis control their movement.
</P>
<P>
   Some 10,000 Gazans have applied for yearlong permits _ magnetic
cards that look like driver's licenses _ and so far about 2,000
have been granted, said Ziad Alabed, the Palestinian official in
charge of safe passage.
</P>
<P>
   Of the applications that have been processed, about 11 percent
have been turned down with no explanation, even though the passage
was supposed to be open even to Palestinians without security
clearance. Some who were turned down for the card will be allowed
access twice a week on army-escorted buses, Alabed said.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the rejected were posted on the wall of the Civil
Affairs Ministry in Gaza, as if on a blacklist, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Few Palestinians _ about 200 _ have applied to travel the route
in the other direction, from the relatively more affluent and
liberal West Bank to Gaza, where wages are much lower and
unemployment much higher.
</P>
<P>
   This makes it clear that at least at first, the route will serve
partly as a one-way labor migration path, testing the West Bank's
limited capacity to absorb unskilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   Juneed, a thin man with a long, sad face, said he had been
earning $1.25 an hour on construction jobs, when he could find
them, and living with his family of five in a single room in the
Balatiya refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents had to help us, which was humiliating to me as a
man,'' he said. ``I have one clear goal in the West Bank: better
job, better money.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gazan merchant, Amir Sarhi, offered him some counsel: ``Go to
Bethlehem, young man. That is where the money is, what with the big
plans for the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   At the checkpoint in Erez, the Gazans filed through processing
lines as Israeli soldiers checked their documents on a computer.
Right before Juneed came to the window, a computer alert sounded,
and after 15 minutes soldiers led the man in front of him away.
</P>
<P>
   Inside his windbreaker Juneed was sweating profusely, and he
sighed with relief when he was ushered through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy,'' he said, as he boarded a bus and took a seat,
shyly smiling. ``This is like a holiday.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Descending at Tarqumiya, where the dry, intense heat of Gaza had
given way to the cool autumn winds of the rocky hills, Juneed
looked about him uncertainly. He had no idea what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he tried to hook up with a neighbor from his refugee
camp, who jumped into a taxi and abandoned him. Surely the next
bus, he said, kicking his worn loafers in the dirt road, would
bring a friend.
</P>
<P>
   He borrowed a cellular phone, called home and admitted to his
sister that he had taken off, with only $50 in his pocket and the
phone number of a distant relative scribbled on a paper scrap. He
cried.
</P>
<P>
   Sarhi, the merchant, tried to console him. ``As far as you have
Arabs around you, you have people you can trust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the next bus arrived, Juneed nodded, spotting someone
getting off. ``I knew it _ there is a friend,'' he said. ``He may
not know any more than me, but I will stick with him and we will be
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed unfazed when the friend barely grunted a greeting his
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inshallah, God willing,'' Juneed said, waving. ``May all your
faces guide me on my way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
