<HEADLINE>
LIFTING A MUSTY CURTAIN FOR A PEEK INSIDE THE CRYPT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany)   By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the gravy-dark recesses of the mind (and backstage
at the New Victory Theater on 42d Street) strange phantasms scuttle
beneath the floorboards and rattle locked doors, demanding to be
let out.
</P>
<P>
   As audiences titter nervously at the Victorian grotesqueries of
``Shockheaded Peter,'' a London troupe's zany ``junk opera'' based
on the 19th-century German children's classic ``Struwwelpeter,''
another drama is unfolding behind the curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Martyn Jacques, the falsetto-voiced accordion player who
improbably set to music Dr. Heinrich Hoffmann's satirical warnings
against being a slob, playing with matches and thumb-sucking,
crouches under a trapdoor, waiting to be hauled onstage by his
(real) pigtail.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Pocock, the sinister Victorian maid (and puppeteer), also
creeps beneath the floor. Graeme Gilmour, her fellow puppeteer,
helps manipulate the stork that brings a couple the child they
yearn for _ until they see what a slovenly monster little Peter is.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Bleach, the ghoulish MC with a weakness for Shakespearean
tragedy, clutches the curtain around his neck and contorts his body
to ``levitate'' his seemingly detached head until his wig falls
off. Backstage he rushes to switch his battered top hat and
tattered tails for a molded baby boy costume (anatomically
correct).
</P>
<P>
   Tamzin Griffin, the poor mother, ducks behind the curtain to
turn into a monster herself, donning a tangled shaggy wig and
yardlong fingernails. Anthony Cairns, her suffering husband, also
gets fitted with the clawlike nails and the red nose of a helpless
inebriate driven to drink by _ what else? _ his incorrigible child.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Jacques' accompanists, the sepulchral Adrian Stout and
the impish Adrian Huge, climb catwalks to turn up unexpectedly at
the upper windows of the set.
</P>
<P>
   Bleach, who developed the show several years ago with the
directors Phelim McDermott and Julian Crouch said that anything
that goes wrong is incorporated into the plot of the show, which
closes on Sunday. As for the script _ well, said Bleach, ``there is
no script.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
