<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SAFE-PASSAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS FLOCK THROUGH `SAFE PASSAGE' ROAD LINKING GAZA WITH
WEST BANK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EREZ CHECKPOINT, Gaza Strip _ Mohammed Ghanem, a diminutive
Palestinian clutching a backpack, edged to the front of a long line
of men and waited to board a bus that would take him on his first
journey to the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   At 19, Ghanem, a new recruit in the Palestinian police, had
never been outside of Gaza, a tiny strip of territory wedged
between Israel, the Mediterranean Sea and the Egyptian Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he and hundreds of other Palestinians finally made
the hourlong trek on the long-awaited ``safe passage'' through
Israel. The 28-mile stretch of road for the first time links Gaza
with the West Bank, the two areas under Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the first time in my life to go there,'' Ghanem
said, moving swiftly past Palestinian guards toward an orange taxi
that would drive him to the bus. ``I can finally see (the rest of)
my homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians said they hoped the passage would help unite the
West Bank and Gaza, politically, economically and socially. Many
Palestinians consider the opening of the safe passage as an
important step toward statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those waiting at the Erez Checkpoint said they were
going to visit relatives, others to work, and still others simply
to see what life was like for their Palestinian brethren in towns
and villages that most had been barred from visiting for years due
to Israeli security restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Israel has imposed stringent security measures that
have prevented most of the 3 million Palestinians from traveling
between the West Bank and Gaza. A limited number were issued
permits to leave their respective territories for work in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to breathe the air,'' said Said Lasda, a 23-year-old
on his way to the southern West Bank town of Hebron to visit
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the passage underscored the good will that has
characterized relations between Israelis and Palestinians since
Israel's new centrist prime minister, Ehud Barak, took office in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Around mid-morning, Israeli and Palestinian officials celebrated
the opening with a modest ceremony at the checkpoint, a massive
area of concrete, metal detectors and turnstiles manned by Israeli
soldiers at one end and Palestinian police at the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very happy that we are implementing the agreement,''
said Jamil Tarifi, the Palestinian minister for civil affairs, who
helped negotiate the safe passage accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been discussing it for five years,'' Tarifi said.
``We're very happy we can start operating it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the first Palestinian car drove up to be
checked by Israeli security personnel wearing white gloves that can
detect traces of explosives. After 10 minutes, the driver, a
Palestinian official, was given permission to head into Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this will be a step toward geographic unity between the
West Bank and Gaza Strip,'' said the official, Mousa Abu Saadeh.
</P>
<P>
   By 11 a.m., the first ordinary Palestinians began making the
hourlong trek through the rolling forests and farmland of central
Israel to the Tarkumia checkpoint at the southern end of the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people want to go because they (feel) they are in a big
prison (in Gaza),'' said Mahmoud Audeh, a 39-year-old government
worker on his way to shop in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to feel a little freer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the agreement, any Palestinian can use the passage
by first obtaining a metallic identity card that is valid for one
year, except those deemed security risks by Israel. But even they
can use the passage twice weekly by riding special buses escorted
by Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
   Most other Palestinians also will use buses designated for the
trip. A limited number will be allowed to use personal cars. Those
in cars will have 90 minutes to reach the other side. Anyone who
arrives late will be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the safe passage was to consist of four specially
marked roads across Israel. After months of haggling, negotiators
reduced the number of designated roads to two. A second passageway
that will lead to the northern West Bank is supposed to open soon.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israelis said they were worried that the passage could make
it easier for terrorists to travel. But most said they hoped the
passage would run smoothly. A handful of Israelis demonstrated
against the passage just north of the checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are afraid,'' said Shimon Cohen, the mayor of Hof Ashkelon,
an Israeli city north of Gaza near the southern route. ``But we
hope the transit will be safe with no stops, and we hope it will
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism between the areas was expected to increase, with
hundreds of West Bank Palestinians heading for Gaza's Mediterranean
coast.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the men waiting in line Monday said they had come in
search of work on the more prosperous West Bank. Most said they had
come to visit the West Bank because, after so many years, they
finally could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to look around,'' said Rami Abu Ata, a 21-year-old
Gazan waiting in line at the Tarkoumiya checkpoint at the entrance
to the West Bank. ``I've never been here before.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
