<HEADER>
A8033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HELMS-RACE-NYTR &LR;      10-25 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELMS-RACE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, HELMS AND COMPANY LAND GOP IN HOT WATER OVER RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans find themselves in a familiar place
these days on matters of race _ on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   With his threat last week to block the nomination of a black
woman and former senator to an ambassadorship, Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., has helped reignite a long-running and divisive debate
about whether his party antagonizes minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   While that suggestion infuriates many Republicans, Helms' action
follows the Senate's rejection earlier this month of a black judge
in Missouri nominated to the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, the climate has turned ugly. Democrats have
stopped short of labeling the Republican Party as racist _ but just
barely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not calling them racist,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, the minority leader. ``But I am simply saying this: I think
it raises some very serious questions about the perception, the
attitude of some on the other side when it comes to minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders counter that the Democrats are playing the
race card by impugning the motives of their GOP colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charges are baseless and blasphemous, and it's a dangerous
game,'' said John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Helms has relied on prepared statements to call
into question former Illinois Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun's fitness to
serve as ambassador to New Zealand. Moseley-Braun, who lost
re-election last year, faced charges that she misused campaign
funds during her tenure.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Helms' earlier comment to a Capitol Hill newspaper
that raised eyebrows. Helms said Moseley-Braun should apologize for
her 1993 opposition to Senate approval of a design patent for the
United Daughters of the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Several black lawmakers said they were insulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly those of us who are students are history know that
the Daughters of the Confederacy grew out of the Confederate
states, which grew out of concerns over slavery, which grew out of
race,'' said Rep. Jim Clyburn, D-S.C., chairman of the
Congressional Black Caucus. ``No matter what you may say about the
War of Northern Aggression _ and that's in quotes _ the fact
remains that slavery was a very big part of the Civil War.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the fight over Missouri Judge Ronnie White has
stirred deep passions. Nominated by President Clinton to serve on
the federal bench, White was rejected by the Senate four weeks ago
on a party line vote. Republicans characterized him as weak on
crime, and they faulted him for overturning some death penalty
cases. White, however, affirmed 70 percent of the death penalty
cases brought to him for review.
</P>
<P>
   Minority groups point to a study by the Constitution Project, a
bipartisan group affiliated with Georgetown University, showing
that white candidates for judicial posts were twice as likely to
win confirmation from the last Congress as minority nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a pattern: Blacks need not apply,'' Clyburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say that each case must be evaluated on its own
merits. They're quick to point out that Rep. J.C. Watts, a black
Republican from Oklahoma, occupies a higher leadership post than
any black Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans complain that they are subjected to a
double-standard because Democratic lawmakers can cast votes that
arguably hurt minority interests without being tagged as racists.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Harrison, co-chairwoman of the Republican National
Committee, noted Clinton's comment this month in which he compared
Irish leaders fighting over a peace plan to drunks in a barroom
brawl.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was covered, but it hardly drew the kind of
attention that the Moseley-Braun and White fights have generated.
``There seems to be selective outrage here,'' Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said it makes no sense for Republicans to alienate
minority voters because they make up a larger share of the
population each year. Two years ago, the RNC launched its New
Majority Council, an outreach program to blacks, Hispanics, and
women.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have a challenge. Time and again, election returns
point to a yawning chasm between black support for Democratic
candidates, which runs 90 percent or better, and support for
Republican contenders, which has rarely broken 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1998 races, black voter turnout proved pivotal in
several Southern campaigns, including governors' races in Alabama,
Georgia, and South Carolina, all of which Democrats won.
</P>
<P>
   David Bositis, a political analyst at the Joint Center for
Political and Economic Studies, predicted recent congressional
action would only further drive minorities away from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started out with a high level of mistrust in the black
community, and they've done so many things to reinforce that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bositis dismissed GOP complaints of a double standard, saying
that the recent nomination fights must be viewed in the context of
the Republican Party's history. That includes opposition to civil
rights legislation, budget cuts to social programs that benefit
minority communities, and the association on the part of some GOP
lawmakers with the Council of Conservative Citizens, which civil
rights advocates describe as a white supremacist organization.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bositis of the Republican Party and black voters: ``It's
like they're strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin is a correspondent in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8035 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-IDAHO-INDIANS-ART-735     10-25 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDAHO-INDIANS-ART-735(TRIMS)(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBE THAT HELPED MAKE AMERICAN HISTORY ASKS FOR HELP TO COME
HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALMON, Idaho _ Here in the valley where the Shoshone teen-ager
Sacajawea led Lewis and Clark to one of the most serendipitous
encounters in the annals of discovery, the stores are full of
Indian art, the pastures are grazed by Indian-bred horses, and the
land itself is imprinted with Indian names. But there are no
American Indians here.
</P>
<P>
   The Lemhi Shoshone, living links to the teen-age girl who was
instrumental in leading the Corps of Discovery over the Continental
Divide in 1805, have been all but erased from this place they have
called home for hundreds of years. The 400 or so Lemhi live on a
reservation 200 miles south of here, on desert land set aside for
two much bigger tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Orphans in an arid land, the Lemhi say they have been down so
long that they use an ironic phrase to describe their current
status. ``Basically, we are the Indians to the other Indians,''
said Rod Ariwite, a leader of the Shoshone Lemhi.
</P>
<P>
   But the tribe's luck may be about to change. Spurred on by an
extraordinary surge of interest in the journey of Lewis and Clark,
hoopla over a new dollar coin honoring Sacajawea and recent
scholarly finds that bolster Lemhi legal claims, the Indians from
the west side of the Continental Divide are stirred by their last
best hope for a homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The Lemhi have asked President Clinton to carve out a small
piece of federal land in the Salmon River country on the
Idaho-Montana border as a place where the tribe can tell its story
to the hordes of Lewis and Clark history buffs, honor their dead
and try to stitch some of the past to the present.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the only visible Indian in this valley is the Salmon
High School mascot, a chieftain who represents ``the Home of the
Savages,'' as the school sign says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have Sacajawea heritage days, they have Sacajawea arts
and crafts, they have everything but the real Indians who are
Sacajawea's people in the valley,'' said Ariwite, an Air Force
veteran and high school principal who grew up in Salmon but now
lives in New Mexico and in Fort Hall, Idaho. ``The feeling we get
is, `We don't want you here, but we want your Sacajawea
heritage.'''
</P>
<P>
   The white leaders of this community say they revere the most
famous native of the valley but are ambiguous about any land being
set aside for the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all believe Sacajawea is not only the most famous Indian,
but the most famous woman in America,'' said Stan Davis, mayor of
this town of 3,000, set in an isolated Rocky Mountain valley of
heart-stopping beauty. ``And the way things are going now, with our
timber, mining and fishing in trouble, it's almost like we've come
full circle. We know what the Indians went through.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While other tribes have spent decades going through long and
usually futile efforts to regain full tribal recognition, the Lemhi
are making a direct appeal to the conscience of the current
occupant of the White House _ a familiar Lemhi tack. In 1875, the
tribe was given a small reservation in this valley by executive
order of President Ulysses S. Grant, who was impressed by the
Lemhi's unique role in Western history and their record of
cooperation with the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   That reservation was overrun by Idaho settlers, who used fish
traps to block the once prodigious salmon runs. The starving Lemhi
abandoned their home in 1907, on a march to the south punctuated by
wails and tears. Virtually every attempt at redress in the 20th
century was held up by government assertions that the Lemhi lacked
a formal treaty to grant them nation status. Their affairs are
handled by the much larger Shoshone-Bannock tribes on the
reservation at Fort Hall, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even late in this century, a small group of Lemhi, Ariwite among
them, continued to live in shacks by the river at the edge of town
here. But that tumbledown village was destroyed by the local
authorities more than 10 years ago. It is now a small park covered
with gravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our home,'' Ariwite said. ``But I guess everyone else
thought it was an eyesore.'' For a man who has an encyclopedic
knowledge of the many slights dealt the Lemhi, Ariwite betrays only
a trace of bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids come up here with me to fish and camp in the summer,
and they say, `Dad, how could you ever give this land up?''' he
said. ``But we haven't given up. The Lewis and Clark bicentennial
is going to be our last fight. In 1805, the Americans asked for our
help. Now we're asking for theirs.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sacajawea was a Shoshone girl who had been kidnapped by Hidatsa
Indians. She became one of two young wives of Toussaint
Charbonneau, a French-Canadian trader who won Sacajawea in a bet
with the Indians. When Charbonneau signed on with Lewis and Clark,
Sacajawea, though just 15 years old and six months pregnant, was
enlisted as an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, she nearly died of a fever. Lewis was counting on
Sacajawea to be a translator with Shoshone people who lived in the
mountains west of the Continental Divide, and he expressed concern
that her death could doom the expedition. He used bark and opium to
relieve her symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   In the late summer of 1805, as the Corps of Discovery climbed
slowly up the mountains of western Montana, the Americans were
running low on food, were without fresh horses and had little idea
about how to find the waters that drained to the Pacific. With
Sacajawea's help, they crossed the Continental Divide at Lemhi
Pass, then came upon a band of Shoshone.
</P>
<P>
   As Stephen Ambrose notes in his best-selling book on the Corps,
``Undaunted Courage'' (Simon and Schuster, 1996), the 60 Shoshone
warriors who encountered the Americans could have wiped them out
easily, ending the expedition. But Sacajawea recognized their
chief, Cameahwait, as her long lost brother, and another Shoshone,
Jumping Fish, as a girl she had not seen since the kidnapping. A
two-day, tearful reunion followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a piece of luck that was,'' Ambrose wrote. ``No novelist
could ever invent such a scene.'' The Americans traded guns, a
medallion from President Jefferson and other items for 29 horses.
They also got a Shoshone guide who helped them find the waters that
flowed to the Columbia River and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   For her services on the expedition, Sacajawea was given nothing,
though her husband, Charbonneau, received $500. Her son,
Jean-Baptist, was later raised in part by William Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The Lemhi Shoshone lived relatively undisturbed until Mormon
missionaries, gold prospectors and cattlemen started to stake out
their land in the second half of the 19th century. An 1868 treaty
that would have given them land and legal standing was never
ratified by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, some of the Lemhi agreed to give up their homeland,
in return for payments, and to join the reservation at Fort Hall.
But in order for that agreement to be valid, it needed the
signatures of two-thirds of the Lemhi men.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Orlan J. Svingen, a professor of American history at
Washington State University in Pullman, who has been helping the
Lemhi, said his research at the National Archives had failed to
turn up the document that supposedly has the signatures of a
majority of Lemhi men.
</P>
<P>
   Also, as other historians have noted, Svingen said, the Lemhi
were told they would lose their food rations if they did not agree
to leave the valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the fact that the Lemhi did not want to leave their
home, and that the document which is supposed to have their
signatures agreeing to the move could not be found _ that makes me
very suspicious they willingly gave up their home,'' Svingen said.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of the Lemhi being restored as a tribe in the valley
where they used to live are certainly long. Even other Indians are
not helping them. The Shoshone-Bannock say the Lemhi belong with
them at Fort Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their treaty was never ratified, so basically they belong down
here,'' said Duane Thompson, chairman of the Shoshone-Bannock
Council, which governs the reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Ariwite said the Lemhi's best hope is to get a small bit of land
from the federal government, which would be used as a Sacajawea
interpretive center, and a home for some tribal members who have
never felt welcome at Fort Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But Interior Department officials expressed doubt about the
Lemhi request. ``It is very hard for us to do something like that
for one group of Indians without doing it for another,'' said
Stephanie Hanna, a spokeswoman for the Interior Department. ``If
conscience was the only factor, a whole lot of Indian land might be
given back based on historic grievances.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been asked by Idaho elected officials to consider
plans for a Sacajawea center here at Salmon, but not one that would
be run by the Lemhi.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're asking for is not very big,'' Ariwite said. ``Let
us build a center here _ in this valley where we have always lived
_ for our first lady. The Lewis and Clark bicentennial is our last
fight. Let us come home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
