<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 31) 
(jt) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shroud of Turin
</P>
<P>
   Q. I understand that the Shroud of Turin will be on public
display next year. A friend saw the shroud when it was last
displayed in 1998 and said a dated and timed ticket had to be
reserved. Can you provide details on the coming exhibition? _ Doug
Bowman, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. As part of the Holy Year in 2000, the Shroud of Turin, which
many faithful believe is the burial cloth of Jesus and thus bears
his image, will be on display from Aug. 26 to Oct. 22 in the
Cathedral of St. John the Baptist in Turin. The shroud, a cloth 14{
feet long by 3 and 6 inches wide, bears the image of a scourged,
crucified man. This will be only the fifth public ex(ibition of the
shroud since 1898.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket reservations can be made in the United States through a
private company, Select Italy. The telephone number is (847)
853-1661. Ticket reservations will also be possible within the next
two months at www.selectitaly.com. Details had not been confirmed
as of late this month, but when Select Italy handled the
reservations during the shroud's 1998 exhibition tickets cost $15
to $19. As you have heard, tickets must be reserved for a specific
date and time of entry.
</P>
<P>
   There are also two companies offering tours to Italy that will
include viewing of the shroud. Select International Tours and
Cruises, 116 Highway 22 East, North Plainfield, N.J. 07060, (800)
842-4842, is conducting a tour Aug. 17 to 30. Besides a stop in
Turin, the itinerary includes a visit to Germany for the Passion
Play in Oberammergau and Expo 2000 in Hanover, along with a Rhine
cruise. The price is $3,799 a person, double occupancy, plus $99 in
airport taxes. The Web site is www.select-intl.com. Unitours Inc.,
411 West Putnam Ave., Greenwich, Conn. 06830, (800) 777-7432,
offers a tour to Italy Sept. 2 to 12 with stops in Turin, Milan,
Assisi and Rome, among other cities. The price is $2,699 a person,
double occupancy, with air fare. The Web site: www.Unitours.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cottages in Scotland
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are planning an extended trip to Scotland and
are interested in renting a country cottage there. Do you have any
recommendations? _ John R. Campbell, Lady Lake, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. The British Tourist Authority, 551 Fifth Ave., Suite 701, New
York, N.Y. 10176, (800) 462-2748, publishes a free guide,
Self-Catering Holiday Homes, which lists individual cottage rentals
throughout Scotland (as well as England, Wales and Northern
Ireland).
</P>
<P>
   It also includes numerous rental agencies in the United States
and these three in Scotland:
</P>
<P>
   Ecosse Unique Ltd., Thorncroft, Lilliesleaf, Melrose,
Roxburghshire, TD6 9JD; telephone (44-1835) 870779, fax (44-1835)
870417.
</P>
<P>
   G.M. Thomson and Co., 27 King St., Castle Douglas, Scotland DG7
1AB; (44-1556) 504030, fax (44-1556) 503277.
</P>
<P>
   Mackay's Agency, 30 Frederick St., Edinburgh, Scotland EH2 2JR;
(44-131) 2253539, fax (44-131) 2265284.
</P>
<P>
   In general, cottage rentals start at about $250 to $335 a week
in high season, usually July and August and the Christmas holiday
season. Rates in the low season, generally November through March,
start at about $150 a week. During all other months expect to pay
from about $235 a week and up. Deposits range from a minimum of $80
to one-third the total rental. Ask whether linens and housekeeping
are included. Rates are calculated at $1.67 to the pound.
</P>
<P>
   There are many individual listings, too, with photographs,
descriptions and details of amenities for each. A small,
well-equipped cottage on the grounds of Kilchrist Castle, (44-1586)
553210, fax (44-1586) 551852, near the Mull of Kintyre, for
example, costs $260 to $660 a week, depending on accommodations and
season.
</P>
<P>
   Or you could try one of five modern cottages on the 80-acre
Cathair Dhubh Estate, telephone and fax (44-1571) 855277, in the
Highlands, for $375 to $1,085 a week. And there are three cottages
on the 200-acre Easter Dalziel Farm, telephone and fax (44-1667)
462213, seven miles east of Inverness, among sheep and cows. The
rent is $225 to $700.
</P>
<P>
   For a stay near another of Scotland's famous creatures, try the
Lochness Bungalows in Drumnadrochit, (44-1456) 450834, fax
(44-1456) 450822, for $385 to $650 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Tours to Iran
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have read that tours to Iran are available. I would like to
know the names and addresses of companies offering such tours. _
Marie Anderson, Pensacola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. Although it is possible for Americans to visit Iran either
independently (you must be invited by the Iranian government), or
as part of an organized tour, the Department of State issued a
warning to American citizens on Sept. 14 to defer travel to Iran.
Although President Khatami of Iran has called for an increase in
meetings between private citizens of both countries, the State
Department warning says, there is some evidence that hostility to
the United States remains in some segments of the Iranian
population and some sections of the government.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1999, violent anti-government demonstrations took place
in Tehran and other cities, and there were accusations that the
United States was behind these, the warning says. Before and since
those demonstrations, some groups of American travelers have
encountered harassment by vigilante groups.
</P>
<P>
   If you still wish to go to Iran, keep in mind that an organized
tour overcomes one difficulty: American credit cards and traveler's
checks are generally not accepted in Iran. With a prepaid tour, you
will not have to carry as much cash. Another advantage of using a
tour operator is that it streamlines the process of getting an
Iranian visa.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies that conduct tours to Iran are these:
</P>
<P>
   Absolute Asia, 180 Varick St., New York, N.Y. 10014, (800)
736-8187; 14- to 19-day trips that include Uzbekistan and
Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
   Bestway Tours and Safaris, Suite 102, 3540 West 41st Ave.,
Vancouver, British Columbia V6N 3E6, (800) 663-0844; among its
offerings is a nine-day tour to Iran, which can be extended with a
visit to Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
   Cyrus Travel, 8245 Boone Blvd., Suite 130, Vienna, Va. 22182,
(800) 558-8770; 12- to 21-day tours.
</P>
<P>
   Distant Horizons, 350 Elm Ave., Long Beach, Calif. 90802, (800)
333-1240; 18-day trips with stops in Yemen and Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
   Geographic Expeditions, 2627 Lombard St., San Francisco, Calif.
94123, (800) 777-8183; has trips of 18 to 24 days, with rigorous
hiking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
