<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Boston, Radical Art Of Pharaohs of the Sun
</P>
<P>
   Boston lies on the Charles River, but it may seem like the Nile
to those who visit the show ``Pharaohs of the Sun: Akhenaten,
Nefertiti, Tutankhamen'' at the Museum of Fine Arts
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition, from Nov. 14 to Feb. 6, focuses on the brief
Amarna Age (1353 to 1336 B.C.), when the Pharaoh Akhenaten (also
spelled Ikhnaton) radically changed religion and art. He moved the
throne to the new city of Amarna, introduced monotheism with the
worship of Aten, the sun god, and turned away from the idealized
imagery of the previous 1,500 years for a more realistic art.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition opens with a monumental traditional piece, a
sculpture of King Thutmose III, Akhenaten's
great-great-great-grandfather, and images of Akhenaten's father,
Ahmenotop III.
</P>
<P>
   But then images of Akhenaten show a new artistic style,
depicting him with elongated head and facial features, skinny
torso, broad hips and overhanging belly. Two illustrations of this
style are colossal statues of Amenhotep that have never before left
Egypt, one of them seven feet high and weighing 3,000 pounds. These
recently restored objects are being lent by the Egyptian Museum in
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   The pharaoh's wife, the mysteriously powerful Nefertiti, was the
only queen depicted in the archetypical images of kingship, as in a
work where she can be seen smiting enemies from the royal barge.
The show also includes a life-size quartzite head of the youthful
Nefertiti from the Egyptian Museum in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The show goes on to look at Tutankhamen, who may have been
Akhenaten's son and who became ruler at age 10, then soon abandoned
Amarna for Thebes and reinstated the worship of Amen.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to ``Pharaohs of the Sun'' is by timed ticket, costing
$6 for ages 5 to 17 to $17.50 for adults on weekends. These are
available from (617) 542-4632, with service and handling charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts is at 465 Huntington Avenue and is open
daily. Information: (617) 267-9300; www.mfa.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ray Cormier
</P>
<P>
   Click for Hotel Rooms In Midtown Manhattan
</P>
<P>
   Reservations at 30 midtown Manhattan hotels can be made through
a new Web site, www.hotres.com _ at discounted rates. Hotres.com
has a block of reserved rooms at reduced rates at the hotels, which
are between 32rd and 59th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   The hotels run from deluxe like the Waldorf-Astoria and the
Grand Hyatt, at $250 and up a night) to midrange (like the
Algonquin or the Roosevelt, at about $200 to $250) to moderate
(like the Milford Plaza or Travel Inn, at about $150 to $200). The
discount is between 10 percent and 50 percent off the published
rate, depending on the time of year.
</P>
<P>
   The main benefit of the service is that the rooms have been
already been reserved by hotres.com, and so lodging may be
available even if a hotel says it is sold out. Bookings can be made
as late as the day before arrival.
</P>
<P>
   After travel dates are entered and a hotel selected, the Web
site provides rates and availability of rooms. Daily prices and
availability are also shown for the week before and the week after.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, information for four other hotels in the same price
range is shown. The site also lists the facilities and services at
each hotel.
</P>
<P>
   When the reservation is completed, a page that can be printed
appears with a confirmation number, a voucher to be presented at
check-in and other information. A confirmation is also sent by
e-mail. The reservation is guaranteed until midnight on the arrival
date with a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An Airport Enters the Realm of Museums
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco International Airport recently became the first
airport to be accredited by the American Association of Museums, a
private organization that sets professional museum standards in the
United States. The association has accredited more than 750
institutions, from the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York to
zoos to local historical sites. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has mounted airport exhibitions since 1980, and
the airport's three terminals now have 17 gallery areas. A
full-time staff of 27 curators, designers and others produces more
than 40 shows a year, featuring photography, folk art and
historical, ethnographic and archeological materials. (There are no
fine art exhibitions.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the current offerings at San Francisco International is an
exhibition on the history of tea, which includes an assortment of
pots, strainers, bowls and canisters, on display through May.
</P>
<P>
   Another exhibition, through January, examines teeth-blackening
and other Japanese cosmetic practices during the late Edo and Meiji
periods (1784-1912).
</P>
<P>
   _ Christopher Hall
</P>
<P>
   A New Way to See Bermuda's Capital
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Bermuda have a new method of transportation _
trolleylike buses that tour the capital, Hamilton, and the dockyard
area.
</P>
<P>
   These 60-seat vehicles have two linked cars and locally are
called trains. Passengers can get on and off an unlimited number of
times throughout the day for a single fare.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamilton Train makes six stops: Albuoy's Point, City Hall,
the Cathedral of the Most Holy Trinity, the botanical gardens, the
Bermuda Underwater Exploration Institute and the flagpole below
Burnaby Hill. The Dockyard Train calls at the crafts market, the
shopping center and a gallery where visitors can watch artisans
work.
</P>
<P>
   A regular day pass costs $10. (A Bermudian dollar is equivalent
to an American dollar.) A $25 ticket includes admission to the
underwater institute (usually $9.75), the National Gallery ($3) and
the tower of the cathedral ($3).
</P>
<P>
   Tickets can be bought at hotels, Oleander cycle shops and the
Hamilton train station.
</P>
<P>
   More information about Bermuda is available at (800) 237-6832 or
(441) 292-0023 and at www.bermudatourism.com.
</P>
<P>
   New Role for Loop Landmark
</P>
<P>
   Daniel H. Burnham, the architect and city planner who designed
many American landmarks, including the Flatiron Building in
Manhattan, conceived the Reliance Building in Chicago as a center
for business and a harbinger of skyscrapers and walls of glass.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen stories high and draped in 12,000 panes of blond terra
cotta, the structure was finished in 1895, incorporating
avant-garde elements, from its airy steel skeleton to a facade of
large bay windows. The interior was furnished with mahogany, white
marble wainscoting, mosaic floors and a quatrefoil motif.
</P>
<P>
   The Reliance, at State and Washington Streets, just east of
Daley Plaza in The Loop, had fallen into such shabby disuse after
nearly a century as an office building that Chicago acquired it
through eminent domain. There was talk of razing it after 1990s
developers found it ill-suited for modern commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But the spirit of reinvention prevailed last year, and the
classic building began a new life. After a restoration by Chicago
engineers and artisans, who sought to replicate as many of the
original details as possible, the old Reliance is a new boutique
hotel, named after its creator.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Burnham, operated by the Kimpton Hotel and Restaurant
Group of San Francisco, opened Oct. 1. Although rooms are just
average in size, there are mahogany writing desks, chaise longues
by the windows and such conveniences as dataports and fax machines.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel contains a casual restaurant, the Atwood Cafe (as in
Charles B. Atwood, Burnham's partner), and room service is
available. It has 103 rooms, with rates starting at $145 a night,
and 19 suites, from $195. Reservations: (877) 294-9712.
</P>
<P>
   _ Caitlin Lovinger
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
