<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8049 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SENATE-TURNABOUT-HNS &LR;      10-25 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TURNABOUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC SENATOR TRIES A REPUBLICAN PLOY TO BLOCK A NOMINEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democratic Sen. Barbara Boxer is trying to beat her
Republican colleagues at one of their favorite parliamentary games.
</P>
<P>
   This game takes only one senator to play, and often the opening
move is made in secret. It's called placing a so-called ``hold'' on
a bill or a nomination, effectively blocking either one unless the
hold is removed.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have blasted Republicans over the last few years for
placing holds on dozens of President Clinton's nominees. Among them
were Bill Lann Lee, the acting head of the Justice Department's
civil rights division, who never made it as official head of the
division. Another was James Hormel, whose nomination to be U.S.
ambassador to Luxembourg was blocked for 18 months because he is
gay. But Hormel got the post in June because Clinton snuck him in
while Congress was not in session.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Barbara Boxer, a liberal Californian, who last week
used the ploy to try to extract a concession from a powerful
Mississippi conservative. But she didn't do it secretly; she issued
a statement about it.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer put a hold on Glenn McCullough, the mayor of Tupelo,
Miss., who was nominated by Clinton for the board of the Tennessee
Valley Authority as a favor to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough's career path is not a concern to Boxer, but his
sponsor, Lott, is.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said in her statement she has ``no problem with Sen.
Lott's nominee ... as long as Sen. Lott and the Republican majority
also consider those who have been waiting for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer is focusing on two California nominees to the U.S. Ninth
Circuit Court of Appeals _ lawyer Marsha Berzon, who has been
waiting more thyears, and U.S. District Judge Richard Paez,
whose nomination has been stalled for almost four years.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer may have struck a responsive chord. Lott's spokesman, John
Czwartacki, said Monday that the majority leader has pledged to
``work with all sides to get these nominations to the floor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
