<HEADLINE>
THE PROBLEMS OF BEING ON ONE'S OWN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Actress  &UR; Natalie Portman &LR; , a freshman at Harvard, told TV Guide
Online how tough she's finding academic life.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping into a pile of the wrong stuff on campus one day, she
said ``it got all over my shoes and really freaked me out. So I got
back to the dorm and just left my shoes on the front steps. I
didn't care if they got stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back and my roommate had seen the shoes sitting there
and put them in my room. I'm like, `Oh, no, what am I going to do?'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I called my mom. She said, `If you've got dog poop on your
shoes, just wipe it off.' I couldn't do it. So I went home for the
weekend and took the shoes, still covered with dog poop, wrapped in
about 20 paper bags. I'm sure you can guess who cleaned off the dog
poop.'' Portman said her mom has always been a big help to her.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Brian Bringardner &LR;  reports that the QEII is coming to San
Francisco on January 21, at the end of one arc (from New York, via
the Panama Canal) in its around-the-world cruise.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of luxury, bamboo gardener  &UR; Rosalie Ross &LR;  reports
that a single tortoiseshell bamboo plant, grown at Hakone Gardens
in Saratoga, was auctioned for $7,000 at the annual meeting of the
American Bamboo Society last week.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bobby Knight  &LR; shot a hunting pal in Wisconsin, and is being
cited by laws in that state.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Norm Macdonald &LR; , who used to be a regular and hosted
``Saturday Night Live'' last weekend, told Details magazine that he
has bet as much as $200,000 a weekend on ball games. ``A lot of
times on `Saturday Night Live,' I'd be thinking about gambling
instead of the show. ... I once considered going to Gamblers'
Anonymous, but I figured it's for losers. I don't see how it can
physically harm you. All it can do is take away your money, and you
can always make more money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOMEN'S WORK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Sonoma (Calif.) Index Tribune reported last week that
 &UR; Patricia Lynn Reilly &LR; , author of ``Imagine a Woman in Love With
Herself,'' would be speaking about that book. Previous works
include ``Be Full of Yourself'' and ``A God Who Looks Like Me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Hostess gets the mostest: In Manhattan last week,  &UR; Sigourney &LR; 
 &UR; Weaver &LR;  hosted a pre-opening party at Chaos, a new club, where
construction was still under way. The walls between ladies' room
stalls had not yet been installed, but most party &LR; - &LR; goers made the
best of the communal arrangements. Owner  &UR; Michael Ault &LR;  said the
hostess was escorted to a nearby bar when nature called.
</P>
<P>
   _ Relief, at last: In his new book, ``The Blonde'' (Chronicle
Books; $29.95),  &UR; Barnaby Conrad III  &LR; quotes Life magazine, which
assured women in 1950 that ``thanks to changed social ideas,''
going blond ``no longer automatically labels a woman `fast.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Lew Hurwitz  &LR; noticed that his daughter's issue of Bride's
magazine came packaged this month with a special stand-apart
``groom's issue'' that features a groom cover model with ``a large
black bar across his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHAPING THE WEB &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Shaping the (relatively) brand-new World Wide Web into a life
form that fits into our culture is the focus of Shift magazine. The
Bay Area's  &UR; Tiffany Shlain &LR; , a proponent of the ``hip-digirati
image,'' has made the cover of its first issue.
</P>
<P>
   Shlain, 29 and glamorous-looking, is the creator of the Webby
Awards for Internet achievement. And what's a form of anything
nowadays that doesn't have an awards ceremony?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to create a new kind of hero,'' she told Shift. ``In
our culture, we have movie stars, sports stars, rock stars. We have
really taken down our ideas of heroes. I want to elevate the unsung
heroes that people can look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Shlain, ``Most people are in the Web to make a
s_-load of dollars. They're serial entrepreneurs. I want to
establish an institution.'' Setting herself apart from the
profiteers, Shlain notes that the Net ``breathes, sputters and
blows a lot of air into the hype machine. And while the Webbys
celebrate the work of the industry, they also ground it in a sense
of irony.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Q: Tell me why lesbians adore whale watching. A: They love
nature. They love the sea and any kind of fish and sea mammal. It's
a huge phenomenon in Provincetown. Oh, God, all the lesbians going
out early in the morning whale watching is a total scene.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Margaret Cho in Girlfriends magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
