<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUCHANAN-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      10-25 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: BUCHANAN COULD BE THE WILD CARD OF THE 2000
CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Minn., Ky., Okla.) (With BUCHANAN-REFORM) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At first glance, Pat Buchanan appears sapped of the
political potency that made him an important player in the 1996
presidential campaign: His pitch then to the economically
distressed now carries little appeal given the resurgency in New
Hampshire. His comments about Hitler in his new book have drawn
hostile denunciations from prominent Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Buchanan's failure to make a dent in polls of
Republican voters practically drove him to the Reform Party. Even
his bid for the party's nomination is hardly assured. Others with
marquee names or fatter bank accounts _ from Donald Trump to Jesse
Ventura to Ross Perot _ may have an easier time navigating the
Byzantine, and costly, Reform Party rules for getting on state
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   And yet for all his apparent weaknesses, Buchanan may be the
wild card of the 2000 campaign. He could cause incalculable
mischief for both Republicans and Democrats because Buchanan has
the unusual potential to strike a chord both among grass-roots
conservatives and with union members who usually vote Democratic.
He is, perhaps, the only candidate since George Wallace who has
some appeal to those wings of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an expert on getting attention for himself,'' said Scott
Reed, who ran Bob Dole's presidential campaign in 1996, ``and he'll
look to keep both parties in line on issues that he cares about
like trade and his nationalist agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he does not ultimately win the Reform Party nomination
next summer, Buchanan _ with his knack for forcefully and
unabashedly speaking his mind _ could help drive the discourse in
the coming months. As a longtime television commentator, he is a
master at commanding television coverage _ and uttering the
perfectly provocative sound bite.
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare scenario for politicians on both sides would be
for Buchanan to pop up on nationally televised debates next fall
and bash both parties, much as he did in his announcement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan poses the biggest threat to Republicans because he
still has a following in that party. On issues like human rights in
China and national sovereignty, Buchanan could force Republican
candidates to move to the right, something that could hurt them in
a general election.
</P>
<P>
   But the most daunting challenge for Republicans may be how to
react to Buchanan. His hard-edged oratory at the Republican
convention in 1992 frightened President Bush's campaign. Some of
the president's aides said he was more damaged by his handling of
Buchanan _ giving him a prime speaking slot at the convention _
than by Buchanan's challenge itself.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
front-runner, said they are concerned that Buchanan, never warm to
the Bush family, will use his new platform to upbraid the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan could also torment Democrats, particularly because of
his appeal to labor. He could prod the Democratic contenders into
stands that could hurt them in a general election, like making
tougher environmental and worker safety regulations a priority to
negotiating future trade treaties.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another, more fundamental, reason for the
Republicans to have more to fear. Except for in 1976, when Jimmy
Carter drew 50 percent of the vote, no Democratic presidential
candidate has ever drawn more than 50 percent since 1964. So the
more divided the vote, the better for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's appeal to conservatives in a general election could
also spell trouble for Republicans because it could enable
Democrats to gain footholds in Southern and Mountain states where
they might not have been competitive.
</P>
<P>
   But for now at least, Buchanan has to get past Trump and others
as he seeks the Reform Party nomination. That is why in his
announcement Monday Buchanan steered clear of topics like abortion
and cultural values and concentrated on campaign finance reform,
trade and other issues championed by the party's founder, Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Buchanan may have trouble convincing Reform Party members
that he deserves their nomination. For all his emphasis on the
party's issues, Buchanan hardly fit the mold of Perot _ or Ventura
_ when he mentioned in his remarks that he had been a
``Goldwaterite'' and spoke with pride about his service to
President Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Buchanan candidacy has the highest likelihood of
transforming the Reform Party from a party that connected politics
to ordinary people to one that is ideological _ and potentially
marginalized,'' said Steven J. Rosenstone, dean of the College of
Liberal Arts at the University of Minnesota and an expert on third
parties. ``With Buchanan you get an attitude and ideology, and
that's a risk for the Reform Party.''
</P>
<P>
   But, increasingly, Republicans appear uneasy with Buchanan as
well. His support among Republicans has stood at about 4 percent in
recent polls by ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Buchanan didn't quit the Republican Party as much as the
Republican Party quite Pat Buchanan,'' said Gary Langer, ABC's
polling director.
</P>
<P>
   His strains with Republicans will probably make it far less
likely that Republican candidates would cave to Buchanan, as they
did in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's assume George W. Bush is the nominee,'' said Mickey
Edwards, a former Republican House member from Oklahoma who now
teaches at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government. ``I don't see
him being pushed.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, advisers to Bush insisted that they would never consent
to include Buchanan in a candidates' debate.
</P>
<P>
   If Buchanan wins the Reform Party nomination, he will get $12.6
million in federal money because Perot drew more than 5 percent of
the vote as the party's candidate in 1996. But while that would
seem like a fortune to Buchanan's bare-bones operation, it would
not go far in a general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Pat a lot,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who has
made a cause of opposing new campaign spending restrictions. ``But
the notion that $13 million is a pot of gold is laughable on its
face. That's about half a Senate race in New York. We're talking
about running for president of the United States!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
