<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN LEAVES GOP TO SEEK REFORM PARTY NOMINATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALLS CHURCH, Va. _ The 2000 race for the White House turned
livelier and more complicated Monday as conservative commentator
Pat Buchanan announced he was bolting from the Republican Party to
seek the Reform Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's decision could spell trouble for Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, giving conservatives another option in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he was abandoning a party in which he had been
active since Barry Goldwater ran for president because it no longer
was distinguishable from the Democratic Party on issues such as
trade and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, candor compels us to admit that our vaunted two-party
system is a snare and a delusion, a fraud upon the nation,'' he
told a crowd of enthusiastic supporters at a suburban Virginia
hotel. ``Our two parties have become nothing but two wings of the
same bird of prey.''
</P>
<P>
   The former CNN talk-show host and speechwriter for Richard Nixon
portrayed himself as the political outsider leading the people
against the establishment that has ``rigged the game to protect the
party favorites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So let me say to the money boys and the Beltway elites who
think that at long last they have pulled up their drawbridge and
locked us out forever: You don't know this peasant army. We haven't
begun to fight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan still faces an uphill battle just to get his name on
the 29 state ballots, where the Reform Party will not automatically
be listed in the 2000 election. The task, which must be completed
well before the party's convention in August, is expected to be
expensive and time consuming.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party is still divided over whether Buchanan should
be its standard bearer. Social issues comprise a significant chunk
of Buchanan's platform, but are absent from the party's agenda,
which has largely focused on political reform, economic issues and
opposition to trade.
</P>
<P>
   And though Buchanan is a household name, thanks to two feisty
yet unsuccessful bids for president in 1992 and 1996, his drawing
power at the ballot box is questionable. He has failed to gain much
traction in this year's GOP race, and many voters say they don't
like him.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas billionaire Ross Perot, the party's founder and former
presidential candidate, has been silent on a Buchanan bid.
</P>
<P>
   But the party's most visible spokesman, Minnesota Gov. Jesse
Ventura, has actively opposed a Buchanan bid and has recruited New
York developer Donald Trump to oppose him.
</P>
<P>
   Trump, who announced this weekend he was defecting from the GOP
to compete with Buchanan for the Reform Party nomination, has
suggested that Buchanan harbors anti-Semitic views because Buchanan
suggests in his latest book that Hitler did not pose enough of a
threat after 1940 to warrant U.S. involvement in Europe in World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   If Buchanan is the Reform Party nominee, he could make life more
difficult for the major-party candidates, particularly Bush, who
not only had urged the commentator not to leave the party but also
refused to join in the criticism of Buchanan's view of World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush seemed content to let Buchanan go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat sees an America that should have stayed home while Hitler
overran Europe and perpetrated the Holocaust,'' Bush said in a
written statement from Austin, Texas. ``Republicans are proud of
America's role in defeating Nazi Germany and know that freedom
still depends on an America that is strong and engaged. ''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who was the first of the presidential
candidates to urge Buchanan to leave the party, chided Bush for
initially courting Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many of my party's leaders made the mistake of trying to
appease Buchanan. His actions today prove that their efforts were
wrong,'' said McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Most polls have shown that a Buchanan candidacy saps more votes
from Bush than from Democratic contenders Al Gore or Bill Bradley
in the general election. Buchanan attracts disgruntled
conservatives who feel Bush is not communicating their views, polls
have shown.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has a history of making trouble for the Bush family. In
1992, Buchanan damaged President Bush when he ran an aggressive
campaign against him in the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   As a Reform Party candidate Buchanan would become eligible for
more than $12 million in federal matching funds, which would give
him the resources to attack Democrats and Republicans in television
ads.
</P>
<P>
   In his address, which was interrupted by microphone
difficulties, Buchanan attempted to marry his own culturally
conservative philosophies with the Reform Party platform, which
largely focus on economic matters.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to traditional Reform Party goals, he spoke about the
need to ``cut out the cancerous trade deficits,'' and the evils of
the trade pacts such as the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Blending populist and isolationist strains, he said that ``we
must phase out foreign aid and start out for the forgotten
Americans right here in the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for a new Supreme Court to ``undo the damage done this
nation by judicial aggressions, beginning with that abomination
they call Roe vs. Wade.''
</P>
<P>
   He also renewed his controversial call for ``a time-out on legal
immigration'' and added that ``all of us must learn our English
language.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's address was peppered with the kind of fiery rhetoric
and muscular prose that has long delighted his supporters and
frightened his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   He attacked candidates of both parties as ``hollow men, the
malleable men, willing to read from TelePrompTers speeches scripted
by consultants and pollsters for whom the latest print-out from the
focus group is sacred text.''
</P>
<P>
   And he warned supporters that ``this year is our last chance to
save our republic before she disappears into the godless New World
Order that our elites are constructing in a betrayal of everything
for which our founding fathers lived, fought and died.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's campaign officials said they would now begin the
arduous task of gathering petitions in the 29 states where the
Reform Party is not currently on the ballot. It is on the ballot in
21 states.
</P>
<P>
   By early summer, Reform Party members will begin voting for
their candidate. The party will choose its nominee at its August
convention in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the Buchanan organizers will have to choose whether
they want to be listed as an independent candidate, which requires
56,116 signatures or Reform Party candidate, which requires 37,380
names.
</P>
<P>
   If he is listed as an independent party candidate _ as Perot was
in 1992 and 1996 _ Buchanan would remain on the ballot even if he
did not get the Reform Party nod.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
