<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: ARGENTINA'S VOTERS REJECT CORRUPTION, NOT POLICIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES _ As Argentines woke up Monday after a night of
dancing in the streets and car-honking celebrations, they were
greeted by triumphant posters that showed President-elect Fernando
de la Rua beside an Argentine flag and the slogan, ``We all won.''
</P>
<P>
   But what exactly did 24 million voters win from a campaign that
was unusually short on issues? What kind of mandate does de la Rua,
the mayor of Buenos Aires, have after winning 48.5 percent of the
vote, a wide plurality but not an outright majority? Finally, is
the Argentina that is about to emerge after 10 years of President
Carlos Saul Menem and his sweeping retooling of the economy likely
to look very different?
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls indicated that voters wanted to send a message
rejecting Menem's flamboyant high living and perceptions that he
tolerated corrupt officials in his government. That helps explain
why de la Rua's principal opponent, Gov. Eduardo Duhalde of Buenos
Aires Province, managed 37.9 percent of the vote, the worst
electoral result for any presidential candidate of the populist
party that was founded by Gen. Juan D. Peron in the 1940s and led
by Menem over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little sign that voters were seeking a radical
change in course, nor even a partial reversal of Menem's policies
of deregulation and privatization of state agencies. Sacrosanct in
all the major presidential campaigns was universal approval of
Menem's policy of pegging the value of the peso one-to-one to the
dollar _ the cornerstone of his success in overcoming Argentina's
hyperinflation to bring the current rate below 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Argentina is aspiring for is better ethics, sincerity and
the rule of law,'' said Martin Redrado, head of an economics
research group and a former aide to Menem. ``On economic policy,
the message is continuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mixing the messages of a strong de la Rua victory over the
governing party was a surprise comeback victory by Menem's vice
president, Carlos Ruckauf, in the governor's race in Buenos Aires
Province, making him the second most powerful elected official in
the country. Ruckauf defeated a leader of the liberal wing of de la
Rua's center-left coalition in what appeared to be a rejection of
anyone who even suggested a fundamental break with the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the strong showing by Menem's former economy
minister, Domingo Cavallo, who came in third in the presidential
race. By winning 10 percent of the national vote with a tiny
organization and no money for television advertising, Cavallo's
small conservative party won enough seats in the lower house to
become a crucial swing vote on economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Cavallo, who is a senator, has pledged to use his bargaining
power to continue the Menem revolution of cutting regulations, as
well as business taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic message is change the people, not the policies,''
Felipe Noguera, a pollster who was a consultant for Cavallo's
campaign, said. ``These elections were about getting rid of Menem,
as opposed to thinking about what comes next.''
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed that 60 percent of those who voted for de la
Rua, a sober 62-year-old who gardens, plays golf and wears ascots,
said they did so because of his honesty. Only a third said they
voted for him because of his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua said he would lower the 14.5 percent unemployment rate
and bridge a growing gap between rich and poor. But he never
explained exactly how he would accomplish those goals.
</P>
<P>
   Some of de la Rua's aides are said to favor some mild forms of
subsidies and protectionism, but the candidate did not go into
specifics. Nor did he explain how he would manage his main hurdle
in the coming months _ financing $16 billion in foreign debt _
beyond saying he would shave government waste and crack down on tax
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua's greatest applause lines of his campaign came when he
and his running mate suggested that corrupt officials in the
current government would face justice. But few analysts expect more
than a few token prosecutions, because the courts remain in the
hands of Menem's Justicialist party, popularly known as the
Peronistas.
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech on Sunday night, de la Rua emphasized his
openness to all political forces and his willingness to reach
consensus. With the Supreme Court and the Senate controlled by the
opposition and his coalition lacking a majority in the lower house,
negotiation will be necessary to achieve anything.
</P>
<P>
   Much as in recent years in the United States, Argentines appear
to be in the mood for divided rule. Over the last several months,
Argentines elected 14 Justicialists in 23 gubernatorial races, even
as de la Rua led in the polls to succeed Menem.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the majority of governors in the hands of the
Peronistas,'' said Joaquin Morales Sola, a columnist at a daily
here, La Nacion, ``the result is a tie in terms of institutional
power. What we will see is a cohabitation of power, a permanent
politics of consensus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
