<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Oct. 26 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please contact
Michael McGarr at (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD-ZACARIAS (Los Angeles) -- In what is expected to be a
showdown over who leads Los Angeles Unified, the board is set to
evaluate Superintendent Ruben Zacarias as his attorney challenges
the process. Zacarias contends the board cannot fairly review him
without allowing him to see the criteria first. Also, the eight
full-time district employees named in a scathing internal audit of
the Belmont Learning Center will be taken out of the chain of
command Tuesday through a combination of buyout offers and
administrative leave. By Greg Gittrich. (Will move on the ``n''
California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-ROWLING (Los Angeles) -- Hundreds of Muggles _ non-magical
children who should have been in school and the parents who left
work to drive them _ lined up Monday, some as early as 4 a.m., for
a chance to meet Harry Potter creator J.K. Rowling. More than 500
parents and children chatted with the British author of the popular
children's books that have been hit with criticism by some parents
who say the tales of sorcerers and magic are not appropriate for
kids. All who wanted theirs books signed left with an autograph,
even though just 250 visitors had tickets to attend. By Cecelia
Chan. (Will move on the ``n'' California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-LANDFILL (Los Angeles) -- In an emotional public hearing,
teachers told state lawmakers they suspect cancer cases at their
schools in Sun Valley and Carson are tied to nearby landfills, but
cancer experts said proving that will be difficult, if not
impossible. The hearing was called by state Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los
Angeles, because of the Daily News' disclosure that concerns about
cancer cases at Polytechnic High School in Sun Valley and Towne
Elementary in Carson prompted state toxics regulators to demand
studies. By David Baker. (Will move on the ``n'' California news
wire.)
</P>
<P>
   SANDPIPER-WEBSITES (Los Angeles) -- Sandpiper Networks went
public Monday through a side door by agreeing to be bought by San
Francisco-based Digital Island for roughly $600 million. Investors
caught on quickly, driving Digital Island's stock sharply higher to
a closing price more than half again its opening value. Sandpiper
is based in Thousand Oaks, a Ventura County community north of Los
Angeles. The Internet startup delivers websites more quickly. By
Jason Cohen. (Will move on the ``n'' California news wire and ``f''
financial wire.)
</P>
<P>
   THQ-EARNINGS (Los Angeles) -- Quarterly results from
Calabasas-based THQ Inc. By Jason Cohen. (Will move on the ``n''
California news wire and ``f'' financial wire.)
</P>
