<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-RESIGNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER AGREES TO RESIGN OVER BOOK CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROGER CROTEAU  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOERNE, Texas _ The high school English teacher who was
reprimanded for assigning an award-winning novel that some parents
said was too graphic has agreed to resign in a deal negotiated with
the school board.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Riley reached an agreement last week with the Boerne
school board, placing her on paid administrative leave until the
end of the year, when her resignation will become effective. The
district also agreed to remove the reprimand from her personnel
file.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with the way it has worked out, and the union did
a great job,'' Riley said, referring to the Texas Federation of
Teachers, which represented her in negotiations with the board.
``And with that, I'd like to lay it to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, Riley assigned the award-winning 1995 David
Guterson book ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' to 80 senior English
students at Boerne High School. The story about a Japanese-American
fisherman accused of murdering a white fisherman in a Washington
state coastal village has sold more than 3 million copies and
received the American Booksellers Award and the PEN/Faulkner Award.
</P>
<P>
   But some parents in the town 25 miles northwest of San Antonio
complained of violence and sex in the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got graphic violence, graphic mutilation of a dead boy's
genitals and a graphic sex scene,'' Boerne Trustee Fred Jones said
at a recent school board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The district initially banned teachers from using the book,
removed it from the library and reprimanded Riley, even though she
had gotten approval from the chairman of the English Department.
</P>
<P>
   The board later voted to put the book back in the school
library, although it is still not allowed for classroom use.
</P>
<P>
   Boerne Superintendent John Kelly said a confidentiality
agreement between the district and Riley prevented him from
answering questions about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a private, confidential matter, and it is the desire of
both parties, as much as possible, that it stay that way,'' Kelly
said.
</P>
<P>
   John Cole, president of the Texas Federation of Teachers, said
the union hired an attorney to represent Riley in negotiations with
the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is free now to go restart her career elsewhere,'' Cole
said of Riley. ``Boerne has lost a good teacher, and another school
district will be lucky to get her.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole and Kelly would not say if the district pressured Riley to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say that after someone has been through something
like this, they may feel their talents are not appreciated where
they are,'' Cole said, ``and they may want to go somewhere where
their talents are appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was reached Oct. 18. The school district will make
no payments to Riley, other than her normal salary, and Riley
proposed the settlement, according to a statement issued by the
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Ms. Riley and the board of trustees acknowledge that
opinions reasonably may differ from individual to individual
whether the use of the book `Snow Falling on Cedars' is appropriate
for a required-reading classroom book, but Ms. Riley voluntarily
stopped using the book when she became aware of concerns regarding
the book's appropriateness,'' the statement reads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
