<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVERNITE-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE AGAINST LARGEST NONUNION TRUCKER TESTS HOFFA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The teamsters' union strike against the nation's largest
nonunion trucking firm, the Overnite Transportation Co., spread
across the nation Monday, but company officials insisted the strike
was having only a negligible effect on its operations.
</P>
<P>
   The strike, which began at a single Memphis truck terminal on
Sunday, is one of the biggest tests faced thus far by James P.
Hoffa, who became president of the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters last March.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa and other teamster officials said they hoped the strike
would lead to Overnite's granting union recognition to the 8,200
drivers and dock workers at its 166 terminals. If the teamsters
succeed in organizing these workers, it would be one of the biggest
successes in unionizing private-sector workers in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Teamster officials said they had called the strike to pressure
Overnite to cease what they insisted were illegal practices, like
dismissing union sympathizers, in an effort to turn back a
unionization drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strike is the bitter fruit of Overnite's unrepentant and
unrelenting violations of its workers' federally protected
rights,'' Hoffa said.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Rosenfeld, a spokesman for Overnite, denied that the company
had broken the law in its efforts to resist the 5-year-old
unionization drive.
</P>
<P>
   To keep its business operating, Overnite, which is based in
Richmond, Va., has hired scores of security guards and replacement
drivers. Calling the strike's effects ``negligible,'' Rosenfeld
said: ``We're close to normal. We'll make all deliveries by the end
of today, as scheduled.''
</P>
<P>
   He said 94 percent of Overnite's employees had reported to work
Monday, although he acknowledged that during the strike Overnite
would consolidate its operations and not use all its terminals.
</P>
<P>
   But Dave Cameron, a teamsters' spokesman, said the company was
distorting how severe the strike's effects were. Cameron said that
there were pickets at more than 40 Overnite terminals, and that by
Tuesday there would be picketing at all 166.
</P>
<P>
   He said the teamsters would seriously inconvenience Overnite and
its customers by having teamster members follow Overnite trucks
when they make deliveries to various locations, like hardware
stores. The teamsters plan to picket those sites as the Overnite
truck unloads, a move that union officials predicted could persuade
customers to shun Overnite during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Overnite officials asserted that many drivers were crossing the
picket lines and that most of the people picketing were teamster
members who did not work for Overnite.
</P>
<P>
   But again, teamster officials had a vastly different version,
stating that, for instance, at the Memphis terminal, only 24 of the
260 workers crossed the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   The union says it represents 3,600 workers at 37 terminals. But
the company argues that because of legal challenges, the union
represents only 1,800 at 22 locations. On Sept. 17, the two sides
broke off negotiations for those unionized workers.
</P>
<P>
   The union has filed hundreds of charges with the National Labor
Relations Board accusing the company of systematically seeking to
block the union by harassing, intimidating and firing workers.
Overnite officials insist all those charges are a public relations
tactic and a pressure tactic intended to force the company to
succumb to the union's demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8078 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TAAS-SUIT-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      10-25 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAAS-SUIT-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE HEARS ARGUMENTS OVER EXIT EXAM IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A federal judge Monday began weighing whether the
state's high-school exit exam is racially biased or ``the Cadillac
of exams'' that has helped push Texas public schools to the
educational forefront of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most challenging decision I've had to
make in the time I have been here,'' U.S. District Judge Edward
Prado said after attorneys for both sides ended their arguments in
the 5-week-old trial debating the Texas Assessment of Academic
Skills test.
</P>
<P>
   Prado, who has been on the federal bench 15 years, is not
expected to rule for at least a month and maybe not until next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund sued the
state more than two years ago, arguing that the test public high
school students must pass to graduate is flawed. They noted that
disproportionately high numbers of Hispanics and black students
fail it.
</P>
<P>
   In education circles nationwide, the case is considered the most
significant education lawsuit to reach the federal courts in at
least the past two decades. It also may have political implications
for Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the GOP front-runner, who has been a
strong supporter of the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test discriminates on race,'' said MALDEF lead attorney Al
Kauffman. ``The state has developed and used an invalid test in an
invalid way to deny opportunity to thousands and thousands of
minority students.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Texas Education Agency, however, contend that
the TAAS test is an integral part of the state's nationally lauded
accountability system and that MALDEF has mischaracterized it as
punishment rather than as a boost to student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not punishment,'' said Assistant Attorney General
Geoffrey Amsel. ``It's ensuring that they get that core education
... This is a safety net.''
</P>
<P>
   MALDEF not only wants the judge to bar the state from using the
exit test as a graduation requirement. The plaintiffs also want him
to order the retroactive awarding of diplomas to thousands of high
school students who, since 1990, completed all their course
requirements but were denied a diploma because they failed one or
more sections of the TAAS test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denial of a high school diploma has tremendous consequences,''
MALDEF lead attorney Al Kauffman said in closing arguments. He
reminded the judge of testimony about students who had been
rejected by the military because they didn't pass the TAAS exam.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 400 exhibits filed by both sides and testimony of an
estimated 50 witnesses are reams of data about students who have
taken the test since 1990, how the test is constructed, analyses of
how students have performed as a whole, and how they perform based
on gender, ethnicity, income and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   Amsel argued that ``the vast majority of students pass the test
by the time they graduate,'' and that only 2 percent to 3 percent
of students never pass it. State witnesses testified they believe
there are a number of other factors that explain why some students
never get a diploma, including high absenteeism and failure to
complete required course work.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman, though, argued that the failure rare of Latinos and
blacks is twice that of Anglos. MALDEF alleges that ultimately 20
percent of blacks and Hispanics fail the TAAS when all their
attempts are counted, compared to 10 percent of whites.
</P>
<P>
   While TEA provided data showing year-by-year passing rates, it
did not provide analyses of overall attempts made by students.
</P>
<P>
   Texas high school students have eight chances to pass the test
while in high school. They may continue to take the test an
unlimited number of times once they have completed their course
work.
</P>
<P>
   MALDEF also argued that minority students are not given the same
opportunity to learn as whites and that they are more likely to
attend schools rated low-performing by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The minority plaintiffs further allege that teachers spend too
much time teaching test-taking techniques to students who have
failed or are at risk of failing the TAAS, depriving them of time
spent on more rigorous academics classes.
</P>
<P>
   Amsel, however, told Prado, ``TAAS is the Cadillac of tests,''
as evidenced by the numerous states who are trying to mimic Texas'
success in setting high education standards and rigorous testing
program.
</P>
<P>
   State witnesses testified that they believe TAAS has raised
student performance and that minorities have been closing the gap
in academic achievement with whites as a result of the TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendents from across the state, Amsel added, testified
that TAAS ``turned public education in Texas around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's going on here is ... they (the plaintiffs) are
trying to paint a frown across a face that's a very happy face,''
Amsel said.
</P>
<P>
   He said if MALDEF were correct in its contention that minority
students do not have the same opportunities to learn as do Anglo
students, the ``dramatic gains'' by minority students on other
nationally recognized tests like the National Assessment of
Educational Progress would not be there.
</P>
<P>
   Prado interrupted closing arguments at several points, asking
the lawyers a variety of questions.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he asked Amsel if the state is acknowledging a gap
between performance of minority students and that of whites.
</P>
<P>
   Amsel agreed there is a gap but said that it is closing.
</P>
<P>
   In a reference to new state academic skills tests being
implemented, Prado asked: ``Is that why we're now going to have a
new test that is harder? So the gap can go back to the way it
was?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
