u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      10-25 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GET A LIFT FROM ROAD TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time for the annual ``take stock after the road trip''report.
</P>
<P>
   After playing six away games, the Bruins jetted home from the
West on Monday, and after victories over San Jose and Anaheim, they
were pleased and relieved at the way the trip ended. They're now
2-5-4, which isn't great, but in two games they went from the
basement of the Northeast Division to the middle of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns said there's still plenty of work to be done but
the 400-pound gorilla is, for the time being, off their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get the media off our backs and the fans,'' said center
Jason Allison. ``It's true, you deserve it when you're
0-and-whatever, there have got to be answers, but I don't think
there are big answers for us. I think it is a matter of little
things and little mistakes. I don't think every guy played good
every night, but we were still playing good enough that we could've
been winning games. Hopefully, we went through our bad spell and
now it's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant general manager Mike O'Connell said until the club is
firing on all cylinders, it will be difficult to figure out its
strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to make an assessment because I don't think our team
has played as well, and players individually haven't played as well
as they can,'' said O'Connell. ``(Against San Jose) you saw a
little bit of what the team was capable of doing but even (against
the Sharks), I think there's a lot of room for improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins tied a franchise-worst start with no wins in nine
games (0-5-4). O'Connell said the slow beginning might be
attributable to the youth of the players and their too-comfortable
opinion of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of good things have been said about these young players
and maybe it went to their heads instead of really doing all the
little things it takes to win hockey games this time of year,''
said O'Connell. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   One factor he wouldn't turn to in terms of explanation, though,
is what some players, and even Burns, mentioned: the absence of
Byron Dafoe, Dmitri Khristich, and Tim Taylor. O'Connell addressed
those who had expressed such opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to a number of players about the situation and let
them know where we stand and why we did some of the things we've
done,'' said O'Connell. ``A lot of the players realize they're a
product of the reason we do things the way we do. Every player we
have on our team wants to win. They want to feel like they're being
given the best chance to win. Sometimes they have to understand, we
pick players off waivers and we make deals because of money. Some
of the best deals that have been made in this organization have
been made because of money.''
</P>
<P>
   One example he used was the deal that sent defenseman Glen
Wesley to Hartford for three first-round draft picks. That deal
yielded Sergei Samsonov and Kyle McLaren.
</P>
<P>
   ``To figure out what we have on the team right now is
difficult,'' he said. ``I saw some more positive signs (against San
Jose). I can tell you one thing, our goalie (John Grahame) is as
fine a young goalie as you'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor, said O'Connell, is that some youngsters are
assuming more important roles than they've had in the past. That
brings added pressure, and it takes time for them to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to be put in different roles,'' he said.
``Players get accustomed to those roles and where they fit in and
how much of a part of this team's success they're going to be. That
is all going to have to be established as well.''
</P>
<P>
   It's only been 11 games, and though there are certainly problems
and several unresolved issues, O'Connell said there's no panic.
Quite the contrary, in fact. Whether he's painting too rosy a
picture remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the players this team has and the players the other
teams have and I'm very happy and I'm very confident in the talent
level we have,'' said O'Connell. ``It's just a matter of all of the
players playing their best individually so we can play better
collectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Pat said, maybe this is our bad time of year. Every team
goes through tough stretches. Maybe this is our toughest stretch.
If we as an organization see there is a glaring weakness, in talent
or personnel, and we feel everyone is playing as hard as they can
and it just doesn't work, then you'd be concerned. But we haven't
seen that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The fingers are in the dike for now. In time, we'll see if the
Bruins spring another leak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
