<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-560(2TAK     10-25 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS OPPONENTS, GORE AND BRADLEY SHARE MANY SIMILARITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley
have a lot more in common than either would like to admit to
presidential primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   Each will try to emphasize differences that matter to those
voters when they debate for the first time Wednesday night in New
Hampshire. But in fact, the two Democrats have spent the bulk of
their public service careers as generally liberal members of
Congress, with quite similar approaches to the job.
</P>
<P>
   Their likenesses start with their voting records during
Bradley's 18 years in the Senate and Gore's eight years there,
after serving eight years in the House. Bradley, plainly seeking to
run to Gore's left on issues from health insurance to gun control,
was a bit more liberal in the eyes of old-fashioned liberals and
environmentalists. But to some groups, like the AFL-CIO and
conservative groups, their records appeared almost identical.
</P>
<P>
   But a congressional record, if it means anything at all, is more
than a compilation of votes, and the Bradley-Gore similarities
extend well beyond the yeas and nays.
</P>
<P>
   Each was effective in learning a complex, ``eyes glaze over''
issue and putting it on the national agenda. For Gore, there was
global warming, arms control questions and high technology. ``I
think my work on arms control made a contribution at a critical
time toward the creation of a new consensus on strategic
stability,'' Gore said in a recent interview. And he said his work
on environmental issues also helped to generate a consensus, both
for the Superfund program to clean up toxic waste sites and for
addressing global environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, there was Third World debt, international trade and
tax simplification. He was central to the 1986 tax reform act that
lowered tax rates and closed loopholes, which he pursued with ``a
single-mindedness that was sometimes irritating to my family,'' he
said in an interview. But in the end, he added, ``It became the
symbol of doing very big things in a bipartisan way.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither man was known in Congress as an orator. But Gore rose to
a dramatic occasion to explain his vote to authorize war in the
Persian Gulf in 1991, when he broke with almost all other
Democrats, including Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia, chairman of the
Armed Services Committee. Bradley was unaccustomedly eloquent the
next year in warning of deteriorating race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was especially chummy with their colleagues, though Gore
had more pals in the House than both of them, put together, had in
the Senate. In the Senate, Gore's run for the presidency in his
first term made him seem presumptuous to some senators, and he was
snidely labeled Prince Albert.
</P>
<P>
   That lack of loyal allies may be one reason why neither had a
striking record of getting laws passed, though each had a few
accomplishments. A more telling reason may be that neither served
long enough to head a committee, though Bradley dealt impressively
with Western water rights as a subcommittee chairman. In a similar
position, Gore first began warning of global warming and the
greenhouse effect.
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign, each will try to make an issue out of past votes,
especially as proof of comparative constancy and sincerity and as
reasons to trust their promises for the future.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
