<HEADER>
A8084 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-DRUGS-HNS &LR;      10-25 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DRUGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS STUDY ON HIGH COSTS OF MEDICINE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton accused the pharmaceutical
industry Monday of ``flat-out falsehoods'' in its effort to stop
his Medicare prescription program and ordered a study on why
medicine costs are so high.
</P>
<P>
   The president lashed out at the industry for running a series of
advertisements in which a fictional senior named ``Flo'' complains
that Clinton's Medicare proposal ``would put big government in your
medicine cabinet.'' He blamed the ad campaign for the inaction by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot stand by and watch the pharmaceutical industry go on
and distort this debate. We have to expose these deceptions and
give the American people the facts,'' Clinton said during an event
at the Old Executive Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   A key Republican, Rep. Bill Thomas of California, called
Clinton's remarks ``cynical and politically manipulative.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90-day study ordered by Clinton would analyze the cost of
the most common prescription drugs for those people with and
without insurance to determine if people without insurance are
paying a higher tab. It would look at medicine spending trends by
age and income to determine if high drug costs are taking a toll on
seniors and people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton previously ordered a state-by-state analysis of seniors'
prescription drug needs. He said the studies should ``help lay the
foundation for a more informed debate'' next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key reasons no action was taken on prescription
drugs this session was because the pharmaceutical industry spent
millions of dollars on an all-out media campaign filled with
flat-out falsehoods,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested high drug costs in the United States forced
seniors who could make the journey to travel to Canada or elsewhere
to purchase the same medicine at much lower prices. He said a
popular drug for lowering cholesterol cost $44 in Canada for 60
tablets and $102 in New Hampshire. ``It's wrong, and we have to
deal with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Clinton unveiled a Medicare proposal to add a
prescription drug benefit and expand the solvency of the
government's health insurance program for seniors to 2027 from
2015. His plan called for devoting 15 percent of the budget surplus
over 15 years _ $794 billion _ to shore up Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   It would create, for the first time, a Part D prescription drug
program starting in 2002. Beneficiaries would pay an initial
premium of $24 a month and the government would pay half their
prescription drug costs up to $1,000 a year. The premium would
increase to $44 a month and the coverage to $2,500 by 2008. The
poor would be exempt from the premium payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already pay for doctor and hospital benefits under
Medicare, but we let many of our seniors go without prescription
drugs and preventive screenings that could keep them healthy and
keep them from having to undergo expensive treatment,'' Clinton
said. ``It doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans countered that it was Clinton who was not making
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the president's talk today, we should all be concerned,
because the president offered `good' politics and proved once again
how infrequently he associates with the truth,'' said Thomas,
chairman of the House subcommittee overseeing Medicare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said Medicare premiums for the elderly would double
under Clinton's drug plan. He also cited a study estimating 50
percent to 75 percent of the private companies would drop
prescription drug coverage for retirees or limit their coverage
should Clinton's plan be enacted.
</P>
<P>
   Alan F. Holmer, the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of
America president, told The Associated Press that drugs are more
expensive in the United States than Canada because of Canadian
price controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that America has the best health care system in
the world and we don't want to copy the Canadian system with its
rationing of health care, its limits of access to medicines and its
waiting lines that are often three times longer than in the U.S.,''
Holmer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the industry trade group's ad campaign also was an
accurate description of Clinton's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested ``Flo'' and her husband ``Bill'' should go on
television to explain why drug costs are so high. ``I wish they'd
spend this ad money explaining why seniors have to get on the bus
and go to Canada to buy drugs at less than half the price they can
buy them in America, when the drugs are made in America, with the
benefit of the American system and American research and American
tax systems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Republicans were ``squandering a golden moment'' by
leaving more than 13 million people without prescription drug
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-2NDTAKE-     10-25 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the future.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gore, for example, has criticized Bradley for voting in 1992,
1994 and 1996 for school vouchers that parents could use to pay
private and parochial school tuition. The New Jersey Democrat says
he only supported an ``experiment,'' and today he opposes them.
That quarrel is designed to attract the votes of public school
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Bradley's insistence that he has always been ``a
consistent and unwavering supporter of a woman's right to choose''
whether to have an abortion is aimed at another important
Democratic primary constituency _ voters for whom abortion rights
are the prime issue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's current position is indistinguishable from Bradley's, but
before he first ran for president in 1987 it was generally
anti-abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, he generally opposed federal funding for abortions
for poor women on Medicaid. In the mid-1980s, the Tennessee
representative regularly wrote to constituents who asked his views
that: ``I have strongly opposed federal funding of abortions. In my
opinion, it is wrong to spend federal funds for what is arguably
the taking of a human life.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time he was seeking votes in Democratic presidential
primaries in 1988, Gore was equivocating, and by 1992 he supported
his party's position in favored of Medicaid funding for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The environment is an important point of comparison. Gore has
built much of his reputation in that area, although when it came to
voting records the League of Conservation Voters judged him
``right'' just 64 percent of the time, compared to 84 percent for
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is best known for big concepts, like global warming and the
threat to the ozone layer. The legislative results were not always
dramatic, although he led a successful effort to limit
chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, in the 1990 Clean Air Act and was
deeply involved with the Superfund program in the House. But since
the Clinton administration has not been nearly as dedicated to
those concerns as Gore was as a lawmaker, they sometimes seem to do
the vice president little good today.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is known more for specifics _ for filibustering an
effort to undo federal protection of millions of acres in Utah, for
securing the Sterling Forest preserve in New Jersey and New York,
and, most of all, for the 1992 California water rights legislation.
That law forced farmers to start paying more than a token price for
Central Valley water and made the water available for urban use.
</P>
<P>
   That legislation began as an issue that Bradley said ``I knew
nothing about'' but was his to deal with when he became a
subcommittee chairman. He studied it, held hearings, found allies
and maneuvered the bill into law, using election year pressures to
get President Bush to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was among an influential band of House Democrats who
threatened in 1983 to oppose deployment of the MX missile unless
the Reagan administration would start talking to Moscow about arms
controls. In the Senate he was among the advocates of reducing the
use of multiple warheads.
</P>
<P>
   One successful legislative effort that brought Gore recent grief
was high technology. In March he said he ``took the initiative in
creating the Internet.'' Republicans laughed him off the political
stage for that one, with Dan Quayle saying that if that was true,
he had invented spell-check. In fact Gore's efforts to promote
supercomputing and high-speed communications networks are
acknowledged by the developers of the process to have played an
essential role.
</P>
<P>
   Today Gore makes his Internet boast in more convoluted language:
``My work on technology included efforts to promote funding for the
technologies that were used by people who expanded early prototypes
of the ARPA-net that later became the Internet.'' He grinned and
added, ``I hope I have buffered that adequately.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's greatest Senate accomplishment was the 1986 tax reform
act that ``nobody in Washington thought would really happen,'' as
he put it in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Tax fairness was an issue he brought to Washington. ``I had
always been upset by a system where people who were able to use
loopholes paid less than people who did not,'' he said. He put the
idea in a book, pestered colleagues, worked with the Reagan
administration and Sen. Bob Packwood, then chairman of the Finance
Committee, and ultimately lobbied the House by playing basketball
with members in the House gym _ an activity he had avoided since
his election in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   But that was 13 years ago. Since 1986, he said, ``Billions of
loopholes have come back in and rates have gone back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley argues that his work on a variety of trade measures,
from the Uruguay Round _ a series of international talks that
resulted in the formation of the World Trade Organization in 1995 _
to the North American Free Trade Agreement, played important roles
in strengthening the economy. And he was an early critic of
Moscow's economic policies in the last days of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   One issue central to his presidential campaign on which he was
almost invisible in Congress is health insurance. In the 1993-1994
fight over President Clinton's plan or various alternatives, the
Finance Committee on which he served was a central battleground. He
explained his inactivity by saying he had followed the lead of Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., the committee chairman, who waited
in vain for Republicans to compromise. ``I was kind of working with
him on this,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   To one longtime observer of Congress, Norman J. Ornstein of the
American Enterprise Institute, what made both Gore and Bradley
``considerably better than average senators'' was their ability to
bring issues to national attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than Pat Moynihan,'' he said, ``I couldn't pick someone
better in the House or Senate to put an issue into play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
