<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STANDING PAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BUCHANAN-REFORM, BUCHANAN-ASSESS) 
(DW) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Buchanan's formal secession from the Republican Party
lost quite a bit of its drama because of a balky sound system. A
political primal scream requires amplification. One minute the
Buchanan of yore was howling about the New World Order, and the
next he was just like any other slightly flummoxed after-dinner
speaker, betrayed by bad audio-visual aids. (``OK, let me go back
and say we're going to cut those cancerous trade deficits. ...'')
</P>
<P>
   It was what his opponents have always dreamed about _ Pat
Buchanan as a soundless sound bite.
</P>
<P>
   His distress brought back memories of another recently departed
presidential candidate, Elizabeth Dole. During the party's
convention in 1996, Mrs. Dole was given the rather daunting
assignment of humanizing her husband, the presidential nominee. She
did a walking-through-the-audience performance that some people
found remarkably polished and others regarded as achingly
overrehearsed. Her arduous preparation extended to a drill over
what to do if her body microphone suddenly and inexplicably failed,
and guess what? The mike went out. Mrs. Dole extended her hand, an
aide put a replacement in her palm as smoothly as an operating-room
team mid-appendectomy, and on she went.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk one up for overrehearsed women.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the great thing about Pat Buchanan. He makes you feel
good about Elizabeth Dole. In fact, he has a genius for making you
feel great about all sorts of things that normally leave you a tad
depressed. Listen to him announce that ``our vaunted two-party
system is a snare and a delusion,'' and suddenly the two-party
system never looked better. You begin to wonder if we give people
like Al Gore and George W. Bush enough credit.
</P>
<P>
   His followers dwindling, his rhetoric getting old, Buchanan is
becoming the political equivalent of Prozac. When he announces that
this is ``our last chance to save our Republic before she
disappears into a godless New World Order,'' you smile benignly and
begin to plan the dinner menu.
</P>
<P>
   As he bade adieu Monday to the party of Lincoln, Buchanan got a
tad weepy about his happy days working for Richard Nixon and Ronald
Reagan, and then assailed the current crop of front-runners as
``hollow men, the malleable men, willing to read from teleprompter
speeches scripted by consultants and pollsters.'' (Do I see a hand
over there? Yes, you sir. Yes, you are correct. Buchanan's service
to Nixon and Reagan involved the writing of speeches.)
</P>
<P>
   The crux of Buchanan's complaint against the Republican Party
(and a fine party it is) seems to be that Larger Powers have been
plotting to deny him another chance at the presidential nomination
he nearly won from Bob Dole. ``Never again will our political
establishment permit a dissident to come as close to capturing a
nomination as we did in 1996,'' he said bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   This is an interesting theory. Buchanan has probably gotten more
free time on TV and talk radio than all the other presidential
candidates combined _ some weeks he is on the air more than the
weather. The all-powerful global elite has apparently not yet
gotten its hands on the communications industry. About that near
miss in 1996: Pitted against the most inept presidential candidate
since Horace Greeley, Buchanan won the New Hampshire primary and
the Louisiana caucus. Last time I looked, we had 50 states.
Suddenly you understand how Buchanan the historian came to develop
his interesting theories on World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the Reform Party offers a hope of a real debate and a
real choice of destinies for our country,'' the ex-Republican told
his followers. Translation: Only the Reform Party is desperate
enough to want him.
</P>
<P>
   To get the Reform nomination, Buchanan has to be deemed to be a
serious candidate by the party's leaders next summer, whoever they
happen to be at that moment. Then he and the other serious
candidates run in a mail-in primary conducted with all the rigor of
the Elvis stamp selection. Then everybody will wind up in court.
The Reform Party has mutated into an organization dedicated to the
cause of direct democracy, run by people who are perfectly willing
to keep changing the rules until they get the result they want. Pat
Buchanan seems perfect for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
