<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUCHANAN-COX     10-25 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buchanan launches Reform candidacy
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALLS CHURCH, Va. _ Lifelong Republican Pat Buchanan bolted
Monday to the Reform Party, urging a ``peasant army'' tired of
Washington politics to catapult him into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   To boisterous cheers of ``Go, Pat, go,'' the thrice-unsuccessful
contender for the GOP presidential nomination declared that his
third-party bid would invigorate America at home and abroad with
``a new patriotism.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Republicans nor Democrats are fighting ``with conviction
and courage to rescue God's country from the cultural and moral pit
into which she has fallen,'' Buchanan told more than 300 supporters
in suburban Washington. He promised to protect U.S. jobs from
unfair trade, fight abortion, keep the nation out of foreign
entanglements, abolish racial quotas, cut taxes and eliminate the
Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   A loser in the 1992 and 1996 Republican presidential primaries,
Buchanan was near the back of the pack in the Republican field
again this year, trailing far behind the frontrunner, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush. He had been mulling switching parties for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I believe, is our last chance to save our republic
before she disappears into a godless world order,'' said Buchanan,
the first to announce his Reform Party candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, billionaire real estate developer and casino operator
Donald Trump moved a step closer Monday to seeking the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   A day after calling Buchanan a ``Hitler lover'' on national
television, Trump changed his Republican voter registration to the
Independence Party. That is the Reform Party's affiliate in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a lot of experience,'' Trump said, ``more than
most people, more than most candidates. . . . I think I would
represent the Reform Party very well, if I decide to do it. That's
an `if.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Trump has said he believes the Reform Party can carve out a
niche between the major parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party has just moved too far to the extreme
right,'' he said Sunday. ``The Democrats are too far to the left. I
believe the Reform Party can be the true centrist party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in a statement, was more critical of Buchanan than in the
past: ``Pat Buchanan is leaving the Republican Party because
Republicans rejected his views during his three failed attempts to
earn the Republican Party's presidential nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   John McCain of Arizona, who had suggested that Bush was
appeasing Buchanan, issued a terse statement Monday. ``I do not
mourn his departure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party nominee will get $12.6 million in federal funds
for campaigning. If Buchanan wins the nomination and if he
participates in nationally televised debates, he could influence
the election, though probably not win, pundits said.
</P>
<P>
   If Buchanan appears poised to capture 10 percent or more of the
presidential vote, it might prompt Bush to select a conservative
vice presidential running mate, said Charlie Cook, a political
analyst for the National Journal, a Washington magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But Cook said he does not anticipate a ground swell of support
for the Reform Party ``with the economy as strong as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The revolutionary impulse (among voters) is really low,'' he
said. ``There are not a lot of people rushing the ramparts yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, Buchanan tried to stir anti-establishment fervor.
</P>
<P>
   In the pugnacious style he was known for as a conservative TV
commentator, after serving in the Reagan and Nixon administrations,
Buchanan peppered his 30-minute speech with blistering criticism of
the political system he thrived in for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vaulted two-party system has become a snare and a
delusion, a fraud upon the nation,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say to the money boys and the Beltway elite, who think
that at long last they have pulled up the drawbridge and locked us
out forever, you don't know this peasant army,'' he said. ``We have
not yet begun to fight.'' The crowd responded enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an admirer of Pat Buchanan,'' said Amityville, N.Y.,
nightclub owner Frank McKay, 32, part of an Independence Party
delegation from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Stewart, a registered nurse who chairs the Independence
Party in Manhattan, said she also planned to call Trump and welcome
him to the Reform Party. Unless Trump announces that he will run, a
decision that could be months away, Stewart said the Reform Party
``will not take him seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry McGuire, a retired Maryland doctor, said Trump ``would be
a great candidate for the emir of Kuwait.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite early sparring between Buchanan and Trump, Stewart said
she is not worried that the candidates' divergent views on topics
such as abortion might hurt the Reform Party. ``The point here is
to bring together divergent people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But outside the hotel where Buchanan spoke, five members of a
group called Shalom International protested what they called the
candidate's sympathetic views about Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   They were upset by Buchanan's recent book in which he contends
the Nazi leader posed no threat to the United States after 1940
because Germany's interests lay to the East.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8101 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      10-25 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUN-LOVING SPORTS CAR BLENDS STYLE, POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - From the same people who brought you the New Beetle
comes another brilliant piece of retro design, the Audi TT Coupe.
But where the VW left off with warm-and-fuzzy collective memories,
the Audi begins with styling that is evocative and purposeful, and
performance that makes driving it as much fun as it looks.
</P>
<P>
   Rounded curves, sharp creases, exposed screw heads and a big,
race-car-style fuel cap are combined into a shape that recalls the
aggressive Auto Union race cars of the 1930s. The TT Coupe also has
something in common with toasters and tea kettles with a look
derived from the famous Bauhaus design school, which took common
objects and redesigned them with an industrial, modern flair.
</P>
<P>
   The TT is the latest in a cadre of playful German sports cars,
joining the BMW Z3, Porsche Boxster and Mercedes-Benz SLK230,
bringing yet another flavor into this diverse group. While it's
tough to pick favorites here, the TT has the edge on all of them in
at least one aspect: the interior is decidedly the roomiest,
especially for an extra-tall driver (such as me).
</P>
<P>
   It's also one of the coolest interiors I've ever seen in a
production car. Intricately designed, it continues the industrial
look of the exterior, with aluminum and brushed-steel rings,
dimpled on the edges, and repeating in functional forms, such as
the air-duct adjustments, the door handles, shifter knob, gauges
and horn ring.
</P>
<P>
   Serious fun stuff, all designed to produce the aura of something
purposeful and highly engineered.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the TT Coupe has the performance to back it all up.
Superb road-holding with a suspension that is supple and
well-controlled, responsive steering, powerful brakes and
aggressive engine power, it's all there, plus a sophisticated feel
that puts it a cut above.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, there will be those who complain that it's not fast
enough, that the small four is just not enough engine, even though
it's turbocharged to produce 180 horsepower, and with minimal turbo
lag. Off-the-line acceleration may be a bit sparse, but midrange
and high-end power is right on the dime.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who think they need more, there will be a
high-performance TT coming out with 225 horsepower and a six-speed
manual transmission.
</P>
<P>
   The TT Coupe is basically a front-wheel-drive car, which also
might turn off some of the hot rodders. The TT driven here was
equipped with Audi's all-wheel-drive Quattro system, which enhances
handling and power delivery tremendously. At $1,750, it's a pricey
option, but worth it.
</P>
<P>
   On an all-day trip along the back roads near Bagdad, Kirkland
and Skull Valley, the TT showed itself to be a great runner,
particularly in terms of fast cornering, hill climbing and sweeping
quickly through curves.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I've learned about driving back roads in Arizona,
anything can happen. Roads that dive headlong into dry washes.
Roads that suddenly turn from smooth asphalt to rocky heaves, or
that are covered with loose sand. The Audi's suspension and drive
system soaked it all up easily, leaving me feeling confident that
it could handle any of it.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, my passenger and I felt secure and comfortable, despite
the challenging drive of more than 200 miles. The ride is nearly as
good as any sedan, despite the short wheelbase and tight
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The interior feels spacious for the driver and front seat
passenger, but just forget about the rear ``seat.'' It's a cruel
joke where only legless and headless passengers will find any
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   The Coupe is actually a hatchback, and the tailgate has a
bizarre warning label prominently displayed that shows what could
happen if you slam it with someone sitting in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Klunk!
</P>
<P>
   One thing you might find lacking in the TT Coupe is the ability
to drop its top. That, too, is coming. So is a Tiptronic automatic
transmission. Currently, only manual is available.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, I think the bottom line comes in at a decent place,
starting at about $30,000 and climbing to about $36,000. Besides
the Quattro at $1,750, there was a comfort package with heated
seats and a trip computer at $700, a performance package of
high-intensity headlamps and 17-inch performance wheels and tires
at $1,000, a premium audio and CD-changer package at $1,200, and a
hands-free mobile phone at $495.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the TT is built on the same platform as the New
Beetle, Jetta and Golf, though with a significantly different
suspension and other architecture. In some ways, it compares to the
new Beetles the way Karmann-Ghias compared with old Beetles.
</P>
<P>
   In other ways, it's like the German equivalent of the Plymouth
Prowler, highly styled with good performance and loads of fun to
drive or be seen driving.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful style, wonderful engineering, the Audi TT is a super
cool car in every way. I want mine. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Audi TT Coupe &QL; 
Vehicle type: Two-passenger (forget the back seat), two-door coupe,
all-wheel drive. &QL; 
Base price: $30,500. &QL; 
Price as tested: $36,170. &QL; 
Engine: 1.8-liter in-line 4, 160 hp at 5,500 rpm, 173 lb-ft of
torque at 1,950 rpm. &QL; 
Transmission:  &QL; 
5-speed manual. &QL; 
Curb weight: &QL; 
3,131 pounds. &QL; 
Wheelbase:  &QL; 
95.6 inches. &QL; 
EPA mileage: &QL; 
20 city, 29 highway. &QL; 
Highs: &QL; 
_Striking design. &QL; 
_Stylish interior. &QL; 
_Responsive performance. &QL; 
Lows: &QL; 
_Laughable back seat. &QL; 
_Some over-the-top details. &QL; 
_Had to give it back. &QL; 
 &QL; 
