<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-ROEPER-PAYNE-STEWART-     10-25 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-PAYNE-STEWART-TRIBUTE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REEL LIFE OF PAYNE STEWART 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the fact that my faith in God is so much stronger
and I'm so much more at peace with myself than I've ever been in my
life.'' _ Payne Stewart, after winning the U.S. Open in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   They got the movie wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, the drama would begin in much the same way it did
in real life. We open in Florida, where the popular and veteran
golf champion Payne Stewart and two other people board the Learjet
co-owned by Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Destination: Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot and copilot prepare the sleek flying toy for takeoff, and
soon the Learjet is soaring at 500 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart _ famous on the tour for his flamboyant ``knickers''
(often reflecting the NFL colors of the city hosting a particular
tournament) and tam o'shanter hat, basking in the glow of his
dramatic 1999 U.S. Open victory, proud of his morally correct
stance against the recent Ryder Cup rebellion by younger and more
selfish players _ settles back in his seat and relaxes.
</P>
<P>
   Life is good. Great actually. In the movie, they want to
illustrate his thoughts in an obvious way, so Payne takes out his
wallet and gazes fondly at a snapshot of wife Tracey and children
Aaron and Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   At 42, he's never felt such inner peace.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to the cockpit, and cue the heartstopping music. Something
has gone terribly wrong, possibly a pressurization failure, and
soon the pilot and co-pilot will be rendered unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   The Learjet is hurtling through the skies at frightening speed
with no one at the controls. Imagine a runaway train in the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, air traffic controllers are unable to establish
communication with the private jet that is climbing to a deadly
altitude of 45,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   By now the media have begun sniffing out the story. Regular
bulletins from the AP, raw live reports on the news channels, a
sudden flurry of phone interviews with retired pilots and FAA
officials and transportation experts. It's not yet a tragedy, but
it's a ``possible tragedy,'' according to the somber-faced anchors.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force F-15 fighter jets and later Air National Guard F-16s
are dispatched to accompany the wayward plane, which is now heading
over the heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Time is running out.
</P>
<P>
   But in a scenario that we've watched in a dozen films, a savvy
air traffic controller and a veteran pilot on the ground are able
to talk Stewart through the paces of steadying the aircraft and
landing it safely.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in the tradition of midair stunt magic from the likes of
``Air Force One'' and ``Executive Decision'' and ``Passenger 57''
and ``Con Air,'' an Air Force pilot manages to board the Learjet in
midair, defying the odds and all laws of science, and saves the day
just in time.
</P>
<P>
   That's what you'd get at the movies. A happy, implausible,
wildly exciting denouement. The impossible, once again, rendered in
somewhat believable terms.
</P>
<P>
   But life is messy. Life laughs at the movies. And as we've seen
so many times before, there is no celebrity immunity from sudden,
bizarre, deadly accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, the paparazzi chase Princess Di and Dodi Fayed
into the Pont de l'Alma tunnel and there's a terrible crash _ but
miraculously, she escapes unharmed, and uses that miracle as her
gateway into an anonymous, blissful existence far removed from the
spotlight. She marries, I don't know, a social worker. Some good
guy with no money.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, John Kennedy Jr.'s plane goes down in the water,
but he and his wife and her sister cling to a piece of the wreckage
and are rescued by the search team.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Janis wakes up with the worst hangover of her life
and swears off the booze; Jimi doesn't suffocate on his own vomit;
Marilyn says ``Who needs the Kennedys?'' and throws herself into
her work.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Elvis comes out of the bathroom and says, ``Man, I
gotta get in shape, I feel like hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Carole Lombard and Glenn Miller and Roberto Clemente and Thurman
Munson and Jim Croce and Buddy Holly _ they don't die in plane
crashes in the movie version. They're the heroes of the story, they
can't go out that way.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Payne Stewart and his fellow passengers do not
succumb to oxygen deprivation. There's nothing unique or exciting
or dramatic about that; it's just horribly unlucky, and terribly
final.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can life be coldly indifferent, it often has absolutely
no sense of story arc. No wonder we go to the movies to escape.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is the co-author of ``He
Rents, She Rents, a guide to guy movies and chick flicks,'' and the
author of ``Urban Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously
Entertaining Myths That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not
True!'' Both are available in bookstores now.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
