<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8104 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-BUCHANAN-COX     10-25 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-BUCHANAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: With Trump in wings, things could get lively
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This country gets along most of the time with two parties,
largely because that's all our system of government needs to
operate.
</P>
<P>
   Administrations can't be dissolved on a vote of confidence,
promoting the organized factionalism found in a parliamentary
system. The Constitution sharply demarcates a difference between
the executive and legislative branches and assumes a degree of
independence on the part of lawmakers that discourages much party
formation.
</P>
<P>
   While not mentioning party at all, the framers designed a
legislative system that lends itself to minimalism, and all 50
states are organized similarly. This year, however, there are other
factors at play, creating new incentives to go off the two-party
reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have rearranged the primary schedules and rigged the game
to protect the party favorites,'' Pat Buchanan said as he threw his
hat into the Reform Party ring Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the primary schedules have been affected more by
competition among the states than any concerted effort to rig the
game. But the effect is identical. The speeded-up schedule wouldn't
even give Buchanan a lot of C-SPAN time in a GOP race, much less a
realistic shot at the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the spadework done by Ross Perot in his last
two races added a big incentive to bolt, in the form of more than
$12 million in federal matching money the Reform Party nominee will
receive.
</P>
<P>
   To lay hands on that money, Buchanan may have to vie with Donald
Trump, who got things off to a congenial start over the weekend by
calling Buchanan a ``Hitler lover'' on national television. But
that beats taking a number to wait for a shot at George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Trump has no financial incentive to seek the nomination _ he has
already said he'd turn down the $13 million _ but a decade of
rich-guy candidates has apparently sparked him to consider getting
in the act as Jesse Ventura's tag-team partner.
</P>
<P>
   On the Jersey side of the George Washington Bridge, there's
currently a billboard advertising Trump's Atlantic City casino
which says: ``He's got it. You want it. Come get it.''
</P>
<P>
   That says enough about the prospective candidate to set fight
fans salivating at the thought of him sparring with the pugnacious
Buchanan in suburban hotel ballrooms across America, a club match
series if there ever was one. But the rules for the Reform Party
nomination are so complicated that it isn't clear just how their
competition will take shape, aside from a lot of name-calling.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear to whom it really matters. Buchanan on Monday
invoked his ``peasant army,'' calling on the memory of his success
four years ago in the New Hampshire Primary with an anti-NAFTA,
populist message.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, it's no peasant, but Perot, who gives
Buchanan his greatest advantage, and there will be no New Hampshire
Primary to serve as a rallying point for his pitchfork-wielding
followers. In a literal way, Buchanan and Trump, if he runs, will
be making this up as they go along.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
