<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8105 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-ALLY-ANST-AZR &LR;      10-25 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ALLY-ANST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLY'S DEJA VU ANGST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - What is it about Ally McBeal?
</P>
<P>
   She's been huge right from the start. The pilot aired, viewers
fell in love, the media swooned. Creator-writer-producer David E.
Kelley was given Emmys. David E. Kelley was given more shows to
write. David E. Kelley was given a raise.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Ally McBeal`` finished its sophomore season as a Top
20 show, tied with the serious and deeply respected ``Law &AMP;
Order.'' All this despite the fact that Ally is a ditzy lawyer in
short skirts working in a ditzy law firm with unisex bathrooms on
the fourth network.
</P>
<P>
   Big thinkers (Is-this-the-death-of-feminism? on the cover of
``Tim''e), not to mention competing network executives, have spent
a lot of time trying to figure it out. To listen to the noise,
you'd come away thinking that any combination of sexual innuendo
and a skinny heroine would pretty much do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   They're all working too hard. The answer is much simpler.
</P>
<P>
   Ally McBeal is Jan Brady.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Brady, in fact, is also Felicity.
</P>
<P>
   Felicity, of course, is also Ally, even earning the nickname
``Ally McBeal goes to college'' from ad executives who screened the
program first.
</P>
<P>
   It's basically the family tree for vulnerable female angst on
TV. And, at the root of it, they're all Mary Richards.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about a character so tormented by her
expectations, so vulnerable yet strong, so able to conquer the
world, if only we'd let her, that makes us really want to learn how
to program the VCR.
</P>
<P>
   And there is comfort in their craziness. We always know that, no
matter what, Ally is going to do something way dumber in that hour
than we did today. We know that Jan will never live up to Marcia,
that Felicity will never be tranquil, that Mary will never be
married.
</P>
<P>
   That's what keeps us coming back for more. Miserable but likable
characters make for great TV; they always have. Think for a moment
what it would be like if Jan had high self-esteem, if Ally settled
down, if Felicity were calm or if Mary were celebrating her fifth
wedding anniversary: We'd just have to hate them.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more accurately, hate her, since she's all the same person.
</P>
<P>
   Need evidence? Hip apartments are always yearned for, success
with boys is always questionable, and authority figures, whether
they be parents, courtroom judges or Lou Grant, are always bemused
by the struggle. There's always a best friend: Rhoda, Renee, Sally.
(Jan didn't have one on-screen, but that's because there were too
many Bradys to keep up with already.)
</P>
<P>
   Our character always has her personal trademarks. For Jan, it's
the desperate ``Marcia, Marcia, Marcia.'' Felicity is talking into
her tape recorder. Ally is dancing _ in the bathroom, with the
baby, in the courtroom, to a hallucination of Al Green. And Mary
has that hat toss.
</P>
<P>
   Bathrooms will always play a big role in our girl's life. Ally
kicks in stalls in the unisex, Jan fights with Marcia over their
unisex, and Felicity decides in a bathroom not to have sex. Mary,
we're sure, used it once or twice, but they didn't show toilets on
television in the '70s. (All we ever saw of the Bradys' latrine was
the sink.)
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the pajamas. You've gotta see a girl in
pajamas if you really are going to know her. So of course, we have.
Remember the Brady girls at bedtime? Hair perfectly brushed
(Marcia's was shinier), beds perfectly turned down, nightgowns tied
to their chins. Mary wore nighties but was embarrassed to be seen
in them. Felicity makes do with a tank top, but Ally's sheep
pajamas are a store knock-off legend.
</P>
<P>
   And, as with most things in the '90s, you can trace the
evolution of the societal function of coffee through our girls.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Jan didn't drink coffee because she wasn't old
enough. We know Mike and Carol drank plenty of it because Alice
always had some made. We can be sure that Marcia drank coffee
before Jan, and there probably would have been an entire 30-minute
episode about it if the show had lasted long enough.
</P>
<P>
   The much-older Mary drank loads of coffee with her friend Rhoda.
They drank it at home, in the tiny kitchen or at the table, and it
was still the nothing-special comfort brew of a pre-Starbucks
universe.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward 20 years to Felicity, and you've got a college
student working in gourmet coffee shops. You don't have friends
over for coffee anymore. You go out. You drink it at as early an
age as is possible. And a cup will cost you as much as a whole can
used to.
</P>
<P>
   And once you reach the age of Ally, coffee's an art. She drinks
her first cup, generally a latte, cappuccino or other formal name,
in a ritualistic, highly sexual manner. Plain black coffee is so 10
years ago. So are mugs. Now you have to have java jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Our girls are all strong in their element. Jan and Felicity are
great students. Mary was a terrific producer. Ally can win cases in
court, as long as they're not too serious.
</P>
<P>
   And there will always be something about our characters that
we'll envy. Jan had Alice _ we'd kill for those cookies after
school. Felicity had that very cool hair (she's cut it now, but it
will grow back). Ally gets to go every night to that really cool
bar that would never exist in real life. And we all wanted the M on
Mary's bedroom wall.
</P>
<P>
   But we'll always really pity our girls because we know that if
they could ever get over the angst and truly empower themselves,
just like we're going to do right after we finish watching
tonight's episode of ``Ally McBeal,'' they'd conquer the world.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of laziness, we're hoping this is never going to
happen. We don't want the show to end. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jaimee Rose can be reached at (602) 444-7975 or at
Jaimee.Rose(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
