<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8106 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SOUTHAFRICA-TRUTH-BOS     10-25 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENT MAY FORCE DE KLERK, BOTHA TO TESTIFY 
</HEADLINE>
 AFRICA-TRUTH-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Minutes from a high-level government meeting
submitted to the Truth and Reconciliation Commission on Monday
provide the most convincing evidence yet that F. W. de Klerk and P.
W. Botha, the last two white presidents of South Africa, were
directly involved in decisions to assassinate prominent
antiapartheid activists.
</P>
<P>
   The document, a record of the secretive State Security Council
from the early 1980s, could finally force Botha and de Klerk, who
have long frustrated the commission with reticence and denials, to
explain their knowledge of gross human rights violations committed
on behalf of their governments.
</P>
<P>
   The men, neither of whom have applied for amnesty from the
commission, are still vulnerable to prosecution on the basis of new
evidence of criminal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But it is still uncertain if the two former presidents will be
called again to testify. The minutes were brought before the
commission's amnesty committee by the lawyers for the family of
slain activist Matthew Goniwe, who was killed with three colleagues
in a 1985 roadside ambush near Port Elizabeth. The committee is now
considering whether to accept the new information filed under an
application for late evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the committee grants the application, the commission will
have to inform all those implicated by the evidence,'' said Phila
Ngqumba, a spokesman for the commission. ``But there is no
ambiguity: The minutes show that the State Security Council took a
decision to kill Goniwe, and the state president chairs the
council.''
</P>
<P>
   During the official lifespan of the commission, from April 1996
to July 1998, Botha and de Klerk successfully eluded full
disclosure. Botha, state president from 1978-89, defied three
subpoenas to appear before the commission, and then successfully
appealed against a court conviction for doing so. He has
consistently derided the panel as a ``circus'' and a ``witchhunt.''
</P>
<P>
   De Klerk, who held important Cabinet posts before following
Botha into office, appeared before the commission twice, portraying
himself both times as shocked and surprised to hear about the
crimes committed in the name of apartheid. ``I'm convinced that
people in superior positions were kept in the dark, and they were
not being told what was happening,'' he said in testimony before
the commission in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   His denials have cost de Klerk, who won international accolades
for lifting the ban on liberation movements like the African
National Congress and freeing Nelson Mandela from prison.
Commission Chairman Archbishop Desmond Tutu said over the weekend
that had he known the former president's true character, he never
would have recommended him to share the 1993 Nobel Peace Prize with
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   While the commission concluded its general hearings into human
rights violations last year, its amnesty committee continues to
operate. Several former security branch police officers from Port
Elizabeth have applied for official amnesty in connection with the
killing of the Cradock Four, a group of prominent antiapartheid
activists who were run off the road late one night, hauled into the
bush, and slain with grotesque brutality. Among them was Goniwe, a
charismatic young leader of the ANC.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ngqumba, the minutes of the State Security Council,
a shadowy inner Cabinet of Botha's government that included de
Klerk as one of its members, indicate that the police commissioner
at the time, Johan Coetzee, and apartheid hitman Craig Williamson
were instrumental in planning the Cradock Four murders.
</P>
<P>
   If the amnesty committee accepts the State Security Council
document as new evidence, Botha, de Klerk, and others implicated
could be called to testify, or even face prosecution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
