<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TEEN-PREGNANCY-GA-COX     10-25 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-PREGNANCY-GA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia among states with lower teen birth rates
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The teenage birth rate has fallen since 1991, with
the sharpest decline among black women, the federal government said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The decline was due mainly to three factors, according to Health
and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala:
</P>
<P>
   _ A fear of contracting AIDS and other sexually transmitted
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   _ A growing rejection of casual sex.
</P>
<P>
   _ Welfare reform laws that sent a message to young men about
child support obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there were 51.1 births last year for each 1,000
women aged 15 to 19, the department said. That was down 18 percent
from a rate of 62.1 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the improvement was due to a 26.1 percent decline in the
same period among black teenagers and a 12.2 percent decline among
Hispanic teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, teen births fell almost 12 percent from 1991 to
1997. The birth rate for the state's black teens was 92.6 per 1,000
teenage women, compared to a national rate of 88.2. For Hispanic
teens, the rate was 125.9 statewide and 97.3 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The figures give some hope to efforts targeting teenagers, said
Isabel Sawhill, president of the National Campaign to Prevent Teen
Pregnancy. ``Lower rates of teen births are a result of less sex,
more contraception and a growing recognition among teens themselves
that their focus should be on education and growing up,'' she said
at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said: ``We believe the strength of teen pregnancy
programs is working in local communities.'' Teens need help
negotiating their way through the pressures of engaging in risky
behavior, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Communities must take the initiative in reducing teen
pregnancies, Sawhill said, using programs tailored to their needs.
She said sex education in the schools is insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the National Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy
released a manual to help communities design successful prevention
efforts. It contains the latest research on teen pregnancies and
provides strategies for after-school activities and building
fund-raising coalitions, Sawhill said.
</P>
<P>
   Raven Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
