<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND CHINA CONCLUDE TALKS ON TRADE ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story was previously eliminated but has been restored.) 
(mk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers finished two
days of meetings in China Monday with both sides extolling
financial cooperation and exuding friendship. But there was no sign
of progress on the overarching issue, China's entry into the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by all accounts, Summers' meetings Sunday with Prime
Minister Zhu Rongji and Monday with the finance minister, Xiang
Huaicheng, and other senior officials were friendly and free of
rancorous rhetoric _ perhaps an achievement in itself since the
countries are still emerging from the icy silence that followed
NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, last
May.
</P>
<P>
   Without discounting the difficult market-opening concessions the
United States demands of China before it will endorse membership in
the global trade body, Summers and other American officials
appeared optimistic that agreement was still possible in the coming
month, before new global negotiations begin.
</P>
<P>
   Summers and other senior economic and security officials came to
China for a meeting of the ``China-U.S. Joint Economic Committee,''
a periodically scheduled exchange of ideas. Officials said no trade
negotiations were held.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders on both sides clearly wanted to present a cheerful
public face and an exchange at Monday's news conference expressed
the mood.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the prospects for a trade agreement, Summers said:
``Any differences can be bridged with good will on both sides. But
certainly there are differences that have to be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Xiang, smiling, replied: ``I agree with the point that with good
will, all the problems can be solved'' _ subtly suggesting,
perhaps, that a decision by the Americans to give China some slack
was now required.
</P>
<P>
   To which Summers quickly retorted, to laughs from the room of
officials and journalists, ``But there is something to be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``something'' is, in the American view, concessions by
China to gradually allow global competitors to enter now-protected,
state-run sectors like financial services and telecommunications,
and to lower barriers to American farm products.
</P>
<P>
   Summers, in meetings and in a speech Monday at Qinghua
University extolling the merits of market forces and the free flow
of information and technology, argued that China will be better off
for letting in competition. This is accepted in principle by many
of China's leaders, but is difficult to carry out in a country with
serious problems of unemployment, farmer unrest and a huge, dying
state enterprise sector.
</P>
<P>
   In a visit to Washington last April, Rongji was said to have
made deep concessions that he hoped would clinch the trade deal,
but President Clinton decided they did not go far enough to satisfy
Congress, which will ultimately have to cooperate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
