</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-RESERVES-660&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATION OF NO-FISHING ZONES PROPOSED TO CONSERVE FISH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Gulf States, New England)  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fearing that conventional fishing restrictions
cannot reverse a steep decline in marine stocks, conservationists
and fishery managers are increasingly advocating that large
expanses of the sea be put entirely off limits to harvesting of
ocean life.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of establishing such ``marine reserves'' has been
successfully employed by other nations and is gaining credence as a
step necessary to restore a variety of dwindling U.S. species that
have been overfished or lost as bycatch in the pursuit of more
valuable prey.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marine Fisheries Service is studying a plan that
would ban fishing in two 100-square-mile blocks of the Gulf of
Mexico off Florida to protect spawning grounds of the gag grouper.
Another proposal is emerging that would create extensive reserves
around the Dry Tortugas in habitat populated by a variety of reef
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the Georges Bank and some scallop grounds off New
England are already closed to fishing and tight restrictions are in
place for the Oculina Bank off Fort Pierce, Fla. Consideration is
now being given to putting large stretches of the California coast
out of bounds and a Caribbean reserve is on the drawing board for
near St. Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates compare establishing huge no-fishing zones to the
practice of creating on-shore game preserves to protect wildlife
populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we don't hunt everywhere on land, we fish just about
everywhere in the ocean,'' said Chris Dorsett, fisheries program
director for the Gulf Restoration Network of New Orleans.
``Scientific evidence shows that protecting important areas can
help restore depleted fish populations _ meaning more fish in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   While aiding the species singled out for protection as well as
other fish, reserves have ancillary benefits in the eyes of
supporters: protecting sensitive habitat from destructive fishing
gear and creation of an environment relatively free of man.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ought to be parts of the ocean where we are minimizing
human activities to the extent that we can see what an unimpacted
marine ecosystem would look like,'' said Kim Davis, who monitors
Atlantic and Gulf of Mexico fisheries issues for the Center for
Marine Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing groups, while not g blanket opposition, are
skeptical of the value of marine reserves. Industry representatives
say the restrictions can have severe unintended consequences such
as causing stocks to drop elsewhere as fleets shift territory in
pursuit of their catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trendy right now, but we have been using time and
area closures for more than 10 years,'' said Justin LeBlanc, vice
president of government relations for the Washington-based National
Fisheries Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is new, and what concerns us a little bit, is when we
hear people saying they want to set aside 20 percent of the world's
oceans,'' he said. ``To unilaterally set aside big tracts of the
ocean without understanding the ramifications seems to be a
disconnect.''
</P>
<P>
   A scientist retained by the Southeastern Fisheries Association,
a group contesting the proposed Gulf gag grouper reserves, said the
new emphasis on marine reserves seems like a desperate search for a
``magic bullet'' solution to fish losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard truth is, there are no magic bullets,'' wrote Trevor
Kenchington, a Canadian fisheries expert, in a review of the Gulf
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Others seem open to the idea, particularly since an array of
fishing restrictions does not appear to be working. Despite
individual bag limits, size limits, sharply defined seasons, caps
on the total annual catch of certain species, restrictions on the
type of gear used, even requirements for bycatch excluder devises,
fish populations continue to struggle and shrink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional methods of fish management are just not
effective,'' said Chris Smith, a spokesman for the Southeast Region
office of the National Marine Fisheries Service in St. Petersburg,
Fla.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That agency is reviewing the gag grouper proposal made by the
Gulf of Mexico Fishery Management Council, a multi-state commission
responsible for protecting Gulf fish stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The council was required to act after evidence showed that the
gag grouper, an important reef fish, was nearing a dangerous
population threshold. Two decades of heavy fishing in gag spawning
areas drastically cut the male population and reduced the size of
the spawning fish. Genetic tests showed heavy inbreeding.
</P>
<P>
   Council members originally designated more than 400 square miles
for the grouper reserve, but cut the area in half in July after
complaints by fishing interests. They also established the reserves
for just four years, saying they would be re-evaluated based on
demonstrated benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the panel are still unhappy and filed objections
with the federal fisheries service, complaining that the reserves
are not well thought out or based on sound science.
</P>
<P>
   Conservation groups were not satisfied, either, saying the size
of the no-fishing zones should not have been cut. But they consider
the grouper reserves a solid first step toward what they hope is
wider use of the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marine reserves hold great potential for both the ecology and
the economy of the Gulf of Mexico,'' said Davis, the Center for
Marine Conservation expert.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-LORDS-NYT &LR;      10-25 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-LORDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LABOR'S BRITANNIA, LORDS BLOW THEIR OWN TRUMPETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Some peers wrote in Latin. Others wrote in verse.
Almost all hoped that their unique credentials _ whatever those
credentials might be _ would prove useful if they were allowed to
stay in the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a small and happy bison farmer with aspirations above
his station. ... '' Lord Seaford began in a written statement last
week describing why he wants to run in what is surely one of the
strangest British elections in memory.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the House of Lords is to begin deciding which 92
hereditary peers, whose titles are inherited, will be allowed to
remain in the chamber when the rest _ some 650 _ are forced to give
up their seats. Although he is running, along with more than 200
other lords, Seaford is no fan of the need to do so. ``Si fractum
non sit, noli id reficere,'' he declared in his statement _ the
Latin for, ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   In manifestoes that are by turns boastful, whimsical, modest,
supercilious and completely off the point, the candidates showed
widely varying approaches to the supremely unaristocratic chore of
begging for votes.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Rennell described himself as ``a sporting diplomat or a
diplomatic sport.'' The Earl of Clanwilliam mentioned an interest
in Chinese medicine. And Lord Geddes, a businessman, came up with a
crisp advertising-style slogan: ``Brains; Breadth; Brevity.''
</P>
<P>
   What has led to this unlikely spectacle is the Labor
government's program of constitutional overhaul. Under Prime
Minister Tony Blair, the government has enacted legislation
decreeing that Britons with inherited titles _ dukes, marquesses,
earls, countesses, viscounts, barons and the like, the overwhelming
majority of whom are Tories _ are no longer to be allowed to sit
and vote in Parliament's upper house. But in a concession to the
hereditaries, as they are known, the government is letting 92 stay
on, along with the 541 life peers, all appointees of one government
or another, whose titles die with them.
</P>
<P>
   All this has forced the peers to apply for jobs that they
inherited in the first place and that have never required anything.
Judging from their statements, it appears that this might be the
first time some of the lords have had to apply for anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been interested in politics,'' wrote Lord
Harding of Petherton, while Lord Blyth proudly noted, ``I have
attended the House on a regular basis and have participated in all
the committees that I have been asked to sit on.''
</P>
<P>
   The peers were given just 75 words to explain themselves and
evoke hundreds of years of family history, so they had to say it
fast. (Lord Pender said it fastest: the word ``DUTY'' was his
entire statement). Some simply listed their achievements. The Earl
of Denbigh and Desmond noted that he is a member of the All Party
Motorcycling Group, while Lord Colwyn pointed to his experience as
chairman of the Refreshment Subcommittee, as well as his civilian
responsibilities as dental surgeon and bandleader.
</P>
<P>
   Several lords seemed almost genetically unable to engage in
self-promotion, something that Britons from old families have
traditionally found most unattractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hardly for me to attempt to proselytize my candidature;
it is a matter for my peers,'' said Lord Morris. The Earl of Onslow
did him one better, getting the word ``vainglorious'' into his
non-manifesto manifesto: ``It would be as vainglorious to proclaim
a personal manifesto as it would be arrogant to list any
achievement,'' he wrote. ``I therefore hope that my fellow peers
will honor me with their vote, on account of their knowledge of my
endeavors.''
</P>
<P>
   When the landed aristocracy really did run Britain and there was
a sense that coming from an impressively titled family meant you
had a duty to your country and a certain degree of innate
intelligence, the House of Lords had a crucial legislative role to
play. In recent years, though, it has been stripped of most of its
power and serves mostly as a tempering influence on the House of
Commons.
</P>
<P>
   Some candidates spoke wistfully of the Lords' tradition of
independence, especially now that the government enjoys such a huge
majority in the House of Commons and dissenting voices are so rare.
</P>
<P>
   When the bulk of the hereditaries hang up their ermine robes for
good, Britain will lose one of its strongest surviving links to the
distant past. Some hereditary peers have titles that date back 600
years, before Parliament even existed, and many have ancestors that
figure prominently in the nation's history. Among the current Lords
are Earl Sandwich, of the sandwich family, and the Marquess of
Queensbury, of the boxing-rules family.
</P>
<P>
   And what legislative body other than the Lords would include a
member who wants to keep her seat on the ground that she ``writes
Lords diary; brings flowers; loves House of Lords,'' as Baroness
Strange does? Or a member whose manifesto supports ``action against
cruelty to animals, especially fishing with rods,'' as Viscount
Monckton of Brenchley's does?
</P>
<P>
   That's not all. If elected, the Viscount wrote, he will do his
best to further his strongly held belief that all cats should be
``muzzled outside to stop the agonizing torture of mice and small
birds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
