<SLUG> BC-BBO-GAME3-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves facing calamity, but remain calm
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All season, the Braves have had a hard time
explaining how they have won. So maybe that's why they seem calm in
the face of their biggest World Series calamity of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   They're just going to do it, not try to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we need to win, period,'' Greg Maddux said. ``We're
not in a good position. We need to come out and play a good game,
do the things we're supposed to do, not beat ourselves, play the
game right.''
</P>
<P>
   Down 2-0 to the Yankees, the Braves need a win tonight from Tom
Glavine over Andy Pettitte to keep breathing. A loss and the end of
the season and the decade-long postseason run is all but a
technicality. No team has ever come back to win a best-of-seven
series after trailing 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves came back, down 3-1, to win the 1996 NLCS. And this
year, they saw the Mets come about as close as a team could to
erasing a 3-0 deficit before chasing them off in the unforgettable
Game 6 of the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves haven't won since.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have been teased in a 4-1 loss in Game 1 after
leading Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez 1-0 in the eighth inning.
Then, they were humiliated 7-2 Sunday night, when a lineup shuffle
backfired for the most-lopsided loss in their 27 World Series games
of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' top two pitchers have been beaten, and their lineup
has been brought to its offensive knees. They have looked as bad as
they can look, but they're still looking ahead.
</P>
<P>
   For that, they owe the Yankees, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were dealing with the exact same situation in 1996.
New York had lost the first two games to the Braves in Yankee
Stadium by a combined 16-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have only to look as far as the other dugout to see how
it's done,'' Chipper Jones said. ``Why not? It's not impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves defied logic for 103 regular-season wins and an
eighth division title of the '90s. They scored more runs than any
other Braves team _ 840 _ without their best power hitter, Andres
Galarraga. They won more games in their last at-bat (31) than any
team in the majors without their best clutch hitter, Javy Lopez,
for the season's second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves led the majors in ERA _ 3.63 _ with their fourth-best
starter Kevin Millwood emerging as the ace and with a volatile
former setup man, John Rocker, as the steadying force in the
bullpen, replacing Kerry Ligtenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they've got to win at least two of three games at Yankee
Stadium to keep this Series alive, against a team that has reduced
the Braves offense to a free-swinging mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we tried too hard,'' said Ryan Klesko, who is
0 for 7 in the first two games of this World Series. ``We just need
to relax. We swung the bats good against Randy Johnson (this
season), the best left-hander in the game. We don't care how good
you are, our offense shouldn't be that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are as cold as they've ever been in a World Series,
hitting only 7 for 58 (.121) in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``(In) my first two at-bats in the first two games I was going
to go to extreme pain to break up a no-hitter,'' Chipper Jones
said. ``Someone asked me about a lack of runs. Who's talking about
runs? We're just trying to get some hits. It's frustrating. This is
a team that's accustomed to scoring runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be shut down the way we have the last two games is a dent
to everyone's ego,'' Jones said, ``but we've just got to relax and
go out and have fun and not worry about the outcome of the game and
compete and hope things turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves can take solace in these numbers: They have lost
their last seven games against the Yankees in Atlanta, dating back
to three losses at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium in the 1996 World
Series. But they have won 7 of their last 11 games at Yankee
Stadium in that time, including two of three in interleague play in
July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows what we're here to do,'' Ryan Klesko said.
``We're not going to hang our heads. We're going to go out, play
hard; if we get beat, we get beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux said, ``We're still hungry to win. We're not going to lay
down. We've got some quality players over here who at any second
could start playing a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
