<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-REGATTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIZERS SATISFIED   AFTER SMOOTH WEEKEND OF RACING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The 40-mile-per-hour gusts that might have
blown everybody halfway to Harvard Yard never happened. Nobody ran
a shell up onto Memorial Drive. Except for the usual fender-benders
and tangled oars between Dead Man's Turn and the Eliot Street
Bridge, there were no pileups. And the right people got the medals.
</P>
<P>
   The 35th Head of the Charles Regatta _ with its 6,500 rowers
from 300 clubs in two dozen countries in 1,400 boats competing in
40 races over two sun-dappled days _ came off with barely a ripple.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, as the tents were being taken down along the
river and the last boat trailers left for North Carolina and
Colorado and points between, executive director Fred Schoch finally
exhaled _ and began thinking about next year.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the 75-member race committee will have its usual
debriefing dinner. Next month, the management team will convene.
``That's when we think about how to tweak the regatta,'' Schoch
said.
</P>
<P>
   No tweaking was necessary in 1965 when the founders had to
recruit entrants by phone. But now that the Head has grown into the
largest two-day rowing event on the planet, the annual questions
have taken on more urgency.
</P>
<P>
   Can the regatta get any bigger? (No, Schoch says.) Are
performance standards necessary? (Probably.) Should the organizers
keep bringing in the international elite? (Yes.) Is the event too
commercial? (Not yet.) Not commercial enough? (God forbid.)
</P>
<P>
   Those are all the same issues that the Boston Athletic
Association grappled with in the '80s after the road running boom
turned its annual marathon into a monster. ``These are the growing
pains of the regatta,'' Schoch conceded. ``We really can't be all
things to all people.''
</P>
<P>
   The charm of the Head is that it has managed to be exactly that.
It offers medals for men and women in 20 events across nine
categories _ youth, club, master, senior master, grand master,
veteran, senior veteran, lightweight, and championship (elite). It
has no qualifying requirements. Anyone who finishes within 5
percent of the winning time is guaranteed an entry for the
following year. The rest are awarded by lottery.
</P>
<P>
   So anyone who ever has dipped an oar into water is eligible to
share the course with an Olympic gold medalist. As Title IX and
America's fascination with lifetime fitness sports have made rowing
a hot sport, the Head's entry lists have exploded from 3,900 in
1990 to 5,600 last year to 6,500 now. As it was, one-third of the
10,000 applicants were shut out.
</P>
<P>
   The event can't get any bigger, regatta officials say. The Head
is not a road race. ``In the marathon, you can stick as many
runners on the course as you want,'' Schoch said. ``Our problem is,
our start is single file. Can you imagine what the marathon would
be like if they started one at a time every 10 seconds? They'd be
running for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   So the pressing issue is who gets to row. The scramble for slots
is so competitive that numerous clubs and colleges have dreamed up
imaginary spinoffs to get more entries. ``That's why you see all
these funny names,'' said Schoch. ``We have to find a sane and fair
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the BAA finally went to qualifying standards for the
marathon, the Head is leading that way, too. ``I wouldn't be
surprised to see a portion of the entries based on performance in
other regattas,'' Schoch said.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of them. ``We want the race to still be a place
where the novice can row on the same river as an Olympian.''
</P>
<P>
   The Head always has been as much about the St. Ursula Academy
women's four from Ohio as the US men's eight, as much about the
Rude &AMP; Smooth BC as the Deutscher Ruderverband. That's essentially
what next month's tweaking session will be about. How can the Head
of the Charles keep finding space for both of them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we should go to a LeMans start,'' Schoch mused
puckishly. ``That would be a crowd-thriller. Put everybody at the
Mass. Ave. bridge _ and let 'em go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
