<SLUG> BC-KYRGYZSTAN-DEMOCRACY-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRACY SPROUTS IN KYRGYZSTAN'S HOSTILE SOIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 was sent on Oct. 22; photo NYT28 is being
sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BISHKEK, Kyrgyzstan _ The deserts, steppes and mountains of
Central Asia have given birth to some of history's most brutal
conquerors, but very few democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Kyrgyzstan, however, there are intriguing hints that the
idea of popular sovereignty may be taking hold. If it does, this
remote and landlocked nation could become the first democracy in
Central Asia's long history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is our heritage as nomads,'' said Askar Sarygulov,
a former government official. ``The Kyrgyz have always lived in
small groups, not under emperors. We're used to thinking for
ourselves. So maybe the ground here is a little more fertile for
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Kyrgyzstan can keep its democratic promise may soon
become clear. Parliamentary and presidential elections are
scheduled for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making every effort to assure that these elections will
be fair and transparent,'' President Askar Akayev said in an
interview. ``This is our test, our examination, and we want to do
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Akayev, a physicist and mathematician, has refused to say
whether he will run for re-election, but stepping down voluntarily
would be an astonishing gesture. Since time immemorial, leaders in
this part of the world have held power until they died or were
forced out.
</P>
<P>
   Holding a free election would also be a radical break with
tradition. Opposition figures say that the police have already
begun harassing them and preventing them from holding rallies.
Akayev blamed overzealous local officials for such abuses and said
he would not tolerate them.
</P>
<P>
   People in Kyrgyzstan, a nation of 4.5 million that was part of
the Soviet Union until 1991, seem to admire Akayev's dedication to
democratic principles. But many consider him too weak for his job.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In eight years as president, Akayev has not been able to return
his people to the living standard they had during Soviet days. Some
of his close relatives and leading supporters have garishly
enriched themselves at public expense. And in the south, Islamic
guerrillas have begun a campaign that could threaten national and
regional stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our president is a great philosopher,'' said Bahrom
Attohojayev, a barber in the southern town of Osh. ``Maybe he would
make a good leader of a country that has no problems. But we have
problems. We need a tough guy who can get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If the opposition managed to unite behind a strong candidate,
Akayev could lose at the polls next year. Such a democratic turn of
events would be unthinkable in any of the other four Central Asian
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring Tajikistan has recently emerged from civil war and
is in ruins. The electoral commission there has disqualified every
opposition candidate who sought to run for president in an election
in November.
</P>
<P>
   Turkmenistan is run by a former Communist who has made himself
the center of a personality cult. The leaders of Kazakhstan and
Uzbekistan are both autocrats who brook no opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In this company, Akayev stands out as a veritable Jeffersonian.
His government has harassed opposition newspapers and political
parties but still allows them to function. Politicians and other
public figures denounce him without fearing for their safety.
</P>
<P>
   Even most of Akayev's critics concede that he is highly
intelligent. But they also say he is easily influenced, unable to
curb rampant corruption, and ill equipped for the challenges of
ruling a turbulent Central Asian nation, particularly one
threatened by social problems and now a religion-based insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A prominent newspaper editor, Zamira Sydykova, recently spent 10
weeks in jail after being found guilty of slandering Akayev. But
soon after her release Akayev invited her to a joint television
appearance and they publicly made peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed his two sides,'' Ms. Sydykova said. ``As a person or
a scientist, he believes in freedom, and that's good for
Kyrgyzstan. But in his identity as president, he isn't doing enough
to fight those who want to kill freedom, including people in his
own group.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   During the interview, at a rural government guest house that
dates to Soviet days, Akayev, 54, wore a business suit and a white
kolpak, the high-peaked felt hat that is traditional for Kyrgyz
men. He said he looked forward to the day when Kyrgyzstan would be
considered ``the Switzerland of Central Asia,'' comparable not only
in Alpine splendor but also in social justice, democracy, ethnic
peace and a thriving economy based on tourism and financial
services.
</P>
<P>
   Many Kyrgyz joke about that vision. They say that although their
country can boast magnificent scenery, it lacks the essential item
necessary to become another Switzerland: Swiss people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
