<HEADLINE>
CHEF PROFILE OF ... MAKO SEGAWA-GONZALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
 &HT;    By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Age: 28. &QL; 
Profession: Executive chef, Maui Beach Cafe, Westwood. &QL; 
Hometown: Hilo, Hawaii. &QL; 
Food background: He grew up watching his dad cook. And from the age
of 7, with help, Segawa-Gonzales started cooking Japanese and
Chinese creations. During his high school years in Tucson, Ariz.,
he worked in restaurants preparing salads, appetizers and hot and
cold foods. He attended the Culinary Institute of America in Hyde
Park, N.Y., for two years and graduated in 1992. He landed a job
working for chef and restaurateur Roy Yamaguchi as line cook and
sous chef at Roy's Kahana Bar and Grill in Kahana, Maui. After
three years there, he moved on and opened Roy's Poipu Bar and Grill
in Poipu, Kuaui, where he was executive chef for 2 1/2 years. In
the summer of 1997, Segawa-Gonzales joined Maui Beach Cafe, which
opened in Westwood in November of that year. &QL; 
Cooking style: Asian cuisine influenced by Hawaiian regional
cooking. &QL; 
Kitchen secret: Clean up as you go and always be prepared
(especially for diners' special request items so you can
accommodate them). &QL; 
Most popular dish he makes: Maui Roll. &QL; 
Three favorite foods: Sushi; a good steak; noodle dishes. &QL; 
Favorite junk food: Oreo cookies. &QL; 
Foods he dislikes: Vinegary-sour types of foods. &QL; 
Secret food passion: Different spices. &QL; 
Favorite restaurants: Allen Wong's in Honolulu and Wild Ginger in
Seattle. &QL; 
Favorite thing to cook and eat: Teriyaki chicken and Kalbi (Korean)
ribs. &QL; 
Favorite kitchen gadget: A vegetable turner that he uses for a lot
of garnishes so that the vegetables come out in thin threads. &QL; 
Pet peeve: When he can't find a matching sock. &QL; 
Ideal vacation: Relaxing in Hawaii for two weeks. &QL; 
What does he do when not cooking?: Plays with daughter Frankie, 4,
and son Makani, 2. &QL; 
If he couldn't be a chef what would he be?: An architect. &QL; 
Dream job: He already has it. &QL; 
Worst kitchen disaster: When the power went out at 8:30 p.m. in the
middle of the dinner rush at Roy's in Kuaui on Christmas Eve (the
restaurant had just been open a month and was very busy). The
restaurant closed; the power came back on 1 1/2 hours later. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
END &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</TEXT>
