<HEADER>
A8131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-BURNOUT-COX     10-25 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BURNOUT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves fever a thing of past?
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gotta light? The fire is missing from fans witnessing
yet another Braves swing at a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Braves began flailing around in the World Series
this year, fans say recent postseasons seem to have lacked the heat
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   We're not just talking about ticket sales, although Atlanta has
been chided for failing to sell out most of its playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   The real change, fans say, is a shortage of Braves fever.
</P>
<P>
   Where have all the tomahawks gone? Where are the fan rallies?
What happened to the face paintings by the bucketful?
</P>
<P>
   _ WXIA (the Atlanta NBC affiliate) president Bob Walker says
preliminary numbers for the first two World Series games captured a
``very strong'' 714,000 households or 42 percent of area homes with
TVs. That's down, however, from about 50 percent of households that
tuned in when the Braves played the Yankees in the first game of
the 1996 World Series, according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It's about dead,'' says Beverly James, who sells $1 bags of
peanuts _ $2 during the World Series _ from a corner stand near
Turner Field. She still sells plenty of peanuts, but she and other
vendors say T-shirt and other merchandise sales are slow and and
fans aren't as rowdy.
</P>
<P>
   _ MARTA bus driver Archie Rayford, who transports fans to Turner
Field, says that fans have been ``laid back.'' Only once in a while
have they worked up to a little polite cheering. And he hasn't seen
anybody _ kids or adults _ with tomahawks painted on their cheeks.
In the past, he said, ``It was unbelievable: Cheering,
tomahawk-chopping. It seemed like everybody had a tomahawk.''
</P>
<P>
   Butch Miller of Flowery Branch, Ga., seemed plenty stoked for a
World Series game over the weekend. He shepherded in his 9-year-old
son, Carey, and two friends, all garbed in appropriate Braves fan
attire. A friend offered to buy their tickets for $500 each, but
Miller and the kids decided it was more important to be at the game
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Miller, a car dealer, understands the drop-off in
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember Christmas when you were 5 years old? Were you
excited? Yeah. You remember Christmas when you were 25? Were you
still excited? No, but you still liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Says John Bevilaqua a sports-marketing consultant, ``The newness
has worn off.'' And besides, says Bevilaqua, metro Atlantans have
busy schedules and plenty of other pro and, particularly, college
teams to share their loyalties with.
</P>
<P>
   Bevilaqua also says the personalities on the Braves team don't
add a lot of extra excitement to the game, despite their obvious
skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team doesn't play with a lot of passion,'' he said. Other
than pitcher John Rocker, he said, ``There are no real rah-rah guys
on the field,'' and that has an impact on the emotion level of
fans.
</P>
<P>
   How does a city that pegs itself as the sports capital of the
world respond to suggestions that over-the-top fan support is
fading?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen it,'' says Gary Stokan, president of the
Atlanta Sports Council, an arm of the Metro Atlanta Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Stokan says the Braves have averaged more than 3 million tickets
sold annually since 1991, while the New York Yankees only managed
to go over the 3 million mark for the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now tabulate that for fan apathy,'' he said. ``There is no fan
apathy in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the contention that metro Atlanta is the sports capital
of the world: It is based on sports facilities and big-name events
held here. And Stokan says that what attracts the event organizers
who select sites are good transportation access, top facilities,
hotel accommodations, support volunteers and corporate backers.
</P>
<P>
   Fan fever doesn't make the priority list.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kempner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
