<HEADER>
A8141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-FLAMES-COX     10-25 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FLAMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old meets new: Flames, Thrashers create new ice age
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The city's great Flame-out is nearly 20 years old. But
the only NHL player to call Atlanta home for all eight seasons is
having difficulty feeling nostalgic about this evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice that they're back, but to be honest I just feel like
it's too late,'' former Atlanta/Calgary Flames goalie Daniel
Bouchard said.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard will be among those in attendance tonight when the old
Atlanta franchise returns to face the new one at Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should've never left here,'' he said. ``Atlanta was one
of the best hockey towns in the league. Everybody wanted to play
here and loved the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing in a nice arena,'' Bouchard said, ``and when
we moved to Calgary, we were playing in a much smaller building,
the Corral, because the new rink wasn't ready yet. I didn't feel
like we were in the NHL anymore. It felt like it was a step down
instead of a step up. That was the sad part.''
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard never embraced Alberta, but he didn't have a lot of
time. He played only 14 games for the Flames in their first season
in Calgary in 1980-81 before being shuttled to Quebec. He wasn't
there when the Flames reached the Stanley Cup finals in 1986 or won
it in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But Bouchard, who coaches the hockey program at Life College,
will be among the former Flames who will be recognized by the
Thrashers after the first period of tonight's game. At least six
players still living in Atlanta will be included in on-ice
ceremonies: Bouchard, Tom Lysiak, Eric Vail, Willi Plett, Tim
Ecclestone and Randy Manery.
</P>
<P>
   Former coach Bernie ``Boom Boom'' Geoffrion, who dropped the
ceremonial first puck at the regular-season opener against New
Jersey, might not attend, because of health reasons. Former owner
Tom Cousins is expected to be in attendance but not be introduced.
It was Cousins who, in need of cash in a sagging real-estate
market, sold the Flames in 1980 to Canadian Nelson Skalbania.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard through the year that the situation wasn't great
financially,'' said Calgary assistant coach Al MacNeil, the Flames'
head coach in their final season here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Mr. Cousins was making efforts to get some corporate
support,'' MacNeil said. ``But I remember late in the season when
Coca-Cola, which was one of the companies Mr. Cousins was talking
to, gave Emory University a hundred million dollars. When I saw
(that) the money went that way, I thought, `We're history.' It
didn't take a rocket scientist to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   MacNeil is one of the few remaining ``active'' links between the
Flames and Atlanta. Others who will be present tonight are
Thrashers equipment manager Bobby Stewart, who spent 26 years with
Atlanta/Calgary, and the Thrashers' director of team services
Michele Zarzaca, who worked in the Flames' marketing department.
</P>
<P>
   The game isn't the Flames' first return to Atlanta since the
move. In 1990, the team played two exhibition games against Boston
at the Omni. MacNeil said, ``I don't know if I'll have any real
strong feelings in the game because we'll be in a different
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Vail agreed that the earlier return ``was more emotional,'' but
he said is looking forward to tonight. He is among several former
Flames still living in Atlanta whom the Thrashers have used in
marketing ventures. As compensation, the team supplied four season
tickets this year for the ex-players to share.
</P>
<P>
   Vail, who scored an Atlanta franchise-high 174 goals, said he
enjoyed his short time in Calgary _ he was traded to Detroit after
little more than one season there _ but has vivid memories of the
final season in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a couple of months to go in the season, the rumors were
flying,'' he said. ``I remember when we were playing the Rangers in
the playoffs and between periods of one of the games, (a team
official) said, `You guys are one step away from going to Calgary.'
He said it trying to motivate us. My guess is it wouldn't have made
a difference. We were gone even if we had won the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
