<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKER-PRIZE-COETZEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J.M. COETZEE'S, `DISGRACE' WINS BOOKER PRIZE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ ``Disgrace,'' J.M. Coetzee's powerful novel about life
in post-apartheid South Africa, won the Booker Prize, Britain's
most important literary award, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Coetzee (pronounced cught-SEE-uh) is the first person in the
31-year history of the Booker, which is worth about $35,000, to win
it for a second time. The first time was in 1983, for ``The Life
and Times of Michael K.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a quiet year for a prize typically characterized by
vigorous arguing, sniping and second-guessing, both among the
five-member panel of judges and from members of London's
gossip-loving literary world. The list of six finalists was most
remarked on not for those who made it, but for those who were left
out _ which included Salman Rushdie's ``Ground Beneath Her Feet''
and Vikram Seth's ``An Equal Music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Disgrace'' tells the story of a 52-year-old college professor
_ Coetzee himself is professor of general literature at the
University of Cape Town _ who is accused of sexual harassment after
an affair with a student and seeks refuge on his daughter's farm.
</P>
<P>
   When she is the victim of a brutal attack, their disagreements
about what course of action to take force an examination of their
place in South Africa's changing world.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Kaufman, a member of Parliament and the chairman of the
judges' panel, said the novel was ``an allegory about what is
happening to the human race in the post-colonial era.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense this is a millennial book,'' he added, ``because it
takes us through the 20th century into a new century in which the
source of power is shifting away from Western Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The six-book short list included Anita Desai's ``Fasting,
Feasting,'' which examines the vast differences between life in
India and in the United States through the story of one Indian
family and which Kaufman said was the judges' second choice for the
prize.
</P>
<P>
   Another book nominated was Michael Frayn's ``Headlong,'' the
story of an academic's efforts to prove that a picture he spots in
a neighbor's house is a long-lost Bruegel.
</P>
<P>
   The list also included Ahdaf Soueif's ``Map of Love,'' about two
parallel love affairs between Westerners and Egyptians, one at the
turn of the century and one in the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Fathers,'' the first novel by the Scottish writer Andrew
O'Hagan, in which a grandson called to his grandfather's death bed
in Glasgow reviews both their lives, was another of the nominees.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth was ``The Blackwater Lightship,'' by Colm Toibin, in
which a young woman grapples with her uneasy relationship with her
mother and grandmother as her beloved brother dies of AIDS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
