<HEADER>
A8144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OIL-EARNINGS-NYT     10-25 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL COMPANIES POST BIG EARNINGS GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major oil companies said Monday that third-quarter earnings rose
substantially, with some more than doubling, largely because of the
increased price of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of all the companies, which had risen in recent months in
expectations of the earnings reports, declined Monday, some by
significant amounts, as investors took profits.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Atlantic Richfield Co., which showed a seven-fold rise
in earnings, saw its stock fall.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO fell $3.125, to close at $90.875. Exxon declined by
$2.8125, to close at $74.625. Chevron fell $3.75 to close at $90.
Texaco Inc. fell the least, by 87.5 cents to close at $62. All are
traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a lot of buying on the expectations and
selling on the news,'' said Tyler Dann, an oil analyst for Banc of
America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Wilson, an oil analyst for JP Morgan Securities, said there
was a lot of profit-taking after many of the stocks had risen by
large amounts. He said, ``People were thinking, `I made a lot of
money in this round. I think I'll take some off the table and lock
in some profits.'''
</P>
<P>
   Exxon's overall earnings totaled $1.5 billion, or 61 cents a
share, for the third quarter, up 7 percent compared to earnings of
$1.4 billion, or 58 cents a share, in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Its profits from exploration and production totaled $1 billion
for the third quarter, more than double the earnings of $485
million in the same quarter the year before.
</P>
<P>
   But in refining, profits were only $137 million in the quarter,
down sharply from the $581 million in the third quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lee R. Raymond, the chairman of Exxon, said that as crude oil
prices rose, the company could not raise prices on its refined
products fast enough to recover higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose to $33.1 billion in the third quarter, up 16 percent
from sales of $28.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Mobil Corp., which Exxon is in the process of acquiring, saw
its earnings rise to $705 million, or 87 cents a share, up 42
percent from earnings of $497 million, or 61 cents a share, from
the third quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 20 percent to $16.4 billion from $13.6 billion the
year before.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco said Monday that its earnings more than doubled to $453
million, or 83 cents a share, up from $208 million, or 37 cents a
share, the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Sales were up 26 percent, rising to $9.68 billion from $7.7
billion the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Peter I. Bijur, the chairman and chief executive of Texaco, said
cutbacks by a coalition of oil producers and strong global
economies which kept up demand were the major reasons for higher
profits.
</P>
<P>
   He warned, however, that ``as we've seen in recent weeks prices
remain volatile.'' The price of crude oil fell from $24 last month
to the $22 range, although they have recently rebounded. The drop
was caused by speculation that the oil cartel may increase
production, although its leaders have said that they had no plans
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron also reported a sharp rise of 82 percent in its
earnings. Profits in the third quarter totaled $702 million, or
$1.07 a share, up from $386 million, or 59 cents a share, in the
third quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose by 33 percent to $10.2 billion from $7.68 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Derr, the chairman and chief executive of Chevron said,
however, that the sharp rise in crude prices ``squeezed margins in
our refining.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that profits from refining totalled $97 million or about
half of the $188 million earned in the third quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Derr said that continued cost-cutting had also helped profits.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company would raise the number of people it will cut
by the middle of next year by 400, to 3,100.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpest rise in earnings came from Atlantic Richfield,
which reported that third-quarter earnings increased sevenfold.
</P>
<P>
   Profits for the third quarter totalled $511 million, or $1.55 a
share, compared to $73 million, or 22 cents a share, in the third
quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose by 26 percent to $3.54 billion from $2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO has been acquired by BP Amoco PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Some executives gave credit for the sharp rise in the price of
crude oil to a coalition of oil producing nations that includes
Mexico, Norway and the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, which cut back production last March by about 5 million
barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts, combined with a recovery in the Asian economies, more
than doubled the price of crude oil since early last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter the price of crude oil averaged $21.71 a
barrel compared with $14.15 a year before in trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange. Some analysts have predicted that the
price of crude oil could rise to close to $30 a barrel in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
