<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SIGNS ONE SPENDING BILL BUT VETOES ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton signed into law a $268-billion
spending bill for the Pentagon on Monday, avoiding the risk of a
crippling split among Democrats at the very moment that the parties
are hurtling toward the finale of their budget showdown. At the
same time, he vetoed a separate spending bill, assailing
Republicans for making ``wrong choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks about the Pentagon bill were decidedly mixed.
He criticized it for budgetary gimmicks and pork barrel projects.
But he said he had concluded that it contained crucial elements,
such as a pay raise for the military, adding: ``I cannot allow our
national security needs to be held hostage to this budget battle.''
</P>
<P>
   With the budget fight entering a critical week, Clinton struck a
particularly combative tone over plans by the Republican leaders of
Congress to include an across-the-board spending cut of up to 1.4
percent in the year's final spending bill. The move is a last
effort by Republicans to put in place a budget that does not touch
Social Security reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The president charged that the across-the-board cut would lead
to layoffs in the military, and harm education and environmental
programs. ``I will not allow Congress to raise its own pay and fund
its pork barrel projects and still make devastating cuts in
everything from education to child nutrition to the FBI,'' he said
in announcing that he had signed the Pentagon bill but vetoed a
measure funding the Commerce, State, and Justice Departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not sign any budget that puts special interests above
the national interest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by signing the Pentagon measure, Clinton shied away from
escalating the confrontation over the budget and instead narrowed
the fight to a manageable set of issues: the shape of education
programs, police hiring, the environment and foreign aid. His
balancing act set the framework for the endgame of the year's
budget struggle, a fight whose outcome both parties believe is
likely to significantly influence the course of the congressional
elections in 2000, particularly in the narrowly divided House.
</P>
<P>
   The final showdown could come as early as this week, because
legislation expires on Friday that has temporarily kept the
government running through the first weeks of the 2000 federal
fiscal year that began Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders praised Clinton and tried to set him
apart from the House Democrats led by Rep. Dick Gephardt, whom they
accused of fomenting partisan confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has rejected the gridlock strategy of Dick
Gephardt,''' said Rep. Tom DeLay, the House majority whip from
Texas. Rep. Dick Armey, the House majority leader who is also from
Texas, said he thought the president's action would make it ''that
much easier'' to negotiate a compromise on the budget.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the president's decision to sign the Pentagon bill gave
the Republicans something they had wanted: a fight over a limited
number of bills which scaled back the possibility that Clinton can
score big wins in negotiations over an omnibus spending package as
has happened in his past confrontations with the Republicans. It
takes 13 annual spending bills to put the budget in place. The
president and Republicans are now struggling over five of the
bills.
</P>
<P>
   For the White House, the decision to sign the Pentagon bill was
a balancing act. Some Democrats believe that the longer a budget
stalemate goes on the better it is for them politically, bringing
back memories of the government shutdown of 1995 that proved
devastating to the Republicans. But the Pentagon measure was
popular and had originally passed the House by the overwhelming
vote of 372-55.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt had pledged to fight vigorously to deliver the 146
Democratic votes needed to sustain a veto. But other senior
Democrats had expressed reservations about a veto that could make
them vulnerable to attack on national security and were threatening
to vote with the Republicans against a veto.
</P>
<P>
   Several White House aides and Democrats familiar with White
House budget strategy said Clinton had decided he did not want the
Republicans to divert the budget fight to national security but
instead wanted to keep the struggle on grounds which Democrats are
more comfortable with, such as education, police and the
environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
