<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8148 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-BANK-MERGER-BOS &LR;      10-25 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BANK-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN UNION, SOMETHING OLD AND SOMETHING NEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the end, the Boston banker put his wing-tipped foot down in
the name of history and heritage. One could not, Charles Gifford
argued, erase every symbol of the nation's oldest bank, whose
venerable customers once included John Hancock and Paul Revere.
</P>
<P>
   In a barometer of changing times, the new company created out of
the megamerger of Fleet Financial Group and BankBoston will
popularly be known as ``Fleet.'' But in a nod to tradition, some
less visible parts of the new bank will be called FleetBoston
Financial _ a last-minute concession to Gifford, the old BankBoston
chief who holds the number-two position in the new company.
</P>
<P>
   In another compromise, Fleet's new logo is an abstract, stylized
version of a winged eagle, the old BankBoston icon. The symbol
replaces Fleet's three sails, which prominent affordable housing
activist Bruce Marks had sought to tarnish in recent years by
comparing to shark fins.
</P>
<P>
   The symbolic changes, which company executives unveiled Monday
in a ceremony with soccer star Mia Hamm and Red Sox celebrity
short-stop Nomar Garciaparra, are the result of an emotional
tug-of-war between Gifford and Terrence Murray, the hard-driving
Fleet chief executive who acquired his crosstown rival for $16
billion earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as three weeks ago, Murray had insisted that the
entire company, now the nation's eighth-largest bank, bear the
Fleet name alone and retain the three sails, insiders familiar with
the situation said Monday. ``I realize there's a great deal of
nostalgia and thinking back to the past,'' Murray said Monday, as
he and Gifford hoisted a corporate flag outside BankBoston.
``However, the '90s is a period of enormous change.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gifford dug in his heels and forced his new boss to make
some concessions. ``Boston is part of me,'' Gifford said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Gifford's fierce lobbying in recent weeks, the
name of the holding company uniting various parts of the bank will
be FleetBoston Financial. That is not a name consumers will
encounter much, unless they read the company's annual reports or
follow Wall Street research.
</P>
<P>
   And the logo accompanying the holding company name will bear a
1784, the year the Massachusetts Bank, which eventually became
BankBoston, was founded to finance Yankee merchant trade with
China. Fleet's new ticker symbol on the New York Stock Exchange is
FBT.
</P>
<P>
   In a rapidly consolidating industry, banks change names all the
time. And mergers that combine two companies with different
philosophies and practices involve painful decisions and personal
sacrifices. Murray, a Woonsocket, R.I., factory worker's son and a
veteran of more than 50 deals, has had to craft ways to work with
Gifford, a Rhode Island banker's scion who grew up in privileged
circles. Gifford is the new Fleet's president and chief operating
officer, and is active in community affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But research showed the name `Boston' did not travel well
outside Massachusetts, where Fleet has many branches. ``We wanted
geographic freedom,'' said Anne Finucane, who heads Fleet's
corporate marketing and communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fleet'' is the name people and businesses will see when they
look at the new bank, which has eight million household customers
across New England and the Northeast. Branches, automated teller
machines, checks, stationery, business cards, billboards at Fenway
Park, and advertisements on television, in newspapers, and
elsewhere will all bear the Fleet name.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at branches and ATMS the name ``Fleet'' stands against a
green backdrop _ another small concession to Gifford. The old Fleet
used only blue, not green.
</P>
<P>
   The new Fleet will keep the BankBoston name in Latin America,
where BankBoston opened in 1917 to finance the New England wool
trade and is a widely recognized brand. BankBoston's investment
bank, BancBoston Robertson Stephens, will drop its first name.
Other units, including Fleet's Quick &AMP; Reilly stock brokerage, will
retain their names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that the deliberations we went through didn't
involve some give and take,'' said Gifford, who said his
relationship with Murray had strengthened as a result of the
process. Fleet's brand name, Gifford admitted, was ``much better
known'' _ a point he said was hammered home during a recent visit
to Yankee stadium, where Fleet is a big advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad has had to make many difficult decisions in the past six
months,'' said Murray, adding that ``every day my respect and
admiration for Chad has grown. Choosing a brand and a logo is
certainly a test of our partnership.'' The two men were speaking to
company executives before the flag-raising ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said Fleet, which has $175 billion in assets, will
produce $3 billion in excess capital, or money available for
investments, stock buybacks, and shareholder dividends, over the
next 18 to 24 months. He said Fleet was unlikely to do acquisitions
``of any significance'' in the next nine months, but did not rule
out smaller nonbank acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Murray also said the imminent dismantling of Depression-era laws
separating banks, insurers, and brokerages would create
opportunities. ``I think this has major potential for our new
company,'' he said. ``We're going to continue to build this into
one of the premier financial services companies in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who temporarily called his company Fleet/Norwest after
one major acquisition but soon dropped the second name, vowed not
to erase the word Boston from the holding company as long as he
heads it. Murray is scheduled to retire at the end of 2001, when
Gifford is due to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's new logo confused some observers. When showed the symbol
by a reporter, Carol O'Grady, a 55-year-old insurance clerk, asked
``What is that _ two half moons?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
