<SLUG> BC-BMW-ROLLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW TO RAISE STAKE IN ROLLS-ROYCE , ITS AEROSPACE PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ BMW will raise its stake in Rolls-Royce PLC to 10
percent and give the British aerospace concern control of a joint
venture that builds plane engines, the companies said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   BMW, which now owns 2 percent of Rolls-Royce, said it would buy
33.3 million new Rolls-Royce shares and 90 million existing shares
under the deal. The arrangement, which contributed to a nearly 19
percent surge in Rolls-Royce stock Monday, will make BMW, Germany's
No. 3 automaker, the biggest industrial shareholder in Rolls-Royce,
with a stake worth about $545 million.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Reitman, an auto industry analyst with Merrill Lynch,
said the maneuver would enable BMW to avoid probable development
costs in the money-losing airplane engine venture and benefit from
the overall profitability of Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has never looked kindly at BMW's foray into
airplane technology,'' he said. ``What the market will welcome in
this is that it re-focuses BMW on its core activities.''
</P>
<P>
   BMW's worries about the profitability of its investments have
been deepening with stubborn losses at its Rover auto subsidiary in
England. The German company says it will make Rover profitable by
2002 _ the same year as BMW-Rolls-Royce Aerospace, the joint
airplane engine venture, is anticipating a profit. ``There was
probably less scrutiny of the losses at BMW-Rolls-Royce when that
was the only problem area,'' Reitman said. ``Now that there are big
problems at Rover, it's a different situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture was formed in 1990 to develop the BR700
engines used in airplanes including the Gulfstream V corporate jet,
the Bombardier Express, the Boeing 717 and the Nimrod 2000, a
maritime reconnaissance plane built by British Aerospace PLC. The
company delivered around 100 engines last year and forecasts an
increase to 210 next year and 250 in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal announced Monday, BMW will relinquish its 50.5
percent stake in the joint company, which will be run as a German
subsidiary of Rolls-Royce GmbH, with its headquarters near Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Rolls-Royce is to assume the entire debt of the joint venture,
estimated by BMW at $546 million _ roughly the same as the value of
its new stake in Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement raised speculation that BMW might bid for
Rolls-Royce, but both sides denied this.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have expressly said they see no reason to increase the
stake,'' John Rose, the chief executive of Rolls-Royce, told
reporters. And, he said, BMW had not asked for representation on
the Rolls-Royce management board.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was the second remolding of the Rolls-Royce corporate
profile in a matter of weeks. In September, Rolls-Royce agreed to
buy Vickers PLC for $933 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rolls-Royce PLC is not directly related to Rolls-Royce Motor
Cars Ltd., the maker of luxury automobiles that was bought by
Volkswagen AG of Germany last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8154 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZIL-EMBRAER-NYT &LR;      10-25 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-EMBRAER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH CONSORTIUM BUYS STAKE IN EMBRAER, BRAZILIAN AIRCRAFT MAKER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Fla.)   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ A French aerospace consortium agreed Monday
to acquire a stake in Empresa Brasileira de Aeronautica SA, a
rapidly growing aircraft maker that is one of corporate Latin
America's biggest success stories.
</P>
<P>
   A group composed of Dassault Aviation, Thomson CSF,
Aerospatiale-Matra and Snecma will pay about $209 million for 20
percent of the voting shares in Embraer, as the Brazilian company
is known. With the deal, the French companies could gain an
advantage in bids to renovate Brazil's fleet of fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is win-win for both sides,'' said David Wheeler, a Bear,
Stearns managing director here. ``Embraer gets access to strong
technological and commercial networks and the French, especially
Dassault, get stronger footing in Latin America's defense market,
with the potential for $8 billion in contracts in Brazil alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Embraer's alliance with the French companies is the latest
chapter in a turnaround that has resulted in one of Latin America's
highest-flying companies, and one of its hottest stocks, with
shares soaring 335 percent in dollar terms this year. The French
group will pay a 25 percent premium over the closing price last
week of 6.8 reais, or $3.45.
</P>
<P>
   Since its privatization in 1994, Embraer, which was created by
the Brazilian military 30 years ago in a rush to catch up with the
aerospace prowess of the rich industrial nations, has been
transformed from a money-losing behemoth. Its competitive strength
has shaken the largest producers of commercial jets _ Boeing,
Airbus Industrie and Bombardier of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Embraer's success reflects a prescient bet on a growing
demand for regional jet aircraft able to shuttle 100 passengers or
so on short flights.
</P>
<P>
   The market for regional jets has become the fastest-growing part
of the commercial aircraft industry, reflecting the efforts by
small feeder airlines to replace older planes with jets, which most
passengers prefer. The increase of commerce in the 1990s in
developing nations has also contributed to the demand for small
jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about 1,000 Brazilian companies doing business in
Argentina today, compared with a couple of hundred a few years
ago,'' said Robert Booth, a Florida-based Latin American aviation
consultant. ``Imagine the impact that has on the need to transport
all those businessmen around.''
</P>
<P>
   After amassing contracts in the United States, Latin America and
Europe, Embraer has a backlog of orders worth about $18 billion.
The company is now seeking to expand its business in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The deal announced Monday suggests that the company is
readjusting to focus more on the armaments market. Now, about 8
percent of Embraer's sales come from military orders, such as the
Brazilian government's contract for radar-equipped jets to help
combat drug-running in the Amazon River basin. Within a few years,
as much as 30 percent of its sales could come from armaments
business, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have 15 air forces around the world flying our
planes,'' said Mauricio Botelho, president of Embraer. ``Of course,
we want to expand that number. And of course, since we're linking
up with the makers of supersonic fighter jets, we want to help our
partners win contracts on our home turf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-STUDIO-INTERNET-NYT &LR;      10-25 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDIO-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMWORKS AND IMAGINE JOIN TO CREATE A WEB SITE OF DIGITAL
ENTERTAINMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ In what its principals say is a first glimmer of the
rapidly approaching digital entertainment world, executives at
Dreamworks SKG and Imagine Entertainment said Monday they would
join to create a new Internet entertainment company and Web site
offering short films, streaming video, live events, games,
performance art, continuing series, ``nonlinear interactive
features'' and whatever else they can think of.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks, a ministudio formed by Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey
Katzenberg and David Geffen, announced the partnership with
Imagine, a film and television production company headed by Ron
Howard and Brian Grazer, and vowed that the new company, to be
called POP.com, would be operating by early spring. The company is
to have offices in New York and Los Angeles, and the announcement
of its first chief executive will be made shortly, Spielberg said.
</P>
<P>
   POP.com is being financed by Vulcan Ventures, the investment
vehicle of Paul G. Allen, the Microsoft co-founder who is already a
major Dreamworks investor. Vulcan has committed $50 million for the
initial phase of the project, Katzenberg said. For that, Vulcan
will get 50 percent of the company; Dreamworks and Imagine will
split the other half.
</P>
<P>
   When it goes online, POP.com is to offer a daily menu of
interactive shorts it calls ``pops,'' most running between 30
seconds and six minutes. The emphasis will be on comedy, but no
genres will be ignored, Spielberg said, and each ``pop'' will come
with its own chat room and instant messaging capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be so seductive and ultimately addictive that
people don't click out after one click,'' Grazer said.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg and Howard, both film directors, said they intended to
contribute their own ``pops'' to the site, though they added that
initially much of their work would be to encourage others to get
involved and to nurture the work of fledgling digital artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an emerging and evolving new format,'' Katzenberg
said. ``The analogy I keep coming back to is 25 years ago when you
had this wonderful style called music and someone said, let's turn
it into an audio and video experience, and out of that was born
MTV. We believe we are at that time and moment now for the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement is indicative of the scurrying in
Hollywood in recent months to find ways to understand and
capitalize on the sweeping technological advancements in online and
digital filmmaking and utilize it to shape the entertainment world
of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Howard said, they want to have some fun. ``This is kind of
free-wheeling, less about narrative drive and all the discipline we
have to live with when we make a movie and more about the
exploration of interesting new ideas,'' he said. ``I think we're
going to able to entice a lot of really talented people to do some
work with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``pops'' presented on the site might also be the seeds of
other, larger projects, from video games to television series to
feature films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly see this as like a large, fertile field,''
Spielberg said. ``You can harvest all sorts of spin-offs, just from
whatever germinates. It could be a book, a piece of music, a movie,
who can say?''
</P>
<P>
   As word of the venture began to make the rounds in Hollywood and
in the investment community, most executives and analysts said they
wanted to reserve judgment until they could see exactly what was
planned, and how it might differ from other, perhaps smaller
Internet sites offering digital films.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do they promote it?'' asked one entertainment analyst.
``It's very nice to digitize films and put them on the Internet,
but where is the value in it for investors? I guess my initial
reaction is, `yeah, so?'''
</P>
<P>
   Digital moviemaking _ sometimes called microcinema _ is a
relatively small but growing movement of small-scale filmmakers
utilizing the cheaper and rapidly evolving digital technology to
make short films and exhibit them on the Internet. The October
issue of Wired magazine listed more than a dozen Internet sites
offering short digital films, among them Atomfilms _ which exhibits
shorts that are festival favorites or Academy Awards nominees and
counts as its partners the HBO and Warner Bros. Online units of
Time Warner _ and the Bit Screen, which offers short first-run
films and episodic series of 10 minutes or less.
</P>
<P>
   POP.com will be different, its founders say, in the scope of its
ambitions, the people associated with it and the strategies it will
use to turn a profit. They intend it as a money-making enterprise.
``We definitely see this as an advertiser and sponsor-supported
business,'' Katzenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks, POP.com plans to talk with Madison Avenue
executives about ideas for advertising on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the same way that we have to really discover these new
forms, Madison Avenue is going to have to reinvent the way it
advertises to this kind of viewer,'' Katzenberg said. ``Each step
that is being taken in this world today is a first step. All of us,
individually and collectively, are on as big a learning curve as
you can be on. There are no rules, and there is no proven formula
for success in this as yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg said they did not intend to corner the market in
digital filmmaking or to muscle out weaker competitors. ``I think
there will be many stimulating sites in the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will still be movies, and there will still be TV,''
Grazer added. ``We're not thinking we're changing the world. We're
just trying to be a part of the sensibility of this new medium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
