<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-ADS-COX     10-25 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As Bush debuts campaign ads, Forbes ready to counterBy Ken
Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Aware that his name is better-known than his
record, Texas Governor George W. Bush today launches a TV ad
campaign aimed at filling in the blanks before his opponents try to
do it for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire campaign is designed not only to communicate the
governor's positive message but it also anticipates some of the
attacks that have already begun in the media,'' said Mark McKinnon,
Bush's media consultant.
</P>
<P>
   On TV today in Iowa and New Hampshire, key early states in the
race for the GOP presidential nomination, are four ads in which
Bush says he can do for the nation what he's done for Texas.
Included is a statement of philosophy that could be taken as a hint
of a promise to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that once top priorities have been funded we should
pass money back to the taxpayers,'' he says on an ad. ``That's what
I've done in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   In a low-key, but intentional, way, one of the ads seeks to
shore up a flank on which Bush expects to be targeted in upcoming
ads from GOP foe Steve Forbes, a wealthy publisher who has vowed to
spend whatever it takes to get his message across.
</P>
<P>
   That message includes an attempt to portray Bush as a
tax-and-spender unworthy of the conservative label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they do things big down in Texas,'' Forbes said this
month. ``But it does seem curious that Governor Bush makes
big-spending Bill Clinton look like a fiscal conservative. Under
President Clinton, federal spending has increased 21 percent. Under
Governor Bush, Texas spending has increased by 36 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the last budget approved before Bush took office, state
spending totalled $35.8 million. Spending for the fiscal year that
begins next September will top $48.6 million, a 36 percent hike.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has noted that the increase includes more federal funds for
some programs, as well as an initial infusion of money from the
settlement of the lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new Bush ads portrays him as a governor who has held
the line on spending increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``As governor, he signed the two biggest tax cuts in Texas
history,'' says an announcer. ``He reduced the growth of state
government spending to the lowest in 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said that claim is based on
year-to-year budget increases since Bush took office. Forbes
adviser Greg Mueller said Monday that Forbes, in coming weeks, will
run ads challenging Bush's handling of taxpayers' money.
   ``We believe in an honest, civil, respectful debate on the
issues,'' said Mueller.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, that included an aggressive ad campaign that
left Bob Dole as damaged goods by the time Forbes was eliminated
from the race for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bush's) record on taxes and spending and education are
certainly areas deserving of an engagement on the issues,'' Mueller
said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Briefing papers used within the Forbes campaign discuss Bush's
``bushels of wasteful spending'' in ``traditionally wasteful and
intrusive arms of government.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush, in one ad, says he cut taxes, the Forbes campaign
says he does not point out that due to other economic pressures,
including increasing property values, many Texans did not benefit.
Some are paying higher tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has noted that Bush unsuccessfully pushed a package of
tax increases in 1997 as part of plan to cut property taxes. His
proposal failed, and lawmakers settled on an alternative that had
far less impact than Bush wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Forbes are primed for a high-dollar airwaves war. Bush
has broken records by raising more than $57 million in seven
months. Forbes, heir to a publishing empire, has already spent more
than $16 million of his own money and there's more where that came
from.
</P>
<P>
   Both are declining federal matching funds, a decision that also
frees them from state-by-state spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials would not detail the cost of the ad buy,
but they termed it a ``mid-sized one'' and said average viewers in
those states would see the ads three to five times per week.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the air is a 60-second Spanish radio ad running in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spotlight is on Iowa,'' the ad says. ``And for the first
time it's shining on the Latino community.''
</P>
<P>
   In the TV ads, Bush, packaged as ``A fresh start for America,''
talks about setting a new political tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to run a campaign that is hopeful and optimistic and
very positive,'' Bush tells viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush ads brought protest from the Texas Democratic Party,
which claim they ``exaggerate a lackluster record.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Democratic National Committee spokesman Rick Hess
declared the ads substance-free, and filled with ``platitude after
platitude full of warm and fuzzy words.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Bush launches what could become the most massive ad
buy in presidential history at a time when he is declining to
debate his opponents until Dec. 2 because he said voters are not
paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   It's a discrepancy that did not go unnoticed Monday in the John
McCain campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like the ads would be a waste of money if nobody is
paying attention,'' said McCain spokesman Howard Opinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look like good ads,'' Opinsky added. ``And I'm hopeful
the governor will come up and talk about them in person in New
Hampshire some time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kherman(AT)(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
