<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8159 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUCHANAN-REFORM-ART-(     10-25 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-REFORM-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIERY BUCHANAN BOLTS GOP TO SEEK REFORM NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also BUCHANAN-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 9 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALLS CHURCH, Va. _ Pat Buchanan put aside a lifetime of
Republican fervor Monday and shifted his lagging presidential quest
to a run for the Reform Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vaunted two-party system is a snare and a delusion and a
fraud upon the nation,'' Buchanan told a crowd of cheering
supporters as he bolted the GOP, showing his fiery instinct for
insurgency. ``Our two parties have become nothing but two wings on
the same bird of prey.''
</P>
<P>
   As visceral on the stump as ever, Buchanan, his campaign for the
Republican nomination frozen in the single-digit doldrums,
lambasted the two major parties as havens for big-money donors and
``hollow'' candidates who have ``rigged the game'' against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We choose not to play our assigned walk-on role in their sham
election,'' Buchanan declared to the delight of an exuberantly
partisan crowd that included Reform Party officials and loyalists
from his three failed bids for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the Reform Party offers the hope of a real debate and a
real choice of destinies,'' he insisted in resorting to the
alternative ticket created by Ross Perot as a lever of populist
power in the 1992 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre contest for the 2000 nomination taking shape
between Reform Party factions, Donald Trump, the real estate
millionaire, is quitting the Republican Party and threatening to
challenge Buchanan, denouncing him as a ``Hitler lover.'' Minnesota
Gov. Jesse Ventura, the party's major elected figure, is looking
with open disfavor on Buchanan's party-switching gambit. And while
Perot is proclaiming neutrality in any rivalry, even the
Buchananites agree Perot remains a quixotic figure.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Buchanan confirmed his third-party course, he was
attacked by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican
front-runner who is considered the candidate most likely to lose
votes in November should Buchanan attract serious numbers of
conservative voters. Insisting that Buchanan left the GOP for no
reason other than a failed candidacy, Bush scored Buchanan's
isolationist views, in particular his controversial thesis that
Hitler initially had presented no serious threat to the United
States in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat sees an America that should have stayed home while Hitler
overran Europe and perpetrated the Holocaust,'' Bush contended in a
statement expressing confidence that most conservative Republicans
would not follow Buchanan. In the weeks leading up to Buchanan's
announcement, Bush had refrained from harsh criticism of him in the
hope of keeping him in the party.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan hardly apologized for his views as he rued the
decline of ``all the great empires of Europe'' and the rise of ``a
superstate in Europe that pays homage to the great god, Mammon''
and, he said, ties up American soldiers in a ``Godless new world
order.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They call us isolationists, and that's one of the nicest
things they call us,'' he declared, drawing laughter from the crowd
at the Doubletree Hotel here in the western Washington suburbs,
miles from what Buchanan termed ``the Beltway elites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if they mean I intend to isolate America from all the
bloody, territorial, tribal and ethnic wars of the 21st century, I
plead guilty!'' he boomed, drawing the crowd to its feet in a wave
of applause and cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Once more offering himself as the unabashed candidate of
America-first policies, Buchanan vowed to ``rescue our lady,
America'' from what he termed ``the cultural and moral pit into
which she has fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a timeout on legal immigration to ease the downward
pressure on workers' wages,'' he maintained, ``and to defeat the
forces of separatism that threaten us and nations all over the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   With fresh campaign logos and a new red, white and blue Internet
site (www.buchananreform.com), the 60-year-old politician sought to
retool his candidacy with a speech laced with the sorts of red-meat
applause lines that first brought him success as a speechwriter for
President Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roared as he denounced President Clinton as ``our own
Elmer Gantry, whose desecration of the temples of our civilization
and personal misconduct disqualify him'' as the nation's leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Buchananites roared again as he declared, ``The appeasement
of Beijing is a bipartisan disgrace!''
</P>
<P>
   And they stood and cheered as he bitterly denounced the Supreme
Court and vowed to ``herd the justices back into the narrow
stalls'' of constitutionalism. ``What is a self-governing people
doing meekly waiting each week for nine jurists to tell us how we
may live and how we should govern ourselves?'' he demanded, playing
to the Reformists' libertarian instincts even as he denounced the
legalization of abortion in ``that abomination they call Roe vs.
Wade.''
</P>
<P>
   Wielding a pallette filled with shades of national sovereignty,
Buchanan attacked employment quotas as un-American, declaring:
``The backsliding toward hyphenated Americanism must end.'' In
short order, he attacked the United Nations, global economic
treaties and ``IMF bailouts of deadbeat dictators.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In abandoning a Republican primary contest dominated solidly so
far by Bush, Buchanan set a course in which he must now fight state
by state within the evolving Reform Party factionalism to win
enough support for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get on 30 ballots,'' said Bay Buchanan,
Buchanan's sister and chief strategist. She noted that the campaign
already had hired Matt Sawyer, an election-law specialist who
helped Perot navigate the dense thicket of widely varying state
election laws in creating the party.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the 30 states that Ms. Buchanan is targeting, the Reform
Party is already established in 20 states where the Buchanan camp
is counting on help from such Reform Party veterans as Pat Choate,
Perot's confidante and former vice presidential running mate. He
has been openly piloting Buchanan`s veer toward the Reform ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Choate conceded that Buchanan might have a problem in the
opposition to his candidacy expressed by Ventura, who is
encouraging talk of a Trump candidacy. ``It's not helpful, but it
will not keep him from getting the nomination,'' Choate said of
Buchanan's chances, estimating that the enthusiastic crowd of more
than 300 people here included a majority of the party's current
state chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have charged that money, not principle, prompted the
party switch by Buchanan. The Reform Party nominee will be entitled
to $12.6 million in federal campaign funds. But Bay Buchanan denied
that this was at the root of the Reform venture, while Buchanan
insisted that disgust drove him from the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party has been good to me,'' he told the crowd.
``And I have tried to be loyal to it. But as John F. Kennedy said,
`Sometimes party loyalty asks too much.' And today, it asks too
much of us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Expressing anguish at quitting his lifelong party, Buchanan
nonetheless beamed in summoning his followers to a new course,
using his old imagery of an assault on the castle of the
establishment. ``You don't know this peasant army,'' he said,
grinning. ``We have not yet begun to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, ever a history buff, noted that this was St. Crispin's
Day _ a reference to King Henry V's defeat of the superior forces
of France in the battle of Agincourt on this day in 1415. ``Let's
make a little history,'' he said, looking eager as he took up a
different battle flag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f       10-25 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOPEZ-BASQUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER GM AND VW EXECUTIVE WANTS A LOPEZ IN EVERY GARAGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Spain, Brazil, Germany)   By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMOREBIETA, Spain _ Jose Ignacio Lopez de Arriortua has long
dreamed of building a car factory here in his Basque hometown. But
that dream caused him, by his own reckoning, to commit the biggest
mistake of his life.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake, he said, was defecting in 1993 from the executive
suite at General Motors, which declined to build the advanced,
cost-efficient plant he envisioned, and joining Volkswagen, which
he said promised to build it but never did.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had known that, I wouldn't have changed. It was my
error,'' said Lopez, 58, the one-time purchasing star under John F.
Smith Jr., GM's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Even after all he has been through, Lopez clings to his dream _
although it means performing the seemingly impossible feat of
producing his own car from scratch, independent of any auto giant.
</P>
<P>
   While at GM and VW, Lopez said his vision was a new system to
build the cars. But now, he has helped design them, too, entering a
tricky field, one in which daring entrepreneurs like John Z.
DeLorean and Preston Tucker had their own problems getting their
ideas to market. DeLorean's sports-car company ended in bankruptcy,
a trial for drug-dealing that ended with DeLorean's acquittal, and
a flurry of lawsuits nearly two decades ago. Tucker managed to
build only a handful of his ``cars of the future'' in the late
1940s before his enterprise crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   As for Lopez, GM accused him, after his defection, of passing
trade secrets to VW, including plans for an innovative factory
called ``Plant X.'' VW settled that dispute in 1997 _ the year
after Lopez had moved on yet again _ by paying GM $100 million and
agreeing to buy $1 billion in GM auto parts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, a tumultuous year for Lopez, a German court dropped
criminal charges of corporate spying against him, while fining him
$230,000, and he also survived a car crash in Spain that left him
in a coma for 10 days and hospitalized for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Lopez never relinquished the vision of the car
factory. He spent $3.7 million on four prototype cars and locked
them in a subbasement in a Bilbao bank, 12 miles from his hometown.
Last month, he presented a plan for the $554 million factory to 200
potential partners and said it could open by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But in a rare departure from the vaunted can-do stance that
earned him, in his days as a cost-cutting executive, the nickname
``Superlopez,'' he also admits that the factory may never be built.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't go well,'' Lopez said, after driving by 260
acres of publicly owned, industrial-zoned land where he would like
to put the factory, ``at least you've tried, with all of your
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   But generally, Lopez has been optimistic. He said that in the
weeks since he approached investors, 200 firms have expressed
interest. He plans, by mid-November, to select his target of 52
auto parts suppliers, which would be minority partners in the
factory and jointly assemble the car.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some surprises, like the one from the Vizcaya
provincial government, owner of the large industrial plot in
Amorebieta. On Sept. 29, hours after Lopez's pitch to investors, it
issued a statement saying that no one had asked it to authorize the
car factory or participate as a shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez had been counting on support from provincial officials,
although he said four other local governments in Spain had offered
to take his factory. But in one that he named, the southern town of
El Puerto de Santa Maria, an official said there had been no talk
about building the factory locally when Lopez visited last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going to do it in the Basque region, not here,'' said
Deputy Mayor Pedro Pablo Lamadrid.
</P>
<P>
   The factory would supposedly produce 300,000 cars annually using
cost-cutting innovations like a modular system to assemble car
sections and a work force of 5,900, drawn mainly from suppliers.
Only 100 workers would be from Lopez's supervising firm, which
would have a 52 percent stake in the venture.
</P>
<P>
   Similar techniques are used at a VW truck factory in Resende,
Brazil, that opened in 1996 under Lopez. He said his car factory
would improve the cost-cutting concept, which unions oppose on the
grounds that it outsources jobs.
</P>
<P>
   One proponent is Karel Bos, 71, chairman of the Bosal Group, a
Belgian-based manufacturer of auto exhaust systems that supplies
GM., VW and other big companies. He said that Bosal, with annual
sales of 610 million euros ($660 million), could account for three
of the 52 suppliers being sought.
</P>
<P>
   `` Lopez is a visionary person who has proven he can translate
his vision to reality,'' Bos said. ``He's done marvelous things at
VW and GM. We want to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts question if the highly competitive European
market wants another car, even if Lopez can deliver his vehicles
with sticker prices of $9,600 to $16,000 _ about a third less, he
said, than equivalent Audis or Volkswagens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overproduction in the European market is legendary,'' said
David Healy, an auto analyst at Burnham Securities. ``It would be
tough breaking into this market as a small producer with 300,000
cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez's brand would be called Loar, a word that combines the
first two letters of his last names and also means ``laud'' in
Spanish. The prototypes permit a third person in the front seat
because the gear-shift box and emergency brake have been removed
from the front-center position. Each of the four models is named
for a Roman Catholic saint important in Lopez's life.
</P>
<P>
   The Our Lady of Carmen model, he said, is similar to an Audi A3
or VW Golf and is named for the patron saint of his hometown of
Amorebieta, reflecting his deep attachment to this medieval
village, in the green Basque hills, with 16,000 residents and 15
percent unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez crosses Amorebieta daily in his chauffeur-driven Audi A8
on the way to his consulting firm, Lopez de Arriortua &AMP; Asociados
SA. The company started in 1996 and has grown to 50 employees in
Europe and Brazil and annual revenues of $6.4 million. It just
moved to larger quarters in the town of Derio, near Bilbao.
</P>
<P>
   He said he also spoke frequently at seminars and donated the
fees to his hometown's Convent of the Carmelite Fathers of Larrea,
where he was married. He plans to build homes adjacent to the
convent for each of his three adult daughters and another for
himself and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, still a tall figure with a direct gaze, has put on weight
since his high-powered stint with the two big auto makers. He
maintains that he never took trade secrets from GM and that ``Plant
X'' was his idea.
</P>
<P>
   He is intrigued by the question, which he raised in front of
eight employees of his consulting firm, of what he would do if GM
and VW suddenly came to him with job offers, a throwback to March
1993 when he chose the offer from Ferdinand Piech, chairman of the
VW management board.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Lopez said, it would be GM.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if neither one calls, it doesn't matter,'' he added. ``I
have my family here, and I'm happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
