<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SIGNS $268 BILLION DEFENSE BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton signed the defense authorization
bill Monday, but vetoed a bill to fund the Commerce, Justice and
State departments in a move that sets the stage for a final
showdown with Republicans over next year's spending.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also threatened to veto two other bills this week that
would fund interior, labor, education and health programs, even
though a temporary government spending measure designed to prevent
a partial government shutdown expires Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are prepared to pass and send another stopgap
spending bill to Clinton before the Friday deadline in order to
keep all government operations running. Clinton said he would sign
it, but he implored Republicans to show ``good faith'' in
negotiating a final spending deal covering the remaining budget
items for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will have to decide whether they want to work with me,''
Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has agreed with Republicans that Social
Security money should be off limits, he insisted that there are
better ways to fund needed programs next year, such as closing
corporate tax loopholes and imposing stiff penalties on polluters.
</P>
<P>
   He also vowed to fight a Republican plan to impose a 1.5 percent
across-the-board cut in overall spending. He said the cuts would
affect important government programs while exempting a 4.5 percent
pay raise for House and Senate members, who also enjoyed a similar
salary increase last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not allow Congress to raise its own pay and fund its
own pork barrel projects and still make devastating
across-the-board cuts in everything from education to child
nutrition to the FBI,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the continued criticism, Republican leaders on Capitol
Hill praised Clinton for signing the defense measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's decision by the president shows that we can work
together and find agreement on the important issues facing this
country,'' said House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who is
directing the GOP strategy in dealing with the White House on
budget matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the president realized that, while there may be still
some disputes over the budget process, it is time to put partisan
politics aside and work together to further our security
interests,'' DeLay added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had considered vetoing the defense bill, but ended up
signing it primarily because it contains a 4.8 percent pay increase
for military personnel and because Democrats appeared ready to join
with Republicans to override a veto.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also noted the $268 billion bill contains about a $4.8
billion boost in defense spending overall, even though he said it
is still filled with a number of ``pork barrel'' items he finds
objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Although he didn't mention Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., by name, he singled out a $375 million ship building
project in Pascagoula for criticism that the senator got added to
the bill to benefit his hometown constituents. The ``mini-carrier''
project will cost $1.5 billion overall, but the Pentagon wanted to
postpone the start on it until at least 2005.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bill contained a $15 million item slipped in by
Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,
that would allow the Gulfstream aircraft company to conduct
research on ``supersonic aircraft noise mitigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lott and Stevens projects were just two of hundreds of
so-called ``add-ons'' designed to benefit special interests that
were written into the defense and other spending bills by House and
Senate members.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other projects included money to fund research on
converting chicken manure into electric generating fuel, and
several hundred million for military facilities in California,
Texas and Wisconsin that are supposed to be closed.
</P>
<P>
   The military base money, which included funding for Brooks Air
Force Base in San Antonio, was described as ``transitional
funding'' to help ease the way for the area hit by the closing. As
it turns out, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., was
instrumental in helping to get the money for Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also criticized a $7 billion program in the budget for
routine maintenance and operations at military bases that
Republicans decided to label as ``emergency'' spending for next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency designation means that the money will not count
against spending limits for next year that Congress and Clinton
agreed to in 1997. But it will still have to paid for. Clinton
suggested that the money could end up coming out of Social Security
despite Republican claims to the contrary unless Congress works
with him to figure out other ways to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Clinton has signed eight of the 13 major appropriations
bills needed for funding the government next year. But by the end
of this week, a total of five bills will have been vetoed,
including the measure funding Commerce, Justice and State that
Clinton rejected Monday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The president said he vetoed that $35 billion bill because it
did not meet his goal of hiring 50,000 more police officers or
provide enough money to support the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process and pay off the nearly $1 billion in delinquent U.S.
obligations owed to the the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to veto a bill the House is likely to approve
Tuesday that would fund labor, education and health programs
because it does not include money to help hire new teachers and to
adequately protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
