<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUV-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD TO INSTALL SAFETY BARS IN BIG PICKUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Ford Motor plans to start installing hollow,
energy-absorbing steel bars below the front and rear bumpers of all
of its industrial-size pickup trucks in the 2001 model year to
reduce the risk that they will ride over cars in crashes, Ford
officials said in interviews Monday at a safety conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is also studying the feasibility of adding such bars to
four-wheel-drive versions of the Ford Expedition and Lincoln
Navigator full-size sport utility vehicles and the F-150 pickup
truck, said Priya Prasad, Ford's top safety researcher. Resembling
in function the cowcatchers on the front of locomotives, the
horizontal bars are designed to catch the bumpers, reinforced door
sills and other safety features of cars.
</P>
<P>
   The Expedition is the nation's best-selling full-size sport
utility vehicle, while the F-150 is the nation's best-selling
vehicle over all. Four-wheel drive vehicles ride several inches
higher than two-wheel drive vehicles, making them potentially more
dangerous to other motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the bars on industrial-size pickups, of which Ford sells
close to 350,000 a year, will be the latest in a series of recent
steps by automakers to make big sport utility vehicles and pickups
less dangerous to other motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has already begun installing the bars on the giant Ford
Excursion sport utility vehicle, which went on sale this autumn but
is a fairly low-volume vehicle. And General Motors has redesigned
the bumpers on the 2000 Chevrolet Suburban and GMC Yukon to extend
four to six inches lower and has redesigned their bodies to ride
lower, though this was done partly to improve fuel economy and make
it easier to climb in.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's disclosure Monday coincided with the release of an
insurance industry study at the gathering here, the 43rd annual
Stapp Car Crash Conference. The insurance study looked at why sport
utility vehicles and pickups are more likely than cars of the same
weight to kill the occupants of vehicles they hit on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The study cited the high hoods and extra stiffness of the light
trucks. Automakers can reduce the deadliness for car occupants of
collisions with sport utility vehicles and pickup trucks by taking
three precautions that are technically feasible but are only done
now on a few models, insurance industry researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Putting side air bags in cars, installing energy-absorbing bars
like Ford's below the bumpers of sport utilities and pickups and
designing light trucks with lower hoods should improve the safety
of car occupants, said Adrian Lund, research director of the
Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, which is seeking to cut the
cost of claims and conducted the tests.
</P>
<P>
   One finding from the crash tests, which were conducted the last
two years, was accidental, insurance researchers said. A Ford F-150
pickup truck with four-wheel drive used in one of the crash tests
happened to be equipped with two tow hooks mounted below the front
bumper. When the pickup slammed into the side of a 1992 Mercury
Grand Marquis full-size sedan, the tow hooks hit the base of the
car first, absorbing part of the impact and helping to push away
from the impact the car and within the car the driver's seat with
the crash dummy in it.
</P>
<P>
   When another F-150 pickup without tow hooks crashed into another
1992 Grand Marquis, the damage was much more severe, with the crash
dummy in the car absorbing more of the impact in the neck and chest
as the pickup's grille and head pierced the car.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Felrice, a former top regulator who is now the senior
manager of regulatory affairs at DaimlerChrysler, said the
institute's study was informative but that more work was needed,
particularly to assess the full range of possible crashes. ``It's
not sufficient to go redesign every vehicle so it crashes well into
a 1992 Grand Marquis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Occupants of sport utilities and pickups already have slightly
higher death rates than car occupants because the light trucks tend
to roll over more easily and are so rigid their occupants fare
poorly in collisions with fixed objects like bridge abutments.
</P>
<P>
   Prasad said that Ford's tests had found that adding bars below
the bumpers had no effect on the safety of sport utility and pickup
occupants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
