<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-YANKEES-FANS-COX     10-25 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKEES-FANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves best ready themselves for all-out NY fan attack
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are the fans who have scripted their insults
for the Braves, who come into tonight's Game 3 of the World Series
here trailing 0-2 _ insults so filthy that even the no-holds-barred
New York Post couldn't print parts of them.
</P>
<P>
   There are fans with a slightly more subtle approach, such as the
guy whose mock Braves war chant reverberated through the clubby
Algonquin Hotel lobby Sunday night as he watched game highlights in
the bar: ``Whoa-whoa-whoa-whoa,'' he droned on and on, ``Two down,
two to go . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   And then there are what might be the scariest of all Yankees
fans, the ones who never stop smiling the whole time they are
firing off insults like lethal brushback pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chipper Jones, Chipper Jones,'' Kurt Evans muttered as he
stared up at a TV in lower Manhattan's Blarney Rock bar Saturday
night, seeming to marvel aloud when Jones' home run gave the Braves
a 1-0 lead in game one. Referring crudely to Jones' extramarital
affair and subsequent divorce: ``He's got bigger things to worry
about than just beating the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   A brief pause, and then Evans, a construction supervisor,
continued in the same loud, sincere tone that practically dared
anyone to disagree with him: ``Hell of a ballplayer, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Hell of an intimidating group, these Yankees fans.
</P>
<P>
   Vanquished at home, the Braves tonight take on perhaps their
toughest opponent yet in The Bronx. The reputation of Yankee fans
for tossing verbal brickbats _ and harder objects _ apparently is
no exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Braves played a World Series game in Yankee
Stadium, in 1996, fans pelted their outfielders and bullpen
pitchers with everything from bagels and miniature bottles to coins
and radio batteries. Some players' wives reportedly were spit on in
the stands. Days earlier, during two playoff games with the Texas
Rangers, police had issued 164 summons for everything from scalping
_ tickets, that is _ to unruly behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves remember well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you play here, you can expect the crowd to be loud
and vocal,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``I expect the same
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be very intimidating playing here because of the
crowd,'' outfielder Otis Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the 1,000 off-duty New York police officers who
reportedly supplemented regular Yankee Stadium security during last
year's postseason games can protect the Braves from the verbal
abuse they're sure to suffer tonight. Playing for the other side in
the Bronx means being taunted nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what happens to players that Yankees fans like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat in the bleachers this year and fans were yelling,
'Griffey, you suck!' `` said Joseph Maggio, who wore a Yankees cap
that looked as if it hadn't been washed in the 31 years he's been
following the team. ``This is Ken Griffey Jr., mind you, who's
probably the greatest centerfielder in history. And they knew it.
They just couldn't help themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the Braves who, most Yankees fans here agree,
have all but asked for it.
</P>
<P>
   Take John Rocker. Please.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bleacher Creatures can't wait to meet Mr. On-and-Off-His
Rocker,'' steamfitter Chuck Koebel, 48, crowed about the Braves'
outspoken reliever. ``I can't imagine what they'll say to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Um, how 'bout this?
</P>
<P>
   ``John Rocker,'' said Tylene Lezotte, an angelic-looking Yankees
fan who was booing Chipper Jones at the Blarney Rock on Saturday.
``He's the one who's inbred, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees fans and Mets fans agree about almost nothing except the
inherent danger in wearing one team's T-shirt to the other's
stadium. But like Mets fans, Yankees fans despise Jones and Rocker
for having reversed the natural order. New York fans should be
dumping on the players, they say, and not the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   As for fans dumping on opposing fans, some Yankee Stadium
regulars who made it into Turner Field last weekend were amazed at
how hospitably they were treated by their Atlanta peers. Any fan
dumb enough to wear a Braves cap into Yankee Stadium tonight
shouldn't expect similar treatment, they warn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either you're going to take that hat off, or someone's going
to take it off for you,'' said Victor Calcano Sr., a Manhattanite
who was at Games 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Some Yankees fans speculate that it's their environment that
makes them so _ what's the word? _ outgoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever Yankees fans come from _ Long Island, Queens, you
name it _ they gotta go in and out of the Bronx,'' said Michael
McHale, another burly steamfitter on lunch break. ``You've got to
be a true fan to want to go in and out of that place, and it's got
to have some temporary effect on people.''
</P>
<P>
   Others insist it's all heredity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta remember, this is New York,'' said Maggio, the Ken
Griffey Jr. defender, smiling almost helplessly. ``It's who we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
