<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0472 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8175 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CHAFEE-OBIT-BOS &LR;      10-25 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAFEE-OBIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
R.I. SENATOR JOHN CHAFEE DIES AT 77 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator John H. Chafee of Rhode Island left the
Senate chamber for a final time Thursday afternoon, leaning heavily
on a cane as he limped down the stairs. He had just voted to
support a woman's right to an abortion, stubbornly defying his
Republican Party's leadership as he had for most of his 22 years in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do what I believe is right,'' Chafee liked to say.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, news of Chafee's death at age 77 brought Capitol Hill
to a virtual standstill, prompting a flood of tearful speeches and
tributes. Colleagues remembered him as a battle-scarred World War
II veteran, a powerful champion for the environment, a genteel
bridge-builder between opponents, and a doting father of five.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Chafee's quiet independence, coupled with his
unflagging honesty, that was remembered repeatedly on the Senate
floor. Indeed, friends said Chafee died having lived up to his
gubernatorial campaign slogan of 1962: ``A man you can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't now and then. You always knew that when John Chafee
cast a vote, his conscience was clean,'' said Senator John W.
Warner, Republican of Virginia, who considered Chafee a friend for
three decades and served as his under secretary when Chafee was
secretary of the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee, who announced in March he would not seek reelection next
year, died of heart failure at 7 p.m. Sunday at Bethesda Naval
Center after going to the hospital earlier that day, his aides
said. In August, Chafee underwent back surgery, but had never fully
recovered from a serious bout of pneumonia last year. He is
survived by his wife, Virginia, five children and 12 grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   His death was not announced until Monday morning, surprising
many of his colleagues who had seen him at work last week. With
flags across Washington lowered to half-staff, dozens of senators
took to the Senate floor to share their memories of Chafee.
</P>
<P>
   ``John was one of the great calming influences in this body, a
man of extraordinary common sense,'' said Senator John F. Kerry. He
said Chafee ``always tried to stand for principle _ not for party,
not for ideology, but for what was best.''
</P>
<P>
   It was perhaps for that reason that Chafee kept his Senate seat
for four terms after first being elected in 1976 to become the only
Republican to hold a Senate seat from Rhode Island in the last 68
years.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee, a descendant of one of the original five families that
settled Rhode Island, had a long history of public service prior to
that election. While still a student at Yale, he left to join the
Marine Corps in 1942, serving at Guadalcanal during World War II.
After graduating from Yale in 1947 and then from Harvard Law
School, Chafee was recalled to serve in the Korean War as a
rifleman in 1951 and 1952.
</P>
<P>
   He was first elected to office in 1956 as a Rhode Island state
representative and served until 1963, when he was elected governor
for the first of three terms. When Chafee first won the
governership _ by a mere 398 votes _ he created the slogan that
would last until his death.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee lost his bid for a fourth term as governor and lost a
Senate race in 1972 to the incumbent Democrat, Claiborne Pell. In
between those two elections, he served as secretary of the Navy
under President Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Chafee finally won an open Senate seat, launching a
career on Capitol Hill that would span four presidents and more
than two decades and would see substantial legislative
accomplishments ranging from the environment to health care.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among his accomplishments was the 1990 Clean Air Act,
which he helped create, as well as laws mandating the prevention
and control of oil spills. Members on both sides of the aisle
credit Chafee with helping pass laws expanding health care coverage
for women and children in his position on the Senate Finance
Committee. Just last week, he used his role on that committee to
push legislation that would restore funding cuts to medical schools
and nursing facilities, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked so hard to find a middle ground,'' said Senator
James M. Jeffords, Republican of Vermont. ``He just had that knack.
He was always so friendly and smiled and made it very difficult to
argue with him. He had a great sense of compromise _ and we saw
that with the Clean Air Act, saw it with health care, saw it with
the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In any age where politics all too often triumphs over policy,
Senator Chafee had the courage to stand up to th eleaders of his
own party. Over the years, Senator Chafee has become well known for
his willingness to do what is right for Rhode Island, and has been
extremely successful in achieving consensus on some very important
legislation,'' Patrick Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping forge national compromises, Chafee
crafted a regional coalition, the dwindling group of New England
Republican moderates who often formed a crucial voting bloc and ate
lunch together every week.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates' votes infuriated GOP leaders at times. Chafee and
his four colleagues _ Jeffords, Maine Senators Olympia Snowe and
Susan M. Collins, and Pennsylvania Senator Arlen Specter _ were
among just 10 Republicans who voted to acquit Clinton during his
impeachment trial. They also helped tip the balance in last week's
vote on an amendment in support of the Supreme Court's landmark
abortion decision, Roe v. Wade, which passed with 51 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often talked about our concerns about where the Senate was
heading,'' Collins said Monday. ``There were times I felt
discouraged, and he was always so proud just to be in the Senate,
even in the low points. He was just proud of the institution, and
of having served here.''
</P>
<P>
   When the five moderates ate lunch together in Chafee's office
last Wednesday, he appeared tired but in good health, Collins said.
But on Friday, Chafee's 77th birthday, he was too tired to go to
work, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   His death left two immediate political questions: Who would fill
his vacancy in the Senate, as well as his chairmanship on the
Senate Environment and Public Works Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Chafee, the senator's son and the mayor of Warwick,
R.I., already had declared he would run for his father's seat after
Chafee announced his retirement last spring. Several political
analysts in Rhode Island said Monday they expected Governor Lincoln
Almond, a Republican, to appoint the younger Chafee to the seat
until the November 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Almond said he would not make that announcement for at least
a week. And Representative Bob Weygand, a Democrat from Rhode
Island who is also running for the seat, said he hoped ``people
would take time out to allow the family to grieve, and the state to
grieve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's time later on for the politics, but that should wait
for another day,'' Weygand said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire is in line to fill Chafee's
seat as chairman of the environment committee. But because Smith
has switched from the Republican Party to become an Independent,
the chairmanship will likely go to Senator James M. Inhofe,
Republican of Oklahoma, Senate aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee was the first senator to die in office since Quentin
Burdick, a Democrat of North Dakota, in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
