<HEADER>
A8178 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-25 1551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GOOD FRIENDS ARE TAKEN AT ONCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On his wrist, Payne Stewart wore a simple cloth bracelet, like
one a child might wear, with the letters WWJD.
</P>
<P>
   What Would Jesus Do?
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, I hope He welcomed Payne Stewart, Robert
Fraley, and the three others who died with them into the Kingdom of
Heaven with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   Fraley and Stewart were friends of each other, and friends of
mine. Both were strong in their Christian faith and led their lives
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   I was much closer to Fraley, who was the agent for Stewart and
some top National Football League coaches, including Bill Parcells,
Tom Coughlin, Joe Gibbs, Bill Cowher, Buddy Ryan, and Ray Perkins,
to name a few, past and present.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, Fraley, Stewart, and Chuck Cook, Stewart's coach and
a close friend of Fraley's, formed a foursome with me at The
Country Club in Brookline, which was to be site of the Ryder Cup in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart wanted to play the course before going to Europe for the
British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Fraley and his wife, Dixie, stayed at our house for the next
three days. Dixie saw Boston with my wife, Denise, and Fraley
played golf with me at some local courses.
</P>
<P>
   During the second week in September, my wife, myself, my
daughter, Cara, the Fraleys, and Dixie's mother were all in New
York and went out to dinner in Manhattan the night before the
Jets-Patriots game.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fraley was absolutely one of the finest people I have
ever met. He saw the glass as half-full. He saw the best in people.
I spent hundreds of hours in his company and never remember him
uttering a single profanity. A former quarterback at Alabama for
Bear Bryant, he was tough-minded but always fair.
</P>
<P>
   I became friends with Stewart through Fraley. Fraley and I were
playing golf years ago at Bay Hill in Orlando, where Stewart had a
house just off the 11th hole. When we got to the tee, Stewart
popped his head over the fence, holding his young son in his arms.
I kidded him about not taking the choke on a putt for $240,000 the
day before, in a Skins Game for TV. He responded, ``Putting for
money doesn't bother us. Putting in the Ryder Cup is a different
story. That's when we all choke.''
</P>
<P>
   That moment came back to me several times as I followed the
tragedy Monday. Stewart was always wonderfully straightforward. You
could needle him about anything and he would come right back at you
with a couple of funny lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne really did a wonderful job turning his life around and
finding his spirituality the last few years,'' said Cook, via phone
from his Austin, Texas, home. Cook was due to join Stewart Tuesday
in Houston, where the Tour Championship will be played this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a state of shock right now,'' said Cook. ``When I spoke
with Payne Monday (Sunday) he told me that he was having the
hardest time in his life playing golf. After winning the (US) Open
this year, and the Ryder Cup, he couldn't get himself motivated.
Winning the Ryder Cup was his No. 1 goal for this year. Winning a
major tournament was the second. He accomplished both of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, `Now I have all these perks I worked toward,
these tournaments and Skins games coming up, and I can't get
motivated to play. The last two tourneys I played in, the Dunhill
Cup and Disney, I had no desire to play.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way Payne was. He was very candid. He didn't always
have the greatest tact, but he was very honest with himself and his
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few years he re-created his thinking, he developed
more feelings about things, and his beliefs became much more
important in his life. I feel good now, that he was able to resolve
a lot of things in his life before this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook said Stewart was on his way to Dallas on a business trip,
to look at a piece of land that might be turned into a golf course.
Fraley and a business associate, Van Arden, who also worked for
Leader Enterprises out of Orlando, went with him. In recent years,
Stewart showed an interest in designing courses, as many top
professionals have done later in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day for golf, and everyone who knew Payne,''
said golf analyst Peter Kostis, who came to know Stewart well over
the years. ``Payne had things going for him in his life the way he
wanted them. He was happy with himself and his game. There just
isn't any way to say the right thing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraley played quarterback at Alabama on the same team with
former Red Sox manager Butch Hobson. He loved Bryant, who helped
him get into law school. Parcells gave Fraley his opening to the
big time when he hired him to negotiate his contract with the New
York Giants in 1983. Fraley never forgot it. Parcells introduced
him to other NFL coaches, who later hired Fraley, setting him up as
one of the top sports agents in America.
</P>
<P>
   There was one thing that made Fraley different from all of the
rest in his chosen profession. He never looked for publicity, never
wanted to be quoted. At one time, he represented about 10 of the
best coaches in the NFL and also was the agent for baseball stars
Orel Hershiser and Frank Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Fraley became fast friends when Stewart moved to the
Orlando area, so close that when Stewart and his wife traveled to
major tournaments, the Fraleys took care of their children.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart loved all sports. About a dozen years ago, he wanted to
come to Boston and see the Celtics play in Boston Garden before
Larry Bird finished his career. Stewart was a big Bird fan, and he
and the Fraleys stayed in town to watch the Boston Marathon. Fraley
came to Fenway Park many times to watch the Sox. When Stewart came
to Boston for the Ryder Cup, he was disappointed that the schedule
prevented him from seeing the Red Sox play.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Fraley injured his shoulder and gave up golf.
This year, after the AT&AMP;T tournament in Pebble Beach, which has the
biggest pro-am in the country, Stewart challenged Fraley to start
playing again so that he could be Stewart's partner next year.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Stewart, Fraley, and Cook came to Boston to play in
Brookline. My wife and I picked them up at Logan after they landed
in a Learjet. Stewart had a deal with a company called Net-Jet to
fly for a certain number of hours a year. It was not always in the
same plane, so I have no way of knowing whether the jet that took
him to Boston was the same one that malfunctioned and crashed in
South Dakota Monday.
</P>
<P>
   We had a fun day at Brookline. Stewart, just a handful of days
after winning the US Open, was in great spirits. He wanted to play
The Country Club because he hadn't been on the course since 1988,
when the US Open was here.
</P>
<P>
   The people at The Country Club were very gracious, going out of
their way to accommodate us. There was a member-guest tourney that
day, but somehow they put us in the middle of it, and Stewart was
terrific to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   On the first tee, after a drive that carried everything down the
left side, he was walking alone when a maintenance cart carrying
two young workers pulled up near him. The kids wanted to say
something but didn't. So Stewart went over and talked to them for a
few minutes until he got to his ball.
</P>
<P>
   As we went around the course, a crowd gathered. Stewart kidded
with everyone who wanted to chat. About the 15th hole, he was
introduced to a young boy named Andrew, I believe, and they talked.
When we were walking to the clubhouse about 30 minutes later, he
stopped, looked back, and yelled to the boy by name, adding, ``Nice
to meet you. Take care of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the four of us were sitting around having a soft drink,
waiting to go back to the airport. Stewart had several hours until
his flight, and he wanted to spend them there rather than at Logan.
In the midst of our conversation, a member came by and asked
Stewart what he had shot for the day. He answered, ``Par.'' The man
seemed unimpressed, so Stewart smiled and added, ``Par isn't bad.
Par just won the US Open on the final day. I'll take par when I
come back here for the Ryder Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   On the final day of that Ryder Cup, Stewart was a true
sportsman. He was paired with Colin Montgomerie, just behind Justin
Leonard and Jose Maria Olazabal, when Leonard sank his dramatic
putt on the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that happened, all the wind was taken out of everyone,''
said Cook, who was walking the course with him. ``There was no
sense in playing anymore. So Payne conceded the match to Colin.''
</P>
<P>
   This went down on Stewart's record as a loss in Ryder Cup play,
but he didn't care. Winning the Ryder Cup was more important. To
him, this was the ultimate in the game he loved, and the game that,
in his final season of playing, loved him back.
</P>
<P>
   Fraley grew up in a small town in Tennessee, with strong values
for family and religion. He treated everyone I ever saw him meet
with great respect. I remember asking him and Dixie once where they
were going on vacation. When they told me Israel, I asked why. And
Fraley answered, ``So we can go to the Holy Land and follow the
path of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   WWJD. What Will Jesus Do? I think we know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
