<SLUG> BC-CRASH-JET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLFER STEWART AMONG THOSE KILLED IN LEARJET CRASH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ U.S. Open golf champion Payne Stewart and at least
four other people died Monday in their Learjet that crashed in a
swampy South Dakota field after an uncontrolled flight almost
half-way across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who was due in Houston on Tuesday to participate in the
Tour Championship, two of his agents and two pilots left early
Monday from Orlando, Fl were headed for Dallas when their
craft veered off course over Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Learjet, believed to have been on autopilot, flew for more
than 1,600 miles before apparently running out of fuel near
Aberdeen, S.D., and crashing. There were no survivors, and
authorities said the victims were probably dead or unconscious
before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said the craft may have suffered a
pressurization failure shortly after takeoff. Pilots of U.S.
fighter jets that were scrambled to shadow the stricken Learjet
reported its windows were iced over as it streaked northwest over
the nation's heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 42, one of the world's top golfers, was known and
recognizable for his trademark tam-o'-shanter cap and knickers,
called ``plus fours.'' He was remembered Monday as a dedicated
family man and an ambassador for his sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to express our sense of shock and sadness over
the death of Payne Stewart,'' said Tim Finchem, commissioner of the
Professional Golf Association Tour. ``This is a tremendous loss for
the entire golfing community and all of sports. Payne was a great
champion, a gentleman and a devoted husband and father. He will
always be remembered as a very special competitor, and one who
contributed enormously to the positive image of professional
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sports agents on the plane were Robert Fraley and Van
Ardan. The pilots were identified as Michael Kling, 43, and
Stephanie Bellegarrigue, 27.
</P>
<P>
   Golf great Jack Nicklaus said he feared that one of his course
designers, Bruce Borland, 40, was also on the craft, but
investigators at the crash site said they could not tell how many
people were on board the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said Stewart's Learjet, a
1976 model Lear 35 of which he was reportedly a part owner, took
off at about 8:20 a.m. EDT from Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   After controllers lost communication with the craft when it was
over Gainesville, the next four hours were nothing but silence as
the plane raced toward its doom, sometimes reaching altitudes of
45,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as an eyewitness described to the Reuters wire service,
the plane fell out of the sky like a rag and crashed in a grassy,
swampy field about two miles west of Mina, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assume it ran out of fuel,'' Maj. Tom Dravland, assistant
superintendent of the South Dakota Highway Patrol, told Agence
France-Presse. ``The wreckage is smoldering, but there is no
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after communications were lost with the Learjet, an Air
Force fighter jet from Tyndall, Fla., which was on a routine
training exercise, was diverted to shadow it, joined later by two
other fighters from Eglin Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   When those planes had to turn back for fuel, two F-16s from the
Oklahoma Air National Guard in Tulsa began shadowing the Lear.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board dispatched a team to
South Dakota to investigate the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Bill Curry said Stewart's family was ``just trying to
survive right now'' as tributes to the popular golfer began to pour
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone just direct their prayers to the Stewart family,''
Curry said. ``That's the best thing anyone can do for the Stewarts
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is survived by his wife, Tracey, and children Chelsea,
13, and Aaron, 10.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton, an avid golfer, said: ``I am
profoundly sorry for the loss of Payne Stewart, who has had such a
remarkable career and impact on his sport and a remarkable
resurgence in the last couple of years, and the members of his
group who were with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush praised Stewart as the ``epitome of
the gentleman sportsman.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart won three major championships _ the 1991 and 1999 U.S.
Open and 1989 PGA Championship _ and 15 other tournaments,
including the Shell Houston Open in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the U.S. Ryder Cup team that pulled off a
dramatic come-from-behind win over the European squad last month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The impact of his death on this week's Tour Championship at
Champions Golf Club in Houston was uncertain. Finchem said
Tuesday's pro-am competition would be canceled and that the
tournament schedule will ``tentatively'' resume Wednesday ``pending
further information on the scheduling of memorial services.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow PGA players gathering for the Tour Championship reacted
with shock and sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even comprehend the scope of it,'' said Tiger Woods, a
six-time winner on the PGA tour this year. ``There is an enormous
void and emptiness I feel right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time U.S. Open champion Curtis Strange said, ``We have lost
someone who was truly a great ambassador for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts said Monday it was premature to speculate on the cause
of the crash, but the icing observed on the windows of the plane
suggested a pressurization problem.
</P>
<P>
   Planes are pressurized because the thin air above 12,000 feet
becomes harder to breathe the higher one goes. To keep atmospheric
pressure inside a plane normal, pressurization systems pump
compressed air in while controlling how much is let out.
</P>
<P>
   Crashes caused by pressurization failures are virtually unheard
of in civil aviation, say experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of one other such case, a turbo-prop plane in the
1970s that crashed in the ocean after its pilots became
incapacitated,'' said Warren Morningstar, spokesman for the
Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressurization systems are so simple _ it's usually easy to
recognize the problem, put on your oxygen masks and descend to a
lower level.''
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar said there was no common theme in the Learjet 35
accident reports to suggest pressurization problems.
</P>
<P>
   Incapacitated passengers and pilots can regain consciousness as
the plane plunges toward Earth, but that's rare, say experts. It
depends on the length of time each was unconscious, the steepness
of the descent and their physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
