<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS BANGED UP   AT KEY POSITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Linebackers Marty Moore and Vernon Crawford
were hobbling Monday. Tedy Bruschi, who has missed the last two
weeks with a strained left knee, said he was ``90 percent'' and
would like to play Sunday in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Terry Allen, who sustained a concussion in last
Sunday's 24-23 win over the Broncos, said he had a slight headache
and was having more tests to determine whether he would be cleared
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker and running back. Two important positions where the
Patriots were hurt Sunday. Allen is probably going to play against
the Cardinals, but coach Pete Carroll will have quite a problem on
his hands if he can't get Bruschi back and somehow has to adjust
the defense so they're always playing a nickel package with six
defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Whigham, a.k.a. linebacker, looked a bit sore Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bobby Grier needs to get busy this week,'' kidded
Whigham, who took over at the weak-side spot when Moore and
Crawford went down.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford heroically returned but had no business being out there
with a sprained right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped us win a game,'' said Carroll. ``That's courage and
toughness and maybe it's being a little dumb. In the heat of
battle, sometimes guys can do some extraordinary things, and I
think he did one of those Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   At present there are two healthy linebackers, Andy Katzenmoyer
and Chris Slade.
</P>
<P>
   Grier, vice president/player personnel, will bring some people
in Tuesday for tryouts. Another possibility is to activate Fall
River's Marc Megna off the practice squad. Much depends on whether
the Patriots have enough salary cap space to bring in a veteran
like Dwayne Sabb, Pepper Johnson, or James Francis or whether
they'll have to bring in a younger player like Dana Cottrell, or
Ron Merkerson, who were on the roster the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how the guys shape up when we look at them,'' said
Carroll. ``In my mind, we're doing everything we can to put the
linebacking position together right now. In my mind, a lot can be
settled if Tedy Bruschi can make it back. He wasn't close this past
week, but he tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen was injured on a third-quarter hit, the third hit he took
on the same play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a helmet-to-helmet (hit),'' said Allen. ``He laid a
lick on me. Those things happen. It's happened to me before. It
doesn't bother me except that I wasn't myself. But I'm all right. I
have a slight headache but I'm OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to talk them into letting me back on the field, but
they wouldn't let me out there.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second concussion of his career, but he doesn't
believe he has suffered any long-term damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' said Allen. ``I don't think it's anything
that's gonna bother me. Steve (Young) doesn't take the hits that I
take. If I was in that situation, I'd worry about it, but I'm not
going to worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the injury, Allen had his best game in two years,
gaining 106 yards on 17 carries, and is excited about the
commitment the Patriots made to the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't remember too much about the game, but we did a great
job,'' he said. ``You never know going in how it's gonna turn out.
All we had to do is execute and make people miss and run the ball
hard. We talked about what we wanted to do and we went out and did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen was excited about turning the corner on a 39-yard run,
lauding a block thrown by Terry Glenn as the key. He also said Tony
Carter's lead blocking was superb. ``He's my personal protector out
there,'' said Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's remark last week that this was ``the best offensive line
I've ever run behind'' elicited some snickers, but those linemen
took heed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They emphasize pass-blocking here because you have a guy like
Drew (Bledsoe),'' said Allen, ``but the run game doesn't get the
attention it needs. Guys stepped up and showed they can run-block,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said he doesn't feel any wear and tear so far. Asked
whether he could carry the ball 25-30 times a game, he said, ``If
they run-block like Monday, I can go 25-30 carries as long as I can
get through to the secondary guys, and as long as the big guys
don't hit me. As long as we win the game I could care less if we
rush for 1 yard, or for 100, as long as we win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story with a twist
</P>
<P>
   Game films seemed to indicate that Denver linebacker Bill
Romanowski was doing the twisting of Ben Coates's left ankle and
knee out of bounds on a pass play. Carroll was coy when asked if he
would file a complaint, but it sounded as if the Patriots would
bring this to the attention of the league. ``This guy's a vicious
football player and great football player,'' said Carroll, ``and if
something happened out of line, the league will take care of it.''
. . . Troy Brown (ankle) will try to practice Wednesday. Carroll
may hold him back so he can have this week and the bye week to
recuperate.
</P>
</TEXT>
