<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIX AND MATCH FRILLS ON FLIGHTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Roger Collis writes the Frequent Traveler column for The
International Herald Tribune. 
By ROGER COLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business travelers are learning to love the growing network of
no-frills airlines _ such as EasyJet, Ryanair, Virgin Express and
British Airways' own low-cost clone Go _ that collectively serve
more than 50 destinations in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal is not just their low fares that can save you up to
80 percent on the cost of full-fare tickets, but low one-way fares
that allow you the flexibility you need for traveling midweek.
There is no requirement for a Saturday night stay-over.
</P>
<P>
   No-frills is the fastest-growing sector of the airline industry
in Europe, which, analysts say, could triple in the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   I can make five round-trips from Nice to London on EasyJet for
the price of one economy (coach) ticket on British Airways, which
carries some restrictions. And even a full house on an EasyJet
737-300 is at least as comfortable, with as much legroom, as on
British Airways.
</P>
<P>
   You pay for snacks and beverages. I buy a pack of smoked-salmon
sandwiches at the airport deli, treat myself to a gin and tonic on
the plane and enjoy. Cost it out.
</P>
<P>
   Business class gets you a separate check-in, the use of an
airport lounge and, usually, a mediocre meal. Increasingly, I can
pay far less for my own airport lounge, my own meals and even my
own limousine if I need one.
</P>
<P>
   Flying in the front of the plane is great, if you can afford it.
First class, however, can cost twice the price of a business-class
fare, which in turn costs up to four times the price of a full
economy ticket and 20 times more than the cheapest excursion
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   It's a stark choice. Do you pay to stretch your ego as well as
your legs? Or save money and endure the exquisite misery of cattle
class?
</P>
<P>
   How you choose to spend your time in the air may depend on your
mode _ office mode, dining mode, relaxation-entertainment mode. On
the red eye out you may want to work; coming home, you may want to
relax or sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, traveling west during the day, when you are going to drop
into bed anyway when you arrive, you might choose to fly economy on
a cheap ticket, especially if you can target an off-peak flight
with an empty seat next to you. Traveling east, you might invest in
a sleeper-seat in business class and forgo dinner.
</P>
<P>
   I've often thought of opening a can of Beluga caviar in economy
class and dining in style. But I've never quite managed to summon
the chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   But Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts came up with Gourmet Meals
to Go back in 1996 for departing guests ``to replace the limited
options of airline dining.'' The program was started at the Four
Seasons Los Angeles in Beverly Hills in response to ``repeated
requests from guests wanting to take popular dishes with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The service is now available at Four Season properties in Bali,
Dallas, Houston, New York, Newport Beach _ and London. Meals are
packed in ``biodegradable mini-suitcase boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Caterers and hotels around the world have taken up the idea. The
Dorset Square and the Covent Garden hotels in London provide
takeout breakfasts for early-morning flights. The five-star
Milestone in Kensington, London, offers ``lunch to go'' picnic
boxes, with cutlery and napkins, containing sandwiches of homemade
bread with such fillings as smoked salmon, ham, cheese and pickle;
crudites with cream cheese, fresh herb and onion dip; rotisserie
chicken with tossed salad; fresh fruit salad; banana and pistachio
nut muffin.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, the Canadian airline Wardair offered quality at
reasonable prices with a single standard of cuisine and service
throughout the plane and a Big Seat option. No matter how much your
ticket cost, you could trade up to a Big Seat in the front of the
cabin for around $33. Alas, Wardair, in spite of a loyal following,
was subsumed about 10 years ago by Canadian Airlines. But it's an
idea whose time may have come _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Given the steady move of many business travelers to the back of
the plane, airlines may be starting to realize that they are out of
sync with the reality of travelers' needs. They generally assume
that travelers fall into two groups: those with expense accounts
and leisure travelers. Never mind that some business travelers have
tight budgets and some leisure travelers like to splurge.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels could also offer options a la carte by selling a standard
or ``deluxe'' room and enabling you to pay extra for amenities:
early check-in, late checkout, use of the health club and the
business center.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Eagle Hotel in Hong Kong has just inaugurated an
Executive a la Carte program offering business travelers more
options. Visitors pay $168 for a basic room and then choose from a
range of upgrades at fixed prices. For example, you can have a
``personalized check-in and checkout, breakfast and a room
upgrade,'' for $50 or an upgrade to the Club Floor with buffet
breakfast and cocktails and unlimited laundry and ironing for $70.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hiring a chauffeur-driven car from a European airport is not as
staggeringly expensive as you might think. Car rental companies
like Hertz, (800) 654-3001, Avis, (800) 331-1084, Budget, (800)
472-3325, or Europcar (44-113) 242 2233, offer a chauffeur service
_ cheaper and more comfortable than a taxi, especially if you are
going to the suburbs, where taxis charge more and may get lost.
</P>
<P>
   You can rent a car by the hour or the day. From Heathrow to the
city, a black cab costs 35 pounds to 45 pounds (about $58 to $117,
at $1.60 to the pound), while a chauffeured ride is $66 to $75 in a
comfortable car. One day of being chauffeured around London, about
five or six hours, is approximately $333, compared with $66 to $75
a day for renting a car and driving yourself.
</P>
<P>
   From London to Oxford, a black cab or minicab will cost $133 to
$166 just to get there, compared with a chauffeur all day for about
$367.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chauffeur drive is most popular in countries where people are
less likely to want to drive themselves _ like Russia, the Middle
East and Africa, where labor costs less,'' said Gareth Wynn at
Hertz in London. ``It becomes less of a luxury and more of a
practical option. In Dubai, for example, you'd pay $77 a day for an
intermediate car plus $45 a day for a chauffeur.''
</P>
<P>
   Budget quotes $34 to $38 an hour for a chauffeured Lincoln Town
Car and $30 an hour for a Ford Mondeo.
</P>
<P>
   Airport lounges are now becoming available to all travelers.
Diners Club offers its cardholders (plus a guest) free use of 84
lounges around the world. All offer free snacks and beverages; some
have a business center; others offer free local calls.
</P>
<P>
   They include four new lounges at Sheremetyevo Airport in Moscow
(three in Terminal 1 and one in Terminal 2), plus others at
Prague's Ruzyne Airport and Leonardo da Vinci Airport in Rome. In
Britain, cardholders have the use of three lounges at Heathrow, two
at Manchester and one each at Gatwick, Stansted, Birmingham,
Edinburgh and Glasgow.
</P>
<P>
   The International Airline Passenger Association has a lounge
program, Priority Pass, that allows access to 200 airport lounges
around the world for around $30 a visit (e-mail:
info(AT)prioritypass.co.uk).
</P>
<P>
   Expensive, but what price do you put on a port in a storm?
</P>
<P>
   Lounges in Europe include Amsterdam, Athens, Berlin, Cairo,
Copenhagen, Dublin, London (Gatwick, Heathrow and Stansted),
Frankfurt, Geneva, Milan, Moscow, Nice, Paris, Rome, Vienna and
Zurich.
</P>
<P>
   Delayed in Frankfurt the other day, I headed for the lounge with
a Bloody Mary in mind. Sorry, no vodka, only soft drinks, wine and
beer. The Lufthansa Senator Club lounge next door for first-class
passengers and elite frequent-flier-club members offered the full
treatment for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. But it goes to show that you cannot yet buy your way
into every sanctum sanctorum.
</P>
<P>
   Wexas International (www.wexas.com), an independent traveler's
club based in London, offers its members access to 55 airport
lounges around the world for $10 to $23 a visit.
</P>
<P>
   United States airlines are required by law to offer club
membership to everyone. American Airlines' Admiral's Club, Delta's
Crown Room Club and United's Red Carpet Club cost around $250 to
join with annual dues of $175 to $200.
</P>
<P>
   Airports and ground-handling agents are starting to offer
lounges to all travelers. BAA, for example, which operates
Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted airports in London, opened its first
lounge at Stansted in May. The charge is $25, which includes
``unlimited refreshments,'' office facilities with Internet and
e-mail connections, newspapers and a music center.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can also use the FastTrack security channel through
the airport. BAA plans to have similar lounges at all four
terminals at Heathrow by the end of 1999 (www.baa.co.uk).
</P>
<P>
   The first Heathrow lounge in the land side arrival area of
Terminal 3, designed for arriving long-haul passengers, is due to
open in spring 2000. There will be showers, valet facilities, an
English breakfast and business facilities.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what class you fly across the Atlantic, you can arrive
in style.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
