<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE LAWYER SAYS SUSPECT IN JASPER SLAYING `NOT A RACIST' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The attorney for the third white man to go on
trial for the brutal dragging death of a black man told prospective
jurors Monday that the defendant is ``not a racist'' and has ``no
motive for committing a racial hate crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Berry, 24, of Jasper is charged with capital murder in the
June 7, 1998, slaying of James Byrd Jr., 49, also of Jasper.
Jurors, who will be chosen over the next two weeks, will decide
Berry's guilt or innocence, and if they convict him, will decide
whether he should die or serve a life prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's two co-defendants, 24-year-old Bill King and 32-year-old
Russell Brewer Jr., both white supremacists, have been tried and
sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's lawyer hopes to set him apart from King and Brewer.
``Shawn Berry is not a racist, was not a racist, and has no racist
writings, is not a member of any white supremacist group and has no
racial tattoos,'' attorney Joseph ``Lum'' Hawthorn told potential
jurors. ``He has no motive for committing a racial hate crime, and
he did not.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray, who also
prosecuted King and Brewer, said the clean-cut, pale young man who
sat in the courtroom Monday has a more menacing side that will be
presented during the trial. Berry gave investigators seven
different written statements, Gray said, and those statements
conflicted with each other and with a story he recited in an
interview in the television news magazine, ``60 Minutes II.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray has subpoenaed CBS producer Mary Mapes and out-takes of the
interview that were not broadcast. CBS is fighting the subpoena,
but state District Judge Joe Bob Golden ordered Mapes to appear
Friday with the required tapes and said he will hear further
arguments on the issue then.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gray said that forensic evidence indicates Berry may
have been the most active participant in beating Byrd, chaining him
by the ankles to the back of the pickup _ which was owned by Berry
_ and in dragging him to his death.
</P>
<P>
   Previous evidence indicated that Byrd was beaten, his face
spray-painted black and his pants pulled down to his ankles before
he was dragged for almost three miles down a back road outside
Jasper. His torso was ripped apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the fundamental issues in this particular trial is
Shawn Berry's credibility,'' Gray said, ``what he has said compared
to facts and the crime scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry was living in an apartment in Jasper with King, a former
high school friend, in the summer of 1998 when they were joined by
Brewer, 32, a former prison buddy of King's who was visiting from
Sulphur Springs, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Berry admits driving his battered Ford pickup in the early
morning hours of June 7, 1998, when he stopped to give a ride to
Byrd, who was drunk and staggering home on foot from a late-night
party.
</P>
<P>
   In his statements, Berry said he and the others drove Byrd to a
remote forest clearing where the other two men began beating Byrd
and then chained him to the truck and dragged him. Berry claimed in
his first statement that he ran away when the beating started. But
he later changed his story to say he tried to get between Byrd and
his tormentors and in the process got Byrd's blood smeared on him.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said Berry's trial will place heavy emphasis on forensic
evidence and the explanation of blood spatters. Unlike the other
two defendants, Berry has no racial tattoos and no history of being
part of racist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn told the jury that ``there are a lot of people who
think I am crazy'' for having the trial in Jasper when he probably
could have had the trial moved. He said Berry helped decide the
keep the case there. ``This crime happened in Jasper County, the
victim was from Jasper, Texas. The defendant is from Jasper,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the day about 170 prospective jurors crowded
into the 110-year-old courtroom. Legal excuses pared that number
down to 132, with 19 blacks among them, by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   They faced state District Judge Joe Bob Golden, the judge in
King's trial, and one table of prosecutors and another with Berry,
Hawthorn and Berry's fiance, Christie Marcontell, who is serving as
an assistant to Hawthorn. Berry is the first of the three
defendants to pay for his own attorney. The others had
court-appointed lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony should begin about Nov. 9, Golden said, and should
last about eight days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
