<HEADER>
A8187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANGELS-DANCE-REVIEW-N     10-25 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELS-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN BALLET THEATER: A CLASSICAL APPROACH TO THE GRAHAM KARMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A woman in white stands onstage, a dancer embodying
contained lyricism, and a man falls to her feet or cartwheels for
joy. Splashed like paint on a canvas, another woman in red embodies
passion as she races across in a diagonal. Her youthful counterpart
in yellow springs onto a partner's shoulders. A male and female
ensemble amplifies these images. The work of course is ``Diversion
of Angels,'' Martha Graham's celebrated and luminous ode to love.
</P>
<P>
   American Ballet Theater introduced the work into its repertory
over the weekend. There was a time when the first performance by a
ballet troupe of any Martha Graham choreography, once reserved for
her own company, would have been a milestone. But the karma was
right and natural at the matinees on Saturday and Sunday at City
Center when two Ballet Theater casts initially essayed ``Diversion
of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   The Martha Graham Dance Company remains the reference point for
the performance of her work, especially after her death in 1991.
But nowadays classical dancers like those in Ballet Theater are
widely exposed to modern dance, and this company premiere was
always true to the essence of ``Diversion of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not just a case of seeing a Graham signature onstage: the
asymmetrical dislocation of a body on the floor, one foot turned
in, the other stretched and pointed. Nor was it the valiant
attempts of the dancers to execute the contraction and release of
the body that is at the base of Graham's idiom, known as Graham
technique.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, this is a splendid staging by the Graham veteran Takako
Asakawa and a fine introduction to Graham's genius for those
unfamiliar with her work. More specifically, it is her genius for
distilling the deepest of feelings rather than merely depicting
them.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of public television viewers have come into contact
with this idea in a clip of Graham's 1930 ``Lamentation.'' There, a
purple-shrouded figure, her body moving into an assemblage of
planes, is less a woman mourning than an abstract embodiment of
grief; ``the thing itself,'' as Graham called it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diversion of Angels,'' which Graham choreographed for her
company in 1948 to a joyful commissioned score by Norman Dello Joio
(conducted here by Charles Barker), is an extension of this
abstract principle.
</P>
<P>
   There were critics in 1948 who found ``Diversion of Angels'' too
lyrical for Graham and lamented the loss of austerity of her early
pieces and the hard-edged poetry of her Americana works. Yet
``Diversion'' is not lush or sentimental, and the dancers
understood this. A gasp went up from the audience as the curtain
rose on Saturday afternoon. Even to those familiar with Graham, the
clarity of the first image is striking. Against a sky-blue
backdrop, Maxim Belotserkovsky, in a typical archaic profile, stood
protectively behind Gillian Murphy, the woman in white whom he
would soon seem to worship.
</P>
<P>
   The production, approved by Ron Protas, the Graham company's
artistic director, and in which Ms. Asakawa was assisted by Kenneth
Topping, another Graham veteran, is a lesson in form recreating
emotion. The patterns stand out in Brad Fields' lighting, based on
Jean Rosenthal's original design.
</P>
<P>
   Ballet Theater is not the first ballet company to dance a Graham
work. In recent years this has been done by the Dutch National
Ballet and the Paris Opera Ballet, with Protas' permission. The
Colorado Ballet has staged ``Appalachian Spring,'' and it would not
have hurt Ballet Theater's dancers to follow the Colorado example
by taking classes in Graham technique.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that there is a difference between imitating Graham
movement and actually doing it. Ms. Murphy, for instance, looks
right in her purity as the woman in white, but she proved too
classical a dancer to capture the shape of the Graham idiom and was
miscast. On Sunday afternoon, by contrast, Stella Abrera,
concentrated in her long-legged stillness and use of a raised hip,
was perfect in the role.
</P>
<P>
   The big surprise on Saturday was the brilliant performance of a
classical ballerina like Ashley Tuttle as the woman in red: she
went deep into her contraction of the pelvis, with leg raised high,
and caught the momentum of the arm-swinging Graham run as she
rushed across the stage in moments of dramatic epiphany. Similarly,
Yan Chen had the right refined exuberance with Joaquin De Luz in
the right spot to catch her.
</P>
<P>
   Each woman had a duet, and Belotserkovsky and Keith Roberts,
with Miss Tuttle, were supple enough. Sean Stewart rounded out the
male group, and wonderful energy came from all, especially the
women's chorus: Jennifer Alexander, Tamara Barden, Erica Fischbach
and Michele Wiles. The ensemble ``got it'' as well on Sunday
afternoon, with Clinton Luckett and Ilona McHugh, Eleena Melamed,
Adrienne Schulte and Alissa Wassung.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Ms. Abrera, partnered by a stalwart Marcelo Gomes,
this is a slightly less convincing cast. Sandra Brown, usually
excellent in works by other modern dance choreographers (Paul
Taylor, Lar Lubovitch) needed more fluency, and her partner, Ethan
Brown, needed more flexibility. The brother-sister team of Erica
Cornejo and Herman Cornejo had the spirit of the ``yellow'' duet.
In all, a fine addition to the repertory, something more than an
experiment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
