<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OPTIONS-MARKETPLACE-(     10-25 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPTIONS-MARKETPLACE-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: THE CHANGING WORLD OF OPTIONS TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bringing increased competition and fairer trading to
the world of equity options is, it seems, easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the Securities
and Exchange Commission, has repeatedly called on the nation's
option exchanges to reduce investors' trading costs by opening
their markets to more competition and linking the various exchanges
electronically. Because of Levitt's jawboning, most equity options
are now traded on more than one exchange. Until recently, most of
them were traded exclusively on either the Chicago Board Options
Exchange, the American Stock Exchange, the Pacific Stock Exchange
or the Philadelphia Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But multiple listing of these securities has reduced profits
significantly for the major Wall Street firms that trade them. As a
result, some firms are casting about for ways to retrieve lost
profits. And some of the practices that the major firms are
exploring may not be in the best interest of investors and may in
fact fragment the market rather than centralize it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the recent developments in the options trading arena are
specialist firms offering payments to other brokerage firms for
their customers' orders. Although this practice, known as payment
for order flow, has been a fact of life in the stock market for
years, it is new in options. Payment for order flow, while legal,
is of concern to regulators, though they have done little to stop
it in the stock markets. By paying for a stream of orders, a firm
has an incentive to match up buy and sell orders internally and
pocket the difference, instead of displaying orders across the
entire market. If more investors see an order, its chance for a
better execution improves.
</P>
<P>
   Big brokerage firms are also exploring alliances with options
exchanges in which the firms could become specialists on the
exchange and funnel all their customers' orders essentially to
themselves. This is known as internalizing or preferencing trades,
and it too can hurt investors whose orders do not get a chance to
interact with the overall market.
</P>
<P>
   Both developments are indicative of the rapidly shifting terrain
in the securities markets in which firms are grabbing market share
wherever they can, however they can. The evolving options practices
are of deep concern to the SEC because they go against the
regulators' goal of increased competition in the options markets.
Annette Nazareth, director of market regulation at the commission,
said, ``Our concern is whether vigorous quote competition, and
therefore better pricing, is compromised when these practices
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Levitt plans to address some issues in the options markets in a
speech before the Securities Industry Association next week.
</P>
<P>
   Options are an increasingly popular investment device that give
the buyer the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell a set
amount of a particular security at a specified price.
Alternatively, sellers of equity options are obligated to buy or
sell a specified amount of shares at a set price.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers of investors trading equity options has risen
sharply in recent years. This year, an average of 1.86 million
option contracts have exchanged hands each day, up from 450,000 on
average in 1990. Options are traded on approximately 3,000 stocks
and on stock indexes such as the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four exchanges, the Chicago Board Options Exchange has
the most trading volume. Through September, the CBOE did 45.3
percent of all equity options trades, compared with 28.2 percent at
the American Stock Exchange, 17.1 percent at the Pacific Stock
Exchange and 9.3 percent at the Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Options can be perilous to trade because there are fewer
safeguards to protect investors from getting bad prices on their
orders. For example, the major stock exchanges have order-handling
rules, requiring dealers to execute their customers' trades at the
best price available in the market and forbidding dealers from
trading for themselves before their customers at a given price.
Options markets have no such rules. As a result, one options
exchange executive conceded that option orders are given the proper
priority only half the time.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt's call last week for an electronic link of the options
markets would eliminate much of this disparity as prices on all the
exchanges would be displayed simultaneously. He has asked for new
proposals from the major exchanges in three months.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, with the bulk of options trading on more than
one exchange, the difference between what an investor pays to buy
and what he receives when he sells _ known as the spread _ has
shrunk. The spread in Intel options, for example, has dropped from
12.5 cents a contract to half that amount since multiple listing
began, according to a trader on the American Stock Exchange.
Because much of the spread is pocketed by the dealers, the profits
in the business are way down.
</P>
<P>
   Susquehanna Partners, in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., is one of the largest
options specialist firms in the United States, trading 460
different options. It has recently begun offering to pay other
brokerage firms to send their customers' options orders to it.
Another large specialist firm said to be pursuing such deals is
Spear, Leeds &AMP; Kellogg; Carl Hewitt, a spokesman for the firm,
declined to comment. Payments for order flow can begin without
regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Noll, associate director at Susquehanna, confirmed that the
firm was holding discussions with other brokerage firms about
buying their orders, but declined to discuss the arrangements.
According to an exchange official, the firm has offered to buy
orders in return for 5 percent of the profit on the business. At
least one unnamed discount brokerage firm was said to have signed
on.
</P>
<P>
   Noll stressed that paying for orders would not keep Susquehanna
from delivering the best execution on all its customers' trades.
And he pointed out that exchange rules prevent options specialists
generally from executing more than 20 percent of total volume in an
option, encouraging competition.
</P>
<P>
   If a firm attracts most of the orders in a contract, though, it
can essentially become the market, reducing competition. The order
would be executed at the current market price but would not get a
chance to receive a better price, known as price improvement in the
securities markets.
</P>
<P>
   A similar problem is presented when brokerage firms become
option specialists and try to internalize their customers' orders.
In such a case, the order is matched with other orders inside the
firm and not shown to the larger market.
</P>
<P>
   As the regulator of the options exchanges, the SEC could reject
such arrangements. Ms. Nazareth said: ``We are aware that some of
the options exchanges have been approached by members to permit
them to direct all their orders to their own specialists. We have
concerns about these proposals, and we would look very carefully at
the impact on the options markets before we permitted these
practices to occur.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
