u a BC-OBIT-WOLF-NYT &LR;      10-25 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WOLF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBARA WOLFF CITY OFFICIAL ACTIVE IN NEW YORK DEVELOPMENT, DIES AT
58  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Switzerland)   By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Barbara Wolff, a veteran New York City official who
was instrumental in setting up the city's business improvement
districts program and in the commercial revitalization program that
followed the blackout of 1977, died Oct. 15 at her home in
Manhattan. She was 58.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was ovarian cancer, said George Glatter, a friend and
colleague, who said Ms. Wolff had kept coming to her office until
several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wolff was assistant commissioner in charge of the
neighborhood development division of the New York City Department
of Business Services, a job she had held for more than a decade.
The division develops and oversees economic programs designed to
benefit neighborhood commercial streets, industrial areas and other
economic centers in the city.
</P>
<P>
   In that post and for some years earlier she played a leading
role in creating the business improvement districts known as BID's,
which now number more than 40. They are self-financing
organizations directed by local property owners and businesses. The
districts offer a variety of services, including sanitation,
security, promotion and marketing. The services are tailored to
each district's needs and supplement the services the city
provides.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest districts include those for Grand Central and Times
Square areas. The smallest are strips of commercial establishments
in neighborhoods like the Brighton Beach section of Brooklyn and
the Steinway Street area of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The program has been credited with strengthening many commercial
areas and some industrial ones by helping attract new businesses
and persuading others to stay.
</P>
<P>
   From 1977 to 1983, Ms. Wolff was with the city's Office for
Economic Development as its director of commercial revitalization.
Glatter, a deputy assistant commissioner in the business services
department, said Ms. Wolff had directed the program, begun as a
response to the damage inflicted on stores around the city in the
looting that took place during the 1977 blackout.
</P>
<P>
   The program has made use of federal and city funds over the
years to provide various kinds of aid to local businesses and
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wolff was born in Manhattan and graduated from Hunter High
School. She received a bachelor's degree from Simmons College in
Boston and a master's degree in political science from the
University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   She also worked for the International Labor Organization in
Geneva, the U. S. Agency for International Development in
Washington, the Parks and City Planning departments in New York and
the City's Public Development Corp., where she was a vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by a brother, William Wolff of Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8198 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-OBIT-CHAFEE-ART-ABRID     10-25 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CHAFEE-ART-ABRIDGED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. JOHN CHAFEE OF RHODE ISLAND DIES AT 77 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (A longer version of this obit has moved in ``a'' category) (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT16,17 _ are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Hubbard Chafee of Rhode Island, the last
of the Rockefeller Republicans and an increasingly isolated voice
of internationalism and bipartisanship in his party, died on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee died of heart failure at the National Naval Medical
Center in Bethesda, Md., a Washington suburb, his office announced.
He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   His major domestic efforts involved the environment and health
policy, and he was responsible for a vast expansion of Medicaid,
the federal health program for the poor, in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   A Marine veteran of Guadalcanal and the Korean War, Chafee made
his last major effort in the Senate this month in seeking to
postpone a vote on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. When the
Senate went ahead and voted on the pact that would have banned
underground nuclear testing, he was one of four Republicans to
support ratification.
</P>
<P>
   In partisan terms, his death will not change the Senate's 55-45
Republican advantage. Lincoln Almond, Rhode Island's Republican
governor and a Chafee protege, will appoint a successor to serve
until Jan. 3, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate impact in the Senate could be on
environmental issues. Chafee, as chairman of the Committee on
Environment and Public Works, has bottled up a number of
pro-business changes in environmental laws that other Republicans
want.
</P>
<P>
   In a larger sense, Chafee's death deprives the Senate of a
relatively moderate Republican in a position of power who was eager
to work with Democrats and willing to cross the Republican
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who had hoped in vain for Chafee's help on
national health insurance in 1993 and 1994, said on Monday: ``Rhode
Island and America have lost a great leader and a fine human being,
who in 23 years in the Senate and in his service as secretary of
the Navy, always put his concern for the American people above
partisanship. When you think of the term `bipartisan,' you
immediately think of John Chafee.''
</P>
<P>
   Chafee was descended from one of the ``five families'' of Rhode
Island, Yankees who ran the state before immigrants changed its
political complexion in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   He was at Yale when World War II began and he enlisted in the
Marines, serving in battles at Guadalcanal and Okinawa, and was
commissioned as a second lieutenant. He returned to Yale and then
went to Harvard Law School before being recalled to active duty in
Korea in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   He practiced law and served six years in the Rhode Island
Legislature, becoming minority leader of the State Assembly. In
1962 he became only the third Republican elected governor in 30
years, squeaking through by 398 votes.
</P>
<P>
   He was an unabashedly liberal governor. He pushed for
anti-discrimination laws in housing and employment before the
federal government passed them. He advocated the construction of
Interstate 95, developed parks throughout the small state and
pushed through a state plan of health care for the elderly before
Congress enacted Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In presidential politics, Chafee opposed Barry Goldwater's bid
for the 1964 Republican nomination, and in 1968 he backed Gov.
Nelson Rockefeller of New York against Richard Nixon and Ronald
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee himself was victim of a political upset that fall, losing
a bid for a fourth term as governor to Frank Licht. Chafee had
halted his campaigning after his 14-year-old daughter, Tribbie, had
died a few weeks before the election after being kicked in the head
by a horse.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his support for Rockefeller, the Nixon
administration found a place for him, and he reveled in the post of
Navy secretary. His most striking decision was made on May 6, 1969,
when he blocked any court martial of the commander and the
intelligence officer of the U.S.S. Pueblo, which had been captured
by North Korea in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   They had been held prisoner for 11 months, and Chafee said,
``They have suffered enough.'' Moreover, he concluded that the
capture was the result of a failure shared by the entire Navy chain
of command.
</P>
<P>
   He resigned in 1972 and ran for the Senate against Claiborne
Pell. But in a strongly Democratic state, he lost despite Nixon's
landslide. After that Chafee returned to practicing law in
Providence, until he ran again for the Senate in 1976 and won.
</P>
<P>
   Year after year in the 1980s, as Congress cut the budget for
other social programs, Chafee engineered expansions of Medicaid,
extending coverage to millions of pregnant women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the changes altered a basic concept of Medicaid,
breaking the link that for more than two decades had tied Medicaid
eligibility to the receipt of cash welfare benefits. As a result of
his efforts, Congress allowed, and in some cases required, states
to help pay medical bills for certain low-income people who were
not receiving welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fighting the Reagan administration over military
spending, he was elected to the Senate Republicans' third-ranking
position, chairman of the Republican Conference, in 1984. He was
ousted from that position in 1990 by the more conservative Thad
Cochran of Mississippi, who in turn was pushed aside by more
conservative rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But that year, he also played a central role in reauthorizing
the Clean Air Act, one of the nation's landmark environmental laws.
That was only one of the achievements hailed by environmentalists
on Monday. Carl Pope, executive director of the Sierra Club, cited
that bill and also said Chafee played an even greater role later as
a ``one-man front line'' defending laws against the ``Republican
far-right wing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, despite the loss of his formal Republican Party
leadership position, his friend, Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, put him
in charge of a task force to define Republican policy on national
health insurance. The Chafee group rejected the idea of requiring
employers to buy coverage for their workers, which was central to
President Clinton's plan, but instead advocated requiring people to
get insurance, with federal subsidies for those who could not
afford it.
</P>
<P>
   As the issue heated up in 1993 and 1994, Dole backed away from
it. When Chafee, Sen. John Breaux, D-La., and others struggled in
dozens of meetings in a Capitol hideaway to compromise with the
Clinton plan, they could get no more than a handful of Republicans
who would vote to break the Dole filibuster. Their effort, like
Clinton's, foundered.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. John Danforth of Missouri, a central ally in that
cause and a frequent dinner companion during late Senate nights,
reflected Monday that one of the best things about Chafee at that
moment was that ``when it fell apart, there was no bitterness.''
Danforth added: ``He was a person who really wanted to make things
better.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the big effort failed, elements of the Chafee-Breaux
``Mainstream Coalition'' plan reappeared in law in later years, and
Chafee played a major role in getting a plan to insure more
children enacted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Virginia; four sons, John Chafee Jr.
of Los Angeles, Lincoln Chafee of Warwick, R.I., Quentin Chafee of
North Kingstown, R.I., and Zechariah Chafee of Providence, R.I.; a
daughter, Georgia Nassikas of McLean, R.I.; three sisters, Janet
Cushman of Quebec, Susan Welch of Bethany, Conn., and Alexandra
Reynolds of North Kingstown, and 12 grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
