A8202 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     10-25 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   401(k) After Divorce, Death 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: As part of my wife's divorce settlement from her first husband,
an airline pilot, she was given rights to half the retirement
benefits he accumulated during their marriage, all of which were in
a 401(k) plan. Sadly, he was killed in a plane crash before
retiring. The airline has rolled over my wife's portion of the
retirement benefits into a new 401(k) account, which it
administers. Because this was her community-property interest in
her ex-husband's plan, rather than her own retirement plan, I
wonder whether she can take money out of the 401(k) without paying
the 10 percent tax penalty for premature withdrawal. (She is less
than 591/2 years old.)
<P>
   A: If the retirement plan is a qualified plan under Internal
Revenue Service regulations, and if the divorce decree is what is
known in legal parlance as a qualified domestic relations order,
then yes, she can take money out of the plan without paying a tax
penalty. She will, of course, have to pay ordinary tax.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, the airline will send your wife a 1099-R form _
the form for pension income _ reminding you how much she withdrew.
It also will send a copy to the Internal Revenue Service, with
coding indicating that the penalty tax does not apply.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Roth Accounts
</P>
<P>
   Q: I noticed that the IRS recently extended the deadline for
conversions of Roth individual retirement accounts from October 15
to the end of this year. Does that mean I still have time to
convert my traditional IRA to a Roth and spread the taxes over four
years?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm afraid you have things mixed up.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline extension gives taxpayers who already have
converted to Roths a little more time to convert back to
traditional IRAs. They would want to do this if they belatedly
discovered that they were ineligible to convert to a Roth _ if they
exceed the legal income limit, for example _ or if they find that
converting back will help them financially.
</P>
<P>
   It would help them financially if their IRA assets were worth
more when they converted to a Roth than they are now. The taxes
incurred when they converted were based on the size of the assets
at that time. If they convert back to a traditional IRA, they can
nullify the original transaction and pay less tax if they convert
back to a Roth.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year rule you are referring to is no longer available.
It allowed taxpayers who converted to a Roth before the end of last
year to spread payment of the conversion tax over four years. That
was a nice break _ but it is gone.
</P>
<P>
   However, you still can convert your traditional IRA to a Roth,
provided you meet the income requirement _ namely, if your adjusted
gross income for the year is $100,000 or less, regardless of
whether you are single or filing a joint return with a spouse.
</P>
<P>
   The income limits are higher if you create a Roth from scratch,
rather than rolling over a traditional plan. Single taxpayers can
do that if they have incomes no greater than $110,000, while
married taxpayers filing jointly can start a Roth if they have
total income no greater than $160,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mutual Funds
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a couple of mutual funds within the same fund family.
I know I can sell my shares and move the money to another fund in
the family without paying a capital-gains tax. I was wondering: Can
I can sell my shares, take the proceeds and buy stock through my
online brokerage firm without paying a capital-gains tax?
</P>
<P>
   A: No _ assuming that you do indeed have capital gains. If you
do, then this is definitely a taxable event. If you don't, then of
course you won't have to pay a capital-gains tax, and you can use a
capital loss to offset gains from other transactions.
</P>
<P>
   But hold on a minute.
</P>
<P>
   You claim that you can avoid the capital-gains tax if you sell
shares but stay within the same fund family.
</P>
<P>
   Who told you that?
</P>
<P>
   The IRS says that's not true for ordinary accounts. ``Any time
you tell them to sell a share, that's a capital event,'' says
spokesman Jesse Weller. You even have to pay taxes when you make a
profit from the sale of a tax-exempt bond fund _ for example, one
that invests strictly in municipal bonds.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you have your fund shares in a
tax-deferred account _ such as a traditional IRA _ then you won't
have to pay a capital-gains tax if you sell one fund within that
account and buy another. However, when you begin withdrawing money
from a traditional IRA, you will be subject to ordinary income tax.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
