</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASKJEEVES-ASK </SLUG>
 JEEVES _ SF CHRON  
 Ask Jeeves Suffers Big Loss After IPO  &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Following in the footsteps of most Internet startups, Ask Jeeves
Inc. in Emeryville reported a substantial net loss for its first
financial quarter since going public in July.
<P>
   The company, which makes natural-language search-engine
technology, announced yesterday a loss of $9.3 million (37 cents a
share) for its third quarter of 1999, which ended September 30.
That compares with a loss of about $918,000 in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter jumped dramatically to $6.5 million from
$113,000 as the company landed a handful of corporate customers,
including Microsoft, Hewlett-Packard and Martha Stewart Living, who
pay Ask Jeeves anywhere from $300,000 to $1 million to license its
technology.
</P>
<P>
   At www.marthastewart.com, for instance, the technology allows
brides-to-be to ask plain English questions like ``How much should
I pay for my wedding?'' and receive instant answers.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeeves also host a popular consumer site at www.ask.com,
where visitors can ask any number of questions and be directed to
the Web site with the appropriate answer.
</P>
<P>
   Ask.com is the 40th-most-popular Web site in the United States,
with about 4 million people visiting the site in September. The
company generates revenue by running advertisements on the site. It
also has an e-commerce component whereby the site links consumers
to other retail sites and then takes a cut of any online
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from the consumer site outpaced corporate sales by a
ratio of about 2 to 1. But the company said it believes revenue
will be split down the middle by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeeves executives also said in a conference call that they
expect the company to keep losing money until 2002 as it invests in
burnishing its brand name, hiring more sales people and beefing up
its technology infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a breakout quarter for us in corporate services,
which is a more substantial opportunity than we originally
expected,'' said Ask Jeeves chief executive Rob Wrubel, in the
conference call. ``To capture market leadership we need to
accelerate our growth strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors weren't quite as enthusiastic about all the red ink.
The stock dropped $5, or about 6 percent, to $78 in yesterday's
regular trading session. Ask Jeeves reported after the closing
bell, but in after-hours trading, the stock was holding at $78.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe there is no real pressure on Ask Jeeves to make
money immediately. Instead, they said, it's more important for the
company to continue to strengthen its position in the corporate
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Wall Street is not forcing them to be profitable,''
said Stan Corker, an analyst with Emerald Research in Lancaster,
Penn. ``They have the freedom to invest in advertising and brand
recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the company is spending money on such marketing ventures
as sponsoring a float at the Macy's Thanksgiving Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   Corker believes the company's real potential is on the corporate
side of the business. That's because companies usually pay about
$15 every time an employee picks up the phone to answer a customer
service question. With the Ask Jeeves technology, companies can
greatly reduce costs because they no longer have to hire real
people to respond to questions, according to Corker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are starting to put a high valuation on Ask Jeeves
just on the corporate side,'' he said. ``The consumer stuff is just
icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Butler, vice president of Officedepot.com, agrees that Ask
Jeeves is a valuable marketing tool for his company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology gives us an understanding of questions that are
being asked and not getting answered, such as `Do you sell yellow
markers?''' said Butler. ``We can evaluate the data and see what
requests we are getting for items we don't carry, but should.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeeves said it expects to sign several hundred corporate
customers by 2002, up from 25 today. It also predicted that revenue
would hit about $250 million by 2002, with $50 million in profits
that year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
