<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-CHEVRON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Chevron Earnings Up, But More Layoffs Planned  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
San Francisco's Chevron Corp. yesterday announced
higher-than-expected earnings but also plans to cut an additional
400 jobs, raising the total to 3,100. It was the third upward
revision the company has made since December, when it announced
plans to cut 1,000 positions.
<P>
   Spokeswoman Dawn Soper said it is not clear how many Bay Area
jobs will be terminated. The cuts are being made through attrition,
early retirement, buyouts and the sale of subsidiaries, she said,
but would give no specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Also yesterday, Chevron said third-quarter earnings before
special charges rose 82 percent from the same period last year,
coming in at $702 million ($1.07 a share), compared with a First
Call consensus estimate of $1.01.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron said lower operating costs and higher energy prices
produced the increase in profits.
</P>
<P>
   After special charges, net income rose 26 percent, to $582
million (88 cents). Special charges included asset write-downs and
a loss on the sale of Koa Oil Co., a joint venture with Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues increased 32 percent, to $10.2 billion from $7.7
billion in the third quarter of last year. The company is on track
to cut $500 million in operating costs this year.
</P>
<P>
   Soper said the job-cut estimates ``have changed as we've gone
through a more in-depth analysis.'' Some of the Chevron's operating
companies still are evaluating their payroll needs as part of an
ongoing restructuring, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron employed 31,617 people worldwide at the end of
September, down from 33,676 at the end of 1998. The conglomerate
has been trimming payroll for many years; in 1990, for example, it
had 54,208 employees. Those numbers do not include service-station
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industrywide movement,'' said Edward Maran, an
analyst with A.G. Edwards. ``Across the board, every single major
integrated oil company is continuing to reduce its head count.
(Companies) are finding they can cut more people without it
adversely affecting their operations.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past five years, under pressure from Wall Street, oil
companies have changed their focus from production growth to
earnings growth, which necessitates cost-cutting, Maran said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon has been the leader,'' Maran said. ``Over the past five
years, Exxon has not grown its production at all, yet its stock
dramatically outperformed the group because it kept dramatically
increasing its profits.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend has accelerated with recent megamergers. For example,
BP recently acquired Amoco, and Exxon now is buying Mobil. ``The
companies that are left, like Shell, Texaco and Chevron, feel a
great need to compete and show they can cut costs aggressively
without doing a merger,'' Maran said.
</P>
<P>
   Oil stocks generally declined yesterday, even more than the
overall market, despite higher than expected earnings from Chevron
and others. Chevron's stock dropped $3.75, to $90. ``I would have
expected, with such strong earnings, they would have at least
matched &UR;  &LR; or outperformed the market (yesterday),'' Maran said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
