<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-PSTEWART-COX     10-25 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSTEWART-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Runaway plane crashes, kills U.S. Open champ Stewart, 4 others
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Golf champion Payne Stewart, his two agents and two pilots took
off Monday morning from Orlando in a Learjet 35. They were supposed
to climb to 39,000 feet near the Florida Panhandle, then cruise
through Dixie on a leisurely flight to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the silvery-white business plane probably lost cabin
pressure _ rendering its crew and passengers unconscious _ then
exhausted its fuel after nearly four hours on autopilot before
spiraling wildly into a South Dakota cow pasture midday Monday,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The reigning U.S. Open champion and his associates probably died
even before the twin turbofan smashed into the flatlands of Mina,
S.D., as television viewers tracked the flight into the country's
heartland.
</P>
<P>
   The thin air of high altitude and a failure of the 23-year-old
plane's pressurization system are suspect in the deadly flight.
Unless planes are pressurized above 12,000 feet, passengers would
have difficulty breathing and eventually die from a lack of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   In vain, Air Force fighters and flight controllers tried
contacting the pilots as the plane flew steadily northwest to its
doom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have happened gradually,'' Mike Boyd, an aviation
consultant in Golden, Colo., said Monday in an interview. ``The air
gets thin if you're not pressurized, and you start falling asleep.
They were probably dead before they got to South Dakota.''
</P>
<P>
   Controllers cleared the plane to reach a cruising altitude of
39,000 feet as it approached Gainesville, Fla., officials said.
It's about there the plane should have turned left toward Texas. By
then, pilots Michael Kling, 43, and Stephanie Bellegarrigue, 27,
probably had switched on the autopilot.
</P>
<P>
   The flight plan listed five people onboard. However, golf legend
Jack Nicklaus said Monday he feared one of his course designers,
40-year-old Bruce Borland, also was on the plane to get acquainted
with Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Air-traffic controllers made their last contact at Gainesville.
Eventually, the plane reached 45,000 feet as the aircraft burned
fuel, shed weight and climbed. At 41,000 feet, the Learjet is
designed to reach 529 mph.
</P>
<P>
   By the time fighter jets sent to intercept the flight reached
Stewart's plane, the windows had already iced over on the inside,
indicating freezing temperatures and loss of cabin pressure. In an
emergency, the pilots of a Learjet 35 can grab oxygen masks, which
deploy automatically for passengers. The plane also has a warning
system for depressurization.
</P>
<P>
   Even casual golf fans recognized Stewart, who wore knickers and
a tam on the golf course. The 42-year-old Orlando resident won the
U.S. Open during a final-hole duel with Phil Mickelson in June. A
graduate of Southern Methodist University in Dallas, Stewart was
expected in Houston today for practice rounds for the Tour
Championship, the Professional Golfers Association last tournament
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous loss for the entire golfing community and
all of sports,'' PGA Tour Commissioner Tim Finchem said. ``He will
always be remembered as a very special competitor and one who
contributed enormously to the positive image of professional
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's agents Robert Fraley and Van Ardan died in the plane,
said family spokesman Bill Curry. Fraley was chief executive
officer of Leader Enterprises Inc., and Ardan was president of the
sports management company.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is survived by his wife, Tracey, daughter Chelsea, 13,
and son Aaron, 10. A 20-year veteran of the PGA tour, Stewart
proclaimed his religious devotion after winning the U.S. Open for
the second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the fact that my faith in God is so much stronger
and I'm so much more at peace with myself than I've ever been in my
life,'' Stewart said. ``Where I was with my faith last year and
where I am now is leaps and bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunset Aviation of Orlando, Fla., which provided the pilots for
Monday's chartered flight, had listed the aircraft for sale on its
Web site. The ad said the plane had more than 10,000 hours total
air time, 7,523 landings, an executive door, drag chute and
auxiliary cabin heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This aircraft is in premium condition inside and out,'' the
online ad said. ``It has high quality paint and interior in a
complimenting gray and burgundy color scheme. . . .The maintenance
performed has been meticulous. . . . All log books are complete and
up to date.''
</P>
<P>
   When the plane veered from its prefiled path, the Federal
Aviation Administration notified the Air Force. Officials
dispatched a fighter from Tyndall Air Force Base on a training
flight near the Florida Panhandle. Two fighters from Florida's
Eglin Air Force Base, also in the Panhandle, then followed before a
pair of Air National Guard F-16s from Tulsa, Okla., took over.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Dunn, the owner of Montana's Bar in Mina, S.D., had
tracked the flight on television. He had heard the broadcast
speculation that the autopilot was switched on and reports that no
one had responded to radio messages. That meant everyone was
unconscious, perhaps dead. The bar owner stepped outside and
watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started flopping and going crazy,'' Dunn said in a
telephone interview. ``Then it just came straight down.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn jumped into his Jeep and was one of the first people to
reach the scene. He called 911.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them there was no need to get real excited about
sending ambulances because everyone was already dead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The descent took about 12 seconds, Dunn guessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a hole in the ground,'' he said. ``Pieces of
aircraft and body parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Olson lives on a Mina farm six miles west of the crash site.
She stepped on her deck and peered through binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw two dark jets,'' Olson said in an interview. ``While I
was watching, I saw a flash, not a fire, but a silver-and-white
flash. Then it came down.''
</P>
<P>
   Postal carrier Lorie Heinz said she climbed out of her Plymouth
minivan during her route when she heard a loud rumble. Fighter jets
thundered overhead about 600 feet. Not till later did she know a
plane was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two planes went by,'' Heinz said on the telephone. ``God,
that's pretty low, I thought. Holy smokes. Then I saw a white
streak. I thought they had dropped something out of their plane. It
flew straight then it nosedived. Then it did two twirls to the
left. It was spinning.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Heinz felt the ground shake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the debris fly,'' she said. ``It was smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the FAA and the National Transportation Safety
Board headed for the crash site Monday. Advisers informed President
Clinton about the accident during a meeting with his economic
staff.
</P>
<P>
   A computer check of the FAA incident data system report showed
one citation on the plane. In 1986, the pilot made an unauthorized
turn during departure from Cincinnati's Lunken Field and caused a
traffic conflict. There were no passengers on board. The pilot was
not identified.
</P>
<P>
   The Learjet 35 has an ``excellent'' safety record, said Pete
West, senior vice president of government and public affairs for
the National Business Aviation Association in Washington. The group
monitors safety issues for businesses that operate planes for
executive commuting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very, very unique situation,'' West said. ``It's
interesting that the Air Force aircraft said they couldn't see
anything. . . . If the autopilot is on, the plane flies until the
fuel runs out.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
