<SLUG> BC-AGILENT-AGILENT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Agilent Sets Terms for an Initial Offering  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Agilent Technologies, the subsidiary of Hewlett-Packard Co.
focusing on test and measurement devices, has set the terms of its
initial public offering of 57 million shares, intended to raise an
estimated $1.1 billion.
<P>
   The company's shares will debut in a projected range of $19 to
$22 apiece, according to a Securities and Exchange Commission
filing.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent spokeswoman Amy Flores said the IPO likely will be held
by the end of the year. However, she said a formula has not yet
been determined for allotting Agilent stock to existing
Hewlett-Packard shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard will retain about 87 percent of Agilent's common
stock. Holders of stock in the Palo Alto computer giant can expect
to receive Agilent shares by the middle of next year, Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard said in March that it will spin off its
noncomputer operations to allow the company to bolster its core
computer and printer businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent, which is slated to begin operating on November 1, will
have annual sales of about $8 billion and will absorb approximately
43,000 Hewlett-Packard employees. The company will be run by Ned
Barnholt, 56, who has been with Hewlett-Packard for more than 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Mona Eraiba, an analyst with Gruntal &AMP; Co. in New York, said the
spin-off ``definitely unleashes the value that Agilent has.''
</P>
<P>
   She said investors probably will find that Agilent's stock will
show more short-term growth than Hewlett-Packard's, though the
parent company will remain a stronger long-term investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Agilent's stock will certainly go higher, and this
will help HP's stock,'' Eraiba said.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard closed yesterday at $76.13, up 25 cents from
Friday. The company's stock is well off its 52-week high of
$118.44, buffeted by general weakness in the technology sector,
last month's earthquake in Taiwan and an expected increase in
semiconductor prices, as well as last week's profit warning from
rival International Business Machines Corp.
</P>
<P>
   According to its SEC filing, Agilent will have 437 million
shares outstanding after the IPO. A share price of $20.50 _ the
middle of the projected offering range _ would give the company an
initial market value of about $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent accounted for roughly 17 percent of Hewlett-Packard's
total revenue of $47 billion last year. However, investors and
analysts seldom take notice of the parent company's production of
diagnostic electronics and testing gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one owns HP for that business,'' said Jim Berlino, an
analyst with CIBC World Markets in New York. ``The fact that
they're spinning it off is an enormous positive. It will make the
HP story less confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hewlett-Packard still isn't winning any prizes for
warp-speed responsiveness to market changes, Berlino gave high
marks to the company's new chief executive, Carly Fiorina, who he
said ``isn't shying away from any of the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Agilent's Flores said work is continuing on the new company's
headquarters, being built on the site where the original
Hewlett-Packard building stood in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 senior executives will move into the space by next
May, she said. Other Agilent operations will remain in their
present locations in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be answering the phones as Agilent Technologies as of
next Monday,'' Flores observed, ``but we'll still be a subsidiary
of Hewlett-Packard until the IPO.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that employees generally have reacted favorably to the
new company's name, which was concocted by San Francisco brand
consultant Landor Associates and drew mixed reviews from
professional linguists.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem happy with it,'' Flores said, ``now that they
realize that not everything has to mean something.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
