<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-EXCITE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 ExciteAtHome to Buy Online Card Company  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Bluemountainarts.com, the folksy online greeting card company that
got its start in a Boulder couple's attic, said yesterday that it
will be acquired by ExciteAtHome Corp. for $780 million in cash and
stock.
<P>
   ExciteAtHome of Redwood City said it is buying privately held
Blue Mountain to cash in on the card company's loyal following. The
site, which lets users send free greeting cards via e-mail, is one
of the most heavily visited on the Web, pulling in more than 9
million unique users per month.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome, which provides Web content and high-speed Internet
access, said it's buying Blue Mountain to generate advertising and
e-commerce revenues and lure subscribers to its high-speed cable
modem business.
</P>
<P>
   It will continue to offer Blue Mountain cards at no cost and for
every occasion _ from National Pig Day (March 1) to birthday cards
for pets.
</P>
<P>
   The variety and price _ free _ are two reasons why Blue Mountain
was the fourth-busiest e-commerce site in September. Users return
to the site an average of two times per month.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition will raise ExciteAtHome from the
sixth-most-visited site overall to No.5, knocking Disney's Go
Network down a notch, according to research firm Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its popularity, Blue Mountain had no aggressive
e-commerce or advertising strategy. ExciteAtHome thinks that it can
use Blue Mountain's heavy traffic to sell more ads and create
online shopping opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a person sending a free birthday card from Blue
Mountain might be enticed to buy a gift online from one of Excite's
retail partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every greeting card represents an event-based commerce
opportunity, whether it's a birthday or a Bar Mitzvah,'' said
ExciteAtHome President George Bell.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell said the main reason for buying Blue Mountain was to
persuade its customers to switch from their dial-up Internet
service provider to AtHome's cable modem service.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the reasons AtHome bought Excite, a major Web
portal, last spring. Company officials said they're committed to
acquiring more Web sites to attract cable-modem users.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main benefit is that it expands the population that are
exposed to ExciteAtHome, and if Excite can utilize that customer
base to market its broadband service, so much the better,'' said
Drake Johnstone, an analyst with Davenport &AMP; Co. in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Mountain site grew out of a traditional greeting card
business run by Susan Polis Schutz and Stephen Schutz. The pair
started Blue Mountain Arts in 1970 by selling silk-screened posters
and greeting cards door-to-door. Three years ago, their son, Jared,
persuaded them to start an Internet site _ Bluemountainarts.com _
as a hobby, and the three ran it out of their attic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It grew beyond all our wildest expectations,'' said Jared
Schutz, Blue Mountain's executive director. ``It struck a chord in
people, and it resonated with something in the consumer psyche.''
</P>
<P>
   Jared Schutz said the company was trying to decide whether to
sell the business or take it public. The owners went with
ExciteAtHome, he said, because Excite agreed to continue offering
the cards for free and shared a similar vision for the company.
</P>
<P>
   The Schutzes are keeping Blue Mountain Arts, the traditional
greeting card company, and are selling only the online division.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Stevens, an executive vice president with ExciteAtHome,
said the Schutz family ``will continue to work with us in a
creative role ... losing that would be a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome will issue about 11 million shares, valued at about
$430 million, and pay $350 million in cash for Blue Mountain.
ExciteAtHome also will assume all outstanding employee options. The
deal is expected to close before the end of the year, the companies
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
