<HEADER>
A8214 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ANTITRUST-ANTITRUST_S     10-25 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTITRUST-ANTITRUST </SLUG>
 _ SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE  
 Proposed Hospital Merger Goes on Trial  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
State Attorney General Bill Lockyer asked a federal judge in San
Francisco yesterday to block the proposed merger of the East Bay's
two largest hospitals, lest they create a ``hegemony'' capable of
raising health insurance rates in Oakland and Berkeley.
<P>
   Lockyer's remarks came on the opening day of a trial on the
proposed merger of Oakland's Summit Medical Center with Berkeley's
Alta Bates Medical Center. Alta Bates is part of Sutter Health, a
chain of 26 hospitals mostly in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer sued Sutter, Summit and Alta Bates in August, alleging
that the combination would give them a 48 percent share of the East
Bay hospital market, enough to institute a post-merger price
increase of at least 5 to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Summit attorney Maureen McGuirl urged District Judge Maxine
Chesney to permit the merger, arguing that it was the only way to
prevent Summit from running out of cash by the end of the year and
laying off 200 workers, or 9 percent of its staff.
</P>
<P>
   Chesney, who has scheduled a four-day trial, listened as
attorneys for the two sides laid out starkly different versions of
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The state asserted that Summit could have merged with a
different hospital chain and continued to compete with Alta Bates,
its main rival.
</P>
<P>
   The Sutter side argued that a merger of the two nonprofit
hospitals would create one healthy system serving Oakland and
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Chesney has not said when she would decide the case, although
attorneys think she will issue her decision before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer challenged the merger after the Federal Trade Commission
ended a long investigation without taking action. Legal sources
said the FTC ducked the case because the federal courts have been
reluctant to block any hospital mergers, particularly those in
urban areas served by many hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief opening remarks, Lockyer acknowledged that this is
the first challenge to an urban-hospital merger in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the antitrust laws to have real meaning it's not enough
that they be applied only to rural areas,'' Lockyer said. ``They
have to be made to apply in the inner East Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer's deputy, antitrust specialist John Donhoff, showed a
map of the Bay Area dotted with 30 hospitals, but said the merger
would give Summit and Alta Bates 48 percent of the market from
Pinole south to Union City, between the bay and the hills.
</P>
<P>
   He said patients would be trapped in this area by traffic and
commute patterns, and unable to switch to cheaper hospitals outside
the area if Summit and Alta Bates used their ``hegemony'' to raise
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can't ask a pregnant mother to go on BART to have her
baby,'' Donhoff argued.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter attorney George Manning ridiculed that assertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe the plaintiff's market (definition), you
believe people still travel in Conestoga wagons, and no one is
going over the hills because they're too high, and you have to
build a boat to go over the bay,'' Manning said.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to prove that Summit still has an alternative to
combining with Alta Bates, state attorneys called as a witness Eric
Tuckman, a vice president with Tenet Healthcare Corp., the nation's
second-largest for-profit hospital chain.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet offered to acquire Summit in March 1998 but was rebuffed.
When asked whether Tenet was still interested in Summit, Tuckman
said ``the hospital still has strategic importance to Tenet and we
would certainly take a look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   But under cross-examination from Summit attorney McGuirl,
Tuckman said Tenet's offer had been conditioned on getting a closer
look at Summit's books, and that he was not in a position to make
``a quantitative offer'' for Summit before considering the
hospital's current financial state.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's trial offered a rare glimpse at the closed-door
deals that dictate prices in the modern hospital market.
</P>
<P>
   The state called Curtis Terry, a vice president from Blue Cross,
to testify about how, in 1997, Sutter had used its market clout to
force the HMO to negotiate one standard payment rate for all of
Sutter's hospitals in Northern California _ instead of negotiating
with each hospital individually.
</P>
<P>
   Terry said that if Summit became part of Sutter, Blue Cross
would immediately have to pay the higher hospital rates that Sutter
has already negotiated at other Sutter hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But under cross-examination from Sutter attorneys, Terry
admitted that other hospital chains, including Tenet, also have
forced Blue Cross to negotiate payment plans that cover every
hospital in the chain.
</P>
<P>
   The state also submitted evidence that the merger is opposed by
nine of 14 health plans serving the East Bay, including Aetna U.S.
Healthcare and the Alameda Alliance for Health, which provides
insurance to poor families. The state, only four health plans,
notably Kaiser and HealthNet, support the merger, with one
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   To expedite the trial, Chesney has limited each side to a few
witnesses. The state will resume its case today by calling James
Langenfeld, former director of antitrust for the FTC, to support
the state's contention a merged Summit and Alta Bates would have
the power to force price increases that would be passed on to HMO
customers in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Sutter and Summit will get a chance to present three
witnesses _ economist Margaret Guerin-Calvert, hospital expert
Bruce Den Uyl, and Summit board member Claude Hutchinson _ to
bolster their case that the current merger deal complies with
federal antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
