<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8220 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BEAR-BEAR_SANFRANCISC     10-25 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAR-BEAR </SLUG>
 _ SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE  
 Alternatives to U.S. Stocks Could Safeguard Your Portfolio  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The aging bull market has suffered some hard knocks in recent
months, leading many investors to wonder whether it finally might
be time to seek an alternative to U.S. stocks.
<P>
   With interest rates edging higher, with inflation warnings once
again in vogue, with market leaders like IBM hobbled by earnings
problems and with the Dow Jones industrial average zigging and
zagging nearly 10 percent below the high reached two months ago,
the bull run of the late '90s no longer looks like a sure thing as
we stagger toward the next century.
</P>
<P>
   But if U.S. stocks scare you, what are the alternatives?
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the stock market has soared so high during
the past five years is that investors haven't come up with a viable
substitute. They have continued to invest their 401(k)
contributions and other money in stocks and stock mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, despite the stock market's hair-raising performance
during the summer and fall, the old bull may have enough life left
to charge ahead. some more. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``I don't believe in trying to time the market,'' says Norm
Boone of Boone Financial Advisors in San Francisco. ``If you're
feeling like the market is too volatile, you probably shouldn't be
a stock investor in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you fear that the market is overpriced and investors
are facing a doomsday scenario and if you absolutely demand an
alternative, three choices come to mind: gold, fixed-income
securities and foreign stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In times of stock-market uncertainty, many eyes turn to gold
because of its centuries-long history as a coveted medium of
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Gold also is supposed to be a classic hedge against inflation
and calamitous political upheaval _ in case you are worried about
Y2K, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Priced above $800 an ounce during the inflationary spiral of the
early 1980s, gold plunged into the mid-$200 range during the
low-inflation 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   However, late last month and early this month, its price surged
by more than $80 per ounce, to as high as $337, though mainly for
technical reasons: The European central bankers canceled a plan to
sell off much of their gold reserves, which would have burdened the
market with too much supply.
</P>
<P>
   Gold since has settled back near the $300 mark _ but if you
think it might resume its upswing, there are multiple ways to
invest in it.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy stock in gold-mining companies, on the premise that
rising gold prices will make them more profitable.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy gold directly _ most conveniently in the form of
coins issued by the U.S. and foreign governments, containing
exactly one ounce of gold apiece. Dealers say they have been doing
a land-office business in gold coins lately.
</P>
<P>
   You can speculate in gold futures _ an extremely risky venture
suitable only for investors with deep pockets and cast-iron
stomachs. By putting down slightly more than $1,000 on margin, you
can buy or sell a 100-ounce gold contract, worth more than $30,000
at current price levels.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, and the price of gold rises, then you can sell
the contract at a profit. On the other hand, if the market moves
against you, your entire margin deposit could be wiped out in a few
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream financial advisers ridicule gold, considering it
quirky, extremist and, worst of all, not necessarily profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Boone contends that gold has little fundamental value. It isn't
backed by corporate earnings, brand names and goodwill. Its value
hinges largely on psychology _ sort of like an Internet stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you're doing is hoping that someone else will be willing
to pay you more for it than you paid,'' he observes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Safe, But Small Returns
</P>
<P>
   If gold isn't the answer, what about fixed-income securities,
such as U.S. Treasuries, money-market mutual funds or bank
certificates of deposit?
</P>
<P>
   They are all safe enough _ particularly Treasuries, which are
widely regarded as the safest investments on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   But even after the recent upticks in interest rates,
fixed-incomes still offer paltry investment returns.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last week, U.S. Treasuries were yielding a bit
more than 6 percent annually, while the highest-yielding
money-market funds were paying about 5.5 percent and the
highest-yielding five-year CDs were at less than 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those yields don't have much appeal for investors who have come
to believe _ based on the experience of the past five years _ that
the stock market goes up 20 percent or more every year.
</P>
<P>
   Even more-realistic investors _ those who know that the
historical average stock-market gain is only about 10 percent
annually, including reinvestment of dividends _ will look down
their noses at 5, 6 or even 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   They already have built expectations of a 10 percent annual
return into their retirement planning. They are counting on that
from their 401(k) plans and their individual retirement accounts.
To accept barely more than half that much even for a short while
would keep them on the job longer than they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, interest rates eventually could rise well above their
present levels, particularly if the Federal Reserve fails to
contain inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But that would be all the more reason not to buy most
fixed-income securities now. You would be locking in interest rates
that are lower than you could get later _ and with Treasuries or
other bonds, you would suffer declining prices, as well, because
bond prices move in the opposite direction from rates.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves foreign stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Buying foreign stocks _ or foreign-stock mutual funds, which
would be the wiser course for Americans who aren't experts on
overseas markets _ has made sense in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Burton Malkiel and Jianping Mei point out in their book,
``Global Bargain Hunting,'' that the performance of foreign stock
markets often runs counter to the performance of U.S. markets.
That's at least partly because the economies of other nations
aren't necessarily in synch with the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   The authors show, using historical data, that a portfolio
holding both U.S. and foreign stocks usually produces a better
investment performance over the long run than a U.S.-only
portfolio. In addition, the performance tends to be less volatile
from year to year in a mixed portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   So, whenever the U.S. market is in the dumps, you might be able
to patch things up by mixing foreign stocks into your portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Asian stocks in particular would have been a great idea
at the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
   While the U.S. market, as measured by the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index, is ahead by only 6 percent since the end of 1998, the
principal market indexes of Korea, Japan and Hong Kong are ahead 47
percent, 35 percent and 28 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Many investment advisers warn that even if the U.S. stock market
scares you, it might not be advisable to do anything as radical as
switching to other types of investments.
</P>
<P>
   The market invariably comes back from slumps, they say, and the
current slump might not turn out to be all that bad. Anyone willing
to risk money in the stock market, their reasoning goes, should get
used to the fact that stock markets have their downs as well as ups
and that nobody can predict them consistently.
</P>
<P>
   Financial planner Richard DelMonte of DelMonte Group in Danville
says: ``I'm not telling anybody to change their mix at all. You
should not be making any changes just because of short-term
turbulence.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Turner, president of Pring Turner Capital Corp. in San
Ramon, believes that stocks might fall another 10 percent from
their current levels.
</P>
<P>
   But to hedge against that, he suggests, investors could cut
their exposure to the market. ``If you are 100 percent invested,
you might want to reduce it to 90 percent or 80 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   That way, if the pessimism is unfounded and prices resume their
climb, you won't completely miss out on the gains.
</P>
<P>
   Turner says you also might want to phase out of high-volatility,
high-risk stocks _ such as Internet and technology issues, or
stocks that have shot up after recent initial public offerings _
and into ``something of high quality, like PG&AMP;E.''
</P>
<P>
   Other advisers recommend that investors keep their U.S. stocks
and buy more if the markets slides more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have at least a 10-year time horizon, then you should
pray for a down market,'' says Kurt Brouwer, of Brouwer &AMP;
Janachowski in Tiburon. ``You should use such an opportunity to add
to your account.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
