<HEADER>
A8222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-STEWART-APPRECIATION-     10-25 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEWART-APPRECIATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOLFER AT THE TOP OF HIS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He achieved victories that men in his profession can only dream
about, US Open titles that had cruelly escaped the grasp of some of
golf's greatest legends. But what spoke volumes about the makeup of
Payne Stewart was what he considered his greatest triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``1982 at Quad City. And that will never change, no matter how
many _ if I'm fortunate enough to win more majors or more golf
tournaments. The 1982 Quad Cities will be my most cherished
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The words were spoken a few months ago, on Father's Day, just
after Stewart had made one of the most dramatic putts in golf
history, a 15-footer to save par on the 72d hole of the US Open.
With that putt, at the fabled Pinehurst No. 2 in Pinehurst, N.C.,
Stewart became just the 18th player to win the US Open more than
once and earned a lofty spot in the game's history.
</P>
<P>
   The paycheck for his Pinehurst win was $625,000, but it couldn't
buy its way to the top spot in Stewart's heart. That remained the
1982 Quad City Classic, his first professional win, which came with
his father in attendance. William Stewart would die a few years
later, but father and son always had Quad City.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was there and we had a good cry on the green,'' said
Stewart, a refreshingly honest and emotional player who used to
joke that he cried easily.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the tears were in his memory.
</P>
<P>
   One of the world's most accomplished golfers, certainly one of
the sport's very special people, the 42-year-old Stewart was among
five people killed in a jet crash in South Dakota. His is survived
by his wife, Tracey, a daughter, Chelsea, 13, and a son, Aaron, 10,
not to mention countless golf fans who respected Stewart for his
determined style of play, his candor, and his willingness to stand
out from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   He did the latter by wearing his trademark knickers, which set
him apart from hundreds of colleagues who dressed so much alike.
Stewart donned the knickers a few years after turning pro in 1979
and was rarely seen in competition without them.
</P>
<P>
   They became part of his ``mystique,'' said Mark Lye, who broke
into pro golf in the early 1980s. But Lye and others felt Stewart
always enjoyed a residual effect _ when he left the course, slipped
into jeans, and went out into the public, no one recognized him.
Dinners were peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he liked that,'' said Lye.
</P>
<P>
   What he liked even more was spirited competition. Growing up in
Springfield, Mo., Stewart was introduced to the game by his father,
who had a passion for golf. It rubbed off on the son, who won the
Missouri State Amateur and earned a golf scholarship to Southern
Methodist University in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart possessed a classic golf swing that was the envy of some
of the world's most polished players, but he was not saturated in
talent. Everything he got out of his game was earned through dogged
determination and a focus that sometimes hurt his image. It
bordered on cockiness early in his career, and as he grew older and
more mature, Stewart conceded that he had rubbed people the wrong
way when he first turned pro.
</P>
<P>
   After breaking into pro golf on the Australasia Tour (he met
Tracey, an Australian, during this time), Stewart returned to the
US PGA Tour in 1981 and though he won three times in the next eight
years, his reputation was that of a golfer who couldn't get the job
done; 18 times he finished second or third.
</P>
<P>
   That wore on him, he would say years later, and led to some
behavior he regretted. Like an outward show of joy (a serious
breach of golf etiquette) as Mike Reid fell apart down the stretch
in the 1989 PGA Championship, thus giving Stewart his first major
championship.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tour Championship a few months later, Stewart should have
won, but he played badly down the stretch, lost a playoff to Tom
Kite, then neglected to shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He overcame all that,'' said Chuck Cook, Stewart's swing coach
for nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne accomplished a lot of things this year, a lot of things
that had been hanging over his head, like not being able to finish
off a tournament. He cemented his reputation professionally.''
</P>
<P>
   He did that by winning at Pebble Beach earlier this year, then
silencing all the critics at Pinehurst. Stewart had won the US Open
in 1991, but people paid more attention to the fact that he had let
chances slip away in 1993 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   When he took a lead into the final round of this year's Open,
Stewart was setting himself for another disappointment. Or so most
of us thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard on television before that one of the detriments of
Payne Stewart's golf game is he's not that good a putter,'' said
Stewart. He flashed a smile as he talked in the Pinehurst media
room minutes after that now-famous 15-footer. ``Well, maybe I
squelched those rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the process he had achieved another personal goal for
1999: He had made the Ryder Cup team for the fifth time.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Stewart was part of the US squad that defeated
Europe at The Country Club in Brookline in one of the most stirring
golf competitions ever staged. He did not play particularly well,
overshadowed by younger, more gifted players such as Tiger Woods
and David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   But with a circus atmosphere enveloping the matches, it was left
to Stewart to bring civility to it all. With the outcome of the
Ryder Cup decided, he conceded his match to Scotland's Colin
Montgomerie late in the competition, when unruly spectators were
feasting on the European. ``We won and he didn't need to go through
it,'' said Stewart. ``(The match) didn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   His gracious act did. It reminded all of us that the idea was
spirited competition, not just a test of golf skills.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons did not stop there. When he returned home, Stewart
with very little fanfare donated $500,000 to the First Baptist
Church in Orlando, where his children attend school and where
Chelsea, though just a seventh-grader, plays first base for the
school's varsity softball team. He then organized a party that
raised another $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 career victories that brought fame and fortune were
tributes to his golf talents, said Cook, but Tracey, Chelsea, and
Aaron were daily reminders of what was important in Stewart's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``His children were raising him religiously,'' said Cook. ``He
was doing a lot of things with them. He had been raised that way
and he got back in touch with that. That's what gave him a
peaceness, a calmness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
