<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-NYT     10-25 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HO-HUM. SLOW DAY AT THE OFFICE AS MAJOR INDEXES DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stock prices weakened a bit Monday as traders in large
capitalization issues took some profits following last week's
bounce in major averages. Market interest rates, which moved higher
in the morning but later retreated and closed little changed,
provided another source of instability.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, traders said the session was an
unexceptional day at the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very slow day,'' said Bill Allyn, head of listed
trading at Jeffries &AMP; Co. ``Barring some big outside event, I think
the market will stay in a trading range for the remainder of the
year. But one more interest rate increase before year-end could be
a negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Worries about higher interest rates, which could put a crimp in
future earnings, helped to drag down the Dow Jones industrial
average.
</P>
<P>
   Despite good earnings reports from a number of companies that
are included in the Dow, the blue-chip index fell 120.32, or 1.15
percent, to 10,349.93.
</P>
<P>
   American Express, Exxon and Chevron, which all reported
quarterly earnings that either met or exceeded Wall Street's
forecasts, fell by 2 points or more.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index slipped 8.02, or 0.62
percent, to 1,293.63, pulled down by weakness in oil, financial
service and drug stocks. The Nasdaq composite index barely budged,
dropping 0.57, to 2,815.95. Declines in issues like Intel and
Qualcomm were offset by big gains in Internet stocks like
Amazon.com and E-Bay. And the Russell 2000 index of small stocks
slipped 0.93, or 0.22 percent, to 417.76.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was light, and declining issues again outnumbered those
that gained in price.
</P>
<P>
   Richard McCabe, chief market analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.,
said the fact that the broader market continued to fare poorly
suggested that additional declines might be in the offing soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rally we had last week was the weakest in terms of depth
and participation,'' he said. ``The Dow, the S&AMP;P 500 and the Nasdaq
were all up between 3 percent and 5 percent. Yet the
advance/decline figures for the week showed more declining issues
than advancing ones on all three exchanges. It's the same old
story: the big stocks rally and the rest of the market
languishes.''
</P>
<P>
   American Express and J.P. Morgan led the Dow lower.
</P>
<P>
   American Express fell 5\, to 143 ]. Traders sold the stock even
though the company reported that third-quarter earnings rose 14
percent, a performance that met consensus forecasts. J.P. Morgan
shed 5 7/16, to 120 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Both stocks, along with other big financial service firms,
posted sharp gains last Friday after the Senate Banking Committee
reached agreement on legislation that would overhaul the financial
services industry.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon and Chevron both fell despite posting healthy earnings.
Other oil stocks fell in sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon lost 2~, to 74. Chevron fell 3}, to 90, even though its
earnings were better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, MidAmerican Energy Holdings jumped 6[, to 33], after
Berkshire Hathaway said it was leading an investor group that would
buy the company for $35.05 a share. The transaction would be the
first energy purchase for Berkshire.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks, which fell during the morning as long-term bond
yields touched 6.40 percent, rallied as long-term rates fell.
</P>
<P>
   Gains in stocks like Immunex, which rose 4[, to 58 1/16,
Amazon.com and E-Bay helped to push TheStreet.com's Internet sector
index up by 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com gained 4[, to 82}. And E-Bay jumped 8\, to 150~.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
