<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8229 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-     10-25 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SIGNS ONE SPENDING BILL BUT VETOES ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout and to add new material; story is
complete in one take) (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton signed into law a $268-billion
spending bill for the Pentagon on Monday, avoiding the risk of a
split among Democrats at the very moment that the parties are
speeding toward the end of their budget battle. At the same time,
he vetoed a separate spending bill for some other federal agencies,
assailing Republicans for making ``wrong choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed the Pentagon spending bill in part out of doubt
that Democrats could sustain a veto. The Pentagon bill was popular
and had originally passed the House by an overwhelming vote of
372-55.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the minority leader, had pledged
to fight vigorously to deliver the 146 Democratic votes needed to
sustain a veto. But other senior Democrats had expressed
reservations about a veto that could make them vulnerable to attack
on national security and were threatening to vote with the
Republicans against a veto.
</P>
<P>
   Signing the bill also allows Clinton and the Democrats to focus
attention on issues they are comfortable with _ such as education,
police and the environment _ rather than getting into a dispute
over national security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Monday said that he could have prevailed on a veto
but that ``it would have been a close call.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes 13 annual spending bills to put the budget in place;
the president and Republicans are now struggling over five of the
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Clinton signed the military spending package, his
remarks about the Pentagon bill were decidedly mixed. The president
criticized it for including budgetary gimmicks and pork-barrel
projects. But he said he had concluded that it contained crucial
elements, such as a 4.8 percent pay raise for the military. ``I
cannot allow our national security needs to be held hostage to this
budget battle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has struck a particularly combative tone over plans by
the Republican leaders in Congress to attach an across-the-board
spending cut, of up to 1.4 percent, to the year's final spending
bill. The move is a last effort by Republicans to put in place a
budget that does not touch Social Security reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The president contended that the across-the-board cut would lead
to layoffs in the military and harm education and environmental
programs, a charge that Republicans deny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not allow Congress to raise its own pay and fund its
pork-barrel projects and still make devastating cuts in everything
from education to child nutrition to the FBI,''Clinton said in
announcing that he had signed the Pentagon bill but vetoed a
measure funding the Commerce, State and Justice Departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not sign any budget that puts special interests above
the national interest,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The president's balancing act set the framework for the endgame
of the year's budget struggle, a fight whose outcome both parties
believe is likely to significantly influence the course of the
congressional elections in 2000, particularly in the narrowly
divided House.
</P>
<P>
   The final showdown could come as early as Friday, with the
expiration of legislation that temporarily has kept the government
running through the first weeks of the 2000 federal fiscal year
that began Oct. 1. Clinton said on Monday that he would sign
another stopgap bill to keep government operations running, but he
asked that Republican show good faith in negotiating a final deal.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders praised Clinton and tried to set him
apart from the House Democrats led by Gephardt , whom they accused
of wanting partisan confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has rejected the gridlock strategy of Dick
Gephardt,'' said Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House majority whip.
Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority leader, said he
thought the president's action would make it ``that much easier''
to negotiate a compromise on the budget.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the president's decision to sign the Pentagon bill gave
the Republicans something they had wanted: a fight over a limited
number of bills, which scaled back the possibility that Clinton
could score big wins in negotiations over an omnibus spending
package, as has happened in his past confrontations with the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   One of those is a $35 billion bill to pay for the Commerce,
Justice and State Departments, which the president vetoed on
Monday. He faulted the measure because it failed to provide money
for his goal of creating 50,000 new community police officers and
because it did not provide for dues and arrears to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   While the Democrats have traditionally protected Social
Security, the Republicans this year have pledged that they will cut
spending without following the tradition in Congress of using some
of the Social Security reserves.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, they have to hold spending on the 13 bills to $592
billion. They say they will meet their goal with the
across-the-board spending cut. Republican leaders had announced
Friday the cut would be 1.4 percent, but key senators want it to be
smaller, and it was still being worked on on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans dismissed Clinton's assertion that the across-the
board reduction would mean cuts in programs and said they were
still increasing spending in some key education areas. ``That's
just demogoguery,'' DeLay said. ``It's about waste. You don't think
we can find enough waste in this place to find one percent?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
