<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-STEWART-REAX-COX     10-25 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEWART-REAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida friends of Stewart pay tribute to golf great
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ In an All-American town with an apple-pie image,
he was a squeaky clean hero who gave money to his church and other
charities.
</P>
<P>
   In a sometimes smug sport filled with cookie-cutter stars, he
stood out for his attire, his demeanor and his sheer enthusiasm for
the game.
</P>
<P>
   In an age of snooty, greedy athletes surrounded by agents and
handlers, he was disarmingly genuine and generous, never too busy
to stop and spend a minute with every-day folks and fans.
</P>
<P>
   Such were the tributes being paid Monday to Payne Stewart as
word filtered around Central Florida that the 42-year-old PGA star
had died in the crash of a private jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just so unbelievable for everyone in Orlando,'' said
Charles Davis, chairman of the National Car Rental Walt Disney
World Classic, a PGA event based in Orlando that just concluded
Sunday. ``We use that word, 'charisma' too often, but Payne really
had it. He was just a super guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who played his college golf at Southern Methodist
University in Texas, moved to Orlando some 20 years ago after
breaking into the ranks of the PGA tour.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn by Florida's year-round golf and a growing array of fine
new courses surrounding Orlando's vacation mecca, he quickly became
an anchor of the region's professional golf community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Team Orlando,'' as it has come to be called in recent years,
now includes such PGA luminaries as Tiger Woods, Mark O'Meara, Nick
Faldo and Scott Hoch.
</P>
<P>
   But while many stars with his success live insulated from the
public, Stewart seemed to be striving to be known as a regular guy.
</P>
<P>
   Active in his church, he was known for his generosity to
charities and his willingness to help his adopted hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved children, he loved to be that example for young
people, the kind of person they could look up to,'' said Orlando
Mayor Glenda Hood, who just two weeks ago presented Stewart with a
key to the city for his civic work.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart recently gave $500,000 to First Baptist Church of
Orlando. After winning the Bay Hill Invitational in 1987, he
donated his entire check to Florida Hospital in Orlando in memory
of his father, who had recently died.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart also was a regular at Orlando Magic basketball games,
and seemed widely respected and admired in the community.
</P>
<P>
   He lived west of downtown Orlando near Bay Hill, an exclusive
golf-and-residential development where tour legend Arnold Palmer
hosts an annual PGA event.
</P>
<P>
   After word about the crash reached the airwaves, a steady stream
of visitors drove down the wooded two-lane street to Stewart's home
Monday. A police officer was stationed outside the sprawling
estate's heavy iron gate. The home, hidden behind lush vegetation,
could not be seen from the street.
</P>
<P>
   Several local PGA players had participated in a charity event at
Bay Hill on Monday, and many left the course immediately upon
hearing of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Tour pros Ernie Els, Mark O'Meara, Lee Janzen and Scott Hoch all
drove to the Stewart home to console Stewart's widow, Tracey. The
couple have two children, Chelsea, 13, and Aaron, 10.
</P>
<P>
   After missing the cut at the Disney tournament over the weekend,
Stewart reportedly used the free time to watch his son play in a
Pop Warner League football game.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's impact in Central Florida could be gauged by the
comments on Orlando's all-sports talk radio station, which was
filled with tributes from admiring fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at the Disney Classic a couple of years ago and wanted
his autograph,'' said one fan who telephoned the program. ``He came
up to us and we didn't even have to ask. He rubbed my 5-year-old on
the head and said, 'How you doing?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the local tournament chairman, told the radio program
that Stewart was unfailingly polite and generous with his time _
something not universal in the world of high-paid, high-pressure
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw Payne have a bad day,'' he said. ``If you needed
something, you could ask him and if he could do it, he would. There
was never any of this, 'Look at me, I'm the big star' attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
