<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8238 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-CHAFEE-AWARD-BOS &LR;      10-25 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CHAFEE-AWARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNED CEREMONY BECOMES AN IMPROMPTU MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
( w/Chafee-obit)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ronald Machtley had planned to introduce his friend
John Chafee Monday night at the New England Council's New Englander
of the Year award ceremony, but instead he ended up taking his
place.
</P>
<P>
   Before the gathering of regional political and business leaders,
who began the evening with a moment of silence in Chafee's honor,
Machtley read remarks that the senator had prepared before he
suddenly fell ill, recalling a man who, through all his years spent
in Washington, never lost the sense of belonging to New England.
</P>
<P>
   Machtley recalled Chafee's stubborn refusal to use his car's air
conditioning, which he felt was harmful to the environment. Former
governor William Weld remembered that Chafee never told him he had
been elected governor of Rhode Island _ he just cancelled their
regular squash game. And a long series of friends and associates
saluted him as a chronic muffler of his own achievements and the
best kind of Yankee public servant.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he saw other New Englanders like Bill Cohen leave, he had a
sense that this was still where consensus came from,'' said
Machtley, 51, a former Rhode Island congressman who is now
president of Bryant College in Smithfield, R.I. ``He talked about
how politics has become a little more strident, and how we in New
England have developed a philosophy of working together.''
</P>
<P>
   In his salute to the four-term Republican, who won admirers on
both sides of party lines, Machtley quoted Ralph Waldo Emerson's
description of ``men who by their sympathetic attractions carry
nations with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s, Chafee's father had served as chairman of the New
England Council, and the senator was ``an obvious and unanimous
choice'' for the annual award, said the group's vice president,
Larry Zabar. The event was to be Chafee's first appearance since
his decision to end four decades in public office, Machtley said.
</P>
<P>
   Weld said Chafee's decision not to run for another term had
brought the senator a measure of relief. Chafee had been ``a little
frustrated with the welfare bill in 1994,'' and was ready to return
to family life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't tired of the game, he wasn't tired of the people,
but he he had become a little bit tired over the last couple of
years,'' Weld said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
