<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8243 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-CABINET-NYT &LR;      10-25 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-CABINET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN MILITARY SAYS 7 CIVILIANS WILL JOIN NEW GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With PAKISTAN-MUSHARRAF, PAKISTAN-SHARIF) 
 (af)  
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan, _ The military announced Monday night the
names of seven civilians who will join the government of Gen.
Pervez Musharraf, the army chief who seized power on Oct. 12 and
ousted Pakistan's elected government.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the civilians were appointed to the cabinet, and four
to the National Security Council, the country's highest
decision-making body under the new military-led administration. Two
of the civilians appointed to the seven-member council _ which will
be headed by Musharraf, and include the chiefs of the navy and the
air service _ were closely associated with previous military
dictators.
</P>
<P>
   The military released only a bare list of the general's choices,
with no resumes attached, after the general left the country Monday
morning to visit Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates. The
announcement set off a scramble by journalists to figure out who
some of the lesser-known appointees were.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best-known choices was Sharfuddin Pirzada, a
constitutional lawyer selected as senior adviser to the general and
ex-officio member of the council. Pirzada was attorney general in
the 1980s under a military ruler, Gen. Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, and
served as law minister in the military government of Field Marshal
Mohammad Ayub Khan in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Pirzadais best known for having drafted a constitutional
amendment on Zia's behalf that allowed the indirectly elected
president to dismiss the directly elected prime minister and
dissolve parliament. This vestige of military dictatorship was only
done away with after Nawaz Sharif, the prime minister who was
toppled this month, was elected in a landslide in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Attiya Inayatullah, the only woman among those appointed to the
council, had also served Zia, advising him on population control
programs. She was formerly a representative to UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
   The other two members of the council are Imtiaz Sahibzada, a
career civil servant from the Northwest Frontier Provinces, and
Muhammad Yaqub, who has been governor of the State Bank of Pakistan
since 1993 and is said to be acceptable to the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   That is an important consideration for military leaders, who
need to persuade the IMF to continue lending money to Pakistan,
which is close to defaulting on its international debts.
</P>
<P>
   The cabinet appointments include Abdul Sattar, who had served as
the top civil servant in the Foreign Ministry and will now be the
foreign minister. Shauhat Aziz, a banker, will be finance minister,
and Aziz Munshi was made attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf announced in a speech a week ago that he would set up
a National Security Council to govern the nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
