<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLEEBAILEY-COX     10-25 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEEBAILEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fee in smuggler case used for comparison
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Assistant U.S. Attorney Marie DeMarco grilled F.
Lee Bailey for a third day Monday, showing that once angered, the
government can be a relentless foe.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to force Bailey to repay $2 million by proving he knew it
was tainted when he took it as a legal fee for representing
infomercial king William J. McCorkle, DeMarco zeroed in on Bailey's
past conduct in a separate case involving a similar dispute with
the government over fees.
</P>
<P>
   DeMarco, 34 and about four months pregnant, has gone toe to toe
with Bailey, whose celebrated career began before she was born.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Bailey has repeatedly challenged and
corrected the prosecutor, who's been in her job for three years.
The two have sparred over legal tactics, the semantics of an
answer, interpretations of law and ethics. At times, DeMarco has
clearly annoyed Bailey; other times she has invoked a kind of
sarcastic respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I believe you're a highly organized person,'' he responded
at one point last week when she searched to verify a point in the
mounds of documents stacked around her.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he chided her like a child: ``No, no and no.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMarco handles general criminal cases and is assigned to the
office's asset forfeiture division. She was pulled into the
McCorkle case to oversee the forfeiture aspect, but became so
well-acquainted with the details that her supervisor made her
co-counsel. Before joining the U.S. attorney's Orlando office, she
practiced privately in Tampa for five years, where she successfully
sued Fred Astaire Dance Studios for scamming elderly women
customers.
</P>
<P>
   DeMarco raised Bailey's ire Monday when she focused on his
conduct in the case of French marijuana smuggler Claude Duboc.
</P>
<P>
   As payment in the case, Bailey said he made a deal with the
government to accept $3 million in pharmaceutical stock and help
prosecutors obtain the rest of Duboc's fortune. The government
contends Bailey was only given the stock to hold and was supposed
to use it to manage property. When Bailey refused to surrender it
after the value jumped upwards of $20 million, U.S. District Judge
Maurice Paul jailed him for 44 days. Bailey eventually turned it
over and dropped his claim. He is now suing for $10.6 million in
the U.S. Court of Federal Claims in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The case also led to an investigation by the Florida Bar, which
last week sent a seven-count ethics complaint to the Florida
Supreme Court. A hearing will be held sometime in the next six
months in Fort Myers.
</P>
<P>
   DeMarco, who clerked for Paul several years before the Duboc
case, asked Bailey again and again if he improperly paid himself
about $3 million after selling off some of the stock. Bailey said
he only used the stock to secure a loan.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he said, ``there was never a forfeiture until (the
government) learned the stock had gone up and then it was suddenly
forfeitable.'' Likewise, he has argued the government never warned
him it was going to pursue his legal fee in the McCorkle case.
</P>
<P>
   DeMarco's cross-examination resumes today.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: jennystaletovich(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
