<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8247 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-WSERIES-LADN-(SLA     10-25 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WSERIES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BASEBALL WORLD ACCORDING TO BUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While major league baseball has been on an upswing in
recent times, its commissioner, Bud Selig, admits there are
ominously distinct boundaries that now exist in the sport between
the wealthy, big-market franchises and those ensconced in small
locales.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt we have a serious disparity problem, and that
it has to be addressed,'' Selig told me the other day during an
interview. ``It's something I've been working hard on since taking
over this job five years ago. I understand the problem very well,
since the team I have owned, the Milwaukee Brewers, is in a small
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I named that blue-ribbon task force with
people like George Will and George Mitchell and Richard Levin
(president of Yale) on it is to see what ideas it can come up with.
We're working very hard to solve our problems, and we're doing more
revenue sharing now among the teams than ever existed in the past.
But it's still not enough. There's still too great a disparity
between the rich teams and those with limited finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball was a sport that had its head in the sand for too
long. It never seriously attempted to solve its problems, and acted
as though they didn't exist. At least we're trying now to do
something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   By the sheerest coincidence, eight of the teams that appeared in
the postseason ranked among the top 12 payrolls in the sport, with
the Yankees holding the top spot with their staggering $86,426.992
payroll and with the Houston Astros having the most modest playoff
payroll at a paltry $51,629.000.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly startling that the Yankees have qualified for
another World Series, with their owner, George Steinbrenner,
willing to give staggering salaries to such prime performers as
Bernie Williams ($9,857.143), Roger Clemens ($8,250.000), David
Cone ($8,000,000), Paul O'Neill ($6,250,000), Chuck Knoblauch
($6,000,000), Andy Pettitte ($5,950,000), Scott Brosius
($5,250,000), Derek Jeter ($5,000,000), Chili Davis ($4,333,333),
Tino Martinez ($4,300,000) and Mariano Rivera ($4,250,000).
</P>
<P>
   Even the journeyman catcher, Joe Girardi, commands wages of $3.4
million and the seldom-used outfielder, Chad Curtis, earns $2
million. Only seven of the Yankees' 25 players make less than $1
million, with utility infielder Clay Bellinger and, curiously,
Darryl Strawberry the lowest at a bread-and-water $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Braves, who list their payroll at $62,652,500, are
cheapskates. Only nine of their players makes less than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   They're actually near the $80 million level themselves, but
three of their players, Andres Galarraga ($8,250,000), Javier Lopez
($5,250,000) and Kerry Lightenberg ($255,000), aren't being counted
because they are on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   It's now apparent that a team must make a huge financial
investment in order to make it into the October test matches.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres went on a spending spree last season, and
it resulted in a World Series appearance. The Florida Marlins did
the same in 1997, and they went on to win a world championship.
</P>
<P>
   But both small-market teams wound up dripping in red ink, and
were forced to get rid of many of their high-priced personnel. And
both immediately dropped out of playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as the Dodgers, whose payroll soared to $79,265,953 in
the wake of their seven-year, $105 million payoff to Kevin Brown,
and Angels, whose payroll went up to $51,830,166 after signing Mo
Vaughn, found out the past season, throwing large amounts of money
around doesn't exactly guarantee success on the field.
</P>
<P>
   But one does wonder if the World Series will become an exclusive
enclave for the game's affluent like the Yankees and Braves?
</P>
<P>
   Will the have-nots like the Pittsburgh Pirates, Minnesota Twins,
Milwaukee Brewers, Kansas City Royals, Oakland A's, San Francisco
Giants, Montreal Expos and the rest never make it to the Fall
Classic in the 21st century?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that doesn't happen because, on the long term, it will
hurt the game,'' said Selig.
</P>
<P>
   The game at the moment has become a warm commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Its television ratings have been up more than 20 percent. Its
regular season attendance once again topped 70 million. Its
playoffs provided riveting daily drama. Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa,
Ken Griffey Jr., Pedro Martinez, Nomar Garciaparra, Tony Gwynn,
Alex Rodriguez, Derek Jeter and Manny Ramirez dispensed Hall of
Fame heroics.
</P>
<P>
   And it even has the glamorous World Series it wanted between the
Yankees and Braves, although it hasn't yet lived up to
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game never has been more popular than it is right now,''
said Selig. ``We've attained levels we never dreamed we could
reach. There's been a Renaissance in this sport that's been
incredible. Some of the on-field performances of our star players
continue to be amazing. And the playoffs were spell-binding.''
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig has had his critics since taking over from the ousted
Fay Vincent in September of 1992, and they were braying loudly
during the sport's disastrous labor dispute in 1994 that led to
Selig's cancellation of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball has made a remarkable comeback since that dark
year, and Selig played a vital role in the owners and players
unions finally reaching a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   He also was responsible for adding a third division in each
league, an extra tier of playoffs and a wild card entrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said that the wild card was going to ruin the
sanctity of the game,'' said Selig. ``But I think just the opposite
has happened. A lot of teams who would be hopelessly out of the
playoffs in September now have a chance to make it because of the
wild card. I think the wild card has created tremendous interest
among a lot of fans who otherwise would be indifferent.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig is downsizing his own office, or, as he puts it, unifying
it.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be an NL or AL president after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of wasteful redundancy that just had to be
eliminated,'' he said. ``And now we plan to have all the umpires
answering to one person in our office. It's unfortunate we had to
go through the umpire problem this summer, and, hopefully, we can
all work together from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   There are vexing other dilemmas confronting Bud Selig like the
perennial Pete Rose Hall of Fame question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The late commissioner, Bart Giamatti, made his decision on
Pete Rose 10 years ago and I still stand by it,'' said Selig,
referring to Giamatti putting Rose on baseball's ineligibility
list. ``I don't think anything has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   That's unfortunate because a vast majority of baseball patrons
feel the game's most prolific batsman belongs in the Cooperstown
shrine, notwithstanding his gambling indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   For certain, a lot has changed in baseball since Bud Selig
assumed command and most of it has been positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of what we've achieved,'' said Selig. ``I feel we've
been moving in the right direction. My father used to tell to tell
me all the time that you can judge whether something is going good
or bad is by comparison to the past. And, if you compare with the
way baseball is going now to its past, I'd have to say it's going
quite good. . .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
