<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- NY-MRSCLINTON, 10-25 --
President Clinton and his wife Hillary Rodham Clinton arrive at the
Ford Center for the Performing Arts in Manhattan Monday night for a
benefit in honor of Mrs. Clinton's birthday as well as a
fundraiser. The event is expected to raise $1 million for Mrs.
Clinton's likely Senate campaign. Chita Rivera, Bebe Neuwirth,
Lauren Bacall and Joel Grey were scheduled to perform in the event.
Mrs. Clinton turns 52 on Tuesday. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- GORE-BRADLEY, 10-25 -- Vice
President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley during campaign
appearances earlier this month. Both have a lot more in common than
either would like to admit to presidential primary voters. So each
will try to emphasize differences that matter to those voters when
they debate for the first time Wednesday night in New Hampshire.
(Paul Hosefros, left, and Tom Landers, right, Boston Globe/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) FREEHOLD, N.J. -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- NJ-FREEHOLD, 10-25 --
A sidewalk cafe in Freehold earlier this month. For years, the town
has been best known as the birthplace of Bruce Springsteen, a
workingman's town that inspired songs like ``Thunder Road'' and
``My Hometown.'' But what was once a quiet enclave of blue-collar
families, farmers and factory hands has been transformed as
Freehold has found itself at ground zero of one of New Jersey's
most spectacular real-estate booms. (Keith Meyers/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) OSH, Kyrgyzstan -- Oct. 25, 1999 --
KYRGYZSTAN-DEMOCRACY, 10-25 -- Two men, one an ethnic Kyrgyz,
right, talks to an ethnic Uzbek, in the Osh Bazaar in the city of
Osh, southwest Kyrgyzstan, earlier this month. The town was the
scene of violent clashes between the two ethnic groups several
years ago. (Staton Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) BOSTON -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- BUSINESS-BOOKS-ONLINE-BOS,
10-25 -- David Wilcox, founder and head of MeansBusiness Inc., with
a few of the books he has incorporated into his new service. On
Nov. 15, he is scheduled to launch www.means business.com, an
on-line database service for researching 1,500 business concepts
along with book summaries distilled from 400 recent books on
business. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
