<P>
   (NYT14) PENSACOLA, Fla. -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- CRASH
MAINTENANCE-4-COX, 10-25 -- Cmdr. Erich Blunt, who oversees
training of enlisted mechanics for the Navy, in his office. In
1980, a Navy mechanic spent from two to five months in initial
training; today, the training lasts from one to two-and-a-half
months. ``The reason we do it that way is to save money,'' Blunt
said. Despite the significant losses of experienced mechanics and
the reduction in training, military commanders said, they have a
better work force, shaped through on-the job training. (Skip
Peterson/Dayton Daily News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PHOENIX -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- CRASH MAINTENANCE-3-COX,
10-25 -- Barbara and Andrew Kaliszek, Capt. Mark R. Nickles' mother
and stepfather, still keep a photo from Nickles' honeymoon
displayed in their kitchen. The Marine Corps F-18 Hornet that Capt.
Nickles and Maj. Danny A. D'Eredita were flying, crashed off the
coast of South Korea on Feb. 9, 1997. The aircraft had been overdue
for servicing by 149 hours. (David Smith/Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) TYNDALL AIR FORCE BASE, Fla. -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- CRASH
MAINTENANCE-2-COX, 10-25 -- Lt. Kenneth Duke Jr. poses with an F-15
during his flight school days at Tyndall Air Force Base. On June
12, 1993, just 12 minutes after takeoff, Duke was flying a National
Guard F-15A fighter when, at 8,500 feet, he lost control of the
aircraft. Duke hit his head on the cockpit canopy as he ejected,
causing a severe head injury that has left him unable to speak
properly or fully control the movement of his arms and legs.
(Handout/Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW ORLEANS, La. -- Oct. 25, 1999 --
CRASH-MAINTENANCE-1-COX, 10-25 -- Lt. Kenneth Duke Jr. gazes at the
air strip at Calendar Field in New Orleans where he flew F-15's for
the Louisiana Air National Guard. On June 12, 1993, just 12 minutes
after takeoff, Duke was flying an F-15A fighter when, at 8,500
feet, the plane became uncontrolable. Duke hit his head on the
cockpit canopy as he ejected, causing a severe head injury which
has left him unable to speak properly or fully control the movement
of his arms and legs. (Skip Peterson/Dayton Daily News)
