</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- SCI-OVARY, 10-25 -- Dr.
Kutluk Oktay, left, slices a cervical-cancer patient's ovaries into
strips before implanting them into her arm at New York Methodist
Hospital in Brooklyn last Thursday. The purpose of the experimental
procedure is to protect the ovaries from radiation and thus prevent
premature menopause. No one knows whether ovarian tissue can live
in a person's arm, but Oktay said he hoped the strips would survive
and act like a normal ovary, producing enough estrogen to prevent
menopause. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- SCI-ARTHUR-CLARKE, 10-25 --
Sir Arthur C. Clarke, writer, dreamer and the man who created HAL,
during an interview in his beloved Chelsea Hotel in Manhattan last
week. Clarke believes strongly that a serious asteroid impact of
earth is inevitable. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- OBIT-STEWART-2,
10-25 -- Payne Stewart after practice at the Country Club in
Brookline just before the start of Ryder Cup competition in August,
1999. A Learjet carrying Stewart flew uncontrolled over the
nation's heartland for hours on Monday before crashing in South
Dakota, killing everyone aboard. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- OBIT-STEWART-1,
10-25 -- Golfer Payne Stewart drives on the 15th hole of his match
against Miguel Angel Jiminez and Padraig Harrington in September
during Ryder Cup competition. A Learjet carrying Stewart flew
uncontrolled over the nation's heartland for hours on Monday before
crashing in South Dakota, killing everyone aboard. (John
Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SEATTLE -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- CRASH-METAL-4-COX, 10-24 --
Paul Patricio lost both of his hands and suffered severe burns on
the rest of his body when, on Feb. 25, 1988, the Army's CH-47D
Chinook helicopter he was in crashed. Of the 19 people on board, 10
were killed and at least 6 others suffered permanent injuries. ``I
didn't want to look at myself,'' Patricio said during an interview
earlier this year at his business. ``At one time, I broke down. I
didn't have any hands. I had to depend on people...to feed me. (Dan
McComb/Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SPRINGFIELD, Ohio -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- CRASH-METAL-3-COX,
10-24 --Brett Roby outside the SPECO'S now-defunct factory. ``I let
my managers know we had this condition,'' said Roby, an inspector
at SPECO, who warned of cracks in gears made with Vasco. ``We had
three out of three that were bad. I was starting to get nervous.''
Roby eventually lost his job in a management reorganization, and
filed a lawsuit in May 1995 against Boeing in federal court in
Cincinnati under the federal False Claims Act. (Skip
Peterson/Dayton Daily News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- CRASH-METAL-2-COX, 10-24 --
This CH-47D Chinook helicopter crashed and burned in Saudi Arabia
during Desert Storm on Jan. 11, 1991. No one was killed. Both the
Army and SPECO blamed the crash on manufacturing defects in a
SPECO-made gear which federal investigators also suspect of being
faulty. (U.S. Army Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Oct. 25, 1999 -- CRASH-METAL-1-COX, 10-24 -- A
team of federal investigators suspect that four CH-47D Chinook
helicopter accidents that killed seven people may be linked to
faulty gears manufactured in Chicago and at a now-defunct factory
in Springfield, Ohio. Boeing contracted with SPECO Corp. of
Springfield, now in bankruptcy, and Litton Precision Gears of
Chicago, now Boeing Precision Gears, to manufacture the gears like
this SPECO part number 145D6301. (Skip Peterson/Dayton Daily News
Photo)
</P>
