<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Z-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: FOR ONLINE ITEMS, THE LETTER `Z' IS POPULAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last letter of the alphabet is becoming the last word, as it
were, in names.
</P>
<P>
   Using a ``z'' at the end of a name _ often in place of the ``s''
that would be there to indicate the plural form _ is growing
increasingly popular in advertising, marketing and the media. There
is a lengthening list of products, services, agencies, Internet
companies and the like that are being named as if Zorro had been
the brand identity consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Examples include Beenz, an online currency; Fritos Racerz, snack
chips shaped like race cars; Adaptz.com, a Web site aimed at
consumers who are disabled; the Lugz and Pure Playaz lines of
footwear and apparel; the animated film ``Antz''; Poweradz.com, a
network of Internet portals based on community newspapers; the Boyz
Channel and the Girlz Channel, cable television networks, and
Flooz.com, a Web site offering online gift certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Those zooming into view with names ending in ``z'' give various
explanations for the eye- and ear-catching practice.
</P>
<P>
   One obvious reason is the rise of hip-hop culture, derived from
rap music and the life styles prevalent in urban America. The film
``Boyz N the Hood'' (1991) was an early influence. Many rap artists
use the letter ``z'' at the end of their names or the names of
their groups: Heavy D. and the Boyz, Jay-Z, Lost Boyz, Youngbloodz,
Ghetto Twiinz, Hoodlumz and Peter Gunz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the `z' would be really cool for the urban
market,'' said Larry Schwartz, executive vice president at JSSI in
New York, the company that sells Lugz, which are advertised by
Amster Yard in New York, part of the McCann-Erickson Worldwide
Advertising unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw fashion changing from sneakers to boots and in fact,
many rappers were starting to wear boots,'' Schwartz said. ``And
the kids were starting to take their cues from the rappers.''
</P>
<P>
   The thinking, then, is that a name that finishes in ``z'' will
be evocative of the hip image, contemporary attitude and
cutting-edge trendiness that pervade hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be in style, to be in fashion, just add a `z,''' said Doug
Raboy, managing partner for creative at Hanft Byrne Raboy &AMP;
Partners in New York, the agency for Flooz.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph and Tommy get it all from the `hood,''' he added,
referring to the designers Ralph Lauren and Tommy Hilfiger, whose
clothing first blew up _ gained success _ in the inner cities
before being adopted by suburban shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Raboy was quick to note, however, that the founders of Flooz.com
named their Web site ``after the slang for cash used in ancient
Mesopotamian trading markets, predating the gold card by 5,000
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``z'' is also supposed to connote an alternate way of
looking at life, in much the same manner that rap is an alternate
form of music.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our movie, our lead character, Z, was somebody who thought
differently, who did things his own way,'' said Brad Lewis, one of
three producers of ``Antz,'' the 1998 animated movie released by
Dreamworks SKG and PDI.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the `z' at the end of `Antz' is a perfect parallel,'' he
added, ``directly analogous.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Frito-Lay division of Pepsico Inc., which introduced
Fritos Racerz in July, the name of the snack-chip brand _ the first
variation in Fritos shapes since 1932 _ was derived from consumer
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we talked, we found that the `z' makes it fun, modern,
fitting with the fast, active theme we intended,'' said Stephen
Quinn, vice president and marketing general manager at Frito-Lay in
Plano, Tex.
</P>
<P>
   That was particularly true with younger consumers, he added,
which was serendipitous because Fritos Racerz is aimed at snackers
between the ages of 8 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   Such appeal o important to the Fox Family Channels in
introducing the Boyz Channel and the Girlz Channel, which are
obviously meant for youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids get it,'' said Rich Cronin, president and chief executive
at the Fox Kids Network unit of the News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept is crystal clear,'' he added: ``quirky, different,
a lot of personality. After all, if Liza were Lisa, would anyone
care?''
</P>
<P>
   Cronin's query brought up the antecedents to the ``z'' trend,
which include the singer Liza Minnelli; ZZZZ Best, pronounced
``Four Z Best,'' a carpet cleaning company that became one of the
best-known financial swindles of the 1980's; the cars sold by
Datsun, now Nissan Motor, like the 240Z, and ``Beanz meanz Heinz,''
a slogan created by the London office of Young &AMP; Rubicam that was
long familiar from British ads for H.J. Heinz.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Z' is an underappreciated letter,'' said Glenn Jasper,
corporate communications director for the Beenz Co. in New York,
which is introducing Beenz as a redeemable currency that computer
users can obtain by visiting Web sites and participating in
Internet promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our founder, Charles Cohen, finds the `s' to be a dull
letter,'' Jasper said, ``and the `z' _ or `zed' as he calls it,
since he's British _ is his favorite letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Using a ``z'' to replace an ``s'' can also help a name stand out
for legal purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `z' makes the name proprietary and protectable,'' said
Quinn of Frito-Lay, meaning that the company could obtain a
trademark for Fritos Racerz. That might not have been the case if
the name had been the generic Racers.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes a ``z'' is just a ``z.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could tell you there's some deeply insightful
reason'' for the name Adaptz.com, said David Brenner, president of
the Web site in New York, a unit of Disabilitysource.com that
recently signed Barnesandnoble.com and the Dodge division of
DaimlerChrysler as initial sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an icon, something to help remember the Web site,'' he
added. ``I didn't think `Adapt.com' had the same zing.''
</P>
<P>
   What trend is next after ``z'' ends a name? Of course, the
opposite. For instance, there's Zwirl.com, a planned E-commerce Web
site where Jessica Adelson calls herself ``ZEO,'' and
Zuniversity.com, which offers students Web sites and e-mail
affiliated with their universities.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Z' is a very powerful and confident letter,'' said Joe Wolf,
co-founder of Zuniversity.com in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Sez who?
</P>
<P>
   ``A relative who's into beads and crystals,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Well, as the saying goes, always consider your sourcez. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
