<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0524 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8267 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HONGKONG-INVEST-NYT &LR;      10-25 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG BEGINS SELLING ITS STOCK PORTFOLIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ When Hong Kong's government plunged into the stock
market in August 1998, buying $15 billion worth of shares, it drew
ridicule from some rather lofty sources. Milton Friedman, the Nobel
Prize-winning economist, called the intervention a ``crazy idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, more than a year after its famous shopping spree, the
government began offering those shares to the public. Whether Hong
Kong is deemed crazy or clever will depend on how many investors
buy them.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the government announced a target price of $1.3
billion for the first batch of shares, packaged in a fund that
tracks Hong Kong's benchmark Hang Seng index. To entice local
investors, it is offering a minimum 5 percent discount on the
market price of the stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities are promoting what is called the Tracker Fund of
Hong Kong with an advertising campaign that features a father
cavorting with his children against the backdrop of a soaring
suspension bridge. The black-and-white ads are rather austere, and
officials here have projected a similarly subdued tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government didn't want to buy these shares,'' said Peter
Churchouse, the managing director and co-head of research here at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Asia. ``They painted themselves into a
corner by doing it, and they're trying to get out of it
gracefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its steep cost, officials here contend that the
intervention was a success because it foiled foreign-currency
traders who had been seeking to weaken the stock market and the
Hong Kong dollar. Officials also note that the value of the
government's portfolio has risen by more than $10 billion, to $25.8
billion, amid the resurgence in Asian stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   But that, of course, is a paper profit. Realizing those gains
will be another matter. And selling such a vast portfolio without
depressing the rest of the market is a challenge not lost on anyone
in this city, where the daily closing price of the Hang Seng index
sometimes seems to be the only box score that counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot more supply out there than the
market can bear,'' said Mac Overton, a financial consultant at the
Sun Hung Kai Trading Company, one of Hong Kong's largest property
developers.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the government has said it intends to dispose of most
of the $25 billion portfolio, analysts said Hong Kong investors
could expect offerings of $2 billion every year for the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, at least, they did not seem too concerned by that
prospect. The Hang Seng index rose 1.33 percent. Analysts said the
market was propelled by increases in two of its largest stocks, Sun
Hung Kai and HSBC Holdings, rather than a warm reception for the
Tracker Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Always on the lookout for a money-making opportunity, Hong Kong
residents lined up at banks Monday to collect applications for the
offering. But just how wide the appeal of the fund will be is the
subject of some debate here.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Machin of Goldman, Sachs, which is coordinating the
offering along with ING Barings and Jardine Fleming, said it would
be attractive to retail investors because of the discount and
because of bonus shares that will be awarded to those who hold the
stock longer than a year.
</P>
<P>
   But Churchouse noted that index funds and mutual funds have
never been popular here, because investors enjoy picking stocks and
trading them almost as a sport. ``People in Hong Kong like to punt
the market,'' he said, using a British term for making speculative
trades.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional investors also prefer buying individual stocks to
funds, Churchouse said. But he added that the Tracker Fund would be
an easy way for fund managers to increase the Asian weightings of
their portfolios. The government will give institutions a discount
as well, though its amount has not been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't unadulterated enthusiasm for the Hong Kong
market,'' he said. ``But slowly, we're seeing money flow back.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said they were skeptical about the Tracker Fund
because, like the index it tracks, the fund is heavily weighted
toward banking and property stocks. Together, HSBC, which is based
in London, Sun Hung Kai and another big property developer, Cheung
Kong Holdings, account for more than half the total market
capitalization of the Hang Seng index.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's attractive,'' said Marc Faber, the head of
his own investment firm here. ``Property shares aren't performing
well. Even after its decline, Hong Kong property is still the most
expensive in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, analysts said, the Tracker Fund is a bet on the
future of Hong Kong itself. After contracting by 5.1 percent last
year, the territory's economy is in the midst of a surprisingly
vigorous recovery. But it still trails Asian nations like South
Korea, Singapore and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors also cannot get past the intervention itself,
which they view as a betrayal of Hong Kong's free-market
principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shouldn't have bought the shares in the first place,''
Faber said. ``Or if they bought them, they should have sold them
sooner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
