<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-APPLE-BLUES-NYT     10-25 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-BLUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWERS' LAMENT: THE CROP'S BRIGHT RED, BUT SO IS THE INK 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTIAT, Wash. _ In one way, the news this year from Bruce Grim's
orchard, and from orchards all over this region that proudly calls
itself the Apple Capital of the World, is very good news indeed.
``Vintage!'' Grim proclaimed as he plucked a red Delicious from a
tree and sliced it open with a pocketknife. ``Lots of crunch. Lots
of snap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great internals,'' he said, referring to the flavor and
texture. ``Terrific external, too,'' he added, appraising the
color.
</P>
<P>
   But wide agreement about the outstanding quality of this year's
crop in the nation's top apple-producing state belies a disturbing
trend: no one here seems to be making any money growing apples.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several years, growers here have had to deal with
some of their worst times ever, a result of stagnation in domestic
demand, grocery-industry consolidation that gives large buyers the
upper hand in negotiating price, and a flood of imports from China
that has driven the price of apples used in making juice so low
that last year many farmers, rather than picking all their product,
simply let some of it rot in the orchard.
</P>
<P>
   That the nation's economy is roaring along in so many other
respects only makes the plight of those who grow this most American
of fruits all the more frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep reading about the big economic boom in Seattle,'' 150
miles to the west, on the other side of the Cascade Mountains, said
Grant Daniel, a grower just across the Columbia River from Grim.
``Well, there's no boom going on out here on these orchards.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the state's apple growers saw their lowest return in
three decades, with the typical family orchard, of 50 acres, losing
between $70,000 and $100,000, according to the Washington Growers
Clearing House Association, an industry group. The association says
that 20 percent of the state's growers have gone out of business in
the last five years and that another 20 percent, or 800 orchards,
will do so over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have financed this year's crop on the credit
card,'' said Kirk Mayer, the association's manager. ``They're
basically trying to buy their orchard all over again from the bank.
But it's a very uphill proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington State grows about half of all the nation's apples,
followed by New York and Michigan, with about 10 percent each.
Growers of all apple varieties in those states and elsewhere around
the country received an average of 17.1 cents a pound for their
product last year, 18 to 29 percent less than in the three years
before and, after adjustment for inflation, one of the lowest
prices since the Great Depression, said Kraig Naasz, president of
the U.S. Apple Association, a national trade group.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in prices for juice apples, generally of lower
quality than apples marketed for eating, has been even more stark.
Having averaged $189 a ton in 1995, those prices have dropped
consistently since then, to an average of $40 a ton last year; many
growers around here say they got as little as $10 a ton.
</P>
<P>
   The apple association, arguing that ``a flood of cheap
apple-juice concentrate imports from China is drowning much of our
industry in a sea of red ink,'' filed a petition earlier this year
with the United States Department of Commerce and the government's
International Trade Commission. The association argued that China,
now the largest apple producer in the world, was dumping its
product _ that is, deliberately undercutting American apples by
selling at below-cost prices _ and sought punitive tariffs on the
United States' Chinese apple-juice imports. A decision is expected
later this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, though, many growers here have either given up
or say they are on the verge of going broke. Many say, too, that
they are particularly angry that even as the prices they receive
have plunged in recent years, the cost to the consumer has actually
inched upward slightly over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   It is not at all hard to understand just why that is happening.
Consolidation in the grocery industry, for one thing, has clearly
given an advantage to the buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have over 100 suppliers in the state of Washington
alone competing for the business of five major buyers,'' Naasz
said, ``it's easy to see who has the leverage in those price
negotiations, and it isn't the apple grower.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the growers themselves are necessarily immune from
responsibility for their plight. For one thing, they may simply
have planted too many trees in recent decades, especially those
that bear the benchmark red Delicious apple, still the No. 1 seller
in the grocery store but typically so plentiful that it fetches a
lower price than many other varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Now some growers here, in a frenzied bid to carve out their
place in ``niche markets,'' are ripping Delicious trees out of
their orchards and experimenting with exotic varieties that many
people find far superior in taste and quality. And other growers
are completely abandoning a fruit that long provided them a
livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think apples are a thing of the past,'' said George Kapral,
who has been growing them for 49 years. His 40-acre orchard once
bore almost nothing but apples, but he has ripped out so many apple
trees over the years in favor of pear that the share for apples is
now down to 4 acres; next year, it will be 2.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that American consumption of apples has
leveled off at around 20 pounds a person per year (compared with 35
pounds in Canada and 50 pounds in parts of Europe).
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition is greater than ever before for a share of the
customer's stomach,'' Naasz said. ``There are all kinds of snacks
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some food critics say demand has flattened because apples simply
do not taste as good as they once did. The red Delicious, in
particular, they say, has been bred over the years for color and
size uniformity, and has lost some of its flavor in the process.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Washington growers, trying to stimulate demand,
have imposed a variety of fees on themselves for a promotional
campaign to persuade Americans to eat an extra apple a day.
</P>
<P>
   The weather here this year _ warm, but not too warm during the
day, cool at night, with just the right amount of rain _ has
combined with the area's rich volcanic soil to turn out a crop of
ideal quality, although one that is expected to be a bit smaller
than last year's. Taken together, those factors could lead to
better prices as the apples come in at warehouses this fall, said
Mayer, of the Washington Growers Clearing House Association. But,
he said, it will take more than one good season to make up for the
punishingly low returns of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Grim, who lost $63,000 last year growing apples on his 90 acres
of orchards, said many suppliers felt particularly frustrated
because they grew up in a time when big families made a fine living
working orchards much smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that a family could raise their kids, send them
to school, have a good life in this community, growing on 10 to 15
acres,'' said Grim, a third-generation grower. ``Well, now I'm
farming about seven or eight of those, and I'm not making any money
at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
