<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-STEWART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PAYNE STEWART, A GOLFER WITH STYLE AND CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With PLANE-STEWART) 
(ms) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until Monday, until his Lear jet's strange and spooky crash,
Payne Stewart's life had never been better. He had won his second
U.S. Open with a 15-foot par putt on the 18th green at Pinehurst
No. 2 in June, and he was on the American team that snatched the
Ryder Cup from the European pros in a Sunday comeback last month at
The Country Club outside Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, for someone who admitted he had been rude
and arrogant occasionally in his younger years, the 42-year-old
golfer had grown into a gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   As the only touring pro who wore plus fours, Payne Stewart
always had style; when he wore long pants, nobody recognized him.
But this year he showed he also had class.
</P>
<P>
   When Stewart, a father of two, won the Open at Pinehurst, he
turned to Phil Mickelson, the runner-up who had been waiting all
week for word that his wife, Amy, had gone into labor with their
first child.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and Amy,'' he said, holding Mickelson's face in his hands,
``you take good care of your baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart later talked about how he had been able to control his
emotions on that winning putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud that my faith in God is so much stronger and I'm so
much more at peace with myself than I've ever been in my life,'' he
said. ``That's why I was able to gather myself and conduct myself.
That gave me the strength to stand up there and believe in myself
and get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   And on the 18th green in his Ryder Cup singles match, Stewart
turned to Colin Montgomerie, the Scot whom too many Americans seem
to love to hate. By then the American team had clinched, so Stewart
conceded Montgomerie's putt, thereby giving the Europeans another
half-point. ``Colin didn't deserve to have to stand over this putt
and try to make it,'' Stewart later explained. ``We had already won
the Ryder Cup; that's what it is, a team event. My individual
statistics don't mean anything in the Ryder Cup, and I wasn't going
to put him through that.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially after the heckling that Montgomerie had been through
that day and the two previous days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had numerous instances of heckling in the gallery; we had a
couple of people removed from the gallery,'' Stewart continued,
referring to their singles match. ``I appreciate the gallery that
we had here, but it's a golf event for pride and honor. You have to
understand that it's not life and death. Some of our fans, they're
a little bit over the top. I don't know how many of them have been
to golf events before.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the fifth fairway, I said: `Colin, if you have a problem, I
will take care of it. This is not what it's about. Some of our fans
are out of control and not appropriate.' I told him that I would
have security or whatever take care of it because this was a
competition between Colin and myself and all of us as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to let the fans be out of control and influence
one of his shots because of the heckling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he respected that from me. And all I can say to Colin
is: `I'm sorry for some of our fans. It wasn't right that they
behaved that way, but that's how it is.' And he said, `Well, I'm
kind of used to it.' And I said, `If you want me to do anything,
I'll take care of it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart didn't have to do that, but he did.
</P>
<P>
   In the years to come, he'll be remembered for what he did when
everybody in golf watched: winning three majors _ the Open this
year at Pinehurst No. 2 and also in 1991 at Hazeltine outside
Minneapolis as well as the 1989 Professional Golfers' Association
Championship at Kemper Lakes outside Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But he also should be remembered for what he did when nobody was
watching: offering to help control the heckling and then conceding
Montgomerie's birdie putt on the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't lward to running after the elusive dollar,''
Stewart said after winning the Open at Pinehurst. ``I'm looking
forward to, as soon as the tournament in Valderrama is over, the
seventh of November; I'm not playing again until the Hawaiian Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had so much fun being at home, being a father, getting up in
the morning, making breakfast, taking my kids to school, going to
high school athletics. That's what my life is right now, so I'm not
going to do what I did in '91 along that line.''
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly and sadly, Payne Stewart's life, which had never
been better, is now over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
