<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-INJURIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS LOSE 4 MORE PLAYERS TO INJURIES, WEAKENING DEPTH CHART 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Giants won the game Sunday but lost
a running back, two safeties and a defensive tackle, a situation
that had Coach Jim Fassel scrambling to find stand-ins _ however
unpolished _ for the Sunday's game in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   During the Giants' 31-3 blowout of the New Orleans Saints, the
starting safety Percy Ellsworth broke the cuboid bone in his left
foot, and four plays later, his backup, Shaun Williams, pulled his
left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the team said that Ellsworth and Williams would be out a
month. So there is a chance the starting free safety for the Giants
against the Eagles will be Brandon Sanders, who had been cast off
two teams this year, the 0-7 Cleveland Browns and the Giants.
Sanders arrives with an undistinguished record. When the Giants
signed him this past summer, they released him a day later.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, whom the Giants expect to sign after a workout Tuesday
morning, had been with the team the past two seasons and was used
almost exclusively as a special-teams player, having never started
a National Football League game. He was taken by Cleveland in the
expansion draft last spring and released by the team in August.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders may seem like a last-resort starter, but the Giants have
few other alternatives. If the strained hamstring of safety Lyle
West, a rookie drafted in the sixth round, does not improve
quickly, the Giants' choices will be down to Sanders or Jeremy
Lincoln, a cornerback who last played safety 13 years ago as a
16-year-old high school senior in Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   West hasn't practiced for the past two weeks. Monday, Fassel
said he wasn't convinced that West could practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, who gave his players time off until Wednesday, said he
would most likely sign two safeties this week. A team official
indicated the team would work out Sanders and Tre Thomas, a rookie
safety the Giants also cut at the end of training camp. Thomas
would probably be signed to the practice squad, providing the
Giants with some insurance against another injury to a safety.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Williams will also affect the Giants' nickel and
dime pass defenses. The rookie cornerback Andre Weathers will have
to take Williams' place in the nickel, and another rookie
cornerback, Bashir Levingston, who was signed primarily as a
kickoff specialist, will have to play in the dime package.
</P>
<P>
   Free safety is not the only place the Giants will be short this
weekend, it is only the most glaring deficiency. Defensive tackle
Robert Harris broke his fibula and sprained his right ankle on
Sunday and will also miss a month of playing time.
</P>
<P>
   With Christian Peter at tackle, the Giants are deep at that
position.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants also lost running back Joe Montgomery, who broke
a bone in his left foot against the Saints while making his Giants
debut. Fassel said Monday that he didn't know when Montgomery hurt
his foot but that the rookie would be out three to four weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
