<HEADER>
A8290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKS     10-25 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S UP TO A QUEASY GLAVINE TO STOP THE YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tom Glavine is the first in the last line of defense
for the Atlanta Braves in this World Series, and over the past two
days, his manager asked the pitcher repeatedly if he has had enough
time to recover from a stomach virus, if he would be ready to pitch
in Game 3 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine says he is. He also says his diet currently consists of
soup and crackers, that he has lost weight, and he has no idea how
many innings he will last.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, the gritty Glavine will take the ball at
Yankee Stadium and try to stop the pinstriped avalanche that is
threatening to bury the Braves in the last World Series of the
century. Andy Pettitte will pitch for the Yankees, who established
dominance in winning the first two games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' success has been based on their strong starting
pitching throughout this decade, and any comeback would have to be
built on the former Cy Young award winners Glavine and John Smoltz,
who is scheduled to start Game 4 Wednesday night. ``Any team that
has good pitching like we have,'' Cox said, ``we can always reel
off three in a row. We've always been able to do something like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Manager Joe Torre said: ``When you win as many games as
they have, they go out there tomorrow night and they're going to be
confident they could beat our brains out. They're going to look for
pitches to hit, be aggressive, and that's what they do best.''
</P>
<P>
   And worst. It became apparent in the first two games of the
Series that the Yankees' pitchers are employing essentially the
same strategy they did against Texas _ another team composed of
aggressive hitters _ in the division series. Orlando Hernandez and
David Cone, the Yankees' starters in Games 1 and 2, threw strikes
with breaking balls early in the ball-strike count, before
successfully tempting the Atlanta hitters to swing at bad pitches
late in the ball-strike count. Generally, Cone said, the Yankees'
pitchers have been advised in scouting meetings that the Atlanta
hitters _ dangerous as they might be _ are capable of hacking far
beyond the limits of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been devastating. ``They couldn't be better,''
Cox said, when asked about the Yankees' starters.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees lost the first two games of the 1996 World Series at
home, as the Braves did this year, and after the Yankees came back
and won, Torre mentioned that despite the two losses early in the
Series, he still felt confident his team would prevail; he had a
sense it was ready to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Braves' workout Monday, Cox explained calmly that
Atlanta has recovered from predicaments before and he believes it
can again. But if he has the same feelings as Torre had in '96,
they exist irrespective of what occurred in Atlanta over the
weekend. The Braves accumulated three errors and four hits in the
first 17 innings of the series, batted .121 over all and botched
pivotal fielding plays. The Game 2 starter, Kevin Millwood, took
the mound with benign stuff and in the one instance when a reliever
pitched in a crucial situation, John Rocker imploded.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius tried to describe the collective frame of mind the
Yankees are playing with now, and there were echoes of 1998, when
sometimes it was as if the Yankees were playing solitaire with a
deck of 51. ``We're just concentrating on coming out and playing
the games, and trying to do whatever is required with each at-bat,
each inning, each situation,'' Brosius said. ``We don't worry about
the historical stuff. We just come out and play the games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have won 10 consecutive World Series games, a streak
that began with Game 3 of the 1996 World Series, and a streak that
is two games shy of the record of 12 consecutive victories, set by
the Yankees when they won the World Series in 1927, 1928 and 1932.
Should the Yankees win the next two games and sweep the Braves,
they would be the first team since the Yankees of 1927-28 to sweep
the World Series in back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's starters, Pettitte and Glavine, are similar:
left-handers who like to throw repeatedly to the outside corner
against right-handed batters, Pettitte with sinking fastballs and
curveballs and Glavine with changeups and fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rippley, scheduled to be the home-plate umpire tonight,
will call balls and strikes and could have a significant impact on
the approach of both pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   If he's calling strikes on the pitches thrown just off the
absolute fringes of the strike zone, the conditions will favor the
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine had been scheduled to pitch Game 1 of the World Series,
but on the eve of the Series, he came down with a stomach virus and
was replaced by Greg Maddux. There was no chance he could have
pitched in Game 2, either, Glavine said, and he has spent the past
few days recovering, assuring Cox he would be fine for Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how my stamina's going to be, to be quite honest
with you,'' Glavine said. ``I think that if it was a summertime
game and was going to be 100 degrees, I'd be a whole lot more
concerned about it than I would be tomorrow, when it's going to be
cool. That obviously will help a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in the American League stadium, the teams will employ
designated hitters _ an advantage for the Yankees, according to
Cox. Chili Davis will probably start at dh for the Yankees, but
Torre was weighing the possibility of starting Jim Leyritz.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Hernandez, acquired from the Cubs during the season, will
be the designated hitter for the Braves. The right-handed-hitting
Chad Curtis will start in left field for the Yankees although he
has gone without a hit in 13 career at-bats against Glavine. Luis
Sojo, who missed Games 1 and 2 following the death of his father,
Ambrosio Sojo, is expected to be in uniform and available for
Tuesday night's game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
