u a BC-NY-HOMELESS-POLICY-2T     10-25 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-POLICY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY TO MAKE HOMELESS WORK FOR SHELTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first time, the homeless in New York City
will be required to work as a condition of shelter under a policy
to be put into effect by the administration of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani before the end of the year, an administration official
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The work requirement is one of a list of rules that those
seeking shelter will have to obey to keep their beds under the
city's plan, which makes the city's homeless shelters subject to
the same system of eligibility screenings, job searches, work
assignments and sanctions that city welfare offices have used since
1995 to move more than 400,000 people off public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The homeless who are able to work and who fail to comply with
the rules could be refused shelter, and in the case of families
with children, the children could be put in foster care, said
Anthony Coles, the senior advisor to Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the city is asking parents to take responsibility
for themselves and to take responsibility for their children,''
Coles said. ``But if parents are unable to take responsibility for
themselves, then it raises a real question of whether they can take
responsibility for their children.''
</P>
<P>
   The requirements are backed by state social services regulations
issued in 1997 and aimed at moving the homeless to work and
self-sufficiency. But the rules were not immediately applied in the
city because of legal challenges by advocates for the homeless
based on court rulings 18 years ago that gave the homeless a
far-reaching right to shelter. The advocates objected that the new
rules threatened to send hundreds of homeless children and adults
onto the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, after an appellate court ruled against the
advocates' objections as they applied to families with children,
city officials said they were making preparations for the shift in
policy, but had set no firm starting date. Until last week,
advocates for the homeless and many private, nonprofit shelter
providers believed that any change would be delayed until after the
cold season, which typically brings a peak in shelter applicants.
</P>
<P>
   But Coles said the administration was ready to apply the new
rules to 4,600 families in the city's homeless-shelter system in 45
to 60 days, and that it expected to be legally free to do the same
for the system's 7,000 single adults within the same period.
</P>
<P>
   At a court hearing on Thursday, city lawyers will officially
notify lawyers for homeless single adults of their intentions and
draw up a briefing schedule, Coles said.
</P>
<P>
   Under current welfare procedures, those seeking exemption from
work requirements because of mental or physical disabilities must
undergo screening every three months by a medical service under
contract to the city. Advocates for the mentally ill have
com that this process is impossible for many disabled
applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents in the city's homeless shelters already work in
exchange for their welfare benefits while their children are in
shelter day care, according to Frederick Shack, the president of an
organization of 42 nonprofit agencies running family shelters under
contract to the city. But at any one time, 10 percent have been
mistakenly cited for noncompliance with welfare rules, he said, and
many others arrive with their public assistance cases wrongly
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, their shelter is not threatened by
such case closings. But under the state regulations the city is
applying, shelters are required to evict those no longer eligible
for public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear exactly how or when such a decision would be made.
Debra Sproles, a spokeswoman for the city's Human Resources
Administration, said details on when the homeless would be ejected
were still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the most controversial issues is whether children can or
should be taken into foster care if their parents _ in most cases,
a single mother _ are expelled from the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Banks, legal counsel to the Coalition for the Homeless,
maintained that to do so violates a longstanding state social
services law and court rulings that children should not be removed
from their families for lack of housing alone.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Crane, the assistant corporation counsel handling the
right-to-shelter litigation for the city, said: ``In some cases, if
it got to that _ and hopefully it wouldn't _ failure to comply with
various regulations could result in children being taken away
because the mother's actions would be tantamount to neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Scoppetta, the commissioner of the city's
Administration for Children's Services, said the issues would be
examined case by case, and that in some instances relatives might
be able to care for the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our only concern would be are the children safe: Are they
being cared for, are they being provided for?'' he said. ``My only
concern is you don't have somebody go out in the street with two
young children and say, `Well, all right, I have to live in the
street now.' We wouldn't let two young children live in the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Another unanswered question is how the new regulations would
affect Department of Homeless Services outreach teams, which try to
persuade homeless people living on the streets to enter the shelter
system. Under current welfare rules, people can be barred from
re &UR; - &LR; applying for assistance for up to 180 days. It was unclear
whether the same waiting period would keep the homeless from
re-entering a shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The city's workfare program _ by far the largest in the country
with about 40,000 participants _ requires welfare recipients to
work at city jobs, including cleaning parks and doing clerical
tasks, in exchange for their benefits. Under current welfare rules,
single adults who miss a single hour of work can see their entire
case closed. Last year 69 percent of these home-relief clients in
the work program were sanctioned and removed from the rolls for
several months at least, city records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extraordinarily callous, with the cold weather coming
now, that the city wants to put vulnerable New Yorkers on the
streets,'' Banks said. ``The track record of workfare programs in
the city hasn't been one in which significant numbers were placed
in jobs that allowed them to pay prevailing rents. It has been
essentially a tool to reduce the caseload through sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coles dismissed such concerns. ``There are always advocates
invested in the old ways of doing things who are going to posit
extreme scenarios for what will happen,'' he said. ``The mayor has
shown time and time again that attaching social responsibilities to
social programs makes for a better and stronger city, it makes for
better and stronger families and for better and stronger
individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   The effects of welfare cutbacks on homeless shelters in the rest
of the country are indirect because most shelter systems are
supported by a patchwork of private charities and limited public
financing, and residents enjoy no legal right to shelter. No other
city in the nation has as comprehensive a publicly financed shelter
system as New York's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
