<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-TORRE     10-25 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-TORRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGES HAVE ADDED DEPTH TO TORRE'S PERSPECTIVE ON LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe Torre peers at sunsets as if he were watching
them for the first time. He recognizes the vibrant flowers he never
bothered to look at before, absorbing their beauty. He sees bright
stars on dark, clear nights, studying them more than staring at
them. Things change.
</P>
<P>
   Every hug with Ali, Torre's wife, includes an extra squeeze. If
Andrea Rae, their 3{-year-old daughter, eats an ice cream cone
sloppily and then kisses him, Torre revels in the sticky smooch and
returns the kiss again and again. These moments are precious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tease him, because he notices the little things more,'' Ali
Torre said. ``Now he takes time to stop and reflect.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer will do that. It is a frightening disease that never
truly goes away. The fear of losing what one has can bring new
appreciation for what one has. Remember to savor life. Torre has
admitted that he does this even more now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more sensitive to everything around me on a daily basis,''
Torre said. ``I'm more aware of things.''
</P>
<P>
   With New York buzzing about baseball, and the Yankees needing
just two victories to secure their second straight World Series and
third in four years under Torre, it is easy to overlook how this
special season started.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer. Manager Joe Torre has prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the words the Yankees heard in spring training when
events like Tuesday night's Game 3 of the World Series were distant
and seemed unimportant in light of their manager's health. The
Yankees wanted to know that Torre would be fine, that the manager
whose soothing approach had guided them would survive. They were
worried about Torre's health, about his ability to continue as a
father and husband, not about losing a manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if this day would ever come,'' said Torre,
referring to the World Series. ``You don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre was outside the visiting clubhouse at Turner Field in
Atlanta, wearing a thick Yankee jacket to protect him from the
swirling winds. He looked weary, but Torre, who is 59, has often
said he has the kind of worn face and brooding brown eyes that make
him look as if he were always tired. It was 90 minutes before the
Yankees overwhelmed the Braves, 7-2, in Game 2 and Torre was wiping
tears away.
</P>
<P>
   He playfully chided a reporter for asking questions that made
him cry. But Torre cried anyway, another sign of his increased
sensitivity. It was a question about how his relationship with
Andrea Rae was strengthened while he missed more than two months of
the season that caused Torre to take his left hand out of his
pocket and rub his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, your first thought is to be alive, to be alive for
my little girl,'' Torre said, his voice wavering. ``So many good
things have happened to me. If nothing good ever happened again,
I'd have a lifetime of great memories. But, with my little girl,
that makes the need to live longer more apparent and more important
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali giggled like a proud mother when she was asked how Torre
entertained their daughter while he was recuperating. ``He did
whatever she wanted him to do,'' Ali said.
</P>
<P>
   That meant watching ``Scooby Doo'' in the morning and switching
to the ``Peter Pan'' videotape when the cartoon was over. Torre
brought Andrea Rae to arts and crafts class on Tuesdays, dipping
his fingers in paint like any other parent and taking her for a
bagel afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always self-conscious of going places because of who I
was, but I became a father,'' Torre said. ``I was oblivious to
everything else that was going on around me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Torre talked about the preventive treatment he will undergo
after the season, his voice naturally sounded more concerned. He
has adopted a strict low-fat diet, works out strenuously five times
a week, drinks green tea for its antioxidants and has leaner muscle
mass on his 212-pound frame. But like other cancer patients, Torre
worries. ``You never know,'' he said. ``This thing could come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Torre underwent surgery at the Barnes-Jewish Hospital in
St. Louis seven months ago, he told his surgeon, Dr. William
Catalona, that he would invite him to the World Series if the
Yankees made it. Catalona, who was in the dugout with Torre before
Game 1, said Torre looked terrific and was probably in better shape
now than he was before surgery. Still, the hospital estimated that
179,000 men would get prostate cancer this year and that 37,000 of
them would die.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always a chance that any type of cancer can
reoccur,'' Catalona said. ``That's why all cancer patients have to
come back for checkups.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Torre, Joe's older brother, who had a heart transplant
three years ago, said: ``He went from being on top of the world to
a life-and-death situation in 24 hours. No matter what Joe tells
you, there's always a little doubt with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre and his wife pray often and remain positive. Her
79-year-old father had surgery for prostate cancer 12 years ago and
has had no recurrence. So whenever Torre received a worrisome
medical report or felt sick, Ali reminded herself about her father
and prayed harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear of cancer and you think of death,'' Ali said.
``That's until you research it, learn more about it and realize
people can survive.''
</P>
<P>
   After Torre guided the Yankees to the 1996 World Series title,
Ali wanted him to retire. They never really discussed retirement
while he was recovering this spring and she rarely mentions it
anymore, because she has a deeper understanding of how happy Torre
is when he is managing. This year, it means more. Things change.
Moments are precious. Torre knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, if I find that I'm in a stressful time, I'll use
what I have been through to relax me,'' he said. ``I'll tell myself
that I'm lucky to be here, so, whatever happens, win or lose, I'm
fortunate. Believe me, I'm lucky.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
