<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES' WILLIAMS PONDERS YANKEE TIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The question made Gerald Williams raise his head and
open his eyes wide. Then he chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   Would Yankee Stadium have an intimidating effect on his team,
the way it seems to have on some visiting baseball players?
</P>
<P>
   ``Intimidated?'' said Williams, the left fielder and leadoff
hitter for the Atlanta Braves. ``I used to play here. I like the
atmosphere. This is a place where the fans are very involved. They
have a lot of energy and a lot of spirit. They embrace baseball.
It's a fine situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should have a positive effect on people who want to
play baseball. I like the atmosphere here. You think and you feel
that you are in the right spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the change of scene will do some good for Williams and
the Braves, who worked out briefly at Yankee Stadium Monday after
dropping the first two games of the World Series in Atlanta over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday night's game, Williams is 0 for 8 and his
teammates have only seven hits among them.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will have vocal crowd support and would presumably
benefit from the switch to the American League rule allowing the
use of the designated hitter. But Williams, a Yankee from 1992
through 1996, dismisses thoughts of a home-field edge for the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at anything as excuses or an advantage,''
Williams said. ``I look at productivity. We've had a lack of
production. What we have to do is stack some hits together and come
out with a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   At 33 years old, Williams has been around long enough to make
many friends in baseball, but few are closer than two Yankees who
are stars of the defending champions: shortstop Derek Jeter and
center fielder Bernie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Gerald Williams, Jeter first shrugged and said
he had nothing to say. Then he began to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gerald's like a big brother,'' said Jeter, who is is eight
years younger. ``He really took care of me from the time I was 18,
my first spring training. He went out of his way to look after me
and give me advice. He took me out to eat. Right from the start,
when I was still in the minor leagues, he was nice. He talked to
me. First spring training, you're sort of wide-eyed, looking at all
the players. Gerald is the one guy who went out of his way to make
me feel comfortable. Even to this day, he lives in Tampa, and we
hang out every day in the off season. He's somebody I go to for a
lot of advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, in the visitors' clubhouse, Williams recalled the
teen-age Jeter as ``making the transition from the minor leagues to
the major leagues, and he had a lot of questions that he wanted
answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams added: ``I tried to answer them as best I could. Our
personalities are similar. We got along very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Bernie Williams, Gerald Williams said people
sometimes assume that they are related because they have similar
personalities and the same last name. He described Bernie Williams
as ``a very good person first, which is consistent with a lot of
guys that I have a certain kind of connection with.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's most important to be a very good person first
because if you are not, who cares what the professional is? You can
only play so long. But you will be a person for the rest of your
life. Indeed, Bernie and I have a lot of history. We are very good
friends. But, right now, Bernie's up 2-0, so friendship is out the
window, right?''
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves in the regular season, Williams batted .275 with
17 home runs and 68 runs batted in. For his career, Williams is at
.263 with 55 home runs and 240 rbi Williams was traded from New
York to Milwaukee during the 1996 season and came to Atlanta before
the 1998 season. That year, he batted a career-best .305.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter said he is glad that his friend has found a regular role.
``I couldn't be happier,'' Jeter said. ``A lot of times in this
game, you get labeled early on in your career. He was always
labeled as a fourth outfielder who never really got a chance. He's
got all five tools and he can play. And when he's been given the
opportunity, he's doing an outstanding job.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the post-season, Williams is batting only .222 with no
home runs and four rbi. He has only two walks in 54 trips to the
plate, not what would be expected as a leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, manager of the Braves, said Williams ``plays a big
role'' and implied that it will be crucial to the fortunes of the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't had many hits in the past six or seven games,'' Cox
said, ``but he can get hot at any time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
