<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ROSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC'S GRAY SAYS HE WAS TRYING TO LET ROSE `MOVE FORWARD' 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after his contentious interview with Pete Rose
before Game 2 of the World Series on Sunday night, NBC reporter Jim
Gray defended his tough questioning of Rose about whether he would
admit to gambling on baseball in order to be reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to be fair and give Pete a chance to move
forward,'' he said, adding that Rose had earlier that day answered
similar questions from the news media and could not have been
surprised by Gray's questions.
</P>
<P>
   Rose described the interview as a ``prosecutor's brief.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said that he didn't believe his style was aggressive or his
tone antagonistic. ``Not with the responses I was getting and the
questions I was being asked by Pete,'' he said. ``I thought it was
very fair. I wasn't aggravated. I didn't have an agenda.'' But, he
added: ``Replaying it in my mind, one could see how that may be the
impression of somebody. There was no intentional act of
belligerence.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview loosed a wave of critical phone calls to NBC's
headquarters and its affiliated stations and e-mails to the NBC
Sports Web site at MSNBC.com.
</P>
<P>
   Gray made one concession to angry fans. ``Last evening, as
always, I was trying to do my job to the best of my ability,'' he
said. ``If the fans felt that the interview went on too long,
particularly on a night of special celebration, then I'm sorry for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray's interview was praised by John Dowd, whose investigation
into Rose's gambling led to the player's exile, and by Fay Vincent,
the former baseball commissioner who was Bart Giamatti's deputy at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tip my hat to Jim Gray,'' Dowd, who compiled a 225-page
report on Rose's gambling, told The Associated Press. ``I thought
he had more guts than any guy I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent said that Rose ``continues to say such absurd things as,
`show me the evidence.' Since Gray really knows the story, he knows
the evidence is all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he had no intention of interviewing anyone beside
Rose, who was one of 18 members of the 30-man all-century team that
was introduced before the game. Rose received the longest and
loudest ovation of any team member.
</P>
<P>
   NBC went straight to the Rose interview after the ceremony,
which produced a weird shift from a happy moment to an unusually
tough pregame conversation. Gray said he did not want to ask a
standard question about what it was like to stand beside Johnny
Bench or Ted Williams in the limited time he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an outpouring of fan support for him and I thought
at this time and moment, with him on a field for the first time in
10 years, he might have taken the chance'' to show contrition and
admit to gambling on baseball, Gray said. As he had before, Rose
refused to admit that he had bet on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Gray thought it was ``possible'' that Rose might make the
confession. ``Was it realistic to expect it?'' he said. ``Much more
realistic than at any time in the past 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Gray said, Rose wasn't visibly angry. ``He just said
he knew it was going to be all about gambling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said no players, including the Yankees Paul O'Neill and Jim
Leyritz, who publicly criticized the interview, confronted him at
Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of guys said something, but nothing exceptional, or
anything to be concerned about,'' he said. ``It seemed to be
innocuous.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plane back to New York Sunday night and again at the
Yankee Stadium clubhouse Monday, however, Yankee players talked
about the possibility of boycotting Gray for the rest of the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Ebersol, the chairman of NBC Sports, said, ``I find a
boycott unimaginable. People have too much respect for Jim. And the
Yankees are too professional for that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
