<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNOBLAUCH WON'T LET DEMONS WIN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The solid single on an 0-2 fastball that Chuck
Knoblauch remembered being ``up and in'' was almost lost in the
machine-gun fire of hits that followed. Someone had to make first
contact against Kevin Millwood, though. Someone had to send the
comforting message to the Yankee dugout Sunday night that Millwood
would not be blowing smoke on what became a very chilly World
Series night for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about getting that leadoff guy on,'' Joe
Girardi said Monday in the warmth of the confident Yankees
clubhouse. ``In a big game like that, it's what ignites the emotion
to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the battleground that is Knoblauch's psyche, there have
been dueling post-season realities, but indications that one side
is advancing. One side is winning. It is the part of Knoblauch that
refuses to surrender to the virus in the communications linkup
between brain and arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be the first to admit that I've had trouble with my
throwing,'' the second baseman said. ``But no one's going to stop
me from going out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Courage is an overused word in sports, and trauma sounds trite
on the morning after an airplane crash tragically defines true
loss. Yet in the context of human imperfection examined through the
lens of the national television cameras, there is something
wonderfully stubborn about Knoblauch's insistence that no one will
eventually remember how his throws _ those delicately floated and
painfully aimed _ reached first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to roll it over there, I'll do it,'' he said. ``And
in the book, all it'll say is 4-3.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been so much said about Knoblauch's throwing
dysfunction, and not enough credit for the way he has, especially
in the post-season, made the best of a bad situation. How he has
found a way to improvise, in the way the Yankees find ways to win.
Frame by frame, the network breaks down his startlingly flawed
mechanics. Inning by inning, Knoblauch survives, two games from
another title.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have scrutinized him, derided him, will have to kiss
his ring when he gets it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Morgan's the worst, and I hope you print that,'' Knoblauch
said Monday, defiant to a fault. ``I think he forgets that he
played the game once. Go back, check his records and see if he was
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, the NBC analyst and Hall of Fame second baseman, has a
job. So does Knoblauch. Beyond the breakdowns, Knoblauch's and
Morgan's, is a penetrating cynicism in sports that borders on
intolerance for those who are suffering, but not from the more
easily comprehended, more conventional, torn rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've heard of other guys who have gone through stuff like
that,'' Scott Brosius said. ``But anything you're dealing with,
you've got to deal with head on. There's no place to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several ways of retreating, of quitting, without
actually disappearing. When he might have gone into a defensive
shell, Knoblauch has been present and accountable at the top of Joe
Torre's lineup. His first-inning hit in Game 2 on Sunday night
began a three-run rally. His eighth-inning sacrifice bunt between
Greg Maddux and Brian Hunter in Game 1 left the Braves in an
inescapable mess.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Knoblauch's opposite in the Braves' lineup, Gerald
Williams, is 0 for two games. ``There's offense, there's base
running, there's taking pitches,'' Knoblauch said. ``All people
want to talk about is the throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   His throwing, not the balls fired wildly by Texas infielders, or
Boston's, or Atlanta's. Granted, Knoblauch's problem is
tantalizing, mystifying. Everyone has an opinion, a suggestion. If
Knoblauch had asked, I would have told him to concentrate on moving
his feet, and let his right arm do what it instinctively knows to
do. A tennis instructor once told me to try that on those awful
days when I have somehow forgotten how to hit a forehand, my best
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch wasn't seeking advice from any weekend hacker, or
anyone else. Not right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell him to fire it, over my head, if he has to,'' Tino
Martinez said. ``Why he doesn't, I don't know. I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not the time to try to figure this all out. Knoblauch is
in the middle of the Yankees' infield, in the middle of a World
Series. He still snaps off a strong throw _ like the pivot on
Sunday's fifth-inning double play _ when there is not time to think
and his feet are properly aligned to throw.
</P>
<P>
   On all other plays, he is, figuratively, just trying to wing it.
Just trying to win. A year ago in the playoffs, he was assailed for
not chasing an errant throw, and deserved it. Not now. Now he
deserves no ridicule, just respect. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
