u s BC-BBO-PETTITTE-COX     10-25 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PETTITTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pettitte thrust intospotlight after season of trade rumors
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andy Pettitte gets his turn now, not that there's any
bargain in that.
</P>
<P>
   After Orlando Hernandez and David Cone held Atlanta to just two
hits in 14 World Series innings, Pettitte starts tonight and, yes,
the numbers make him a little uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I went more than five innings without giving up
more than one hit in may career,'' he said. ``Yeah, that's not too
much of a concern when I'm trying to follow those two acts.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Yankees cannot recall exactly why the team did not
trade Pettitte away last summer (or the summer before that), this
should be a refresher. It is the postseason and there are worse
things than having Pettitte on the mound. He is uncertain about the
best game he's ever thrown, but it was either last week in the
ALCS-clinching Game 5 against Boston or his work in Game 5 of the
1996 World Series in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the starters, when we were talking with one another, we
knew if we were going to win this thing, it would be our
pitching,'' Pettitte said. ``We've got some guys who have been
there and we're able, I guess, to focus a little bit more maybe
whenever we get in tough situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Without intending to, Pettitte just delineated the different
performances by the two Series rotations and why New York holds a
2-0 edge. But that it is Pettitte doing the delineating might be
unusual, given how the Yankees worked so hard to deal him away at
midseason.
</P>
<P>
   New York's thinking was Anaheim's Chuck Finley would give the
Yankees a more experienced left-handed arm, in addition to the
mental toughness that some in the organization insisted Pettitte
lacked. At 5-7 (5.59 ERA) at the All-Star break, Pettitte was
rumored for weeks to be on his way out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It knew it was out of my control if the organization wanted to
get rid of me,'' he said. ``I was going through a struggle and
there was nothing else I could do. I couldn't work any harder.''
</P>
<P>
   It eventually paid off, though pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre
worked more on his confidence more than any mechanical adjustment.
Pettitte was 9-4 in the second half with a 3.84 ERA, lowest among
Yankee starters.
</P>
<P>
   Now making his fourth career Series start, Pettitte faces
Atlanta for the third time, and after the Braves carved him up in
Game 1 of the 1996 Series (six hits and seven runs in 2 1/3
innings), he has made amends.
</P>
<P>
   He wound up beating the Braves in Game 5 that fall and last
October won the clinch game against San Diego that brought the
Yankees the championship. Moreover, he has not given up a series
run since the mauling by Atlanta, bringing a 15 2/3-inning
scoreless streak to Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He also will be pitching on eight days' rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always concerned about that,'' he said. ``I'm not a guy
that likes to go on a lot of rest, especially pitching here in
Yankee Stadium. The crowd gets so into it. Sometimes the juices get
flowing too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
