<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SEASON IS AN ICEBERG NOT AN ICICLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scariest line heard around the Los Angeles Kings dressing
room last Friday wasn't coming from inside, where coach Andy Murray
was laying into his team for a lousy effort against the Phoenix
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   It came from a passerby looking for either the bathroom or an
exit to the parking lot. ``Hey, do you know if the Lakers won?''
</P>
<P>
   Less than three days after the Staples Center opened, the Kings
buzz had moved on with one fan. The team's one-month window _ when
they are the only game in town _ was closing.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, the posh club for season-ticket holders that was
jammed on opening night had about a dozen stragglers _ albeit a
dozen stragglers in either sequins or spandex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, they looked really bad tonight,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   There will be plenty of nights to party at the new arena, but
the city of Los Angeles has to realize that the Kings' season is
not a sound byte, it is a six-month process. It will include great
moves by Ziggy Palffy, bad passes by Aki Berg, defensive lapses by
Ziggy Palffy and great penalty kills by Aki Berg.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a race to the Stanley Cup. This team is not equipped
to go that far this year. But it is a playoff team and well worth
following for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   Knee-jerk reactions are not solely an L.A. thing. In Montreal
where he grew up, Luc Robitaille would need a wig and fake mustache
to go out after scoring one goal in five games after scoring seven
in the first week.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey is a sport finding its way in the U.S. even if it has
been here forever. And that goes for the hockey hotbeds, where
people frequently talk about Los Angeles as LA-LA Land.
</P>
<P>
   __ Vanbiesbrouck back: In Philadelphia, there nearly was civil
unrest when the Flyers began the season 0-5-1. There was talk they
needed to get rid of overpriced underachiever Eric Lindros, who
wants no part in leading the team. And they were writing obituaries
about 36-year-old goaltender John Vanbiesbrouck.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Sunday night, the Beezer, as he is known to those who
subscribe to the Hockey News, recorded his third consecutive
shutout as the Flyers killed off their 18th straight penalty in
winning their fourth in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Vanbiesbrouck has gone 214 minutes, 27 seconds without giving up
a goal, just short of his career record of 218 minutes, 42 seconds,
set last January. Of his three shutouts, two came last week against
the New York Rangers, then Sunday's against his other former team,
the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a dead man.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if deep down it felt great to shut out teams that had
given up on him, Vanbiesbrouck said, ``Somewhere not so deep
inside. You think about it. I have a great amount of respect for
Florida and their organization. There is some personal satisfaction
just because you know the people over there a little bit closer.''
</P>
<P>
   In savvy New York, where the World Series resumes tonight,
diehard Rangers fans are crushed.
</P>
<P>
   After the two straight losses to the Flyers, they dropped their
third consecutive shutout to the Vancouver Canucks and their former
captain Mark Messier, who led them to Stanley Cup glory just five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since Messier left town two years ago, the Rangers have not made
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that Messier, now 38 years old, is a shell of
his former greatness who was outplayed on Saturday by former Kings
center Olli Jokinen, now with the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have the league's highest payroll at $58 million and
its worst power play. The crowd got excited earlier when the team
won three straight and free-agent signee Theo Fleury was scoring a
few goals.
</P>
<P>
   Not they think that's all gone. Hey, the season just started. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Come back, Primeau: Carolina is off to a 4-2-3 start without
holdout center Keith Primeau, who doesn't look like he'll be back
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes tied the Maple Leafs 3-3 on Wednesday in Toronto,
Primeau's hometown. He was seen around town in an NHL union jacket
but didn't visit his teammates and declined interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   Primeau's agents, Don and Todd Reynolds, recently met with
Carolina GM Jim Rutherford, but the impasse continues. Don Reynolds
said the club rejected a five-year deal worth more than $4 million
annually. Primeau, a restricted free agent, already had rejected
the Hurricanes' offers of five years for $20 million, two years for
$7 million and two years for $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The agents have not asked that Primeau be traded. Carolina
insists he won't be, saying the only way he'll get more than $3
million a year from the 'Canes is if the team has to match a
lucrative offer sheet; Primeau is not likely to get one. Both sides
say they are prepared to wait each other out for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't good for a team that is just 2 for 26 on the power
play or has sold just 6,000 season tickets in its new arena in
Raleigh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
