<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-RATINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BCS: It's FSU, Penn St.
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If college football's regular season had ended Saturday, Florida
State and Penn State would be playing in the Sugar Bowl for the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   That was the verdict of the first Bowl Championship Series
ranking released Monday night, which had Florida State No. 1 and
Penn State a No. 2 by a half-point margin over No. 3 Virginia Tech.
Once-beaten Tennessee was a distant fourth, followed by undefeated
Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS standings use four components to establish a numerical
ranking for college football teams: the average ranking of the two
major opinion polls (Associated Press media poll and USA Today/ESPN
coaches poll); the average ranking in eight computer polls (with
the lowest ranking thrown out); a strength of schedule rank; and a
team's losses, which count one point each in the formula. The lower
the total, the higher the team is ranked.
</P>
<P>
   These rankings will be released weekly until Dec. 5, when the
top two teams in the final BCS ranking will be picked to go to the
Sugar Bowl, which will be played Jan. 4 in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State (8-0) had the lowest total and thus the No. 1
ranking, because it was No. 1 in both major polls and was ranked no
lower than second in seven of eight computer polls. Its No. 4
ranking in the Dunkel Index was thrown out. FSU's strength of
schedule, now at 21, figures to only get better with games
remaining against Virginia (4-3), Maryland (5-2) and Florida (6-1).
</P>
<P>
   Penn State (8-0) edged out Virginia Tech (6-0) for No. 2 thanks
to its strength of schedule. The Nittany Lions' schedule is No. 8
while Virginia Tech of the Big East is No. 42. Penn State's
schedule will get stronger as it faces Illinois, Minnesota,
Michigan and Michigan State down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, if Florida State and Penn State win the rest of
their games, they will meet in the Sugar Bowl regardless of what
Virginia Tech does.
</P>
<P>
   But if one or both of those teams struggle, the door will be
open for Virginia Tech, Tennessee, Kansas State or Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has lost to Florida, Tennessee is ahead of unbeaten
Kansas State because its schedule is ranked No. 4 while K-State's
is 43. Florida, ranked No. 6, could improve its strength of
schedule by beating Georgia this week. The Gators still have a date
with No. 1 Florida State and would face a ranked team should they
reach the SEC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech (5-1) is ranked No. 7 in both major polls but is
No. 8 in the BCS rankings. Its current strength of schedule, now at
No. 64, figures to improve with games against N.C. State, Clemson,
Virginia and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   1.Florida State
</P>
<P>
   2.Penn State
</P>
<P>
   3.Virginia Tech
</P>
<P>
   4.Tennessee
</P>
<P>
   5.Kansas State
</P>
<P>
   6.Florida
</P>
<P>
   7.Nebraska
</P>
<P>
   8.Georgia Tech
</P>
<P>
   9.Wisconsin
</P>
<P>
   10.Texas
</P>
<P>
   11.Miss. State
</P>
<P>
   12.Michigan
</P>
<P>
   13.Alabama
</P>
<P>
   14.Marshall
</P>
<P>
   15.Michigan State
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
