<SLUG> BC-PLAYMATE-BILLIONAIRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS JUDGE SAYS HIS COURT HAS SOLE JURISDICTION OVER FORTUNE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
 
By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Texas judge on Monday said former Playmate of the
Year Anna Nicole Smith can pursue her bankruptcy claims in Los
Angeles, as long as the federal court there does not try to divide
the estate of her deceased billionaire husband.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County Probate Judge Mike Wood said his court has sole
jurisdiction over divvying up the fortune of Houston oil tycoon J.
Howard Marshall II, estimated at $200 million to $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The estimates are divergent because most of Marshall's wealth
was tied up in Koch Industries stock, a Wichita, Kan., oil pipeline
and mineral conglomerate that is the nation's second-largest
privately held company. Since the company is private, its value is
in dispute. According to Forbes magazine, the company earned $700
million last year on sales of $35 billion, 18th in sales among all
U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said he has jurisdiction over the estate because the
probate lawsuit was filed first in Harris County after Marshall's
death in 1995 at age 90. A trial is to begin in Wood's court Jan.
24.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said rulings made May 20 by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Samuel
Bufford in Los Angeles may have already infringed on his
jurisdiction here. But he said he will ``wait and see'' what
happens in Bufford's court in the near future before reaching a
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the bankruptcy court has any jurisdiction to
enter any order on the estate,'' Wood said. ``It strikes me that
reading the order from May 20, it does interfere with the estate.''
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy trial is scheduled to begin Wednesday in Los
Angeles. Bufford's May 20 order stipulated that Smith and E. Pierce
Marshall of Dallas are entitled to ``share equally'' in the estate
and Koch Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Bufford's decision was not based on the merits, but as a way to
sanction E. Pierce Marshall, 60, the youngest of two sons, for
allegedly destroying evidence and not showing up for depositions.
The younger Marshall claims his father willed him the entire
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   His attorneys deny that they or their client did anything to
warrant such sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's attorney, Tom Cunningham, told Wood on Monday that
Bufford's rulings do not affect the estate because Smith is suing
E. Pierce Marshall personally in bankruptcy court, and she is
making no claim there against the estate. He also said Bufford has
indicated he will ``not step on the toes'' of the Harris County
court and that his May decisions could be retracted.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's finally got her day in court; she's finally got a judge
to listen to her,'' Cunningham told Wood. ``Now they're trying to
come to you and say shut it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it would be ``unprecedented'' for Wood to issue an
injunction in an attempt to stop the bankruptcy proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Wood was skeptical that the May 20 rulings would not encroach on
his jurisdiction, but said he would ``accept Mr. Cunningham's
representations,'' for now.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said it seemed to him that, with one exception, all
the legal claims Smith is making against E. Pierce Marshall in
California appear to infringe on his jurisdiction
</P>
<P>
   E. Pierce Marshall's attorney, Don Jackson, said all the claims
Smith is pursuing against his client in bankruptcy court are
inexorably linked to the estate. Smith is suing E. Pierce Marshall
personally, on grounds that he fraudulently transferred estate
money to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Although E. Pierce Marshall's attorneys asked Wood to halt the
Los Angeles proceedings, they said Monday that Wood's statements
will likely protect their client adequately.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said Smith's attorneys are seeking a judgment in
bankruptcy court that would determine what she is owed by the
estate. Smith is claiming she is entitled to at least $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the bankruptcy court would be unable to render a
monetary judgment without ruling on issues under the sole
jurisdiction of the Harris County court, including determining
Koch's value and whether it is part of the estate.
</P>
<P>
   Under a living trust signed by J. Howard Marshall II in the
early 1980s, all his interests in Koch was gradually transferred
from his estate to a company called Marshall Petroleum Inc., which
today is owned by E. Pierce Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   E. Pierce Marshall's attorneys are claiming that Smith is only
entitled to a portion of the estate, but that MPI is not part of
it. They have said the estate has no more money in it.
</P>
<P>
   J. Howard Marshall II's eldest son, J. Howard Marshall III, has
also sued, claiming he is owed half of the family wealth and that
his brother fraudulently deprived him of his share.
</P>
<P>
   Both the claims of Smith and the eldest son are based on oral
contracts they allegedlyd into with J. Howard Marshall II.
The 1992 will, which they claim is invalid, does not mention either
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, also a former Guess? jeans model, said she agreed to
marry Marshall in 1994 after he promised he would will her half of
his wealth. She claims she met Marshall in 1991, when she was a
19-year-old topless dancer in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   She filed for bankruptcy in 1996 because of mounting bills and
what her lawyers called ``questionable lawsuits'' against her,
including a libel suit filed against her by E. Pierce Marshall. The
son intervened in the bankruptcy case to protect his interest in
the suit, and Smith countersued him there.
</P>
<P>
   J. Howard Marshall III, 63, who owns a Los Angeles company that
makes devices to test X-ray machines, claims his father promised
him half of the estate for cooperating in a 1980 matter involving
Koch Industries. He asked last week to be allowed to intervene into
the California bankruptcy case to protect his interest in the
estate, but Bufford denied the motion, his attorney James Hartnett,
Jr. of Dallas told Wood on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
