u w BC-PLANE-STEWART-1STLEDE     10-25 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-STEWART-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OPEN GOLF CHAMPION AMONG THOSE KILLED IN PLANE CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS lede and grafs 2&AMP;3 to correct details and add background;
adds new 10th graf (bgng `The FAA said...' with details on
passengers and identity of possible sixth passenger; adds 2 lines
to end of 13th graf (bgng `In a conference call...') with details
on time of crash and flight path; subs   4th graf from end to add
that both passengers were killed in 1997 crash. ) 
(ATTN: Fla., Texas)  (See also STEWART-OBIT) 
(ART ADV: Two graphics, one depicting the flight route and the
other showing Stewart's career highlights, are being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Learjet that took off from Orlando, Fla., Monday
morning, carrying the golfer Payne Stewart and apparently five
others, traveled a wayward path across the country for four hours
with no one at the controls shadowed by Air Force jets that watched
it finally crash in a South Dakota field. Everyone on board,
including the two pilots, was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators said the pilots appeared to have lost
consciousness or died, possibly from a lack of oxygen, shortly
before they were supposed to turn west toward Dallas, their
intended destination.
</P>
<P>
   The plane crashed after running out of fuel, ending the life of
one of golf's most recognizable figures, known as much for his
traditional knickers and tam-o'-shanter as for his achievements on
the course. Stewart won his first major tournament, the
Professional Golfers' Association championship, in 1989, and
followed it up with a victory in the U.S. Open two years later. But
he went into a slump, and his success tapered off over the next
seven years. In this year's Open, in June at Pinehurst in North
Carolina, he outdueled Phil Mickelson by sinking a 15-foot putt on
the last hole. It was the longest putt to ever decide the Open on
the final hole.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart had been headed for a tournament in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The twin-engine, high-performance, $2.5 million jet, which can
carry eight passengers, left Orlando at 9:19 a.m. The pilots' last
contact with air traffic controllers was routine, at about 9:45,
when the plane was northwest of Gainsville, Fla. But the pilots
stopped responding to air traffic controllers soon after.
</P>
<P>
   Controllers at the Federal Aviation Administration's
Jacksonville center called the Air Force, which dispatched planes
from Tyndall Air Force Base, near Panama City, in northern Florida;
from Eglin Air Force Base, in the Florida panhandle; and from bases
in Tulsa, Okla., and Fargo, N.D. An Air Force F16 pilot reported
that there was no movement in the cockpit and the plane appeared to
be on autopilot.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Chris Hamilton, another Air Force pilot, reported that
the windows of the Learjet were fogged, possibly a sign that the
cabin had become so chilled with stratospheric air that the
moisture in the cabin atmosphere had spread itself like dew or
frost on the windows. That may have been from loss of cabin
pressure or from smoke on board, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said, ``It's a very helpless feeling to pull up
alongside another aircraft and realize the people inside that
aircraft potentially are unconscious or in some other way
incapacitated.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's nothing I can do physically from my aircraft even
though I'm 50 to 100 feet away, to help them at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said two crew members and three passengers were on the
jet, including Stewart's agents, Robert Fraley and Van Ardan, and
two pilots, Michael Kling and Stephanie Bellegarrigue. But the
golfer Jack Nicklaus said he believed that a golf course designer
who works with him, Bruce Borland, was also aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Under a standing Pentagon rule, called ``instructions for
destruction of derelict airborne objects,'' an out-of-control
aircraft can be shot down, with permission from the president, if
it threatens public safety, said Major Michael G. Birmingham of the
U.S. Army, a spokesman for the North American Aerospace Defense
Command, which coordinated the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds kind of cold but that's what it is,'' said
Birmingham, adding that he did not believe that a plane had ever
been shot down under the policy.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with the FAA and the Pentagon, Air Force
officials considered shooting the plane down, Birmingham said, but
concluded, about an hour and seven minutes before the crash, that
the plane, which was flying northwest, would come down in a
sparsely populated area in South Dakota. In their preliminary
reports, the FAA put the time of the crash at 1:26 p.m. and the Air
Force put it about nine minutes earlier. Preliminary radar data
showed that the plane made a U-turn, doubling back in the last few
minutes of the flight, but investigators have not verified this.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was informed of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   After the crash, investigators from the National Transportation
Safety Board rushed to the scene but had little hope of retrieving
useful information from the cockpit voice recorder, because it had
a standard tape loop of only 30 minutes, and the incident took over
four hours.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said cabin depressurization was a key suspect in
disabling the pilots, but that it was also possible that smoke or
some other problem was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The plane was equipped, as airliners are, with a red light and a
horn, which pilots cannot turn off, to warn when the atmospheric
pressure inside the cabin is equal to the pressure outside at
10,000 feet. If the pressure in the cabin reaches the pressure
outside at 14,000 feet, oxygen masks for the passengers are
supposed to drop automatically.
</P>
<P>
   One air safety investigator who is not directly involved in this
crash said that depressurization ``could be very insidious.'' He
explained that the problem could slowly deprive the crew of its
ability to know what was happening. ``It could be one of those
things where you're feeling good, you're feeling happy, and you
don't know what's going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some planes have suffered ``explosive decompression,'' or sudden
loss of pressure, but the initial impression of experts was that
this did not happen on Monday because the plane continued to fly
for hours with no apparent structural damage, which would be
expected with a sudden loss of pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA was unable to say Monday precisely when it had concluded
that the pilots had stopped responding, but at 10:08 a.m. ET,
planes were sent from Tyndall Air Force Base. At 10:22, an F16 and
an A-10 from Eglin, already in flight, were diverted to catch the
Learjet, but only the F-16 made it.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who was flying the F-16, broke off a half hour later
to land at Scott Air Force Base, near St. Louis, for lack of fuel,
and four F-16s from the Oklahoma Air National Guard, on a training
mission over Kansas, gave chase but never caught up. Later, F-16s
from Fargo, N.D, found the Lear and watched it spiral through the
clouds, probably because one of its two engines had run out of
fuel, and crash.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian interceptors were waiting on their side of the border
in case the plane made it that far, Birmingham said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, a Lear 35 built in 1976, was operated by Sun Jet
Aviation, of Sanford, Fla., near Orlando. It had been cleared to
39,000 feet by controllers in Jacksonville, according to James E.
Hall, chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board, who
said it had reached 37,000 feet at the time of the last contact
with the crew, at 9:44.
</P>
<P>
   The Lear carried an autopilot system that could keep the nose
pointed at a constant compass heading and could maintain an
altitude or a rate of climb. It may have been set to maintain a
rate of climb but stopped at 45,000 feet, the maximum altitude the
model can reach.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout its flight, whether the crew was incapacitated or
dead, the plane itself continued to function. A transponder, or
radio beacon, continued to broadcast the plane's identity and
altitude as it was interrogated by FAA radars en route.
</P>
<P>
   Accidents in which pilots are disabled or killed in planes that
then fly for hours on autopilot are rare but not unprecedented. In
January 1997 the pilot of a four-seat Piper Dakota took off from
Long Island and was overcome by carbon monoxide leaking in through
the heating system; as his 71-year-old mother took the controls and
radioed for help, a flight instructor in an interceptor plane
rushed to her assistance. But the mother, too, was overcome with
the gas, and the plane flew to northern New Hampshire, where it
crashed, killing both.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980 an earlier model Lear had a similar accident, flying
from Shreveport, La., into the Atlantic off Virginia, also
apparently on autopilot. The plane carried Bo Rein, the Louisiana
State University football coach.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas A. Williams, a commercial pilot with 7,000 hours of
experience in Learjets, said that if the altitude warning system
went off, the proper procedure was to contact air traffic
controllers and drop to 10,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   A pressure loss could have been too gradual for the crew to
notice, he said, ``but I can't imagine the airplane's warning
system not working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0546 </DOCNO>
