u f BC-LATIMES-ARENA-NYT &LR;      10-25 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIMES-ARENA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER MAGAZINE SHARES PROFITS WITH A SUBJECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Except for its girth _ 164 pages _ the Oct. 10 issue of The Los
Angeles Times Magazine did not appear to be unusual. Its sole theme
was the new Staples Center sports arena, but newspaper magazines
often devote entire issues to one topic, like fashion or
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   But what was far less common was a financial arrangement between
The Times and the arena. According to the executive editor of the
magazine and a manager who worked on the project in its early
stages, the newspaper and the arena shared the profit from the
issue. The manager, Holly Bowyer, confirmed that the issue brought
in more than $2 million in advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual for a newspaper to share profits with an
institution that is the focus of continuing news coverage. The
arrangement, which provoked anxiety in the newsroom, evolved from a
broader business contract, signed last year, that makes The Times
one of 10 ``founding partners'' _ a version of corporate
sponsorship _ of the Staples Center. It gives The Times a corporate
box and allows it to advertise around the arena, according to two
managers on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Times officials declined to comment on the arrangement. The
communications director of the Staples Center did not return three
messages left on his voice mail Monday afternoon. The center is
owned by three main investors: Philip Anschutz, a Denver
billionaire and a large shareholder of Qwest Communications; Ed
Roski, a wealthy real estate executive, and News Corp., which holds
a 40 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The arena, which cost $400 million to build, is home to the
Lakers and Clippers professional basketball teams and the Kings
professional hockey team . It is the centerpiece of a downtown
renewal movement supported in editorials by the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between advertising and news has been a source
of anxiety in the newsroom of The Times since 1997, when Mark
Willes, then the newspaper's publisher, announced that he would
foster closer ties between the business and news sides of the
paper.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing two years, the anxiety had dissipated somewhat in
the absence of any evidence of business-side interference with the
newsroom. But recent events _ like the Staples-Times profit-sharing
arrangement _ have rekindled it.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine issue on the Staples Center provoked enough concern
on the part of the city editor, Bill Boyarsky, that he resisted
allowing his reporters to be associated with it. ``I was concerned
because this was an advertising-generated issue of the magazine,''
Boyarsky said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Boyarsky added that after he arranged to have the main
responsibility for a critical examination of whether the Staples
Center could help revive downtown Los Angeles, he dropped his
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Drex Heikes, the executive editor of the magazine, said that he
did not know about the profit-sharing arrangement until about 10
days ago, when a business executive came into his office and asked
him to calculate what the news department had spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The content of the magazine was exclusively controlled by
editorial,'' Heikes said. The magazine had perhaps a dozen articles
of varying lengths, including a profile of Anschutz by The Times'
sports editor, Bill Dwyre; an examination of various personalities
who put the arena deal together, and the exploration of the urban
renewal issues.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bowyer, who had until earlier this year been the magazine's
general manager _ a position developed under Willes' aegis to help
coordinate the efforts of the news and business departments _
confirmed on Monday the outline of the profit-sharing agreement but
would not say what percentage each side would get.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Goldstein, a spokeswoman for Times Mirror, the
newspaper's parent, declined to comment on the arrangement except
to say, ``We don't talk about contractual relationships with our
advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that with the Oct. 10 issue of the magazine,
``Editorial was in full control of the content.'' She continued,
``Advertisers were interested because the Staples Center is very
important to the rebuilding of downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the profit-sharing arrangement was first
disclosed last week in New Times, one of the city's alternative
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Parks, the editor of The Times, said in a telephone
interview on Sunday: ``I really don't know the details on Staples.
It was a very complex arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he and John McKeon, the newspaper's senior
vice president for advertising, had advised the publisher, Kathryn
Downing, against planning a similar, 200-page special issue of the
magazine to coincide with next summer's Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were discussions of what to do in terms of the
Democratic convention and whether we could do a magazine'' pegged
to that event, he said, adding, ``Both John McKeon and I advised
the publisher that 200 pages was not a realistic thing,'' because
they doubted that either reader or advertiser interest would be
sufficient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
