<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS ROOKIE PRODUCING HIGHLIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Lamar Odom exhibition-tour highlight reel is
threatening to grow into a mini-series. The early reviews are
promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the most spectacular things I've ever seen,''
said Los Angeles Clippers assistant coach Jim Todd, referring to a
scene the 6-foot-9, four-position rookie produced in the second
half of Sunday's 104-93 victory over Seattle at Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   If you only see one Odom highlight, his teammates said, this was
the one. Until the next game.
</P>
<P>
   After a quick trip to the replay booth, we offer something less
than justice for Sunday's play that began with Odom getting bumped
off balance on a long defensive rebound. With the ball still up for
grabs, Odom went horizontal to retrieve it while surveying the
court ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   What he saw was Tyrone Nesby speeding toward the Clippers hoop.
To complete the play, Odom _ a lefty _ whipped a right-handed,
behind-the-back bounce pass to Nesby, who took it in stride and
finished with a polite jam.
</P>
<P>
   Odom left Spokane with an impolite 19 points, a game-high 14
rebounds and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a special kind of player,'' said teammate Maurice Taylor,
who had 27 points and 9 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   After the Clippers' weekend sweep _ they won at Vancouver on
Friday _ Odom is averaging 17 points and eight rebounds per game.
By making 15 of 24 shots, he improved his field-goal percentage
from 39 to 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still learning,'' coach Chris Ford said. ``The entire
season is going to be a learning experience.''
</P>
<P>
   That could go double for players assigned to guard him.
</P>
<P>
   __ Reality check: While the Clippers finished the exhibition
road trip at 4-2, they realize that only one of their six foes _
Phoenix _ finished the previous season in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made some strides,'' Taylor said, ``but we're not where
we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford said he'll remain picky about two areas that require
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to continue to get better defensively,'' he said,
``and what goes hand in hand with that is rebounding. There has to
be a conscious effort from all five guys on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want gang rebounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, whose meager rebounding last season was indirectly
included in owner Donald T. Sterling's list of reasons for
withholding a lucrative contract-extension offer, checked in with
20 over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody tells me what I !ital!can't do, I show 'em what
I !ital!can do,'' the power forward said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fast breaks: Eric Piatkowski (sore ribs) didn't play in the
Seattle game and Derek Anderson (back spasms) was forced to leave
the lineup early. Both are expected to play in Wednesday's
exhibition home opener vs. the Milwaukee Bucks at Staples Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
