<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-WIRELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ALLIANCE WILL PROMOTE WIRELESS ACCESS TO INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of leading technology companies said Monday that they
would form an alliance to create products that would allow
consumers to get high-speed Internet access through a wireless
system within the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium _ which is led by Cisco Systems Inc., the giant
Internet networking company, and Motorola Inc., the maker of
wireless telephone products _ is essentially backing an alternative
to delivering broadband Internet access through underground cables
and wires.
</P>
<P>
   The race to bring broadband Internet access to consumers has led
to several alliances that promise to deliver that kind of service
through satellites, cellular telephone networks and standard cable
and telephone lines. Now, the group headed by Cisco and Motorola is
trying to provide a cheaper and more effective solution to digging
up the ground and laying cables: They want to deliver data, voice
and video services over the airwaves and directly into buildings
and homes that are affixed with antennas or the equivalent of a
satellite dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the technology that is going to take the fixed
broadband wireless market into the next millennium,'' said Steve
Smith, director of marketing in the broadband wireless business
unit at Cisco Systems, which is based in San Jose, Calif. ``This
gets consumers Internet access without tearing up the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Cisco Systems said Monday that a group of 10
companies _Motorola, Texas Instruments, Broadcom, Bechtel
Telecommunications, Samsung, Toshiba, LCC International, EDS, KPMG
Consulting and Pace Microtechnology _ had agreed to create and
develop products that use a Cisco technology, one that is equipped
to deliver Internet service over a radio frequency called MMDS.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that the AT&AMP;T Corp. was moving into cable television and
developing a system capable of delivering high-speed Internet
access through its cable services, MCI Worldcom and Sprint have
spent about $1 billion in the last few years to buy many of the
companies that owned the licenses to the MMDS radio spectrum. Three
weeks ago, MCI Worldcom agreed to acquire Sprint in a $115 billion
merger.
</P>
<P>
   If the technology is successful, it appears that Internet
service providers will be able to choose among cable operators,
wireless service providers and perhaps even satellite operators
like Teledesic LLC, which is developing a kind of ``Internet in the
Sky'' technology, a multibillion-dollar plan backed by the cellular
telephone pioneer Craig McCaw and William H. Gates of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems and Motorola are also backing something called
LMDS, which is another radio frequency that offers broadband
access, mostly to businesses. According to Cisco officials,
however, the MMDS system is more effective in crowded urban areas
and is more easily available to everyday consumers and the mass
market.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Edwards, a spokesman at Motorola, which is based in
Schaumburg, Ill., said Monday that the company was backing both the
LMDS and MMDS technologies and working to develop a large portfolio
of offerings so that big technology companies and consumers could
have a wide range of alternatives to getting broadband access.
</P>
<P>
   The companies involved in the agreement Monday said that the
ability to deliver high-speed broadband access through a wireless
system would also rapidly accelerate the introduction of broadband
services to rural areas and urban centers, and do so more easily
and inexpensively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0549 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8320 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-STEWART-OBIT-COX     10-25 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEWART-OBIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Payne Stewart, professional golfer, dead at 42
 &HT;    (EDS: MOVING TO (A) GENERAL NEWS AND (S) SPORTS CATEGORIES.)
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ With his trademark knickers and tam
o'shanter cap, Payne Stewart never had a problem standing out in
the crowd. Neither did his game.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, one of the most recognizable and talented golfers to
play the game, died Monday when a private plane he was on crashed
in South Dakota, killing all passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Most golf fans will remember Stewart, the reigning U.S. Open
champion, for his fashion statements. But it was his game and
personality that caught the eye of other top professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``That smooth swing, the plus-fours, his tongue-in-cheek wit ...
that's what I'll remember most about Payne,'' Jack Nicklaus said.
``He always had a little bit of a needle out. He always had fun
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 42, had plenty of reasons to smile during a career in
which he won 18 times around the world, with three majors among his
11 PGA Tour titles. He was just finishing the best season of his
20-year career, highlighted by his second U.S. Open victory and a
spot on the U.S. Ryder Cup team. He was third on the PGA Tour's
1999 money list with more than $2 million in earnings and stood
eighth in the world ranking of golfers.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of Stewart pumping his fist in the air after he made a
15-foot putt on the final hole _ the longest such putt to win a
U.S. Open _ remained an indelible impression with most golf fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much left for him,'' Nick Price said. ``That's
what makes this so tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart also won the 1989 PGA Championship and the 1991 U.S.
Open, which should earn him a ticket to the World Golf Hall of
Fame. After the second U.S. Open victory, Stewart credited his
new-found faith for helping to carry him through some difficult
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so much more at peace with myself than I've ever been in
my life,'' he said. ``Where I was with my faith last year and where
I am now is leaps and bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was traveling Monday from his Orlando home to Dallas,
where he was to play in a corporate outing before going to Houston
today for the PGA Tour Championship. Two other golfers from
Orlando, Stuart Appleby and Lee Janzen, had considered flying to
Texas with Stewart until they learned he was leaving a day early
because of the outing.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Stewart's death _ which took more than four hours to
confirm because the plane flew out of control before crashing when
it ran out of gas _ left the golf world stunned. Before the plane
crashed, stars such as Mark O'Meara, Janzen, Ernie Els and Scott
Hoch already had rushed to Stewart's home to comfort his wife
Tracey and their two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an enormous void and emptiness I feel right now,''
Tiger Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer called Stewart's death ``one of the most terrible
tragedies of modern-day golf.''
</P>
<P>
   USGA president Buzz Taylor, who handed the championship trophy
to Stewart at Pinehurst, said: ``The first thing that came to my
mind was Tony Lema (who died in a plane crash after winning the
1964 British Open). What a loss he was for the game, and I feel the
same way about Payne.''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour said Stewart's spot in the elite Tour Championship
field will not be filled. A blue ribbon was attached to his
nameplate in the parking lot and the flags at the club and at the
Tour's headquarters were flown at half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to express our sense of shock and sadness over
the death of Payne Stewart,'' PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem
said. ``This is a tremendous loss for the entire golfing community
and all of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of Stewart's death was also felt in Europe. Stewart
proudly displayed his patriotism while playing in five Ryder Cups,
but even during last month's controversial matches at Brookline _
when the Americans were criticized for celebrating too much _
Stewart was praised by the European team for his show of
sportsmanship. He was particularly critical of some fans' abusive
treatment of Colin Montgomerie during their singles match, and told
Montgomery he would speak to hecklers if Montgomerie wished.
</P>
<P>
   Masters winner Jose Maria Olazabal had to choke back tears when
he spoke of Stewart's death. ``A true sportsman on the course and a
gentleman off it. We have lost a precious man and someone who still
had good years ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the players who kept both feet on the ground and
didn't get carried away,'' said Jupiter. Fla.'s Jesper Parnevik.
``I know Montgomerie spoke very highly of him after the last round.
Payne always had a big heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when Stewart won the 1987 Bay Hill Classic, he donated
his entire winner's check to an Orlando hospital in memory of his
father, William, who had died of cancer two years earlier. He was
very active in many other charitable ways in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Success didn't come easy for Stewart. After turning pro in 1979,
it took the Springfield, Mo., native two years to make the PGA
Tour. Then he promptly lost his playing card and supported himself
by playing in Asia and Australia, where he met his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget Payne was a journeyman pro who had to work his
way onto the PGA Tour,'' Price said. ``He made himself into a great
player.''
</P>
<P>
   He also made himself marketable when he decided in 1982 to wear
knickers as a way of drawing attention to himself. ``I won my first
tournament that week,'' he said, ``and the rest is history.''
</P>
<P>
   But by donning the knickers, Stewart was doing more than trying
to make endorsement money. He was trying to be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne didn't want to be another blond-haired, blue-eyed
golfer,'' Mark Calcavecchia said. ``He wanted to make a statement.
It took a lot of nerve to wear some of those outfits _ I remember
one of them where he looked like a giant bumblebee. But he always
said what was on his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Price: ``He was always a firm believer in what he believed
in.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a comedic side to Stewart. Just ask Paul Azinger,
who holed a bunker shot at the final hole to beat Stewart in the
1993 Memorial Tournament. When Azinger went to his locker after the
round, he found bananas in his shoes, compliments of you-know-who.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne was always so upbeat, the life of the party,''
Calcavecchia said. ``I never saw him down, even when he wasn't
playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart managed to transform his game where he was sometimes
referred to as ``Avis'' (because he finished second so often) into
a cinch Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question he's in the Hall of Fame,'' Nicklaus said.
``He won three majors and there's not 10 guys in the world who can
say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many fans will undoubtedly remember Stewart simply as the
guy who wore the knickers. Those who knew him best said that
wouldn't be right.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear people talk about his knickers all the time,'' said
close friend and fellow pro Larry Rinker. ``But let's face it, if
he hadn't won those three majors and wasn't on TV all the time, the
knickers wouldn't have mattered. People should remember him for
what he did, not for what he wore.''
</P>
<P>
   Also killed were Stewart's agents, Robert Fraley and Van Ardan,
and the two pilots, identified as Michael Kling, 43, and Stephanie
Bellegarrigue, 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Post reported late Monday night that Bruce
Borland, 40, also died in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Borland's wife, Kate, said she contacted the private jet
terminal Monday afternoon and spoke to an employee who had greeted
her husband and confirmed he intended to board the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dolch writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. The Associated Press contributed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
