<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-VECSE     10-25 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKEE FANS MUST GUARD THEIR GUESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Something happened in Atlanta in recent days that was
bizarre by New York standards. Yankee fans bearing the ``NYY''
emblem on their caps, jackets and shirts were allowed to attend the
World Series games unmolested.
</P>
<P>
   As Goya scribbled on his sketches from the battlefield, this I
have seen:
</P>
<P>
   _ Yankee fans riding the Marta trains and buses, chatting with
Braves' fans: ``You guys have great pitching but we've got Jeter
and Williams.'' And nobody got beat up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Norman and Sandra Bell of Lithonia, Ga., with son Brandon, age
9, and daughter, Teylar, age 5, all with Yankee caps, strolling
safely through the corridors of Turner Field. Wise parents would
hesitate to bring children in visiting insignia to a New York ball
park, out of fear of our lionized bullies.
</P>
<P>
   _ People with Munson and Mattingly jerseys chanting ``Go _
Yankees _ Go!'' in unison from their seats. Let's be honest: the
reverse could not happen in Shea and Yankee stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd get the daylights beaten out of you,'' admitted Steve
Kahn, originally from Flanders, N.J., now living in Birmingham,
Ala., whose brother, Bruce, flew down for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think something should be done,'' Steve Kahn said of
the antisocial behavior in our home region.
</P>
<P>
   The best time to stop the self-indulgent crudeness is Tuesday
night in Yankee Stadium for the third game of the World Series. The
Yankee fans are surely more vociferous than the sedate Atlanta
fans, who had little to cheer over the weekend anyway, but this is
not about good honest noise. This is about violence. It is time for
the civil people left in New York to show some leadership and not
allow the louts to browbeat fans of other persuasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just New York, it's a lot of places,'' said Stan
Kasten, originally from New Jersey, but now the president of the
Braves and Hawks. ``The fans in the Northeast take it more
seriously than anywhere else, but we've all got to do a better job
to make it more pleasant at the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasten was being polite. It is drastically uglier in Fenway
Park, where some fans rioted over a few bad umpiring calls in the
league series, and in Veterans Stadium in Philadelphia, where some
fans cheered the sight of an inert (and nearly paralyzed) Michael
Irvin of the Cowboys, and in Yankee and Shea stadiums where, during
the playoffs, I heard language and saw aggression that would fit
the out-of-towners' stereotype of rampant back-street New York
muggers.
</P>
<P>
   But these were not, technically, criminals. These were people
who could afford tickets to playoff games. These were fans who
drove home to the suburbs in sport utility vehicles. On a few
snootfuls of very expensive beer, they were using something as
trivial as a ball game to take out their anger at, well, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   I saw New Yorkers snatch Braves and Red Sox caps off the heads
of visitors. I heard people yell things that would inflame a
rational person, to say nothing of a hothead like John Rocker, the
Braves' reliever. Tom Glavine and John Schuerholz of the Braves
have spoken of the batteries and invective hurled at their
families. To paraphrase Walt Kelly, we have met the enemy and it is
our brothers and our sons.
</P>
<P>
   The cretins get away with it because we think it is cute. One
New York tabloid treats the Yankee Stadium Bleacher Creatures as if
they were funny rather than borderline sociopaths. We shrug and
say, ``Hey, it's New York.'' I hope not. I'm a lifelong New Yorker,
but I've about had it with the creeps at our ball parks.
</P>
<P>
   Things were much sweeter at the ball park in Atlanta, a city I
have grown to like since the end of the 1996 T-Shirt Shack
Olympics. People are nice. For all the image of Atlanta's becoming
a city of corporate transients, there are enough locals left who
say ``good morning'' to strangers, who chat while waiting for a
bus.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantans say that when they visit New York, people help them
with directions and praise their mellifluous accents. Alas, when
visitors buy tickets to our stadiums, they face physical
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, that diehard Yankee fan, and
George Steinbrenner, who blusters about law and order, should
insist that security forces actually protect visitors. Up to now,
when a visitor has his ball cap ripped off his head, the Stadium
ushers shrug as if to say, ``Hey, what did you expect?'' Atlanta
fans have the same right to cheer as Yankee fans did in Turner
Field. If we don't stop the assaults, the championships are
tainted. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
