<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0552 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NCAA-WOMEN-NYT &LR;      10-25 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN NEARER TO EQUALITY, NCAA SAYS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, the NCAA predicted that it would take 10 to 12
years to achieve equality in men's and women's athletic programs at
its member schools.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are still inequalities, according to a report
issued Monday by the NCAA, more women are participating in
intercollegiate athletics and more women are receiving athletic
scholarships, with parity projected in just six years.
</P>
<P>
   Since the association issued its last report on disparities
between the sexes in 1997, the number of women participating in
athletics in Division I has increased by an average of 28 a school.
By comparison, the number of male athletes increased by an average
of 15 a school.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of all students on intercollegiate teams in
Division I are women, the report found. The proportion was 37
percent two years ago. Women attending Division I schools received
41 percent of scholarship dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such gains, NCAA officials said they felt movement
toward equality was occurring too slowly. They said, for example,
that in every division except I-AAA, at least two-thirds of the
recruiting budgets were spent recruiting athletes for men's teams,
and that head coaches of men's teams received about 60 percent of
salary expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improvements are being made, but being made much too slowly,''
Cedric Dempsey, the president of the NCAA, said in a news
teleconference. ``To be fully committed to providing opportunities
for all athletes, we must continue to add programs for women and
dedicate more resources to women's programs on our campuses at a
faster rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey pointed out that Division I schools spent an average of
$172,000 on recruitment for men and $72,000 for women. ``That's
just not good enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 83-page report was based on a survey of NCAA member schools
conducted in the fall of 1998. Nearly three-quarters of the 747
colleges and universities responded to the survey, which helps
track compliance with Federal regulations at colleges. Similar
studies have been conducted since 1991, with the findings were
published in 1992 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA officials were so disheartened by the disparities found in
the 1997 report that Dempsey said if progress continued at that
rate, it could take 10 to 12 years to reach parity.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the new survey left him cautiously optimistic.
``Looking at the growth we've seen these past two years, we should
achieve our goal in six years,'' he said. ``I'm encouraged by the 3
percent growth from where we were two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Levick, who heads the NCAA's committee on women's
athletics, said parity in intercollegiate athletics would be
achieved only when women reached the 50 percent mark in
participation, scholarships, recruitment and salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're at 40 percent participation, 41 percent in
scholarships, 30 percent in recruiting, 40 percent in head coaches'
salaries and 21 percent for assistant coaches,'' Levick said.
``We've made progress, but until we get percentages equal, we
haven't hit our mark.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
