r f BC-SANDPIPER-WEBSITES-LA     10-25 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDPIPER-WEBSITES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL BUYS OUT NET FIRM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON Z. COHEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, CALIF. -- Sandpiper Networks went public through
a side door by agreeing to be bought by San Francisco-based Digital
Island in a deal valued at $1 billion by the time the financial
markets closed.
</P>
<P>
   Investors caught on quickly Monday, driving Digital Island's
stock sharply higher to a closing price more than 68 percent above
its opening value.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Garrahan, technology analyst for Lehman Brothers
Securities, said the merger puts Sandpiper in the public arena well
ahead of competitor Akamai, which has an initial public offering
scheduled for later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're effectively going public by being bought,'' Garrahan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sandpiper and Akamai have systems to move Internet content
closer to the user, speeding download time.
</P>
<P>
   If Akamai prices in the middle of its expected range, its market
capitalization after the initial offering would be $1.5 billion,
Garrahan said.
</P>
<P>
   By that comparison, he said Digital Island is getting a bargain
at the price it is paying for Sandpiper.
</P>
<P>
   Investors apparently agreed, trading in Digital Island's stock
as if it were a fresh new offering. More than 12 million of the
company's shares changed hands Monday after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The stock ended trading at $38.6875, up $15.6875 per share on
the day.
</P>
<P>
   The combined companies will be able to share their abilities for
better service, Garrahan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination gives them a fuller end-to-end solution to
their customer,'' he said. ``It allows them to sell more services
to current customers. It lets them both to deploy their services
faster using the strengths each one has.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the merger, which is subject to approval by shareholders
and regulators, Digital Island Chief Executive Officer Ruann Ernst
will become CEO of the combined company. Sandpiper CEO Leo Spiegel
will be president.
</P>
<P>
   Sandpiper shareholders will receive 1.07 shares of Digital
Island stock for each share they own.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 27.4 million shares of Digital Island stock will be
issued in the transaction. At Digital Island's Friday close, the
merger had a value of $630 million.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day Monday, the price tag had climbed to $1.06
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials, who could not be reached Monday, said in a
joint statement the combination will allow Sandpiper and Digital
Island to offer their services as a package to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Island provides Internet hosting and commerce
capability, and Sandpiper offers speedy content delivery to the
mix.
</P>
<P>
   Garrahan said he expects the combined company will have fiscal
2000 revenues of $46 million. The following year, Garrahan is
projecting revenues of $117 million. The company is expected to
begin generating profits some time in fiscal 2002, he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
