<SLUG> BC-THQ-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THQ EXPECTED TO POST HIGH EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON Z. COHEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, CALIF. -- Even without new offerings from its two
major product lines, video gamemaker THQ Inc. is in position to
report strong growth in its earnings, analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among Wall Street analysts is that THQ will show
third-quarter earnings of 30 cents per share when it reports
Tuesday, despite a lack of fresh titles coming out of its
professional wrestling and Rugrats lines.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Stuart Halpern of Banc of America Securities said he
wouldn't be surprised if THQ's earnings report _ expected to be
released before the market opens _ contains better results than the
First Call consensus estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``THQ has a very long history of exceeding expectations. There
is a definite upside to that number based on the strong
fundamentals and based on some good product success,'' Halpern
said. ``Even if all they do is make the estimate, they're showing
phenomenal growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's earnings for the same period a year ago were 21
cents per share, 42.9 percent lower than the estimate for this
year's third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern, who is bullish on the video game sector as an industry,
said hardware makers are selling more machines, creating more
demand for the software to run on them.
</P>
<P>
   The company's license with World Championship Wrestling has
expired, but it expects to begin shipping games under license from
the larger World Wrestling Federation some time in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern said the video game sector is poised for a busy holiday
season, which he predicts will be its best ever.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
