<SLUG> BC-PLANE-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIME OF MOURNING AMONG GOLFERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Also see PLANE-STEWART, OBIT-STEWART) (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The area around this tourism destination is home
to many of the best touring professionals, including Payne Stewart,
who died in a plane crash Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A pro-am tournament at the nearby Bay Hill Club and Lodge, the
site of the Bay Hill Invitational in March, was in progress when
word came that Stewart had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made a lot of people sick,'' said Bob Usher, an employee
at the club. ``About 70 percent of them dropped out of the
tournament.'' The flag at the club was lowered to half staff.
</P>
<P>
   The dropouts included fellow PGA players Mark O'Meara and Lee
Janzen, both friends of Stewart. They, along with John Cook, Ernie
Els, Scott Hoch, Ian Baker-Finch, Larry Rinker and Frank Nobilo
later went to the Stewarts' home in a rural area southwest of
Orlando to help comfort Stewart's wife, Tracey, and their two
children, Chelsea, 13, and Aaron, 10.
</P>
<P>
   Three Orange County sheriff's deputies stood guard outside the
gated home. Also there was Ken Williams, a Stewart family friend,
to help police identify friends.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer declined to be interviewed as he left the Bay Hill
club, where he was host of the tournament. ``There's too much going
on right now,'' said Palmer, who was headed to the airport to fly
to Pennsylvania to see his wife, who is ill.
</P>
<P>
   Orange County Sheriff's Deputy Scott Lynch was first to arrive
at the Stewart family home, at 1 p.m. Within an hour, the place was
swarming with members of the news media, and many were still there
after nightfall arrived. Family friends arrived periodically; Lynch
estimated that upward of 100 cars passed through the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Ray Wood, a family friend, said Stewart had been stalwart
in helping a police fund-raising event for children every
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a super person with a huge heart,'' Wood said. ``You'd
see him down at the grocery store and he'd speak to everybody. His
kids played in the youth leagues; in fact, sometimes Payne would
umpire if they needed it. He was just a regular guy, except that he
won three majors and 18 tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fraley, 46, a prominent sports agent, was also killed in
the crash. Among his clients were four current or former National
Football League coaches: Bill Parcells of the Jets, Bill Cowher of
Pittsburgh, Dan Reeves of Atlanta and Joe Gibbs, formerly of
Washington. He also represented Seattle Seahawks defensive tackle
Cortez Kennedy and Mets pitcher Orel Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   Fraley's father, Charles, said his son and Stewart were good
friends who often golfed together and at one time lived near each
other in the same Orlando subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were real close,'' he said. ``In fact, Robert was
godfather to his children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
