A8441 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MANDELA-COX     10-25 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANDELA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mandela urges Mideast to defy `prophets of doom'
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former South African President Nelson Mandela left
office in June. In July, he turned 81 years old. Yet one would be
hard-put to describe him as having retired.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela spoke in Atlanta on Monday night, fresh from a tour of
the Middle East. He outlined his proposals for peace in that region
_ proposals that call for a complete Israeli withdrawal from all
Arab lands seized in the 1967 war. He scoffed at those who say that
will never happen, saying he has ``confounded the prophets of
doom'' more than once in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's proposal has three parts: the Israeli withdrawal; a
``firm and unequivocal declaration'' from the Arab states that they
recognize Israel's right to exist within secure borders; and the
creation of an international commission to monitor the
implementation of the Arab commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No proud Arab leader will engage in negotiations with Israel
as long as Israel continues to occupy Arab territories she
conquered in the 1967 war,'' Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he added that Israel had acted in self-defense in 1967 and
could not be expected to yield the territories without being
assured of its security.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela said he had discussed his proposals with many leaders in
the region, as well as with President Clinton and other world
leaders. He said serious political leaders had told him it would be
impossible to persuade the Israelis to withdraw from all occupied
territories, but he disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   He said people had predicted that apartheid could not be
overthrown in South Africa without the spilling of ``rivers of
blood.'' And he said people had predicted, too, that he would never
persuade Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi to turn over the suspects in
the bombing of Pam Am flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We confounded the prophets of doom,'' Mandela said. ``We did
precisely what they said was impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Mandela said, it is necessary for an outsider to help
participants in a struggle, such as that in the Mideast, to
understand the problem in its totality.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are dealing with a problem that has been there a long
time,'' he said, ``you reach a point where nobody is perfectly
correct and nobody is perfectly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela came to Atlanta to participate in an Aspen Institute
conference on closing the ``International Poverty Gap.'' He said he
had been invited to an important conference in Asia, but chose
instead to come to Atlanta out of respect for former President
Jimmy Carter, who also participated in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Carter and Mandela lavished praise on each other Monday.
Introducing Mandela, Carter praised his personal courage and said,
``I don't think there's a beating heart here that wasn't stirred
when our speaker was released from prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, in turn, praised Carter for his dedication to working
``with the poorest of the poor.'' And both men took turns
criticizing what they said is the ever-increasing gap between the
world's rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
   The similarity between the two men did not end there. Mandela's
post-presidential activities look an awful lot like Carter's. Not
only has Mandela just finished a round of shuttle diplomacy in the
Middle East, something Carter has done more than once, but he also
has established the Nelson Mandela Foundation, which appears
similar to the Carter Center.
</P>
<P>
   The goals of Mandela's organization: promoting international
peacemaking and eradicating ``the degrading scourge of poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Melvin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
