<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING 52, MRS. CLINTON FEELS LIKE RAISING A MILLION, AND DOES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With skits, songs and speeches, a lineup of Broadway
stars celebrated Hillary Rodham Clinton's 52nd birthday Monday
night in a mix of politics and high-cost entertainment that helped
her raise close to $1 million for her expected campaign for the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and President Clinton took their 10th-row aisle
seats at the Ford Center for the Performing Arts in Times Square at
7:45 p.m. _ 45 minutes late _ and the curtain immediately rose to
reveal the actress Christine Pedis, dressed in a blond wig and a
black pantsuit, singing ``I'll Take Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the audience, who had paid up to $1,000 for a seat,
howled with laughter upon realizing that Ms. Pedis was
impersonating Mrs. Clinton. They cheered when a dancing line of
cast members from ``Chicago,'' dressed in blue-and-white Yankee
jerseys and caps, joined her in a slightly altered version of ``New
York, New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These Washington blues, are melting away,'' Ms. Pedis sang.
``If she can make it through, she'll make it anywhere,'' the chorus
line echoed. ``Come on, come through, New York, New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's event was notable because it was one of the few
times that Clinton has campaigned with his wife since she began her
exploratory effort.
</P>
<P>
   Although some Democrats have expressed concern that Clinton
might, in the waning days of his presidency, become something of a
drag on his wife's campaign, aides to the Mrs. Clinton said they
welcomed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is an asset,'' said Howard Wolfson, her
spokesman. ``He carried counties in the state that no president has
carried in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening act at Monday night's Broadway salute set the tone
for a comical, if clearly, pointed night. Mrs. clinton laughed
along with the audience at the obvious parody of one of her bigger
political obstacles _ the portrayal of her as an out-of-towner
trying to make it in New York _ as well as the reminder of her
attempt to portray herself as a Yankee fan by plunking a Yankee cap
on her head at a White House ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell was the moderator, and from the outset, she made
it clear that if Mrs. Clinton was the honoree of the night, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, Mrs. Clinton's expected Republican opponent, was
the target.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cast of `Smokey Joe's' wanted to be here tonight, but the
mayor had them arrested outside for loitering,'' Ms. O'Donnell
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the actor Alec Baldwin took the stage briefly to encourage
members of the audience to help Mrs. Clinton raise even more money,
he said: ``I thought we'd take a moment to remind everyone why
we're here _ which is because we're going to kick Rudy Giuliani.''
He was drowned out by cheers.
</P>
<P>
   The evening started with a reception at the Supper Club and
ended with a private dinner for big donors at the Russian Tea Room.
It included a diverse group of entertainers, including Mia Farrow,
who read from Mrs. Clinton's book, ``It Takes a Village,'' Chita
Rivera and the Gay Men's Chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, introduced at the first event by Edward Koch, the
former mayor, clearly seemed delighted by all the birthday
attention (her birthday is actually Tuesday and appeared to drop
any pretense that her interest in a race for Senate was only
exploratory.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to work to make it possible for every New Yorker to
feel that they have a vote and a voice in the Senate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's day of raising campaign funds came as Giuliani
showed signs of spending some of his own on his likely campaign.
His aides began making inquiries about purchasing television time
statewide in November.
</P>
<P>
   That would mark an extraordinarily early start for advertising
in the Senate campaign, though it would be in keeping with the
early pace of this race. Bruce J. Teitelbaum, who is head of
Giuliani's political action committee, declined comment on the
campaign's intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The speeches and the performance came in yet another night of
New York fund-raising featuring Clinton, though the president's
appearance was unusual for one reason: the beneficiary was his
wife. Clinton's frequent trips to the city have been on behalf of
either his own candidacy, the Democratic National Committee or the
party's congressional committees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
