<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORD TO ADD SAFETY BARS TO ITS BIG PICKUP TRUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor plans to install hollow, energy-absorbing steel bars
below the front and rear bumpers of all of its industrial-sized
pickup trucks in the 2001 model year to reduce the risk that they
will ride over cars in crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is also studying adding such bars to four-wheel-drive
versions of its big Ford Expedition and Lincoln Navigator sport
utility vehicles and the F-150 pickup truck to make them less
dangerous to other motorists.
</P>
<P>
   OIL PROFITS RISE, BUT STOCKS FALL
</P>
<P>
   Large oil companies said that third-quarter earnings rose
substantially, with some more than doubling. But investors had
anticipated the gains because of the increased price of crude oil
and took profits. Even ARCO, which showed a sevenfold rise in
operating earnings, lost $3.125 a share, to $90.875.
</P>
<P>
   DREAMWORKS AND IMAGINE IN VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks SKG and Imagine Entertainment announced they would
create a new Internet entertainment company, to be called Pop.com,
and World Wide Web site with a variety of offerings for the rapidly
approaching digital entertainment world.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS FALTER ON PROFIT TAKING
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices weakened as traders, worried about higher interest
rates, took profits in large capitalization issues after last
week's bounce in major averages. The Dow Jones industrial average
fell 120.32 points, to 10,349.93; the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index slipped 8.02, to 1,293.63, and the NASDAQ composite index
edged down 0.57, to 2,815.95.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond prices recouped early losses. The yield on the
30-year bond, after climbing to a two-year high of 6.40 percent,
ended at 6.35 percent, up from 6.34 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN EXPRESS MEETS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   American Express said its third-quarter profit rose 13 percent,
to $648 million, or $1.42 a share, meeting expectations as
customers spent more with its credit cards and increased
investments with its financial planners.
</P>
<P>
   3M PROFIT GAIN TOPS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing, the maker of Post-It notes
and Scotch tape, reported a greater-than-expected 18 percent gain
in third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFETT LEADS MIDAMERICAN DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire Hathaway, the investment vehicle of Warren Buffett, is
leading an investor group that will buy MidAmerican Energy Holdings
for $2 billion. The price, $35.05 a share, represents a 29 percent
premium to Friday's closing. The Buffett group, which will also
assume about $7 billion in debt, plans to take the company private.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP PLANS WIRELESS NET ACCESS
</P>
<P>
   A group of big technology companies led by Cisco Systems and
Motorola said it planned an alliance to create products that would
allow consumers to get high-speed Internet access through a
wireless system.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. AND CHINA FINISH MEETINGS
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-Chinese talks brought no visible progress toward China's
proposed entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG BEGINS SHARE SALE
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's government begins reselling stock that it bought in
a massive market intervention a year ago. Analysts wonder if the
sale isn't too much for the market to bear.
</P>
<P>
   BMW RAISES STAKE IN ROLLS-ROYCE
</P>
<P>
   BMW raised its stake in aircraft-engine maker Rolls-Royce PLC
and gave Rolls control of the two companies' joint venture so that
BMW can focus on its money-losing Rover unit.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH GROUP TAKES BRAZILIAN STAKE
</P>
<P>
   A French aerospace consortium agreed to acquire a stake in
Embraer, the Brazilian aircraft maker, possibly giving the French
companies an advantage in bids to renovate Brazil's fleet of
fighter jets.
</P>
</TEXT>
