<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8453 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CRASH-SCENE-HNS &LR;      10-25 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SCENE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH AND FAMILY LED STEWART'S PRIORITIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Filed in ``a'' and ``s'' categories) 
 
By EDDIE SEFKO 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When professional golfer Dennis Paulson's airplane
touched down Monday in Houston, he instinctively did what he always
does upon exiting the jetway.
</P>
<P>
   He turned on his cell phone and checked his messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had three voice mails,'' Paulson said. ``The first two were
congratulating me for getting into the Tour Championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he clicked onto the third message and learned of the death
of PGA star Payne Stewart in an air tragedy Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made the first two calls seem pretty insignificant,''
Paulson said.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling shrouded Champions Golf Club on Monday. While
players began arriving at the Tour Championship, nobody could
concentrate on golf. Players, fans and tournament officials instead
were grasping for answers about how one of the most popular golfers
in the world _ who in the past few years had come to realize how
important his faith and family were to him _ could be gone so
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   A Learjet in which Stewart was a passenger crashed into a South
Dakota field Monday shortly after noon. Stewart, 42, was to have
traveled from Orlando, Fla., to Houston via Dallas, where he was
going to inspect some property he was considering purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, players who have competed on golf courses around
the world with Stewart began to realize something tragic had
happened. Flags at Champions were lowered to half staff. The
festive atmosphere of anticipation that always precedes a big golf
tournament suddenly became a somber pall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel bad for any family when a tragedy like this
strikes,'' said golfer Jim Furyk. ``But Payne is one of our own. He
was very dear to all of us, and this really hits home. There's
nothing I can say. It's just a terrible thing to have happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tragedy that could make anyone wonder why. Stewart was
enjoying the best season of his career. He had won more than $2
million on the PGA Tour this year and won the U.S. Open in July,
his third major championship and his 18th career victory worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But more important than what was happening on the course was
what Stewart called his personal triumphs. He had recommitted his
life to God in recent years. And with that came a similar
commitment to his family: his wife, Tracey; 13-year-old daughter,
Chelsea; and 10-year-old son, Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Stewart had reiterated that as the years had
gone by, he realized what was really important in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to blink and miss my family growing up,'' he
said after winning the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach Pro-Am in February. ``I'm
going to be a father. That's very important to me. Golf is
secondary to my family.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Stewart had life figured out.
</P>
<P>
   And then, it was taken from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's in shock,'' said Jeff Maggert of the nearby The
Woodlands, who counted himself among Stewart's close friends on the
tour. ``All you can say is you don't know what to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had grandparents pass away, but I've never had a friend
this close pass away. Payne was just a lot of fun to be around.
Payne made a point to be friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like he had a lot of respect for me and my golf game,
and I had a lot of respect for him and his ability. I don't have
that with a lot of players on tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggert said the U.S. Ryder Cup team, which overcame the biggest
margin in Cup history to beat the Europeans last month, became like
a fraternity, with Stewart one of the pledge chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he was everything I respect about a golfer,'' Maggert
said. ``He had the competitiveness, the ability to play under
pressure, his honesty and his feelings, good or bad. He was the
kind of person who could tell you something you didn't want to
hear. But he would step up and say it if he thought you needed to
hear it. He was just a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   One who will be remembered as much for who he was as what kind
of golfer he was. Stewart was a man who once donated his entire
winner's check from a PGA event to the Florida Hospital Circle of
Friends in his father's memory. And yet he was the guy in the funny
knickers who had such a sweet swing that other tour pros freely
admitted they would copy it if they could.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone ever saw Payne Stewart hit a golf ball, it was the
most beautiful, effortless swing you could imagine,'' said Ben
Crenshaw, who captained Stewart and the rest of the Ryder Cup team
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Stewart also was a showman. Because of the way he dressed,
he knew he would draw attention to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understood pro sports, but he also knew it was
entertainment,'' said fellow pro Tom Kite.
</P>
<P>
   But while the memories will live as Stewart's legacy, there was
no overcoming the sorrow Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what else to say other than to wish the best for
Tracey and the whole family,'' Furyk said. ``There's never a right
thing to say in this situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't prepare for something like this. It takes everybody
by surprise, and there's nothing I can say. It's a terrible thing
to have happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Said tour pro Duffy Waldorf: ``My reaction is shock. I was
driving down the freeway, and I got a call on my cell phone and
heard about it. I drove way past the golf course while I was on the
phone, just because my mind was on the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were calling to make sure I was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldorf was among the players in Orlando over the weekend for
the National Car Rental Classic. He said that if Stewart had
offered him a ride in his plane to the next tournament destination,
there was a good chance he would have accepted the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Payne had asked me to hop on the plane with him, I probably
would have,'' Waldorf said. ``This just makes you think of all the
times you've ever flown on an airplane. As pro golfers, we fly
everywhere. You never think of it as being a risky thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what you have to realize is that every day could be
your last. So you'd better live it to the fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire golf world felt Monday like Stewart got shortchanged
in days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you've lost a big part of the game,'' Waldorf
said. ``It's not something you can expect. And it's hard to deal
with. You're not used to having one of your good friends die.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never be able to replace Payne.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
