<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-TV-ART-NYT     10-25 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TV-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV ADS SHOW BUSH AS AN UPBEAT LEADER PROMISING A FRESH START 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the front-runner for
the Republican presidential nomination, unveiled his first
television advertisements Monday, and they cast him as a humble,
upbeat leader devoted to lower taxes and better education.
</P>
<P>
   In four commercials set to begin airing on Tuesday in Iowa and
New Hampshire, the states with the earliest Republican contests
next year, Bush keeps his wish list deliberately modest as he
offers the United States ``a fresh start,'' the thematic phrase
that concludes each spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that government should do a few things,'' he
explains in one advertisement, ``and do them well.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush's gaze is placid and his voice gentle, the
commercials represent his campaign's opening salvo in what will
undoubtedly be a bitterly fought and lavishly funded television air
war, among both the Republicans and the Democrats seeking their
parties' nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advertisements are designed in particular to anticipate _
and deflect _ any attacks on his political record in commercials by
the wealthy publisher Steve Forbes, a Republican rival who is
dipping deep into his personal fortune in an effort to neutralize
the unprecedented amount of money that Bush has raised. By Sept.
30, Bush's tally had topped $56 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers have said they are prepared, if necessary, to
spend up to $20 million on advertising in the four and a half
months leading up to the thick cluster of primaries in mid-March,
and Forbes' advisers have pledged to keep pace.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has had commercials on the air since June, an unusually
early start in a presidential contest, and while the advertisements
have not targeted Bush, Bush's advisers are girding for the kind of
negative attack Forbes waged against Bob Dole in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be championship wrestling at its finest,''
said Alex Castellanos, a Republican media consultant who is not
officially affiliated with any presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With the start of advertising campaigns by several candidates in
addition to Bush over the last few weeks, the presidential race has
entered a newly intense phase.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks ago, Vice President Al Gore, who is locked in a
tightening battle with former senator Bill Bradley for the
Democratic nomination, introduced his first television commercial,
a 60-second spot condemning the Senate Republicans' defeat of a
nuclear testing ban. Bush had sided with Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has since released two more television advertisements: a
60-second spot fleshing out his biography and a 30-second spot
stating his opposition to offshore oil drilling. These commercials
have run mostly in targeted areas like Iowa, New Hampshire and
California.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has yet to run a single radio or television commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell M. West, a political science professor at Brown
University who monitors political advertising, said that Bradley's
success in getting positive ``free media'' from news organizations
and his steady rise in the polls have allowed him to conserve
resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the luxury of waiting a while,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen.r John McCain of Arizona, who is arguably the most serious
Republican challenger to Bush, has not begun television
commercials, either, a reflection in part of a budget much tighter
than Bush's. McCain had raised about $9.1 million through Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain began airing three different 60-second radio
commercials in New Hampshire last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said their advertisements, each 30 seconds long,
would appear in many of the states with early primaries, but the
advisers would not release a schedule or spending figures.
</P>
<P>
   What is most striking about the first commercials is what they
do not contain: personal and biographical information. Advisers
said such an introduction to the candidate was not necessary,
because of the candidate's surname.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a terrific brand in American politics,'' said Mark
McKinnon, the chief media consultant in charge of producing the
spots. ``We don't have to waste a lot of time talking about where
he comes from. What voters are interested in knowing is what he
plans to do, what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four advertisements address that question head-on.
One focuses on Bush's stewardship of Texas and makes a specific set
of claims _ about Bush's role in cutting taxes and pruning
government spending _ that are intended to shore up his
conservative credentials and address the aspects of Bush's record
that Forbes is most likely to criticize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to fill in the blanks of who George W. Bush is and
what he's actually accomplished before things that are negative and
inaccurate fill the vacuum,'' said Ralph Reed, an adviser to the
Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also seems to be sending a warning to Forbes in an
advertisement in which Bush says, ``I believe oftentimes campaigns
resort to mud throwing and name calling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are sick of that kind of campaigning,'' Bush adds.
</P>
<P>
   This commercial, like two of the other three, prominently
features Bush talking directly to the camera or an offscreen
interviewer and indicates his advisers' believe that Bush's
personal warmth is one of his greatest assets.
</P>
<P>
   One advertisement focuses solely on Bush's ideas on education
and is densely populated by black and Hispanic children, reflecting
the campaign's repeated overtures to minorities. The Bush campaign
is also running a radio commercial in Iowa this week entirely in
Spanish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
