<SLUG> BC-GLF-STEWART-CADDIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART'S CADDIE HEARS NEWS AT COURSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EDDIE SEFKO 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Monday started out so normally for a couple of PGA
Tour caddies.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hicks, the caddie for Payne Stewart, and Brian Sullivan,
who loops for The Woodlands' Jeff Maggert, were at Champions Golf
Club in the cool morning hours walking the front nine of the
course.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart had missed the cut at the National Car Rental Classic
near his home in Orlando, Fla. Hicks flew home to be with his
family for a couple of days before coming to Houston. On Monday
morning, he decided to get a head start on learning the intracacies
of the Cypress Creek Course so he would be armed with accurate
yardages when Stewart arrived later Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the span of one hole, the wonderful morning turned into
uncertainty. And then tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just doing what we normally do,'' Sullivan said. ``We
were walking the course, making sure we had good yardages and then
Mike's cell phone rings as we're coming off the ninth tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of falls behind while he's on the phone and then when
we get up the fairway, he catches up and says, `You're not going to
believe the phone call I just got.'
</P>
<P>
   ``A pro at the club he belongs too in Raleigh (N.C.) called him
and said the plane Payne was on was having trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike told me that Payne was on his way to Dallas to look at
some property that they were thinking about buying (for a possible
golf-course design). He kind of staggered off the ninth green.
</P>
<P>
   ``And from there, pain turned into horror. We knew it was bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people know pro golfers as well as their caddies. And the
fraternity of caddies is a close-knit one. Players and caddies form
bonds that last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks wasted no time departing Houston. But Sullivan and others
were stunned about the news of Stewart's death when the plane in
which he was a passenger veered off-course and crashed in rural
South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not only a shroud over this tournament, but the rest
of this year,'' said Sullivan, who has been Maggert's caddie for
many years and is one of the most respected bag-haulers on Tour.
``And what about next year's U.S. Open. That's going to be a very
hollow event.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said the memories of Stewart will be what everybody in
the pro golf industry will try to concentrate on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wore the funny clothes,'' Sullivan said. ``We called it a
clown outfit. But Payne had the personality that he could take it
when you said that about him. And he'd dish it right back to you.
He was fun to be around because he was a fun person.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he was a champion's champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Champions Golf Club founder Jack Burke Jr.: ``His daddy
always told him that it was OK to be different. He encouraged him
to be different.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart certainly was.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's two lasting, defining moments will be the images of
him pumping his fists and hugging Hicks as the two celebrated his
15-foot tournament-winning putt at the U.S. Open in June and his
role in the incredible Ryder Cup comeback for the U.S. team against
the Europeans last month.
</P>
<P>
   After that comeback, the Americans celebrated unabashedly and
made no apologies for their partying. Europeans took offense, which
seems a little insignificant now.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last month, there's been a lot of criticism about the
Ryder Cup celebration, and some of that has been aimed at Payne,''
said Tour player David Ogrin. ``Doesn't that all seem petty right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
