<SLUG> BC-WTO-HERMAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR SECRETARY TOUTS WTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN and ARTHUR C. GORLICK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Clinton administration Monday opened the defense
of its vision for labor in the global economy _ calling for greater
worker protections in the midst of free trade _ by coping with
angry protesters seeking a greater voice and displaced Boeing Co.
workers.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton dispatched Labor Secretary Alexis Herman
to Seattle Monday to pave the way for his arrival at next month's
World Trade Organization meeting. Herman pledged to push for a
working group within the trade body that would address a litany of
labor concerns, including child labor and forced labor.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the administration hopes to make labor issues a
higher priority during the trade body's deliberations, Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO ``offers a chance to make a difference ... (and) put
labor at the center of trade problems,'' Herman said at a meeting
in Benaroya Hall on the impact of globalization on the world's
workers.
</P>
<P>
   In her one-day sweep of Seattle, Herman also took a closer look
at the global economy's impact on the Puget Sound region. She
visited a training center that is teeming with former Boeing
workers striving to adapt their skills for jobs outside the
aerospace giant.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton's administration's attempt to balance the needs of
workers with the demands of free trade hasn't pleased everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Activists greeted Herman with allegations that the president is
ignoring their concerns. For example, they claim multinational
firms dominate the WTO's agenda to the detriment of working people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fraud,'' yelled David Rice, a Seattle resident who
is protesting the policies of the World Trade Organization, as
Herman discussed trade and labor matters.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters held up a variety of handmade signs stating such
things as ``All talk, no change'' and other slogans.
</P>
<P>
   The protests are only a preview of the marches, demonstrations
and other events that are expected to greet delegates from 135
countries when they descend on Seattle for the start of a new round
of trade policy talks, Nov. 30-Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Herman defended the adminstation's record on labor
issues, saying it continues to make progress in stregthening global
labor rights. She repeatedly cited a recent international child
labor convention, designed to crack down on the use of child labor.
</P>
<P>
   But with the workforce and the workplace changing everyday, she
added that such accords are only the beginning, in an address
earlier in the day at downtown Seattle's Washington Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   She said other international bodies, such as the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund could also play a greater role in
protecting workers from abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, Herman may get a chance to address the
Puget Sound's struggles to adjust to the emerging global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based Boeing is a key player in many debates about
global trade as the nation's leading exporter. Growing competition
from rival Airbus Industrie has spurred the manufacturer to
streamline its operations and layoff thousands of workers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Herman visited a worker retraining center _ run jointly
by the International Association of Machinists and Boeing _
designed to help those workers land new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   As she toured the center, she talked with former Boeing
Machinists now seeking training and jobs in a wide range of fields,
from fiberoptics to airline mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   The center, however, can't keep up with the number of Boeing
employees flowing out of the region's plants. Currently, 500 people
are on the waiting list to tap the center's resources.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say that number is expected to grow in the
coming months as Boeing continues to seek greater efficiencies on
its assembly lines and copes with a downturn in airplane orders
</P>
<P>
   So, the center expects to seek additional federal funding _ on
top of the $20.4 million it received earlier this year _ in the
next month to help deal with the demand.
</P>
<P>
   Herman didn't publicly address the issue, and the IAM said
nothing has been decided, but she said today's workers generally
need ``skills to find new jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2332EDT &QL; 
