<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FRONT-ROW-NYT &LR;      10-25 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONT-ROW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWELRY BY TWO SISTERS IN STEP WITH THE TIMES  
 SHATOOSH AND ALLIGATOR: ONE OF THEM HAS A STIGMA ATTACHED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla., La.)  (mk) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Costly earrings, necklaces and bracelets _ the kind
one guesses supermodels wear with a bit more enthusiasm than the
sort they have promoted for lower-tier jewelers _ have become the
fastest-growing segment of the jewelry market. That must come as
little surprise in an era when millionaires are as commonplace as
expensive apartments. Still, it bodes well for two
jewelry-designing sisters who are about to open shop on the Upper
East Side (they already have a high-profile clientele from a first
store in Los Angeles and from a Manhattan showroom).
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 1, the Slane sisters, Landon, 33, and Heath, 34, who
grew up in North Carolina, will open Slane &AMP; Slane in a 1910 town
house at 30 E. 74th St.
</P>
<P>
   The Slanes, whose work is also sold at Ian Schrager's latest
hotel, the St. Martin's Lane in London, specialize in elegantly
modern _ which is to say, un-hippie-ish _ sterling silver pieces
priced from $125 to $1,200. They also design architectural pieces
in 18-karat gold, many with exotic stones, priced from $300 to
$40,000.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters took up jewelry design just a few years ago after
vigorous bouts of career experimentation. Landon Slane dabbled in
television production, social work and retailing in three different
cities before settling in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Heath Slane, who runs the Los Angeles store on North Robertson
Boulevard, designed menswear for Ralph Lauren, tried landscape
photography and served a stint in the art department at Details
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a real love of stones,'' Heath Slane said. The
sisters' clients include Gwyneth Paltrow, Sharon Stone, Serena
Altschul of MTV and the makeup artist Kevyn Aucoin, who bought many
of his Christmas gifts from the Slanes last year. They also make
cuff links for men and count Peter Duchin and Dominick Dunne among
their clients.
</P>
<P>
   With Stigma (and Without)
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry is mostly controversy-free. Shatoosh, another
high-priced indulgence, is not. The fiber derived from the wool of
the threatened Tibetan antelope, or chiru, is the basis for coveted
shawls costing upward of $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   But trade in shatoosh has been illegal since 1979 under the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild
Fauna and Flora, although that fact has not been widely known until
recently.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, a number of shatoosh-owning socialites, including
Nan Kempner and Beth Rudin de Woody, were subpoenaed by the U.S.
District Court in Newark, N.J., to testify before a grand jury
about how they had come to possess their wraps.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, building on the publicity that probe has received,
the World Wildlife Fund initiated a ``Don't Buy Shatoosh''
campaign. As part of the effort, the model Shalom Harlow plans to
write to fashion editors, encouraging them to alert readers to the
dangers to chirus, which are slaughtered by poachers for their
wool, and whose population has been reduced to fewer than 75,000,
George Schaller, a Tibetan wildlife expert, has estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a stigma attached to this product,'' said Ginette
Hemley, the vice president for species conservation at the World
Wildlife Fund. ``There's no problem with habitat. The biggest
threat to this animal is poaching because of this product.''
</P>
<P>
   An animal about which there is a reverse confusion these days is
the alligator. Last week at a fabric trade show at the Javits
Convention Center in New York, J. Don Ashley, an alligator-farming
consultant from Tallahassee, Fla., set up a booth with the menacing
14-foot skin of an American alligator, in an attempt to resurrect
domestic fashion interest in the reptile. It was removed from the
endangered species list by the federal government a decade ago. (It
is still listed as threatened under the wildlife protection treaty,
but skins can be traded as long as they are tagged and numbered,
meant to prevent poaching.)
</P>
<P>
   Today more than 50 percent of American alligator skins, most of
which are harvested from breeding farms or on private property in
Louisiana and Florida, are now exported to France. (John Galliano
showed a full-length alligator dress for fall.) But Americans are
apparently still squeamish about the skin. Ashley said that at
least 10 retailers and product developers who wandered by his booth
wondered, ``Is this really all legal?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes. The alligator population is thriving, said
Ms. Hemley of the World Wildlife Fund, because of sound
conservation and harvesting. ``The alligator is one of our success
stories,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
