<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
90 GROUPS IN NEW YORK STATE APPLY TO OPERATE CHARTER SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ninety groups have applied to open charter schools in New York
state next year, including 35 whose schools would be run by
profit-making companies, state officials announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest batch of applications include 27 from New York City,
mostly in Brooklyn and the Bronx. But applications also poured in
from groups throughout the state, including 9 in Buffalo, 11 in
Rochester and 14 on Long Island. The number of applications has
soared since last winter, when only 15 groups applied for the first
round of charters.
</P>
<P>
   The State University of New York can grant 50 charters under a
state law passed last December, and the State Board of Regents can
issue 50 more. The first eight applications were approved in June,
and three of those schools opened in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proves that there is broad interest from people all
across the state who want to provide a new kind of choice in public
schools,'' said Robert J. Bellafiore, executive director of the
Charter Schools Institute, an arm of the SUNY board of trustees.
Under the state's charter school law, the trustees decide which
applications to approve.
</P>
<P>
   The applications will go through a complex review process, and
the SUNY trustees will make a final decision in January. Although
the state has room for 92 additional schools, not all of those
charters will be granted for next fall, Bellafiore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bellafiore said he was not surprised by the large number of
profit-making companies, like Victory Schools and Edison Schools,
that want to run charter schools, which are publicly financed but
independent from their school districts. In New York, such
companies have to join with nonprofit organizations if they want to
open charter schools. But the companies can run the day-to-day
operations of the schools.
</P>
<P>
   The companies typically provide enough money to get a school
running, and in return, they keep a percentage of the annual state
aid that the school receives.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the companies interested in running the next round of
charter schools are already running schools in other states,
Bellafiore said. Victory Schools is running New York City's first
charter school, the Sisulu Children's Academy in Harlem, and hopes
to open five more next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Bellafiore said it was too early to know how successful Sisulu
and another for-profit school, the New Covenant Charter School in
Albany, would be at making money. ``Frankly, most of the companies
view this as a long-term investment,'' he said. ``But I've visited
both of these schools several times, and they have demonstrated
what we believe to be structured, effective learning
environments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
