<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-BLUEMOUNTAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCITE (AT) HOME TO ACQUIRE BLUEMOUNTAIN WEB SITE FOR UP TO $1
BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the third item instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(DW) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Excite (at) home will pay up to $1 billion to acquire
Bluemountain.com, a privately held electronic greeting card company
with little revenue but millions of loyal users.
</P>
<P>
   Although a top-rated site on the Web, Bluemountain.com does not
actually sell anything. It was created in 1994 by two former
hippies, Stephen Schutz and Susan Polis Schutz, to be a ``spiritual
and emotional center for the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple, owners of the Blue Mountain Arts Publishing Co., a
successful paper greeting card and poetry publisher, decided to
give away E-greeting cards for free. Using only word-of-mouth as
advertising, Bluemountain.com swiftly grew to be one of the most
consistently popular sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   That popularity is what attracted Excite (at) home, which is
majority-owned by the AT&AMP;T Corp., serves as a gateway or portal, to
the Internet. Excite (at) home predicted that the acquisition would
increase its audience by 40 percent, to encompass approximately 34
percent of Internet traffic. With a 34 percent share, it would pass
the Disney portal Go.com for fifth position, right behind Lycos,
but still a long stretch from dominant players like America Online,
Microsoft and Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, the combined audience will allow both sites to
raise their rates for advertisers. Additional revenue will also
come from opening up Bluemountain to commerce like flowers,
chocolates and gifts. Stock analysts generally praised the move,
and Excite (at) home's stock gained 75 cents to close at $39.8125
as the overall market and technology stocks generally fell.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, Excite (at) Home will issue
approximately 11 million new shares, valued at approximately $430
million, and $350 million in cash. If Bluemountain.com meets
certain targets for holiday traffic, it will get as much as $270
million more in the acquirer's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Excite (at) home's long-term strategy is to be a leading planner
in broad-band _ high-speed Internet access over cable television.
(at) home, which focuses on the cable business, acquired Excite to
create a narrow-band Internet presence and said that it had similar
intentions with Bluemountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize the importance of making the narrow-band end of
the funnel as robust as possible explicitly for the purpose of
converting those users to broadband eventually.'' said George Bell,
Excite (at) home's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Devotees of the Bluemountain site use its cards for everything
from celebrating Robert Burns Day to proposing marriage to far-away
lovers. According to MediaMetrix, an Internet audience measurement
firm, it now ranks 14th among sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have been approached for more than a year by
numerous companies, the Schutzes said they had declined to sell
because they wanted to keep creative control. But costs forced
their hand. ``As we got more and more popular, it got
extraordinarily expensive,'' said Ms. Polis Schutz. ``We had 300
servers and 86 employees. We could not handle it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Excite (at) home, which started the bidding process more than a
year and a half ago, made its third offer a few months ago, just as
the Schutzes were concluding they had to sell. The family was
impressed that Excite offered many of the features they wanted to
incorporate _like a calendar, date book and gift registry _ and
would have paid to develop themselves. They also clicked with Bell,
whose colorful past includes a long stint as an independent
documentary producer for organizations like National Geographic and
the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Excite (at) home team are understanding about the nature
of our community, and we are confident they will continue to be
good stewards into the future,'' said Jared Schutz, who is Stephen
and Susan's oldest son and executive director of Bluemountain.
Stephen will continue as editor in chief of Bluemountain for at
least another year, under the terms of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   While making a commitment to Bluemountain's community, Excite
(at) home savors the site's untapped commercial potential. ``The
beauty is you have roughly a million people ordering cards
everyday, and most all are for events that have gifts,'' said
Arthur Newman, an Internet analyst at Schroders.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo ran into trouble when it tried to bring a more commercial
approach to Geocities, a similar acquisition in 1998. A site where
users could make their own Web pages for free, Geocities had lots
of loyal customers who revolted when Yahoo tried to force members
to relinquish copyright on their Web creations.
</P>
<P>
   Bluemountain was spun off from the publishing company earlier
this year. Both companies are privately held by the Schutz family,
but Ms. Polis Schutz said the benefits of the merger would be
widely felt. ``Every musician, every artist, every employee has
options,'' she said. ``We are thrilled for them, that they are
going to be rewarded for their incredible dedication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
