<HEADLINE>
RECRUIT STILL SOLD ON USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Whether or not sophomore quarterback Carson Palmer
returns this season from his broken collarbone is probably the most
intriguing question left for USC.
</P>
<P>
   But what effect will Palmer's decision have on Chatsworth High
quarterback Matt Cassel, who orally committed to USC last spring?
</P>
<P>
   Cassel committed with the idea he would redshirt his freshman
year and at worst be the backup during Palmer's senior year. In a
best-case scenario, Palmer would leave USC after his junior season,
allowing Cassel to start as a redshirt freshman.
</P>
<P>
   But the injury has made things uncertain _ at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Cassel, however, has not wavered in his commitment to the
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My decision is final,'' Cassel said. ``It's kind of weird.
Maybe if he redshirts, maybe it changes the situation. Maybe it
kicks me back another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking for him to leave early. It would be nice if he
left, but if he doesn't leave early, it's OK with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassel said even if Palmer decided to stay through his senior
season, he would be happy with his decision to attend USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping if it all works out, Carson leaves early,'' Cassel
said. ``If not, I'll come in as a redshirt sophomore.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Recruit watch: Among those attending Saturday's game were
linebacker Amon Gordon and quarterback/tight end Teyo Johnson of
Mira Mesa High in San Diego, along with Harvard-Westlake tight end
Alex Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   __ For the record: With Saturday's loss to Stanford, quarterback
Mike Van Raaphorst is 7-7 as a starter. Palmer is 5-3 and John Fox
is 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   __ Home and away: USC is two different teams under coach Paul
Hackett. At the Coliseum, the Trojans are 8-2, but on the road the
Trojans are only 3-7.
</P>
<P>
   __ Arizona State game time: USC's game on Nov. 6 with Arizona
State at the Coliseum will either be at 12:30 p.m. or 3:30 p.m.,
but a decision will not be made until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The game will be televised by ABC (Channel 7) at 12:30 p.m., or
Fox Sports West at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lucky charms?: USC coach Paul Hackett is open to suggestions
for what it will take to break the Trojans' three-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for any good-luck charms, any rabbit's feet,
whatever it's going to take to have us relax and play the full 60
minutes we're capable of,'' Hackett said. ``Any possible way to get
ourselves out of this week.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Questions, please: Unlike last week, Hackett patiently
answered questions during Monday's booster luncheon that is open to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   __ First-half team: USC is outscoring opponents 146-51,
including 77-27 in the second quarter. But in the fourth quarter
and overtime, the Trojans have been outscored 78-41.
</P>
<P>
   __ Scouting Cal: Although California's offense has struggled
this season, the Bears' running game will be a focus for USC this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman tailback Joe Igber, who is only 5-foot-8, has had three
consecutive 100-yard games, including a freshman-record 182 yards
last weekend against Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
