<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-MAGAZINE-FASHION-ART-     10-25 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW BREED OF MAGAZINES DESIGNED TO STARTLE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you opened the August issue of Flaunt magazine smack in the
middle expecting to see a picture of, say, Elizabeth Hurley
languishing at the beach, the fringes of her Gucci halter dress
tickling the water's surface, you would have been disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   There, instead, were two full-page, borderless close-ups of
women's faces, their skin splotchy, their expressions drained of
any life-affirming look of curiosity. Displaying clothes is the
ostensible purpose of a fashion picture, but the garments worn by
the models _ a dress and coat by Valentino, as a credit line
revealed _ were barely visible. The models looked a week shy of 72.
</P>
<P>
   Flaunt, unleashed last fall in Los Angeles, is one of a breed of
small, independently owned, increasingly influential style
magazines that exist more as a venue for far-reaching experiments
in fashion photography than as showcases for clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, more than half a dozen similar
publications _ V, Big, 2wice, Surface, aRude, Issue _ have emerged
in the United States, in the spirit of European fashion
publications like The Face, I.D. and the newer Dutch, which has
attracted an international cult following. Over the summer,
Matthias Vriens, then the editor in chief of Dutch, was hired by
the Armani company to be its creative director, signaling the
seriousness with which these little magazines are now taken.
</P>
<P>
   The publications, which claim readerships of 10,000 to 100,000,
compar a circulation of a million for Vogue, are not only
affecting the lives of a select group of talented young people, but
also reshaping the business of image-making itself. While working
for important American fashion magazines used to be considered an
essential step for a young photographer hoping to advance to
lucrative advertising work, the presence of these publications is
making that step unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are taking more chances with people who haven't been
tested at the big magazines,'' said Andrew Thomas of Art +
Commerce, a photography agency representing renowned photographers
like Annie Leibovitz and Steven Meisel, as well as newcomers like
Luis Sanchis, who catapulted from shooting for niche European
magazines to photographing campaigns for Gucci and Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Warwick Saint, 28, a photographer who shot exclusively for
magazines like I.D., Dutch and Flaunt, where he became known for
technically striking portraits, got to shoot advertising campaigns
for Costume National, Diesel and Levi's on the basis of that work.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Meijer, head of a photo agency that manages rising stars
like Taryn Simon (who has shot Levi's ads and promotional material
for the band Nine Inch Nails) said, ``The whole status of working
for Harper's Bazaar and Vogue _ everyone's over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally Singer, Vogue's fashion news director, said she didn't
think so. ``If a young photographer gets a call from Vogue or
Bazaar, I think he's going to go,'' she said. ``What's great about
the small magazines is that they do allow young photographers to
experiment. But Vogue is about showing clothes to readers who
probably want to see the whole skirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Editors and art directors for the independent magazines say they
are motivated by disenchantment with the predictability of
mass-market fashion magazines _ increasingly devoted to the lives,
poodles and handbags of movie stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, editors were really editing a magazine,''
said Long Nguyen, one of three founding editors of Flaunt. ``Today
they are like flight attendants serving ready-made food on a
tray.''
</P>
<P>
   Alix Browne, the editor of V and a former staff member at
Harper's Bazaar and Mirabella, said of the fashion pages in
mainstream women's magazines: ``Everyone is doing the same story.
You see the same Gucci story, the same Prada story, the same
celebrity on every cover.'' V is a provocative if not always
legible fashion magazine that began publishing in New York last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The new magazines both here and abroad are read by both women
and men (a Flaunt survey showed that almost 50 percent of its
readers are men), although, suffice it to say, by women and men who
could more easily pick Frank Gehry and Issey Miyake out of a
line-up than Regis and Kathie Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Editors of the independents readily admit that their magazines
make little or no money. ``It's been difficult,'' said Marcelo
Juunemann, the owner and editor of Big, a beautiful publication
that comes out six times a year. It reports a circulation of 32,000
and, like almost all of these magazines, remarkably enough is
replete with big advertisers, like Gucci, Calvin Klein and DKNY.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers typically pay about $7,000 a page in an independent
magazine _ about a sixth of the price of a page in Vogue. ``We're
not making a fortune,'' Juunemann said, ``but we pay the bills and
have money to buy the paper and keep going.'' Indeed, production
costs are exorbitant at these publications, where printing is
top-end and the paper sometimes thicker and glossier than what you
see in Vogue or Elle.
</P>
<P>
   One place the money doesn't go is into the pockets of the
photographers who are the magazines' creative mainstays. They are
generally paid nothing. Sometimes they are reimbursed for expenses.
This does not seem to bother them, given the prospect of lucrative
future commissions, not to mention that when they receive an
assignment from a Dutch or a Flaunt, it isn't really an assignment
in the traditional sense. They are generally free to point their
cameras in whatever direction they feel a tug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for the glory,'' said Alexi Hay, 25, a photographer who
is coming of age in this subculture. ``There's no one standing over
you telling you what clothes to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old formula of finding a location and getting beautiful
girls is obsolete.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current issue of Dutch, Hay mused on the subject of
street-tough posturing in an astonishing 23 pages. There were bits
of Versace this and Gaultier that on male ``models'' he cast at the
Puerto Rican Day parade in New York. His hair and makeup person was
a Lower East Side barber.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of such endeavors, Hay recently landed an ad
campaign for Armani's A/X line, thanks to Vriens' appointment at
Armani.
</P>
<P>
   While they are flight paths for young talent, the small
magazines now also attract celebrated photographers like David
LaChapelle and Mario Testino, drawn to the genre's use-your-wings
ethos.
</P>
<P>
   As LaChapelle's surreal colored, elaborately produced celebrity
portraitures in Vanity Fair and Rolling Stone would indicate, he is
not a man easily reined in. But despite the freedom he is afforded
by mainstream magazines, he appreciates the chance to work in what
he describes as a different mind-set, even at his own expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to look at a blank page and think I can do
whatever I want,'' he said. ``There's creative anarchy going on.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   LaChapelle recently shot pictures for Flaunt, based very loosely
around some Helmut Lang clothes that depict fears of the
apocalypse. More arresting than any single pair of pants is the
image of a nearly naked, overweight man lying on a floral
comforter, his body covered in red blotches. The entire shoot was
inspired by a panic-inducing article on smallpox in The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Helmut Lang would be horrified,'' LaChapelle said.
``He sent me a fax saying he really liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   To judge by the many ad pages in these new ventures, designers
(and liquor companies, the other ad constituency) are very
supportive them, despite the fact the editors seem a little
confused on the whole subject of consumerism.
</P>
<P>
   ``They represent a different approach to fashion editorial,''
said Trey Laird, executive vice president and corporate creative
director of Donna Karan International. ``They attract a reader who
is on the edge of fashion. It's a reader we want to reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to big fashion publications, he said: ``Magazines go
through different periods. There's been a safety and commercial
approach to the presentation of fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to suggest that advertisers are diverting their
money away from the Vogues and Bazaars of the world. With a hunger
to keep their images cool, they simply want to be everywhere. The
major magazines will no doubt endure, since it is safe to assume
that more people will want to look at Winona Ryder in Chanel than
at pictures of diseased and unclothed middle-aged men.
</P>
<P>
   At their best, the images in alternative fashion magazines offer
color-saturated studies in loneliness, emotional dislocation and
suburban tedium, sometimes more conceptually evolved than anything
on the Independent Film Channel. At their worst, they present a
trite, dissipated sexuality that is meant to shock and doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a punk sensibility that's now old hat,'' said Simon
Doonan, the creative director of Barneys New York. Doonan said he
had lost faith in alternative magazines he used to turn to for
ideas. Pictorially, he said, ``it's still people lolling around
looking like they've been hit over the head with a frying pan.''
</P>
<P>
   For his latest ad campaign, he found inspiration in a poster
purchased at the Good Will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
