<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FALWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MR. FALWELL'S PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Oct. 26:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When warring communities get together for the purpose of
increasing understanding and combating violence, it is a noteworthy
event. The gathering of the Rev. Jerry Falwell and his supporters
and 200 gay Christians in Falwell's Thomas Road Baptist Church in
Lynchburg, Va., last weekend was such an occasion _ and a telling
moment in Falwell's personal evolution and that of the gay rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell, the political and theological conservative who founded
the Moral Majority, has long deployed harsh anti-gay rhetoric in
his fund-raising appeals. He told the meeting he would not change
his view that homosexuality is a sin, but he agreed to tone down
statements that, among other things, have provided a moral context
for those who commit violence against gay people.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell's willingness to dispense with anti-gay vitriol is a
measure of how far the gay rights movement has progressed toward
cultural acceptance, and recognition on Falwell's part that the
murder of Matthew Shepard, the gay college student who died after a
brutal assault a year ago in Wyoming, has made it less acceptable
to be seen as spewing hatred against gays. Falwell was persuaded to
hold the meeting by the Rev. Mel White, a minister who worked as a
ghostwriter on Falwell's autobiography in the 1980's, several years
before declaring his homosexuality. White apparently struck a chord
when he told Falwell in August that his organization's language
about homosexuals was so harsh it could inspire anti-gay violence.
</P>
<P>
   While Falwell has agreed to tone himself down, he remains
opposed to measures designed to end discrimination on the basis of
sexual orientation. His stance continues to send a damaging message
that gay people are second-class citizens and lesser human beings.
It also says that Falwell's break from bigotry is still incomplete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0578 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-25 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-BUCHANAN-NYT &LR;      10-25 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUCHANAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TO THE REAR, MARCH! 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Oct. 26:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early on, George W. Bush and some other prominent Republicans
went through the motions of trying to prevent Patrick Buchanan's
announcement that he was ``ending my lifelong membership in the
Republican Party.'' But in the end, no one seemed very upset by
Buchanan's exit or by Donald Trump's simultaneous defection to the
Reform Party. But while Trump's presidential dreaming had the feel
of a self-indulgent lark, Buchanan's seems a blend of financial
scheming, retro rage and perhaps a bit of self-delusion. Does
anyone believe that Buchanan's ``peasant army'' really exists? They
may be ready to storm the castle, but they certainly did not help
their man in the GOP polls.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's failure to make the grade against Bush and John
McCain will not matter, of course, if he can get hold of the
party's $12.6 million in federal funds. Then Buchanan, a wealthy
Washingtonian, will have all the money he needs to mount his
faux-populist crusade against the ``money boys and the Beltway
elites.''
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, he embarked on his departure with an allusion to the
St. Crispin's Day speech in Shakespeare's ``Henry V,'' a paean to
what true leadership meant in the Middle Ages. He then went on to
promise battle on a number of issues that most Americans have
already worked through. At a time when American culture and
economic values are on the march around the globe, Buchanan wants
to save America ``before she disappears into a godless New World
Order.'' His mission, he said, is to end the racial quotas that
have helped minorities enter the mainstream and to force a ``time
out'' in the immigration that perpetually revitalizes an
immigrants' nation. He promised to keep America from entering ``all
the bloody, territorial, tribal and ethnic wars'' of the 21st
century, thus crippling the halting but vital effort to find
international remedies to genocidal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Such efforts to isolate America from the real issues of the 21st
century should help isolate Buchanan. Already his views on why the
United States should not have entered World War II against Hitler's
Germany have drawn understandable outrage, not only from veterans
but also historians. Trump, who sees himself as a possible antidote
to the Buchanan forces, calls Buchanan a ``Hitler lover.'' Buchanan
has rejected such a label, but his warlike oratory draws fringe
voters and surrounds his candidacy with the persistent whiff of
racism and anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan seems to believe that his divisive social views will
open up pockets of discontent in the middle class and that his
protectionist trade policy and promises of job protection can pull
in suburban and union workers normally loyal to the major parties.
First, of course, he must wrest the Reform Party from the likes of
Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota; Ross Perot, whose ambitions for
the party are still fairly cloudy, and perhaps even Trump.
Meanwhile, we have to wonder if the idealists who initially joined
the Reform Party think that roster adds up to a rational definition
of reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-25-99 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991025.0579 </DOCNO>
