<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY SO PERFECT TURNS INTO TRAGEDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By FRAN BLINEBURY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Against the backdrop of a bright blue quiet sky, if
you squint through the sun, it is a perfect afternoon to stand at
the driving range and watch Jeff Maggert hit balls.
</P>
<P>
   Long and high and straight and true.
</P>
<P>
   It is warm and slightly breezy, the kind of ideal day made for
golf.
</P>
<P>
   And other things.
</P>
<P>
   What we always learn about tragedy is that we are never ready
for it to occur.
</P>
<P>
   It is an idyllic scene at Champions Golf Club, where the
fairways have been mowed so neatly, where the greens have been
rolled to look as hard and smooth as giant billiard tables, where
the flower beds are filled with all the colors of a painter's
palette, where even the pine trees seem primped to stand at
attention, where everything is precisely the way it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Except the flags are flying at half-mast.
</P>
<P>
   While Maggert beats golf balls and his roiling, churning
emotions with each controlled, even swing, inside the clubhouse a
large-screen TV is showing images of a pasture in South Dakota
where a private plane carrying Payne Stewart and four others has
crashed, killing all aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The reigning U.S. Open champion, No. 3 on the money list,
Stewart was scheduled to arrive in Houston for the Tour
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   But something went so horribly wrong inside the plane, producing
the bizarre story of the pilotless jet, bound from Orlando to
Dallas, streaking across airspace in the middle of the country
until running out of fuel and falling out of the sky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THERE ARE NO WORDS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here, on the golf course at Champions, two mockingbirds chase
after each other from railing to railing on a pair of spectator
platforms, a chubby little brown rabbit darts across a cart path
and through an open flap in one of the hospitality tents and a
couple of fathers hold their sons by the hand as they stroll and
enjoy the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Out in front of the clubhouse, where the VIP parking lot has
spaces reserved for each of the players with painted nameplates,
somebody has already tied a blue ribbon next to the sign that says
``Payne Stewart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a loss for his family, his wife and kids,'' said
Maggert. ``You feel so helpless because you can't change the
outcome. All I can say is I don't know what to say.''
</P>
<P>
   What can he say? The 8x11 sheet on the clubhouse table shows the
pairings for this morning's (now cancelled) pro-am: ``9:09 _ Payne
Stewart and Jeff Maggert.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not one big traveling fraternity on the PGA Tour with all
of the guys taking turns hanging out in each other's hotel rooms
from week to week. But relationships develop, friendships grow and
Stewart is one of those who has crept inside the gallery rope a lot
of the players put up around themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the general public may have known him mostly for the
distinctive wardrobe of Plus-Fours he wore on the golf course, an
homage to the game and a time gone by.
</P>
<P>
   But he was also the honorable sportsman who conceded a long putt
to halve the match with Colin Montgomerie at the end of the
contentious Ryder Cup last month. And the players knew him as
fun-loving, glib, quotable and as fiery a competitor as you'll
find.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MOMENTS OF JOY PASS QUICKLY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The image that was played over and over on Monday was from
Pinehurst, N.C., in June. It showed him sinking that 15-foot,
bending-to-the-right putt through the drizzle on the final hole
that gave him his second U.S. Open title, and it showed him
triumphantly pumping his right fist into the air twice, then
catching his jubilant caddie, Mike Hicks, who raced across the
green and leapt into Stewart's arms.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, Hicks was at Champions, getting everything in
order for Stewart's arrival, when he received a phone call that
told him the unthinkable had happened.
</P>
<P>
   They are so bright, full of life and celebrity and money and
maybe that is why it's always so shocking. A handsome, wealthy son
of a former president climbs into a private plane with his
beautiful wife to fly to a wedding and they never arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The sports world has had its share: Roberto Clemente and Thurman
Munson from baseball, Knute Rockne from football and golfer
``Champagne'' Tony Lema just after winning the British Open in
1964. It is part of the privilege that comes with their riches _
and part of the danger.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing we learn about tragedy is that no one and no time
is ever immune.
</P>
<P>
   Over by the practice green, three women sip cold drinks as the
sun bakes their bare arms and nod their heads in approval as
somebody rattles a long putt into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   It is warm and slightly breezy, the kind of ideal day made for
golf.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of a bright blue quiet sky, a thousand
miles away, a TV image shows a chopper hovering over a burnt scar
in a pasture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
